text=https://i.imgur.com/WTCZurQ.png%0a(:include GameRef.Directorycity:)%0a----%0a%25center%25https://i.imgur.com/l5E7f87.png%0a----%0a(:toc:)%0a[[#top]]%0a%0a!%25center%25'''Pittsburgh'''%0a%0a!!%25center%25''Overview''%0a%0aPittsburgh is located in the southwest of the state, at the confluence of the Allegheny River and the Monongahela River, forming the Ohio River. Pittsburgh is known both as "the Steel City" for its more than 300 steel-related businesses and as the "City of Bridges" for its 446 bridges. The city features 30 skyscrapers, two inclined railways, a pre-revolutionary fortification and the Point State Park at the confluence of the rivers. The city developed as a vital link of the Atlantic coast and Midwest, as the mineral-rich Allegheny Mountains led to the region being contested by the French and British empires, Virginians, Whiskey Rebels, and Civil War raiders.%0a%0aAside from steel, Pittsburgh has led in the manufacturing of other important materials - aluminum and glass - and in the petroleum industry. Additionally, it is a leader in computing, electronics, and the automotive industry. For part of the 20th century, Pittsburgh was behind only New York City and Chicago in corporate headquarters employment; it had the most U.S. stockholders per capita. Deindustrialization in the 1970s and 1980s laid off area blue-collar workers as steel and other heavy industries declined, and thousands of downtown white-collar workers also lost jobs when several Pittsburgh-based companies moved out. The population dropped from a peak of 675,000 in 1950 to 370,000 in 1990. However, this rich industrial history left the area with renowned museums, medical centers, parks, research centers, and a diverse cultural district.%0a%0aAfter the deindustrialization of the mid-20th century, Pittsburgh has transformed into a hub for the health care, education, and technology industries. Pittsburgh is a leader in the health care sector as the home to large medical providers such as University of Pittsburgh Medical Center (UPMC). The area is home to 68 colleges and universities, including research and development leaders Carnegie Mellon University and the University of Pittsburgh. Google, Apple Inc., Bosch, Facebook, Uber, Nokia, Autodesk, Amazon, Microsoft and IBM are among 1,600 technology firms generating $20.7 billion in annual Pittsburgh payrolls. The area has served as the long-time federal agency headquarters for cyber defense, software engineering, robotics, energy research and the nuclear navy. The nation's fifth-largest bank, eight Fortune 500 companies, and six of the top 300 U.S. law firms make their global headquarters in the area, while RAND Corporation (RAND), BNY Mellon, Nova, FedEx, Bayer, and the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) have regional bases that helped Pittsburgh become the sixth-best area for U.S. job growth.%0a%0aIn 2015, Pittsburgh was listed among the "eleven most livable cities in the world". The Economist's Global Liveability Ranking placed Pittsburgh as the most or second-most livable city in the United States in 2005, 2009, 2011, 2012, 2014 and 2018. The region is a hub for Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design and energy extraction.%0a%0a%25right%25[[#top|&#8593; back to top]]%0a%0a!%25center%25'''Early colonization (1747 to 1763)'''%0a%0aThe first Europeans arrived in the 1710s as traders. Michael Bezallion was the first to describe the forks of the Ohio in a manuscript in 1717, and later that year European traders established posts and settlements in the area. Europeans first began to settle in the region in 1748, when the first Ohio Company, a Virginian land speculation company, won a grant of 200,000 acres in the upper Ohio Valley. From a post at present-day Cumberland, Maryland, the company began to construct an 80-mile wagon road to the Monongahela River employing a Delaware Indian chief named Nemacolin and a party of settlers headed by Capt. Michael Cresap to begin widening the track into a road. It mostly followed the same route as an ancient Amerindian trail which is now known as Nemacolin's Trail. The river crossing and flats at Redstone creek, was the earliest point and shortest distance for the descent of a wagon road. Later in the war, the site fortified as Fort Burd (now Brownsville) was one of several possible destinations. Another alternative was the divergent route that became Braddock's Road a few years later through present-day New Stanton. In the event, the colonists did not succeed in improving the Amerindian path to a wagon road much beyond the Cumberland Narrows pass before they were confronted by hostile Native Americans. The colonists later mounted a series of expeditions in order to accomplish piecemeal improvements to the track.%0a%0aThe nearby Native American community of Logstown was an important trade and council center in the Ohio Valley. Between June 15 and November 10, 1749, an expedition headed by Celeron de Bienville, a French officer, traveled down the Allegheny and Ohio to bolster the French claim to the region. De Bienville warned away British traders and posted markers claiming the territory.%0a%0aIn 1753, Marquis Duquesne, the Governor of New France, sent another, larger expedition. At present-day Erie, Pennsylvania, an advance party built Fort Presque Isle. They also cut a road through the woods and built Fort Le Boeuf on French Creek, from which it was possible at high water to float to the Allegheny. By summer, an expedition of 1,500 French and Native American men descended the Allegheny. Some wintered at the confluence of French Creek and the Allegheny. The following year, they built Fort Machault at that site.%0a%0aAlarmed at these French incursions in the Ohio Valley, Governor Dinwiddie of Virginia sent Major George Washington to warn the French to withdraw. Accompanied by Christopher Gist, Washington arrived at the Forks of the Ohio on November 25, 1753%0a%0aProceeding up the Allegheny, Washington presented Dinwiddie's letter to the French commanders first at Venango, and then Fort Le Boeuf. The French officers received Washington with wine and courtesy, but did not withdraw.%0a%0aGovernor Dinwiddie sent Captain William Trent to build a fort at the Forks of the Ohio. On February 17, 1754, Trent began construction of the fort, the first European habitation at the site of present-day Pittsburgh. The fort, named Fort Prince George, was only half-built by April 1754, when over 500 French forces arrived and ordered the 40-some colonials back to Virginia. The French tore down the British fortification and constructed Fort Duquesne.%0a%0aGovernor Dinwiddie launched another expedition. Colonel Joshua Fry commanded the regiment with his second-in-command, George Washington, leading an advance column. On May 28, 1754, Washington's unit clashed with the French in the Battle of Jumonville Glen, during which 13 French soldiers were killed and 21 were taken prisoner. After the battle, Washington's ally, Seneca chief Tanaghrisson, unexpectedly executed the French commanding officer, Ensign Joseph Coulon de Jumonville. The French pursued Washington and on July 3, 1754, George Washington surrendered following the Battle of Fort Necessity. These frontier actions contributed to the start of the French and Indian War (1754-1763), or, the Seven Years' War, a global confrontation between Britain and France fought in both hemispheres.%0a%0aIn 1755, the Braddock Expedition was launched, accompanied by Virginia militia officer George Washington. Two regiments marched from Fort Cumberland across the Allegheny Mountains and into western Pennsylvania. Following a path Washington surveyed, over 3,000 men built a wagon road 12 feet wide, that when complete, was the first road to cross the Appalachian Mountains. Braddock's Road, as it was known, blazed the way for the future National Road (US40). The expedition crossed the Monongahela River on July 9, 1755. French troops from Fort Duquesne ambushed Braddock's expedition at Braddock's Field, nine miles from Fort Duquesne. In the Battle of the Monongahela, the French inflicted heavy losses on the British, and Braddock was mortally wounded. The surviving British and colonial forces retreated. This left the French and their Native American allies with dominion over the upper Ohio valley.%0a%0aOn September 8, 1756, an expedition of 300 militiamen destroyed the Shawnee and Lenape village of Kittanning, and in the summer of 1758, British Army officer John Forbes began a campaign to capture Fort Duquesne. At the head of 7,000 regular and colonial troops, Forbes built Fort Ligonier and Fort Bedford, from where he cut a wagon road over the Allegheny Mountains, later known as Forbes' Road. On the night of September 13-14, 1758, an advance column under Major James Grant was annihilated in the Battle of Fort Duquesne. The battleground, the high hill east of the Point, was named Grant's Hill in his memory. With this defeat, Forbes decided to wait until spring. But when he heard that the French had lost Fort Frontenac and largely evacuated Fort Duquesne, he planned an immediate attack. Hopelessly outnumbered, the French abandoned and razed Fort Duquesne. Forbes occupied the burned fort on November 25, 1758, and ordered the construction of Fort Pitt, named after British Secretary of State William Pitt the Elder. He also named the settlement between the rivers, "Pittsborough" (see Etymology of Pittsburgh). The British garrison at Fort Pitt made substantial improvements to its fortification. The French never attacked Fort Pitt and the war soon ended with the Treaty of Paris and French defeat. They ceded their territories east of the Mississippi River.%0a%0a%0a%0a!!%25center%25''Gateway to the West (1763 to 1799)''%0a%0aIn 1760, the first considerable European settlement around Fort Pitt began to grow. Traders and settlers built two groups of houses and cabins, the "lower town," near the fort's ramparts, and the "upper town," along the Monongahela as far as present-day Market Street. In April 1761, a census ordered by Colonel Henry Bouquet counted 332 people and 104 houses.%0a%0aAfter Britain's victory in the French and Indian War, increasing dissatisfaction among Native Americans with British policies led to the outbreak of Pontiac's War. The Odawa leader Pontiac launched an offensive against British forts in May 1763. Native American tribes from the Ohio Valley and the Great Lakes overran numerous British forts; one of their most important targets was Fort Pitt. Receiving warning of the coming attack, Captain Simeon Ecuyer, the Swiss officer in command of the garrison, prepared for a siege. He leveled the houses outside the ramparts and ordered all settlers into the fort: 330 men, 104 women, and 196 children sought refuge inside its ramparts. Captain Ecuyer also gathered stores, which included hundreds of barrels of pork and beef. Pontiac's forces attacked the fort on June 22, 1763, and the siege of Fort Pitt lasted for two months. Pontiac's warriors kept up a continuous, though ineffective, fire on it from July 27 through August 1, 1763. They drew off to confront the relieving party under Colonel Bouquet, which defeated them in the Battle of Bushy Run. This victory ensured British dominion over the forks of the Ohio, if not the entire Ohio valley. In 1764 Colonel Bouquet added a redoubt, the Fort Pitt Blockhouse, which still stands, the sole remaining structure from Fort Pitt and the oldest authenticated building west of the Allegheny Mountains.%0a%0aThe Iroquois signed the Fort Stanwix Treaty of 1768, ceding the lands south of the Ohio to the British Crown. European expansion into the upper Ohio valley increased. An estimated 4,000 to 5,000 families settled in western Pennsylvania between 1768 and 1770. Of these settlers, about a third were English-American, another third were Scotch-Irish, and the rest were Welsh, German and others. These groups tended to settle together in small farming communities, but often their households were not within hailing distance. The life of a settler family was one of relentless hard work: clearing the forest, stumping the fields, building cabins and barns, planting, weeding, and harvesting. In addition, almost everything was manufactured by hand, including furniture, tools, candles, buttons, and needles. Settlers had to deal with harsh winters, and with snakes, black bears, mountain lions, and timber wolves. Because of the fear of raids by Native Americans, the settlers often built their cabins near, or even on top of, springs, to ensure access to water. They also built blockhouses, where neighbors would rally during conflicts.%0a%0aIncreasing violence, especially by the Shawnee, Miami, and Wyandot tribes, led to Dunmore's War in 1774. Conflict with Native Americans continued throughout the Revolutionary War, as some hoped that the war would end with expulsion of the settlers from their territory. In 1777, Fort Pitt became a United States fort, when Brigadier General Edward Hand took command. In 1779, Colonel Daniel Brodhead led 600 men from Fort Pitt to destroy Seneca villages along the upper Allegheny.%0a%0aWith the war still ongoing, in 1780 Virginia and Pennsylvania came to an agreement on their mutual borders, creating the state lines known today and determining finally that the jurisdiction of Pittsburgh region was Pennsylvanian. In 1783, the Revolutionary War ended, which also brought at least a temporary cessation of border warfare. In the 1784 Treaty of Fort Stanwix, the Iroquois ceded the land north of the Purchase Line to Pennsylvania.%0a%0aAfter the Revolution, the village of Pittsburgh continued to grow. One of its earliest industries was boat building. Flatboats could be used to carry large numbers of pioneers and goods downriver, while keelboats were capable of traveling upriver.%0a%0aThe village began to develop vital institutions. Hugh Henry Brackenridge, a Pittsburgh resident and state legislator, introduced a bill that resulted in a gift deed of land and a charter for the Pittsburgh Academy on February 28, 1787. The Academy later developed as the University of Western Pennsylvania (1819) and since 1908 has been known as the University of Pittsburgh.%0a%0aMany farmers distilled their corn harvest into whiskey, increasing its value while lowering its transportation costs. At that time, whiskey was used as a form of currency on the frontier. When the federal government imposed an excise tax on whiskey, Western Pennsylvania farmers felt victimized, leading to the Whiskey Rebellion in 1794. Farmers from the region rallied at Braddock's Field and marched on Pittsburgh. The short-lived rebellion was put down, however, when President George Washington sent in militias from several states.%0a%0aThe town continued to grow in manufacturing capability. In 1792, the boatyards in Pittsburgh built a sloop, Western Experiment. During the next decades, the yards produced other large boats. By the 19th century, they were building ocean-going vessels that shipped goods as far as Europe. In 1794, the town's first courthouse was built; it was a wooden structure on Market Square. In 1797, the manufacture of glass began.%0a%0a%0a!%25center%25'''Iron City (1800 to 1859)'''%0a%0aCommerce continued to be an essential part of the economy of early Pittsburgh, but increasingly, manufacture began to grow in importance. Pittsburgh was located in the middle of one of the most productive coalfields in the country; the region was also rich in petroleum, natural gas, lumber, and farm goods. Blacksmiths forged iron implements, from horse shoes to nails. By 1800, the town, with a population of 1,565 persons, had over 60 shops, including general stores, bakeries, and hat and shoe shops.%0a%0aThe 1810s were a critical decade in Pittsburgh's growth. In 1811, the first steamboat was built in Pittsburgh. Increasingly, commerce would also flow upriver. The War of 1812 catalyzed growth of the Iron City. The war with Britain, the manufacturing center of the world, cut off the supply of British goods, stimulating American manufacture. In addition, the British blockade of the American coast increased inland trade, so that goods flowed through Pittsburgh from all four directions. By 1815, Pittsburgh was producing $764K in iron; $249K in brass and tin, and $235K in glass products. When, on March 18, 1816, Pittsburgh was incorporated as a city, it had already taken on some of its defining characteristics: commerce, manufacture, and a constant cloud of coal dust.%0a%0aOther emerging towns challenged Pittsburgh. In 1818, the first segment of the National Road was completed, from Baltimore to Wheeling, bypassing Pittsburgh. This threatened to render the town less essential in east-west commerce. In the coming decade, however, many improvements were made to the transportation infrastructure. In 1818, the region's first river bridge, the Smithfield Street Bridge, opened, the first step in developing the "City of bridges" over its two rivers. On October 1, 1840, the original Pennsylvania Turnpike was completed, connecting Pittsburgh and the eastern port city of Philadelphia. In 1834, the Pennsylvania Main Line Canal was completed, making Pittsburgh part of a transportation system that included rivers, roads, and canals.%0a%0aManufacture continued to grow. In 1835, McClurg, Wade and Co. built the first locomotive west of the Alleghenies. Already, Pittsburgh was capable of manufacturing the most essential machines of its age. By the 1840s, Pittsburgh was one of the largest cities west of the mountains. In 1841, the Second Court House, on Grant's Hill, was completed. Made from polished gray sandstone, the court house had a rotunda 60 feet in diameter and 80 feet high.%0a%0aLike many burgeoning cities of its day, Pittsburgh's growth outstripped some of its necessary infrastructure, such as a water supply with dependable pressure. Because of this, on April 10, 1845, a great fire burned out of control, destroying over a thousand buildings and causing $9M in damages. As the city rebuilt, the age of rails arrived. In 1851, the Ohio and Pennsylvania Railroad began service between Cleveland and Allegheny City (present-day North Side). In 1854, the Pennsylvania Railroad began service between Pittsburgh and Philadelphia.%0a%0aDespite many challenges, Pittsburgh had grown into an industrial powerhouse. An 1857 article provided a snapshot of the Iron City:%0a%0a939 factories in Pittsburgh and Allegheny City employing more than 10K workers producing almost $12M in goods using 400 steam engines. %0aTotal coal consumed  22M bushels%0aTotal iron consumed  127K tons%0aIn steam tonnage, third busiest port in the nation, surpassed only by New York City and New Orleans.%0a%0a%0a!%25center%25'''Steel City (1859 to 1946)'''%0a%0aThe iron and steel industry developed rapidly after 1830 and became one of the dominant factors in industrial America by the 1860s.%0a%0a!!%25center%25''Scots Irish leadership''%0a%0aIngham (1978) examined the leadership of the industry in its most important center, Pittsburgh, as well as smaller cities. He concludes that the leadership of the iron and steel industry nationwide was "largely Scotch Irish". Ingham finds that the Scotch Irish held together cohesively throughout the 19th century and "developed their own sense of uniqueness."%0a%0aNew immigrants after 1800 made Pittsburgh a major Scotch-Irish stronghold. For example, Thomas Mellon (b. Ulster 1813-1908) left northern Ireland in 1823 for the United States. He founded the powerful Mellon family, which played a central role in banking and industries such as aluminum and oil. As Barnhisel (2005) finds, industrialists such as James Laughlin (b. Ulster 1806-1882) of Jones and Laughlin Steel Company comprised the "Scots-Irish Presbyterian ruling stratum of Pittsburgh society."%0a%0a!!%25center%25''Technology''%0a%0aIn 1859, the Clinton and Soho iron furnaces introduced coke-fire smelting to the region. The American Civil War boosted the city's economy with increased production of iron and armaments, especially at the Allegheny Arsenal and the Fort Pitt Foundry. Arms manufacture included iron-clad warships and the world's first 21" gun. By war's end, over one-half of the steel and more than one-third of all U.S. glass was produced in Pittsburgh. A milestone in steel production was achieved in 1875, when the Edgar Thomson Works in Braddock began to make steel rail using the new Bessemer process.%0a%0aIndustrialists such as Andrew Carnegie, Henry Clay Frick, Andrew W. Mellon, and Charles M. Schwab built their fortunes in Pittsburgh. Also based in Pittsburgh was George Westinghouse, credited with such advancements as the air brake and founder of over 60 companies, including Westinghouse Air and Brake Company (1869), Union Switch & Signal (1881), and Westinghouse Electric Company (1886). Banks played a key role in Pittsburgh's development as these industrialists sought massive loans to upgrade plants, integrate industries and fund technological advances. For example, T. Mellon & Sons Bank, founded in 1869, helped to finance an aluminum reduction company that became Alcoa.%0a%0aIngham (1991) shows how small, independent iron and steel manufacturers survived and prospered from the 1870s through the 1950s, despite competition from much larger, standardized production firms. These smaller firms were built on a culture that valued local markets and the beneficial role of business in the local community. Small firms concentrated on specialized products, particularly structural steel, where the economies of scale of larger firms were no advantage. They embraced technological change more cautiously than larger firms. They also had less antagonistic relations with workers and employed a higher percentage of highly skilled workers than their mass-production counterparts.%0a%0a!!%25center%25''Geography of industrialization.''%0a%0aBeginning in the 1870s, entrepreneurs transformed the economy from small, craft-organized factories located inside the city limits to a large integrated industrial region stretching 50 miles across Allegheny County. The new industrial Pittsburgh was based on integrated mills, mass production, and modern management organization in steel and other industries. Many manufacturers searched for large sites with railroad and river accessibility. They purchased land, designed modern plants, and sometimes built towns for workers. Other firms bought into new communities that began as speculative industrial real estate ventures. Some owners removed their plants from the central city's labor unions to exert greater control over workers. The region's rugged topography and dispersed natural resources of coal and gas accentuated this dispersal. The rapid growth of steel, glass, railroad equipment, and coke industries resulted in both large mass-production plants and numerous smaller firms. As capital deepened and interdependence grew, participants multiplied, economies accrued, the division of labor increased, and localized production systems formed around these industries. Transportation, capital, labor markets and the division of labor in production bound the scattered industrial plants and communities into a sprawling metropolitan district. By 1910 the Pittsburgh district was a complex urban landscape with a dominant central city, surrounded by proximate residential communities, mill towns, satellite cities, and hundreds of mining towns.%0a%0aRepresentative of the new industrial suburbs was the model town of Vandergrift, according to Mosher (1995). Caught up in a dramatic round of industrial restructuring and labor tension, Pittsburgh steelmaker George McMurtry hired Frederick Law Olmsted's landscape architectural firm in 1895 to design Vandergrift as a model town. McMurtry believed in what was later known as welfare capitalism, with the company going beyond paychecks to provide for the social needs of the workers; he believed that a benign physical environment made for happier and more productive workers. A strike and lockout at McMurtry's steelworks in Apollo, Pennsylvania, prompted him to build the new town. Wanting a loyal workforce, he developed a town agenda that drew upon environmentalism as well as popular attitudes toward capital's treatment of labor. The Olmsted firm translated this agenda into an urban design that included a unique combination of social reform, comprehensive infrastructure planning, and private homeownership principles. The rates of homeownership and cordial relationships between the steel company and Vandergrift residents fostered loyalty among McMurtry's skilled workers and led to McMurtry's greatest success. In 1901 he used Vandergrift's worker-residents to break the first major strike against the United States Steel Corporation.%0a%0a!!%25center%25''Germans.''%0a%0aDuring the mid-19th century, Pittsburgh witnessed a dramatic influx of German immigrants, including a brick mason whose son, Henry J. Heinz, founded the H.J. Heinz Company in 1869. Heinz was at the forefront of reform efforts to improve food purity, working conditions, hours, and wages, but the company bitterly opposed the formation of an independent labor union.%0a%0a!!%25center%25''Labor unions.''%0a%0aAs a manufacturing center, Pittsburgh also became an arena for intense labor strife. During the Great Railroad Strike of 1877, Pittsburgh workers protested and had massive demonstrations that erupted into widespread violence, known as the Pittsburgh Railway Riots. Militia and federal troops were called to the city to suppress the strike. Forty men died, most of them workers, and more than 40 buildings were burned down, including the Union Depot of the Pennsylvania Railroad. Strikers also burned and destroyed rolling stock: more than 100 train engines and 1000 railcars were destroyed. It was the city with the most violence of any affected by the strikes.%0aIn 1892, a confrontation in the steel industry resulted in 10 deaths (3 detectives, 7 workers) when Carnegie Steel Company's manager Henry Clay Frick sent in Pinkertons to break the Homestead Strike. Labor strife continued into the years of the Great Depression, as workers sought to protect their jobs and improve working conditions. Unions organized H.J. Heinz workers, with the assistance of the Catholic Radical Alliance.%0a%0a%0a!!%25center%25''Carnegie.''%0a%0aAndrew Carnegie, an immigrant from Scotland, a former Pennsylvania Railroad executive turned steel magnate, founded the Carnegie Steel Company. He proceeded to play a key role in the development of the U.S. steel industry. He became a philanthropist: in 1890, he established the first Carnegie Library, in a program to establish libraries in numerous cities and towns by the incentive of matching funds. In 1895, he founded the Carnegie Institute. In 1901, as the U.S. Steel Corporation formed, he sold his mills to J.P. Morgan for $250 million, making him one of the world's richest men. Carnegie once wrote that a man who dies rich, dies disgraced. He devoted the rest of his life to public service, establishing libraries, trusts, and foundations. In Pittsburgh, he founded the Carnegie Institute of Technology (now Carnegie Mellon University) and the Carnegie Museums of Pittsburgh.%0a%0aThe third (and present) Allegheny County Courthouse and Jail was completed in 1886. In 1890, trolleys began operations. In 1907, Pittsburgh annexed Allegheny City, which is now known as the North Shore.%0a%0a%0a!%25center%25'''Early 20th century'''%0a%0aBy 1911, Pittsburgh had grown into an industrial and commercial powerhouse:%0a%0aNexus of a vast railway system, with freight yards capable of handling 60K cars%0a27.2 miles (43.8 km) of harbor%0aYearly river traffic in excess of 9M tons%0aValue of factory products more than $211M (with Allegheny City)%0aAllegheny county produced, as percentage of national output, about:%0a24%25 of the pig iron%0a34%25 of the Bessemer steel%0a44%25 of the open hearth steel%0a53%25 of the crucible steel%0a24%25 of the steel rails%0a59%25 of the structural shapes%0a%0a!!%25center%25''Prohibition''%0a%0aDuring the Prohibition era, 1920 to 1933, Pittsburgh was a hotbed of bootlegging and illicit alcohol consumption. Several factors fed into resistance to Prohibition, including a large immigrant population, anti-establishment animosity dating to the Whiskey Rebellion, fragmented local government, and pervasive corruption. The Pittsburgh crime family controlled significant portions of the illegal alcohol trade.%0a%0aDuring that time, Prohibition Administrator John Pennington and his federal agents engaged in 15,000 raids, arrested over 18,000 people and closed down over 3,000 distilleries, 16 regular breweries, and 400 'wildcat' breweries. Even the term "Speakeasy," meaning an illegal drinking establishment, is said to have been coined at the Blind Pig in nearby McKeesport, Pennsylvania.%0a%0aThe last distillery in Pittsburgh, Joseph S. Finch's distillery, located at South Second and McKean streets, closed in the 1920s. In 2012, Wigle Whiskey opened, becoming the first since the closure of Finch's distillery.%0a%0aThe Pittsburgh Post-Gazette produced a large web feature on this period in the city's history.%0a%0a!!%25center%25''Environment''%0a%0aDuring the late 19th century, city leaders debated the responsibility and expense of creating a waterworks system and disposal of sewage. Downstream users complained about Pittsburgh's dumping of sewage into the Ohio River. Allegheny County cities did not stop discharging raw sewage into rivers until 1939. Pittsburgh's smoke pollution, seen in the 1890s as a sign of prosperity, was recognized as a problem in the Progressive Era and was cleared up in the 1930s-1940s. Steel plants deposited mountains of slag until 1972, especially in Nine Mile Run Valley.%0a%0aIn November 1927, 28 people were killed and hundreds were wounded in an explosion of a gas tank.%0a%0aTo escape the soot of the city, many of the wealthy lived in the Shadyside and East End neighborhoods, a few miles east of downtown. Fifth Avenue was dubbed "Millionaire's Row" because of the many mansions lining the street.%0a%0aOn March 17 and 18, 1936, Pittsburgh suffered the worst flood in its history, with flood levels peaking at 46 feet. This catastrophe killed 69 victims, destroyed thousands of buildings, caused $3B (2006 dollars) in damages, and put more than 60,000 steelworkers out of work.%0a%0a!!%25center%25''High culture''%0a%0aOakland became the city's predominant cultural and educational center, including three universities, multiple museums, a library, a music hall, and a botanical conservatory. Oakland's University of Pittsburgh erected what today is still the world's fourth-tallest educational building, the 42-story Cathedral of Learning. It towered over Forbes Field, where the Pittsburgh Pirates played from 1909 to 1970.%0a%0a!!%25center%25''New immigrants and migrants''%0a%0aBetween 1870 and 1920, the population of Pittsburgh grew almost sevenfold, with a large number of European immigrants arriving to the city. New arrivals continue to come from Britain, Ireland, and Germany, but the most popular sources after 1870 were poor rural areas in southern and eastern Europe, including Italy, the Balkans, the Austro-Hungarian Empire, and the Russian Empire. Unskilled immigrants found jobs in construction, mining, steel mills and factories. They introduced new traditions, languages, and cultures to the city, creating a diversified society as a result. Ethnic neighborhoods developed in working-class areas and were built on densely populated hillsides and valleys, such as South Side, Polish Hill, Bloomfield, and Squirrel Hill, home to 28%25 of the city's almost 21,000 Jewish households. The Strip District, the city's produce distribution center, still boasts many restaurants and clubs that showcase these multicultural traditions of Pittsburghers.%0a%0a!!%25center%25''African Americans''%0a%0aThe years 1916-1940 marked the largest migration of African Americans to Pittsburgh during the Great Migration from the rural South to industrial cities of the Northeast and Midwest. These migrants came for industrial jobs, education, political and social freedom, and to escape racial oppression and violence in the South. Migrants going to Pittsburgh and surrounding mill towns faced racial discrimination and restricted housing and job opportunities. The black population in Pittsburgh jumped from 6,000 in 1880 to 27,000 in 1910. Many took highly paid, skilled jobs in the steel mills. Pittsburgh's black population increased to 37,700 in 1920 (6.4%25 of the total) while the black element in Homestead, Rankin, Braddock, and others nearly doubled. They succeeded in building effective community responses that enabled the survival of new communities. Historian Joe Trotter explains the decision process:%0a%0aAlthough African-Americans often expressed their views of the Great Migration in biblical terms and received encouragement from northern black newspapers, railroad companies, and industrial labor agents, they also drew upon family and friendship networks to help in the move to Western Pennsylvania. They formed migration clubs, pooled their money, bought tickets at reduced rates, and often moved ingroups. Before they made the decision to move, they gathered information and debated the pros and cons of the process....In barbershops, poolrooms, and grocery stores, in churches, lodge halls, and clubhouses, and in private homes, southern blacks discussed, debated, and decided what was good and what was bad about moving to the urban North.%0aThe newly established Black communities nearly all endured, apart from Johnstown where blacks were expelled in 1923. Joe Trotter explains how the Blacks built new institutions for their new communities in the Pittsburgh area:%0a%0aBlack churches, fraternal orders, and newspapers (especially the Pittsburgh Courier); organizations such as the NAACP, Urban League, and Garvey Movement; social clubs, restaurants, and baseball teams; hotels, beauty shops, barber shops, and taverns, all proliferated.%0aThe cultural nucleus of Black Pittsburgh was Wylie Avenue in the Hill District. It became an important jazz mecca because jazz greats such as Duke Ellington and Pittsburgh natives Billy Strayhorn and Earl Hines played there. Two of the Negro League's greatest baseball rivals, the Pittsburgh Crawfords and the Homestead Grays, often competed in the Hill District. The teams dominated the Negro National League in the 1930s and 1940s.%0a%0a!!%25center%25''1930s''%0a%0aPittsburgh was a Republican stronghold starting in the 1880s, and the Republican governments provided jobs and assistance for the new immigrants in return for their votes. But the Great Depression starting in 1929 ruined the GOP in the city. The Democratic victory of 1932 meant an end to Republican patronage jobs and assistance. As the Depression worsened, Pittsburgh ethnics voted heavily for the Democrats, especially in 1934, making the city a stronghold of the New Deal Coalition. By 1936, Democratic programs for relief and jobs, especially the WPA, were so popular with the ethnics that a large majority voted for the Democrats.%0a%0aJoseph Guffey, statewide leader of the Democrats, and his local lieutenant David Lawrence gained control of all federal patronage in Pittsburgh after Roosevelt's landslide victory in 1932 and the election of a Democratic mayor in 1933. Guffey and Lawrence used the New Deal programs to increase their political power and build up a Democratic machine that superseded the decaying Republican machine. Guffey acknowledged that a high rate of people on relief was not only "a challenge" but also "an opportunity." He regarded each relief job as Democratic patronage.%0a%0a!!%25center%25''1940s''%0a%0aPittsburgh was at the center of the "Arsenal of Democracy" that provided steel, aluminum, munitions and machinery for the U.S. during World War II. Pittsburgh's mills contributed 95 million tons of steel to the war effort. The increased production output created a workforce shortage, which resulted in African Americans moving en masse during the Second Great Migration from the South to the city in order to find work.%0a%0a!!%25center%25''Postwar''%0a%0aDavid Lawrence, a Democrat, served as mayor of Pittsburgh from 1946 to 1959 and as Pennsylvania's governor from 1959 to 1963. Lawrence used his political power to transform Pittsburgh's political machine into a modern governmental unit that could run the city well and honestly. In 1946 Lawrence decided to enforce the Smoke Control Ordinance of 1941 because he believed smoke abatement was crucial for the city's future economic development. However, enforcement placed a substantial burden on the city's working-class because smoky bituminous coal was much less expensive than smokeless fuels. One round of protests came from Italian-American organizations, which called for delay in enforcing it. Enforcement raised their cost of living and threatened the jobs of their relatives in nearby bituminous coal mines. Despite dislike of the smoke abatement program, Italian Americans strongly supported the reelection of Lawrence in 1949, in part because many of them were on the city payroll.%0a%0a!%25center%25'''Renaissance I (1946 to 1973)'''%0a%0aRich and productive, Pittsburgh was also the "Smoky City," with smog sometimes so thick that streetlights burned during the day as well as rivers that resembled open sewers. Civic leaders, notably Mayor David L. Lawrence, elected in 1945, Richard K. Mellon, chairman of Mellon Bank and John P. Robin began smoke control and urban revitalization, also known as Urban Renewal projects that transformed the city in unforeseen ways.%0a%0a"Renaissance I" began in 1946. Title One of the Housing Act of 1949 provided the means in which to begin. By 1950, vast swaths of buildings and land near the Point were demolished for Gateway Center. 1953 saw the opening of the (since demolished) Greater Pittsburgh Municipal Airport terminal.%0a%0aIn the late 1950s and early 1960s, the lower Hill District, an area inhabited predominantly by people of African descent, was completely destroyed. Ninety-five acres of the lower Hill District were cleared using eminent domain, forcibly displacing hundreds of small businesses and more than 8,000 people (1,239 black families, 312 white), to make room for a cultural center that included the Civic Arena, which opened in 1961. Other than one apartment building, none of the other buildings planned for the cultural center were ever built.%0a%0aIn the early 1960s, the neighborhood of East Liberty was also included in Renaissance I Urban Renewal plans, with over 125 acres of the neighborhood being demolished and replaced with garden apartments, three 20-story public housing apartments, and a convoluted road-way system that circled a pedestrianized shopping district. In the span of just a few years during the mid-1960s, East Liberty became a blighted neighborhood. There were some 575 businesses in East Liberty in 1959, but only 292 in 1970, and just 98 in 1979.%0a%0aPreservation efforts by the Pittsburgh History and Landmarks Foundation, along with community neighborhood groups, resisted the demolition plans. The neighborhoods containing rich architectural heritage, including the Mexican War Streets, Allegheny West, and Manchester, were spared. The center of Allegheny City, with its culturally and socially important buildings, was not as lucky. All of the buildings, with the exception of the Old U.S. Post Office, the Carnegie Library, and Buhl Planetarium were destroyed and replaced with the "pedestrianized" Allegheny Center Mall and apartments.%0a%0aThe city's industrial base continued to grow in the post-war era partly assisted by the area's first agency entirely devoted to industrial development, the RIDC. Jones and Laughlin Steel Company expanded its plant on the Southside. H.J. Heinz, Pittsburgh Plate Glass, Alcoa, Westinghouse, U.S. Steel and its new division, the Pittsburgh Chemical Company and many other companies also continued robust operations through the 1960s. 1970 marked the completion of the final building projects of Renaissance I: the U.S. Steel Tower and Three Rivers Stadium. In 1974, with the addition of the fountain at the tip of the Golden Triangle, Point State Park was completed. Although air quality was dramatically improved, and Pittsburgh's manufacturing base seemed solid, questions abound about the negative effects Urban Renewal continues to have on the social fabric of Pittsburgh. Pittsburgh, however, was about to undergo one of its most dramatic transformations.%0a%0aLike most major cities, Pittsburgh experienced several days of rioting following the assassination of Martin Luther King Jr. in April 1968. There were no further major riots, although tension remained high in the inner-city black neighborhoods.%0a%0a%0a!%25center%25'''Reinvention (1973 to present)'''%0a!!%25center%25''Collapse of steel''%0a%0aFree market pressures exposed the U.S. steel industry's own internal problems, which included a now-outdated manufacturing base that had been over-expanded in the 1950s and 1960s, hostile management and labor relationships, the inflexibility of United Steelworkers regarding wage cuts and work-rule reforms, oligarchic management styles, and poor strategic planning by both unions and management. In particular, Pittsburgh faced its own challenges. Local coke and iron ore deposits were depleted, raising material costs. The large mills in the Pittsburgh region also faced competition from newer, more profitable "mini-mills" and non-union mills with lower labor costs.%0a%0aBeginning in the late 1970s and early 1980s, the steel industry in Pittsburgh began to implode along with the deindustrialization of the U.S. Following the 1981-1982 recession, for example, the mills laid off 153,000 workers. The steel mills began to shut down. These closures caused a ripple effect, as railroads, mines, and other factories across the region lost business and closed. The local economy suffered a depression, marked by high unemployment and underemployment, as laid-off workers took lower-paying, non-union jobs. Pittsburgh suffered as elsewhere in the Rust Belt with a declining population, and like many other U.S. cities, it also saw white flight to the suburbs.%0a%0aIn 1991 the Homestead Works was demolished, replaced in 1999 by The Waterfront shopping mall. As a direct result of the loss of mill employment, the number of people living in Homestead dwindled. By the time of the 2000 census, the borough population was 3,569. The borough began financially recovering in 2002, with the enlarging retail tax base.%0a%0a!!%25center%25''Corporations''%0a%0aTop corporate headquarters such as Gulf Oil (1985), Koppers (1987), Westinghouse (1996) and Rockwell International (1989) were bought out by larger firms, with the loss of high paying, white collar headquarters and research personnel (the "brain drain") as well as massive charitable contributions by the "home based" companies to local cultural and educational institutions. At the time of the Gulf Oil merger in 1985 it was the largest buyout in world history involving the company that was No. 7 on the Fortune 500 just six years earlier. Over 1,000 high paying white collar corporate and PhD research jobs were lost in one day.%0a%0aToday, there are no steel mills within the city limits of Pittsburgh, although manufacture continues at regional mills, such as the Edgar Thomson Works in nearby Braddock.%0a%0a!!%25center%25''Higher education''%0a%0aPittsburgh is home to three universities that are included in most under-graduate and graduate school national rankings, The University of Pittsburgh, Carnegie Mellon University and Duquesne University. Carnegie Mellon University and the University of Pittsburgh had evolved in the mid-20th century along lines that followed the needs of the heavy industries that financed and directed their development. The collapse of steel put pressure on those two universities to reinvent themselves as research centers in science and technology which acted to pull the regional economy toward high-technology fields. Other regional collegiate institutions include Robert Morris University, Chatham University, Carlow University, Point Park University, La Roche College, Pittsburgh Theological Seminary, Trinity School for Ministry (an Episcopal seminary) and the Community College of Allegheny County.%0a%0aBeginning in the 1980s, Pittsburgh's economy shifted from heavy industry to services, medicine, higher education, tourism, banking, corporate headquarters, and high technology. Today, the top two private employers in the city are the University of Pittsburgh Medical Center (26,000 employees) and the West Penn Allegheny Health System (13,000 employees).%0a%0a%0a!!%25center%25''Civic improvements''%0a%0aDespite the economic turmoil, civic improvements continued. In the mid-1970s, Arthur P. Ziegler, Jr. and the Pittsburgh History and Landmarks Foundation (Landmarks) wanted to demonstrate that historic preservation could be used to drive economic development without the use of eminent domain or public subsidies. Landmarks acquired the former terminal buildings and yards of the Pittsburgh and Lake Erie Railroad, a 1-mile  long property at the base of Mt. Washington facing the City of Pittsburgh. In 1976, Landmarks developed the site as a mixed-use historic adaptive reuse development that gave the foundation the opportunity to put its urban planning principles into practice. Aided by an initial generous gift from the Allegheny Foundation in 1976, Landmarks adapted five historic Pittsburgh and Lake Erie Railroad buildings for new uses and added a hotel, a dock for the Gateway Clipper fleet, and parking areas. Now shops, offices, restaurants, and entertainment anchor the historic riverfront site on the south shore of the Monongahela River, opposite the Golden Triangle (Pittsburgh). Station Square is Pittsburgh's premier attraction, generating over 3,500,000 visitors a year. It reflects a $100 million investment from all sources, with the lowest public cost and highest taxpayer return of any major renewal project in the Pittsburgh region since the 1950s. In 1994, Pittsburgh History and Landmarks Foundation sold Station Square in to Forest City Enterprises which created an endowment to help support its restoration efforts and educational programs. Each year the staff and docents of Pittsburgh History and Landmarks Foundation introduce more than 10,000 people - teachers, students, adults, and visitors - to the architectural heritage of the Pittsburgh region and to the value of historic preservation.%0a%0aDuring this period, Pittsburgh also became a national model for community development, through the work of activists such as Dorothy Mae Richardson, who founded Neighborhood Housing Services in 1968, an organization that became the model for the nationwide NeighborWorks America. Activists such a Richardson shared the aim of Landmarks to rehabilitate Pittsburgh's existing built landscape rather than to demolish and redevelop.%0a%0aIn 1985, the J & L Steel site on the north side of the Monongahela river was cleared and a publicly subsidized High Technology Center was built. The Pittsburgh Technology Center, home to many major technology companies, is planning major expansion in the area soon. In the 1980s, the "Renaissance II" urban revitalization created numerous new structures, such as PPG Place. In the 1990s, the former sites of the Homestead, Duquesne and South Side J&L mills were cleared. In 1992, the new terminal at Pittsburgh International Airport opened. In 2001, the aging Three Rivers Stadium was replaced by Heinz Field and PNC Park, despite being rejected by voter referendum. In 2010, PPG Paints Arena, replaced the Civic Arena, which at the time was the oldest arena in the National Hockey League.%0a%0aAlso in 1985, Al Michaels revealed to a national TV audience how Pittsburgh had transformed itself from an industrial rust belt city.%0a%0a%0a!%25center%25'''Pittsburgh today'''%0a%0aPresent-day Pittsburgh, with a diversified economy, a low cost of living, and a rich infrastructure for education and culture, has been ranked as one of the World's Most Livable Cities. Tourism has recently boomed in Pittsburgh with nearly 3,000 new hotel rooms opening since 2004 and holding a consistently higher occupancy than in comparable cities. Meanwhile, tech giants such as: Apple, Google, IBM Watson, Facebook, and Intel have joined the 1,600 technology firms choosing to operate out of Pittsburgh. As a result of the proximity to CMU's National Robotics Engineering Center (NREC), there has a boom of autonomous vehicles companies. The region has also become a leader in green environmental design, a movement exemplified by the city's convention center. In the last twenty years the region has seen a small but influential group of Asian immigrants, including from the Indian sub-continent.%0a%0a%0a%0a%25right%25[[#top|&#8593; back to top]]%0a%0a%0a!%25center%25'''City Time Line'''%0a%0a%25center%25'''History of Pittsburgh Pennsylvania'''%0a!!1700's%0a%0a'''1717'''%0a*Michael Bezallion, Pennsylvania fur trader, passed the future site of Pittsburgh en route from the Illinois country to Philadelphia, where he made a report of the trip.%0a%0a*White traders began to establish trading posts in the territory of the Ohio, Allegheny, and Monongahela valleys. The largest settlement was Logstown (now Ambridge), about four miles north of the fork of the Ohio.%0a%0a'''1748'''%0a*Conrad Weiser (1696-1760), the German, who for thirty years was prominent in Pennsylvania's negotiations with the Indians, was the guest of the Delaware Indian Chief Shannopin at the mouth of Two Mile Run (the present Lawrenceville section of Pittsburgh).%0a%0a'''1749'''%0a*August 7, Celoron de Blainville (1693-1759), with 43 French soldiers, 180 Canadians, and a band of Indians, floated past the site of Pittsburgh, once more claiming possession of the Ohio Valley for King Louis XV of France. Chaplain Father Bonnecamps kept a journal and made a map of the trip.%0a%0a'''1751'''%0a*May, Philippe Thomas Joncaire, with a troop of Indians, passed by en route to Logstown to establish a French trading house there.%0a%0a'''1752'''%0a*May 28, Joshua Fry, James Patton, and Lunsford Lomax, Virginia agents chosen to treat with the Indians at Logstown, held a conference with Chief Shannopin.%0a%0a'''1753'''%0a*November 23,  The 21-year old Major George Washington (1732-99), emissary from Virginia's Governor Robert Dinwiddie to the French commandant at Fort LeBoeuf on French Creek (now Waterford, Pa.), observed the land at the junction of the Allegheny and Monongahela rivers (where Pittsburgh is today) and described it as "extremely well situated for a Fort; as it has the absolute Command of both Rivers. The Land at the Point is 20 or 25 Feet above the common Surface of the Water; and a considerable Bottom of flat, well timbere%0a%0a*December 30, George Washington and his guide, Christopher Gist, were stranded on Garrison Island in the Allegheny River after their raft had been dashed to pieces by floating ice.%0a%0a'''1754'''%0a*February 17, William Trent (1715-87), the Indian trader, came to the forks. When the militiamen whom he had enlisted in the Monongahela Valley arrived, Trent began to build a fort and named it Fort Prince George.%0a%0a*April 13, Ensign Edward Ward, temporarily in charge of Fort Prince George, learned that French troops were on the march against him.%0a%0a*April 17, When the French force of about 500 men, under Commandant Pierre de Contreoeur, arrived at the forks, Ensign Ward and his 41 men had to surrender their building. The French began to build a large fort on the spot and named it Fort Duquesne, after the Marquis de Duquesne (1700-78), governor general of New France from 1752 to 1755.%0a%0a*July 4, The French subdued Colonel Washington at Fort Necessity.%0a%0a*July 28, The Scotsman Robert Stobo, a friend of Governor Dinwiddie, was one of two hostages taken to Fort Duquesne after the battle at Fort Necessity. During his imprisonment he sent out letters and a sketch of the fort to the English.%0a%0a'''1755'''%0a*May 24, The French commandant announced that Fort Duquesne was completed.%0a%0a*July 9, A British expedition under General Edward Braddock, marching to attack Fort Duquesne, was defeated not far from the fort by an army of French and Indian warriors. Some of the English captives were burned alive by the Indians.%0a%0a'''1756'''%0aSpring Fort Duquesne was damaged by a flood.%0a%0a'''1758'''%0a*August 30, The French commandant at Fort Duquesne learned that a British force led by General John Forbes was at Loyalbanna (the present Ligonier) and was planning to advance against the fort.%0a%0a*September 14, Major James Grant, with Forbes's army, received permission to attack Fort Duquesne. He led his force of 800 into disaster; one third of his men were killed.%0a%0a*November 24, General Forbes's army took possession of the remnants of Fort Duquesne, which the French had burned and evacuated earlier in the day.%0a%0a*November 25, The English flag flew over the ruins of the demolished Fort Duquesne.%0a%0a*November 26, Five thousand soldiers knelt near the fort in observance of Thanksgiving.%0a%0a*November 29, A detachment of soldiers who had been with Major Grant on his fateful attack in September, buried the bodies of their dead comrades.%0a%0a*November 29, ...the camp at Fort Duquesne was referred to as Fort Argyle.%0a%0a*December 1, General Forbes formally named the camp Pittsburgh. On January 21 the following year, writing from Philadelphia, the general told William Pitt, the English prime minister, that he had "used the freedom of giving your name to Fort Duquesne, as - - - it was in some measure the being activated by your spirits that now makes us Masters of the place."%0a%0a*December 4, Indian chiefs, at a conference in the fort, promised peace to Colonel Henry Bouquet (1719-65), the Swiss soldier who accompanied General Forbes. They also promised the return of all English captives.%0a%0a'''1759'''%0a*January 9, Temporary barracks, about a thousand feet from the site of Fort Duquesne, had been built; General Forbes authorized a payment of 124/13/2 for the work.%0a%0a*March 1, The building of a permanent fort -- Fort Pitt -- had begun under the direction of a new commanding officer, General John Stanwix, and engineer Harry Gordon.%0a%0a*October 24, General Stanwix made a treaty of peace and friendship with the Indians.%0a%0a*October 29, Adam Stephen, a lieutenant colonel in the Virginia regiment who survived Grant's defeat, complained that the Pennsylvania Indian traders were taking over the lucrative fur trade and that the Indians had brought 20 tons of skins and furs to Fort Pitt in the previous three months.%0a%0a''1760''%0a*July, Colonel James Burd counted the population of Pittsburgh; he found that 149 people, besides the soldiers, were living there.%0a%0a*August 12, General Robert Monckton, in command at Fort Pitt, reaffirmed Stanwix's treaty with the Indians.%0a%0a*August 12, James Boggs, Allegheny's first white settler, built his cabin.%0a%0a'''1761'''%0a*March, Lieutenant Bernard Ratzer drew up a plan for the British military reservation which included 40 acres of vegetable and flower gardens and the "King's Orchard" of apple and pear trees in the area between Fort Pitt and the Allegheny River.%0a%0a*April 14, According to a count ordered by Colonel Bouquet, Pittsburgh's population consisted of 163 men, 45 women, and 25 children, who lived in 160 houses outside the fort.%0a%0a*October 12, George Croghan, an Irishman who came to America in 1741, was the most prominent of the Pennsylvania traders. As Indian agent at Fort Pitt, he noted that the Indians had returned 338 white captives to the fort since June 1759.%0a%0a*December, Fort Pitt, surrounded by moats drawing water from the Allegheny River, was completed. Its cost was estimated between 60,000 and 100,000.%0a%0a'''1762'''%0a*January 9, The Allegheny, Monongahela, and Ohio rivers, reaching a stage of 39.2 feet at the Point, badly damaged the fort. All but 13 barrels of powder were destroyed.%0a%0a*May 2, The Indian Chief Delaware George a faithful friend of the British, was buried with full military honors on the north side of the Allegheny River opposite Fort Pitt.%0a%0a'''1763'''%0a*March 9, When the rivers rose to 41 feet at the Point, Fort Pitt was inundated by six inches of water.%0a%0a*March 30, Pontiac's uprising against the whites brought all the inhabitants from the outside within the confines of Fort Pitt. Most of the surrounding homes were demolished.%0a%0a*June 3, Those houses which had not been destroyed were burned by the Indians.%0a%0a*August 11, Colonel Bouquet's army defeated the Indians at the Battle of Bushy Run on August 5 and 6, thus the siege of Fort Pitt had come to an end. The people, who had taken shelter in the fort, returned to the places where they once lived and set out to build new cabins.%0a%0a'''1764'''%0a*October 3, Bouquet's army forced the Delaware and Shawnee Indians to fulfill their agreement and bring all their English captives to the fort.%0a%0a*November 15, The Indians brought 60 captives to Fort Pitt%0a%0a*November 15, Colonel Bouquet's Redoubt -- the Blockhouse, which is still in existence -- was built outside the walls of the fort, midway between the Ohio and Monongahela bastions.%0a%0a*November 15, John Campbell made a plan for the town, consisting of four blocks between Water and Second streets and Ferry and Market Streets, with an alley, Chancery Lane, between Ferry and Market.%0a%0a*November 15, Richard and William Butler's log cabins were the first to be completed after the lifting of the siege.%0a%0a'''1766'''%0a*March, Baynton, Wharton, and Morgan, the well-known Philadelphia trading firm, erected a storehouse, the first shingle-roofed building in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a'''1768'''%0a*April, Conferences between the Indians and the British were held at Fort Pitt; 1103 male Indians came with their retinue of wives and children.%0a%0a'''1769'''%0a*The Penn's Pittsburgh Manor, some of it within the present Golden Triangle area, was surveyed and found to include 5766 acres.%0a%0a'''1770'''%0a*October, George Washington arrived for a visit in Pittsburgh. He noted in his diary: "We lodged in what is called the Town, distant about 300 yards from the Fort, at one Mr. Semples, who keeps a very good house of entertainment."%0a%0a%0a'''1772'''%0a*October 12, Captain Charles Edmonstone of the Eighteenth Royal Regiment, in command at Fort Pitt, sold the installation to William Thompson and Alexander Ross for 50 pounds New York currency. Thus ended the Crowns jurisdiction over the military reservation and fort at Pittsburgh.%0a%0a'''1773'''%0a*John Ormsby was granted the right to keep the first licensed ferry across the Monongahela River.%0a%0a*Pennsylvania obtained permission from Great Britain to garrison militia at Fort Pitt.%0a%0a'''1774'''%0a*January 6, The unsettled boundary between Pennsylvania and Virginia became hotly contested when Dr. John Connolly posted a proclamation on the walls of Fort Pitt to announce his appointment by Lord Dunmore, governor of the southern colony, as "Captain, Commandant of the Militia of Pittsburgh and its Dependencies." He ordered the people to assemble as a militia on January 25.%0a%0a*January 24, Pennsylvania challenged Virginia's claim to Pittsburgh by arresting Dr. Connolly and removing him to Hannastown to stand trial.%0a%0a*February 2, By promising to return in April for trial, Dr. Connolly persuaded the sheriff of Westmoreland County to release him. He then obtained a commission as justice of the peace from the court of Augusta County, Virginia, which was held to include Pittsburgh, and returned to the forks, took possession of Fort Pitt, and organized his militia.%0a%0a*April 25, Governor Dunmore ordered all the inhabitants "to pay their quit-rents and all public dues" to officers appointed by him.%0a%0a%0a'''1775'''%0a*February 21, Dr. Connolly changed the name of Fort Pitt to Fort Dunmore. The Augusta County Court, which had been adjourned from Staunton, Virginia, on December 6, 1774, was organized at the Fort.%0a%0a*February 23, Jacob Bausman was licensed by the Virginia Court to keep a ferry over the Monongahela at the foot of Wood Street where John Ormsby had his establishment for the previous two years.%0a%0a*March, Governor Dunmore advised Dr. Connolly to disband his militia and devote himself to winning the support of the Indians for the British cause.%0a%0a*May 16, In a convention held at Pittsburgh, frontiersmen of the territory set up a Committee of Safety approved the action of the colonies in their revolt against the Crown, and resolved that it was the "indispensable duty of every American" to resist tyranny.%0a%0a*July 25, Dr. Connolly left for Virginia; Pennsylvania authority prevailed generally in the Pittsburgh area.%0a%0a*August, John Neville (1731-1803), with 100 militia, took possession of the fort.%0a%0a*August 25, A band of "patriots" burned the tea stock of the merchants Joseph Symonds and John Campbell.%0a%0a*October 7, By the Treaty of Pittsburgh, the chiefs of the Indian tribes in the area pledged friendship and neutrality in the conflict between Great Britain and her colonies.%0a%0a%0a'''1776'''%0a*October, By a Second Treaty of Pittsburgh, the Indians confirmed their agreement of the year before.%0a%0a%0a'''1777'''%0a*June 1, Fort Pitt, once again bearing its proud name, became a United States fort when Brigadier General Edward Hand took it over from Captain John Neville.%0a%0a*August 20, The Virginia Court moved out of the fort.%0a%0a%0a'''1778'''%0a*June, David Rogers, with about 40 men, left Fort Pitt to bring a much-needed cargo of ammunition from New Orleans. His return was intercepted.%0a%0a%0a'''1779'''%0a*August 11, Colonel Daniel Brodhead left Fort Pitt with 600 men to destroy the Seneca Indian villages along the upper Allegheny River.%0a%0a%0a%0a'''1781'''%0a*Hugh Henry Brackenridge arrived from Philadelphia to practice law. He soon became an important civic and political leader in western Pennsylvania.%0a%0a%0a%0a'''1782'''%0a*The German Evangelical Protestant (Congregational) Church, the first organized religious group in Pittsburgh, held services in a small block-house at the corner of present Wood and Diamond streets. Reverend John William Weber was pastor.%0a%0a%0a'''1784'''%0a*June, In the first real estate sale on record, Isaac Craig and Samuel Bayard purchased three acres of land lying between Fort Pitt and the Allegheny River.%0a%0a*June, Bouquet's Redoubt-the Blockhouse was converted into a dwelling and continued as such until April 1, 1894.%0a%0a*June, The Penns' Pittsburgh Manor was laid out in lots by George Woods and Thomas Vickroy. The manor embraced the tongue of land between the two rivers as far as present Grant Street and Eleventh.%0a%0a%0a'''1785'''%0a*August 15, The Supreme Executive Council of Pennsylvania ordered John Ormsby to "take possession of Fort Pitt in behalf of the Commonwealth, upon its being relinquished" by the United States.%0a%0a*August 15, Lodge No. 45, Ancient Order of York Masons, was organized.%0a%0a%0a'''1786'''%0a*February 28, The State Legislature granted a charter for the Pittsburgh Academy "for the education of youth in useful arts, sciences and literature." Judge Hugh Henry Brackenridge was prime organizer.%0a%0a*July 29, The Pittsburgh Gazette, first newspaper west of the Allegheny Mountains, was published as a weekly by John Scull and Joseph Hall, printers.%0a%0a*July 29, In the columns of the newly launched gazette, Hugh H. Brackenridge wrote that, at the junction of the three rivers in the morning, "a light fog is usually incumbent." But, he observed, "in as much as it consists of vapor. . . Which the sun of the preceding day had extracted from trees and flowers and in the evening had sent back into dew it is experienced to be healthful."%0a%0a*July 29, Niles Weekly Register reported that "36 log houses, one stone house, one frame house, and five small stores" extended along Chancery Lane and Market Street.%0a%0a*September 24, The Penns donated two and one half lots each to the First Presbyterian, the German Evangelical Protestant, and the Trinity Protestant Episcopal churches.%0a%0a*September 29, The First Presbyterian Church was incorporated by an act of the Legislature.%0a%0a*September 29, David Redick was appointed by the Supreme Executive Council to lay Out the "Town Common and lots in the reserve tract opposite Pittsburgh." The reserved tract had been authorized by the Legislature in September 1787.%0a%0a*September 29, The first market house was erected.%0a%0a%0a'''1788'''%0a*September 24, Mainly through efforts of Hugh H. Brackenridge, lawyer and state assemblyman, Allegheny County was created out of parts of Westmoreland and Washington counties; Pittsburgh was decreed the county seat.%0a%0a*November 19, Lots in the reserved tract were sold at public sale in Philadelphia.%0a%0a*December 16, The first Quarter Sessions Court of Allegheny County convened in Pittsburgh at Andrew Watson's tavern.%0a%0a*December 16, Regular mail service to Philadelphia was inaugurated.%0a%0a*December 16, A Mechanical Society, devoted to the betterment of the workingman, was organized.%0a%0a%0a'''1789'''%0a*March 14, The first Court of Common Pleas convened in Andrew Watson s tavern.%0a%0a*July 2, The gazette reported: "Yesterday was brought to this place and buried, the bodies of two young men, named Arthur Graham and Alexander Campbell, who had gone out to fish. They were killed by the savages about two miles from this place."%0a%0a*July 2, Captain Thomas Hutchins, geographer of the United States, died at John Ormsby's.%0a%0a%0a'''1790'''%0a*April, Army garrison officers gave a theatrical presentation -- Cato and All the 'World's a Stage.%0a%0a'''1791'''%0a*February, Isaac Craig was appointed quartermaster general and was given permission to repair Fort Pitt.%0a%0a*September 6, Robert Johnson, the revenue collector, was tarred and feathered by angered citizens.%0a%0a*November, An army hospital was established "in a rented house in the town," with Dr. Carmichael in charge. Samuel Slater started a cotton mill with a staff of nine children from seven to twelve years of age.%0a%0a%0a'''1792'''%0a*May 1, Captain Hughes, in command of the army garrison at Fort Pitt, occupied Fort Fayette (LaFayette), just completed near the Allegheny close to the old bastion.  General Anthony Wayne and his army arrived in town.%0a%0a'''1793'''%0aSeptember 12, %0aThe city's first fire engine was purchased at a cost of 1200, and the Eagle Fire Engine and Hose Company, the first to be organized in the town, was formed with headquarters at First Street (Avenue) between Market and Ferry.%0a%0a*October 14, Regular river packet service was inaugurated by Jacob Myers between Pittsburgh and Cincinnati.%0a%0a*October 14, Modern Chivalry, volume three, a novel by Hugh Henry Brackenridge. was printed by John Scull. It was the first book printed west of the Allegheny Mountains.%0a%0a*October 14, George Anshutz built a small furnace in Two Mile Run (present Shadyside). One of its first tasks was to manufacture cannon balls for General Anthony Wayne's army.%0a%0a%0a'''1794'''%0a*April 22, Pittsburgh was incorporated as a borough.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 19, 1794%0aGeorge Robinson and Josiah Tannehill were chosen chief burgesses in the first borough election.%0a%0a*August, Farmers who protested against the collection of excise tax on whisky marched to Pittsburgh from their rendezvous at Braddock's Field.%0a%0a*November 12, Burgess George Robinson and three other Pittsburghers were among 18 southwestern Pennsylvanians arrested by General Irvine's troops during the "dreadful night" of the Whisky Insurrection.%0a%0a%0a%0a1795%0aFirst glass factory was built by Major Isaac Craig and General O'Hara on the north bank of the Ohio River across from the Point. It manufactured bottles.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 18, 1795%0aWeekly mail service was established between Pittsburgh and Philadelphia.%0a%0a%0a%0a1796%0aA census of Pittsburgh showed a population of 1300.%0a%0a%0a%0a1796%0aThe first Methodist Episcopal Church service was held in the "unoccupied meeting house" of the Presbyterians.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 28, 1797%0aRed Pole, great Shawnee Indian chief, died at Pittsburgh and was buried in Trinity churchyard.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 5, 1797%0aNotice of July 8 advertised the sale of all building material remaining on the site of the abandoned Fort Pitt.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 19, 1798%0aThe ship President Adams was launched at nearby Elizabeth; it was built in Pittsburgh and armed for service against the Spaniards on the lower Mississippi. The Senator Ross was built in Pittsburgh the same year. Glass was blown at O'Hara's Glass-works, the first flint glass made west of the Alleghenies.%0a%0a%0a%0a1799%0aThe first courthouse, a two-story brick structure, was completed. It stood on the western half of the Diamond. County, state, and federal courts convened here until 1841.%0a%0a%0a%0a1799%0aReformed Presbyterian Church was organized.%0a%0a1800's %0a%0a%0a1800%0aZadok Cramer, a New Jersey printer, purchased Gilkinson's Book Store, renamed it the Sign of the Franklin Head, began a printing and book-binding business, and printed his first Almanack.%0a%0a%0a%0a1800%0aPittsburgh commercial life revolved around 63 shops, 23 of them general stores, six shoe shops, four bakeries, and four hat shops.%0a%0a%0a%0a1800%0aPopulation: 1565; Allegheny County, 15,087.%0a%0a%0a%0a1800%0aPerkins store, first "department store" west of Philadelphia, was opened.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 16, 1800%0aThe city's second news-paper, Tree of Liberty, was published by John Israel, with Hugh Henry Brackenridge as chief backer and chief editorial writer.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 24, 1801%0aThe associate Presbyterian Church was organized. Zadok Cramer printed the first edition of the Navigator. a guide to river navigation.%0a%0a%0a%0a1802%0aJeffery Scaife Tin and Japanned Ware Manufactory, parent organization of the William B. Scaife & Sons Company began business in the Diamond.%0a%0a%0a%0a1802%0aPittsburgh Almanack stated that industry in Pittsburgh included one large brewery, two glassworks, one fine-glass factory, one large paper mill, several oil mills, powder works, ironworks, saltworks, saw - and grist - mills, and a boat yard.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 9, 1802%0aThe Borough Council ordered four public wells to be sunk on Market Street -- the beginning of Pittsburgh's water system.%0a%0a%0a%0a1803%0aThe Pittsburgh Almanack for the Year 1803 estimated the total value of Pittsburgh manufacturing at $358,903. Of that amount, iron manufacturing accounted for $56,548 from the production of 180 tons of castings and bar iron and 40 tons of nails. Textile manufacturing was second in value with $46,825.%0a%0a%0a%0a1803%0aThe rivers were beginning to be used for the shipment of coal from Pittsburgh to Philadelphia via New Orleans.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 26, 1803%0aIn the first theatrical production in the city, the Bromly and Arnold traveling troupe of actors presented a tragedy, The gamester, at the courthouse.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 26, 1803%0aA public meeting was held to consider a proposal for a bank in the borough.%0a%0a%0a%0a1804%0aA newly established stagecoach line was offering "speedy" six-day service between Pittsburgh and Philadelphia. Peter Eltonhead, an Englishman, founded the first large-scale cotton mill.%0a%0a%0a%0a1804%0aGeneral Presley Neville, burgess of Pittsburgh, asked George Stevenson, president of the Council, to study smoke problems and, in particular, the possibility of higher chimneys as a smoke-control measure. His letter stated that "not only the comfort, health and, in some measure, the con-sequence of the place, but the harmony of the inhabitants, depends upon speedy measures being adopted to remedy this nuisance."%0a%0a%0a%0a1804%0aThe Pittsburgh Foundry (predecessor of Mackintosh-Hemphill Company), first in the city, was established at Fifth and Smithfield by Joseph McClurg.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 9, 1804%0aPittsburghs first bank, a branch of the Bank of Pennsylvania at Philadelphia, opened for business at a location on Second Street, between Market and Ferry.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember, 1804%0aIn the first recorded strike in Pittsburgh, traveling journeymen shoemakers "made a turnout for higher wages."%0a%0a%0a%0a1805%0aCommonwealth, a weekly newspaper, began publication.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 1, 1805%0aCornerstone was laid for the Old Round Church of St. Luke's Protestant Episcopal Congregation. Its charter was granted on September 1.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 21, 1806%0aThe United States gazette for the Country, at Philadelphia, published a letter from a Pittsburgh correspondent reporting: "On Wednesday last (the 8th inst.) a duel was fought in the vicinity of Pitts-burgh between Tarleton Bates, Esq., the prothonotary of Allegheny County, and a person of the name of Stewart, a storekeeper here, in which Mr. Bates was killed at the second fireThe minds of the people of Pittsburgh appear much inflamed."%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary, 1806%0aThe first company prepared to build a turnpike from Pittsburgh to Harrisburg was incorporated.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 10, 1806%0aA flood of 37.1 feet was recorded.%0a%0a%0a%0a1807%0aGeorge Robinson and Edward Ensel glassworks was in operation. Anthony Beelen established the Eagle foundry.%0a%0a%0a%0a1807%0aGeorge Miltenberger's Copper and Tinware Manufactory was established.%0a%0a%0a%0a1808%0aBakewell and Page purchased the Robinson and Ensel glassworks. In 1818 the firm furnished President Monroe "a complete set of flint glass, each piece engraved with the arms of the United States."%0a%0a%0a%0a1808%0aJames B. Scott and Company (Follansbee Steel Corporation) was founded by James Park.%0a%0a%0a%0a1809%0aPittsburgh Steam Flour Mill, the first west of the Alleghenies, was established by Oliver and Owen Evans.%0a%0a%0a%0a1810%0aBank of Pittsburgh, second in the borough and first with local capital, was organized and operated for a time under the name of Pittsburgh Manufacturing Company.%0a%0a%0a%0a1810%0aPopulation: 4786; Allegheny County, 25,317.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 9, 1810%0aThe city was inundated by a flood of 35.2 feet.%0a%0a%0a%0a1811%0aThe Reverend Francis Herron began a 49-year pastorate in the First Presbyterian Church.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 31, 1811%0aThe Vigilant Fire Company was organized.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 24, 1811%0aFirst Masonic Hall dedicated.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust, 1811%0aOld St. Patrick's Church, the city's first Roman Catholic church, was dedicated at Liberty and Washington streets.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 25, 1811%0aThe New Orleans, which was built at a cost of $40,000 by Nicholas Roosevelt, sailed down the Ohio to establish the first regular packet service between Natchez and New Orleans and thus became the first steamboat to navigate western rivers.%0a%0a%0a%0a1812%0aThe first rolling mill was built by Christopher Cowan.%0a%0a%0a%0a1812%0aRigging for Oliver H. Perry's fleet on Lake Erie was made in the borough. Steam-engine works, built by Oliver Evans and managed by Mark Stackhouse, went into operation in May.%0a%0a%0a%0a1812%0aChristopher Cowan built a steam mill for slitting iron.%0a%0a%0a%0a1812%0aElliott Nursery was established at Smithfield Street.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 7, 1812%0aWilliam Turner and Company opened what is believed to have been the city's first theater.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 10, 1812%0aThe Pittsburgh Blues, a military unit, left on a year's expedition in the Ohio Country, in the service of the United States.%0a%0a%0a%0a1813%0aThe Comet, a stern-wheel steamboat, was built.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 10, 1813%0aHumane Society was organized.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 27, 1813%0aFirst recorded meeting of the Pittsburgh Permanent Library Company.%0a%0a%0a%0a1814%0aA stern-wheel steamboat left Pittsburgh with a cargo of guns destined for General Jackson at New Orleans. Pepin, Brishard, and Cayetano conducted the first circus.%0a%0a%0a%0a1814%0aWestern Medical Society was organized%0a%0a%0a%0a1814%0aAllegheny Arsenal was established by the federal government. It was designed by B. H. Latrobe and built in the Lawrenceville district under the direction of Colonel Abraham R. Butler at a cost of $300,000.%0a%0a%0a%0a1814%0aAnchor Steam Paper Mill, first paper-mill in Pittsburgh, was built by Henry Holdehip.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 10, 1814%0aA letter printed in the gazette said: "Although much of the prosperity of Pittsburgh is owing to its 'Fires,' it is not be concealed that the effects of those fires have become subjects of complaint. That the evil (if it be an evil to be enveloped in smoke) is daily increasing and that relief is now universally called for."%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 23, 1814%0aBank of Pittsburgh was reorganized with capital of $600,000 and George Wilkins as president.%0a%0a%0a%0a1815%0aPittsburgh Directory for 1815, the city's first directory, was compiled and published by James M. Riddle.%0a%0a%0a%0a1815%0aThe Farmers and Mechanics Bank, founded by John Scull, was incorporated.%0a%0a%0a%0a1815%0aThe weekly Mercury began publication.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch, 1815%0aNewspapers advocated "some plan for smoke abatement."%0a%0a%0a%0a1816%0aWhale-oil lamps were installed as the city's first street lights.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 27, 1816%0aAccording to the gazette, Alexander Thompson, "who resides on the turnpike road 4~2 miles from Pittsburgh," reported that during 1815, excluding iron shipments, a total of "5,800 road waggons laden with merchandise, etc., passed his farm for Pittsburgh. The greater part of these waggons returned loaded with cordage, salt petre, etc., to the east of the mountains."%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary, 1816%0aFlood waters reached a stage of 36.2 feet.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 18, 1816%0aPittsburgh was incorporated as a city under an act providing for a mayor, one select and one common council, 12 aldermen, and a recorder.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 9, 1816%0aEbenezer Denny, merchant, began serving term as the first mayor of Pittsburgh; James Ross as first president of the select council; William Wilkins as first president of the common council.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 2, 1816%0aThe Farmers and Mechanics Bank was chartered.%0a%0a%0a%0a1817%0aFirst shoe-jobbing firm in United States, H. Childs and Company, was established.%0a%0a%0a%0a1817%0aA branch of the second Bank of the United States was established in Pittsburgh with John Thaw as cashier. This bank took over the business of the defunct Bank of Pennsylvania and was named Office of Discounts and Deposits of the United States.%0a%0a%0a%0a1817%0aJohn Darragh began his eight-year term as the city's second mayor.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 5, 1817%0aPresident James Monroe visited arsenal in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 25, 1818%0aTen thousand men, women, and children witnessed the first execution of a white man in Allegheny County, the hanging of John Tiernan, who was found guilty of killing his best friend.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 6, 1818%0aPittsburgh first bank robbery, $104,000 was stolen from Farmers and Mechanics Bank; the accused robbers, Pluymart and Emmons, were captured soon thereafter.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 20, 1818%0aA federal court for Western Pennsylvania was established here; Jonathan Hoge Walker was appointed first judge by President James Monroe. The Pittsburgh-Harrisburg turnpike was opened to travel.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 18, 1819%0aPittsburgh Academy was rechartered by the Legislature and renamed Western University of Pennsylvania; its location was on Third Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 16, 1819%0aGeneral James O'Hara, Pittsburgh's pioneer industrialist, died at his home at the Point.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 16, 1819%0aThe first bridge across the Allegheny River (Federal and St. Clair streets) was completed. It served till 1860, when it was replaced by a suspension bridge.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 16, 1819%0aMonongahela Bridge was erected at a cost of $102,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 16, 1819%0aAngle iron was rolled at the Union Rolling Mill, the first complete rolling mill in the United States.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 16, 1819%0aThe city's first steam cotton mill, James Arthurs and Sons Cotton Factory, began production.%0a%0a%0a%0a1820%0aPopulation: 7248; Allegheny County, 34,927.%0a%0a%0a%0a1820%0aThe city's Alms House was built.%0a%0a%0a%0a1821%0aTurnpike was completed from Pittsburgh to Erie, via Butler, Mercer, and Meadville.%0a%0a%0a%0a1821%0aThe Pittsburgh Recorder, a Presbyterian journal, was first issued.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune, 1821%0aPittsburgh Medical Society was organized.%0a%0a%0a%0a1822%0aN. Holmes and Sons, the city's first family-owned bank, was established.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 28, 1823%0aHenry Clay was a visitor. The Apprentice Library was established as Pittsburgh's first free public library.%0a%0a%0a%0a1824%0aWestern University of Pennsylvania conferred bachelor's degrees for the first time. There were six in the graduating class.%0a%0a%0a%0a1824%0aThe Councils passed an ordinance providing for a central city water system.%0a%0a%0a%0a1825%0aAllegheny Theological Seminary was established in Allegheny by the Associate Reformed Presbyterian Church.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 7, 1825%0aWestern Theological Seminary was founded in Allegheny City by Presbyterian Church.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 30, 1825%0aThe Marquis de Lafayette arrived at the Mansion House for a two-week visit. One of the most spectacular social events was a ball held at Colonel Ramsay's Hotel on Wood Street at Third Avenue in honor of the French statesman.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 4, 1826%0aComposer Stephen Collins Foster was born at 3600 Penn Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember, 1826%0aThe city's first water reservoir was completed on Grant's Hill.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember, 1826%0aWork was started on the Pennsylvania Canal.%0a%0a%0a%0a1827%0aSt. Paul's Church was organized under leadership of Father Charles Bonaventure Maguire, and a building, which six years later became St. Paul's Cathedral, was erected at Fifth Avenue and Grant Street.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary, 1827%0aThe Bethel African Methodist Episcopal Church, the first Negro church west of the Allegheny Mountains, was instituted at Water and Smithfield streets.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril, 1827%0aThe Albion, first steamboat to travel up the Allegheny River as far as Kittanning, left the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 20, 1827%0aHenry Clay, Secretary of State, visited the city again.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 16, 1827%0aWestern Theological Seminary was opened for study.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 22, 1827%0aWestern Penitentiary, the first state penal institution west of the mountains, was completed in Allegheny.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 28, 1827%0aContract was let to construct the Aqueduct to carry the Pennsylvania Canal over the Allegheny River to the city.%0a%0a%0a%0a1828%0aJohn Irwin was elected the first burgess of Allegheny.%0a%0a%0a%0a1828%0aFirst museum and art gallery was opened to public.%0a%0a%0a%0a1828%0aEtna Iron Works, first iron-pipe manufacturing plant west of Alleghenies, was built by H. S. Spang and Son (Predecessor of Spang, Chalfant and Company).%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 14, 1828%0aAllegheny was incorporated as a borough.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 3, 1828%0aFoundation stone was laid for the Washington Lock, the first of four, to connect the Pennsylvania Canal and the Monongahela River.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember, 1828%0aThe city's first water-supply system, with a reservoir on Grant's Hill and a pumping station at the foot of Cecil Alley, was ready for service.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 10, 1829%0aThe Aqueduct carrying the Canal over the Allegheny River to the Canal basin in the city went into service.%0a%0a%0a%0a1830%0aThe anti-Masonic, anti-Jackson councils elected Mathew B. Lowrie mayor.%0a%0a%0a%0a1830%0aPopulation: Pittsburgh, 12,568; Allegheny, 2801 citizens, eight slaves; Allegheny County, 50,552.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch, 1830%0aNatural gas was discovered in Saw Mill Run at depth of 627 feet.%0a%0a%0a%0a1831%0aDavid G. Blythe, the artist, arrived in the city to study wood carving.%0a%0a%0a%0a1831%0aJohn H. Mellor established on Wood Street a firm said to be the first piano house in America.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 12, 1831%0aPittsburgh Times began publication.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 1, 1831%0aFirst steam ferry began operating at the foot of Penn Street. Duquesne Grays, a citizens' militia, was organized.%0a%0a%0a%0a1832%0aJohn M. Roberts and Son opened a jewelry and watchmaking establishment at Fifth Avenue and Market.%0a%0a%0a%0a1832%0aSamuel Pettigrew was chosen mayor.%0a%0a%0a%0a1832%0aThe Farmer's Deposit National Bank of Pittsburgh began business as the Pittsburgh Savings Fund Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 10, 1832%0aFlood waters reached a level of 38.2 feet at the Point.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 5, 1832%0aOrphan Society of Pittsburgh and Allegheny, the present Protestant Home for Children and the oldest institution of its kind in Pennsylvania, was founded. It was incorporated in 1834.%0a%0a%0a%0a1833%0aSt. Paul's Roman Catholic Church was dedicated. It was consecrated the sect's first cathedral in the city on August 7,1843.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 4, 1833%0aDaniel Webster visited.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 30, 1833%0aThe gazette, under management of John I. Scull and Morgan Neville, became a daily paper.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 2, 1833%0aThe Pittsburgh Theater, known as Old Drury and located on Fifth Avenue between Wood and Smithfield streets, opened with the play Busy Body and the afterpiece Age of Tomorrow. Tyrone Power played 7-lam let in the third presentation at the theater.%0a%0a%0a%0a1834%0aPennsylvania canal system from Philadelphia to Pittsburgh was completed at a cost of $10,000,000.%0a%0a%0a%0a1834%0aSamuel Pettigrew was returned to office in the first public election for mayor.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 27, 1834%0aThe first historical society was organized.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch, 1834%0aA route between Pittsburgh and Philadelphia via canal and rail-road (Pennsylvania Canal, Portage and Columbia railroads) was opened.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 9, 1834%0aWilliam Lesky, sheriff, issued a proclamation establishing a "general system of common schools."%0a%0a%0a%0a1835%0aThe Pittsburgh, the first steam locomotive to be built west of the Allegheny Mountains, was built by McClurg, Wade, and Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 8, 1835%0aThe select and common councils authorized the first gas works to be built in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 11, 1835%0aPittsburgh's first public school opened in a rented room in a Seventh Street building; five pupils attended class taught by James F. Gilmore.%0a%0a%0a%0a1836%0aJonas R. McClintock was first successful public candidate for mayor.%0a%0a%0a%0a1836%0aN. R. Smith founded a system of lyceums which dominated the city's intellectual life for the next ten years.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 26, 1836%0aThe Councils adopted an ordinance establishing a system of police to include one captain of the watch, two lieutenants, and 16 watchmen.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 31, 1836%0aThe Monongahela Navigation Company was chartered and began construction of locks and dams in Monongahela River.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 26, 1836%0aA city ordinance was passed authorizing the initial grading of Grant's Hill, familiarly known as "the Hump," a cut of ten feet in Fifth Avenue hill just east of Central City.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 6, 1836%0aFourteen trade unions amalgamated to form the Pittsburgh Central Labor Union.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 13, 1836%0aA cornerstone was laid for construction of the second courthouse.%0a%0a%0a%0a1837%0aIsaac Harris' Directory for 1837 estimated the value of Pittsburgh manufacturing at $11,606,350.%0a%0a%0a%0a1837%0aThe Orphan Society built its first orphanage.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 6, 1837%0aFor the first time, manufactured gas lighting appeared on the streets of the city and in many stores.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 15, 1837%0aAll Pittsburgh banks suspended gold payments as the result of nationwide inflation caused by overexpansion of business and "disorderly currency."%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 1, 1837%0aThe first public school for Negroes was opened.%0a%0a%0a%0a1838%0aMechanics Bridge was built over the Allegheny River at Sixteenth Street.%0a%0a%0a%0a1839%0aThe bridge over the Allegheny River at Hand (Ninth) Street was completed. The roof of the bridge became a fashionable promenade.%0a%0a%0a%0a1839%0aGrogan Company, jewelers, was established.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch, 1839%0aOver 1400 canal boats carrying 25,000 tons of freight passed through Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember, 1839%0aValley Forge, the first large iron steamboat, was built by Robinson and Minis.%0a%0a%0a%0a1840%0aPittsburgh developed as a coal port; in this year coal shipments out of city totaled 464,826 tons.%0a%0a%0a%0a1840%0aPeter Duff's Mercantile College (Duff's Business College) established.%0a%0a%0a%0a1840%0aPopulation: 21,515; Allegheny City, 10,089; Allegheny County, 81,235.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 13, 1840%0aAllegheny was incorporated as a third-class city with a population of 10,989.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 4, 1840%0aClayton's "aerial mail packet" balloon, bound for Philadelphia, took off from Pittsburgh and landed the same evening in the vicinity of Tarentum.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 17, 1840%0aWilliam Robinson was inaugurated as first mayor of Allegheny City.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary, 1841%0aEn route to Washington for his inauguration, President-elect William H. Harrison visited the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril, 1841%0aThe hostelry Monongahela House, opened its doors.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 31, 1841%0aA strike followed by riots in six cotton factories in Allegheny. September 8: The Pittsburgh Weekly Chronicle began publication.%0a%0a%0a%0a1842%0aThe second courthouse, designed by John Chislett, was completed on Grant's Hill.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 20, 1842%0aCharles Dickens, the English author, arrived with his wife at the Exchange Hotel, Penn Avenue at Sixth, for a three-day visit.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 10, 1842%0aPittsburgh Daily Morning Post was first published. The Henry Oliver family, including 2-year-old Henry William Oliver, emigrated from Ireland to Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0a1843%0aThe Aqueduct was rebuilt on the suspension principle, using wire cable made by John Roebling. This was the first great public work in which wire cable was used in place of wooden beams.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 7, 1843%0aThe See of Pittsburgh was created with the Right Reverend Michael O'Connor as first bishop.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 22, 1843%0aSeven Sisters of Mercy arrived from Ireland to establish their Order here.%0a%0a%0a%0a1844%0aJoseph Woodwell, well known in the city as a wood carver of unusual ability, entered the hardware business in partnership in a store named Walker and Woodwell.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 13, 1844%0aThe Monongahela River was formally opened for navigation as far as Brownsville; seven dams and 11 locks were in operation.%0a%0a%0a%0a1845%0aSteamboats were first used here for towing coal barges.%0a%0a%0a%0a1845%0aThe iron frigate Allegheny was built here for the United States Navy.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 10, 1845%0aA fire that started in the back of an icehouse at Ferry Street and Second Avenue destroyed 982 buildings, made about 12,000 persons homeless, resulted in damage estimated between $5,000,000 and $8,000,000 and left one third of city in ashes.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 22, 1845%0aMary Cassatt, noted impressionist painter, was born in Allegheny. (She died in 1926.)%0a%0a%0a%0a1846%0aFirst manufacture of a new explosive gun cotton.%0a%0a%0a%0a1846%0aSamuel M. Kier, Pittsburgh druggist, began to sell crude oil for medicinal purposes.%0a%0a%0a%0a1846%0aThe covered wooden bridge over the Monongahela River at Smithfield Street was replaced by a wire suspension one, the first so constructed by John Roebling, builder of the Brooklyn Bridge.%0a%0a%0a%0a1846%0aA Society of Jews, forerunner of the Rodef Shalom Congregation, was formed.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 8, 1846%0aThe Pittsburgh Dispatch, first successful penny newspaper west of Alleghenies, was founded by Colonel J. Heron Foster.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 13, 1846%0aThe Pennsylvania Railroad was incorporated.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 22, 1846%0aDuquesne Grays and Jackson Blues, first Pittsburgh regiments, left by boat for New Orleans and Vera Cruz to join in the war against Mexico.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 29, 1846%0aPittsburgh dispatched its first telegraphic message, a report from General Bowman of the Pennsylvania militia notifying President Polk that the second Pennsylvania regiment was ready to leave for Mexico.%0a%0a%0a%0a1847%0aThe Post became the first city newspaper to utilize the telegraph for news coverage.%0a%0a%0a%0a1847%0aPittsburgh-born Jane Grey Swisshelm, reformer and abolitionist, began publication of The Saturday Visitor, a weekly journal.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 1847%0aThe Sisters of Mercy opened their first hospital here, called it the "Mercy."%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 1, 1847%0aThe Joseph Woodwell Company, situated at Second Avenue and Wood Street, opened its doors to the public.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 5, 1847%0aThe Monongahela House, rebuilt after being destroyed in the 1845 fire, was opened.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 9, 1847%0aA citizens' meeting was held to plan erection of a public hospital.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 13, 1847%0aThe Mercantile Library Association, a union of several library groups, was founded.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 1, 1848%0aThe Mercury published the city's first Sunday newspaper.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 18, 1848%0aWestern Pennsylvania Hospital (West Penn) was chartered.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 9, 1848%0aSisters of Mercy completed a hospital on Stevenson Street with bed capacity for 60 patients.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 17, 1848%0aAllegheny Medical Society was organized as a branch of the State Medical Society.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 17, 1848%0aThirteen-year-old Andrew Carnegie and his family left Scotland for Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 17, 1848%0aAnesthesia in the form of chloroform was used for the first time in Pittsburgh by Dr. William H. Wright in a tooth extraction.%0a%0a%0a%0a1849%0aIron City Industrial Congress was organized by 23 local unions.%0a%0a%0a%0a1849%0aPittsburgh City Glass Works was started by Wilson Cunningham and his two brothers.%0a%0a%0a%0a1849%0aA second cut, this one seven feet, was made in the "Hump."%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 22, 1849%0aAn advertisement appeared in Daily gazette announcing that "J. Horne, Trimmings, Notions, Millinery and Fancy Goods," was open for business at 63 Market Street.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 20, 1849%0aPuddlers and boilers in iron mills began a five-month strike in protest against a reduction in wages; this action led to later organization of the Sons of Vulcan.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 20, 1849%0aA two-hour speech by Salmon P. Chase, Ohio Free-Soil senator, at Allegheny Market House, set the trend of abolitionist thinking in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 20, 1849%0aFirst waterworks in Allegheny was completed.%0a%0a%0a%0a1850%0aColonel James Anderson established in Allegheny an Apprentices' Library and opened it to working boys. Andrew Carnegie was one of the regular boy patrons.%0a%0a%0a%0a1850%0aThe value of Pittsburgh manufacturing was estimated at $50,000,000 by Samuel Fahnestock in the Pittsburgh Directory for the Year 1850.%0a%0a%0a%0a1850%0aB. F. Jones resigned as manager of the Pennsylvania Canal to begin operating a puddling iron works on the south bank of the Monongahela River.%0a%0a%0a%0a1850%0aPopulation: Pittsburgh, 46,601; Allegheny City, 21,262; Allegheny County, 138,290.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary, 1850%0aPassavant Hospital, founded in 1849 under the name Pittsburgh Infirmary by the Reverend William Passavant of Zelienople, was chartered.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 7, 1850%0aJoseph Barker, an itinerant reformer, was elected mayor while serving a year's term in jail for disturbing the peace.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 10, 1850%0aPennsylvania Railroad began operating trains between Pittsburgh and Johnstown.%0a%0a%0a%0a1851%0aA Marine Hospital, designed to care for disabled rivermen, was established by the federal government at nearby Woods Run.%0a%0a%0a%0a1851%0aThe report-card system was established in the city schools.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary, 1851%0aJane Grey Swisshelm, advocate of women's rights, polled only three votes in her campaign for the office of mayor.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 25, 1851%0aIn the city's greatest musical event of the era, Jenny Lind, under the management of Phineas T. Barnum, sang at Masonic Hall, Fifth Avenue, before 1000 persons who paid an average of $7 each for tickets sold on auction.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 16, 1851%0aEvergreen Hamlet, an experiment in communal living, started.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 30, 1851%0aRegular passenger service was inaugurated by the Ohio and Pennsylvania Railroad (Fort Wayne) between Allegheny and New Brighton.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 10, 1851%0aThe Pennsylvania Railroad formally began business in the city of Pittsburgh with its rail line extended as far as Turtle Creek. At that point passengers transferred to stagecoach, which bridged a 28-mile gap in the rail connection.%0a%0a%0a%0a1852%0aPittsburgh Board of Health was created.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 19, 1852%0aThe rivers went to a stage of 35.1 feet in another flood.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 19, 1852%0aFlood waters reached a mark of 31 feet, 9 inches.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember, 1852%0aThe National Free-Soil Convention, one of the first mass abolitionist meetings in the country, was held in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 17, 1852%0aThe Ohio and Pennsylvania Railroad posted regular schedules between Pittsburgh, Alliance, Canton, Massillon, and Wooster, Ohio. It offered four trains daily, the first leaving Pittsburgh at 8 A.M. and arriving in Wooster at 3:30 P.M.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 29, 1852%0aThe Pennsylvania Railroad opened an all-rail route from Pittsburgh to Philadelphia, utilizing the Portage and Columbia railroads.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 29, 1852%0aThe Pennsylvania State Teachers Association was organized at a meeting in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0a1853%0aThe Economites, a religious society near Ambridge, Pa., completed the Saw Mill Run Railroad to Banksville, a distance of three miles.%0a%0a%0a%0a1853%0aThe city's first Jewish congregation held services in a temporary synagogue located over the Vigilant Fire Engine House on Third Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0a1853%0aThe borough of West Pittsburgh was formed.%0a%0a%0a%0a1853%0aThe first Pittsburgh post office and federal government building was erected at Fifth Avenue and Smithfield Street.%0a%0a%0a%0a1853%0aThe Pittsburgh Legal Journal (second law periodical in the United States and third in the world) was published by Thomas J. Keenan and John Hastings.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune, 1853%0aBenjamin F. Jones formed a partnership with Bernard and John Lauth and Samuel Kier, with whom he had operated the Mechanics Line, a canal boat line from Pittsburgh to Philadelphia. They established on the south bank of the Monongahela River puddling furnaces and rolling mills under the name of Jones, Lauth and Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember, 1853%0aThe Morning Post listed the following hotels in operation in Pittsburgh: Monongahela House, Exchange Hotel, Merchants Hotel, American Hotel, United States, Spread Eagle, Miller's Mansion House, and Broadhurst Mansion House.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 15, 1854%0aThe Summit tunnel of the Pennsylvania Railroad was opened, allowing continuous rail travel between Pittsburgh and Harrisburg.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch, 1854%0aThe first bill was introduced in the Legislature to consolidate the cities of Pittsburgh and Allegheny.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember, 1854%0aThe Pittsburgh Post reported a total of 400 deaths in two weeks in the city's worst cholera epidemic.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember, 1854%0aRodef Shalom Congregation was organized.%0a%0a%0a%0a1855%0aA new city hall and market, at Diamond and Market, was completed.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch, 1855%0aLadies were first employed as clerks in dry-goods stores.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 24, 1855%0aAndrew W. Mellon was born in East Liberty.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 19, 1855%0aThe Dollar Savings Bank, founded as the Pittsburgh Dollar Savings Institution, was opened for business.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 29, 1855%0aThe first county Republican convention adopted an abolition resolution.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 25, 1855%0aThe first public high school (Central) was opened in rented quarters, at 508 Smithfield Street, for 114 pupils.%0a%0a%0a%0a1856%0aJoseph L. Lowry built the first steam fire engine for the city.%0a%0a%0a%0a1856%0aJohn Lauth, sold his interests in Jones, Lauth, and Company to the other partners. James A. Laughlin bought into the business.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 29, 1856%0aThe Allegheny Valley Railroad was opened to Kittanning.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 22, 1856%0aThe first national convention of Republicans met in Lafayette Hall in Pittsburgh for a two-day session to complete national party organization.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 29, 1856%0aThe Pittsburgh, Fort Wayne and Chicago Railroad was incorporated and its line was opened through to Chicago from Allegheny.%0a%0a%0a%0a1857%0aThe Pennsylvania Railroad purchased the Pennsylvania Canal for $7,500,000.%0a%0a%0a%0a1857%0aThe Diamond Savings Institution (predecessor of the Union National Bank of Pittsburgh) was founded.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 23, 1857%0aNovelist Margaret Wade Deland was born in Allegheny. (She died in 1945.)%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust, 1857%0aThe financial panic reached a climax in Pittsburgh when all local banks, with the exception of the Bank of Pittsburgh, suspended payments "until such time as the Philadelphia banks resume."%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember, 1857%0aCharlotte Jones, convicted of killing her aunt and uncle for their money in the notorious "McKeesport cabin murder," became the first woman to be hanged in Allegheny County. She said, "I did this for the great love I had for Denny Fife."%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 22, 1857%0aThe first railroad bridge across the Allegheny River, a wooden structure, was opened to bring the Ohio and Pennsylvania Railroad into the city of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0a1858%0aMackeown and Finley agreed to sell to the A. C: Ferris and Company of New York City two thirds of their output of carbon oil. This contract marked the beginning of the use of petroleum products in New York.%0a%0a%0a%0a1858%0aSamuel Kier set up his first commercial oil refinery or "still" in his drugstore basement at 363 Liberty Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0a1858%0aA small group of iron puddlers, meeting in an old Diamond Street hotel, organized the Sons of Vulcan, first union movement in the iron industry in Pittsburgh. The action was the result of the financial panic of 1857, which had forced their wage to be reduced to $3.25 per ton.%0a%0a%0a%0a1858%0aIn Millvale, the Kloman brothers began operating the forge works which led to the Carnegie steel organization. The first tin plate (iron coated with tin) ever made was produced by C. G. Hussey and Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 10, 1858%0aThe first train operated from Allegheny into the city's first Union Station, located at Seventh Street and Liberty Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 26, 1858%0aThe United Presbyterian Church of North America was created by the merger of the Associate Reformed and the Associate Presbyterian churches. The merger took place in the old City Hall in Market Square.%0a%0a%0a%0a1859%0aCold rolling of iron and steel was invented and patented by Bernard Lauth, a partner of Benjamin F. Jones.%0a%0a%0a%0a1859%0aH. Samson began operating as a funeral director.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 10, 1859%0aThe Western Pennsylvania Historical Society held its first meeting in the Merchants Exchange.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 22, 1859%0aThe Citizen Passenger Railway Company was granted a charter for construction and operation of first street railway in city. The first track was laid on Penn Avenue from St. Clair (Sixth) Street to 26th Street.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly, 1859%0aJames Laughlin, a banker and merchant, built the first two Eliza blast furnaces with beehive coke ovens, on the north side of the Monongahela River, directly opposite the Jones, Lauth plant. The new plant was known as Laughlin and Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 5, 1859%0aThe first horsecar, "a single-truck vehicle, seating 14 passengers, dimly lighted at night," began operating; the fare from Butler Street to East Liberty was six cents.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 29, 1859%0aThe petroleum industry had its birth when Colonel Edward L. Drake struck oil at 69 feet at Titusville about 75 miles north of the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 1, 1859%0aThe Union National Bank was organized as a successor to the Diamond Savings Institution.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 16, 1859%0aClinton, the second blast furnace built in the district, and the first to use coke for the blast, went into operation at the South Side plant of Graff, Bennett, and Company.%0a%0a%0a%0a1860%0aAllegheny Observatory was founded.%0a%0a%0a%0a1860%0aPopulation: 49,221; Allegheny City, 28,702; Allegheny County, 178,031.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 22, 1860%0aAn announcement was made of the opening of "books to receive subscription of stock" for construction of a "free bridge" over the Allegheny.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 29, 1860%0aProfessor S. Wilson ascended from Pittsburgh in his balloon, great Western, disappeared from view, and landed hours later on a bill near Sharpsburg.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 1, 1860%0aThe Prince of Wales, the later Edward VII of the United Kingdom, was warmly greeted by Pittsburghers when he arrived at the Monongahela House for an overnight stay. He visited factories and manufacturing establishments.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 28, 1860%0aBecause of Civil War clouds, all Pittsburgh banks except the Bank of Pittsburgh suspended specie payments.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember, 1860%0aThe city refused to comply with the Secretary of War's order for the transfer of guns from the Allegheny Arsenal to the South.%0a%0a%0a%0a1861%0aBaltimore and Ohio Railroad, via connecting railroads, was extended to the city.%0a%0a%0a%0a1861%0aThe Trimble Construction Company began operations as the Crawford, Trimble and Gilliland Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 15, 1861%0aFrom a balcony of the Monongahela House, President-elect Lincoln, who had stopped in the city on his way to Washington, in a reference to the secession from the Union of southern states, declared that "notwithstanding the trouble across the river, there is no crisis but an artificial one."%0a%0a%0a%0aApril, 1861%0aCamp Wilkins, near Penn Avenue and 26th Street, was established by Governor Andrew G. Curtin; a home guard was organized.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 24, 1861%0aEighty men comprising "Turners Rifles" departed for Harrisburg to join Union troops; they became the first Pittsburgh soldiers to see action in the war.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust, 1861%0aBernard Lauth retired and James Laughlin bought his interest. Jones, Lauth, and Company became Jones and Laughlin's American Iron Works.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 21, 1861%0aProperty damage was heavy in a flood that reached a mark of 30 feet, 9 inches.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober, 1861%0aUnited States Sanitary Commission, designed to receive donations of clothing and medical supplies for the Army, was established by the Citizens Committee of 100, which had been selected at a mass meeting in City Hall on April 15.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 1862%0aIron City Forge Company, the parent of Kloman and Company and of the Carnegie iron and steel interests, was organized as a partner-ship of the Kloman brothers, Thomas Miller, and Henry Phipps.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 4, 1862%0aThe Home for the Friendless was chartered.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 17, 1862%0aSeventy-eight persons, mostly boys and girls employed there, were killed and twice as many injured in an explosion at the Allegheny Arsenal in Lawrenceville, where munitions were being manufactured for the Union army.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 25, 1862%0aEthelbert Nevin, composer, author, and pianist, was born in nearby Edgeworth. He was the composer of "The Rosary."%0a%0a%0a%0a1863%0aThe iron frigates Manayunk and Umpqua were built.%0a%0a%0a%0a1863%0aThe Third National Bank of Pittsburgh was founded at the corner of Wood Street and Virgin Alley (Oliver Avenue)%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch, 1863%0aThe Pittsburgh Trades Assembly was organized by representatives of 46 local unions.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril, 1863%0aThe United States Christian Commission, directed by the Reverend Herrick Johnson, assumed most of work of Sanitary Commission and hospital activities of the Subsistence Committee.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 14, 1863%0aIn a Sunday meeting at the Monongahela House, Pittsburgh businessmen and manufacturers, fearing a raid by the Confederate cavalry forces of J. E. B. Stuart, decided to suspend business and set up a defense.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 16, 1863%0aTwo thousand men, paid at rate of $L25 per day by their own employers, began digging rifle pits on hills as a line of defense around the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 25, 1863%0aPittsburgh militia and home guard prepared for an attack on receipt of a telegraphic message that Jeb Stuart's troops had occupied McConnellsburg and were moving toward the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 26, 1863%0aThere were 11,828 men at work on 32 separate defense installations in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 4, 1863%0aAll fortifications were completed, but the Confederate retreat after the Union victory at Gettysburg removed the threat to Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 5, 1863%0aFollowing their surrender to Union troops at Lisbon, Ohio, 118 officers of General John H. Morgan's cavalry, the only Confederate prisoners held in Pittsburgh in the Civil War, were brought to Western Penitentiary.%0a%0a%0a%0a1864%0aThe firm that was the forerunner of the A. M. Byers Company was established.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary, 1864%0aNew city hall, market house, and weight house, bordering on the public square in Allegheny City, were completed.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 13, 1864%0aStephen Collins Foster, Pittsburgh's best-known composer, died destitute in New York.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 21, 1864%0aUlysses S. Grant, en route to take command of the Army of the Potomac, was the guest of honor at a dinner in the Monongahela House.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 2, 1864%0aAndrew Carnegie, at 29, entered the iron-producing business by purchasing a sixth interest in the Iron City Forge Company for $8,925. Other shareholders included Andrew Kloman and Henry Phipps.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 16, 1864%0aAllegheny City's Sanitary Fair closed after raising $363,570 in 16 days for benefit of Union soldiers and their dependents. At the end of the war $200,000 unused funds were given to West Penn Hospital as a nucleus for an endowment.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 30, 1864%0aThe first train ran between Pittsburgh and Erie.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 19, 1864%0aThe Quarterly Trade Circular reported that there were 58 oil refineries in the city with a weekly capacity of 26,000 barrels.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 11, 1864%0aThurston's (oil) Stock Exchange opened on Fourth Street.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember, 1864%0aNewspapers reported that the wage of iron puddlers had risen from $3.56 per ton in October 1861 to $9 per ton.%0a%0a%0a%0a1865%0aThe new Pennsylvania Railroad Station went into service. Located at 11th Street and Liberty Avenue, it was a four-story structure with upper floors assigned to a hotel.%0a%0a%0a%0a1865%0aThe Sisters of St. Francis converted a frame building into a hospital for 12 patients.%0a%0a%0a%0a1865%0aPittsburgh Diocese of the Protestant Episcopal Church was created. John E. Kerfoot was the first bishop. Pittsburgh School of Design was instituted.%0a%0a%0a%0a1865%0aMerchants' and Manufacturers' Bank was organized.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary, 1865%0aAfter an eight-month strike, the first trade-union agreement in America was made between the Sons of Vulcan and the iron industry. Among major provisions of the con-tract was a sliding wage scale on economic conditions in the industry.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 5, 1865%0aThe Pittsburgh Clearing House Association was opened for business with John Harper as president.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch, 1865%0aCyclops Mill, a Thomas Miller and Carnegie enterprise, was completed.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 25, 1865%0aThe Keystone Bridge Company was organized, designed to use iron from the Iron City Forge and the new Cyclops Mill.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 1, 1865%0aIron City Forge and Cyclops Mill were merged to form Union Iron Mills.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 4, 1865%0aA tremendous ovation was given General Grant when he arrived in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 31, 1865%0aGeorge Westinghouse, at 19, received his first patent for the invention of a rotary steam engine.%0a%0a%0a%0a1866%0aSmith and Porter (H. K. Porter Company) began manufacturing locomotives in Pittsburgh. The first one operated under its own steam on street car rails across a Monongahela River bridge.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 3, 1866%0aPeoples Savings Bank of Pittsburgh was chartered.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust, 1866%0aHomeopathic Medical and Surgical Hospital and Dispensary was founded.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 29, 1866%0aThe police night call, "All's well," was abolished.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 13, 1866%0aOnce more General Grant came to Pittsburgh, this time with President Andrew Johnson and Admiral David G. Farragut.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 13, 1866%0aAnnual exchange clearings of the Pittsburgh Clearing House Association, reflecting the amount of business activity in Pittsburgh, totaled $83,791,242.%0a%0a%0a%0a1867%0aFirst fire-alarm telegraph system was established in Allegheny.%0a%0a%0a%0a1867%0aSamuel Pierpont Langley was appointed Director of the Allegheny Observatory.%0a%0a%0a%0a1867%0aAndrew Carnegie acquired the controlling interest in the Union Iron Mills.%0a%0a%0a%0a1867%0aRosenbaum and Company was established at 76 Market Street as Rosenbaum and Fleischman, a retail and wholesale millinery firm.%0a%0a%0a%0a1867%0aThe Peoples First National Bank and Trust Company was founded as the Safe Deposit Company.%0a%0a%0a%0a1867%0aAn act of the Legislature officially transferred to the city of Allegheny the Allegheny Parks, the land of which was originally the gift of the Penn family.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril, 1867%0aThe councils of Allegheny and Pittsburgh agreed on a plan of union in the first definite step toward consolidation.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 12, 1867%0aMonongahela Incline Plane Railroad, up the face of Mount Washington, was chartered.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 30, 1868%0aThe city of Pittsburgh extended its eastern boundary by annexing the townships of Pitt, Peebles, Liberty, Collins, and Oakland.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 8, 1868%0aCornerstone was laid for the new City Hall on Smithfield Street.%0a%0a%0a%0a1869%0aH. J. Heinz, at 25, planted in Millvale a three-quarter of an acre patch of horseradish, and thus began the world-renowned H. J. Heinz Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 9, 1869%0aThe Boggs and Buhl department store was opened at 512 Federal Street in Allegheny as the Boggs, Blair and Buhl notions and dry goods shop.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 13, 1869%0aIn the first practical demonstration, an air-brake train made a trip from Union Station in Pittsburgh to Steubenville.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 10, 1869%0aThe Home for Aged Protestant Women was founded.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly, 1869%0aGeorge Westinghouse's first major enterprise, the Westinghouse Air Brake Company, was organized to manufacture air brakes for steam railways. The first site of the company was at 25th Street and Liberty Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 10, 1869%0aPennsylvania Female College (now Chatham College) opened. The new telephone switchboard provided service to 777 subscribers.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 14, 1869%0aPresident Ulysses S. Grant visited the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 11, 1869%0aPennsylvania College for Women, founded by the Reverend W. T. Beatty, was incorporated.%0a%0a%0a%0a1870%0aThe 642-foot Monongahela Incline, first in the city, was completed to the top of "Coal Hill" (Mount Washington).%0a%0a%0a%0a1870%0aJacob, Henry, Morris, and Isaac Kaufmann, German immigrants with $1500 between them, opened a men's clothing business in an I 8-by-28 foot storeroom at 1918 Carson Street, primarily to serve puddlers of the nearby Jones and Laughlin steel mill (Kaufmann's Store, incorporated in 1871).%0a%0a%0a%0a1870%0aThe Pittsburgh Coal Exchange was chartered for coal companies engaged in river transportation.%0a%0a%0a%0a1870%0aAllegheny Bar Association was incorporated.%0a%0a%0a%0a1870%0aThe establishment of Pittsburgh titles for land belonging to the Penns was completed.%0a%0a%0a%0a1870%0aPopulation: 86,076; Allegheny City, 51,180; Allegheny County, 262204.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 1870%0aThe Old Drury Theater closed its doors after 37 years of service.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 2, 1870%0aJudge Thomas Mellon, the father of Andrew W. and Richard B. Mellon, retired from the bench to open a private banking establishment under the name of T. Mellon and Sons on Smithfield Street near Sixth Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 17, 1870%0aThe first professional teachers organization was established in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 6, 1870%0aThe Pittsburgh and Ormsby Passenger Railroad Company was incorporated to construct a railway from the borough of Ormsby to a Market Street terminal.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 13, 1870%0aPittsburgh's first paid fire department was organized.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 28, 1870%0aPennsylvania College for Women opened under the auspices of the Presbyterian Church.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 13, 1870%0aThe first Pittsburgh Weather Bureau was established by the War Department and Signal Corps at 25 Fifth Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0a1871%0aThe Pittsburgh Grand Opera House, on Fifth Avenue, was completed.%0a%0a%0a%0a1871%0aMaking of steel castings from crucible steel was begun at the Pittsburgh Steel Casting Company.%0a%0a%0a%0a1871%0aBaltimore and Ohio Railroad opened continuous service from the east to Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 24, 1871%0aThe retail division of the Joseph Horne Company moved into Library Hall (Penn Avenue), a building which previously had housed Mercy Hospital.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 30, 1871%0aGeneral George G. Meade, a Civil War military leader, and Governor John W. Geary were speakers at a dedication of the Soldiers Monument on Monument Hill in Allegheny.%0a%0a%0a%0a1872%0aThe Mount Oliver Incline; 1600 feet long and the first to be cable-driven, was built.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 2, 1872%0aThe city of Pittsburgh annexed the boroughs of South Pittsburgh, Monongahela, Allentown, St. Clair, Lawrenceville, Temperanceville, Birmingham, Sligo, Mount Washington, West Pittsburgh, and Ormsby.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay, 1872%0aThe Lucy furnace of Kloman, Phipps, and Carnegie went into blast.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 18, 1872%0aIt was reported that Pittsburgh oil refineries were using about 10,000 barrels of crude oil daily from the Oil Creek and Allegheny River fields.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 23, 1872%0aThe new City Hall, erected at Smithfield and Oliver Way at a cost of $600,000, was officially opened.%0a%0a%0a%0a1873%0aThe Duquesne Club was founded by a group of industrialists and financiers. The Pittsburgh Art Society was organized.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 13, 1873%0aCarnegie, McCandless, and Company, with $750,000 capital, was organized to build a steel-rail mill at nearby Braddock; Andrew Carnegie had one-third interest.%0a%0a%0a%0a1874%0aConstruction started on the Union Bridge (Manchester) to connect Allegheny with the Point.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 27, 1874%0aThe Central District and Printing Telegraph Company was organized as the first telephone company in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 26, 1874%0aOne hundred and fifty persons died in the "Butcher's Run Flood" which deluged Allegheny, Woods Run, West End, South Side, and neighboring communities.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 12, 1874%0aEdgar Thomson Steel Company, Limited, with $1,000,000 capital, was organized and took over Carnegie, McCandless, and Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember, 1874%0aThe first Exposition Society was formed to exploit Pittsburgh goods, and built several great halls on Killbuck Island.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 5, 1874%0aAt a meeting in the Germania Bank Building, at Wood and Diamond, the Pittsburgh Chamber of Commerce was organized, with General Thomas H. Howe as the first president.%0a%0a%0a%0a1875%0aNatural gas was first used in manufacturing.%0a%0a%0a%0a1875%0aWomen's Club of Pittsburgh, the first such club in Pennsylvania and the second in the nation, was organized.%0a%0a%0a%0a1875%0aMrs. William A. Herron and Mrs. William Thaw organized the Pittsburgh Association for the Improvement of the Poor.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 19, 1875%0aA "heavy smoke" entry in the daily journal of the Weather Bureau stated: "Extremely dark this morning. Had to keep all gaslights burning until 11 o'clock. Street lamps were lighted for a time after 9 o'clock (AM.)"%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 1, 1875%0aThe Duquesne Incline Plane Company was chartered to build an incline to the top of "Coal Hill" (Mount Washington)%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 1, 1875%0aThe first steel rail was rolled at the Edgar Thomson works, under the supervision of Captain William R. Jones. This was the first use of the Bessemer process in the United States.%0a%0a%0a%0a1876%0aPoet Richard Realf dedicated his "Hymn of Pittsburgh" to the city. The poem started with the line, "My father was a mighty Vulcan".%0a%0a%0a%0a1876%0aThe Point Bridge was completed, providing an important connection between the central portion of the city and the south and west parts.%0a%0a%0a%0a1876%0aThe London Bakery (predecessor of the Ward Baking Company of New York) was opened by R. B. Ward on Penn Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 11, 1876%0aThe See of Allegheny was created by the Roman Catholic Church.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 11, 1876%0aWriter Mary Roberts Rinehart was born. (She died on September 22, 1958.)%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 8, 1876%0aPittsburgh Chamber of Commerce was chartered.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 4, 1876%0aThe unions of steel heaters and steel roll hands, in convention in Pittsburgh, merged to form the Amalgamated Association of Iron and Steel Workers.%0a%0a%0a%0a1877%0aThe Pittsburgh and Lake Erie Railroad completed organization and began building its first rail line from Pittsburgh to Youngstown.%0a%0a%0a%0a1877%0aArmstrong Cork Company was organized.%0a%0a%0a%0a1877%0aThe first public exhibition of electric lights took place on Duquesne Heights.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune, 1877%0aFirst experiment with the telephone was made by Captain William Boylston and T. B. A. David of the Central District and Printing Telegraph Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 19, 1877%0aPittsburgh railroad workers struck in protest against a nationwide reduction of railroaders' wages and a Pennsylvania Railroad order cutting employment of brakemen.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 20, 1877%0aLarge crowds gathered at 28th Street crossing of Pennsylvania Railroad; switches and trains were blocked.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 21, 1877%0aTwenty-six were killed and many wounded in the "Battle of 28th Street," which started when militiamen from Philadelphia fired on strikers.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 22, 1877%0aThe gazette proclaimed: "Riot Law Triumphant-The Reign of Anarchy in the Smoky City" The Union Depot was burned out and Pennsylvania Railroad property was destroyed as far as 33rd Street. Damage was estimated at $5,000,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 18, 1877%0aThe See of Allegheny of the Roman Catholic Church was merged with the See of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 4, 1877%0aThe first exposition opened on Smoky Island, Allegheny; the city's first telephone was in operation there.%0a%0a%0a%0a1878%0aT. B. A. David strung telephone wires from his office in the First National Bank Building to the Iron Exchange on Fourth Avenue and publicly engaged in the first telephone conversation in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 21, 1878%0aPittsburgh Oil Exchange (forerunner of the Pittsburgh Stock Exchange) was organized with a membership of 180.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 1, 1878%0aOrder of the Holy Ghost began operating a college.%0a%0a%0a%0a1879%0aThe city's water pumping station at Brilliant went into operation.%0a%0a%0a%0a1879%0aThe beginning of electric street lighting.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 24, 1879%0aThe Pittsburgh and Lake Erie Railroad inaugurated rail traffic between Pittsburgh and Youngstown.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 27, 1879%0aThe Pittsburgh and West End Railway Company was chartered; it ran a line from Fifth Avenue near the Union Station to West End and the Washington Turnpike.%0a%0a%0a%0a1880%0aThe Allegheny County Light Company, first ambitious electric light concern in the city, began operation with a generator that supplied energy to 40 lights at one time.%0a%0a%0a%0a1880%0aThe F. J. Kress Box Company was founded for the manufacture of wooden boxes.%0a%0a%0a%0a1880%0aAssessed valuation of real estate in the city of Pittsburgh was set at $99,600,000.%0a%0a%0a%0a1880%0aPopulation: 156,389; Allegheny City, 78,682; Allegheny County, 355,869.%0a%0a%0a%0a1881%0aThe Homestead mill of the Pittsburgh Bessemer Steel Company, built by Andrew Kloman and a group of other Pittsburgh industrialists, went into operation.%0a%0a%0a%0a1881%0aThe Union Switch and Signal Company, a pioneer in the manufacture of automatic signals for trains, was founded by George Westinghouse.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch, 1881%0aThe Pittsburgh Press Club was organized by newspaper workers at a meeting in the Common Council Chambers at City Hall.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 15, 1881%0aWith Samuel Gompers a prime mover the Federation of Organized Trades and Labor Unions (American Federation of Labor) was organized, in a Pittsburgh convention, by the Knights of Labor and other trade unions, including the Amalgamated Association of Iron and Steel Workers.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 25, 1881%0aAndrew Carnegie made his first move to create a free library for Pittsburgh; he offered $250,000 on the condition that the city government agree to appropriate $15,000 annually for its maintenance. The city was unable to accept the gift as it had no funds on hand for such a purpose.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 28, 1881%0aPittsburgh Catholic College of the Holy Ghost (Duquesne University) received a state charter.%0a%0a%0a%0a1882%0aHistorical Society of Western Pennsylvania became the new name for the Old Residents' Association of Pittsburgh and Western Pennsylvania, founded in 1879 as the fourth historical society in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 6, 1882%0aThe Homestead mill of the Pittsburgh Bessemer Steel Company had its first strike when millworkers refused to sign "yellow dog" contracts; violence followed.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 5, 1882%0aH. C. Frick Coke Company was incorporated with $2,000,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 7, 1882%0aThe second courthouse, on Grant's Hill, was destroyed by fire.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 1, 1882%0aA nationwide strike resulted from a general stoppage of work called by the Amalgamated Association of Iron and Steel Workers in a wage dispute.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 22, 1882%0aJane Grey Swisshelm, newspaper publisher, reformer, author, and one of the first nurses to accompany Union troops in the Civil war, died.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 4, 1882%0aAllegheny General Hospital was incorporated.%0a%0a%0a%0a1883%0aThe 17th Street Incline was built by the Penn Incline Company.%0a%0a%0a%0a1883%0aCarnegie, Phipps and Company was organized to purchase and operate the Homestead mill, owned by a coalition of seven Pittsburgh firms.%0a%0a%0a%0a1883%0aJones and Laughlin's American Iron Works became Jones and Laughlin, Limited, and the first stock was issued.%0a%0a%0a%0a1883%0aOfficers were Benjamin F. Jones, Sr., chairman, G. M. Laughlin, secretary treasurer; T. M. Jones, general manager.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary, 1883%0aThe Penn Fuel Gas Company opened a line to 16th Street from Murraysville, location of the areas first gas field opened in 1878, and thus brought the first natural gas into the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 1, 1883%0aWestern Pennsylvania Medical College was opened.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 8, 1883%0aThe county commissioners offered $2500 each to five outstanding architects to prepare sketches for a new courthouse and jail.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 3, 1883%0aThe first Exposition buildings on Smoky Island in Allegheny burned to the ground.%0a%0a%0a%0a1884%0aAn incandescent lamp was used for the first time in Pittsburgh in a restaurant located at 52-1/2 Fifth Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0a1884%0aThe first school for nurses between the Allegheny Mountains and Chicago was opened at the Homeopathic Medical and Surgical Hospital and Dispensary.%0a%0a%0a%0a1884%0aGeorge Westinghouse began the manufacture of electric lamps.%0a%0a%0a%0a1884%0aMonongahela Natural Gas Company was organized.%0a%0a%0a%0a1884%0aBenjamin F. Jones, Sr., became president of the American Iron and Steel Association, a post he held for 18 years.%0a%0a%0a%0a1884%0aA Postal Telegraph bureau was established in Pittsburgh as a rival for Western Union.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 1, 1884%0aHenry Hobson Richardson, noted for his Romanesque architecture, was appointed by the county commissioners to design the new courthouse.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 6, 1884%0aThe city was flooded, the rivers reached a mark of 36.5 feet.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay, 1884%0aGeorge Westinghouse drilled a gas well on his property in the Homewood district, and his home was the first in Pittsburgh to be lighted and heated by gas.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 20, 1884%0aPittsburgh Press, a daily newspaper, began publication as the Evening Penny Press.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly, 1884%0aGeorge Westinghouse acquired control of the one-year-old Philadelphia Company for the development of natural gas; it became the world's largest in that field.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 5, 1884%0aWilliam F. (Buffalo Bill) Cody visited the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 1, 1884%0aA contract for construction of the new courthouse was let to Norcross Brothers of Worcester, Massachusetts, on a bid of $2,243,024.%0a%0a%0a%0a1885%0aBoggs and Buhl announced installation of a telephone. The store also introduced delivery service, utilizing a wheelbarrow and a horse and wagon.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 5, 1885%0aThe Pitt Medical College was opened.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 13, 1885%0aThe cornerstone for the new courthouse was laid on the 49th anniversary of the cornerstone laying for the previous courthouse.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 30, 1885%0aThe Western Pennsylvania Exposition Society was chartered for the purpose of establishing a technical school in the city, and buildings were erected on Duquesne Way; dissolved, April 10, 1934.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember, 1885%0aElizabeth Cochrane (1867-1922), the Nellie Bly of the "Around the world in 72 days" fame began her newspaper career as a reporter for the Pittsburgh Dispatch. She investigated the factories and public institutions of the city and reported about them.%0a%0a%0a%0a1886%0aGeorge Westinghouse introduced Saturday as half holiday for employees and vacations with pay for salaried employees.%0a%0a%0a%0a1886%0aRiverside Penitentiary of Western Pennsylvania (Western Penitentiary) was built in Woods Run on the Ohio River to replace the old institution in Allegheny.%0a%0a%0a%0a1886%0aAndrew Carnegie offered the city of Allegheny $300,000 for a Carnegie free library, with provision that the city maintain it.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 8, 1886%0aThe Westinghouse Electric Company was established in Garrison Alley to manufacture and promote the use of equipment for the alternating electric current system.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 19, 1886%0aJones and Laughlin constructed two seven-ton Bessemer converters at the South Side plant for the job of making its first steel.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember, 1886%0aWestern Pennsylvania Medical College was established on Brereton Street, near West Penn Hospital.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 27, 1886%0aThe Fidelity Trust Company was incorporated.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember, 1886%0aThe Federation of Organized Trades and Labor Unions changed its name to the American Federation of Labor.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 18, 1887%0aPittsburgh Hospital for Children was incorporated.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 30, 1887%0aPresident Grover Cleveland visited Pittsburgh. At the sight of natural gas he remarked: "An uncanny picture, a superb spectacle".%0a%0a%0a%0a1888%0aThe Oliver interests were reorganized to form the Oliver Iron and Steel Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 31, 1888%0aUnder the name of the Pittsburgh Reduction Company, the first aluminum producing company was organized at the home of Captain Alfred E. Hunt, 272 Shady Lane (Avenue), by five young men, all under 35. They were Captain Hunt, a military figure; Charles Martin Hall, developer of the new metal; Romaine C. Cole, George H. Clapp, and Howard Lash.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 7, 1888%0aThe first electric streetcar was placed in service by the Pittsburgh, Knoxville and St. Clair Street Railways, but was destined to failure.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 24, 1888%0aThe new Allegheny County courthouse and jail, designed by H. H. Richardson, was dedicated on the final day of the county's centennial anniversary.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 3, 1888%0aFire destroyed Machinery Hall and other exposition buildings. The Arabian, the first steam locomotive to run in the United States, and Stephen Foster's piano were among the exhibits destroyed.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember, 1888%0aCharles M. Hall and Arthur V. Davis poured the first commercial ingot of aluminum in the Smallman Street plant of the Pittsburgh Reduction Company.%0a%0a%0a%0a1889%0aNew exposition buildings were built at the Point.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 29, 1889%0aThe Pittsburgh Chamber of Commerce began urging construction of a Lake Erie and Ohio River canal.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 31, 1889%0aPittsburgh dispatched aid to Johnstown, where the flood toll was mounting to 2300 dead.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember, 1889%0aAllegheny City's first trolley operated on Pennsylvania Avenue and was the first to run into downtown Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 4, 1889%0aThe Western Exposition opened.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 12, 1889%0aThe Fifth Avenue Horse Car System was replaced by cable cars, which reduced the running time from Downtown to East Liberty by 30 minutes to one hour. The five-and-a-half-mile system, built by the Pittsburgh Traction Company, was considered to be the city's first "rapid transit" facility.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 2, 1889%0aThe Pittsburgh Reduction Company, its pilot plant having demonstrated the success of the Hall aluminum making process, was capitalized at $1,000,000, and 10,000 shares were issued.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 26, 1889%0aSouth Side Hospital was founded.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 28, 1889%0aThe Union Trust Company of Pittsburgh was established in the Oil Exchange Building.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 30, 1889%0aMrs. Mary E. Schenley presented the city of Pittsburgh with 300 acres of land for park purposes, and Schenley Park, the city's first, was developed.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 16, 1889%0aPlaywright George S. Kaufman was born in the city. (He died in 1961.)%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 8, 1889%0aHervey Allen, novelist, was born in East Liberty. (He died on December 28, 1949.)%0a%0a%0a%0a1890%0aThe Joseph Horne Company was the first large store in the city to substitute electricity for gas illumination. The Pittsburgh Incline to Knoxville was rebuilt.%0a%0a%0a%0a1890%0aAssessed valuation of Pittsburgh real estate totaled $207,300,000. Annual clearings of the Pittsburgh Clearing House Association totaled $786,694,231.%0a%0a%0a%0a1890%0aPopulation: 238,617; Allegheny City, 105,287; Allegheny County, 551,959.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 16, 1890%0aA. W. Mellon and his brother, Richard B. Mellon, acquired their first stock in the Pittsburgh Reduction Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 25, 1890%0aNellie Bly completed her trip around the globe in 72 days 6 hours and 11 minutes.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 6, 1890%0aAndrew Carnegie repeated his original library proposal first made November 25, 1881, and offered to increase his gift to $1,000,000 to include funds for a museum of natural history and art gallery and for branch libraries.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 13, 1890%0aThe Carnegie Library in Allegheny, the first Carnegie Free Library, was opened to the public after being dedicated by President Benjamin Harrison.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch, 1890%0aOil discovery in Westview.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 4, 1890%0aChildren's Hospital opened.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 17, 1890%0aThe city of Allegheny celebrated its Golden Jubilee.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 15, 1890%0aWestern Pennsylvania Institute for the blind opened in Oakland. The site was given by Mrs. Mary Schenley.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 13, 1890%0aMarc Connelly, playwright, was born in McKeesport, The Second Avenue Line, the city's first successful electric trolley line, began operating between Downtown and Glenwood.%0a%0a%0a%0a1891%0aThe United States Glass Company, one of the country's first large industrial combines, was formed; 17 flintglass factories, most of them in or near Pittsburgh, were acquired.%0a%0a%0a%0a1891%0aA "Roads Congress" was held in Allegheny Carnegie Library lecture hall, under auspices of the Chamber of Commerce, to consider ways of improving public roads.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary, 1891%0aPittsburgh eyes were on nearby Youngwood, where 100 miners were killed in a mine explosion.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 6, 1891%0aAndrew Carnegie gave the promised $1,000,000 to be controlled by a Board of Trustees appointed by the City Council, for a library and other buildings to be erected in Oakland.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 2, 1891%0aCoke workers went on strike at the Morewood mines of the H. C. Frick Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 3, 1891%0aCity Council adopted an ordinance authorizing erection of Carnegie Library on a 19-acre tract acquired from Mrs. Schenley.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 13, 1891%0aSamuel Gompers, of the AFL, hailed the "eight-hour day" during a Pittsburgh visit.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember, 1891%0aThe Alvin Theater opened with Pauline Hall and her opera company in La Belle Helene.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober, 1891%0aThree hundred delegates of the American Street Railway Association assembled at the Monongahela House for their 10th annual national convention. The convention slogan was "The Mule Must Go."%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 19, 1891%0aFirst telephone line between Pittsburgh and New York City was in operation.%0a%0a%0a%0a1892%0aThe Castle Shannon Incline was built. City Council enacted Pittsburgh's first antismoke ordinance, which proved to be a wholly ineffective instrument.%0a%0a%0a%0a1892%0aWestern University of Pennsylvania instituted a Department of Medicine and absorbed the Western Pennsylvania Medical College.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 30, 1892%0aH. C. Frick discharged the entire labor force of 3800 workers at the Homestead works after they threatened to strike for higher wages.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 6, 1892%0aThree hundred Pinkerton men were engaged by millworkers in a pitched battle at the Homestead works after arriving via the Monongahela River on two barges; 16 men were killed and many more wounded.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 6, 1892%0aThe central branch of the Pittsburgh Young Women's Christian Association was incorporated.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 13, 1892%0aNational Guard troops were ordered to Homestead by the governor to prevent further violence; the strike ended soon thereafter.%0a%0a%0a%0a1893%0aHighland Park opened.%0a%0a%0a%0a1893%0aThe Joseph Horne Company opened a modern new six-story building at Penn Avenue and Fifth (Stanwix).%0a%0a%0a%0a1893%0aConstruction work started on "steel headquarters" -- the 15-story Carnegie Building on Fifth Avenue, regarded city's first "skyscraper."%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 20, 1893%0aGround was broken for the first Ferris wheel, invented by George Washington Ferris of the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly, 1893%0aConstruction began for Carnegie Public Library in Oakland.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 7, 1893%0aPhipps Conservatory in Schenley Park was completed.%0a%0a%0a%0a1894%0aFree textbooks were adopted in city schools.%0a%0a%0a%0a1894%0aJones and Laughlin scrapped 40 puddling furnaces and discontinued a highly successful wrought-iron business.%0a%0a%0a%0a1894%0aOliver Wire Company, a merger of all the Oliver wire interests, was incorporated.%0a%0a%0a%0a1894%0aMrs. Mary Schenley presented to the D.A.R. the Blockhouse at the Point.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 15, 1894%0aPittsburgh citizens contributed to a fund to be used to put 1000 to 2000 unemployed men to work on city projects.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril, 1894%0aPittsburgh Stock Exchange was in operation.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 3, 1894%0aThe vanguard of General Coxey's army of 300,000 unemployed men reached Pittsburgh en route to demonstrate in Washington, D. C.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 1, 1894%0aThe city of Pittsburgh annexed the borough of Brushton.%0a%0a%0a%0a1895%0aThe Carnegie Steel Company moved from 48 Fifth Avenue into its new building, the steel frame of which had been allowed to stand unfinished one year to demonstrate the use of steel as a construction material.%0a%0a%0a%0a1895%0aThe National Tube Works of John and Harvey Flagler became the first company in America to manufacture seamless steel tubing by the rotary piercing method for the bicycle, automobile, and pipe industries.%0a%0a%0a%0a1895%0aWomen were first admitted to the Schools of Law and Pharmacy at the Western University of Pennsylvania.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 4, 1895%0aPresbyterian Hospital was founded.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 22, 1895%0aEye and Ear Hospital received a charter to operate.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 13, 1895%0aMiss Agnes Watson was the first woman admitted to the Allegheny County Bar.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 5, 1895%0aThe Carnegie Library building was dedicated and opened to the public in a ceremony marked by Andrew Carnegie's announcement of an additional gift for enlarging the building.%0a%0a%0a%0a1896%0aThe city purchased the Point Bridge for $750,000 and the Smithfield Street Bridge for $1,152,583.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 27, 1896%0aThe Pittsburgh Orchestra, which developed from the "Symphony Society," presented its first concert at Carnegie Music Hall with Frederic Archer as conductor.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 25, 1896%0aThe 22nd Street Bridge, first toll free bridge to be built in the city, was dedicated to public use.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 22, 1896%0aExperimental X-rays were successful at Homeopathic Hospital.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 12, 1896%0aSt. John's Hospital was opened.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 8, 1896%0aAs the result of recurring typhoid epidemics, the city appointed a Pittsburgh Filtration Commission to study water problems; it subsequently recommended that the city's water be filtered.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 25, 1896%0aPittsburgh Stock Exchange officially began operating under that name.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 24, 1896%0aThe conversion from cable cars to electric streetcars began on Fifth Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 7, 1896%0aThe Lumiere company's Cinematographe, the French forerunner of motion pictures, opened in Harry Davis' Avenue Theater.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 23, 1896%0aThe police department organized a bicycle corps.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 5, 1896%0aThe First International Art Exhibition was held at Carnegie Institute with 312 paintings on display; 19 Pittsburgh artists were represented.%0a%0a%0a%0a1897%0aThe 15-story Park Building, one of the city's earliest "skyscrapers," was erected on Fifth Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 3, 1897%0aJoseph Horne and Company department store was destroyed by fire.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 29, 1897%0aThe Union Trust Company and Pittsburgh Stock Exchange were destroyed by fire.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 3, 1897%0aIn a Founders Day speech at Carnegie Institute, President William McKinley praised Pittsburgh for its progressive spirit.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 18, 1897%0aD. Herbert Hostetter announced that five of the largest gas companies in the city were consolidated into a new company capitalized at $5,000,000. He also announced a plan to build an $800,000 plant on the site of the Pittsburgh Gas Company on Second Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0a1898%0aThe Pittsburgh Chamber of Commerce opposed free and unlimited grants of street franchises, contending that they should be held by the city in trust for the people.%0a%0a%0a%0a1898%0aVictor Herbert, cellist and composer of operas, began a six-year reign as conductor of the Pittsburgh Orchestra.%0a%0a%0a%0a1898%0aWilla Cather, novelist, joined the staff of the Pittsburgh Dispatch. Two years later she became reporter for the Pittsburgh Leader, the city's leading newspaper.%0a%0a%0a%0a1898%0aMesta Machine Company was formed by the merger of the Leechburg Foundry (George Mesta) and the Robinson-Rea Manufacturing Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 1, 1898%0aThe borough of Beltzhoover was annexed by the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 29, 1898%0aTroops for service in the Spanish-American War entrained for camp at Mount Gretna.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 4, 1898%0aThe Edgar Thomson Steel Works began shipping rails to South Africa and Japan.%0a%0a%0a%0a1899%0aCity Council authorized a purifying system for the city water supply.%0a%0a%0a%0a1899%0aPittsburgh Coal Company of Pennsylvania was organized.%0a%0a%0a%0a1899%0aThe Duquesne Club erected a five-story building on Sixth Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0a1899%0aNational Tube Works consolidated with other pipe producers to form the National Tube Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 4, 1899%0aJames Whitcomb Riley, poet, lectured in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay, 1899%0aThe city's first six-hole golf course, known as Belmar, was laid out in Homewood, and the Western Pennsylvania Golf Association came into being.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 4, 1899%0aFirst automobile races conducted in Schenley Park.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember, 1899%0aWestern University began playing regular football schedules at Recreation Park; it was the first school in the city to do so.%0a%0a1900's%0a%0a%0a1900%0aAssessed valuation in the city totaled $321,700,000.%0a%0a%0a%0a1900%0aAnnual clearings of the Pittsburgh Clearing House Association amounted to $1,615,641,592.%0a%0a%0a%0a1900%0aIsaac Seder and Jacob A. Frank formed a partnership and organized a wholesale firm known as the Pittsburgh Wrapper Manufacturing Company, the forerunner of the Frank and Seder Store.%0a%0a%0a%0a1900%0aThe 12-story Empire Building was erected at 508 Liberty Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0a1900%0aPopulation: Pittsburgh, 321,616; Allegheny City, 129,896; Allegheny County, 775,058.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch, 1900%0aBarney Dreyfuss began a 32-year reign as owner and president of the Pittsburgh Pirates professional baseball club.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 1, 1900%0aThe Carnegie Company, with capitalization of $320,000,000, was formed by the merger of the H. C. Frick Coke Company and Carnegie Steel Company, Limited.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 1, 1900%0aGrant Boulevard (Bigelow Boulevard), a "rapid transit" road to the east, conceived in 1891 by E. M. Bigelow and cut out of the side of Bedford Hill, was opened to traffic after three years of work.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 14, 1900%0aAt a dinner of Carnegie Institute trustees in the Schenley Hotel, Andrew Carnegie proposed an endowment of $1,000,000 for establishment of a polytechnic school on condition that the city provide a suitable site for it.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 12, 1900%0aAt a testimonial dinner for him in New York, Charles M. Schwab, president of the Carnegie Company, made a speech that impressed one of the guests, J. P. Morgan, and led later to organization of the United States Steel Corporation, the greatest steel corporation in the world.%0a%0a%0a%0a1901%0aThe 18-story Arrott Building on Wood Street and the 16-story Peoples-Pittsburgh Trust Building on Fourth Avenue and Wood were completed.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 1, 1901%0aUnited States Steel was incorporated; the founding companies included Federal Steel Company, American Steel and Wire Company, National Tube, National Steel, American Tin Plate, American Steel Hopp Company, and the American Sheet Steel Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 17, 1901%0aEthelbert Nevin, Pittsburgh composer of "Cradle Song," "A Day in Venice," "The Rosary," and other well-known songs, died.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 7, 1901%0aThe "ripper" act, changing the city charter, became law. William J. Diehl, of the Magee-Flinn "ring," was ousted as mayor; Adam M. Brown, first president of the Allegheny County Bar Association and a judge of Common Pleas Court, was named first city recorder.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 11, 1901%0aAndrew Carnegie sold his steel interests to J. P. Morgan receiving value of $492,000,000 for it.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 14, 1901%0aAndrew Carnegie announced a $4,000,000 pension plan for employees and a gift of $1,000,000 for maintenance of the Homestead, Braddock, and Duquesne libraries established by him.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 17, 1901%0aAll exposition buildings near the Point, excepting Machinery Hall, were destroyed by fire. They were soon replaced by new structures.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 1, 1901%0aJ. P. Morgan completed organization of the world's largest steel trust. The United States Steel Corporation was capitalized at $1,402,000,000. Charles M. Schwab became its first president.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 17, 1901%0aFirst automobile accident in the city was reported.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 20, 1901%0aThe Triangle had a flood equaling that of February 1884, when floodwaters reached a level of over 36 feet.%0a%0a%0a%0a1909 and July 14, 1901%0aThe Amalgamated Association of Iron, Steel and Tin Workers called a general strike against the U.S. Steel Corporation subsidiaries, the first steelworker's strike since 1892.%0aand%0aThe Amalgamated Association of Iron, Steel and Tin Workers was eliminated as a bargaining factor in the steel industry as the result of a 14-month strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 5, 1901%0aNewspapers and the general public demanded construction of a water filter system as hospitals became crowded with 266 victims of typhoid fever.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 21, 1901%0aThe Mellons sold their street car interests to the Philadelphia Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 12, 1901%0aThe new Pennsylvania Railroad Station, at 10th and Liberty, went into service.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 20, 1901%0aThe Iron City Trades Council (Pittsburgh Central Labor Union) was organized by craft and trade unions of the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 10, 1901%0aThe first Sunday gazette was issued.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 27, 1901%0aThe Pittsburgh Railways Company was created by the merger of several city traction companies, including Southern Traction.%0a%0a%0a%0a1902%0aThe l4-story Keystone Bank Building was built at 325 Fourth Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 1902%0aThe Pittsburgh Railways Company took over properties of the Consolidated Traction Company and United Traction Company, and began operating a city-wide system of 400 miles of single track.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 5, 1902%0aAndrew Carnegie announced a gift to form Carnegie Technical Schools, the present Carnegie Institute of Technology.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 30, 1902%0aThe notorious Biddle boys, Edward and John, convicted murderers of grocer Thomas D. Kahney and Detective Patrick Fitzgerald, sawed their way out of their cells, overpowered guards, and escaped from the county jail.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 1, 1902%0aAnother flood disabled the city, the rivers rising to a level of 35.6 feet at the Point.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 15, 1902%0aThe first tenants moved into the 20-story Frick Building, erected by H. C. Frick on Fifth Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 21, 1902%0aThe Daughters of the American Revolution (DAR) won a legal suit to prevent removal of the historic Blockhouse from its original site at the Point.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly, 1902%0aT. Mellon and Sons was incorporated as the Mellon National Bank.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 4, 1902%0aA crowd estimated at between 75,000 and 100,000 assembled on Flagstaff Hill to hear a Fourth of July oration by President Theodore Roosevelt.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 14, 1902%0aThe Union Savings Bank began operations.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 25, 1902%0aHenry Steele Commager, noted historian, was born in the city. Benjamin F. Jones, Sr. died; Jones and Laughlin, Limited, and Laughlin and Company, Limited were reorganized to form Jones and Laughlin Steel Company.%0a%0a%0a%0a1903%0aThe 24-story Farmers Bank Building, on Liberty Avenue, and the 13-story Bessemer Building, at 100 Sixth Street, were constructed.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 24, 1903%0aA "Greater Pittsburgh" bill was passed in Harrisburg to permit annexation of the territory surrounding the city of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 23, 1903%0aThe office of mayor was restored to the city charter; William B. Hays, who had taken office as city recorder on March 17, 1903, assumed the title of mayor.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 9, 1903%0aThe Pennsylvania Railroad presented plans to Councils for construction of a new passenger station in East Liberty.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober, 1903%0aThree months prior to the Wright Brothers' historic Kitty Hawk flight, Samuel Pierpont Langley, director of the Allegheny Observatory and builder of the famous "Whirling Table" in the early 1880s, experimented with a man-carrying airplane, which became known as "Langley's Folly."%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 13, 1903%0aThe first of baseball's modern World Series ended in Pittsburgh before 7455 persons at Exposition Park; the Pirates were defeated by Boston, 4 to 3, and lost the Series three games to five.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 19, 1903%0aThe Wabash Bridge over the Monongahela collapsed.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 4, 1903%0aMrs. Mary E. Schenley died in London.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 7, 1903%0aThe Nixon Theater, built by Samuel F. Nixon-Nirdlinger with support from Senator George T. Oliver and others, was described as the "world's most perfect playhouse" at its formal opening.%0a%0a%0a%0a1904%0aMcCreery's Department Store opened for business at Sixth and Wood with 450 employees.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 23, 1904%0aThe rivers reached a 32-foot flood level.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 4, 1904%0aCity Councils passed an ordinance permitting the Wabash Railroad to enter the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 9, 1904%0aHenry W. Oliver, who was instrumental in opening up the Mesabi iron ore regions to Pittsburgh steel and iron manufacturers, died at the age of 64 at his home at Ridge and Grant Avenues.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 21, 1904%0aVirgin Alley, one of the first streets in the city, was renamed Oliver Avenue in honor of Henry W. Oliver.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 2, 1904%0aAfter three years' struggle and conflict, George Jay Gould's Wabash Railroad operated its first train out of Pittsburgh -- a special to the World's Fair at St. Louis.%0a%0a%0a%0a1905%0aA special windshield glass was invented by Banker Brothers.%0a%0a%0a%0a1905%0aGeorge Jay Gould built his ornate Wabash Railroad terminal and 11-story office building on Liberty Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0a1905%0aGround was broken 20 miles down the Ohio River for the new Aliquippa works of Jones and Laughlin. The Gulf Oil Company began using its first tank wagons in Pittsburgh to haul gasoline and other fuel. The 13-story Diamond National Bank Building was erected.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 3, 1905%0aOn a Schenley Park site provided by the city, ground was broken for the first group of buildings for the Carnegie Technical Schools.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 16, 1905%0aThe world's first mainline electric locomotive was demonstrated in the East Pittsburgh railway yards.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 19, 1905%0aThe "Nickelodeon," the country's first all-motion picture house, was opened by Harry Davis and John P. Harris at 433-35 Smithfield Street with the showing of two short films, "Poor but Honest" and "The Baffled Burglar." It was a great success, with people flocking to the place and marveling at the moving figures.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 25, 1905%0aThe Pennsylvania Railroad began construction of elevated rail-road tracks on Duquesne Way along the Allegheny River.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 16, 1905%0aFirst Carnegie Technical Schools buildings were opened.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 31, 1905%0aThe 'Gayety,' which later became one of the best-known burlesque houses in the nation, opened as a legitimate theater for the carriage trade.%0a%0a%0a%0a1906%0aAmong the large structures built in the city in this year were the Fort Pitt Hotel, the 21-story Commonwealth Building on Fourth Avenue, the 19-story Frick Annex on Diamond, and the 19-story Benedum-Trees Building on Fourth Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 7, 1906%0aThe Carnegie Steel Company announced plans for a $7,000,000 expansion of the Homestead works.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 20, 1906%0aHistoric old City Hall, in "the Diamond," a Civil War landmark, was destroyed by fire.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 4, 1906%0aThe University Club was in the process of purchasing a site on Grant (Bigelow) Boulevard, in the Bellefield district, for its new home.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 2, 1906%0aGeorge W. Guthrie was inaugurated as Mayor. He held office for three years.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 12, 1906%0aBy a majority of 19,943 votes, an act of the Legislature uniting the cities of Pittsburgh and Allegheny was approved in a public referendum.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 1, 1906%0aThe Pennsylvania Railroad's elevated line on Duquesne Way was ready for service, and the removal of tracks from Liberty Avenue (where since 1851 they had occupied the center strip of the street from 11th Street to the Point) was completed.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 24, 1906%0aSt. Paul's Cathedral, one of the city's most notable examples of Gothic architecture, built at a cost of $885,481, was consecrated.%0a%0a%0a%0a1907%0aThe city's first Bureau of Smoke Control was instituted. William Holdship Rea was chief inspector, 1907-09. Pittsburgh Reduction Company was renamed the Aluminum Company of America.%0a%0a%0a%0a1907%0aPittsburgh's death rate was 143.6 per 100,000 persons.%0a%0a%0a%0a1907%0aThe 21-story Union National Bank Building was erected at 306 Fourth Avenue and the 12-story Century Building at 130 Seventh Street.%0a%0a%0a%0a1907%0aThe Frank and Seder organization rented a storeroom on Fifth Avenue and launched a retail business.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 15, 1907%0aDuquesne Way was under nine feet of water and River Avenue on the North Side under 14 feet in a flood that recorded a crest of 38.7 feet.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 11, 1907%0aAndrew Carnegie formally presented the $6,000,000 Carnegie Institute in a dedication ceremony witnessed by 20,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 15, 1907%0aAn ordinance giving the Pittsburgh Subway Company the right to build a subway to East End was introduced in Councils.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 4, 1907%0aThe historic old Union Bridge, built about 1835 over the Allegheny River at the Point, was closed to traffic, and dismantling of it began.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 19, 1907%0aThe Schenley Park oval and matinee race track was opened.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 21, 1907%0aLillian Russell at the Nixon Theatre in the comedy, Wildfire.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 23, 1907%0aThe Pittsburgh Stock Exchange closed for a three-month period because of the effects of the nationwide depression.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 18, 1907%0aThe United States Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of the Guthrie-Watson Greater Pittsburgh bill.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 7, 1907%0aPittsburgh officially annexed Allegheny City and became a city of 521,000 population, the sixth largest in the nation.%0a%0a%0a%0a1908%0aThe number of typhoid cases in Pittsburgh was 1853 for the year 1908, compared with 2969 in 1905, and 5730 in 1906.%0a%0a%0a%0a1908%0aThe Jones and Laughlin Steel Company built a 12-story office building on Ross Street.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 4, 1908%0aBeechview borough was annexed.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary, 1908%0aWages of millworkers at the Homestead works were reduced 10 to 30 per cent by the Carnegie Steel Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 3, 1908%0aJudge Thomas Mellon died at his home on Negley Avenue at the age of 95.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 26, 1908%0aCarry Nation, the celebrated crusader against the saloons, came for a visit.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 11, 1908%0aWestern University of Pennsylvania was rechartered as the University of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 2, 1908%0aAs a climax of the city's sesquicentennial festivities, two cornerstone -- laying ceremonies were staged in Oakland, one for Soldiers and Sailors Memorial Hall and the other for State Hall (School of Mines), first building to be erected in the new University of Pittsburgh campus.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 18, 1908%0aThe city's filtration plant, undertaken in 1905, began delivering the first filtered water to residents.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 4, 1909%0aThe city's first taxicab company, organized by John Weibley, began operating with a fleet of 18 motorized cabs.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 23, 1909%0aCornerstone was laid for the $300,000 East Liberty Y.M.C.A.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 29, 1909%0aPresident William H. Taft arrived for a two-day visit, watched the Pirates lose to Chicago, 8 to 3, and participated in the dedication of Memorial Fountain in Arsenal Park.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 31, 1909%0aGladys Schmitt, novelist, was born in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune, 1909%0aMontefiore Hospital was founded.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 9, 1909%0aThe University of Pittsburgh began its removal from the North Side to Oakland, where it dedicated State Hall, laid the cornerstone for Thaw Hall (School of Engineering) and broke ground for the School of Medicine.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 10, 1909%0aThe Pennsylvania Railroad and borough of Wilkinsburg agreed on a plan for elevating the main-line tracks and thus eliminating all grade crossings in the borough.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 27, 1909%0aMayor William A. Magee, inaugurated on April 5 of this year was credited with settling the two-day strike of 2900 motormen and conductors; settlement was a blow to railroads, which had put on 400 extra cars in absence of trolley service.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 29, 1909%0aIn the final game played in Exposition Park, the Pittsburgh Pirates defeated Chicago, 8 to 1.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 30, 1909%0aForbes Field, named after the head of the British forces in 1758, General John Forbes, was dedicated; 30,338 persons watched the Pirates lose the opening game there to Chicago, 3 to 2.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 15, 1909%0aRioting workers of the Pressed Steel Car Company, near McKees Rocks, clashed with guards; Coal and Iron Police and State Constabulary were called out; many strikers were wounded by volleys of buckshot fired to halt their charges; state police were ordered to "shoot to kill" if attacked by strikers.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 23, 1909%0aFive were killed, scores injured in two more riot battles between police and Press Steel Car strikers.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 29, 1909%0aPlans were announced for a $450,000 state armory (18th Regiment) on a site in Schenley Farms.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 12, 1909%0aThe Pittsburgh Aero Club was organized, with Philip S. Flinn as first president, and planned an international balloon race for Pittsburgh as its first project.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 16, 1909%0aThe Pittsburgh Pirates, winners of 110 games in their regular season, defeated the Detroit Tigers, 8 to 0, to win the seventh and deciding game of the World Series before 17,562 fans at Forbes Field.%0a%0a%0a%0a1910%0aPopulation: Pittsburgh, 553,905; Allegheny County, 1,018,463.%0a%0a%0a%0a1910%0aU. S. Bureau of Mines established a center in Oakland District.%0a%0a%0a%0a1910%0aAnnual clearings of the Pittsburgh Clearing House amounted to $2,587,325,785.%0a%0a%0a%0a1910%0aNew 215-bed Homeopathic Hospital opened at Center and Aiken avenues. Assessed valuation of real estate in the city rose to $745,700,000.%0a%0a%0a%0a1910%0aA. W. and R. B. Mellon announced that they were providing funds for creation of Mellon Institute for Industrial Research.%0a%0a%0a%0a1910%0aThe Pittsburgh Courier was published for the first time.%0a%0a%0a%0a1910%0aJohn Kowalski, marine engine maker, recorded the first flight of an airplane built in Pittsburgh when he accidentally took off in a four-cylinder plane he had devised.%0a%0a%0a%0a1910%0aBecause of lack of funds, the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra was disbanded.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 23, 1910%0aThree were dead and communications and streetcar service disrupted in a nine-inch snowfall.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 1, 1910%0aThe new Henry W. Oliver Building, 25 floors high, was ready for occupancy.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 9, 1910%0aSoldiers and Sailors Memorial Hall was dedicated.%0a%0a%0a%0a1911%0aThe Pittsburgh Industrial Development Commission was organized by the Chamber of Commerce for the purpose of securing diversified industries for Pittsburgh; it received contributions of $136,473 to begin work. The Jenkins Arcade was erected on Liberty Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 1911%0aThe first old age retirement plan for United States Steel employees was created with a fund of $12,000,000. of which $4,000,000 had been provided by Andrew Carnegie ten years before.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 19, 1911%0aThe Elizabeth Steel Magee Hospital, founded by Christopher L. Magee, began operation.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 2, 1911%0aNew St. Joseph's Hospital was opened to the public.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 1, 1911%0aThe Pittsburgh Catholic College of the Holy Ghost became Duquesne University and was chartered to award degrees in major educational fields.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 16, 1911%0aThe county commissioners formally declared the Sixth, Seventh, Ninth, 16th, and 30th Street Bridges free to the public.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 26, 1911%0aA new city charter act, replacing the Select and Common Councils with a single Council of nine members, was signed by Governor John K. Tener.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 5, 1911%0aCalbraith Perry Rodgers, Pittsburgh aviator, completed the first transcontinental flight, which started at Sheepshead Bay, Long Island, on September 17. Rodgers Field in Allegheny County was later named for him.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 23, 1911%0aAn Art Commission was organized under a state act to pass official judgment on plans for buildings, bridges, and other structures in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 31, 1911%0aNew West Penn Hospital was opened.%0a%0a%0a%0a1912%0aThe 26-story First National Bank Building, the city's tallest to this date, was erected at 511 Wood Street.%0a%0a%0a%0a1912%0aThe Syria Mosque in Oakland was dedicated.%0a%0a%0a%0a1912%0aThe Gulf Oil Company opened on Baum Boulevard the first company-owned service station in the world, forerunner of the modern super-service station.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 22, 1912%0aA 28-foot crest was reached by the rivers.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 5, 1912%0aA contract was let for the grading of Grant's Hill on Fifth Avenue from Smithfield Street to Sixth Avenue and from Fourth to Sixth Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 20, 1912%0aThe Carnegie Technical Schools were renamed Carnegie Institute of Technology.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 12, 1912%0aAlexander Moore, editor of the Pittsburgh Leader, was married to the singer, Lillian Russell.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 18, 1912%0aIn a pre-election speech before 12,000 persons at Duquesne Gardens, Governor Woodrow Wilson, of New Jersey, Democratic candidate for president, attacked the government's "protective tariff."%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 19, 1912%0aThe Pitt Panthers were defeated, 45 to 8, by Jim Thorpe and the Carlisle Indians.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 21, 1912%0aWilliam Jennings Bryan appeared before 4000 at the Lyceum and made three other speeches in the Pittsburgh district in behalf of the democratic ticket.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 5, 1912%0aAlthough Woodrow Wilson won over Bull Moose candidate Theodore Roosevelt and regular Republican candidate William Howard Taft in the presidential election, Roosevelt carried Pittsburgh by a plurality of 8300 votes.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 26, 1912%0aAndrew Carnegie, at 77, turned over all but $25,000,000 of his vast fortune to the Carnegie Corporation for charitable and philanthropic distribution.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 11, 1912%0aCity and county officials agreed on a joint plan to erect a City-County Building at Grant and Diamond.%0a%0a%0a%0a1913%0aThe Bell Telephone Company of Pennsylvania built a 20-story office building and equipment headquarters on Seventh Street.%0a%0a%0a%0a1913%0aThe Central District Telephone and Printing Company was incorporated with other telephone companies into the Central District Telephone Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 1913%0aThe first parcel-post deliveries were made in Pittsburgh by the post office at a rate of five cents for the first pound and one cent for each additional pound.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 9, 1913%0aThe rivers crested at 31 feet in another flood.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 14, 1913%0aThe famous evangelist Billy Sunday held a revival meeting in a tabernacle erected for that purpose on the site of the present Heinz Chapel.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 25, 1913%0aA number of people were killed in a sewer explosion.%0a%0a%0a%0a1914%0aDr. Heinrich Koppers sold the patents for his by-product coke ovens to Andrew Mellon for $300,000, and the Koppers Company, founded in Illinois, was reorganized with main offices in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0a1914%0aThe Gulf Oil Company began the practice of issuing free road maps to motorists, one of the most successful promotion efforts in the country.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 1914%0aExcavations of 14.9 feet at Fifth and Grant and of 16.3 feet at Fifth and Wylie completed the grading of Grants Hill.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 25, 1914%0aA public subscription campaign for the University of Pittsburgh was completed with a total of $2,000,000 collected.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 10, 1914%0aThe cornerstone was laid for the Masonic Temple on Fifth Avenue in Oakland.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 12, 1914%0aGeorge Westinghouse died in his country home in Lenox, Massachusetts.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 5, 1914%0aTen thousand Westinghouse workers went on strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 31, 1914%0aThe Pittsburgh Stock Exchange suspended operations (for four months) because of the economic effects of the World War.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 6, 1914%0aEugene (Wild Bill) Heth piloted a Wright biplane to Pittsburgh, the first to carry a passenger, Colonel Harry C. Fry, to the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 1, 1915%0aThe Carnegie Steel Company announced that it was increasing employment rolls by 8000 in order to meet increasing demands for steel.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 26, 1915%0aThe Mellon Institute for Industrial Research, on O'Hara Street, Oakland, was dedicated.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 1, 1915%0aAll steel mills in Pittsburgh were operating night and day to meet steel demands of nations at war.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 9, 1915%0aThe new Manchester Bridge, connecting the Point with the North Side, was ready for traffic.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 9, 1915%0aRosenbaum and Company moved into its new building at Sixth and Liberty.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 24, 1915%0aHenry Clay Frick repaid schoolchildren the savings ($169,000) they lost when the Pittsburgh Bank for Savings closed its doors.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary, 1916%0aThe Pittsburgh Coal Company was created through the merger of the Pittsburgh Coal Company of Pennsylvania and the Monongahela River Consolidated Coal and Coke Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch, 1916%0aThe William Penn Hotel was completed on Grant Street at Sixth at a cost of $6,000,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 18, 1916%0aThe cornerstone was laid for the new City-County Building.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 27, 1916%0aA strike of 24,000 miners was settled.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 1, 1916%0aMartial law was declared in Braddock following riots at the Edgar Thomson works.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 9, 1916%0aThirty thousand Westinghouse workers were on strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 30, 1916%0aPittsburgh troops entrained for the Mexican border as trouble increased in Mexico.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 6, 1916%0aA $200,000 fire destroyed the city block bounded by Second and Third avenues and Market and Ferry streets.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 25, 1916%0aThe Mellons purchased a site at the corner of Smithfield Street and Oliver Avenue for construction of a new bank building.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 16, 1916%0aBeginning of the last exposition held in the old Exposition Buildings.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 17, 1916%0aSchenley High School in Oakland opened.%0a%0a%0a%0a1917%0aThe 15-story Union Trust Building, rated architecturally as one of the finest structures in the nation, was erected on a Grant Street block-square site.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 27, 1917%0aThe Grand Opera House was destroyed by fire, along with other Fifth Avenue buildings, including the Frank and Seder Store.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 1, 1917%0aThe new Chamber of Commerce Building, at Seventh and Smithfield, was completed.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 5, 1917%0aEnrico Caruso, the great Italian tenor, gave his first Pittsburgh concert.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 20, 1917%0aThe first draft lists were published; many Pittsburghers were destined to go overseas in the 28th and 80th divisions.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 25, 1917%0aEx-President Theodore Roosevelt visited the city; 30,000 people listened to his address.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 29, 1917%0aThe University of Pittsburgh organized a hospital unit to go overseas.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 22, 1917%0aTrolley fares were raised to six cents.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 24, 1917%0aTwenty were killed in a Mount Washington streetcar accident in one of the city's worst transit tragedies.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 7, 1918%0aThe new Grand Theater (Warner) was opened on the site of the old Opera House.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 11, 1918%0aPittsburgh branch of the Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland began business at Ninth Street and Liberty.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 1, 1918%0aDaylight-saving time, conceived and promoted by Robert Garland, of Pittsburgh, went into effect.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 23, 1918%0aSixteenth Street Bridge burned.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 18, 1918%0aExplosion at nearby Etna Chemical Company killed 114 persons, many of them were residents of the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 1, 1918%0aA Red Cross benefit show, starring George M. Cohan, established a box-office record for the city with one-night receipts of $138,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 12, 1918%0aPittsburgh ranked third in the nation in per capita sales of war savings stamps.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 24, 1918%0aPittsburgh fire fighters staged a strike for higher wages, leaving the city without fire protection for six hours.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 5, 1918%0aAn influenza epidemic, starting at the Cantonment Hospital in Point Breeze, victimized 23,268 Pittsburgh residents. Of the total, 1374 died of lobar pneumonia and 678 of bronchopneumonia.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 20, 1918%0aAllegheny County went $10,000,000 over its $165,000,000 quota in the fourth Liberty Loan drive.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 29, 1918%0aA group of the city's leading citizens met and formulated the Citizens Committee on City Plan for Pittsburgh; C. D. Armstrong was elected president; R. B. Mellon, vice-president, and J. D. Hailman, secretary.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 11, 1918%0aA summary at the Armistice showed approximately 60,000 Allegheny County men had seen service in the war, mostly in the 80th and 28th divisions; 1527 died or were killed in action; government war contracts executed in Pittsburgh totaled $215,405,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember, 1918%0aFrederick Bigger, one of the city's first planning engineers, was named full-time executive secretary of the Citizens Committee on City Plan; under his direction work was started toward a master plan; studies were initiated to cover playgrounds, a street plan, transit problems, parks, railroads, and waterways%0a%0a%0a%0a1919%0aNatural gas was discovered in nearby McKeesport.%0a%0a%0a%0a1919%0aAir transportation was inaugurated in Pittsburgh with the organization of the Kennedy Aircraft Company.%0a%0a%0a%0a1919%0aMayer Field, Pittsburgh's first commercial airport, was established in Bridgeville by Casper P. Mayer, realtor and aviation pioneer.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch, 1919%0aThe Aero Club -- for Pitt and Carnegie Tech war fliers -- was organized in a leather shop on First Avenue, with Barney Mulvihill as president and Joseph M. (Hap) Slater as vice-president.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 10, 1919%0aThe Pittsburgh district went over the top in the fifth Liberty Loan with subscriptions totaling $117,210,350.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 14, 1919%0aHenry John Heinz, founder of the H. J. Heinz Company, one of the world's largest food manufacturing firms and owner of one of the nation's outstanding private art collections, died of pneumonia at the age of 75 at his home, 7009 Penn Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 15, 1919%0aThe streetcar system suspended operation at midnight when motormen and conductors struck to enforce demands for a 12-cent hourly pay increase.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 8, 1919%0aPittsburgh voters authorized a $22,996,000 improvement program, including $6,000,000 for a proposed Downtown subway system.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 1, 1919%0aThe five cent zone fare was discontinued; trolley fares were raised to 10 cents.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 11, 1919%0aAndrew Carnegie died in his eighty fourth year at his summer home, "Shadowbrook," in Lenox, Massachusetts, after three days of pneumonia. His philanthropies up to this time had totaled $350,000,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 15, 1919%0aThree thousand streetcar men again walked off the job, this time in protest against War Labor Board's award of a six-cent-an-hour raise, only half of what they asked.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 26, 1919%0aThe Pittsburgh Railways Company attempted to operate strike-bound cars; the result was a series of riots in downtown Pittsburgh and other sections of the city; many of the strikers were injured.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 28, 1919%0aThe streetcar strike was broken when the national union expelled local leaders; the strikers returned to work with great reluctance.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 21, 1919%0aA campaign to unionize the steel industry started in Pittsburgh when a strike was called by National Committee for Organizing Iron and Steel Workers, headed by William Z. Foster, later general secretary of the American Communist party; 365,000 steel workers struck throughout nation for union recognition and reduction of the 12-hour day.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 29, 1919%0aThe United States Bureau of Mines dedicated its new $1,000,000 laboratories on Forbes Street in a three-day ceremony.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 17, 1919%0aDr. Frank Conrad began regular broadcasting of phonograph records (8XK).%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 23, 1919%0aKing Albert of Belgium visited the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 1, 1919%0aForty two thousand miners in Pittsburgh district left jobs in start of nationwide strike closing coal mines; the National Guard was alerted.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 2, 1919%0aGulf Oil Company opened its first Downtown gasoline service station, at Liberty Avenue and Water Street.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 2, 1919%0aHenry Clay Frick, industrial and financial leader of Pittsburgh, died suddenly at his New York residence at the age of 69; his body was brought to Pittsburgh for burial. His philanthropies while living were said to total $60,000,000. His probated will disposed of a total estate of $143,000,000 and left $20,000,000 to public, educational, and charitable institutions of Pittsburgh. The city received a 150-acre plot for a park in Fern Hollow, below Beechwood Boulevard, in addition to a $2,000,000 endowment fund to maintain it.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 10, 1919%0aThe nationwide coal strike ended, but a national coal conservation order, restricting use of coal everywhere except in private homes, went into effect under rigid enforcement.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 20, 1919%0aGround was broken for the Liberty Tubes with Governor William C. Sproul participating.%0a1920%0a"Population: 588,343; Allegheny County, 1,018,463.%0a%0a%0aJanuary 2, 1920%0aA total of 233 suspected leaders of the Communist movement in Pittsburgh were arrested by federal agents in two days as part of a nationwide roundup ordered by Attorney General A. Mitchell Palmer.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 11, 1920%0aJudges wore gowns in court for the first time in Allegheny County.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 13, 1920%0aThe Pennsylvania Railroad announced a $100,000,000 improvement and expansion program for the Pittsburgh area.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 15, 1920%0aHenry Ford came to Pittsburgh to place in person $15,000,000 worth of steel contracts in the area.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 20, 1920%0aThe national steel workers' organizing strike ended after the fourth month without achieving its objective.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 22, 1920%0aB. F. Jones, Jr., of Jones and Laughlin Steel, purchased the old Monongahela House for $750,000 with the intention of converting it into an office building.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 28, 1920%0aThe great Italian tenor, Enrico Caruso, sang at the Syria Mosque.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 1, 1920%0aThe United States Supreme Court declined to dissolve the United States Steel Corporation and its subsidiary companies as asked by the federal government in a suit alleging violation of antitrust laws.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 28, 1920%0aDr. John Brashear, noted astronomer and maker of astronomical lenses and other scientific instruments, died at 80 at his South Side home.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune, 1920%0aThe Citizens Committee completed the first of a series of six major studies leading toward a comprehensive city plan, issued a report analyzing the city's recreational deficiencies, and recommended a system of playgrounds.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 2, 1920%0aAllegheny County women appeared at polling places to cast their first ballots.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 2, 1920%0aStation KDKA, first licensed radio broadcasting station, gave the Harding-Cox election returns as its first scheduled broadcast Allegheny County gave Harding a plurality of 105,000 over Governor Cox.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 6, 1920%0aRepeated landslides occurred below Bigelow Boulevard as rainfall continued; engineers waged a losing fight in their efforts to stop the slides and protect Pennsylvania Railroad tracks.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 20, 1920%0aGeneral George W. Goethals, builder of the Panama Canal, on invitation of city officials, came to Pittsburgh and inspected the Bigelow Boulevard slide. He reported: "The situation will prevail until all has come down."%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 31, 1920%0aThe Citizens Committee on City Plan was incorporated and chartered as the Municipal Planning Association, with a goal of promoting "orderly and efficient development of municipalities" and "scientific methods of city and municipal planning."%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 2, 1921%0aChurch service was broadcast from the Calvary Protestant Episcopal Church in East Liberty -- the worlds first such broadcast.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 4, 1921%0aAndrew W. Mellon, Pittsburgh financier, was appointed Secretary of the Treasury, and James J. Davis, former union steelworker of Pittsburgh, was named Secretary of Labor in the cabinet of President Warren G. Harding.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 16, 1921%0aTo relieve traffic congestion, City Council banned automobile parking on Downtown streets between 4:30 and 6 P.M. daily.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 25, 1921%0aMadame Marie Curie, famed French scientist and co-discoverer of radium, arrived in Pittsburgh for a visit but was taken ill and confined to the home of Mrs. Henry R. Rea in Sewickley. Although weak from her illness, Madame Curie appeared at Memorial Hall the following day to receive her fifty-ninth honorary degree, conferred by Chancellor Bow-man of the University of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 4, 1921%0aThe Carnegie Corporation of New York announced a $21,662,888 appropriation for Carnegie Institute and Carnegie Tech.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 29, 1921%0aThe Reverend Hugh C. Boyle was consecrated bishop of the Catholic diocese of Pittsburgh; 100,000 persons assembled in and around St. Paul's Cathedral for the ceremony.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 30, 1921%0aThe $30,000,000 will of the late steel magnate, William P. Snyder, was contested in court.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 13, 1921%0aThe body of Thomas F. Enright, first American soldier killed in action in the World War, was brought home to Pittsburgh. The Enright Theater in East Liberty was later named in his honor.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 8, 1921%0aThe Boulevard of the Allies was dedicated.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober, 1921%0aKQV, the city's second radio station, began operation.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 4, 1921%0aSecretary of War Weeks gave the county commissioners final warning to raise all bridges over the Allegheny River in order to make the river free for navigation.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 4, 1921%0aCensus report for 1920 listed 20,297 persons over 10 years of age in Pittsburgh as illiterate.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 8, 1921%0aWilliam A. Magee, Republican, was elected Mayor of Pittsburgh by 50,000 votes over William N. McNair, Democrat.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 10, 1921%0aMarshal Ferdinand Foch, leader of French forces in the war, was given a tremendous ovation during a daylong visit to Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 26, 1921%0aA. W. and R. B. Mellon presented a 14-acre H. C. Frick estate tract in Oakland, valued at $2,500,000, to the University of Pittsburgh for further development of a campus. This became the site of the Cathedral of Learning.%0a%0a%0a%0a1922%0aRadio Station WCAE began broadcasting.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 2, 1922%0aMrs. Enoch Rauh, long active in welfare work, became the first woman to hold a cabinet post in a major Pennsylvania city when she took office as head of the Department of Charities in the new Magee administration.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 2, 1922%0aWestinghouse's radio station KDKA at East Pittsburgh was broadcasting nightly from 7:30 to 10 o'clock.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 9, 1922%0aMrs. Minnie Penfield was the first woman to serve on a jury in Allegheny County.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 9, 1922%0aThe cost of the Boulevard of the Allies, nearing completion, was expected to be $1,600,000 per mile, said to be most expensive road construction job in the world.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 15, 1922%0aHotel Chatham, a "popular hostelry" on lower Penn Avenue, was purchased by the Manufacturers Club of Pittsburgh for its headquarters.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 11, 1922%0aThe first Liberty Tube was completed.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 3, 1922%0aAnnouncement was made of a $7,000,000 plan to develop the Hotel Schenley into a "galaxy of the finest and most modern metropolitan structures" by building apartments immediately adjoining the hotel.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 5, 1922%0aA posse of humane agents routed 500 "cocking main" enthusiasts assembled in an amphitheater at Keller's Grove, Mount Nebo Road, a historic spot for cock fighting.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 6, 1922%0aMrs. Lillian Russell Moore, wife of Alexander Moore, died at the age of 61 at her Point Breeze home.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 21, 1922%0aPart of Reserve Township was annexed to the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 5, 1922%0aA new record for auto fatalities in a single day in Allegheny County was established when the coroner's office reported five deaths.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 21, 1922%0aA $1,000,000 fire destroyed three buildings at the Duquesne Steel Foundry.%0a%0a%0a%0a1923%0aJones and Laughlin became a corporation and sold its first stock on the open market.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 13, 1923%0aHenry Ford announced purchase of the Allegheny Plate Glass Company plant at Glassmere for establishment of the first Ford plant in the Pittsburgh district.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 14, 1923%0aDaily newspapers Dispatch and Leader ceased publication.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 4, 1923%0aAlexander Moore, of Pittsburgh, was appointed ambassador to Spain.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 5, 1923%0aThe Pittsburgh Skin and Cancer Foundation opened a clinic at 1901 Fifth Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 6, 1923%0aGovernor Pinchot created a Metropolitan Plan Commission for the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust, 1923%0aHarry Greb, of Pittsburgh, defeated Johnny Wilson in New York to win the middleweight title he held for three years.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust, 1923%0aThe city's first zoning ordinance, one of the earliest in the United States, became effective amid claims of opposition that it would discourage construction in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober, 1923%0aThe Municipal Planning Association issued its final report; it included recommendations for canalization of the Ohio River, a river rail terminal, greater use of wharves, and a system of water-storage reservoirs for flood protection advocated by the 1911 Flood Commission.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 2, 1923%0aBoulevard of the Allies was opened to traffic.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 24, 1923%0aHistoric Mount Mercy Academy, on Fifth Avenue, suffered $100,000 damages in a fire which injured seven.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 24, 1923%0aIn a speech at Syria Mosque, David Lloyd George, war-time Premier of Great Britain, pleaded for mercy to end wars.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 27, 1923%0aThe last horse car on Sarah Street suspended operation.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 13, 1923%0aTwenty thousand persons attended formal opening of new banking room of Union Trust Company at Fifth and Grant.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 13, 1923%0aThe first unit traffic-light system was installed as an experiment at all corners intersecting the Boulevard of the Allies in the downtown area.%0a%0a%0a%0a1924%0aBettis Field, sponsored by Samuel Brendel, Harry Neal, and D. Parr Peat, of McKeesport, was established on the Pittsburgh-McKeesport road as a commercial flying enterprise.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 1924%0aThe Schenley Apartments, consisting of five structures in a new-type housing development, were ready for occupancy at monthly rents of $150 and up.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 4, 1924%0aThe rivers hit a crest of 30.4 feet causing $5,000,000 damage, heaviest from a flood in the city since 1913.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 30, 1924%0aThe Liberty Tubes were opened for a two-week chemical test.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 7, 1924%0aParts of lower St. Clair Township were annexed.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 10, 1924%0aIt was announced that the first city-county airport would be built and named in honor of Calbraith Perry Rodgers of the city, first aviator to span the U.S. on November 5, 1911.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 21, 1924%0aA few days after her final performance in The Closed Door here, Eleanora Duse, celebrated tragedienne on tour, died in her suite at the Schenley Hotel.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 10, 1924%0aThe city's fifth trolley strike in 15 years started; the Downtown area was jammed with automobile traffic; the Pittsburgh Railways imported 900 electric railways operators and guards from New York to run trolleys.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 10, 1924%0aThe Liberty Tubes were closed for further work on the ventilation system after 12 persons were overcome by gas; a trolley strike had caused a traffic jam in them.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 12, 1924%0aMotormen and conductors voted to return to work, ending the 39-hour streetcar strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 22, 1924%0aSeven police inspectors and three fire chiefs were demoted in the biggest police shake-up in 20 years.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune, 1924%0aRodgers Airfield, on a 41-acre tract near Aspinwall, was completed for operation as the first city-county airport.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 3, 1924%0aA total of $2,266,893 was pledged by 8341 Jewish residents of the city for construction of new Montefiore Hospital.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 4, 1924%0aCalvin Coolidge, in winning the presidential election, carried Allegheny County by 75,000 votes.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 6, 1924%0aPitt Chancellor John G. Bowman announced plans for a "52-story" Gothic skyscraper to be built at a cost of $10,000,000 and known as the Cathedral of Learning.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 1, 1924%0aIn the face of heated protests, the county commissioners asked for bids for the razing of the Ninth Street Bridge.%0a%0a%0a%0a1925%0aThe United States Steel Corporation developed a process for producing seamless pipe 16 inches in diameter, more than twice the size previously possible.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 1, 1925%0aBurton W. Marsh, the city's first traffic engineer, submitted his first traffic survey to City Council, recommending strict parking regulations for the downtown area.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 8, 1925%0aH. P. Davis, president of Westinghouse, urged broadcasting stations to link themselves together by short wave for simultaneous broadcasting of programs.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 31, 1925%0aCity Council enacted an ordinance eliminating the practice of compelling policemen to work two days a month without pay.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 1, 1925%0aA city assessor's report fixed total taxable values of Pittsburgh's 28 wards of realty at $990,000,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 13, 1925%0aA bill to create a Greater Pittsburgh by joining all boroughs and townships to the city was killed in committee at Harrisburg.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 22, 1925%0aGeorge Mesta died.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 10, 1925%0aEvangeline Booth visited the city to dedicate the new Salvation Army home for business girls, located on the Boulevard of the Allies.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 13, 1925%0aCounty commissioners tabled action on a plan to remove the county jail from Its Ross Street site, purchase nearby sites, and erect a $3,500,000 county office skyscraper and jail.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 14, 1925%0aThe largest electric locomotive in the world, 152 feet long and weighing 1,275,900 pounds, was given a test run at Westinghouse's East Pittsburgh yards.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 19, 1925%0aThe fund for construction of the Cathedral of Learning reached a total of $5,597,782 -- more than twice as much as ever raised in the city's history for an educational or philanthropic purpose.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 23, 1925%0aThe Young Men's and Women's Hebrew Association in Oakland was dedicated.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 26, 1925%0aThe Philadelphia Company dedicated its new $3,500,000 building, on Sixth Avenue, and President Arthur W. Thompson announced a five-year, $100,000,000 utility improvement program.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 27, 1925%0aThe Keystone Athletic Club announced purchase of the old St. Charles Hotel property, at Third Avenue and Wood, and plans for construction of a 20-story, $3,000,000 building.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 8, 1925%0aPlans were announced for erection of another Downtown skyscraper -- the Law and Finance Building.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 26, 1925%0aPitt Stadium, with a capacity of 60,000, was formally opened with the Panthers defeating Washington and Lee, 28 to 0, before a crowd of 20,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 15, 1925%0aThe Pittsburgh Pirates defeated the Washington Senators, 9 to 7, in the seventh and deciding game of the World Series before 42,856 at Forbes Field; Downtown stores suspended business, and traffic stopped as Pittsburghers celebrated the victory.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember, 1925%0aGeneral W. W. Atterbury, president of the Pennsylvania Railroad, in Pittsburgh with other railroad officials to inspect the $14,000,000 station and street improvement program, stated: "While Pittsburgh has called for all the Pennsylvania Railroad could produce, Pittsburgh itself has been our greatest producer." Motor buses were introduced on a large scale on city streets.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 6, 1925%0aUnited States Steel stock jumped 5-1/2 points in one day to 138, highest quotation ever recorded to this date.%0a%0a%0a%0a1926%0aThe $1,650,000 Webster Hall, on Fifth Avenue, was erected as a hotel to specialize in club residences for men.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 5, 1926%0aR. B. Mellon, president of the Mellon National Bank, was elected chairman of Allegheny County Planning Commission.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 26, 1926%0aMarcus Loew announced plans to erect the largest theater in Pennsylvania, a 4000-seat house on the site of the old Hotel Anderson, Sixth and Penn, at cost of $2,500,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 3, 1926%0aTwenty men were killed in an explosion that wrecked a mine of the Pittsburgh Terminal Company at Horning, near Castle Shannon.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch, 1926%0aThe Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra, reorganized and financed by its own musicians, began playing public concerts.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 18, 1926%0aPittsburgh voters approved a $19,902,000 bond issue for various city improvements.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 12, 1926%0aApproximately $60,000,000 was being expended to improve steel mills in the area.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 13, 1926%0aThe new Seventh Street Bridge was opened.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 28, 1926%0aPlans were announced for a $7,000,000 campaign for establishment of a Presbyterian "medical center."%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 28, 1926%0aDuquesne Light Company announced a plan to build the "largest and most modern" electric power plant in the world at Shippingport on the Ohio River at a cost of $40,000,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 27, 1926%0aGround was broken for the University of Pittsburgh's Cathedral of Learning.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember, 1926%0aDouble-deck trolleys, declared too dangerous for Pittsburgh, were abandoned.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 6, 1926%0aOfficial opening was held for Armstrong Tunnels, named for Commissioner Joseph G. Armstrong.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 13, 1926%0aAn air show featured dedication of Bettis Field as a Pittsburgh-McKeesport airport.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 27, 1926%0aCarnegie Tech upset Notre Dame, 19 to 0 at Forbes Field before 45,000.%0a%0a%0a%0a1927%0aConstruction crews began erecting the Pittsburgher Hotel on Diamond Street.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 1, 1927%0aForty-five thousand miners in the district joined in a nationwide coal strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 21, 1927%0aCarrying .a single pouch of mail, an open cockpit Waco belonging to Clifford Ball, Inc., the city's pioneer airline, inaugurated airmail service between Pittsburgh and Cleveland.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 24, 1927%0aAfter a Sunday concert, which drew an audience of 4000, nine members of the executive board of the Pittsburgh Symphony were arrested on charges of violating "blue laws". All were found guilty and fined $25 each by Alderman Samuel McKinley; group included Richard S. Rauh, secretary of the society; Edward Specter, chairman of the orchestra committee; Elias Breeskin, assistant conductor, and seven others.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 3, 1927%0aCarrick Borough was annexed to the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 12, 1927%0aThe Buhl Foundation was established with a $15,000,000 gift announced by Henry Buhl, Jr.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 12, 1927%0aThe New Point Bridge was dedicated.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 25, 1927%0aFrick Park, 380 acres in Squirrel Hill willed to the city by H. C. Frick, was opened for public use.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 2, 1927%0aAfter a series of negotiations the Post-Gazette came into being under ownership of Paul Block, and the Sun-Telegraph was organized under ownership of William Randolph Hearst.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 3, 1927%0aCharles Lindbergh, the first to fly alone over the Atlantic to Europe, was feted by the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 12, 1927%0aThe widening of Grant Street, Downtown, was started.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober, 1927%0aThe new Roosevelt Hotel, at Sixth Street and Penn, was opened.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 8, 1927%0aThe Pittsburgh Pirates lost the fourth straight game of the World Series, 4 to 3, to the New York Yankees.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 13, 1927%0aPresident Coolidge was guest speaker at the Carnegie Institute's 31st Founders Day exercises at Carnegie Music Hall. He also appeared before Carnegie Tech students in accordance with a promise made to them by Samuel H. Church, Institute president, and made a speech -- a nine word address: "I shall not break Colonel Church's promise to you."%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 27, 1927%0aJ. P. Morgan, Jr., New York financier, became chairman of the board of the United States Steel Corporation.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 27, 1928%0aStanley Theater opened.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 27, 1928%0aThe Liberty Bridge was dedicated and opened to public use.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay, 1928%0aThe 23-story Clark Building, on Liberty Avenue, was ready for occupancy.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 2, 1928%0aAir express service was inaugurated between Pittsburgh and Cleveland by the Clifford Ball Air Line; 1000 spectators watched Pilot Dewey Noyes take off in a plane carrying first express parcels.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 31, 1928%0aThe National Elimination Balloon Races, witnessed by 150,000 persons at Bettis Field, resulted in the death of two balloonists -- W. W. Morton and Lieutenant Paul Evert, of the United States Army.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 26, 1928%0aAllegheny County voters approved a $43,680,000 bond issue for public works, including $6,000,000 for a town hall, $2,550,000 for a county office building, and $10,930,000 for new boulevards and highways.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 3, 1928%0aFire destroyed the Cameo Theater building at 347 Fifth Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 12, 1928%0aState Superior Court approved Sunday symphony concerts for Pittsburgh; Sabbath Association announced it intended nevertheless to demand enforcement of the blue laws of 1794.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 16, 1928%0aThe first film "talkie," titled Tenderloin, was introduced at the Stanley Theater. Previewers said it had less than 10 minutes' "audible" dialogue, and one commented the "project is so new that its possibilities scarcely can be gauged yet."%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 17, 1928%0aCalled the "scenic boulevard of Pittsburgh," Mount Washington Roadway, to the top of Mount Washington, was opened with a mile-long parade followed by a celebration.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 8, 1928%0aWestinghouse staged what was said to be the world's first demonstration of "motion pictures broadcast by radio" -- "television" -- in its East Pittsburgh laboratories. The idea was worked out by Dr. Frank Conrad, assistant chief engineer at Westinghouse.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 15, 1928%0aAir passenger service from the city was instituted.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 28, 1928%0aSite for a new county airport (Lebanon Church Road) was chosen.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 6, 1928%0aIn the election of Herbert Hoover as President, Allegheny County gave Hoover 213,681 votes, and Al Smith 159,718.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 19, 1928%0aTwo thousand scientists, representing 20 different nations, assembled at Carnegie Tech for the opening of the Second International Conference on Bituminous Coal, initiated in 1926 by Tech President Thomas S. Baker.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 26, 1928%0aA constitutional amendment to permit Pittsburgh and Allegheny County to consolidate into a metropolitan district was approved by a state-wide vote.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 11, 1929%0aDeclaring that the city should assume leadership in the fight against air pollution, City Council authorized installation of smoke prevention equipment at the city's pumping station at Brilliant.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 13, 1929%0aPresident James A. Farrell, of the United States Steel Corporation, announced a $20,000,000 expansion program for subsidiary plants at Duquesne, McKeesport, and Braddock.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 1, 1929%0aThe 37-story Grant Building, tallest in the city and topped by an airplane beacon spelling out Pittsburgh in Morse code, was ready for occupancy.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 7, 1929%0aA metropolitan charter bill, designed to make Pittsburgh the fifth largest city in the United States with a consolidated population of 1,319,684, was prepared for the State Legislature.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch, 1929%0aThe 32-story Koppers Building was opened to tenants.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 25, 1929%0aThe Pittsburgh Metropolitan District Charter, submitted to an Allegheny County vote, failed to acquire the required two thirds majority in each of 62 municipalities, a majority of the total in the county; city voters were eight to one in favor of the bill, but only 47 municipalities cast two thirds vote.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 28, 1929%0aA five-day work week was adopted by the building trades of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 12, 1929%0aContract for the new airport on Lebanon Church Road was signed.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember, 1929%0aFreda Seund became the first woman in Pittsburgh to be instructed in flying and to solo at a Pittsburgh airfield.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 24, 1929%0aMount Mercy College for Women was opened.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 18, 1929%0aA crowd of 100,000 persons viewed a river pageant marking the completion of the canalization of the Ohio River.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 5, 1929%0aPittsburgh residents voted overwhelmingly in favor of adoption of voting machines in Pennsylvania.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 5, 1929%0aR. B. Mellon, president of Mellon National Bank, resigned as chairman of the County Planning Commission in order, he said, to make a trip to Europe. His action was construed as an indication that a proposal to built a $6,000,000 town hall would be delayed.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember, 1929%0aThe Gulf Oil Company was making final plans for erection of its 11 million dollar office building at Seventh and Grant.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 16, 1929%0aMaurice Falk announced creation of a $10,000,000 fund by the Maurice and Laura Falk Foundation for welfare and charitable purposes.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 21, 1929%0aSaw Mill Run Boulevard was opened to the public.%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a1930%0aPopulation: 669,817.%0a%0a%0a1930%0aKDKA announced the erection of a powerful transmitter at Saxonburg.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 3, 1930%0aThe United States purchased land for a new Post Office Building.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 12, 1930%0aPittsburgh taxi drivers held a mass meeting at Duquesne Gardens to begin a strike against the Green and Yellow Cab companies in protest against what they claimed was a pay cut.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 28, 1930%0aUnited States Steel reported record peacetime profits of $197,531,349.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 14, 1930%0aPolice used tear-gas bombs to disperse a crowd on Center Avenue; two cabs were burned and 10 persons arrested as taxi strike violence continued.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 16, 1930%0aThe cornerstone was laid for the new $2,700,000 county office building at Ross and Diamond Streets.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 9, 1930%0aJones and Laughlin announced a $20,000,000 expansion program for its plants in Pittsburgh and Aliquippa.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 10, 1930%0aThe Better Traffic Committee recommended a ban on all Downtown curb parking; it also urged Mayor Charles H. Kline to eliminate the practice of "fixing" traffic tags.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 11, 1930%0aThe Baltimore and Ohio Railroad applied for a federal permit to build a river-rail terminal on the Monongahela River.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 27, 1930%0aSara Soffel was sworn in by Judge Richard Kennedy as judge of County Court, the first woman jurist in Pennsylvania.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember, 1930%0aConstruction work started on the $6,000,000 Mellon Institute building at Fifth and Bellefield.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 18, 1930%0aChamber of Commerce recommended to the United States Census Bureau a Greater Pittsburgh metropolitan area with 4043 square miles in 13 counties of Pennsylvania, Ohio, and West Virginia with a population of 2,203,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 2, 1930%0aRear Admiral Richard E. Byrd addressed 3000 at Syria Mosque during National Safety Congress here.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 12, 1930%0aEucharistic Congress was held in Forbes Field.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 21, 1930%0aCity Council passed an emergency proposal to set up a fund of $100,000 to aid families in need.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 21, 1930%0aMcCann and Company opened for business in its new 10-story building at Diamond and Ferry Streets.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 25, 1930%0aThe Mississippi Valley Association, in convention at St. Louis, endorsed proposed construction of an Ohio River-Lake Erie canal at the request of Pittsburgh and Youngstown business interests.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 25, 1930%0aA capacity audience filled the Stanley Theater for a benefit show for Pittsburgh unemployed and needy families; among those featured were Phil Baker, Fred Stone and Dick Powell.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember, 1930%0aThe Gulf Oil Company was engaged in the construction of a research center at Craft Avenue and the Boulevard of the Allies.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 30, 1930%0aA deed of trust filed by Andrew Mellon created the A. W. Mellon Educational and Charitable Trust.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 15, 1931%0aThe Chamber of Commerce reported that 27 new manufacturing plants and warehouses, representing investments totaling $2 9,502,-000, started operations in the Pittsburgh district in 1930.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 16, 1931%0aTheir funds exhausted, relief agencies warned that approximately 47,750 Pittsburgh district residents would "begin starving" immediately.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 27, 1931%0aGulf Oil opened a new refinery on Neville Island.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 5, 1931%0aMcClintock-Marshall and Bethlehem Steel Companies merged.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 11, 1931%0aThe Homer Smith, pleasure steamboat, burned at the North Side wharf.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 17, 1931%0aThe county commissioners voted $3,000,000 for construction of the Homestead High Level Bridge.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 11, 1931%0aPittsburgh's first police radio "cruisers" were patrolling the streets as WPOU, police radio station, began broadcasting.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 3, 1931%0aBuhl Foundation announced plans for a 45-acre housing development on Mount Washington to be known as Chatham Village, the first low-rent community housing project in the nation.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 14, 1931%0aFlorenz Ziegfeld's Follies opened the new season of their 23rd edition at the Nixon Theater; among those featured in the cast were Helen Morgan, Gladys Glad, Ruth Etting, Harry Richman, and, in the chorus, two Pittsburgh girls -- Zecil Silvonia and Mony Lange.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 25, 1931%0aMayor Kline was indicted with Bertram L. Succop, former director of supplies, on 49 counts of misdemeanor in office.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 30, 1931%0aAbout 5000 hunger strikers paraded in the city streets.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 23, 1931%0aForty-two aged men and women were killed in or died from the effects of a fire that destroyed the Little Sisters of the Poor Home at Penn Avenue and South Aiken; 157 others were hurt.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 29, 1931%0aWiley Post and Harold Gatty, renowned round-the-world fliers, were given an enthusiastic welcome in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 19, 1931%0aThe McKees Rocks-Ohio River Boulevard Bridge was opened.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 15, 1931%0aFor the first time in Allegheny County, voting machines -- 186 of them -- were used in the primary election.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 21, 1931%0aThe Bank of Pittsburgh announced its decision to close to conserve interests of depositors and stockholders.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 30, 1931%0aThe 583 feet tall Gulf Building went into construction.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 28, 1931%0aThe Edgar Thomson works in Braddock prepared to re-open; plans were announced to reemploy about 7000 at Homestead and Braddock.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 4, 1931%0aHunger Marchers, en route in trucks and autos to Washington, D.C., to urge an unemployment insurance bill, stopped over in Pittsburgh and requested food and shelter from Helping Hand Society headquarters.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 22, 1931%0aFive million dollars were distributed to various institutions by the H. C. Frick estate.%0a%0a%0a%0a1932%0aOf the 197 homes designed on Buhl Foundation's Chatham Village, 129 were completed.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 5, 1932%0aLed by Father James R. Cox, a jobless army of 15,000 men left St. Patrick's Church, at Seventeenth Street and Liberty Avenue, and headed for the Capital of the nation; many were afoot in a driving rain.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 6, 1932%0aThe county government was reorganized, and six departments were created: Highways, Property and Supplies, Parks, Airport, Elections, and Law.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 8, 1932%0aExhausted and hungry, Father Cox's jobless army arrived home after making a plea to Congress and President Hoover for immediate relief and jobs and warning that "something must be done to avert violence."%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 17, 1932%0aMore than 55,000 persons, in a rally at Pitt Stadium, cheered Father Cox, "Shepherd of the Unemployed," as he announced formation of the "Jobless Party" and himself as its candidate for president.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 22, 1932%0aPatrick T. Fagan, president of District 5, United Mine Workers, announced union acceptance of a 10 per cent wage cut for coal miners employed by the Pittsburgh Terminal Coal Corporation.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 4, 1932%0aA. W. Mellon, at the age of 76, was appointed ambassador to Great Britain after serving 11 years as Secretary of the Treasury.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 5, 1932%0aBarney Dreyfuss, president and owner of the Pittsburgh Pirates since 1899 and an organizer of the first World Series, died at the age of 66 at Mount Sinai Hospital in New York.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 7, 1932%0aWinston Churchill visited the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 28, 1932%0aIn order to provide employment for the needy, the city began to extend the Mount Washington Road project; six stations were also set up for free food distribution.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 28, 1932%0aThe "Snodgrass-Herron" plan for a $5,500,000 Downtown subway to relieve traffic congestion was presented to Council.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 26, 1932%0aA $5,000,000 unemployment relief bond issue was approved in the primary election by Pittsburgh voters.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 14, 1932%0aMayor Charles H. Kline and his ousted supplies director, Bertram L. Succop, were found guilty of misconduct in office in a jury trial in Butler.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 6, 1932%0aA "Bonus Army", World War I veterans seeking payouts from the government, marches through Pittsburgh en route to Washington.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 8, 1932%0aStudents demonstrated against General Douglas MacArthur when he delivered the commencement address at the University of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 8, 1932%0aConstruction was started on the new $8,000,000 federal building and post office on Grant Street.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 5, 1932%0aOrganized labor of Pittsburgh held its first parade in a dozen years and ended it at West View Park, where William Green, president of the AFL, called for shorter working hours and a more equitable distribution of wealth.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 10, 1932%0aThirty thousand persons attended the dedication of the George Westinghouse Bridge, the $1,750,000 link in relocated Lincoln Highway over Turtle Creek.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 15, 1932%0aMayor Kline returned to City Hall and to his "political fence mending" after Judge Thomas D. Finletter reversed a jury verdict and set him free; former Supplies Director Succop was sentenced to one year in jail.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 15, 1932%0aPresident Herbert Hoover campaigned in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 19, 1932%0aSpeaking as a presidential candidate before 30,000 at Forbes Field, Governor Franklin D. Roosevelt, of New York, expressed opposition to payment of the soldiers' bonus "until the government has balanced the budget and has a surplus of cash in the treasury." It was his first public; declaration on the bonus issue since his nomination.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 8, 1932%0aFranklin D. Roosevelt carried Allegheny County by 40,000 votes in the Democratic sweep that placed him in the White House.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 14, 1932%0aDistribution of free milk to 50,000 needy and undernourished children was started in 500 schools of Allegheny County.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 14, 1932%0aThe Duquesne National and Diamond banks closed their doors because of heavy withdrawal of deposits.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember, 1932%0aThe Duquesne Club was building a 13-story addition to its Sixth Street headquarters.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 2, 1932%0aProperty owners threatened a "taxpayers' strike" unless Mayor Kline reduced proposed $25,000,000 budget for 1933 by 25 per cent.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 15, 1932%0aCity Council lowered the mill levy and cut Mayor Kline's budget 20 per cent.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 10, 1933%0aThe 10th Street Bridge was completed and opened to traffic.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 5, 1933%0aThe Pittsburgh Stock Exchange closed at the start of a bank holiday ordered by the President; the Pittsburgh Clearing House prepared to issue scrip.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 9, 1933%0aAt a rally of 2000 persons in Syria Mosque, plans were made to send a delegation to Harrisburg to fight for city-manager form of government for Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 14, 1933%0aThirty-three banking institutions in Pittsburgh reopened for normal business activity and were crowded through the day with thousands of depositors.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 31, 1933%0aMayor Charles H. Kline, described as a "defeated and broken man," resigned after seven years in office; Council President John S. Herron became Mayor.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 7, 1933%0aThe Post-Gazette reported: "With a whoop of joy, thousands of parched Pittsburgh throats greeted the end of the Great Dry Era at 12:01 o'clock this morning." Large crowds milled about outside Pittsburgh breweries waiting for first legalized 3.2 beer.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 11, 1933%0aA group of 224 men -- the first from Pittsburgh to join President Roosevelt's reforestation army -- entrained for Virginia.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 5, 1933%0aRelocated and widened Pittsburgh-Butler Highway (Route 8) was opened to traffic.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 1, 1933%0aThe Chamber of Commerce estimated that 95 per cent of all Pittsburgh businesses were enrolled under the banner of the NRA Blue Eagle.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 20, 1933%0aModern professional football began in Pittsburgh when the Pittsburgh Pirates, under ownership of Arthur J. Rooney, lost, 23 to 2, to the New York Giants before 25,000 at Forbes Field.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 9, 1933%0aAfter President Roosevelt ordered "captive mine" owners to make peace, 75,000 miners of western Pennsylvania returned to work. Philip Murray, international vice-president of the United Mine Workers, and Thomas Moses, president of the H. C. Frick Coke Company, began negotiating differences.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 11, 1933%0aThree thousand men ended a six-day attempt to "bring back prosperity" by staying on the job and producing steel while barricaded inside the Clairton byproducts plant of Carnegie Steel Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 7, 1933%0aPittsburghers voted out the "blue laws" and voted in Sunday baseball and other sports. They also approved a constitutional amendment to permit the State Legislature to draft a new metropolitan charter for Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 7, 1933%0aWilliam McNair was elected Mayor.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 10, 1933%0aIn a conference at the White House, President Roosevelt advised Mayor-elect McNair and his campaign chairman, David L. Lawrence: "Now give the people of Pittsburgh good administration."%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 1, 1933%0aRichard Beatty Mellon, junior partner in the Mellon banking empire, brother of A. W. Mellon, died at the age of 75 in his Fifth Avenue mansion.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 1934%0aNew year reports showed Pittsburgh business in 1933 increased 18 per cent in volume over 1932.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 2, 1934%0aAccording to news accounts, "pandemonium broke loose" at City Hall as Mayor McNair, in his first day in office, began feuding with Council over confirmation of his cabinet appointments.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 14, 1934%0aCivil Works Administrator Harry L. Hopkins ordered an investigation into trade union charges of "political favoritism" in the hiring of men for CWA jobs in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 13, 1934%0aPlans were announced for a $350,000 juvenile court and detention home in Oakland.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 26, 1934%0aAn Akron-to-Pittsburgh passenger train of the Pennsylvania Railroad plunged off a bridge at Merchant Street as it sped into the North Side station; nine persons were killed and 39 injured.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 27, 1934%0aSteel mills in the Pittsburgh district retained the 40-hour week and granted 10 per cent pay raises so 100,000 steel workers, increasing district payrolls by a total of approximately $1,750,000 per month.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune, 1934%0aHervey Allen, Pittsburgh novelist, visited in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 28, 1934%0aThe government approved a $25,000,000 loan to the Allegheny County Authority for a construction program entailing 12,000 jobs for unemployed men.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 9, 1934%0aPittsburgh artist John Kane became a controversial figure in the national art world.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 13, 1934%0aPostmaster James A. Farley dedicated Pittsburgh's new $7,000,000 post office-federal building in an outdoor ceremony on Grant Street.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 28, 1934%0aOne of the lecturers at the meeting of the American Association for the Advancement of Science, attended by a selected group of 400 scientists, was Professor Albert Einstein; he spoke on the "equivalent of mass and energy" in the Carnegie Tech Little Theater.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 2, 1935%0aBusiness activity in Pittsburgh in 1934 was 68 per cent higher than 1933; industrial production was up 5.6 per cent over 1933 and 20 per cent over 1932, according to business summaries.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 19, 1935%0aAndrew Mellon announced that he would give his art collection to the federal government to be housed in a gallery in Washington, D.C.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 25, 1935%0aThe United Engineering and Foundry Company of Pittsburgh received a $3,000,000 order for the Zaporoptal Steel Works in Soviet Russia -- one of the largest contracts ever placed in the United States for foreign shipment.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 26, 1935%0aIn what was said to be the largest industrial dismantling project in the city's history, the National Tube Company began disassembling its Pennsylvania plans, Second Avenue, and Republic plant, on 24th Street, South Side.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 1, 1935%0aA slight earth tremor was felt in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 4, 1935%0aIn a Democratic caucus in Harrisburg, State Democratic Chairman David L. Lawrence demanded that the McNair ripper bill be pushed through the Legislature. While he later denied having made such a speech in the caucus, he was quoted as saying: "I put him [McNair] in, and I'll take him out."%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 21, 1935%0aTwo Pittsburghers -- William P. Witherow, representing industry, and Philip Murray, representing organized labor -- were named by President Roosevelt to the NRA board.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 21, 1935%0aFather Cox's Old St. Patrick's Church, a 125-year-old Pittsburgh landmark and one of the most popular churches in the city, was destroyed by fire.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 12, 1935%0aThe Monongahela House, where policy-making party caucuses were held prior to and during the first Republican convention in 1856 and said to be, for that reason, the "birthplace of the Republican Party," closed its doors. A plan to convert it to Jones and Laughlin office building failed to materialize.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 12, 1935%0aNearly 6000 persons gathered in and about the chapel for dedication of the East Liberty Presbyterian Church, built at a cost of more than $4,000,000 by Mr. and Mrs. R. B. Mellon as a memorial to their respective mothers.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 3, 1935%0aMayor McNair installed a bed in his office in preparation for a long siege in the event the ripper bill against him was passed by State Legislature.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 19, 1935%0aThe Pittsburgh Metropolitan District Charter bill, amended drastically by the House, was defeated in the State Senate.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 23, 1935%0aThe McNair ripper bill died with adjournment of the Legislature.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 14, 1935%0aAndrew Mellon announced a gift of $10,000,000 for construction of the National Gallery of Art in Washington, D.C.; his private art collection, accumulated at a cost of $25,000,000 and valued at $40,000,000, was made immediately available to the gallery.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 5, 1935%0aPittsburgh and Allegheny County voters approved Sunday movies by a vote of three to one.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 24, 1935%0aLarge crowds filled theaters of the city as Sunday movies were shown for the first time.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 16, 1935%0aIn the city's healthiest economic signs since before the 1929 crash, Jones and Laughlin announced a $40,000,000 expansion program, including a new $25,000,000 sheet and strip mill on Second Avenue, and the Pennsylvania Railroad placed an order for 10,000 brake sets with the Westinghouse Air Brake Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 2, 1936%0aBusiness reviews showed a definite upturn of Pittsburgh business in 1935; general business activity was up 14.7 per cent over 1934 and 45.3 per cent over 1932; department store sales were up 6.5 per cent.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 25, 1936%0aDr. Robert E. Doherty, Yale dean and electrical researcher, was elected president of Carnegie Tech to succeed Dr. Thomas S. Baker.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 26, 1936%0aAn ice gorge formed in the Allegheny River and moved toward Pittsburgh; flood waters swept over many Western Pennsylvania communities.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 17, 1936%0a(St. Patrick's Day): The rivers rose to 34 feet at the Point, and for the first time in 23 years water flowed over the city's low-level streets.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 18, 1936%0aFloodwaters reached a crest of 46.4 feet, highest in the city's history, and began receding; some streets were inundated by 20 feet of water.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 19, 1936%0aMore than 60 persons were believed dead as the flood stage dropped to 32.1 feet; health, relief, and city agencies mustered support to fight disease, hunger, and cold; explosions and fires added to the peril.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 19, 1936%0aBetween 5000 and 7000 men, women, and children were rescued from flooded homes in the McKees Rocks "Bottoms."%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 20, 1936%0aThe flood death toll was reported at 46 known dead and 384 injured; the Red Cross was attempting to assist 50,000 homeless persons; drinking water was restored; bandits and vandals roamed the area.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 20, 1936%0aMunicipal officers from 200 cities arid towns in the Tri-State area met here in an emergency conference to discuss flood prevention for the future.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 22, 1936%0aThe Pittsburgh district struggled to get back to normal, but 110,144 men, women, and children remained homeless in Allegheny County.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 24, 1936%0aCity Council asked the federal government for $10,000,000 to replace and repair 1000 homes destroyed and 8000 damaged by flood waters.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 27, 1936%0aThe flood death toll rose to 74. The Chamber of Commerce, representing the business interests of Pittsburgh, informed the federal government that the delay of an adequate flood-control program, sought since 1907, had cost Allegheny County between $150,000,000 and $200,000,000 in property loss.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 30, 1936%0aThe National Guard was withdrawn, the Triangle was reopened.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 18, 1936%0aMayor McNair was jailed for disobeying a court order directing him to return a $100 fine to an alleged numbers writer who had successfully appealed his conviction to County Court; the Mayor was released from jail on agreeing to return the fine.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 17, 1936%0aThe Steel Workers' Organizing Committee held its first meeting in the Commonwealth Building and named Philip Murray, international vice-president of United Mine Workers, as chairman of a planned organizing campaign.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 22, 1936%0aCongress passed the flood-control act, setting up funds for flood-control work in this district.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 27, 1936%0aNewly completed Allegheny General Hospital was dedicated.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 2, 1936%0aAddressing 50,000 persons at Forbes Field, President Roosevelt predicted a balanced budget based on an increase in national income.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 6, 1936%0aWith no advance notice, William H. McNair resigned and turned the office of Mayor over to Cornelius P. Scully, president of Council and McNair's bitterest personal enemy in his three years in office.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 8, 1936%0aThe Reverend Charles E. Coughlin, Detroit radio priest and head of the National Union for Social Justice, in a speech to an overflow crowd of 4500 at Syria Mosque, charged that President Roosevelt "has adopted communistic activities."%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 11, 1936%0aOne hundred thousand Catholic men of Pittsburgh assembled at Pitt Stadium for a eucharistic rally.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 13, 1936%0aMayor McNair repented and withdrew his resignation, but Council declined to accept it. Mayor Scully fired Leslie Johnston, public works director.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 27, 1936%0aGovernor Alfred M. Landon, of Kansas, appeared in Pittsburgh as the Republican presidential candidate and spoke to a crowd of 20,000 at Duquesne Gardens.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 3, 1936%0aA total of 560,000 Allegheny County citizens voted in the presidential election to set a balloting record, 150,000 above the previous high. President Roosevelt carried the county by 188,478 votes; county Democrats won five seats in Congress, two in the United States Senate, and 27 in the State House.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 8, 1936%0aAt the conclusion of a two-day meeting of the CIO, headed by John L. Lewis, Lewis refused to meet William Green of AFL to discuss peace terms between the two union groups.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 20, 1936%0aIn a mass meeting at the Fort Pitt Hotel, Philip Murray, CIO chairman, declared in his keynote speech that "the company union must be put out of business." Employee representatives of 42 steel plants pledged full support to the CIO in its drive to organize all steel workers into one trade union.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 1937%0aPittsburgh business in 1936 was at its highest level since 1930, up 29.2 per cent from 1935.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 14, 1937%0aWith 500 business guests in attendance, the Carnegie-Illinois Steel Corporation formally opened a new $10,000,000 plant in Homestead, a 100-inch semicontinuous plate mill with a capacity of 729,000 tons per year.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 15, 1937%0aWilliam A. Irvin, president of United States Steel, and Benjamin F. Fairless, president of Carnegie-Illinois, announced plans for the expenditure of $60,000,000 for the expansion and improvement of plants at Clairton and Braddock.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 20, 1937%0aThree-month strike of 6000 Pittsburgh Plate Glass workers ended with an agreement for an eight-cent hourly pay raise.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 3, 1937%0aThe famed Lucy Furnace, first blast furnace built by Andrew Carnegie and named for his brother's wife, was dismantled.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 17, 1937%0aFive United States Steel subsidiaries, headed by Benjamin F. Fairless, of Carnegie-Illinois, signed the first wage contract with the Steel Workers Organizing Committee. It established in the steel industry the $5-a-day minimum wage, the 40-hour week, vacations with pay, seniority rights, and grievance procedure.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 21, 1937%0aBuhl Foundation gave $750,000 to the city for a planetarium and institute of popular science on the site of the old Allegheny City Hall.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 26, 1937%0aRivers hit crest of 35.1 feet, but only low-lying areas were affected. State Senator William B. Rodgers, Jr. demanded federal government make an immediate start on the long-delayed flood control program.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 4, 1937%0aThe Better Traffic Committee endorsed Mayor Scully's plan to make Forbes Street and Fifth Avenue one-way streets and to construct a short trolley loop in the downtown area.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 6, 1937%0aAndrew W. Mellon dedicated the $10,000,000 Mellon Institute at the start of a five-day program in Carnegie Music Hall, highlighted by an announcement of a new successful treatment for pneumonia, developed by Institute scientists. Among the scores of leading scientists in attendance were three Nobel prize winners -- Drs. H. C. Urey, W. P. Murphy, and Irving Langmuir.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 11, 1937%0aMayor Scully proposed a $70,400,000 "pure water supply" to be brought to Pittsburgh and neighboring communities by an aqueduct system from northern creeks.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 12, 1937%0aTwenty-five thousand men were idled at Jones and Laughlin's Pittsburgh and Aliquippa plants by a strike ordered by Philip Murray in the Steel Workers Organizing Committee organizational drive. Jones and Laughlin and a group of other operators were accused by the union of violating the Wagner Labor Relations Act by refusing to sign wage scale contracts.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 20, 1937%0aIn the nation's largest collective bargaining election, steel workers in Jones and Laughlin plants voted 17,028 for the CIO Amalgamated Association of Iron, Steel, and Tin Workers and 7207 against.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 21, 1937%0aGovernor Earle signed a bill to create a turnpike commission to is-sue $50,000,000 to $65,000,000 in bonds to finance construction of an "all-weather" toll highway from Pittsburgh to Harrisburg.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 22, 1937%0aThe Carnegie-Illinois Steel Corporation broke ground for its new Irvin works in West Mifflin Township estimated to cost $63,000,000 and employ 4000 men.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 2, 1937%0aThe Stephen C. Foster Memorial adjoining the Cathedral of Learning was dedicated.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 4, 1937%0aThe Westinghouse Electric Corporation was building a cyclotron.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 7, 1937%0aAs the climax of a week-long celebration of the 150th anniversary of its founding, the University of Pittsburgh celebrated the completion of its 42-story Cathedral of Learning a decade after construction on the building was started.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 10, 1937%0aThe Kelsey-Hayes Wheel Company of Detroit, nation's largest manufacturer of auto wheels, announced purchase of a Neville Island property as site for a $1,000,000 plant to employ 1500 persons.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 13, 1937%0aThe Post-Gazette initiated a series of articles by Ray Sprigle, exposing United States Supreme Court Justice Hugo L. Black as a member of the Ku Klux Klan; the articles led to demands for Justice Black's resignation.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 13, 1937%0aThe PWA in Washington announced a $2,847,000 appropriation for construction of a proposed psychiatric hospital on the Pitt campus.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 16, 1937%0aThe AFL-Central Labor Union expelled its president, Patrick C. Fagan, for his support of Mayor Scully. The Mayor had opposed the union's endorsement of the Kane-McArdle faction in the Democratic primary. All other CIO delegates were also expelled, and Fagan immediately announced formation of a "CIO-Central Labor Union" (Steel City Industrial Union).%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 20, 1937%0aAndrew W. Mellon, who died on August 26, left his vast estate to his son, Paul Mellon, and son-in-law, David K. E. Bruce, to be administered "as they shall deem advisable and for best interests of my estate." The will bound them only to the deed that created the A. W. Mellon Educational and Charitable Trust, under which Mr. Mellons bequest to the public was estimated at between $100,000,000 and $500,000,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 1, 1937%0aIn a nationwide radio talk Justice Hugo Black admitted membership in the Ku Klux Klan, as charged by Ray Sprigle, but stated that he resigned after a successful primary race for the United States Senate and disclaimed all sympathy for the movement.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 20, 1937%0aChief Justice John W. Kephart, of the State Supreme Court, dedicated the new $350,000 Juvenile Court here, calling it a "monument to an enlightened judicial system."%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 20, 1937%0aGround was broken at Crooked Creek dam site on upper Allegheny River, first of a network of dams to protect the Pittsburgh area from floods.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 21, 1937%0aAfter a 10-year rebuilding job, directed by Edward Specter, the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra, backed by a successful public campaign for $300,000, presented its first concert as a major orchestra with Otto Klemperer as guest conductor.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 27, 1937%0aBenjamin F. Fairless was elected president of the U.S. Steel Corp.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 20, 1937%0aThe Homestead High Level Bridge was dedicated.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 2, 1937%0aAllegheny Housing Authority was established.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 3, 1937%0aAir pilots said Pittsburgh appeared "like a ball of black ink" as one of the city's heaviest smoke screens cut Downtown visibility to 300 feet, slowed traffic, and caused lights to be turned on at high noon; home furnaces were held to be the chief cause.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 8, 1937%0aPittsburgh became the center of national steel production when United States Steel decided to move its management headquarters to Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 8, 1937%0aThe federal government earmarked $10,000,000 for low-cost housing projects planned by the Pittsburgh Housing Authority.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 1938%0aReports showed that, de-spite a recession in the closing months of the year, Pittsburgh business activity for 1937 was up 8.7 per cent over 1936; the total resources of 97 banks in Allegheny County were reported to be $1,507,604,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 1938%0aAt this date wage contracts between the Steel Workers Organizing Committee and the steel industry totaled 445.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 20, 1938%0aFallingwater, Edgar Kaufmann's country home designed by Frank Lloyd Wright, was viewed by interested visitors.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 27, 1938%0aA plan for creating a historic memorial park in Pittsburgh, covering a 36-acre area at the Point and including proposed restoration of Fort Pitt and Fort Duquesne on their original sites, was before the National Park Service in Washington.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 27, 1938%0aThe WPA fixed the cost of a proposed sewage-disposal system to end stream pollution in Allegheny County at $25,000,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 3, 1938%0aFritz Reiner, noted Hungarian conductor, was appointed full-time director of the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 26, 1938%0aSix hundred Pittsburgh business and civic leaders, at a dinner in the William Penn Hotel, were informed that Secretary of the Interior Harold Ickes had approved the Point as a site for a historic memorial. A Point Park commission was promoting the plan under chairmanship of Frank C. Harper.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 5, 1938%0aMyron C. Taylor resigned as chairman of the board of United States Steel.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 14, 1938%0aUsing the same gold-plated shovel that started the grading of Grant's Hill, known locally as the Hump, Mayor Scully broke ground for the $1,050,000 Buhl Planetarium.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 2, 1938%0aRay Sprigle was awarded the Pulitzer Prize for his expose of Justice Hugo Black's affiliation with Ku Klux Klan.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 5, 1938%0aDowntown traffic was bottled up by a city-wide strike of parking-lot and garage attendants called by taxi-cab drivers' union.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 11, 1938%0aThe Pittsburgh Railways Company, which had emerged from a receivership in 1922, again went into bankruptcy.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 12, 1938%0aHomeopathic Hospital changed its name to Shadyside.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 12, 1938%0aA survey conducted by the city's Bureau of Smoke Regulation indicated that smog was a major factor in Pittsburgh's high pneumonia death rate.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 17, 1938%0aThe Allegheny and Ludlum Steel companies were merged.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune, 1938%0aSteel Workers Organizing Committee contracts in the steel industry were increased to cover 529 mills.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 24, 1938%0aCarnegie-Illinois announced a reduction in steel prices to approximately the level prior to 1938.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 2, 1938%0aDouglas "Wrong Way" Corrigan, solo transatlantic flier, was a special guest at the opening of Allegheny County's Sesquicentennial Anniversary celebration.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 1, 1938%0aThe Pittsburgh Housing Authority announced its first low-cost housing project would be located in the Hill District and named Bedford Dwellings, initial step in a $40,000,000 city-county slum-clearance program.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 8, 1938%0aThe Democrats lost heavily in Allegheny County.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 15, 1938%0aIn its first constitutional convention at the Grotto, in North Side Pittsburgh, the CIO became a permanent organization; it also voted for a "no compromise" stand for peace on its own terms in its three-year war with the AFL.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 20, 1938%0aAfter five years in construction, the Heinz Chapel, topped by a 235-foot spire, was dedicated on the Pitt campus as the gift of the Heinz family.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 21, 1938%0aDavid L. Lawrence testified in Harrisburg before a legislative committee investigating charges that he and other high officers of state had engaged in a conspiracy involving "bribery, extortion, and coercion."%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember, 1938%0aThe Pittsburgh Regional Planning Association, successor to the Municipal Planning Association, undertook a series of studies to attempt to find ways of halting the decline of property values in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 13, 1938%0aThe world's largest slabbing mill went into operation at the Edgar Thomson works of Carnegie-Illinois in Braddock.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 15, 1938%0aNearly 2000 business leaders attended dedication of new $60,000,000 Irvin works.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 19, 1938%0aAgain with the gold-plated "Hump shovel," Mayor Scully broke ground for the $3,000,000 Bedford Dwellings, low-cost housing community for 420 families.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary, 1939%0aA $5,000,000 Monongahela River front improvement was started with WPA funds.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 3, 1939%0aThe effects of a business recession were felt in 1938, when business activity was down 39.3 per cent from 1937.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 21, 1939%0aArmy engineers recommended a $207,000,000 Beaver-Youngstown canal with "dead end" at Youngstown. Pittsburgh civic and business interests immediately mobilized to continue their 20-year fight for a canal extending to Lake Erie.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 5, 1939%0aThe University of Pittsburgh's greatest era as a national football power ended with the resignation of Dr. John B. (Jock) Sutherland as head coach.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 10, 1939%0aPitt students went on strike in protest against Dr. Sutherland's resignation and against what they called "autocratic administrative evils" and the "bungling policies" of Chancellor John G. Bowman.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 13, 1939%0aThe city began construction of an $890,000 incinerator plant, its first, at the foot of 29th Street in Lawrenceville.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 14, 1939%0aA new metropolitan commission was created at a meeting of business, labor, and civic representatives; its purpose was to formulate a "political reorganization which will produce the maximum of efficiency under the maximum of home rule."%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 17, 1939%0aThe newly proposed metropolitan plan of government, seeking to establish Pittsburgh as the nation's fifth city in size with a population of 1,700,000, was defeated at Harrisburg when it failed to receive the backing of Allegheny County senators, Democrats and Republicans alike.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 27, 1939%0aAfter five years of planning, work was underway to widen and re-build Bigelow Boulevard into a four-lane highway at a cost of $1,800,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 27, 1939%0aFederal Court issued an injunction, sought by the Pittsburgh Railways Company, to restrain the city from enforcing a one-way traffic plan on Forbes and Fifth Avenue during closing of Bigelow Boulevard.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 27, 1939%0aA 310-family project in McKees Rocks, with rents averaging $12.50 to $15 per month, was authorized by President Roosevelt for immediate construction as the first project in Allegheny County's $19,000,000 public-housing program.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune, 1939%0aA glass house, the first of its kind to be made, was built in the city to be exhibited at the World's Fair in New York.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 2, 1939%0aBecause of improved business conditions, Westinghouse made full restoration of pay cuts ordered in 1938.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 19, 1939%0aState Supreme Court upheld a verdict awarding $800,000 to Pennsylvania Railroad for damages against the city as the result of 1920 Bigelow Boulevard landslide.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 3, 1939%0aThousands of persons of all faiths, attending the county fair, joined in a peace demonstration as Great Britain declared war on Nazi Germany.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 24, 1939%0aBuhl Planetarium, built at a cost of $1,100,000 and containing a giant projector, was dedicated; 400 scientists were guests at the first sky show.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 3, 1939%0aPittsburgh had its first movie "world premiere" in Hollywood style, with the showing of Allegheny 'Uprising at Loew's Penn'; among guests was Claire Trevor, one of the stars of the film.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 16, 1939%0aAfter a three-month study, Robert Moses, of New York, and other leading planners unveiled their comprehensive "arterial plan" for solution of the Triangle traffic problem. At a total cost of $38,000,000, the plan included a Pitt Parkway, from a point east of Wilkinsburg to downtown Pittsburgh; a cross-town highway at upper border of the Triangle; reconstruction of Duquesne Way as the first step in a highway system to encompass the Triangle; removal of the Wabash Station and railroad tracks leading to it.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 8, 1939%0aDemocratic State Chairman David L. Lawrence was acquitted by a Dauphin County jury of three counts of conspiracy, one of statutory blackmail, and one of violating election laws. Thus the politically inspired charges came to nothing. Next day five thousand cheering Democratic leaders and workers gave Lawrence an enthusiastic welcome when he arrived at Pennsylvania Station from Harrisburg.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 26, 1939%0aThe Duquesne Light Company announced a $16,000,000 program of expansion and construction in the Pittsburgh district.%0a%0a%0a%0a1940%0aPopulation: 671,659.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 2, 1940%0aPittsburgh business activity for 1939 was 34.9 per cent over that of 1938, approaching 1929 levels in the closing months.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 5, 1940%0aCity and county officials announced that the $38,000,000 "Moses Plan" would be put into motion in 1940 with reconstruction of Duquesne Way, at a cost of $2,500,000, as the first project. Next on the list were a $1,400,000 Liberty Tubes grade separation plaza and a $1,500,-000 extension of Saw Mill Run Boulevard to West End.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 25, 1940%0a"Musical Americana" the national radio program of Westinghouse, was instituted by KDKA.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 15, 1940%0aA 20-inch snowfall stopped auto and trolley traffic and forced a two-day suspension in business and trading activities.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 26, 1940%0aInvestigators for the Dies Congressional Committee raided Pittsburgh Communist headquarters at 305-7 Seventh Avenue following arrest of James H. Dolsen, local Communist leader, on a congressional contempt citation.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 27, 1940%0aDavid L. Lawrence and seven other state Democratic leaders went on trial in Harrisburg on charge of conspiring to "mace" state payrolls (forcing employees to make political contributions); the original charges were made by ex-Attorney General Charles J. Margiotti. On April 12 Lawrence and his co-defendants were acquitted by a Dauphin County Court jury.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 15, 1940%0aBedford Dwellings, the first large federal public housing development, was completed.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 4, 1940%0aThe Pirates played their first night game in Forbes Field.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 4, 1940%0aIrving S. Olds succeeded Edward R. Stettinius, Jr., as Chairman of the United Steel Corporation.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 13, 1940%0aIndustrial leaders met with public officials to plan mobilization of Pittsburgh district resources for the nation's $5,000,000,000 defense program.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 28, 1940%0aHighland Park Zoo, completely overhauled and modernized, was reopened to the public.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 1, 1940%0aA reorganization plan, consolidating 55 interlocking street transit systems into a single company, was filed, in Federal Court by trustees for the bankrupt Pittsburgh Railways Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 18, 1940%0aSpear and Company leased a Wood Street 14-story building, formerly occupied by McCreery's Department Store, and announced plans for a $1,000,000 renovation program.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 22, 1940%0aPreparations were made to raze old Allegheny General Hospital and 25 other buildings in a congested North Side section, site of a huge new Sears, Roebuck and Company store and parking lot.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 23, 1940%0aThe two-level Water Street Bypass, built at a cost of $3,000,000 to relieve Downtown congestion, was opened to traffic.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 16, 1940%0aThe Mesta Machine Company received an $8,390,000 contract for "artillery material," largest national defense order placed in the Pittsburgh district to this date.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 1, 1940%0aThe nation's longest toll expressway, the 160-mile, $70,000,000 Pittsburgh-to-Harrisburg "dream highway," was opened, and 1560 motorists paid tolls to use it the first day. Governor James ordered the speed limit fixed at 50 miles per hour.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 3, 1940%0aWendell L. Willkie spoke at a campaign rally in Forbes Field.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 4, 1940%0aFritzie Zivic, of Pittsburgh, won the decision from the favored Henry Armstrong to capture world's welterweight title in a bout at Madison Square Garden, New York.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 10, 1940%0aPlans for a park at the Point were announced.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 11, 1940%0aAfter inspecting the flood-control program in the area, President Roosevelt arrived in Pittsburgh for a brief visit; in a two-and-a-half hour period he toured steel mills, inspected armament plants, and personally dedicated the $13,800,000 Terrace Village, second largest public-housing project in the nation.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 16, 1940%0aA total of 188,876 Allegheny County men registered for the nation's first peacetime draft; of that number, 89,069 were city residents.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 5, 1940%0aA record vote of 630,000 was cast in Allegheny County which gave President Roosevelt a majority of 105,599 over Wendell L. Willkie.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 14, 1940%0aTwo hundred men, women, and children escaped serious injury and probable death when the roof of the 50-year-old Harris-Alvin Theater, on Sixth Street, collapsed, bringing down tons of masonry and rafters; four persons were slightly hurt.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 14, 1940%0aMayor Scully created a new Point Park commission, with Councilman Fred Weir as chairman.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 22, 1940%0aPhilip Murray was unanimously elected president of the CIO at the conclusion of its Atlantic City convention; in a speech he protested President Roosevelt's efforts to force a merger of the CIO and AFL.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 25, 1940%0aA group of 40 young men, comprising the city's first draft contingent, passed physical examinations and entrained for Fort Meade, Maryland.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 11, 1940%0aFor his work in labor and national defense, Philip Murray was honored by the Junior Chamber of Commerce as Pittsburgh's "man of the year".%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 18, 1940%0aCrucible Steel Company announced a $10,000,000 expansion of its Midland plant.%0a%0a%0a%0a1941%0aAn influenza epidemic caused the absence of 6000 pupils and 138 teachers from the city's schools.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 1941%0aSpurred by war demands for goods, business activity in the Pittsburgh district in the closing months of 1940 equaled that of 1929, according to surveys. Steel firms were operating at 100 per cent of capacity; all mills were planning major expansion; defense contracts placed with Pittsburgh district industries totaled $75,000,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary, 1941%0aMrs. Alan M. Scaife presented a cyclotron to the University of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 5, 1941%0aDr. I. Hope Alexander, city health director, stepped up his efforts for a smoke-abatement campaign as a black smoke pall blotted out the sun and hung over the city. The Allegheny County Medical Society endorsed efforts to obtain an anti-smoke law.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 9, 1941%0aHoward Heinz, president of the H. J. Heinz Company, and son of its founder, died at the age of 63 in a Philadelphia hospital.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 13, 1941%0aCity Hall was flooded with mail complaints about the smog that continued to blanket the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 14, 1941%0aThe Koppers Company received orders totaling $10,000,000 for coke ovens.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 19, 1941%0aEight members of City Council visited St. Louis in a body to witness the effects of that city's smoke-control program. They were advised by Mayor Bernard F. Dickmann that Pittsburgh's air could be cleansed, too, "if you have the courage of your convictions."%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch, 1941%0aRichard K. Mellon was elected president of Pittsburgh Regional Planning Association to succeed Howard Heinz.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 20, 1941%0aDr. Joseph H. Barach of Presbyterian Hospital, in the first public hearing before the smoke commission, testified that smog increased the incidence of colds, pneumonia, and other illnesses in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 14, 1941%0aA major strike in the steel industry was averted when "Big Steel" signed a pact with the Steel Workers Organizing Committee for a 10-cent hourly wage increase for 240,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 5, 1941%0aThe University of Pittsburgh Bureau of Business Research reported that business activity in Pittsburgh was at its highest level in the 57 years for which records were available.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 22, 1941%0aPaul Block, publisher of the Post-Gazette, died at the age of 63 in the Hotel Waldorf-Astoria in N.Y.C.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 1, 1941%0aPittsburghs eight major hotels were closed by a strike of 2400 AFL service employees.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 1, 1941%0aA new and more stringent smoke control ordinance was passed by the City Council. Its enforcement was postponed because of the war.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 16, 1941%0aThe 15-day strike which closed the hotels was settled when union members voted to accept pay raises totaling $215,000 a year.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 22, 1941%0aM. W. Clement, president of the Pennsylvania Railroad, announced the beginning of a program to modernize the Pittsburgh Pennsylvania Station.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 4, 1941%0aW. P. Witherow, Pittsburgh industrialist, was elected president of the National Association of Manufacturers.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 7, 1941%0aPittsburgh was shocked over the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 8, 1941%0aMore than 1200 Pittsburgh young men volunteered for enlistment in the armed services in one day.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 12, 1941%0aDr. Frank Conrad, father of radio broadcasting, died.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 1942%0aAn industrial review for 1941 showed the steel industry produced approximately 18,000,000 net tons of steel ingots in 1941 to set a new production record; the output was 200 per cent greater than that of 1938 and 500 per cent over 1932.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 1942%0aThe amount of prime defense contracts awarded to Pittsburgh industries totaled $137,865,000, and industry expansion projects amounted to $137,106,000. During the previous year, 23,000 workers were added to payrolls of iron and steel industry in the area.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 1942%0aUnited States Steel prepared to move ahead with construction of a $75,000,000 mill in Homestead.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 9, 1942%0aArchaeologists excavating near the intersection of the Boulevard of the Allies and Liberty Avenue found what was believed to be part of the curtain of Fort Pitt.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 16, 1942%0aA total of 115,000 Allegheny County men in the expanded 20-to-44-year age group registered for the draft.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 1, 1942%0aDomestic use of natural gas was curtailed as a war measure.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 3, 1942%0aA 17-inch snowfall, one of the city's heaviest in history, paralyzed traffic.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 5, 1942%0aThe Dravo Corporation became the first defense industry to receive the all-Navy "E" in a ceremony highlighted by the launching of a submarine chaser built by Dravo.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 5, 1942%0aAir raid drills were organized.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 6, 1942%0aAn estimated 300,000 persons assembled in the Downtown area to watch 35,000 marchers in an Army Day demonstration of loyalty and patriotism.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 7, 1942%0aFor the first time since labor's split in 1936, CIO President Philip Murray and AFL President William Green spoke from the same platform and renewed their pledge of labor peace in a rally at Syria Mosque.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 19, 1942%0aThe 13 and 16 year-old sons of David L. Lawrence, national Democratic committeeman, were both killed in an automobile crash north of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 19, 1942%0aCorporal Frank Basa, wounded hero of the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor, was welcomed home by 40,000 persons who turned out for a parade in Lawrenceville.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 20, 1942%0aFollowing an auction sale of prize dairy herds, bulldozers began leveling an 1100-acre tract of the old Bell farm in Moon Township for a $3,000,000 defense airport.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 29, 1942%0aPittsburgh and nine surrounding counties were designated by the federal government as a defense rental area, and rents were frozen.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay, 1942%0aAfter serving as first assistant to nine city solicitors, Anne X. Alpern was appointed city solicitor by Mayor Scully as replacement for William A. Stewart, who entered the army. She was the first woman to become the chief legal officer of a major American city.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 23, 1942%0aThe United Steel Workers of America, successor to the Steel Workers Organizing Committee, in convention at Cleveland, elected Philip Murray its first president at $20,000 a year.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 28, 1942%0aPhilip Murray was ousted as vice-president of the United Mine Workers as result of his break with John L. Lewis; John O'Leary, of Pittsburgh, was appointed to succeed him.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 8, 1942%0aFirst "blackout" practice took place.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 3, 1942%0aThe Army War Show was given at Pitt Stadium.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 17, 1942%0aUnited Steel Workers' wage policy committee, meeting at William Penn Hotel, accepted a 44-cents-a-day wage increase granted by War Labor Board to employees of "Little Steel" firms.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 11, 1942%0aWestern State Psychiatric Hospital, a 17-story building started in 1938 and built at a cost of $2,500,000, was dedicated by Governor Arthur H. James.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 16, 1942%0aThe Pittsburgh and West Virginia Railroad began razing its huge steel train shed behind the old Wabash Station and consigned it to the Pittsburgh scrap drive.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 22, 1942%0aWomen bus drivers were first employed%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 9, 1942%0aH. J. Heinz, II, president of the 1942 United War Fund, which conducted a successful $4,500,000 drive, was honored by the Junior Chamber of Commerce as the "man of the year".%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 9, 1942%0aJohn P. Busarello, a John L. Lewis follower, was elected president of District 5, United Mine Workers, defeating Patrick T. Fagan, holder of the office for 22 years and a leader of the Murray forces.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 25, 1942%0aFor the first time in Pittsburgh's history the steel mills operated on Christmas Day.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 30, 1942%0aAllegheny and Monongahela rivers overflowed, crested at 36.6 at the Point, forced war plants and Downtown theaters to close, made 7500 persons temporarily homeless, and disrupted auto and trolley traffic.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 2, 1943%0aThe Pittsburgh district was recognized as the nation's No. 1 steel center after its 1942 record of having produced 20,000,000 tons of steel, chiefly for war purposes; employment was up 10 per cent.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 1, 1943%0aJudge Sara M. Soffel, of Common Pleas Court, became the first woman ever to preside over an Allegheny County criminal court.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 1, 1943%0aThe Allegheny County War Transportation Committee appealed for "no compromise" co-operation from business in proposed plan to stagger working hours in order to prevent serious traffic congestion.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 11, 1943%0aTwenty-nine German aliens living near war plants in the Pittsburgh district were arrested.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 17, 1943%0aThe USO-Variety Club Canteen at Pennsylvania Station was opened with 1700 servicemen as guests.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 20, 1943%0aPittsburgh police, enforcing an OPA ban on pleasure driving, stopped scores of motorists and cited a total of 403 in two days for violation of ration rules.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 24, 1943%0aDrastic curtailment of bus and taxi service was required by ODT's 40 per cent cut in Pittsburgh's gasoline allotment; the city faced a serious transportation problem as Pittsburgh Railways eliminated five bus routes, curtailed nine others.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 26, 1943%0aThe nation's first gasoline "night court," set up by the OPA office here to speed up action against pleasure driving, opened in the Fulton Building.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 3, 1943%0aMayor Scully had his gas-ration privileges suspended for three months for violating the OPA driving ban by making a 350-mile trip to West Virginia.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 14, 1943%0aA federal grand jury began a probe of an insurgent strike which hampered coal production in Western Pennsylvania for nearly a month and slowed steel mills.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 20, 1943%0aColonel Richard K. Mellon, 44-year-old Pittsburgh financier, was named director of the Pennsylvania Selective Service.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 19, 1943%0aThe $2,000,000 Duquesne Way improvement, another link in the planned Downtown arterial highway system, was opened to traffic. The county commissioners announced that the next step in the Moses Plan would be construction of a cross-town highway at a cost of about $10,000,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember, 1943%0aThe Allegheny Conference on Community Development was incorporated as a private, nonprofit organization "to develop, stimulate, encourage, and coordinate" planning activities in the area.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 12, 1943%0aA "Hollywood Cavalcade" at Forbes Field sold $87,000,000 in United States war bonds; among those featured were Greer Garson, Fred Astaire, and Harpo Marx.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 1, 1943%0aThe 19-county western Pennsylvania area went $6,567,000 over its $305,808,900 quota in the third War Loan bond drive.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 11, 1943%0aSamuel Harden Church, 85, president of Carnegie Institute, died at Shadyside Hospital after he was stricken at his desk while planning the Institute's 46th annual Founders Day.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 26, 1943%0aWilliam Frew was elevated from the position of vice-president to the presidency of Carnegie Institute.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 29, 1943%0aContracts for the long planned Pitt Parkway (known as the Parkway East today) were signed in Harrisburg but the start of construction was postponed to the end of the war; the cost for the nine-and-a-half mile toad was estimated at$20,000,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 2, 1944%0aHarry S. Truman, Democratic nominee for vice-president, called for the re-election of President Roosevelt at Syria Mosque.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 14, 1944%0aAlthough granted a 10 per cent raise at the first of the year, 290 city garbage collectors staged their eighth strike in three years for higher wages.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 18, 1944%0aA "ceiling zero" smog blanketed Pittsburgh and prevented thousands of war workers from reaching their jobs and homes%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 23, 1944%0aPrivate haulers, hired by the city to collect accumulation of garbage, were operating under protection of an 80-man police squad after some trucks were attacked by roving pickets.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 24, 1944%0aOn the 11th day of the garbage strike, City Council passed two ordinances to end the three-year-old municipal operation and to place the collection of garbage in the hands of private contractors.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 2, 1944%0aThe city garbage collectors voted to return to work and began hauling away 9000 tons of refuse that had accumulated during their 20-day walkout.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 24, 1944%0aPittsburgh Symphony Orchestra went on tour.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 24, 1944%0aTechnical Sergeant Charles E. "Commando" Kelly, Pittsburgh's first Congressional Medal of Honor winner in World War II, received a hero's welcome when he arrived home.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 10, 1944%0aMrs. Eleanor Roosevelt made her second visit to Pittsburgh in three months, spent the day touring the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 30, 1944%0aLST-750, financed by Allegheny County residents through the purchase of $5,000,000 worth of extra war bonds, was launched at Dravo's East shipyard on Neville Island before a crowd of 25,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 8, 1944%0aIn a mass rally outside the East Pittsburgh plant, 20,000 employees of Westinghouse reaffirmed a no-strike pledge for duration of the war.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 13, 1944%0aThe fifth War Loan went $5,000,000 over the $334,914,500 quota for the 19-county Western Pennsylvania area.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 7, 1944%0aA survey showed that war contracts completed to date or underway in Pittsburgh district plants totaled $903,398,644, with $322,000,000 of it delivered to the front lines.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 20, 1944%0aGovernor Thomas E. Dewey, of New York, Republican candidate for president, in a pre-election address at Hunt Armory in Pittsburgh, charged the New Deal with having "turned collective bargaining into political bargaining." While in the city he conferred with top union representatives of 65,000 coal miners in Western Pennsylvania.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 8, 1944%0aIn winning his fourth term, President Roosevelt carried Allegheny County with a 75,582 majority over Thomas E. Dewey.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 9, 1944%0aAs the county's first postwar project, the county commissioners scheduled construction of the $4,000,000 Dravosburg Bridge over the Monongahela River.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 14, 1944%0aIn one of the district's worst trolley disasters, six persons were killed and 34 injured when a Homestead-East Pittsburgh streetcar loaded with war workers crashed into the rear of an empty East Liberty-Homestead car at Munhall Junction.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 4, 1944%0aPittsburgh realty values dropped to $980,000,000, their lowest point in 25 years and about $30,000,000 under the 1941 assessment.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 11, 1944%0aThousands of Monday night Christmas shoppers were stranded Downtown by a 15-inch snowfall; all hotels were filled to capacity and lobbies were pressed into service as shelter; mills, schools, and many other activities were forced to suspend for two days.%0a%0a%0a%0a1945%0aWork stoppages were reduced 50 per cent during the year by a United States Steel -- United Steel Workers agreement on principle of a "fair day's work for a fair day's pay," setting up 32 job classifications and eliminating "speed up."%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary, 1945%0aPittsburgh Foundation was instituted.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 3, 1945%0aMayor Scully signed an ordinance setting the 1946 budget at $25,417,422 -- highest since 1931.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 30, 1945%0aPark H. Martin, who, as chief engineer of the County Works Department, formulated the county's long-range planning program in 1936, was appointed executive director of the Allegheny Conference on Community Development by Dr. Robert E. Doherty, chairman.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 16, 1945%0aDr. John G. Bowman the nation's highest-paid educator of the day at $31,500 a year, resigned after 15 years as chancellor of the University of Pittsburgh; Dr. Rufus H. Fitzgerald, vice-chancellor, was designated his successor.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 7, 1945%0aHeavy production losses resulted and 25,000 persons in industry were idled by swollen rivers which rose to a crest of 33.4 feet.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 10, 1945%0aThe city marked the 100th anniversary of its great fire of 1845 with a parade and pageantry.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 12, 1945%0aThe city and county governments, business, schools, and all other activities were suspended, all churches scheduled special prayer services, and Mayor Scully asked all amusement places to close in mourning for President Franklin D. Roosevelt.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 30, 1945%0aDr. Paul R. Anderson, dean of Lawrence College in Appleton, Wisconsin, was elected president of Pennsylvania College for Women to succeed Dr. Herbert L. Spencer.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 8, 1945%0aCouncilman George E. Evan, chairman of the Pittsburgh Housing Authority and a pioneer in slum-clearance planning, died at the age of 69.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 25, 1945%0aOne hundred thousand persons turned out to extend a hero's welcome to 64 officers and enlisted men returning home from the war.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 25, 1945%0aStockholders of the Pittsburgh Coal Company approved a merger with the Consolidation Coal Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 9, 1945%0aRussian labor leaders arrived to tour the district's steel mills.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 14, 1945%0aThe city was jubilant over the surrender of Japan.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 17, 1945%0aPittsburgh district industries laid off 7000 workers as the first cancellation of a war contract became effective.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 6, 1945%0aDavid L. Lawrence, 56-year-old Democratic state chairman, was elected Mayor of Pittsburgh by a margin of 12,000 votes; five Democratic councilmen retained their seats.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 14, 1945%0aAt meeting of civic leaders in the Duquesne Club, Richard K. Mellon, president of Regional Planning Association, urged concerted action on plans for a proposed 36-acre $6,000,000 state park at the Point.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 5, 1945%0aCouncil passed an ordinance setting the highest real estate levy in the city's history-28 mills on land and 14 mills on buildings, a 12 per cent increase over that of 1945.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 15, 1945%0aArtemas C. Leslie, son of State Senator Max G. Leslie, was elected district attorney by the judiciary to succeed Russell H. Adams, judge-elect.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 18, 1945%0aThe county commissioners approved a resolution to create the Allegheny County Sanitary Authority to build and operate a $50,000,000 county-wide sewage disposal system.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 21, 1945%0aPark Superintendent Ralph E. Griswold angrily resigned in protest against an "archaic administrative system" for maintaining and operating the city's $25,000,000 park system.%0a%0a%0a%0a1946%0aCarnegie Institute of Technology received an $8,000,000 grant from the Carnegie Foundation.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 7, 1946%0aSworn in as the city's 47th mayor for the start of the 13th year of unbroken Democratic rule in the city, Mayor David L. Lawrence promised that his basic objective was to make Pittsburgh "outstanding where it is now merely good."%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 10, 1946%0aThe Commonwealth asked the city and county to contribute a total of $6,000,000 as their share of the estimated $31,000,000 cost of the Penn-Lincoln Parkway.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 15, 1946%0aIn the Pittsburgh district 18,000 Westinghouse employees joined a nationwide strike of 200,000 electrical industry workers seeking a $2-a-day wage increase.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 20, 1946%0aIn the largest single walk-out in the nation's history, 800,000 CIO United Steel Workers -- 227,000 of them in the Pittsburgh district -- closed down the steel industry after President Truman's 11th hour fact-finding efforts failed. The first picket line appeared at the Irwin works and National Tube plant.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 21, 1946%0aAll mills in the district were silent, steel production hit a 50 year low; Philip Murray, in nation-wide broadcast from Pittsburgh, accused American business of an "evil conspiracy" to destroy labor unions.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 27, 1946%0aR. K. Mellon and Sarah Mellon Scaife announced gift of a 13-acre tract of land at Fifth and Penn and $100,000 in cash for development by the city of a public recreation center.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 12, 1946%0aTrolley service was suspended and the area was blacked out by a one-day strike of 3400 Duquesne Light employees demanding a 20 per cent cost-of-living pay increase.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 15, 1946%0aSeventy thousand United States Steel employees in the Pittsburgh area began to return to work following the signing of an agreement for an 18-cent hourly wage increase, ending a 27-day shutdown of mills.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 28, 1946%0aAttorney General James H. Duff, a Carnegie citizen, was slated as Republican nominee for governor.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 1, 1946%0aThreats of a power blackout were removed when Duquesne Light's independent union agreed to arbitrate the wage dispute.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 6, 1946%0aA $200,000, five-alarm fire destroyed a building-supply building at 410 Liberty Avenue, and flames spread to the nearby Pittsburgh and West Virginia Railroad trestle and to part of the old Wabash Terminal.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 14, 1946%0aThe county commissioners proposed a $300,000 people's bond issue for public improvements, including $8,000,000 for the Greater Pittsburgh Airport and an Ohio River Boulevard extension through the North Side into the Triangle.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 14, 1946%0aThe Farmers Deposit National Bank prepared to become a $200,000,000 institution with acquisition of the Pitt National Bank.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 18, 1946%0aMaurice Falk, Pittsburgh philanthropist, co-founder of the Falk Chemical Company, and originator of the Maurice and Laura Falk Foundation, died at the age of 79 in Florida.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 22, 1946%0aAnother fire, with damages estimated at $500,000, gutted the Wabash Terminal and railroad trestle and damaged 11 warehouses. It was this group of structures which blocked the development of the Point area.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 22, 1946%0aState police moved into areas around Westinghouse plants to enforce a court order limiting picketing in the 67-day strike of Westinghouse workers.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 25, 1946%0aGeneral Brehon B. Somervell, commander of the Army Service Forces in World War II, was elected president of the Koppers Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 1, 1946%0aSmoke-control regulations, suspended with the start of the war, were revived in a new ordinance establishing October 1 as the effective date for first half of program.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 4, 1946%0aEnforcement of home provisions of the smoke-control ordinance was postponed one year as result of an agreement worked out by the Allegheny Conference on Community Development and the Western Pennsylvania Conference on Air Pollution, representing coal producers.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 12, 1946%0aAn 18-cent hourly wage raise was awarded to Duquesne Light workers by the arbitration board.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 7, 1946%0aFederal Court ordered the Pittsburgh Railways to reorganize and find an immediate solution to its financial problems.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 9, 1946%0aA 115-day strike of 75,000 Westinghouse workers -- longest major walkout since the war -- ended with the CIO-United Electrical accepting an 18-cent hourly wage increase; 15,000 Pittsburgh district employees approved pact and prepared to go back to work.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 3, 1946%0aThe Civic Light Opera, founded on a $50,000 gift from Edgar J. Kaufmann and the 10-year efforts of a civic group headed by A. L. Wolk, H. Edgar Lewis, Mrs. Clifford Heinz, and others, opened its first eight-week summer season with a performance of Victor Herbert's Naughty Marietta before 5000 persons at Pitt Stadium.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 19, 1946%0aPittsburgh's Billy Conn was knocked out at Yankee Stadium, New York, in the eighth round of his second attempt to win the heavyweight boxing championship from Joe Louis.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 26, 1946%0aOfficial casualty lists of the United States War Department placed Allegheny County's World War II dead at 3982 out of a total of 26,554 for Pennsylvania.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 8, 1946%0aThe Mellon National Bank and Trust Company became a billion-dollar financial institution, one of the nation's largest and strongest, as the result of an approval of merger by directors of the Union Trust Company of Pittsburgh and the Mellon National Bank.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 18, 1946%0aGround was broken in Moon Township for a $10,000,000 Greater Pittsburgh Airport extension.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 27, 1946%0aThe first Civic Light Opera season ended as a success, with total attendance of 270,000 and gate receipts at $319,121.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust, 1946%0aConstruction work started on a new bus terminal on the site of the old Monongahela House at Smithfield and Water streets.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 4, 1946%0aThe 13-story, 500-room Roosevelt Hotel was purchased by Charles M. Morris and Norbert Stern for $1,800,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 8, 1946%0aAfter 47 years under ownership of the Dreyfuss family, the Pittsburgh Pirates Baseball Club was purchased, at a price reported to be about $2,250,000, by a combine headed by Frank E. McKinney, Indianapolis banker, and including singer Bing Crosby, attorney Thomas P. Johnson, of Pittsburgh, and realtor John W. Calbraith, of Columbus, Ohio.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 3, 1946%0aIn a move to break a deadlock in their wage dispute with the Duquesne Light Company, members of the 3800-member power union voted to strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 24, 1946%0aThe city's power supply was cut to 45 per cent when Duquesne Light Company employees failed to report for work; Union President George L. Mueller was sentenced to one year in jail for inspiring the strike in defiance of a court restraining order. Pittsburgh labor leaders, headed by County Commissioner John J. Kane, protested Mueller's arrest.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 25, 1946%0aEight thousand steel and electrical workers in the Pittsburgh district struck in protest against George Mueller's arrest; despite Mueller's plea to them to return to work, union members voted in a meeting to refuse to consider a company offer until the court lifted its antistrike injunction. Trolley service was cut 50 per cent; many stores closed.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 26, 1946%0aNegotiations were resumed and formal picketing started when the contempt citation against George Mueller was dismissed.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 28, 1946%0aTrolley service was stopped by a sympathy strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 1, 1946%0aThe city's eight major hotels -- William Penn, Roosevelt, Fort Pitt, Pittsburgher, Keystone, Webster Hall, Schenley, and Henry -- closed at midnight when AFL hotel restaurant employees, Local 237, walked off job to enforce wage demands.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 1, 1946%0aThe city's smoke-control law became effective for industry, railroads, and commercial establishments.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 7, 1946%0aClosed two weeks because of the power blackout, the department stores reopened and were stormed by crowds of eager shoppers.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 14, 1946%0aDespite the power strike, business and social life in Pittsburgh returned to near-normal; a number of auxiliary generating plant appeared on sidewalks outside Downtown buildings; traffic into the Downtown area increased 25 per cent; steel production was running at from 80 to 100 per cent of capacity; schools opened; crime decreased.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 14, 1946%0aTrolley and bus operators voted to cross the electric union picket lines, and limited transit service was resumed.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 21, 1946%0aFull street lighting was resumed after the union agreed to submit wage demands to arbitration, ending the 27-day power strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 5, 1946%0aThe Very Reverend Daniel Ivancho, 38-year-old Cleveland priest, was consecrated bishop of the Byzantine-Slavonic Rite of the Roman Catholic Church in a four-hour ceremony at St. Paul's Cathedral; he was the second American to be so honored.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 12, 1946%0aCity Council approved an ordinance creating a five-man Urban Redevelopment Authority as an instrument for acquiring and clearing land in the city's fight against blight and slums; Mayor Lawrence became its chairman.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 18, 1946%0aIn a meeting called by the United Smoke Council, a majority of municipal officers of Allegheny County demanded that the proposed county-wide smoke-control law include all railroads.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 22, 1946%0aA 53-day shutdown of eight Pittsburgh hotels ended when 1700 striking employees voted to go back to work.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 25, 1946%0aThe city's first "brown-out" became effective with a national order to curtail electric power consumption as the result of a coal short-age caused by another nationwide strike of miners.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 26, 1946%0aPittsburgh was assured funds for the Conemaugh Dam flood-control project when the Truman administration decided to spend an additional $55,000,000 for such work.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 5, 1946%0aSome 120,000 steel workers, railroaders, and miners were idle in the Pittsburgh area because of the coal strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 9, 1946%0aAt the annual dinner of the Regional Planning Association in the Duquesne Club, announcement was made of the organization of the Pittsburgh Public Parking Authority and a plan to build 20 new parking garages for 25,819 cars daily at a total cost of $36,000,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 11, 1947%0aThe Veterans Administration approved plans for a 1248-bed hospital above Pitt Stadium at a cost of $11,000,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 22, 1947%0aHundreds of persons were forced to seek overnight shelter Downtown when an 11-inch snow-storm hit the city and disrupted traffic.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch, 1947%0aPittsburgh's new "Ladycops," 100 strong, appeared for the first time at school crossings to protect children from traffic.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 17, 1947%0aBen Moreell, Chief of the United States Navy Bureau of Yards and Docks in World War II and organizer and commander of the construction battalions -- the famed "Seabees" -- was elected president and chairman of the board of Jones and Laughlin.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 20, 1947%0aMayor Lawrence ordered all-out crackdown on railroad violators of the city's new antismoke law.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 20, 1947%0aRichard K. Mellon, as president of the Regional Planning Association, expressed wholehearted support of all 10 bills in the "Pittsburgh Package" legislative program for improving the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 2, 1947%0aA six-month brewery jurisdictional war ended with a truce between AFL Teamsters and CIO Brewery Workers.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 18, 1947%0aWestinghouse and the United Electrical Workers signed a pact providing for an 11-1/2-cent hourly wage increase for workers.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 18, 1947%0aA record opening-day crowd at Forbes Field -- 38,2 16, including Bing Crosby -- saw the Pittsburgh Pirates, under new ownership, defeat Cincinnati, 12 to II.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 18, 1947%0aThe new bus terminal was opened at Water and Smithfield Streets and hailed as the first step in "the Downtown of tomorrow."%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 20, 1947%0aUnited States Steel granted a $1-a-day wage increase to 140,000 employees.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 23, 1947%0aPitt announced plans to build a $2,000,000 field house and gymnasium.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 30, 1947%0aThe State Senate passed, 25 to 4, a county-wide smoke-control bill covering railroads; also enacted in the Legislature was a bill to create a county-wide system of incineration.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 6, 1947%0aDefeated in the House, a bill to create the Pittsburgh Parking Authority was rescued by Governor Duff and submitted for reconsideration.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 9, 1947%0aA 31-day taxi strike ended when 900 members of Local 128, AFL Teamsters, agreed to a 45-cent hourly pay raise.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 21, 1947%0aPhilip Murray issued a two-year, no-strike order to 3000 United Steel Workers locals.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 23, 1947%0aAs the first step in a station improvement program, the Pennsylvania Railroad began dismantling its huge passenger train shed.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 27, 1947%0aA major advancement in smoke control was represented in the Pennsylvania Railroad's announcement of a complete dieselization program, with the first 47 diesel locomotives scheduled for operation before the end of 1947.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 4, 1947%0aThe Allegheny Conference on Community Development, in its first "mass transit" report, branded Pittsburgh's transportation system as outmoded; it recommended an Oakland to Downtown subway, express buses, a curb parking ban, and other measures.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 5, 1947%0aThe Parking Authority Act became law.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 8, 1947%0aIn the preceding 15-year period, the A. W. Mellon Educational and Charitable Trust contributed a total of $76,000,000 to local and national institutions, a trust report showed.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 12, 1947%0aThe Brentwood Motor Coach strike ended after 44 days of one of the longest transportation tie-ups in city history.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 19, 1947%0aThe annual assessment report showed assessed valuation in the city had dropped to $957,234,801- nearly $250,000,000 below the 1936 figure.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 31, 1947%0aA 60-day strike which idled 2500 truck drivers in Western Pennsylvania ended.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 31, 1947%0aThe Allegheny County Free Fair drew the largest one-day crowd in its history-roughly estimated at 450,000 persons.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 2, 1947%0aFor the first time police began enforcing the city's ban on Downtown curb parking between 8 and 9,30 AM, and 4:30 and 6 P.M. daily.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 9, 1947%0aA river excursion boat, the Island Queen, said to be the largest river pleasure boat in the world, exploded as it was tied to the Monongahela River wharf; 19 persons were fatally injured.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 9, 1947%0aCity voters approved a $21,000,000 bond issue for an assortment of municipal improvements to cover sewers, streets, parks, and other facilities.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 23, 1947%0aMayor Lawrence returned to his desk after a six-week layoff enforced by a delicate eye operation.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 1, 1947%0aThe city's antismoke ordinance, expected to save the city $16,000,000 a year in cleaning, health, and decorating bills was extended to 141,788 coal-burning private homes.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 3, 1947%0aA survey showed that the steel industry was spending "in excess of $100,000,000" in the Pittsburgh district for expansion and replacement of old equipment.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 23, 1947%0aA three-man congressional investigating committee opened a hearing on Pittsburgh's critical housing shortage. Its climax came when the committee chairman, Senator Joseph R. McCarthy, of Wisconsin, threatened to expel City Solicitor Anne X. Alpern from the hearing room when she repeatedly called attention to the senator's failure to support public housing measures.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 29, 1947%0aPresident Richard K. Mellon of the Pittsburgh Regional Planning Association, at its annual dinner, announced plans for redevelopment of 70 acres of the Lower Hill District and creation there of a "Pittsburgh Center," to include a sports arena for 18,000, apartment housing, a new street pattern, and other improvements.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 4, 1947%0aWilliam S. Rahauser, Democrat of Coraopolis, was elected district attorney over incumbent Artemas C. Leslie; five Democratic councilmen were re-elected; County Commissioners Kane and Rankin were re-elected; Earnest Hillman was elected minority commissioner.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 10, 1947%0aA financial drive to back Henry A. Wallace for president as a third-party candidate was launched in Pittsburgh at Syria Mosque, where he spoke to an overflow crowd.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 24, 1947%0aMayor Lawrence presented to Council an all-time high budget, totaling $30,110,973 for 1948.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 28, 1947%0aCity Council passed the record-high budget and enacted three new special taxes -- mercantile, amusement, and personal property -- over the bitter opposition of business interests.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 28, 1947%0aThe Pittsburgh Board of Education adopted an $18,000,000 budget, an increase of $3,000,000 over 1947, and levied a new $5-a-year head tax on all city residents over 21 years.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 5, 1948%0aTrolley fares went up to 10 cents cash and three-for-a-quarter tokens were eliminated.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 15, 1948%0aSecretary of State George C. Marshall spoke at the 74th annual dinner of the Pittsburgh Chamber of Commerce, warned against any cuts in United States aid to Europe.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 19, 1948%0aState Supreme Court upheld the city's new mercantile and personal property taxes.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 20, 1948%0aRichard K. Mellon, the Jaycees' "man of the year," announced creation of a $6,400,000 Richard King Mellon Foundation -- the seventh to be set up by members of his family.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 29, 1948%0aA long-smoldering feud between left- and right-wing factions of the CIO-United Electrical flared into riot proportions during a meeting at the Fort Pitt Hotel.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 31, 1948%0aBoggs and Buhl, 79-year-old North Side department store, was purchased for $2,500,000 by a group of Pittsburghers and New Yorkers and thus saved from liquidation; plans were announced for a $1,000,000 rejuvenation.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 4, 1948%0aThe Equitable Life Assurance Society of New York purchased the 33-story Koppers Building for $6,000,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 14, 1948%0aWorkmen Evert J. Hungerford and John E. Morse were killed in a rock fall during construction of the Squirrel Hill Tunnels of the Penn-Lincoln Parkway.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 16, 1948%0aAt the outset of a strike of 1100 Yellow Cab drivers, Louis Di Lembo, 28, a striker, was killed on a Downtown street by a shot fired from a passing Owl Cab.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 24, 1948%0aFritz Reiner announced his resignation after 10 years as conductor of the Pittsburgh Symphony.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 26, 1948%0aThe Pennsylvania Railroad announced plans to build a $4,500,000 warehouse covering three blocks between Penn and Liberty avenues.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 9, 1948%0aThe 24-day Yellow Cab strike came to an end.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 11, 1948%0aJudge William H. McNaugher ruled invalid a 1947 city ordinance to sell the historic Diamond Market House. He held that the city had no right to sell because it never legally owned the property, which was laid out in 1784 as a "public square" by John Penn and John Penn, Jr.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 21, 1948%0aDuquesne Light announced plans for a $28,000,000 power plant at Elrama, near Clairton, to serve the area.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 31, 1948%0aGeorge Hubbard Clapp, one of five men responsible for the production of aluminum, the founder of the Aluminum Company of America and the oldest alumnus of Pitt, died at the age of 90 at Sewickley Valley Hospital.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 11, 1948%0aDr. John B. (Jock) Sutherland, coach of the Pittsburgh Steelers and regarded as Pittsburgh's greatest gridiron figure, died at the age of 59 at West Penn Hospital.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 12, 1948%0aSoft-coal miners of western Pennsylvania began returning to work on the 29th day of a walkout that won for them $100-a-month retirement pay.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 14, 1948%0aThe rivers went to 29.5 feet in a "surprise" flood.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 15, 1948%0aThomas A. Mellon, retired president of Mellon-Stuart Company and nephew of the late A. W. Mellon, died at the age of 74.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 22, 1948%0aUnited States Steel announced a $25,000,000 price cut after rejecting demands for a pay increase.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 24, 1948%0aPennsylvania Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of the Pittsburgh Public Parking Authority and opened the way for the start of a parking program in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 26, 1948%0aW. L. Mellon, at 80, retired as chairman of the board of the Gulf Oil Corporation after 45 years as the firms active head; J. F. Drake was named his successor; S. A. Swensrud was named president. At the same annual meeting the company announced plans to spend $250,000,000 for expansion.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 31, 1948%0aA five-alarm fire destroyed Pitt's chemical engineering and metallurgical laboratory on the upper campus at a loss of $500,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 1, 1948%0aThe Philadelphia Company, Pittsburgh utility holding company, was ordered by the Securities Exchange Commission to dispose of its gas and transportation properties and dissolve its business.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 3, 1948%0aThe University of Pittsburgh announced the greatest single expansion move in its 161-year history, a $19,500,000 program to build eight new structures, including a new medical school, nurses' home, and library. A campaign for $16,500,000 in public subscriptions was started.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 20, 1948%0aWestinghouse agreed to an 8 per cent wage increase for 70,000 employees.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 1, 1948%0aWallace Richards, 44, director of Pittsburgh Regional Planning for 11 years and one of Pittsburgh's leading professional planners, became assistant director of Carnegie Museum in charge of a revitalization program for that institution.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 20, 1948%0aUnited States Steel raised prices of finished steel product an average of $9.34 per ton.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 22, 1948%0aThe city hired Herbert J. Dunsmore, Michigan expert in food and milk sanitation, as its first public health engineer.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 9, 1948%0aPlans were announced for a 40-story combination United States Steel-Mellon National Bank and Trust Company office skyscraper to connect with the Mellon Bank Building on Fifth at Smithfield.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 23, 1948%0aThe city signed a $3,475,000 contract with the Broadway Maintenance Corporation of New York for installation and maintenance of an entirely new and modern street-lighting system.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 1, 1948%0aThe Veterans Administration revealed plans for a $17,000,000 hospital to consist of 11 major buildings on a 200-acre site adjoining the city's Leech Farm Tuberculosis hospital.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 2, 1948%0aEdward V. Babcock, World War I Republican Mayor, former member of Council, county commissioner, and multimillionaire lumberman, died at the age of 84 at his home, 5135 Ellsworth Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 9, 1948%0aWilliam N. McNair, Pittsburgh's most publicized, most quixotic Mayor and the city's best-known and most fervent single-tax advocate, died at the age of 68 when he was stricken in the St. Louis, Missouri, Union Station. He had gone to that city to address the Henry George School of Social Science.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 15, 1948%0aTens of thousands of Pittsburghers visited the Freedom Train during its stopover at Pennsylvania Station.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 28, 1948%0aBernard Nieman, president of Frank and Seder, died at the age of 68 at his home, 5405 Northumberland.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 1, 1948%0aSenator Alben W. Barkley, Democratic vice-presidential nominee, campaigned in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 2, 1948%0aPittsburgh Playhouse announced plans for a new theater.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 3, 1948%0aMrs. William Thaw, Jr., once the "grand matron" of Pittsburgh society, died at the age of 94 at her home, 5427 Forbes Street.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 11, 1948%0aIn a major campaign address before 20,000 at Hunt Armory, Governor Thomas E. Dewey offered a 12-point program for labor to strengthen "free society."%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 18, 1948%0aHenry A. Wallace, Progressive candidate for President, spoke to a crowd of 3100 at Duquesne Gardens.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 22, 1948%0aGeneral Motors leased the Ambridge shipyards for a metal stamping plant.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 23, 1948%0aPresident Truman addressed 25,000 enthusiastic partisans in and around Hunt Armory. Philip Murray shared the platform and spoke in support of the President's re-election.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 25, 1948%0aGeneral Motors announced plans to build a second metal stamping plant in the Pittsburgh district after purchasing a Mifflin Township site from Carnegie-Illinois Steel for its Fisher Body Division.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 27, 1948%0aWestinghouse gave $200,000 to Pitt for a science building.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 31, 1948%0aA four-day smog began to lift from the Pittsburgh district after causing the death of 20 people in nearby Donora.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 2, 1948%0aAllegheny County gave Truman 325,411; Dewey 252,638; Wallace 10,883 in the presidential election. Congressman John R. McDowell, Republican member of the House un-American Activities Investigating Committee, was defeated by Harry J. Davenport in his bid for re-election.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 19, 1948%0aFor the second time in less than a year, the Pittsburgh Railways sought a fare increase -- to 12 cents cash; the Bell Telephone Company requested a 25.5 per cent increase for private phones.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 22, 1948%0aCity Council authorized City Solicitor Anne X. Alpern to wage a fight against the "highly unjust advance" asked for trolleys.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 23, 1948%0aThe United States Public Health Service, in a 100,000-word survey report, charged that the city was deficient in its health department and recommended $1,000,000 worth of improvements.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 24, 1948%0aCaptain Thomas J. Hamilton, twice football coach of the United States Naval Academy at Annapolis, was named athletic director of the University of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 1, 1948%0aEdgar J. Kaufmann, president of the Civic Light Opera Association, announced plans for construction of a $1,000,000 amphitheater with a retractable roof.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 7, 1948%0aThe H. J. Heinz Company disclosed plans for a $15,000,000 expansion program at its North Side plant, including construction of four new buildings.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 13, 1948%0aCarnegie Tech announced a $4,000,000 building and renovation program in a move to relieve overcrowding.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 27, 1948%0aThomas J. Fitzpatrick, head of the left-wing forces in Local 601, United Electrical Workers, was defeated in his bid for re-election as president. The "Rank and File" forces, headed by Phil Counahan, assumed control of the union after a long and bitter fight.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 28, 1948%0aThe job of building the nation's first atomic-powered engine -- for use in propelling a navy ship -- was assigned by the Atomic Energy Commission to the Westinghouse Electric Corporation, which immediately made preparation to employ some 600 persons in the district for the project.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 2, 1949%0aA report by the Pittsburgh Industrial Development Council of the Chamber of Commerce showed that 50 new industries were established in the Pittsburgh area in 1948.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 4, 1949%0aJones and Laughlin Steel prepared to launch a $210,000,000 postwar expansion program, including a new six-furnace open-hearth shop at the South Side works.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 4, 1949%0aA report from the Building Owners and Managers Association showed the rate of occupancy in 40 Pittsburgh office buildings was 99.8 per cent.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 11, 1949%0aPittsburgh's first television station -- DuMont's WDTV, Channel 3 -- went on the air with a program originating on the stage of Syria Mosque.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 2, 1949%0aThe Aluminum Company of America announced plans for the nation's first all-aluminum office skyscraper.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 13, 1949%0aThe State purchased from the Pennsylvania Railroad 1 3 acres for the projected Point Park.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril, 1949%0aThe largest project in a flood -- control network to protect Pittsburgh -- the $44,000,000 Conemaugh Dam, near Saltsburg -- went into construction.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 2, 1949%0aA minor riot had to be quelled by police when a crowd outside Carnegie Music Hall, North Side, closed in on 250 Communists after a rally.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 11, 1949%0aMore than 100,000 items went on sale at auction at the Hotel Henry preparatory to its demolition to clear the site for the new United States Steel-Mellon building.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 13, 1949%0aA grant of $225,000 for revival of the International Exhibit of Contemporary Painting at Carnegie Institute was provided by the A. W. Mellon Educational and Charitable Trust.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 23, 1949%0aThe Mellon family gave $4,000,000 to the city for acquisition of a midtown site and establishment of a park over a 1000-car, block-square underground parking garage.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 17, 1949%0aHarry W. Fowler, 58-year-old chairman of the County Planning Commission, became the first North Sider to be named to the board of county commissioners.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 19, 1949%0aCrucible Steel opened a new $18,000,000 sheet and strip mill at its Midland works.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 21, 1949%0aMore than 200,000 persons lined the banks of the Monongahela River to watch Carnegie-Illinois's Homestead defeat Jones and Laughlin's William Larimer Jones by inches in a modern-day race of stern-wheelers.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 28, 1949%0aThe Pittsburgh Public Parking Authority announced a program to build four off-street parking garages Downtown to alleviate the growing traffic problem.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 6, 1949%0aCarnegie Institute of Technology opened a nuclear research center at nearby Saxonburg.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 9, 1949%0aDr. J. C. Warner, chemistry department head and wartime atomic scientist, was named to succeed Dr. Robert E. Doherty on the latter's retirement July 1, 1950, as president of Carnegie Tech.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 18, 1949%0aThe United Engineering and Foundry, the Mesta Machine Company, and Westinghouse received major portions of a $149,360,000 contract for a French steel mill scheduled for construction under the European Recovery Administration program.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 28, 1949%0aOn request of the city, the State Supreme Court postponed trolley rate increases indefinitely.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 13, 1949%0aThe Urban Redevelopment Authority announced the first public-private project of its kind in the nation-a plan to clear 30 South Side blocks of substandard housing and small business for Jones and Laughlins $42,000,000 South Side expansion, improve surrounding streets, and eliminate three railroad grade crossings.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 5, 1949%0aPresident Truman addressed an estimated crowd of 200,000 at the County Fair; later, 15,000 AFL members marched through Downtown in the city's first Labor Day parade in eight years.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 13, 1949%0aFollowing a bitter campaign, Mayor Lawrence won the nomination for re-election; his primary election opponent was AFL-backed Councilman Edward J. Leonard.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 20, 1949%0aThe Equitable Life Assurance Society approved plans to convert 23 acres in lower Triangle into a modern, landscaped business area, the first project consisting of three 20-story office buildings.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 22, 1949%0aThe Mellon Educational and Charitable Trust Fund gave $13,600,000 to the University of Pittsburgh to build and operate a Graduate School of Public Health.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 2, 1949%0aBecause of alleged Communist leanings, the United Electrical Workers Union was expelled from the CIO in a convention at Cleveland; United Electrical locals in the Pittsburgh area, under right-wing control, withdrew from the parent union and prepared to charter a CIO electrical union.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 8, 1949%0aMayor Lawrence was given a majority of 56,000 votes, the largest ever accorded a Mayoralty candidate of Pittsburgh, in his victory over Timothy F. (Tice) Ryan for reelection to his second term.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 11, 1949%0aA 42-day strike, which halted production in steel mills of the district and nation, was ended when United States Steel signed a contract with the CIO-United Steel Workers for a company-financed pension plan.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 11, 1949%0aThe city had its largest Armistice Day parade in 31 years, with 20,000 veterans of three wars participating.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 16, 1949%0aThe Pennsylvania Railroad raised district commuter fares 22 per cent.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 20, 1949%0aAfter an eight-month trial, the Post-Gazette printed the final edition of its Sunday paper and returned to a six-day operation; copyrights and features were sold to the Sunday Sun-Telegraph.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 23, 1949%0aThe 12-cent trolley and 15-cent bus fare became effective; State Supreme Court refused the citys plea for a further suspension of higher rates.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 5, 1949%0aMayor Lawrence again submitted to Council a record-high budget, proposing appropriation of $34,400,000 for 1950.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 11, 1949%0aEdward T. Leech, 57, editor of the Pittsburgh Press for 18 years, died at Mercy Hospital.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 15, 1949%0aUnited States Steel announced a price increase averaging $4 a ton.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 21, 1949%0aCharles R. Cox resigned as president of Carnegie-Illinois Steel and was succeeded by Clifford Hood.%0a%0a%0a%0a1950%0aPopulation: 676,806. Pittsburgh is listed as the 12th largest city in America.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 4, 1950%0aFor the third time in two years, the Pittsburgh Railways Company announced rate increases -- to 15 cents on trolleys and 20 cents on buses.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 11, 1950%0aLawsuits brought by property owners in the Lower Triangle were dismissed by State Supreme Court and the way was clear for construction of the 23-acre Gateway Center.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 25, 1950%0aJanuary heat records were shattered when the temperature went to 76.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 10, 1950%0aDetailed plans were disclosed for construction of the Penn-Lincoln Parkway West with a large interchange in Carnegie.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 14, 1950%0aFifty million dollars worth of contracts were signed in the Mayor's office for the start of Gateway Center. At the same time the Urban Redevelopment Authority announced purchase of the Jones and Laughlin building, on Ross Street, for use as civic headquarters. The city also announced purchase of the Peoples Gas building for $1,116,000 for demolition in the Mellon Square Park project.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 22, 1950%0aIn testimony before the House committee, Matt Cvetic placed the number of Communist party members in Western Pennsylvania at 550, listed a number of Pittsburgh organizations as Communist "fronts," and exposed the names of many Pittsburghers alleged to be connected with the Communist party.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 27, 1950%0aThe Central Christian Church in Bellefield was destroyed by fire; the loss was estimated at $175,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 3, 1950%0aA power-conserving "dimout" ended in the Pittsburgh district as the United Mine Workers and coal-mine operators agreed on a wage increase to settle a nationwide strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 21, 1950%0aCity Council passed six ordinances banning billboards along the route of the Penn-Lincoln Parkway, except for a portion west of Bates Street.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 30, 1950%0aThe Nixon Theater-47 years and 48 seasons old-closed its doors with a performance of Mae West's Diamond Lil before an audience of 2256.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 2, 1950%0aSome 150,000 persons were without transportation after 130 drivers of the Harmony Short Line, serving the Allegheny Valley, went on strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 15, 1950%0aGovernor Duff gave the signal that set in motion an 1800-pound demolition ball that began wrecking a 103-year-old building at 110 Penn Avenue, first of many destined for destruction in the 36-acre Point Park area.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 17, 1950%0aFive additional bus lines were idled by a strike of 750 drivers, depriving 450,000 district residents of transportation.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 18, 1950%0aMayor Lawrence and Ben Moreell, president of Jones and Laughlin, jointly broke ground for the start of Jones and Laughlin's $60,000,000 open-hearth plant at its South Side works.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 31, 1950%0aAllegheny County's smoke-control ordinance, covering 128 municipalities, became partially effective.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 9, 1950%0aA strike of 3250 dairy drivers shut off milk supplies to seven counties of Western Pennsylvania.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 29, 1950%0aMembers of Local 205, AFL Teamsters, agreed to wage terms, ending a 21-day milk strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 1, 1950%0aWestern Pennsylvania's famed 28th Division was called into active service to strengthen United States ground forces in the Korean war.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 11, 1950%0aState Supreme Court overrode arguments of the city of Pittsburgh for a postponement and permitted 15-cent trolley and 20-cent bus fares to take effect.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 29, 1950%0aA 118-day strike of Harmony Bus Line drivers ended.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 31, 1950%0aSteve Nelson, Western Pennsylvania Communist party leader, was arrested with two other party leaders on bench warrants sworn out by Judge Michael A. Musmanno and charged with sedition. Later in the day Judge Musmanno personally led a raid on Communist headquarters in the Bakewell Building.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 4, 1950%0aThe Senator motion-picture house on Liberty Avenue became the new Nixon Theater with the opening of Oklahoma.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 10, 1950%0aMore than 130,000 Catholic men filled Forbes Field for a Holy Name rally in one of the citys largest religious demonstrations in history.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 13, 1950%0aA 119-day Brentwood Motor Coach strike ended.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 19, 1950%0aOriole Motor Coach drivers ended their 125-day strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 29, 1950%0aAt a height of 550 feet, the U.S. Steel-Mellon Building is topped out in a flag-raising ceremony. Thirty-five feet shorter than the Gulf Building, it was the city's second-tallest skyscraper. (The building later became known as Three Mellon Center and is now officially called 525 William Penn Place.)%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 1, 1950%0aTwo hundred mailing-room employees failed to report for work because of a contract dispute, forcing the Sun-Telegraph, Press, and Post-Gazette to suspend publication and idle 2500 other employees.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 15, 1950%0aUnder leadership of the Pittsburgh local of the American Newspaper Guild, members of 10 unions idled by the newspaper strike published the Daily Reporter after two weeks of a virtual news and advertising blackout.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 15, 1950%0aGround was broken for the 16-story nurses' residence, first major project to be started in the building program for the Pitt Medical Center.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 15, 1950%0aExcavation started for construction of three stainless steel office buildings in Gateway Center and a large underground parking area.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 19, 1950%0aGeneral Dwight D. Eisenhower, president of Columbia University, told a Carnegie Institute Founders Day audience at Carnegie Music Hall that "there is no such thing as a preventive war." The occasion marked the opening of the Institute's 38th International Art Exhibit, its first in eleven years.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 6, 1950%0aBranch Rickey, builder of the St. Louis Cardinals and Brooklyn Dodgers, was named general manager of the Pittsburgh Pirates.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 6, 1950%0aAFL Teamster delivery truck drivers began a strike against Kaufmann's, Gimbel's, and Horne's.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 8, 1950%0aCIO telephone workers of the district joined a nationwide strike, interrupting telephone service here.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 18, 1950%0aAfter posing for years as a Communist Party member, Matt Cvetic, 41-year-old executive secretary of the American Slav Congress of Pittsburgh, appeared before the House Un-American Activities Investigating Committee in Washington and revealed himself to be an FBI undercover agent.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 18, 1950%0aThe 47-day-old newspaper strike ended; 3000 employees returned to their jobs.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 24, 1950%0aAuto, bus, and trolley traffic was brought to a standstill by a 30.5-inch snowfall -- heaviest in the citys history. Snowbanks on streets were piled as high as automobile tops.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 27, 1950%0aThe city and its environs were snowbound. Newspapers failed to publish; most stores were closed; schools were closed; deaths resulting from the storm totaled 15.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 29, 1950%0aDowntown stores reopened with National Guardsmen on hand to prevent a traffic impasse. Trolleys and buses resumed operation.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 30, 1950%0aCity tow trucks began removing some 5000 snowbound autos from trolley routes; snow-removal machines were also in action.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 1, 1950%0aNational Guard road-blocks were removed and the blocks were removed and the Triangle was opened to all traffic.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 18, 1950%0aMore than 8000 members of 19 other AFL unions returned to work after AFL delivery drivers ended a 29-day strike against the three major department stores-Kaufmann's, Gimbel's, and Horne's.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 22, 1950%0aBishop Hugh C. Boyle, 77-year-old spiritual leader of 800,000 Roman Catholics in the Pittsburgh diocese, died in Mercy Hospital; he was immediately succeeded by Coadjutor Bishop John F. Dearden.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 2, 1951%0aThe State Supreme Court sustained the city's controversial "A-B-C" restaurant sanitation code, and the Department of Public Health prepared to enforce it.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 18, 1951%0aAnother trolley fare increase-this one raising the price of tokens one and three-quarters cents- became effective.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 27, 1951%0aWilliam Alvah Stewart, a city councilman, was appointed a federal judge by President Truman.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 6, 1951%0aKoppers' Kobuta rubber plant was knocked out of defense production for three months by a $500,000 fire.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 26, 1951%0aIn a message to City Council, Mayor Lawrence outlined plans for Pittsburgh's third major redevelopment program-the clearance of 100 acres of slums in the Hill District and construction of a public arena, 30 acres of housing, and other improvements.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 1, 1951%0aMayor Lawrence invited representatives of school districts and colleges and universities to meet with him to discuss organization of an educational television station for Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 16, 1951%0aDesign of a giant lighted fountain, shooting a brilliant column of water 100 feet into the air, was approved by the Point Park committee as an appropriate decoration for the tip of Point Park.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 19, 1951%0aI. W. Wilson, senior vice-president, was elected president of the Aluminum Company of America.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 5, 1951%0aMrs. Edith Oliver Rea, who pioneered in the field of Veterans' Rehabilitation (World War I) and who instituted the Grey Ladies service of the Red Cross, died in Boston, Massachusetts.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 25, 1951%0aThe Pittsburgh Railways Company asked the Public Utilities Commission for permission to abandon its 79-year-old Mount Oliver Incline.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune, 1951%0aWashington Boulevard was flooded and one woman, trapped in her car, was drowned.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 27, 1951%0aA special grand jury recommended indictment of Mayor Lawrence, City Controller Edward R. Frey, and nine others as the result of an investigation into city light and coal contracts.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 18, 1951%0aJoe Walcott, 37, knocked out Ezzard Charles in the seventh round in a heavyweight championship fight at Forbes Field before 28,272 persons -- a record fight turnout for Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 25, 1951%0aIn the primary election, Judge Michael A. Musmanno upset the Democratic leadership and won a 21-year term on the bench of Pennsylvania State Supreme Court.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 10, 1951%0aIn connection with the Penn-Lincoln Parkway project, the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad agreed to get its passenger station out of the way and build a new one at the foot of Grant Street.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 10, 1951%0aPittsburgh Railways asked that fares be raised to 17 cents on trolleys and 23 cents on buses.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 17, 1951%0aSteve Nelson, already on trial on sedition charges, was arrested by the FBI with five other district Communist leaders in the latest of a nationwide series of raids.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 31, 1951%0aAfter a 35-week trial, Communists Andrew Onda and James Dolsen were found guilty by a Criminal Court jury of advocating overthrow of the government by force and violence.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 9, 1951%0aIn a radio and television speech Mayor Lawrence denounced the management of the Pittsburgh Railways Company and appealed to the public to join the city in fighting fare increases.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 20, 1951%0aJudge Timothy F. (Tice) Ryan, 1949 Republican Mayoralty candidate, died at 65 at his East End home.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 5, 1951%0aMayor Lawrence was cleared by a grand jury, but seven other officials were indicted in connection with alleged discrepancies in contracts for a new city lighting system.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 11, 1951%0aKaufmann's department store announced purchase of the 19-story Frick Annex building for the start of a multi-million-dollar enlargement program.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 24, 1951%0aA district epidemic of bank frauds spread to Pittsburgh; three officials of the Federal Credit Union of Kaufmann's were arrested on charges of embezzling $338,901.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 30, 1951%0aDefense Mobilizer Charles E. Wilson tapped the first heat, putting into operation the new $70,000,000 open-hearth shop at the South Side plant of Jones and Laughlin Steel Corporation.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember, 1951%0aThe Pittsburgh Housing Authority initiated construction of the 1089-unit St. Clair Village housing project on the South Side.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 6, 1951%0aJames F. Malone, Republican leader, was elected district attorney over Judge Francis J. O'Connor; Democratic County Commissioners Kane and Fowler were reelected; State Senator John M. Walker of Oakmont was named minority commissioner.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 26, 1951%0aThe 67-mile $77,500,000 western extension of the Pennsylvania Turnpike was dedicated at the Ohio border with Governor Frank J. Lausche, of Ohio, promising that his state would extend the expressway.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 29, 1951%0aThe first mass transit study made under sponsorship of the Allegheny Conference on Community Development urged reconsideration of a Triangle subway estimated to cost $65,000,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 22, 1951%0aCity Council, at Mayor Lawrence's request, passed another record-high budget, totaling $41,881,900 for 1952.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 19, 1952%0aFive years after its opening, the Union Bus Terminal, Downtown, closed its doors because of bankruptcy, leaving five bus lines "homeless."%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 25, 1952%0aWilliam Steinberg, director of the Buffalo Philharmonic Orchestra, was appointed conductor of the Pittsburgh Symphony; he became the orchestra's first permanent director since the departure of Fritz Reiner in 1948.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 29, 1952%0aC. L. Austin, a former banker, was elected president of Jones and Laughlin; Ben Moreell relinquished that post but continued as chairman of the board.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 31, 1952%0aFollowing a 19-day trial, a Criminal Court jury found Steve Nelson guilty of sedition.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 6, 1952%0aEdward Specter, manager of the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra, resigned.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 24, 1952%0aThe Bigelow, first apartment house to be built in downtown Pittsburgh, was opened to tenants.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 1, 1952%0aThe Carlton House, the city's first new hotel in 25 years, received its first guests.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 1, 1952%0aAt midnight 100 men of the United States Steel Corporation sat around a horseshoe table in the Carnegie Building, then emptied of all tenants, and drank a toast to what had been "steel headquarters" for 57 years. At 8 AM, demolition crews began the long and arduous task of disassembling this structure, beam by beam, to clear the site for a Kaufmann's annex.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 3, 1952%0aAllegheny County reduced taxes to a 22-year low while adopting a $32,400,000 budget, highest in its history.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 8, 1952%0aPresident Truman ordered steel mills seized, and the United Steel Workers called off a scheduled strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 21, 1952%0aA precedent was established when Pittsburgh industry and business, through 65 of its leaders, pledged financial support to the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra; they approved a novel plan under which companies were to be designated sponsors with contributions of $10,000 annually.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 23, 1952%0aClifford Ball, 61-year-old aviation promoter for more than 35 years and founder of Pennsylvania (Capital) Airlines, was named director of the new Greater Pittsburgh Airport.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 29, 1952%0aPresident Truman s seizure of the steel industry was declared illegal by Federal Court and district steel workers joined 650,000 throughout the nation in a walkout that paralyzed the industry.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 31, 1952%0aThe new Greater Pittsburgh Airport, completed at a cost of $33,000,000, was dedicated, and more than 100,000 persons went to Moon Township over the holiday weekend to inspect the 1600-acre air terminal.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 2, 1952%0aCommercial airlines began flying a total of 228 flights daily into and out of the new airport.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 25, 1952%0aPittsburgh Railways asked the Public Utilities Commission for permission to institute a 20-cent trolley and 25-cent bus fare-the sixth rate increase in four years and the third in less than 20 months.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 30, 1952%0aJudge Henry Ellenbogan ruled out the Public Parking Authority's plan for the sale of gas, oil, and services in its parking garages.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 24, 1952%0aAt the White House, President Truman, flanked by Philip Murray and Benjamin F. Fairless, announced settlement of the 53-day steel strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 8, 1952%0aPittsburgh's Old City Hall, built in 1872 at a cost of $600,000, was sold for nearly $2,500,000 to a real estate group planning to demolish it for commercial development.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 11, 1952%0aPolice Superintendent Harvey J. Scott, the city's police chief for 13 years, was fired by Safety Director George E. A. Fairley for misconduct.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 15, 1952%0aThe Point Park Commission approved detailed plans for landscaping and developing Point Park. Wallace Richards, Parking Authority chairman, suggested a 1000-car parking garage be built on the park fringe area.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 22, 1952%0aCornelius Decatur Scully, who had served nine consecutive years as Mayor, died at the age of 73 in Winchester, Virginia.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 6, 1952%0aWilliam D. Mansfield, former state senator, former county commissioner, editor of the McKeesport Daily News, and one of McKeesport's best-known citizens, died at 74 in McKeesport Hospital.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 8, 1952%0aSenator Richard M. Nixon, Republican candidate for vice-president, charged in a speech to 3900 persons at Syria Mosque that the Communist party was aiding the Democrats.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 22, 1952%0aPresident Truman, in an address to an overflow crowd at Syria Mosque, accused General Eisenhower of following a "straight isolationist line."%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 27, 1952%0aAfter being welcomed by huge crowds, General Eisenhower, in an address at Hunt Armory, promised that the first objective of a Republican administration in Washington would be an "honorable" peace in Korea.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 29, 1952%0aCity Council approved an ordinance, recommended by Mayor Lawrence, to create a municipal authority to purchase and reconstruct the city's deteriorated water-supply system at a cost of $27,000,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 29, 1952%0aPittsburgh's first public parking garage, a 776-car facility built at a cost of $2,100,000 at Sixth Avenue and Bigelow Boulevard, was officially opened by Mayor Lawrence and Authority Chairman Wallace B. Richards.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 30, 1952%0aGovernor Adlai Stevenson, of Illinois, in a final bid for votes, declared to a crowd of 25,000 at Hunt Armory that General Eisenhower was a captive candidate of the Republican "Old Guard," the "depression party."%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 4, 1952%0aIn losing the presidential election to General Eisenhower, Governor Stevenson carried Allegheny County by 13,820 votes.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 6, 1952%0aSpecial demolition crews began the delicate task of taking apart H. J. Heinz's "Little House Where We Began" to permit expansion of the North Side plant. The house was later reassembled in its original state at Ford's Greenfield Village in Dearborn, Michigan.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 8, 1952%0aAt its 75th anniversary celebration, Duquesne University announced a $13,300,000 program to clear blight and create a modern, 25-acre Bluff campus. Ground was broken earlier in the day for construction of a women's dormitory, the first of eight new buildings.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 9, 1952%0aPhilip Murray, 66-year-old president of both the CIO and the United Steel Workers, died unexpectedly in his room at the Mark Hopkins Hotel in San Francisco after addressing 350 delegates at the United Steel Workers' western regional conference.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 14, 1952%0aA storm of protest from Downtown merchants prompted the city to postpone enforcement of a rigid curb-parking restriction adopted for Downtown streets.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 20, 1952%0aJones and Laughlin, the Urban Redevelopment Authority, and city officials signed contracts for their second joint industrial redevelopment project-the conversion of 30 acres of blighted land in Hazelwood into a productive plant.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 20, 1952%0aThe city's second parking garage, a six-level, 815-car structure on Fourth Avenue, built at a cost of $1,500,000, was opened to the motoring public.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 24, 1952%0aIn the first event of its kind ever staged, Pittsburgh's First International Contemporary Music Festival, a week-long series of concerts featuring works of contemporary composers, opened at Carnegie Music Hall.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 3, 1952%0aThe Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra played the first of a series of experimental "industrial" concerts for 1600 persons in Scott High School auditorium in North Braddock. It was the first time that any major orchestra attempted to take its music directly to an industrial community.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 5, 1952%0aMayor Lawrence signed into law the city's first fair employment practices code, prohibiting job discrimination against minority groups; Pittsburgh thus became the 23rd city in the nation with FEPC.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 23, 1952%0aTwo ultra-high frequency television stations were authorized for Pittsburgh by the Federal Communications Commission; they were channels 16 and 47.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 30, 1952%0aChancellor Rufus H. Fitzgerald, of the University of Pittsburgh, announced that 22 Pittsburgh business and industrial firms had subscribed a total of $4,836,000 for construction of a $15,000,000 building for the schools of the health professions.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 30, 1952%0aThe ten-month-old Carlton House was sold to a New York syndicate for $7,400,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 14, 1953%0aMayor Lawrence announced that articles of incorporation were ready to be filed for formation of Pittsburgh's "Metropolitan Educational Television Station, Inc.," WQED.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 15, 1953%0aGrading and seeding started at the Point Park in time for greenness in the spring.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 22, 1953%0aMayor Lawrence announced his candidacy for election to a third term in order to see through "to its climax of achievement" Pittsburgh's rebuilding program.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 26, 1953%0aPlans were announced for construction of a 2000-unit, $24,500,000 low-rent housing project in City View-Summer Hill section of the North Side. Residents of the area immediately announced plans to fight it.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 2, 1953%0aA 60-day trial of rigid no-parking rules Downtown went into effect; only 17 autos were towed away by police to the city auto pound.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 8, 1953%0aAfter obtaining Edgar J. Kaufmann's approval of the use of a $1,000,000 grant originally pledged to the Civic Light Opera, Mayor Lawrence announced plans to proceed with construction of a $7,000,000 sports-theater arena, with a retractable roof, as the key project in the Lower Hill District redevelopment area.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 10, 1953%0aDavid J. McDonald, secretary-treasurer of the United Steel Workers since its inception in 1937 and once a prospect for Hollywood filmland, was elected, without opposition, second president of the 1,100,000 union.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 4, 1953%0aThe Allegheny Conference on Community Development revealed plans for a toll tunnel under Mount Washington as the most feasible way to finance that link in the Penn-Lincoln Parkway.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 12, 1953%0aA $30,000,000 public-works program for new bridges, highways, and other improvements was announced by the county commissioners.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 26, 1953%0aDr. Jonas E. Salk, 38-year-old University of Pittsburgh researcher and professor, reported success of a new polio vaccine tried on 90 human beings; the vaccine was developed by him and his staff at Pitt.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 20, 1953%0aCarnegie Tech announced a move to raze Carnegie Inn, a campus landmark, and build a modern $700,000 mens dormitory.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 6, 1953%0aBecause of Pittsburgh Railways' opposition, the city discarded its plan for making Forbes Street and Fifth Avenue one way in order to relieve traffic congestion expected with temporary closing of the Boulevard of the Allies.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 12, 1953%0aThe $4,500,000 Nurses' Residence for the Medical Center was dedicated and its quarters were opened for 600 student nurses and 46 staff members.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 19, 1953%0aIn the primary election, City Solicitor Anne X. Alpern received both the Democratic and Republican nominations to a judgeship.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 4, 1953%0aPittsburgh's most publicized and highest paid baseball player, Ralph Kiner, was traded to the Chicago Cubs.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 5, 1953%0aMany state and local officials participated in a ribbon cutting opening the $18,000,000 Squirrel Hill Tunnel, the most costly single project ever undertaken by the State Highways Department. This placed in service the first eight mile stretch of the $34,000,000 Penn-Lincoln Highway.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 8, 1953%0aThe first and most troublesome of many detours resulting from new highway work took the Boulevard of the Allies out of service for some 30,000 motorists using it daily. This marked the start of Pittsburgh's most critical period of traffic congestion.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 22, 1953%0aThe Allegheny Conference on Community Development released its second citizens' mass transit study; it recommended creation of a transit authority to acquire and unify bus and trolley lines in the county.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 5, 1953%0aIt was announced that the Wabash Building, a city landmark, was to be demolished to make way for further development in the Gateway Center.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 5, 1953%0aA building in Oakland, gift of the Pittsburgh Plate Glass to the University of Pittsburgh, was provided for the headquarters of educational television in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 25, 1953%0aFollowing a six-month trial, Steve Nelson, already under a 20-year sentence to the Workhouse, and five other Communist leaders of Pittsburgh were convicted under the Smith Act in Federal Court and sentenced to five years in prison.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 7, 1953%0aJohn M. Phillips, pioneer industrialist and well-known conservationist, died at the age of 92 at his home at 2336 Brownsville Road, Carrick. He was the father of Pennsylvania's basic game code, used by many other states as a model.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 15, 1953%0aAt the start of a week-long dedication, the Aluminum Company of America opened its new 30-story office building for public inspection. On the first night 7500 invited guests toured the skyscraper, the nation's first with an all-aluminum exterior.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 18, 1953%0aTwo thousand Pittsburghers and state officials traveled to Saltsburg by special train and auto to participate in the dedication of the Conemaugh Dam, $46,200,000 bulwark against floods, the largest and most important dam in a $125,000,000 flood-control system. The speaker, Major General S. D. Sturgis, Jr., chief of army engineers, warned that navigational locks and dams in the Ohio River were in desperate need of rehabilitation.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 23, 1953%0aThe newly constituted Metropolitan Study Commission of Allegheny County formed 10 committees to begin the job of assembling information on urban expansion under a $50,000 grant provided by Buhl Foundation.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 28, 1953%0aRichard K. Mellon, head of the nation's greatest banking empire, tacitly endorsed the Democratic leader, Mayor Lawrence, for re-election. He did so in a short speech at ground-breaking ceremonies for the Mellon Square Park and underground garage, site of which was acquired with a $4,000,000 grant from the Mellon family.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 29, 1953%0aTen thousand campaign volunteers began canvassing homes in the Pittsburgh area in solicitation of 100,000 family subscriptions of $2 each for educational television station WQED; the proceeds were to supplement grants of $350,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 6, 1953%0aPittsburgh voters overwhelmingly defeated a proposed raise in school taxes following a bitter battle.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 15, 1953%0aThe $15,000,000 Penn-Lincoln Parkway West, opening up a fast route between Downtown Pittsburgh and the Greater Pittsburgh Airport and routes west was dedicated by Governor John S. Fine and Senators James H. Duff and Edward Martin. All, as governors, were instrumental in various phases of its construction. The dedication ceremony was held at the interchange in Senator Duff's home town Carnegie.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 23, 1953%0aThe Allegheny Foundation, a new organization to aid charitable, scientific, literary, and other public activities, was chartered by the Mellon family.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 28, 1953%0aThe Public Auditorium Authority was created by Mayor Lawrence and the county commissioners for the purpose of building and operating an all-purpose civic arena in the Hill District. Brehon B. Somervell, president of Koppers Company, was chosen first chairman.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 3, 1953%0aDavid L. Lawrence defeated Leonard P. Kane by 54,000 votes and became the first Mayor in the history of Pittsburgh to be elected to a third consecutive term. The Democrats swept the city and county.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 23, 1953%0aA brief noon-time ceremony was held at Gateway Center to inscribe into history "November 23, 1753," as the date on which George Washington first envisioned the Point as a natural site. Pittsburgh thus memorialized its distinction of being "the only city in the United States to have had its location chosen by the first president."%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 27, 1953%0aFive hundred delivery truck drivers of Local 249, AFL Teamsters, began a strike against the city's major department stores. The stores remained open; the Joseph Horne Company's warehouse was stoned in the first incidence of violence.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 2, 1953%0aEdgar J. Kaufmann, charter financial backer of Lower Hill District civic arena project, promised to contribute $500,000, in addition to $1,000,000 already pledged, if needed on completion of fund-raising efforts.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 2, 1953%0aFor the first time in seven months, the Boulevard of the Allies was open to traffic on a restricted basis.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 4, 1953%0aMayor Lawrence presented to City Council what he termed the "most difficult" budget in the eight years of his administration; he also indicated reluctant approval of a wage tax as a means of raising money.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 27, 1953%0aDelayed 17 months by court orders resulting from actions started by City Solicitor Anne X. Alpern, trolley and bus rate increases -- to 20 and 25 cents, respectively -- became effective.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 30, 1953%0aAnne X. Alpern (Mrs. Irwin Swiss in private life) was sworn in as a judge of Common Pleas Court. She was the first Democratic woman in Pennsylvania elected to a judgeship.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 31, 1953%0aMayor Lawrence signed into law another record high budget, with appropriations totaling $47,282,991; it also committed the city to a 1 per cent tax on all, earned incomes within the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 1954%0aFifty squads of policemen and detectives manned road blocks in the city to halt violence in the 36-day department store strike; earlier the homes of two store executives were stoned and "paint bombed."%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 3, 1954%0aThe Pennsylvania Railroad unveiled a $3,611,400 plan for a new ramp and platform for trains to and from the west as part of its $27,000,000 station modernization program.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 4, 1954%0aAfter Mayor Lawrence was sworn in for his third term, City Council received from him a recommendation for a precedent-shattering wage tax ordinance estimated to yield the city $6,300,000 in 1954.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 18, 1954%0aIn one of the largest grants of its kind ever made, the Mellon family, represented by three foundations, gave $15,000,000 to the University of Pittsburgh for medical education. The money was designated chiefly for development of Pitt's first full-time medical school teaching staff.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 21, 1954%0aPowered by the world's first atomic engine, built by the Westinghouse Electric Corporation, the submarine USS Nautilus, christened by Mrs. Dwight D. Eisenhower, was launched at Groton, Connecticut.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 25, 1954%0aThe city's first wage tax was adopted with March 1 as the effective date. Councilman John F. Counahan was Council's only dissenter in the vote.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 25, 1954%0aState Supreme Court dismissed the Common Pleas Court conviction and 20-year sentence of Communist Steve Nelson on grounds that the case legally belonged in Federal Court under the Smith Act.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 24, 1954%0aThe attention of parents around the world was on Arsenal Elementary school in Lawrenceville, where Dr. Jonas E. Salk began his polio vaccine tests on a large-scale basis. In the gymnasium of that school 137 youngsters, first of 5000 Pittsburgh school volunteers, were given injections of the new serum.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 25, 1954%0aThe Chamber of Commerce and Allegheny Conference on Community Development undertook a joint campaign to form an "industrial development corporation" to bolster Pittsburgh's economy by attracting new light industry.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 1, 1954%0aThe wage tax of one cent on each dollar of earned income went into effect in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 9, 1954%0aFrederick Bigger, Pittsburgh's "dean of planners," resigned after 31 years of membership on the City Planning Commission, which he served for 20 years as chairman. He was co-organizer of Regional Planning Association and was noted nationally as chief planner in the New Deal's famed model-town projects of "Greenbelt," Maryland, "Greenhills," Ohio, and "Greendale," Wisconsin.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 12, 1954%0aThe Regional Planning Association issued its first report on a suburban community under an expanded new policy. The report recommended that a planned industrial district, first in the Pittsburgh area be developed in a blighted McKeesport district at the Monongahela -Youghiogheny river junction.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 24, 1954%0aTeamster delivery truck drivers ended their 113-day strike against five furniture stores -- Hahn's, Spear and Company, Ruben's, Obringer's, and May-Stern.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril, 1954%0aThe University of Pittsburgh began demolishing 32 structures on a 10-acre Oakland site preparatory to erecting its graduate school of public health.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril, 1954%0aDr. M. Graham Netting, a member of the staff for 32 years, was named director of Carnegie Museum to succeed Wallace Richards after the latter was stricken ill.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 1, 1954%0aStation WQED, the world's first community-sponsored educational noncommercial television station, went on the air.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 12, 1954%0aThe Atomic Energy Commission assigned to the Westinghouse Electric Corporation and Duquesne Light Company the job of building the first atomic electric power plant in the world. It also announced the site as Shippingport, a once important river port on the Ohio River 25 miles north of Pittsburgh. Operation of the plant also was assigned to Duquesne Light.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 28, 1954%0aA "schematic plan" for rebuilding 1286 deteriorating acres of North Side property was proposed by the Regional Planning Association, in a dinner at the H. J. Heinz plant, as the fourth major redevelopment project in the city. It included recommendations for 3000 new parking spaces, an "Allegheny Center" shopping district, new housing, additional recreation, planned neighborhood and industrial districts, all compatible with the proposed Ohio River Boulevard high-speed extension through the North Side.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 2, 1954%0aFour new buildings were dedicated on the campus of the Pennsylvania College for Women.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 9, 1954%0aDozens of traffic tie-ups occurred after bus and trolley were cut off by a strike of 2700 operators.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 11, 1954%0aThe Chamber of Commerce recommended the Allegheny Valley as the most practical route for the proposed Pittsburgh-to-Erie extension of the Pennsylvania Turnpike.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 23, 1954%0aThe garages of the Public Parking Authority were ruled tax-exempt by the State Supreme Court; the way was thus opened for construction of more garages. The same ruling held as that for taxable garage space rented to private interests for commercial purposes.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 28, 1954%0aDistrict Attorney James Malone warned against "paint bombings" after eight homes were hit by a wave of vandalism in the sixth month of the department store strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 14, 1954%0aTrolleys and buses resumed normal operation with the settlement of the 34-day strike, longest and costliest in the history of Pittsburgh Railways Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 23, 1954%0aThe Board of Education approved a $5,000,000 bond issue for a building and renovation program and elected attorney J. Garfield Houston as its new president.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 28, 1954%0aMrs. Alan M. Scaife, wife of the president of the board of trustees of the University of Pittsburgh, turned the first spade of earth to start excavation for the $15,000,000 building to house the schools of medicine, dentistry, pharmacy, and nursing.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 29, 1954%0aUnited States Steel and the United Steel Workers union signed a contract for a five-cent hourly wage increase, forestalling a scheduled strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 1, 1954%0aGround was broken on Fifth Avenue site, facing the Cathedral of Learning, for Pitt's new $2,500,000 center of natural sciences. It was named in memory of George Hubbard Clapp, the noted scientist, co-founder of the Aluminum Company of America, and president of the University of Pittsburgh board of trustees for 42 years until his death in 1949.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 11, 1954%0aContracts were awarded for the basic design of the $25,000,000 Fort Pitt Tunnel through Mount Washington.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 28, 1954%0aThe State General Authority completed negotiations with Equitable Life Assurance Society for purchase of a Gateway Center site, at a price of $1,041,143, for construction of a new $8,000,000 state office building to serve as capital of Western Pennsylvania.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 28, 1954%0aAllegheny General Hospital broke ground for a two-story building to house a "cobalt bomb," second such cancer-treatment unit to be established in the city. The first was in process of construction at Mercy Hospital.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 29, 1954%0aThe State Department of Commerce issued a report showing 46 new industries or expansions in 1954 in the Pittsburgh district; investments totaled $125,000,000, and 13,448 persons were added to payrolls.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 10, 1954%0aDr. Bryn J. Hovde, executive director of the Pittsburgh Housing Association and a nationally known expert on housing, died at the age of 58 after he was stricken on a Downtown streetcar.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 27, 1954%0aThe Board of Education announced plans to construct four new schools in the biggest building program in many years.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 2, 1954%0aThe Pittsburgh Parking Authority announced it was ready to proceed with construction of 1388 additional off-street spaces in two parking garages, to be built at a total cost of $6,000,000 and operated by Kaufmann's store primarily for the shopping convenience of customers.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 6, 1954%0aIn Denver, 1600 miles away, President Eisenhower waved an "atomic wand" over an electronic cabinet. He thus relayed the impulse that sent into motion huge steam shovels at the Shippingport site of the world's first atomic power plant. Some 1 500 business, industrial, and scientific leaders of the Pittsburgh area attended the Labor Day ground-breaking ceremony starting construction of the $45,000,000 installation.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 7, 1954%0aCity Council passed an ordinance to permit erection of a $3,500,000 eight - story apartment building on the Shady Avenue site of the historical Kenmawr Hotel, a 90-year-old landmark. The ordinance upset height building regulations for this East End area.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 11, 1954%0aA strike against the Westinghouse Electric Corporation was averted at the zero hour with the signing of a two-year contract.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 12, 1954%0aVice-Admiral Joel T. Boone, chief medical officer for the Veterans Administration, dedicated the new 11-story, 750-bed VA general medical and surgical hospital, situated above Oakland.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 17, 1954%0aUnited States Steel announced a $10,000,000 expansion program for its Homestead Works.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 21, 1954%0aThe Peoples First National Bank and Trust Company announced plans to construct a central headquarters building in the Gateway Center.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 10, 1954%0aAfter 16 months of restrictions, the vital Boulevard of the Allies was fully reopened to traffic.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 18, 1954%0aThe National Foundation for Infantile Paralysis contracted to buy the Salk polio vaccine for 9,000,000 persons in 1955.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 27, 1954%0aJones and Laughlin Steel announced a $51,000,000 program for expanding and improving its plants in 1955.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 29, 1954%0aSidney A. Swensrud, board chairman and chief executive officer of the Gulf Oil Company, became chairman of the Public Auditorium Authority following the resignation of Brehon B. Somervell. The Authority set spring of 1956 as its target date for starting construction of a civic arena in the Lower Hill District redevelopment area.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 2, 1954%0aThe county gave State Senator George M. Leader, 37-year-old chicken farmer, a plurality of more than 87,000 votes over Lloyd H. Woods for the governorship in a Democratic victory that ended 16 gears of Republican rule in Harrisburg.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 16, 1954%0aThe Allegheny County Redevelopment Authority prepared to proceed with a $3,500,000 slum clearance and redevelopment project in McKees Rocks.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 19, 1954%0aThe Baltimore and Ohio Railroad announced a decision to abandon plans for a central office building and to construct instead a small new passenger station in connection with its Penn-Lincoln Parkway relocation project.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 22, 1954%0aState Supreme Court dismissed complaints of North Side residents, enabling the Pittsburgh Housing Authority to proceed with plans for construction of a 1000-unit low-rent housing project on Summer Hill.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 26, 1954%0aTeamster delivery drivers signed a contract ending their strike against five Downtown department stores on the eve of its first anniversary; but the union served notice the drivers would not resume deliveries until 11 other store unions ended their strike. It was estimated that the walkout cost the 760 drivers and helpers a total of $5,000,000 in wages.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 3, 1954%0aWestinghouse Electric Corporation announced purchase of Pittsburgh's pioneer television station, WDTV, from DuMont Laboratories, Inc., for $9,750,000, highest amount ever paid for a television station.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 3, 1954%0aThe Pittsburgh Board of Public Education adopted an "austerity" budget of $23,882,326 for 1955, rejecting teachers' requests for pay raises but retaining kindergartens for another year.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 5, 1954%0aThe county commissioners made public proposed legislation, drafted by a seven-member citizens' committee, for creation of a countywide public transportation authority to acquire and consolidate bus and trolley lines. The legislation required approval of voters in a referendum scheduled for primary election of 1956.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 6, 1954%0aOne hundred and eighteen business firms, schools, and hospitals 80 years or older were honored by the Pittsburgh Chamber of Commerce at its 80th anniversary dinner, attended by 900 persons in the William Penn Hotel. The speakers were William Block, publisher of the Post-Gazette, the city's oldest (1786), and Alan M. Scaife, chairman of the board of the Scaife Company, second oldest (1802). Each received a special plaque.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 10, 1954%0aThe University of Pittsburgh announced plans to build four additional structures at a total cost of $2,900,000-a 336-parking-space garage, and physicians' office building to serve the Medical Center, a student union, and men's dormitory.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 12, 1954%0aDr. John C. Warner, Carnegie Tech president, was named national president of the American Chemical Society for the year 1956. He was the second Pittsburgher to be so honored. The first was Dr. E. R. Weidlein, director of the Mellon Institute, in 1937.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 15, 1954%0aEquitable Life Assurance Society of New York announced it had decided to construct a parking garage in Gateway Center for at least 600 cars.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 22, 1954%0aDuquesne University announced it was ready to build the third structure in its $13,000,000 campus expansion program -- a hall of law and business, featuring a moot courtroom made possible by a $100,000 grant from the Maurice and Laura Falk Foundation.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 24, 1954%0aMayor Lawrence signed a $48,320,473 budget for 1955, the eighth record high appropriation ordinance in eight consecutive years.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 4, 1955%0aFive employees at the Westinghouse Electric Corporation's East Pittsburgh plant were fired as "undesirable" following hearings at Washington by Senator McCarthy's investigations subcommittee.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 18, 1955%0aThe Allegheny County School Board approved working plans for a $1,300,000 new school construction program.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 1, 1955%0aThe Board of Public Education supported redevelopment of the Lower Hill area by indicating they would relinquish several vital properties situated in the heart of the district.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 14, 1955%0aGeneral Brehon Somervell, Koppers Company board chairman and president, died at 62.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 22, 1955%0aJames J. Thomas, director of District 15, CIO United Steel Workers, and veteran organizer in the steel industry, died.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 1, 1955%0aPittsburgh's new housing code -- an attempt to upgrade the city's residential property -- became effective. Every residential unit was required to have electricity, effective heating facilities, hot and cold running water, kitchen sink, a flush water closet, lavatory basin, and either a bathtub or a shower.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 9, 1955%0aW. F. Munnikhuysen was elected chairman of the board of Koppers Company, and Fred C. Foy was named president and chief executive officer at a special meeting of the hoard of directors.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 10, 1955%0aThe Defense Department announced that $15,000,000 would be spent during 1955 for antiaircraft defense of Pittsburgh. Half of the sum was to pay for installation of Nike missiles, the rest for support of the 18th AAA Group.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 13, 1955%0aHenry Kaufmann, 94, pioneer Pittsburgh merchant, one of the four founders of Kaufmann's Department Store, died in New York City.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 17, 1955%0aAFL Teamsters prepared to roll delivery trucks at the five Downtown department stores for the first time in nearly 16 months. Pickets were removed although some differences remained to be negotiated.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 15, 1955%0aEdgar J. Kaufmann -- merchant prince and pioneer planner of Pittsburgh's physical and cultural redevelopment -- one of the city's outstanding citizens, died suddenly at 69 in his Palm Springs, California home.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 25, 1955%0aBell Telephone Company announced that its new headquarters building -- the fifth structure to be added to Pittsburgh's Gateway Center -- was going into construction.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 28, 1955%0aJones and Laughlin Steel Corporation added $86,000,000 to its expansion program, including new mills to be constructed in the Pittsburgh area.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 2, 1955%0aBenjamin F. Fairless resigned as board chairman and chief executive officer of the United States Steel Corporation; he was succeeded by Roger M. Blough%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 3, 1955%0aIt was announced that construction on the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad's new passenger terminal, at the foot of Grant Street, would begin within the next month.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 23, 1955%0aA capital improvement program for 1955, amounting to almost $6,000,000, was submitted to City Council by Mayor Lawrence. Plans included a start on rehabilitation of the city's water system, construction of new fire stations, a fire-police training center, street and sewer repairs, and grants to the Auditorium Authority and Carnegie Library.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 1, 1955%0aApproximately 10,000 Westinghouse Electric Corporation workers voted to stay away from their jobs in protest against disciplinary furloughs given 1100 East Pittsburgh workers.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 8, 1955%0aThe strike at East Pittsburgh and three other Westinghouse plants was settled.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 13, 1955%0aGeneral Matthew B. Ridgway was appointed chairman of the board of Mellon Institute. Dr. E. R. Weidlein remained as president and member of the board.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 20, 1955%0aThe Regional Industrial Development Corporation, a nonprofit organization, was created.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 22, 1955%0aT. M. Girdler resigned as chief executive officer of Republic Steel Corporation, but remained as board chairman. C. M. White, the firm's president, was named chief executive officer.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 1, 1955%0aA nationwide steel strike began, but ended 12 hours later when agreement was reached.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 8, 1955%0aAt a hearing conducted by the Public Utility Commission, it was decided to remove the Pennsylvania Railroad's last Downtown elevated, leaving Fort Duquesne Boulevard free to be developed into a sunlit, landscaped, riverside drive.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 14, 1955%0aCounty Commissioners adopted broad revisions in the smoke-control ordinance, giving industry an additional two to four years to comply.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 15, 1955%0aPittsburgh's fourth municipal parking garage, at Boulevard of the Allies and Smithfield Street, was opened.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 29, 1955%0aGreyhound Lines announced plans for a new bus terminal covering more than two and one-half acres bounded by 11th Street, 12th Street, Penn Avenue, and Liberty Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 8, 1955%0aMore than 2200 members of Local 601, CIO International Union of Electrical Workers, struck at Westinghouse Electric Corporation in protest against the company's time-study program.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 15, 1955%0aThe city's first heliport was established atop the Gateway Parking Garage, at Fourth Avenue and Stanwix Street, in anticipation of regular helicopter service between Downtown and the airports.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 24, 1955%0aThousands of persons gathered at Greater Pittsburgh Airport for the dedication of a spectacular fountain as a memorial to the county's dead of all wars.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 30, 1955%0aH. J. Heinz Company announced plans for immediate construction of one of the world's most advanced food research centers at a cost of $3,000,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 6, 1955%0aPlans for construction of a new $3,000,000 chemical plant on Neville Island were made by Pittsburgh Coke and Chemical Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 9, 1955%0aDr. James Purdy Kerr, 91, the oldest active surgeon in the country, died at St. Joseph's Hospital, which he had helped to found.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 12, 1955%0aAt the annual dinner of the Allegheny Conference on Community Development, Commissioner James W. Follin of the Urban Renewal Authority, Washington, assured Pittsburgh of $17,386,610 for slum clearance and redevelopment of the Lower Hill District.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 17, 1955%0aForty-four thousand members of the CIO International Union of Electrical Workers started another strike against the Westinghouse Electric Corporation.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 18, 1955%0aMellon Square Park -- the most spectacular in the city's expanding park system -- formally became a possession of the citizens of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 24, 1955%0aHarry W. Fowler, a member of the board of Allegheny County Commissioners since 1949 and long a leader in the county's highway planning and designing, died at 64.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 25, 1955%0aA contract signing set the stage for the four-year four-month job of moving families out of the 100 acres of Lower Hill District scheduled for redevelopment. The Housing Authority of Pittsburgh agreed to handle relocation of 1800 families.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 27, 1955%0aJones and Laughlin Steel Corporation announced it would enlarge its 1955-56 expansion program to an expenditure of $250,000,000 covering 1955-58.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 14, 1955%0aDr. Charles F. Lewis, director of the Buhl Foundation since it was organized in 1928, announced his retirement, effective June 30, 1956.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 15, 1955%0aThe National Steel Corporation planned to spend a minimum of $200,000,000 on additions to existing plants within the next three and one-half years.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 30, 1955%0aPennsylvania College for Women was renamed Chatham College and announced a $12,000,000 development program.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 14, 1955%0aDr. Charles B. Nutting, vice chancellor of the University of Pittsburgh, was named director of the Buhl Foundation.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 20, 1956%0aContracts totaling $10,333,062 for two major projects on the Penn-Lincoln Parkway -- the Downtown link and the Fort Pitt Bridge -- were awarded by the State Highways Department.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 8, 1956%0aThe University of Pittsburgh's Cathedral of Learning was officially dedicated to President Honorarius John G. Bowman, who served as Pitt's Chancellor from 1921 to 1946.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 19, 1956%0aDr. Edward R. Weidlein, long-time president of Mellon Institute announced his retirement.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 20, 1956%0aThe long and bitter Westinghouse strike came to an end after 156 days.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 1, 1956%0aTwenty-two persons were killed when a twin-engine TWA plane crashed just after taking off from Greater Pittsburgh Airport. This was the first disaster at the airport and the worst in the history of local commercial aviation.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 4, 1956%0aMayor Lawrence recommended a new and broader attack against neighborhood blight under a $4,740,250 capital improvement program. Included was more than $800,000 to represent the city's first cash commitments to the Lower Hill redevelopment and Crosstown Boulevard projects.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 18, 1956%0aIrwin D. Wolf, 61, who succeeded Edgar J. Kaufmann as president and general manager of Kaufmann Department Store, a civic and philanthropic leader, died at his Fifth Avenue home after a long illness.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 8, 1956%0aUnited States Steel Corporation formally opened its newly built Research Center, consisting of four buildings and covering 142 acres in Monroeville.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 9, 1956%0aThe Koppers Company revealed plans for a multimillion-dollar research center in the borough of Monroeville.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 10, 1956%0aRodef Shalom Congregation observed its 100th anniversary and dedicated its new Temple at Fifth and Morewood avenues.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 11, 1956%0aHilton Hotels Corporation announced that it would build a $15,000,000 hotel next to Point State Park.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 1, 1956%0aA nationwide steel strike began. Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service entered the dispute which idled 600,000 United Steelworkers.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 16, 1956%0aThe last canvas tent performance of Ringling Brothers and Barnum & Bailey Combined Shows was given at Heidelberg Raceways, marking the end of an era of entertainment.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 27, 1956%0aA master settlement, providing a three-year, no-strike agreement, ended the strike which shut down 85 per cent of the nation's steel productive capacity for 27 days.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 9, 1956%0aThe United Steelworkers and the Aluminum Company of America signed a three-year no-strike agreement ending a nine-day strike of 18,000 members of 12 of the company's 21 plants.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 13, 1956%0aRazing of the Gardens, historic landmark and scene of sports events for more than 50 years, was begun, to make room for an eight-story apartment house containing 127 luxury-type dwellings.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 16, 1956%0aA program to expend $81,304,000 for additions to the National Tube Division of United States Steel in McKeesport was announced.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 5, 1956%0aAccording to a Navy announcement, an atomic reactor for the world's first nuclear powered surface warship would be built by Westinghouse.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 3, 1956%0aDemocratic presidential candidate Adlai E. Stevenson spoke in the city and made a network television broadcast from KDKA-TV.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 3, 1956%0aThe last steam engine in the Pittsburgh area was sent to the scrap heap.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 8, 1956%0aEx-President Harry S. Truman campaigned in Pittsburgh for the Democratic ticket.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 9, 1956%0aPresident Dwight D. Eisenhower made a major campaign speech at Hunt Armory for the Republican ticket.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 17, 1956%0aAdmiral Benjamin Moreell, chairman of Jones and Laughlin Steel Corporation, received the John Fritz Medal -- one of the nation's highest awards for scientific and engineering achievement -- at the National Convention dinner of the American Society of Civil Engineers in the Penn-Sheraton Hotel.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 31, 1956%0aThe Pittsburgh Department of Public Health revealed that nine of every ten North Side houses examined by city housing inspectors were in violation of the new code.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 31, 1956%0aMore than 12,000 jammed into Hunt Armory to hear a major address by the Democratic presidential candidate, Adlai E. Stevenson.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 1, 1956%0aTheodore L. Hazlett, Jr., executive director of the Urban Redevelopment Authority, warned that a critical shortage of housing for relocation of families threatened to undermine Pittsburgh's ambitious program for eliminating blight.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 5, 1956%0aThe Commission on Human Relations announced the formation of a Citizens Committee for Integrated Housing, to be composed of about 150 persons from all segments of community life, and a subcommittee of builders and mortgage bankers, to work on plans for a pilot integrated housing project.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 6, 1956%0aPresident Eisenhower was re-elected for a second term. He won a smashing victory in Allegheny County, moving the area into the Republican column for the first time since 1928. Adlai E. Stevenson carried the city of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 8, 1956%0aFinal totals for the Allegheny County United Fund Drive, the county's first combined charity appeal, amounted to 107.8 per cent of the goal, a total of $9,564,222.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 20, 1956%0aMayor Lawrence recommended an all-time high city budget of $44,273,292, but at the same time called for a slight reduction in real estate taxes.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 30, 1956%0aH. K. Porter Company made it known that it would build a 17-story, $7,000,000 office building at the corner of Sixth Avenue and Grant Street.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 11, 1956%0aEquitable Life Assurance Society announced plans for a 15- to 22-story office building in the Gateway Center, costing between $9,000,000 and $12,000,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 23, 1957%0aWestern Pennsylvania's heavy construction industry and the Laborer's District Council ended a three-week strike by signing a two-year wage contract.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 4, 1957%0aPaul H. Martin, retiring head of the Pittsburgh Regional Planning Association, urged comprehensive planning on a regional basis for the Pittsburgh area.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 19, 1957%0aThe Board of Education voted to spend another $10,000,000, most of it within the next five years, to build new schools and modernize a number of others. Money was to be raised by selling general obligation bonds.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 1, 1957%0aA federal grant for construction of a new east-west runway at the Pittsburgh Airport was announced.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 8, 1957%0aCarnegie Institute of Technology embarked on a $26,000,000-plus plan of progress.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 9, 1957%0aSix industrial concerns were named as violators of the country's smoke-control ordinance.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 13, 1957%0aPublic Works Director James S. Devlin said that $2,850,000 would be spent in street resurfacing and rebuilding projects during 1957.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 14, 1957%0aThomas E. Kilgallen, former president of City Council, died at 64.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 17, 1957%0aGround was broken for construction of the $17,000,000 Fort Pitt Tunnels under Duquesne Heights, to provide the final link between the eastern and western sections of the Penn-Lincoln Parkway.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 26, 1957%0aThe State Office Building in Gateway Center was dedicated.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 11, 1957%0aDr. Edward H. Litchfield was inaugurated as the 12th chancellor of the University of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 21, 1957%0aThe Allegheny Conference urged state, county, and city governments to join in a long-range highway program to meet traffic requirements.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 4, 1957%0aThe last three contracts were awarded for construction of an east loading dock, the first major expansion of the terminal building at Greater Pittsburgh Airport.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 21, 1957%0aThe University of Pittsburgh announced plans for a new graduate program to train engineers in all phases of air pollution control in keeping with the city's pioneering advances in that field.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 26, 1957%0aPlans were made for the merger of Pittsburgh Xenia Theological Seminary (Presbyterian), North Highland Avenue, and the Western Theological Seminary (Presbyterian), Ridge Avenue, North Side.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 26, 1957%0aErnest T. Weir, 81, long a "rugged individualist" in the well-organized steel industry and former chief executive of the National Steel Corporation, died in Philadelphia.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 25, 1957%0aTelevision City, Incorporated, was granted authority by the Federal Communications Commission to operate a Pittsburgh television station on Channel 4.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 25, 1957%0aAvery C. Adams, president and chief operating officer of Jones and Laughlin Steel Corporation, was elected chief executive officer, effective October 1. Admiral Benjamin Moreell remained as board chairman and chairman of the executive committee.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 1, 1957%0aCarnegie Institute of Technology was purchasing eight acres of property fronting on Forbes Street near Morewood Avenue for faculty and student residences.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 14, 1957%0aThe National Steel Corporation elected George M. Humphrey, former Secretary of the Treasury, as its chairman of the board.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 28, 1957%0aDrilling began on the $17,000,000 Fort Pitt Tunnels.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 1, 1957%0aPittsburgh's Channel 4, WIIC, began broadcasting as the nation's newest and most powerful VHF television station.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 10, 1957%0aThe city was assured of a federal grant of nearly $11,000,000 with which to begin urban renewal in East Liberty and the North Side's Manchester District.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 20, 1957%0aGround was broken at Gateway Center by Conrad N. Hilton for the new Hilton hotel.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 14, 1957%0aA strike by operators of the Pittsburgh Railways Company began.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 18, 1957%0aA Pittsburgh to Erie extension of the Pennsylvania Turnpike became a definite prospect with the announcement that it had been added to the National Interstate Highway System.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 5, 1957%0aMayor Lawrence won a fourth term victory by a 59,500 vote majority over his Republican opponent, John Drew.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 2, 1957%0aA total municipal budget of more than $54,000,000 for 1958 was proposed by Mayor Lawrence.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 9, 1957%0aThe transit strike ended and within hours the trolley and bus lines were in operation.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 18, 1957%0aPittsburgh started receiving electricity generated by atomic power from Shippingport, Pennsylvania, site of the world's first full-scale atomic electric power plant.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 18, 1957%0aWestinghouse was awarded a $46,050,000 Navy contract for nuclear power plant components for the world's first atomic-powered aircraft carrier.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 17, 1958%0aPenn-Lincoln Parkway, in its 12th year of construction was directly linked to the Downtown Triangle with the opening of a new Grant Street outbound ramp.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 27, 1958%0aMayor Lawrence presented his 1958 capital improvements budget to City Council, calling for expenditure of $13,221,300.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 12, 1958%0aBoggs and Buhl, one of Pittsburgh's oldest department stores, announced it would go out of business after 89 years of operation.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 3, 1958%0aMayor Lawrence agreed to run for the Democratic nomination for governor in order to end a contest that threatened to split the Democratic party.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 5, 1958%0aSpear and Company, which had operated a department store in the city since 1893, was sold to the Hahn Furniture Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 18, 1958%0aMrs. John M. Phillips, for more than 40 years an outstanding figure in Pittsburgh life, and a militant fighter for the rights of others, died in Mercy Hospital at 76.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 31, 1958%0aMayor Lawrence and Governor George M. Leader set off a charge that created an opening in the upper arc of Fort Pitt Tunnel's north portal, above West Carson Street.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 8, 1958%0aAllegheny County's Common Pleas Court judges ordered a drastic reform in court procedure and urged the Legislature to create four new judgeships to reduce the ever-increasing backlog of civil cases in the court.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 9, 1958%0aCommon Pleas Court judges extended their battle to speed up justice to the year-and-one-half backlog in Criminal Court.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 28, 1958%0aThe United Presbyterian Church of the United States of America was formed by the merger of the Presbyterian Church USA and the United Presbyterian Church of North America in ceremonies at Fifth Avenue and Bigelow Boulevard. Dr. Theophilus Mills Taylor of Pittsburgh Xenia Theological Seminary was elected moderator.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 3, 1958%0aAllegheny County prepared to start on a public improvement program authorized in the May primary. Projects included a $9,575,000 Glenwood Bridge over the Monongahela, a new high-level bridge over the Allegheny and a $5,000,000 viaduct to span Turtle Creek in East Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 17, 1958%0aIt was revealed that the Mellon family foundations had paid $3,000,000 for 3650 acres in six strategic locations in Allegheny County. The land was to be sold to the county at cost for a regional park system for Pittsburgh's suburbs.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 11, 1958%0aThe United States Steel Corporation announced that production at its Edgar Thomson Works would be curtailed because of declining demand. About 1500 men were to be laid off.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 24, 1958%0aAlan M. Scaife, a leader in Pittsburgh's cultural life, died at 58.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 30, 1958%0aLeland Hazard, vice-president and general counsel of the Pittsburgh Plate-Glass Company and one of the sparkplugs for Pittsburgh's renaissance was named professor of industrial administration and law at Carnegie Institute of Technology.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 3, 1958%0aThe Urban Redevelopment Authority began final planning for the $15,000,000 Chateau Street-West renewal project in the Manchester District of the North Side.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 6, 1958%0aThe federal government assured Pittsburgh of aid for the proposed $15,000,000 redevelopment project for substandard areas at East Liberty.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 6, 1958%0aThe State Highway Department approved plans for a new Glenwood Bridge, thereby making it possible for the county to receive $10,000,000 in federal aid.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 29, 1958%0aJones and Laughlin Steel Corporation was to spend $35,000,000 on mill improvements at its Pittsburgh and Aliquippa plants, increasing planned projects for 1958-1959 to $93,000,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 5, 1958%0aBy switching WQEX, the new educational outlet, from channel 22 to channel 16, the Federal Communications Commission assured the operation of a second educational television station in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 9, 1958%0aChancellor Edward H. Litchfield of the University of Pittsburgh unveiled a huge long-range, multimillion-dollar campus development plan, which would require eviction of the Pittsburgh Pirates from Forbes Field.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 21, 1958%0aJudge A. Marshall Thompson, 86, oldest member of Allegheny County Common Pleas Court, died. A former dean of the University of Pittsburgh Law School, he was serving his third 10-year term on the court.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 22, 1958%0aMary Roberts Rinehart, 82, a native of Pittsburgh, died in New York City.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 22, 1958%0aA 22-day strike at Pittsburgh's five major hotels ended.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 27, 1958%0aPresident Dwight D. Eisenhower campaigned for the Republican ticket in an address at the Syria Mosque.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 28, 1958%0aCarnegie Institute of Technology received a gift of $2,800,000 from Mr. and Mrs. Roy A. Hunt for the construction of a campus library.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 4, 1958%0aMayor Lawrence was elected governor of Pennsylvania over Republican Arthur T. McGonigle.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 9, 1958%0aThe General Services Administration announced that Pittsburgh's new Federal Building would be constructed near the Greyhound Terminal, ending a three-year debate over location.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 9, 1958%0aDr. I. Hope Alexander, director of the Pittsburgh Health Department for 20 years before retirement in 1956, died at 79.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 20, 1958%0aThe Crosstown Boulevard moved nearer reality when the State Highway Department awarded two contracts for $3,349,690 to start its construction.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 27, 1958%0aThousands assembled in Point State Park, at the very spot where Fort Duquesne once stood, to hear Mayor David Lawrence and General Matthew B. Ridgway begin the city's bicentennial celebration. It was two hundred years ago that the French abandoned Fort Duquesne (on November 24, 1758) and General Forbes' army took possession of the area.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 28, 1958%0aSale of Forbes Field to University of Pittsburgh is approved; the Pirates will stay on for five years, until new Northside stadium is built. In reality, the Pirates stayed on not for five but for twelve years, until 1970 when the new stadium opened.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 1, 1958%0aRed Manning hired as coach of Duquesne University's basketball team.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 16, 1958%0aA. W. Mellon Educational and Charitable Trust gives $12 million to the University of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 17, 1958%0aJohn Dearden, Roman Catholic bishop of Pittsburgh, is appointed archbishop of Detroit.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 23, 1958%0aCity Solicitor Anne X. Alpern named attorney general of Pennsylvania.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 1959%0aThe 51-year-old Frank & Seder's department store will have a going-out-of-business sale.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 16, 1959%0aCity Council President Thomas Gallagher sworn in as mayor of Pittsburgh, replacing David Lawrence, who on January 20 will he inaugurated as governor.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 31, 1959%0aIn a trade that will later be credited with making the Pittsburgh Pirates pennant winners in 1960, the baseball team obtains Harvey Haddix, Don Hoak, and Smoky Burgess from the Cincinnati Reds.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 7, 1959%0aArt Rooney, president of the Steelers, is dissatisfied with Pitt Stadium and wants to return his club to Forbes Field.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 9, 1959%0aGovernor David Lawrence will ask the state legislature for a law banning racial discrimination in housing.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 16, 1959%0aThe Democratic slate of candidates for May primary includes Joseph M. Barr for mayor; John Kane and William McClelland for county commissioners.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 19, 1959%0aThirteen men are arrested in a raid on the headquarters of the alleged numbers-racket boss Tony Grosso.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 25, 1959%0aIndustrialist Paul Reinhold enters race for mayor on the Republican ticket.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 18, 1959%0aJohn J. Wright is installed as Roman Catholic bishop of Pittsburgh in St. Paul's Cathedral.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 27, 1959%0aDavid J. McDonald, president of the United Steelworkers asserts that big-steel management is "hell-bent" on fomenting a strike when contract expires July 1.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 10, 1959%0aA consensus is forming for legislation to provide for public ownership of mass transit.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 11, 1959%0aUnited Steelworkers refuse one-year extension of their contract.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 17, 1959%0aA mock air-raid is a failure; passersby laughingly refuse to take cover.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 21, 1959%0aThe Allegheny Conference on Community Development urges support for publicly-owned mass transit.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 1, 1959%0aJones and Laughlin announces a $234 million capital expenditure program.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 6, 1959%0aWalter A. Munford becomes president of United States Steel.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 13, 1959%0aA bill establishing public ownership of mass transit is reported out of committee in Harrisburg.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 19, 1959%0aIn the primary election, Joseph Barr and Paul Reinhold win nominations for mayor on the Democratic and Republican tickets respectively.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 21, 1959%0aPeoples First National Bank and Trust and Fidelity Trust approve the merger of their institutions.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 1, 1959%0aPittsburgh becomes second city in the United States to ban discrimination in residential renting or purchasing, due to a new "Fair Housing Practices Ordinance."%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 4, 1959%0aUp to $60 million in residential and commercial construction, designed for the Pittsburgh of tomorrow, is envisioned for the Lower Hill District in bids from eleven developers. The development did not materialize.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 4, 1959%0aAlcoma Golf Club suffers considerable fire damage.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 8, 1959%0aThe Public Utility Commission authorizes shift from trolleys to buses, on a temporary basis, as the tracks may not be removed.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 8, 1959%0aPossibility of a $722,000 federal loan for Allegheny County's new Northside sports stadium is announced.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 11, 1959%0aAllegheny County Boroughs Association votes to oppose the mass transit bill in its present form. The bill, bitterly attacked by spokesmen for the Independent Bus Operators and others, is sent back to House committee for further amendments.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 19, 1959%0aFort Pitt Bridge, vital link in Penn-Lincoln Parkway, is opened.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 23, 1959%0aAllegheny County's transit bill is passed by House; goes to state Senate for final action.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 24, 1959%0aH. I. Casteel, businessman, dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 1, 1959%0aFour members of Pittsburgh Pirates picked for All-Star Game: Smoky Burgess, Dick Groat, Elroy Face and Bill Mazeroski.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 7, 1959%0aPittsburgh hosts All-Star Game (National League wins 5-4; Vice President Richard M. Nixon throws out first ball).%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 14, 1959%0aPickets at the steel mills, as another steel strike begins.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 15, 1959%0aJohn J. Kane announces his withdrawal from race for re-election as county commissioner.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 21, 1959%0aSteel strike slows down construction of the Civic Arena.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 28, 1959%0aUnited Steelworkers union extends contracts with nation's major aluminum producers, averting walkout of 30,000 members.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 30, 1959%0aMichael L. Benedum, multimillionaire oil wildcatter dies two weeks after his 90th birthday.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 4, 1959%0a2,000 striking steelworkers in a rally at Memorial Hall voice all-out support to union leadership in their fight for wage increase and benefits.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 23, 1959%0aIn violent storms, three city buildings were damaged.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 25, 1959%0aSteelworkers President McDonald declares that the USW will stay on strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 2, 1959%0aTwo officials of the Russian embassy are in Pittsburgh to arrange details of Nikita Khrushchev's forthcoming tour.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 19, 1959%0aThe unfinished East Hills Shopping Center is offered to highest bidder at auction ("largest sheriff's sale ever"). The center is worth $8 million.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 20, 1959%0aReligious services mark a protest against Khrushchev's visit. Khrushchev arrives and speaks of eagerness for peace. Thousands of Pittsburghers are on hand to see him.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 25, 1959%0aSteelworkers Union breaks off talks in 73-day steel strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 29, 1959%0aDr. Jonas Salk gets a March of Dimes grant of $413,439 to continue his study at the University of Pittsburgh of viruses and cells.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 1, 1959%0aSam Grosso and ten of his racketeers are found guilty.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 9, 1959%0aPresident Eisenhower invokes the Taft-Hartley Act to break the deadlock between management and labor in the steel industry.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 20, 1959%0aThe Carnegie Institute of Technology gets $2.25 million grant from the Ford Foundation.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 23, 1959%0aThe new Port Authority (mass transportation) gets off to a shaky start.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 3, 1959%0aJoseph M. Barr, Democrat, elected mayor. Barr --124,500; Reinhold -- 71 ,202.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 8, 1959%0aAfter striking for 116 days, steelworkers return to the mills.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 13, 1959%0aA new site, closer to Allegheny River, is chosen for the stadium.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 23, 1959%0aRepresentatives of trolley operators and representatives of the Pittsburgh Railways negotiate.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 31, 1959%0aPittsburgh Railways rejects new union contract offer.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 2, 1959%0aJoseph M. Barr sworn in as 51st mayor of the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 4, 1959%0aMayor Barr invites trolley union and management to a meeting.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 8, 1959%0aAfter the Mayor's proposal is rejected by management and labor, trolley strike begins.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 13, 1959%0aVote of 914-11 ratifies a 26 cent-per-hour increase in wages, as trolley strike ends after six days.%0a%0a%0a%0a1960%0aJanuary 11, 1960%0aThe eight-year-old stalemate about trolley-to-bus conversion in West End routes threatens to jeopardize key "Renaissance" projects near Point State Park.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 21, 1960%0aThe Public Auditorium Authority announces that Deeter and Ritchey Architects of Pittsburgh, Michael Baker Jr. of Rochester, and Osborn Engineering of Cleveland are commissioned to design the Northside stadium.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 2, 1960%0aRacketeer Sam Grosso sentenced to 16-32 months in Western Penitentiary.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 14, 1960%0aTwelve-inch snowstorm closes airports and schools.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 21, 1960%0aKDKA performers, members of the American Federation of Television and Radio Artists, go on strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 1, 1960%0aA $500,000 fire destroys ten downtown businesses.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 11, 1960%0aAnnouncement is made of the departure in 1961 of Dr. Jonas Salk from the University of Pittsburgh. He will become the head of a research institute in San Diego, California.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 14, 1960%0aA $20 million new construction work in Pittsburgh district highway program will begin in the spring. Included is the linkage of the Penn-Lincoln Parkway with the turnpike.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 23, 1960%0a$170 million is set for improvement expenditures at the University of Pittsburgh within the next ten years.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 14, 1960%0aThree Pittsburgh bishops -- John Wright, Roman Catholic, Austin Pardue, Episcopal, and Nicholas T. Elko, Byzantine Catholic -- oppose ballot issue to allow betting on harness racing.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 18, 1960%0aA new chapter in Pittsburgh redevelopment begins with Simpson Brothers' plan to build private homes.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 22, 1960%0aThe afternoon Sun-Telegraph is purchased by the Post-Gazette.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 26, 1960%0aThe issue of harness racing, opposed by the bishops (see above) is defeated -- 219,509 people voted "No"; 167,195, "Yes.".%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 14, 1960%0aGeneral Matthew B. Ridgway, the chairman and chief executive officer of Mellon Institute, retires.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 25, 1960%0aCity Safety Director Louis Rosenberg orders halt to all bingo games, even those sponsored by churches.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 9, 1960%0aAFL and CIO merge.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 19, 1960%0aNorthside "Lower Belt" plan for $99 million interstate expressway wins formal support of State Highway Secretary Park H. Martin.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 31, 1960%0a17,000 baseball fans crowd Greater Pittsburgh Airport to welcome 1st-place Pirates home from Chicago.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 1, 1960%0aFort Pitt Tunnel is opened.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 25, 1960%0aPirates win National League pennant, even though losing 4-2 to Braves. (St. Louis Cardinals' loss on same day gives Pirates the victory.)%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 5, 1960%0aWorld Series begins. Pirates beat Yankees in first game, 6 - 4.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 10, 1960%0aSenator John F. Kennedy, the Democratic presidential candidate, speaks in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 13, 1960%0aWith the World Series even, three games each, the Pirates win the seventh game 10-9 with a home run by Bill Mazeroski in the ninth inning.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 24, 1960%0aRichard Nixon, the Republican presidential candidate, speaks in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 25, 1960%0aUniversity of Pittsburgh will buy five blocks in Oakland to build new dormitories.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 3, 1960%0aPresident Eisenhower and former President Harry Truman speak in Pittsburgh for their party's nominees.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 8, 1960%0aAllegheny County joins in Pennsylvania's support of John F. Kennedy, who is elected to the presidency.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 5, 1960%0aThe six-year battle for the "Lower-Belt" system in Northside is won.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 18, 1961%0aNorth Park ice skating rink opens.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 24, 1961%0aEast Liberty urban renewal project is approved.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 2, 1961%0aConversion from trolleys to buses is discussed again.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 5, 1961%0aJohn J. Kane, retired county commissioner, dies at the age of 70.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 20, 1961%0aThe Carnegie Institute of Technology receives grant by Ford Foundation to help raise the standards of the American theatre.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 6, 1961%0aYellow Cab drivers and mechanics go on strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 5, 1961%0aAlcoa joins with a Kansas City real estate developer to rebuild the 79-acre commercial area, part of Northside renewal.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 15, 1961%0aAfter 70 days, cab strike is settled.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 18, 1961%0aLiquor sales at hotel bars on Sunday become legal.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 16, 1961%0aJones and Laughlin plans a quarter of a billion dollar expansion program.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 30, 1961%0aThe Post-Gazette celebrates its 175th birthday.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 25, 1961%0aPort Authority rejects Pennsylvania Railroad's bid for public subsidies to keep its commuter trains running.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 17, 1961%0aCivic Arena opens for the public.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 1, 1961%0aPlans for a 55,000-seat, $22 million sports stadium go before the city and county officials.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 6, 1961%0aPlans for the thirteen-story IBM building in Gateway Center is approved.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 7, 1961%0aDemocrats sweep elections in city and county. Barr elected to his first full term as mayor.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 28, 1961%0aAllegheny County voters will have the final say on unified mass transit for the county.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 1962%0aBenjamin Fairless, former president of US Steel, dies at 71.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 20, 1962%0aCivic Arena reaches agreement over jurisdiction with unions. Agreement insures that the arena will be the summer home for the Civic Light Opera.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 11, 1962%0aUnited States Steel sets increase of $6 a ton as a "catch-up adjustment."%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 20, 1962%0aTroubles at the Civic Arena as air conditioning cooling system fails during the Western Pennsylvania Kennel show.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 14, 1962%0aAn $84 million rebuilding plan for the Golden Triangle is announced.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 12, 1962%0aPresident Kennedy assails Republicans in the city. 300,000 Pittsburghers welcome him.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 6, 1962%0aWilliam Scranton elected governor of Pennsylvania.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 19, 1962%0aAllegheny County Port Authority has acquisition agreements with 23 of 30 local bus companies.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 9, 1963%0aCity and county oppose merger of Pennsylvania Railroad and New York Central system.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 11, 1963%0aAn outer space research center will be built in Oakland by the University of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 21, 1963%0aMcClelland and McGrady announce re-election drive for county commissioners.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 23, 1963%0aChancellor Litchfield of University of Pittsburgh says Pirates baseball team may remain at Forbes Field, now owned by Pitt.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 29, 1963%0aSeven Northside buildings were destroyed by fire.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 31, 1963%0aWilliam H. McNaugher resigns from the Common Pleas bench, to be succeeded by Henry Ellenbogen.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 1, 1963%0aDavid L. Lawrence sworn in as chairman of President's Commission on Equal Opportunity in Housing.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 14, 1963%0aThe University of Pittsburgh leaves up to its individual schools whether they will boycott clubs that practice racial discrimination.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 21, 1963%0aChild Welfare Services of Allegheny County approved by the county commissioners.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 28, 1963%0aMayor Joseph Barr criticizes County Commissioner William McClelland in his continuing controversy over Northside stadium.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 2, 1963%0aStadium financing plan deemed dead.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 28, 1963%0aTwo more major fires add to previous wave of fires; arson again suspected.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 7, 1963%0aPittsburgh Pirates reject demand that they give $3,830,000 to Northside stadium project.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 28, 1963%0aUS Steel announces that cutbacks will result in 1,000 workers being laid off.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 8, 1963%0aPittsburgh building trade unions (except Brotherhood of Electrical Workers) agree to accept black men in their ranks.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 29, 1963%0aMilk strike starts; the main reason for it: job security.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 23, 1963%0aWestinghouse offers its four major unions a 14 cent raise and a five-year pension improvement.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 27, 1963%0aAfter a record drought, showers bring relief to the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 5, 1963%0aDemocratic victory in the Allegheny County election. Reelected are Commissioners McClelland and McGrady. The only Republican to be elected to major office is the new district attorney, Robert W. Duggan.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 11, 1963%0aMayor Barr announces that he is "looking into" the possibility of imposing an occupation tax on all working in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 11, 1963%0aAvery Adams, chairman of Jones and Laughlin's executive committee, dies at age 65.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 19, 1963%0aEarl Belle, "financial wizard," returns from Brazil to face trial.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 28, 1964%0aFormer Judge William H. McNaugher dies at age 72.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 2, 1964%0aDapper Dan banquet gives top award to Pitt football coach John Michelosen.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 28, 1964%0aPort Authority wins control of the Pittsburgh Railways Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 11, 1964%0aIn the worst flood of the past decade, water reaches 31.6 foot crests.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 17, 1964%0aFire destroys the Pittsburgher Motel.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 5, 1964%0aSabin anti-polio vaccine is administered to 800,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 29, 1964%0aPolice Detective Ralph Barnett sworn in as city's first black police inspector.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 1, 1964%0aPittsburgh's WIIC-TV, Channel 11, sold by Post-Gazette and Brennan family to the Cox Broadcasting Company for more than $20 million.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 20, 1964%0aGroundbreaking ceremonies at Chatham Center.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 27, 1964%0aPresident Lyndon B. Johnson arrives for rally in Civic Arena.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 29, 1964%0aRepublican presidential candidate Barry Goldwater speaks at the Civic Arena.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 3, 1964%0aIn the presidential election, the Johnson-Humphrey ticket wins, defeating the Republican ticket of Goldwater-Miller.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 6, 1964%0aI. W. Abel, United Steelworkers secretary-treasurer, will oppose USW President David J. McDonald in the forthcoming election of the Steelworkers.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 30, 1965%0aI. W. Abel wins the presidency of USW.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 6, 1965%0aJohn W. Galbreath plans a 60-story building at a cost of $50 million to house U. S. Steel offices.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 27, 1965%0aEdward Litchfield resigns as chancellor of the University of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 5, 1965%0aUnited Steelworkers accept new 35-month wage agreement.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 2, 1965%0aMayor Barr and his five City Council running mates are re-elected, with new councilman Peter Flaherty leading the ticket.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 11, 1966%0aSarah Mellon Scaife's bequest of $7.9 million to institutions is announced. The University of Pittsburgh will receive $5 million.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 20, 1966%0aBill Austin named new Pittsburgh Steelers head coach.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 26, 1966%0aDr. Stanton C. Crawford, acting chancellor of the University of Pittsburgh, dies. He is succeeded by David Kurtzman.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 9, 1966%0aPittsburgh is granted National Hockey League franchise.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 5, 1966%0aK. C. Morrissey named as first president of Allegheny County Community College. Monument Hill, Northside, will be the site of the college's first campus.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 19, 1966%0aPittsburgh board of public education takes first steps in a $50 million construction program.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 22, 1966%0aCourt ends roadblock to construction of new stadium brought about by taxpayers' suit.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 25, 1966%0aThe creation of UHF television Channel 53 is announced.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 10, 1966%0aHarry Keller is appointed fire chief, succeeding Steven Adley.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 30, 1966%0a"Commuter bandit" hits the Oakland Western Pennsylvania National Bank branch for $9,554. This is the "commuter's" 14th robbery.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 6, 1966%0aPittsburgh Symphony is given a $2.5 million grant by the Ford Foundation.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 11, 1966%0aStadium Authority declares that the projected stadium as designed is too costly. It asks for alternative designs.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 9, 1966%0aThe University of Pittsburgh appropriations bill -- $ 19,757,200 -- passes the state House and Senate and is sent to the governor for his signature. It will enable Pitt to reduce tuition for full-time Pennsylvania residents to $450 annually.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 25, 1966%0aThe new stadium plans are unveiled; it is similar to stadiums in St. Louis and Atlanta and it will cost $12 million less than the original design.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 14, 1966%0aA plan to merge Mellon Institute and Carnegie Institute of Technology is announced by Paul Mellon and Aiken Fisher, the respective board chairmen of the two institutions.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 19, 1966%0aClasses began for some 950 students at the Community College's Allegheny Campus and at Boyle Campus, then named East Campus on October 6.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 21, 1966%0aRoy Arthur Hunt, 85, retired president and chairman of Alcoa's executive committee and member of its board of directors since 1914, dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 14, 1966%0aRichard K. Mellon retires as chairman of the Board of Mellon National Bank and Trust Co.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 17, 1966%0aThe State Highway Department discloses that a bridge might be built over the Ohio River parallel to the West End Bridge.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 21, 1966%0aDavid L. Lawrence, who on November 4 suffered a heart attack while attending a political rally at the Syria Mosque, dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 1, 1966%0aMaury Wills traded to Pittsburgh Pirates.%0a%0a%0a%0a1967%0aA survey conducted in 1967 by the American Insurance Association gave the city's fire defenses the worst rating in Pittsburgh's history.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 13, 1967%0aWesley Posvar named chancellor of the University of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 27, 1967%0aMrs. Henry Hillman elected county Republican party chairman.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 15, 1967%0aUS Steel breaks ground for its new skyscraper headquarters, the world's second largest high-rise office building.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 19, 1967%0aH. J. Heinz II and the Howard Heinz Endowment acquire the Penn Theater for the Pittsburgh Symphony.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 9, 1967%0a"Secret" project entailing new wing for Carnegie Institute financed by Scaife family is reported.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 21, 1967%0aState Highway Commission says that the finishing of the "Bridge to Nowhere" will start shortly.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 17, 1967%0a"Commuter Bandit" hits the Bloomfield branch of the Pittsburgh National Bank for the second time.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 11, 1967%0aA master plan for a new $200 million terminal and cargo complex for Greater Pittsburgh Airport that would accommodate 12 million passengers by the year 2000 is unveiled. The first phase of the extension is planned to be completed by 1980.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 23, 1967%0aA Northside grocer, William Zeiler, arrested. FBI agents and city police believe him to be the "Commuter Bandit," who is responsible for sixteen robberies totaling more than $200,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 29, 1967%0aU.S. attorney's office announces that "Commuter Bandit" Zeiler will be charged with committing five bank robberies. His alleged accomplice, Richard P. Chiocca, surrendered to police.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 20, 1967%0aState Senator John Devlin, minority leader, dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 14, 1967%0aCounty Commissioner McClelland, rejected by the Democratic party, will run on the Constitutional party ballot with George Shankey as the other candidate.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 11, 1967%0aAn 11-mile, $160 million superhighway that will cut through Oakland to link major highways in the North and South Hills is under consideration.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 18, 1967%0aPlanners for a second Skybus to run between downtown and the South Hills have shelved survey work on an $800 million regional-rapid transit system for all of Allegheny County. The new system, different from its predecessor at South Park, will cost $60 million in state, federal, and local funds.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 7, 1967%0aLeonard C. Staisey and Thomas J. Foerster elected new Democratic majority commissioners. Robert Duggan, Republican, reelected as district attorney. Robert Friend, former Pirate pitcher, new county controller.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 14, 1967%0aCanon Robert Appleyard elected new bishop of Episcopal Diocese of Pittsburgh to succeed Bishop Austin Pardue who will retire in August of 1968. More than 70 clerics and 220 lay Episcopal deputies cast their votes in separate elections.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 29, 1967%0aA report for the Allegheny County Port Authority states that Skybus would be cheaper than a conventional "steel on steel" mass transit system, spreading over 60 miles, but would be more costly to run. Either could be in operation in seventeen years.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 12, 1968%0aPittsburgh Stadium Authority approves final plans and specifications for the 52,000-seat stadium on the Northside that could be built for $28,000,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 23, 1968%0a"Commuter Bandit" Zeiler is sentenced to 15 years.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 20, 1968%0aThe Penn Sheraton Hotel goes on the auction block after Local 327 Hotel and Restaurant workers refuse to accept the management's terms to end their 43-day old strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 29, 1968%0aPittsburgh Federation of Teachers (AFL-CIO) goes on strike despite injunction against union leadership.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 8, 1968%0aA plane crash into Lake Michigan takes the lives of Dr. Edward Litchfield, former chancellor of the University of Pittsburgh, his wife, his mother, and his two sons.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 10, 1968%0aPittsburgh Public Schools teachers' strike ends. Board of Education must accept elected bargaining agent as exclusive bargaining agent for teachers.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 14, 1968%0aCarnegie-Mellon President H. Guyford Stever discloses proposals for the University for the next three years. CMU will broaden its scope by creating a Graduate School of Urban and Public Affairs and a College of Humanities and Social Sciences.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 29, 1968%0aAfter sweeping the Indiana Pacers, the Pittsburgh Pipers soon faced the Minnesota Muskies in the Eastern Division Finals of the American Basketball Association. The Pipers went on to win the ABA Championship.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 5, 1968%0aGangs of black youth wreaked destruction in the Hill District and in other sections of the city following the April 4 assassination of Martin Luther King, Jr., the black civil rights leader.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 7, 1968%0aMayor Barr imposes a five-day curfew for Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 10, 1968%0aLing-Temco-Vought, Inc. of Texas offers $85 a share for up to five million shares of Pittsburgh's Jones and Laughlin Steel. The deal would give LTV 63 percent of J and L stock.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 22, 1968%0aHotel Penn Sheraton is sold to Pittsburgh investors. Local 327 and Bartenders Union Local 188 reaches agreement with new owners.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 6, 1968%0aDr. Sidney Marland resigns as superintendent of the city school system and is succeeded by Bernard J. McCormick.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 11, 1968%0aWilliam K. Whiteford, retired chairman and chief executive of Gulf Oil Corp., killed in traffic accident.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 12, 1968%0aState Supreme Court Justice Michael Angelo Musmanno 71, one of the prosecutors in the Nuremberg trials, dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 16, 1969%0aPittsburgh Federation of Teachers reaches agreement preventing teachers' strike in city schools.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 24, 1969%0aThe Democratic Policy Committee unanimously endorses Judge Harry Kramer to run for Democratic nomination for Mayor against City Councilman Peter Flaherty who announced his candidacy earlier.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 2, 1969%0aJohn Tabor accepts Republican nomination for mayor.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 28, 1969%0aPope Paul appoints Bishop John Wright of Pittsburgh a cardinal. He will be a member of the Curia at the Vatican.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 16, 1969%0aDr. Louis Kishkunas is named to succeed Dr. Bernard McCormick as school's superintendent.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 20, 1969%0aCouncilman Peter Flaherty wins Democratic nomination for mayor, in an upset victory against the Democratic machine.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 4, 1969%0aVincent M. Leonard, the auxiliary bishop to Wright becomes the new bishop of the Diocese.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 23, 1969%0aDemocratic majority commissioners approve PAT's Skybus-PATway (Early Action) mass transit plans.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 9, 1969%0aDanny Murtaugh named to manage Pittsburgh Pirates for the 1970 season.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 4, 1969%0aPeter Flaherty elected mayor over Republican John Tabor. Cyril Wecht, lawyer-doctor, elected county coroner.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 30, 1969%0aPenn Theater approved as new home for Pittsburgh Symphony.%0a%0a%0a%0a1970%0aJanuary 2, 1970%0aMayor-elect Flaherty replaces Police Supt. James Slusser with Inspector Stephen Joyce. The city council holds over confirmation of Mayor Flaherty's cabinet appointments: Joseph W. Cosetti for City Treasurer, Ralph Lynch, Jr. for City Solicitor and Bruce D. Campbell for Director of Lands and Buildings.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 7, 1970%0aFlaherty, the new mayor, freezes city jobs.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 18, 1970%0aThe Flaherty administration fires 71 rank-and-file pay-rollers begins its austerity plan.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 2, 1970%0aFlaherty threatens to close Pittsburgh Zoo.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 1, 1970%0aAttorney John H. Bingler named Director of Public Safety.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 4, 1970%0aAllison Krause of nearby Churchill was among four Kent State University students killed by National Guardsmen.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 3, 1970%0aRichard King Mellon, 70, the key figure in Pittsburgh's Renaissance, dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 23, 1970%0aBoard of Public Education votes to abandon "Great High School" plans.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 16, 1970%0aAfter many delays, the Three Rivers Stadium on Northside opens with Pirates losing to Cincinnati 3-2.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 27, 1970%0aWilliam R. Roesch named Jones and Laughlin Steel president and chief operating officer.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 11, 1970%0aRobert J. Paternoster named City Planning Director; Bruce D. Campbell the interim planning director becomes Executive Secretary to the mayor.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 13, 1970%0aJohn F. Counahan, president of City Council, dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 2, 1971%0aThe elimination of city truck drivers from driving plumbers to install water meters leads to a ten-day strike of the city's non-uniformed employees.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 17, 1971%0aPressmen at the Pittsburgh Press, on strike for twelve days, are back at work.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 4, 1971%0aThomas Kennelly succeeds Harry Keller as Fire Chief.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 10, 1971%0aMayor Flaherty replaces Stephen Joyce with Robert E. Colville, as superintendent of police.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 16, 1971%0aTwo police inspectors retire; demoted Joyce replaces one of them.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 17, 1971%0aFirst moves toward correcting a system by which police collected unearned witness fees is taken by Robert Peirce, the new county clerk of courts.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 25, 1971%0aPeirce announces the introduction of new witness-fee system.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 25, 1971%0aU.S. Representative Robert Corbett, 65, who had represented the 18th district in Congress for half his lifetime, dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 15, 1971%0aBecause of the pressmen's strike at the Post-Gazette, both Pittsburgh's daily newspapers cease to appear.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 10, 1971%0aHeinz Hall for the Performing Arts opens.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 20, 1971%0aJohn Bingler resigns as city's safety director, because he finds the position unnecessary. Henceforth, Mayor Flaherty will act as his own safety director.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 20, 1971%0aIn a July 28 letter the state Department of Commerce urged Flaherty to abandon his administration's support of the Mon Plaza site for the proposed convention center.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 21, 1971%0aAllegheny County files suit to get back more than $41,000 in witness fees allegedly collected by 34 Pittsburgh policemen.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 22, 1971%0aThe Flaherty administration serves notice in court that it will resist any attempt by PAT to renovate the old Wabash Tunnel, which is a vital link to the Early Action phase of the Skybus lines to the South Hills.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 6, 1971%0aPittsburgh Pirates win National League pennant.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 6, 1971%0aJames Fulton, Dormont Republican, dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 22, 1971%0aIn a defeat for the Mayor, city council votes unanimously in private caucus to throw full support behind PATs Early Action mass transit plan.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 26, 1971%0aRobert R. Dorsey, president of Gulf Oil, will become chief executive officer of the company.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 2, 1971%0aIn the election, Robert Duggan is re-elected district attorney. Republican William Hunt, a Skybus opponent, wins largest vote for county commissioner; Straisey and Foerster also re-elected. Robert Peirce, county clerk of courts by appointment, is also elected.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 8, 1971%0aMrs. Gladys McNairy, a black woman, elected president of the Pittsburgh Board of Public Education.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 23, 1971%0aDanny Murtaugh, who retired as Pirate manager, is replaced by Bill Virdon.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 1, 1971%0aMayor Flaherty announces that the second annual surplus will allow a reduction in taxes.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 23, 1971%0aCounty commissioners again refuse to hold a referendum on Skybus issue.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 27, 1971%0aPAT and the John F. Casey Company went to court to seek relief from malicious interference by the City of Pittsburgh to halt renovation of the Wabash Tunnel.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 28, 1971%0aMayor Flaherty lifts tunnel blockade.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 10, 1972%0aFlaherty, Commissioner William Hunt and the mayors of 14 communities file suit to enjoin PAT from spending any money on Early Action (Skybus) program until it complies with six specific legal requirements PAT allegedly ignored.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 12, 1972%0aFlaherty, saying that the city must have tighter control over the Highland Park Zoo and aquarium, cancels all existing agreements with the Pittsburgh Zoological Society for the operation and maintenance of the facility.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 22, 1972%0aPAT formally charges that anti-Skybus suit is a delaying tactic without legal foundation.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 10, 1972%0aPittsburgh Zoological Society sues Mayor Flaherty to enjoin him from taking control of Zoo.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 16, 1972%0aCommon Pleas Court order re-establishes Zoological Society as operator of Highland Park Zoo.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 16, 1972%0aHarold Joseph (Pie) Traynor, third baseman and former Pittsburgh Pirates' star, dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 6, 1972%0aArthur Van Buskirk, 76, leader in Pittsburgh's postwar renaissance, dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 13, 1972%0aEugene Coon elected Democratic party chairman of Allegheny County.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 8, 1972%0aSkybus trial comes to an end after 69 days.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 10, 1972%0aCarnegie-Mellon University chooses Dr. Richard Cyert as its sixth president.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 26, 1972%0aJ. F. Hillman, 83, prominent coal operator and philanthropist, dies. The survey of the American Insurance Association indicates that Pittsburgh's fire protection services are the best since World War II.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 24, 1972%0aFlood water crests at 35.82 feet, about eleven feet over flood level.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 17, 1972%0aCommonwealth Court rules that the mayor must sign over to PAT parcels of land at both ends of the Wabash Tunnel.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 24, 1972%0aJudge Anne X. Alpern orders the halt of further spending on the Early Action transit program.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 14, 1972%0aPittsburgh-born pianist Oscar Levant dies in Hollywood at the age of 65.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 3, 1972%0aGladys Schmitt, novelist and Carnegie-Mellon faculty member, dies at age 61.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 6, 1972%0aJudge Alpern issues a permanent injunction halting financing and construction of the proposed rapid transit system. Decree moves case closer to final adjudication in the state Supreme Court.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 29, 1972%0aEdgar B. Speer elected chairman of the board of US Steel.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 1, 1972%0aMayor Flaherty announces that the 13.5 million surplus in 1972 will allow the elimination of the wage tax imposed in 1954, adjustment in the amusement tax and tax on parking lot operators. He also announces a 60 million dollar Capital Improvement Program.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 31, 1972%0aRoberto Clemente, Pirates outfielder, died in the crash of a cargo plane on mercy mission to Managua, Nicaragua.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 19, 1973%0aThe State Supreme Court by 6-1 vote overturns Judge Alpern's injunction and puts Skybus back on the track.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 13, 1973%0aCity Councilman Richard Caliguiri announces candidacy for Democratic nomination for mayor.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 24, 1973%0aAfter Mayor Flaherty's announcement that he will seek reelection, the Democratic city committee endorses Richard Caliguiri.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 15, 1973%0aFlaherty wins both the Democratic and Republican nominations for re-election.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 24, 1973%0aFederal grand jury opens investigation into business activities of Allegheny County District Attorney Robert W. Duggan.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 6, 1973%0aBill Virdon fired as Pirates' manager; he will be succeeded by Danny Murtaugh.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 12, 1973%0aMayor Flaherty unveils his transit plan, which will cost $82 million. He would utilize the existing rail lines and would upgrade trolley lines to southern suburbs.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 29, 1973%0aPittsburgh "numbers boss" Tony Grosso testifies that former county racket squads chief Samuel G. Ferraro had received payments from him.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 2, 1973%0aFerraro found guilty by federal jury; sentenced to six years in prison and a $30,000 fine.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 6, 1973%0aMayor Flaherty, Sheriff Coon, Coroner Wecht are re-elected.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 6, 1973%0aIt is revealed that District Attorney Duggan had married Cordelia Scaife May, a Mellon heiress, on August 29.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 9, 1973%0aAccording to a Post-Gazette story, Duggan's marriage took place less than a week after his new wife was to appear before the Internal Revenue Service. Duggan calls the newspaper story "sick."%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 2, 1973%0aPatrick Fagan, ex-city councilman, dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 21, 1974%0aThe end of the Professional Theater at Pittsburgh Playhouse had been decided.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 30, 1974%0aState Crime Commission charges that District Attorney Robert W. Duggan concealed $68,000 in contributions and expenditures, squeezed more than $36,000 from employees, and falsified election records in his 1971 re-election campaign. Duggan replies that the mistakes happened because of "poor bookkeeping practices."%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 22, 1974%0aGrand jury demands Duggan's financial records.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 5, 1974%0aRobert W. Duggan found dead in his Westmoreland County home. Not long after his death, the federal grand jury charges against him becomes known. He supposedly evaded $93,000 in income taxes.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 12, 1974%0aThe Westmoreland County coroner closes investigation of Duggan's death without ruling.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 1, 1974%0aStrike at the Post-Gazette and the Pittsburgh Press. For six weeks the city is without newspapers.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 21, 1974%0aIn the primary, the home-rule charter for Allegheny County is defeated. Mayor Flaherty wins nomination for the senatorial race over ex-insurance commissioner Herbert S. Denenberg.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 13, 1974%0aGulf Building shaken by dynamite explosion, causing a million dollars damage. No one was hurt. A caller identifying himself as member of the terrorist Weather Underground said the bomb had been planted by his group. Another caller told Associated Press that the bombing was to protest Gulf's "racist policies" in the Portuguese colony of Angola.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 8, 1974%0aJames Higgins becomes board chairman of the Mellon National Corporation.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 30, 1974%0aDedication of the Point State Park Fountain. After three decades of planning and construction, Point Park is finally completed.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 5, 1974%0aA smaller and cheaper Penn Central site between Ft. Duquesne Blvd. and Penn Avenue is recommended by Mayor Flaherty for the city's convention center.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 9, 1974%0aPresident Ford visits Pittsburgh among cheers and boos -- booed for giving pardon to ex-President Nixon.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 27, 1974%0aCounty Commissioner Thomas Foerster pronounces Sky-bus "deader than a doornail."%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 15, 1974%0aUrban Mass Transportation Administration says Skybus is feasible. It says local governments must resolve conflict over the plan or lose federal funds.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 25, 1974%0aColorful inaugural reception is held at the magnificent Sarah Scaife gallery in Oakland.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 5, 1974%0aIn the senatorial race, Peter Flaherty is defeated by incumbent GOP Senator Richard S. Schweiker.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 12, 1974%0aMayor Flaherty announces balanced budget for 1975. There won't be a tax increase.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 10, 1974%0aCity of Pittsburgh and Allegheny County settle their differences about the construction of the convention center; they will go jointly to the state agencies to seek approval of plan.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 9, 1975%0aMayor Flaherty increases exhibit space of proposed convention center from 104,000 to 135,000 square feet.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 12, 1975%0aSteelers win Super Bowl in New Orleans, 16-6 over Minnesota Vikings. 10,000 people invade Downtown area after victory; 224 were arrested for drunkenness.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 19, 1975%0aWilliam Steinberg, because of ill health, resigns as Director of the Pittsburgh Symphony.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 31, 1975%0aJohn Robin calls for independent engineering study of proposed mass-transit systems (rail vs. rubber tire).%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 3, 1975%0aCounty Democratic chairman Eugene L. Coon calls for federal investigation of U.S. Atty. Richard L. Thornburgh, whom Coon says was motivated by partisan politics in his investigation of alleged official corruption.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 4, 1975%0aPAT directors authorize creation of 8-member task force to develop independent engineering study. Mayor Flaherty, county commissioners included. Decision comes after Federal Urban Mass Transportation administrator Herringer sets deadline for new attempt to resolve mass-transit controversy.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 4, 1975%0aThornburgh defends himself against Coon's charges of partisan politics.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 6, 1975%0aNAACP, state attorney general and minority groups sue City of Pittsburgh charging race and sex discrimination in police hiring and promotion. Similar charges had been filed with regard to hiring in the Bureau of Fire in 1972 and subsequent year, charges which consequently were dismissed.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 7, 1975%0aThe Mayor and county commissioners agree on convention center proposal. Proposal is for a 130,000 - 140,000 sq. foot site center on site bounded by Penn Avenue, Tenth Street and Ft. Duquesne Blvd.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 11, 1975%0aI. W. Abel, United Steelworkers president who will retire in June of 1977, says he will refuse election to George Meany's job as head of AFL-CIO.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 14, 1975%0aStaisey and Foerster announce they will run for renomination as county commissioners, as a team, in May 20 primary election.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 16, 1975%0aMayor Flaherty will cooperate with Allegheny Conference on Community Development in exploring possibilities for a 1984 World's Fair in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 28, 1975%0aRobert Coll replaces Robert Colville as Superintendent of Police. Colville resigned to run for the office of District Attorney.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 17, 1975%0aPerle Mesta, the fabulous hostess, dies. She will be buried in Homewood Cemetery.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 9, 1975%0aPort Authority Transit (PAT) begins construction route from Downtown through Mt. Washington Trolley Tunnel and up Sawmill Run Boulevard.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 21, 1975%0aUniversity of Pittsburgh receives $1 million from Japan Iron and Steel Federation as an endowment for Pitts Asian Studies Program. It would finance a rotating visiting professorship in Japanese studies and an Asian library.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 28, 1975%0aZoological Society will quit all operations by August 1, charging "senseless, irrational interference and harassment by City officials."%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 4, 1975%0aMayor Flaherty plans three new structures in the Zoo to replace 80 year old main Zoo building.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 14, 1975%0aAndre Previn appointed as the new Director of the Symphony.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 18, 1975%0aThe city administration hires Illinois firm of McFadzean and Everly to design new plan for Zoo.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 20, 1975%0aLeonard Staisey denied renomination as county commissioner by Democratic voters. Ticket will be Thomas J. Forester and James Flaherty, brother of the Pittsburgh mayor. Republicans nominate Robert N. Peirce and Dr. William Hunt, incumbent GOP commissioner.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 21, 1975%0aJames Flaherty, the Mayor's brother, and Thomas J. Foerster win in primary election for County Commissioners.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 25, 1975%0aUniversity of Pittsburgh School of Medicine will graduate Elaine Morris, the first black woman.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 3, 1975%0aJones and Laughlin will lay off 1200, bringing total to 2600 out of work at its Pittsburgh Works.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 4, 1975%0aMayor Flaherty and the State agree on a six-lane East Street Valley Expressway.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 9, 1975%0aCity policemen sent home for having long hair. They do eventually get it cut before returning to duty.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 16, 1975%0aDeLeuw, Cather & Company will study Skybus concept. The firm of engineers chosen by Transit Task Force will receive for the study $446,745.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 20, 1975%0aA great fire destroys part of Kennywood Amusement Park, causing $400,000 damage. Roadrunner, Ghost Ship and the 75 year old dance hall burn down.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 25, 1975%0aDavid M. Roderick is elected President of United States Steel Corporation. He will replace W. A. Walker on August 1st.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 27, 1975%0aAs Teamsters Local 211 calls a strike, the City of Pittsburgh is without newspapers till July 28.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 3, 1975%0aThe top floors of the old Duquesne University Administration building are destroyed by fire, apparently caused by lightning.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 4, 1975%0aPittsburgh celebrates the country's 199th birthday with fireworks and firecrackers.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 27, 1975%0aThe month-long strike of teamsters against the Pittsburgh Press and Post-Gazette comes to an end.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 28, 1975%0aThe conviction of former State Senator Frank Mazzei on federal extortion charges is upheld by the Third Circuit Court of Appeal.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 7, 1975%0a"Medic One" superambulance begins its operation.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 21, 1975%0aJones and Laughlin Steel Corporation signs a $200 million pollution control agreement with the Environmental Protection Agency assuring J & L's continued operation and jobs for its 6,000 workers.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 30, 1975%0aThe wildcat strike by West Virginia and Western Pennsylvania coal miners spreads, in spite of union and court demands.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 8, 1975%0aPittsburgh School Board announces a $45 million school desegregation plan.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 25, 1975%0aGovernor Milton Shapp joins the race for the 1976 Democratic Presidential nomination.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 29, 1975%0aPittsburgh Symphony musicians go on strike for the first time in the orchestra's 49-year history.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 8, 1975%0aThe School Board announces a 113 million dollar budget.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 30, 1975%0aRadio Station KDKA and the Pittsburgh Pirates fire Bob Prince and Nellie King, their longtime baseball announcers.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 5, 1975%0aControl of the Board of County Commissioners is retained by the Democrats when Thomas Foerster and Jim Flaherty defeat their Republican opponents Robert Peirce and William Hunt.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 13, 1975%0aThe 46-day strike of the Symphony musicians ends.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 1, 1975%0aCity Public School teachers vote overwhelmingly for a strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 10, 1975%0aH. John Heinz III announces his candidacy for the U.S. Senate.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 15, 1975%0aMilo Hamilton is chosen as Pirate announcer, replacing Bob Prince.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 17, 1975%0aAt Three Rivers Stadium, the Steelers defeat the Baltimore Colts 28-10 in the Super Bowl play-off before a crowd of 50,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 30, 1975%0aGulf Oil's own fact-finding committee confirms that the corporation's executives had a multimillion dollar political "slush fund."%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 8, 1976%0aA 7-inch snowfall snarls traffic in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 12, 1976%0aThe striking teachers are ordered by the court to return to work.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 16, 1976%0aThe Steelers beat the Dallas Cowboys 21 to 17, retaining the title as World Champions. Three days later the city celebrates the victory in bitter cold weather with a downtown parade.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 26, 1976%0aSchool strike ends; teachers ratify a compromise contract.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 27, 1976%0aJames R. Maloney becomes executive director of the Pittsburgh Port Authority (PAT).%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 1, 1976%0aA 10 cent fare increase goes into effect on PAT buses and trolleys.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 12, 1976%0aGovernor Shapp withdraws as a Democratic Presidential candidate.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 19, 1976%0aThe two young daughters of banker Seward S. Mellon are abducted. Their abduction is a part of the battle between the banker and his wife.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 24, 1976%0aCity Civil Service Committee asks for the hiring of equal numbers of whites and minorities in the fire department.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 13, 1976%0aThe Pirates rout the St. Louis Cardinals 14-0 in the season opener with 40,937 fans in attendance at the Three Rivers Stadium.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 27, 1976%0aCity voters, by a 3 to 2 margin, retain an elected school board.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 12, 1976%0aDemonstrators stage a sit-in at Rockwell International headquarters, protesting the corporation's involvement with the B-I bomber.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 15, 1976%0aHelped by a $5 million grant from the Allegheny Foundation, City authorities will rehabilitate the Pittsburgh and Lake Erie R.R. Station.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 25, 1976%0aU.S. Steel Corporation will reduce the level of air pollution at its Clairton coke works.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 4, 1976%0aA giant Bicentennial Fourth of July celebration with fireworks from atop the US Steel Building.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 9, 1976%0aJones and Laughlin will install new electric blast furnaces which will reduce pollution and increase productive capacity; it will also cost 700 jobs.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 13, 1976%0aIn a wildcat strike pickets close down the East Pittsburgh plant of Westinghouse Electric.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 18, 1976%0aTwo more unions representing 28,000 workers join a nationwide strike against Westinghouse.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 2, 1976%0aThirteen-year-old Terry Ford is killed in his Sewickley home when a bomb, intended for his brother, blows up in his face.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 5, 1976%0aMost of the mines in the district are closed by a wildcat strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 27, 1976%0aA federal grand jury indicts 38 district magistrates charging them with conspiracy and racketeering.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 3, 1976%0aTwo of the three Cleveland gunmen convicted of murdering UMW leader Jock Yablonski, his wife and daughter are sentenced to life imprisonment.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 15, 1976%0aGovernor Shapp signs an agreement with the Volkswagen Corporation of Germany ensuring the establishment of the firm's American assembly plant at New Stanton.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 30, 1976%0aMembers of the State's General Assembly receive a 20%25 pay raise, while the pay of the city's firemen raise, while the pay of the city's firemen is boosted by $1,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 1, 1976%0aDuquesne Light Co. ask the Public Utility Commission for a rate increase which would raise the average residential electric bill by 31.6%25. Oct. 8, Mayor Flaherty orders all rookie policemen to walk the beat instead of riding in patrol cars.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 12, 1976%0aThe county's "flu clinics" close and an investigation is launched into the cases of three residents whose illnesses were related to their "swine flu" inoculations.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 28, 1976%0aAssistant District Attorney Jo Ann D'Ariggo is dismissed from the courtroom by Judge Nicholas Papadakos who refused to hear her because she was dressed in a pant-suit.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 2, 1976%0aIn the presidential election of 1976 Democrat Jimmy Carter narrowly defeats Gerald Ford. H. John Heinz III  is successful in his Senate bid.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 17, 1976%0aThe State Superior Court upholds the legality of the Sunday "Blue" laws which prohibit most retail stores from doing business on Sunday.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 1, 1976%0aAllegheny County's mass transit system grinds to a halt as Port Authority Transit workers shut down all public transportation.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 2, 1976%0aA snowstorm snarls traffic.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 30, 1976%0aA $600 million "cleanup" pact is signed by U.S. Steel and county and state officials. It provides for an extensive anti-pollution rehabilitation of the Clairton Coke Works.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 1977%0aPitt Panthers beat Georgia 27-3 in the Sugar Bowl to tighten their grip on the 1977 National College Football Championship.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 17, 1977%0aRecord low temperatures of -17 F and gas shortages force the closing of the public school system.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 20, 1977%0aA blast at Langley Hall on the University of Pittsburgh campus caused by a gas leak kills three and injures 22.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 23, 1977%0aAs ice-packed rivers rise to danger levels the river towns brace for floods.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 1, 1977%0aA gaping crack threatening its collapse was found in the $50 million bridge on Interstate 1-79, which was completed in 1976 as part of the Bicentennial celebration.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 2, 1977%0aRichard Karp, 94, musical director of the Pittsburgh Opera for 35 years dies of cancer in Montefiore Hospital.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 9, 1977%0aIn the election for president of the United Steelworkers of America, AFL-CIO Lloyd McBride, the organization candidate, turns back Edward Sadlowski, the candidate of the rank and file reform movement.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 18, 1977%0aFour city policemen who moonlighted as "security guards" at a North Side "pornography warehouse" are suspended.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 21, 1977%0aPresident Carter names Pittsburgh Mayor Pete Flaherty as Deputy U.S. Attorney General.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 25, 1977%0aGeorge E. Lee, whose massage parlor operations are under investigation, shot dead in a parking lot on Seventh Street.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 8, 1977%0aCity Democrats choose County Commissioner Thomas J. Foerster for Mayor.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 1, 1977%0aAn Oakland cobbler arrested for bookmaking invented an ingenious method for taking bets. He wrote them on the soles of shoes which he repaired.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 9, 1977%0aA tentative three-year contract which includes some lifetime income security is approved by the Steelworkers Union.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 11, 1977%0aRichard S. Caliguiri is sworn in as Mayor in City Hall, replacing Pete Flaherty who resigned.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 25, 1977%0aEleanor Cutri Smeal, a housewife from Mt. Lebanon, is elected president of the National Organization of Women.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 10, 1977%0aStriking Teamsters block installation of voting machines for the upcoming primary elections.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 17, 1977%0aThomas Foerster wins the Democratic Mayoral primary and prepares to campaign against Joseph Cosetti, the Republican nominee and Richard Caliguiri who runs on the independent ticket.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 20, 1977%0aThe nude body of 18-year-old Brenda Lee Ritter is found on a bill, the fourth young woman to be slain in Washington County during the past six months.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 21, 1977%0aThirty-nine suspected heroin pushers are arrested in a drug bust.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 25, 1977%0aFlooding and explosions kill 45 people in Johnstown.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 27, 1977%0aThe Board of Education rejects a plan to reinstate corporal punishment in the city's schools, a measure backed by the Teachers' Union.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 1, 1977%0aThe strike of 14,000 steelworkers is the first major walkout in the basic steel industry during the past eighteen years.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 7, 1977%0aSeventeen prisoners escape from the Allegheny County jail.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 19, 1977%0aThousands of state employees, including guards at several prisons and aides in hospitals, join a "sick out," protesting the state's failure to pay their salaries because of the budget crisis in Harrisburg.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 20, 1977%0aThe state budget is passed and paychecks go out to state employees.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 26, 1977%0aThe PAT board, by an 11-1 vote, approves application for $93 million in federal funds to construct a $110 million busway from downtown to the eastern suburbs.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 8, 1977%0aThe report by Sheriff Eugene 'Gene' Coon about the deterioration of the County jail stirs the prison board into approving sweeping reforms.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 19, 1977%0aJones and Laughlin Corporation lays off some 500 workers.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 29, 1977%0aWest View Park, an amusement attraction for over four decades, will close its doors.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 6, 1977%0aOver the next six months U.S. Steel intends to lay off 4,500 of its white collar employees.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 8, 1977%0aIn the mayoral election Richard Caliguiri defeats Thomas Foerster. Democrats sweep the contested City Council seats.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 14, 1977%0aMayor Caliguiri announces plans for a no-tax-hike budget and for the beginning of "Renaissance II," to revitalize the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 16, 1977%0aMassage parlor operator Anthony Robert Pugh is found shot to death at his suburban apartment. Dec. 27 Webster Hall Hotel, a landmark in Oakland, will be converted into luxury apartments.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 20, 1978%0aAnother big snowfall made January the snowiest month since the "Big Snow" of 1950.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 22, 1978%0aFormer Mayor Pete Flaherty announces his Democratic candidacy for Governor.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 24, 1978%0aA blizzard strikes the area, knocking out power and disrupting telephone service. Rivers crest two feet below flood level at the Point.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 29, 1978%0aUMW President Arnold Miller declares that the miners' strike might go on indefinitely.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 6, 1978%0aUMW strikers stage a large rally downtown; they demonstrate before the U.S. Steel and Duquesne Light buildings.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 27, 1978%0aThirty-five-year-old Phyllis Wyberg, from the North Side, becomes the third million dollar winner in the Pennsylvania lottery.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 1, 1978%0aBus driver Rosie Lee and her passengers are routed from their No. 87 Ardmore bus by a rat.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 2, 1978%0aA large group of truck drivers stage a slowdown to protest the huge potholes on 1-70 between the Turnpike and the Pennsylvania border.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 6, 1978%0aUMW rank and file rejects a proposed contract; President Carter invokes the Taft-Hartley Act; miners must return to work.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 7, 1978%0aThe miners vow to defy the Taft-Hartley injunction.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 14, 1978%0aJennifer Lee Wesner, a former topless model, draws the top spot in the Democratic primary for governor.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 17, 1978%0aSchool officials confiscate knives, guns, baseball bats and an ax after a racial brawl at Brashear High School.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 25, 1978%0aArea miners prepare to return to work under a new contract which they first opposed but which had been accepted by the majority of the UMW's members.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 28, 1978%0aSchenley High School's Spartans win the Pennsylvania Triple A Basketball Championship, defeating Lebanon High 5 1-50 at Hershey, Pa.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 30, 1978%0aThe state government authorizes over $55 million in federal, state and local funds to pay for the first phase of the proposed East Bus-way in Allegheny County.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 4, 1978%0aThe City Council overrides Mayor Caliguiri's veto of an antipornography referendum designed to provide a mandate for "cleaning up" Liberty Avenue and other pornography retail areas.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 6, 1978%0aThe FBI and the District Attorney's Office begin their investigation of Community Action Pittsburgh, the Agency which is dispensing federal anti-poverty funds.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 9, 1978%0aThe majority in the county commission votes against putting the anti -pornography referendum on the May 16 primary ballot.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 23, 1978%0aPennDot seeks a three-year guarantee from all asphalt contractors.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 16, 1978%0aWilliam Steinberg, 78, music director emeritus of the Pittsburgh Symphony who was conductor of the Symphony for more than a quarter century, dies in New York.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 17, 1978%0aPeter Flaherty and Richard Thornburgh win the respective Democratic and Republican gubernatorial nominations.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 23, 1978%0aAfter being pinned by his legs for two hours atop the Brady Street Bridge, a screaming construction worker is freed by a physician who climbs to the top of the bridge and amputates his leg.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 6, 1978%0aBail Bondsman David Wander and Edward Reddington are convicted on a sex-blackmail scheme against County Commissioner Robert N. Peirce.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 19, 1978%0aMayor Caliguiri, speaking before the U.S. Conference of Mayors, throws his support behind a plan which would make it easier for cities to annex their suburbs.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 27, 1978%0aState legislature approves the death penalty.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 5, 1978%0aNathaniel Rosen, the Pittsburgh Symphony's first cellist, wins the Tschaikovsky Gold Medal in Moscow.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 5, 1978%0aEdward Suratt, wanted for two murders, is arrested in Florida.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 6, 1978%0aA major urban renewal project in Market Square will be spearheaded by the 40-story Pittsburgh Plate Glass Building.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 6, 1978%0aThe Greater Pittsburgh Airport reports a $2.3 million profit.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 8, 1978%0aParkway East is "papered" with money for the second consecutive day, with an accident littering a mile-long stretch with canceled Series E government savings bonds. The day before, a collision with a messenger's car causes scores of welfare checks to be strewn on the road.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 11, 1978%0aThe State Supreme Court unanimously upholds a Commonwealth Court order requiring the city to submit a desegregation plan to the Pennsylvania Human Relations Commission before fall, 1979.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 15, 1978%0aParents and community groups charge the city School Board with promoting a racially segregated system.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 7, 1978%0aThomas Ware, a city detective with fifteen years service, is charged with the murder of a city fireman in the Hill District.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 21, 1978%0aEdward Suratt of Aliquippa, already charged with three murders and a suspect in 17 others, is convicted of the rape of a woman and her daughter in Vilano Beach, Florida.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 25, 1978%0aNorthview Heights public housing project wins a $10 million federal grant to rehabilitate its deteriorating North Side complex.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 23, 1978%0aThe federal government charges Westinghouse Corporation with making false statements to cover up overseas bribery.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 2, 1978%0aPittsburgh is allocated $23.9 million and Allegheny County $27.19 million to operate the Comprehensive Employment and Training Act (CETA) programs in the coming fiscal year.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 8, 1978%0aRichard Thornburgh upsets Peter Flaherty by 200,000 votes to become Governor of Pennsylvania. In 25 Congressional races, the Democrats lose three seats and gain one. Allegheny County voters overwhelmingly reject a home rule charter.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 28, 1978%0aSixteen-year-old Dorene Crawford is shot to death in the stairway of her Terrace Village apartment. City homicide detectives search for her boyfriend, twenty-six-year-old Fred Mahaffey.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 13, 1978%0aAlcoa Corporation intends to spend $5.1 million on an "extensive renovation" of the William Penn Hotel.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 23, 1978%0a"Lonesome George," the Pittsburgh Zoo's only gorilla, dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 31, 1978%0aThe Steelers defeat the Denver Broncos 33-10 before a crowd of 48,921 and advance to the final game of the Championship, Super Bowl XIII.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 4, 1979%0aThe sexually assaulted and strangled body of Monica Renee Jones, an 18-year-old Pitt coed, is found in the basement of her dormitory.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 16, 1979%0aGovernor Richard Thornburgh is sworn in in Harrisburg, pledging "integrity, frugality, simplicity and humanity."%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 19, 1979%0aMembers of the Fraternal Association of Steel Handlers (FASH) vote to end their violence-torn strike as a result of a court-ordered injunction.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 22, 1979%0aThe Steelers defeat the Dallas Cowboys 35-31 in Miami to return their World Championship title for a third consecutive year.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 26, 1979%0aDuquesne Light, having just implemented a billing increase, announces another which will increase the average monthly electric bill by $5.70.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 2, 1979%0aAn estimated 7,000 fans join in a Steelers' victory celebration at Market Square.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 11, 1979%0aController John P. Lynch begins an investigation of the county morgue in connection with private bank accounts used for deposit of cut-of-county autopsy receipts.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 5, 1979%0aController John P. Lynch indicates that Coroner Cyril Wecht and members of his staff might be liable under theft of service statutes for the private autopsy work which they performed at the county morgue.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 7, 1979%0aThe $10.8 billion state budget will he financed in part by an increase in the gasoline tax.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 14, 1979%0aAccording to the county's law department, Coroner Wecht's private autopsy work was illegal.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 28, 1979%0aA cooling failure in the Three-Mile Island nuclear plant results in its shutdown as radiation begins leaking in the Harrisburg area. Pittsburghers worry about the implications for nuclear facilities in the city and its vicinity%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 4, 1979%0a3,500 Volkswagen workers at New Stanton are laid off.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 15, 1979%0aAn investigating grand jury will crack down on the massage parlor industry.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 18, 1979%0aPolice and paramedics work for more than 373 hours to free a driver from his wrecked truck which hung precariously from a Fort Pitt Bridge ramp.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 30, 1979%0aSteel trucks begin to roll as steel haulers vote to end their three-week strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 1, 1979%0aThe strike at the Pittsburgh Brewing Company stops the production of Iron City Beer.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 7, 1979%0aThe federal government formally commits $265 million to PAT for the proposed light-rail transit system that will connect the South Hills with Downtown.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 10, 1979%0aThe unexplained failure of a 23,000-volt line ignites sewer gas, touching off a series of electrical explosions, setting overhead wires on fire and knocking out power in 25,000 East End homes.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 4, 1979%0aThe U.S. Attorney's office loses its second major Medicare fraud case when a federal judge acquits Dr. Leonard Merkow of Squirrel Hill.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 9, 1979%0aAn Erie jury finds former Allegheny County Manpower director Robert L. Hawkins guilty of payroll frauds totaling $80,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 21, 1979%0aIndependent truckers launch a nationwide shutdown; gunfire erupts on the highways.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 25, 1979%0aShots are fired at produce trucks on a highway near the city, as the striking truckers attempt to shut down the shipment of food.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 28, 1979%0aThe strike by service station owners, resulting in long lines at the few open stations, lulls. A new 'odd-even' gas rationing plan eases the run on gasoline.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 3, 1979%0aHope fades for an early resolution of the state budget deadlock which has already ended payments to thousands of state workers and families on welfare.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 8, 1979%0aTheodore L. Hazlett, President of the A. W. Mellon Educational and Charitable Trust, and the legal architect of the city's Renaissance, dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 14, 1979%0aOnly 11%25 of the area's service stations are open. Pittsburgh motorists are hit hard by the shutdown of the independent station operators.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 16, 1979%0aAn eleventh-hour attempt by federal mediators fails to avert a strike by 38,000 Westinghouse workers.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 25, 1979%0aThe City Council gives preliminary approval to a P.P.G. Industries plan to build its $100 million headquarters in Market Square, but area merchants are fighting the plan.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 2, 1979%0aAn 11-year-old girl and her teenage panderer are arrested on a downtown street on prostitution charges.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 3, 1979%0aA woman jogger told police she was attacked under Panther Hollow Bridge near the area where Carol Jursik, a Pittsburgh University graduate student, disappeared.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 7, 1979%0aThe body of Carol Jursik is found. Her murderer is never apprehended.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 15, 1979%0aAllegheny County Health Agency might lose $197,000 in federal air pollution aid as a result of bureaucratic bungling.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 4, 1979%0aMt. Lebanon schools are the latest to be closed in a rash of teacher's strikes affecting more than 30,000 pupils in ten Western Pennsylvania school districts.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 11, 1979%0aLawyers, businessmen and office workers are routed from the Law and Finance Building, as flames race through its 14th floor.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 17, 1979%0aThe illegal numbers racket is doing well in spite of the state lottery's success.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 6, 1979%0aThe Pirates win the National League pennant by defeating the Cincinnati Reds 7-1 at Three Rivers Stadium.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 9, 1979%0aOver strong objections by two city school directors, the school board held its fifth closed meeting of the year on desegregation.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 11, 1979%0aThe Pittsburgh Pirates defeat the Baltimore Orioles 3-2 in the second game of the World Series.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 12, 1979%0aA tentative agreement is reached in the six-weeks-old Mt. Lebanon school teachers' strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 13, 1979%0aEdgar B. Speer, President of U.S. Steel Corporation, dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 16, 1979%0aThe Pirates tie up the World Series 3-3 by beating the Orioles 4-0.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 17, 1979%0aThe Pirates defeat the Baltimore Orioles 4-1 to win the 1979 World Series.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 19, 1979%0a25,000 fans welcome the World Champion Pirates at Market Square.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 22, 1979%0aCoroner Cyril Wecht files a seven million dollar suit against Controller John P. Lynch because of Lynch's alleged defamatory remarks on a radio show.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 25, 1979%0aThe crash of a PAT bus on Center Avenue injures forty people. A massive probe into Pittsburgh organized crime is launched by state and local authorities.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 2, 1979%0aThe Hillman Company was to take back a chemically contaminated Ohio River Park site on Neville Island which the firm had donated to the county in 1976.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 7, 1979%0aDemocrats are assured control of the County Board of Commissioners as Thomas J. Foerster and Cyril Wecht are elected to majority seats on the Board. Most of the other county offices in the election were also won by Democrats.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 13, 1979%0aMayor Caliguiri asks the City Council for a 1%25 wage tax hike.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 26, 1979%0aThe State Human Relations Commission allows the Pittsburgh School Board 18 days to submit a plan for desegregating.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 27, 1979%0aU.S. Steel announces massive cuts in production; 13,000 jobs will be lost, 1,800 of them in Western Pennsylvania.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 1, 1979%0aState Labor and Industry Secretary Charles J. Lieberth declares that Pennsylvania would have to borrow $350 million from the federal government to cope with the projected layoffs by U.S. Steel.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 5, 1979%0aMoments after the newly-elected Pittsburgh School Board takes office, its members agree to begin school desegregation.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 10, 1979%0aThe Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Corporation presents its employees with an ultimatum: accept cuts in their "excessive" incentive pay or see the firm's Allenport plant closed.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 14, 1979%0aController Lynch asks for the dismissal of Coroner Wecht's lawsuit against him.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 28, 1979%0aWorkers at U.S. Steel's Ambridge Works vote to accept a paycut in order to keep the plant from closing.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 31, 1979%0aThe City Council overrides Mayor Caliguiri's veto of its 28-mill land tax increase.%0a%0a%0a%0a1980%0aJanuary 7, 1980%0aThe Steelers dump the Houston Oilers 27-13 to get their fourth shot at the Super Bowl.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 9, 1980%0aThe newly installed County Commissioner Cyril Wecht announces his resignation as County Coroner.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 14, 1980%0aA large crowd sends the Steelers off to their fourth consecutive Super Bowl game in Miami.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 20, 1980%0aThe "Super Steelers" rally three times in a close contest to defeat the Los Angeles Rams 31-19 and win Super Bowl XIV, the fourth Super Bowl victory in six years.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 23, 1980%0aUniversity of Pittsburgh students make hundreds of dollars worth of free long distance calls when the pay phones in a dormitory lobby malfunction.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 30, 1980%0aU.S. Steel reported a loss of $293 million, the largest quarterly decline in the firm's history.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 1, 1980%0aA jury orders the electrocution of Bennie Graves, a Homewood-Brushton man convicted in the strangulation killing of two children for whom he had been babysitting.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 6, 1980%0aContract negotiations continue between the United Steelworkers and the "Big 9" companies.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 8, 1980%0aPAT's Board of Directors approve a 10 cents fare increase.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 11, 1980%0aRobert L. Hawkins, Jr., former Allegheny County Manpower Director, receives a 6-1/2-year prison sentence and is ordered to pay a $10,000 fine and $79,000 restitution on 83 counts of payroll fraud.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 17, 1980%0aA Carnegie Mellon University study asserts that the outlook for the steel industry in Pittsburgh is brighter than expected because the firms will invest $1.1 billion dollars updating equipment, building new facilities and installing environmental controls.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 18, 1980%0aA record number of speakers and spectators packed the school board's public hearing to oppose the board's desegregation plan.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 21, 1980%0aSix days before the deadline set by the state Human Relations Commission, the school board remains divided over desegregation.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 28, 1980%0aThe County Commissioners offered a $18.3 million plan to line the Allegheny River with parks.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 1, 1980%0aPAT bus and trolley fares are raised 10 cents despite a last-ditch court battle by a community group.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 4, 1980%0aDozens of couples line-up in the pouring rain for more than 24 hours at the doors of the Catholic Social Services of Allegheny County in the hope of adopting children.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 10, 1980%0aPenn Dot's "pot hole patching team" begins its season under a new Director, District Engineer Roger Carrier.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 8, 1980%0aSenator Edward Kennedy, campaigning at the Cyclops Steel Corporation plant in Bridgeville, accuses President Carter of reneging on his promise to protect steel jobs.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 11, 1980%0aA State Supreme Court Justice orders a halt to P.P.G. Industries' $100 million downtown development plan until the court can decide on the legal issues raised by five Market Square merchants opposing the plan.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 14, 1980%0aVice President Mondale attacks the policies of Senator Kennedy in a campaign visit to the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 15, 1980%0aLeaders of the United Steelworkers ratify a 3-year contract providing an estimated $2.85 hike in wages and fringe benefits.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 17, 1980%0aSenator Kennedy, Republican candidate George Bush and Rosalyn Carter are in the Pittsburgh area campaigning for votes in the Pennsylvania presidential primary.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 19, 1980%0aJail terms and fines against striking Western Penitentiary guards are ordered by a Commonwealth Court judge.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 22, 1980%0aThe federal Nuclear Regulatory Commission declares that a low-level radioactive leak, at a nuclear plant in nearby Shippingport is not dangerous.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 23, 1980%0aIn the Pennsylvania presidential primary, George Bush defeats Ronald Reagan and Senator Edward Kennedy wins over President Carter.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 10, 1980%0aThe steel lay-offs might reach 60,000 by September.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 22, 1980%0aPenn Dot announces that an $8 million reconstruction project on the Parkway West will begin in June.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 27, 1980%0aU.S. Steel will temporarily shut down its third and last furnace at the Edgar Thomson Works in Braddock.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 31, 1980%0aOxford Development Company reveals plans for a 46-story $100 million office-commercial building on Grant Street.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 19, 1980%0aIndependent presidential candidate John Anderson campaigns in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 21, 1980%0aThe six-week strike by moving van drivers ends.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 25, 1980%0aThe School Board announces a lay-off of 141 teachers as a result of declining enrollment, low attrition and the pending desegregation plan.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 26, 1980%0aOliver Tyrone Corporation will build a 20-story office tower at Stanwix Street.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 27, 1980%0aThe PAT board reveals plans for a downtown transit center at the old B&O railroad depot.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 30, 1980%0aUnemployment in the area reaches 7.8%25.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 18, 1980%0aAn agreement between the Market Square merchants and the PPG Industries is made. The merchants will get space for their stores elsewhere. The agreement clears the way for the construction of the PPG skyscraper.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 18, 1980%0aThe State Human Relations Commission asks the Commonwealth Court to stop the city's Board of Education from implementing its desegregation plan.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 21, 1980%0aOn the first day of the draft registration, there is widespread vandalism at the city's post offices.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 24, 1980%0aThe Commonwealth Court rules against school desegregation, paving the way for the school board bussing plan.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 27, 1980%0aThe University Health Center announces a $250 million expansion plan for the city hospitals.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 6, 1980%0aRichard Wallace is named city school superintendent.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 18, 1980%0aLeland Hazard -- the philosopher at the Pittsburgh Renaissance -- dies at the age of 87. His autobiography "Attorney for the Situation" was published in 1975.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 20, 1980%0aU.S. Steel will recall 800 furloughed employees to the Edgar Thompson works.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 31, 1980%0aThe 28-year old Canton House one of the city's great hotel buildings, is demolished, to make way for the Dravo skyscraper which later was named One Mellon Center.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 2, 1980%0aDesegregation plan affecting 12,000 students begins.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 4, 1980%0aThe County Grand Jury recommends the filing of six criminal charges against County Commissioner Cyril Wecht, who allegedly used the morgue when he was coroner "to the benefit of his private laboratory."%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 8, 1980%0a"I have not committed any crime or engaged in any misconduct" responds Wecht to the charges.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 12, 1980%0aPAT approves a 15-cent increase in base transit fares.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 19, 1980%0aAn investigating grand jury determines that the April 24: drawing of the Daily Number "666" has been fixed. Six persons including WTAE-TV's popular Nick Perry are charged with conspiracy.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 29, 1980%0aGipsy, the monkey, an escapee from the Zoo for over a week, pelts officers who try to capture him with a barrage of crabapples.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 4, 1980%0aSihugo "Si" Green, who played on the Duquesne University basketball team, which won the national invitation tournament in 1955, dies of cancer at the age of 46.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 29, 1980%0aUrban Redevelopment Authority designates Grant Liberty Development Corporation to build a $26 million hotel complex across from the Convention Center.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 5, 1980%0aFormer California Governor and movie actor Ronald Reagan defeats President Carter in the presidential election. Republican Arlen Specter is elected to the U.S. Senate. Leroy Zimmermann wins the race for the State Attorney General.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 10, 1980%0aMayor Richard Caliguiri announces a balance budget for 1981 without raising taxes.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 13, 1980%0aJ&L Steel will close the continuous strip and sheet department of its Pittsburgh works. Thousands of steelworkers will lose their jobs.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 6, 1980%0aA contaminated water system leaves 20,000 South Hills residents without fresh water.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 17, 1980%0aThe Mellon Stuart Company announces the construction of office building for its headquarters In the North Shore.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 18, 1980%0aA grand jury identifies WTAE-TVs personality Nick Perry as the planner of the $1.8 million lottery fix. Perry supposedly netted $35,000 as his share of the winnings.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 19, 1980%0aAllegheny County's 1981 budget includes a 5-mill increase in the real estate tax.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 21, 1980%0aThe playwright Marc Connelly, best known for his play The Green Pastures, dies at the age of 90. He was born in McKeesport.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 21, 1980%0aAllegheny Ludlum Steel is purchased by a local investment group for $195 million.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 29, 1981%0aGulf Oil settles its fight with Westinghouse over monopolistic activities with a payment of $25 million.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 3, 1981%0aMayor Caliguiri plans to increase the city's $10 annual occupation tax to $40.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 7, 1981%0aThe David L. Lawrence Convention Center opens with a ribbon-cutting ceremony.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 13, 1981%0aDuquesne Light receives from the Public Utility Commission the approval of a $47.5 million annual rate increase.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 20, 1981%0aThe 13-week strike of the Steel Valley teachers comes to an end, enabling 2,700 pupils to return to the classrooms.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 24, 1981%0aThe Pirate organization files suit for the annulment of their 40-year lease with the Three Rivers Stadium Authority.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 2, 1981%0aAfter the state Supreme Court refused to allow Dr. Joshua A. Paper to keep his post, Sanford H. Edberg becomes Allegheny County Coroner.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 3, 1981%0aPenn-DOT launches a two-year construction program for Parkway East.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 15, 1981%0aPlans for 400 condominiums and apartments, 60,000 square feet of office and retail space, and a 600-car parking garage are proposed for Mt. Washington. The development will cost $60 million.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 18, 1981%0aBecause of a wildcat strike, twelve Southwestern Pennsylvania coalmines are closed.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 14, 1981%0aStriking Mesta Machine Company workers end their 45-day walkout at the West Homestead plant.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 16, 1981%0aAccording to a grand jury report the Allegheny County Jail was a haven of administrative corruption, drug trafficking, sexual assaults during the five-year administration of former warden James Jennings.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 27, 1981%0aMayor Caliguiri sues the city of New Orleans and the Louisiana Superdome in Federal Court to stop interference with Pittsburgh's contract dispute with the Pirates.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 28, 1981%0aA federal judge orders the school districts of Churchill, Edgewood, Swissvale, Turtle Creek and General Braddock to consolidate their desegregation plans.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 17, 1981%0aAfter the 380 striking employees of the Pittsburgh Brewing Company accepted the company's offer, the only remaining brewery in the city will continue operations.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 18, 1981%0aStriking United Mine Workers block the entrances to the headquarters of Consolidation Coal Company in Upper St. Clair.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 19, 1981%0aFormer coroner Cyril Wecht is acquitted of the charges that he used the city morgue for private gain.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 19, 1981%0aA new building and fire code is passed by the City Council. Houses in Pittsburgh must install smoke alarms.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 20, 1981%0aThe voters of Allegheny County approve a plan for a harness racing track.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 26, 1981%0aCommon places Court orders PAT to roll back base fare to 60 cents and transfers to 10 cents; also to realign bus and trolley zones and eliminate all savings on pass purchases.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 28, 1981%0aA fire at a Lawrenceville industrial building forces the closing of the 62nd Street Bridge.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 29, 1981%0aEnd of the twenty-two-day-old strike by county employees.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 31, 1981%0aEnd of the fifty-day-old major league baseball strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 5, 1981%0aThousands of air traffic controllers across the country (including 58 from Pittsburgh) get their pink slips after defying the President's back-to- work-order.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 20, 1981%0aAs part of an adjustment to population changes, three Allegheny County House seats are eliminated by the Reappointment Commission in Harrisburg.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 25, 1981%0aMayor Caliguiri proposes a 15 percent cut in capital spending for 1982. Inflation hits 19.2%25 for July.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 4, 1981%0aPAT eliminates buses dinning between 1:30 A.M. and 5 A.M. With this the "night coach era" coach era comes to an end.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 8, 1981%0aA school desegregation plan combines five east suburban districts into one.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 11, 1981%0aSix thousand Nabisco women employees are awarded $5 million in damages against the company.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 3, 1981%0aThe federal governments plan to build 100 B-I bombers by Rockwell International will add $400 million to the company's profits in the next seven years.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 10, 1981%0aThe eight-block area between the Monongahela River and the Boulevard of the Allies (from Grant to Stanwix Streets) is proposed to become Firstside.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 16, 1981%0aDr. Joshua Perper is cleared of perjury charges.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 21, 1981%0aGovernor Thornburgh's proposed private enterprise liquor store system fails in its first test vote.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 28, 1981%0aGovernor Thornburgh and Mayor Caliguiri announce that two of the four "missing link" highways will be built. The East Street and North Shore Expressways get the green light. Crosstown Boulevard and North Hills Expressway will be built later.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 4, 1981%0aMayor Caliguiri is reelected, the Democratic Party keeps their domination in Pittsburgh and in Allegheny County.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 24, 1981%0aGovernor Thornburgh vetoes Abortion bill.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 29, 1981%0aThe city's budget for 1982 will be $229 million.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 6, 1982%0aRand McNally's Places Rated Almanac, names Pittsburgh as the third most livable city in the country.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 7, 1982%0aU.S. Steel obtains 51 percent of Marathon Oil stock.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 7, 1982%0aThe budget of the state government is $13 billion.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 8, 1982%0aAt the Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Company, 40%25 of the work force is laid off.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 10, 1982%0aThe Crucible Steel Plant in Beaver County is up for sale.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 19, 1982%0aPenn-DOT asks a federal court to free $302 million in highway funds frozen by a judge because the state failed to put an auto emissions inspection program into effect. Twenty-four hours later the freeze is lifted.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 17, 1982%0aThe cost of living in the city is ranked $700 below the national average in a year.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 20, 1982%0aThe city's public schools are ordered to improve the racial balance in three high schools and ten elementary schools.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 25, 1982%0aFederal prosecutors investigate bid-rigging and anti-trust violations by contractors who were handling public roadway work in Western Pennsylvania.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 19, 1982%0aState police and city detectives complete a large sting operation. They arrest fifty people in connection with a stolen goods operation.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 8, 1982%0aColt Industries will sell its Crucible Stainless & Alloy Division in Midland to Cyclops Corporation.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 16, 1982%0aGround is broken for the East Street Valley Expressway.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 18, 1982%0aThe city asks additional millions in taxes to improve Three Rivers Stadium so the Pirates can be kept in Pittsburgh. $11 million will be needed to renovate the stadium.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 29, 1982%0aAllegheny Ludlum will spend $12 million on modern equipment at its West Leechburg plant as a trade-off for contract concessions from its employees.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 17, 1982%0aA 150,000-pound drill press falls off a truck on the Parkway West and levels a Scott Township house.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 21, 1982%0aThe City Council gives a tentative approval to the proposed takeover of Three Rivers Stadium by the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 22, 1982%0aColt Industries refuses to sell its crucible plant to Cyclops Corporation.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 26, 1982%0aA last-minute contract settlement averts a nationwide strike by 30,000 Westinghouse employees, half of them Pittsburgh residents.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 29, 1982%0aColt Industries begins closing its Crucible Steel Plant. 400 employees will lose their jobs.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 29, 1982%0aThe USW rejects the steel industry's plea for concessions from 300,000 basic steel employees.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 2, 1982%0aMellon Bank agrees to merge with Girard, a Philadelphia holding company.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 3, 1982%0aToxic waste halts the construction of Bloomfield Bridge.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 27, 1982%0aThe basic fee for riding PAT buses and trolleys will be raised to $1 beginning October 3, 1982.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 31, 1982%0aMayor Caliguiri announces a six-year, $504 million capital spending plan that stresses street, bridge, water and sewage systems.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 9, 1982%0aAfter more than a decade of planning, the redevelopment of the North Shore begins.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 14, 1982%0aCommon Pleas Judge Silvestri refuses to order the McKeesport Area School District to resume the busing of 1,900 high school students.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 24, 1982%0aThe National Football League players go on strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 6, 1982%0aState police in Homewood arrest 25 people involved in drug operation.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 20, 1982%0aCarnegie-Mellon University concludes an agreement with IBM to become an experimental computer center, with more than 20,000 PC's.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 25, 1982%0aA desegregation plan is agreed to by city schools.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 26, 1982%0aAfter 20 months of repairs costing $58 million, the Parkway is at last open to full traffic.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 27, 1982%0aUS Steel has an $82 million loss in its third quarter and cuts its dividend from 50 cents to 25 cents.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 3, 1982%0aElection Day: Republican Governor Thornburgh wins a second term in a close race against Alan Ertel. H. John Heinz III is re-elected to the U.S. Senate, defeating his Democratic opponent, Cyril Wecht, by 700,000 votes.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 5, 1982%0aUnemployment in Pennsylvania hits 11.5 percent.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 17, 1982%0aThe 57-day NFL players' strike ends.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 11, 1982%0a"Spectator," a Philadelphia management firm, has been chosen to run the Three Rivers Stadium.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 16, 1982%0aUniversity of Pittsburgh football player Todd Joseph Becker is killed in a fall from his dorm window.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 17, 1982%0aPAT agrees to a record budget of $133.5 million, $8 million more than the year before.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 24, 1983%0aCity inspectors charge Warner Cable with electrical safety violations.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 9, 1983%0aMesta Machine files for bankruptcy after a foreclosure by three local banks.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 12, 1983%0aThe East is buried by three feet of snow.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 13, 1983%0aMrs. Henry Hillman ("Elsie") is named by the Pittsburgh Chapter of Vector International as "Woman of the Year."%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 17, 1983%0aA rock and mudslide on Saw Mill Run Boulevard closes the road for three weeks.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 1, 1983%0aCity government will spend $1.7 million in surplus funds to create short-term jobs for the unemployed.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 3, 1983%0aU.S. Steel will start up the No. 2 blast furnace at the Edgar Thomson works and recall 300 employees.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 15, 1983%0aAldege "Baz" Bastien, general manager of the Penguins, is killed in a motor car accident.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 6, 1983%0aPresident Reagan visits Pittsburgh and makes a reassuring speech about the survival of the steel industry. Four thousand protestors boo him.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 23, 1983%0aCity officials launch a multi-million dollar reclamation project along the Monongahela and Allegheny Rivers.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 10, 1983%0aCounty Commissioner Cyril Wecht is ordered to pay back $172,000, the sum be allegedly made through the misuse of the morgue.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 11, 1983%0aUSW head Lloyd McBride announces that the steelworkers' organization will sue US Steel to prevent the corporation from importing foreign steel.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 18, 1983%0aIn the primary election the voters of Allegheny County oust County Commissioners Cyril Wecht and William Hunt.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 25, 1983%0aCyrus C. "Cy" Hungerford, whose cartoons brightened newspaper pages for over 70 years, dies in his 95th year, four days after the death of his wife Dorothy. Until his retirement in 1977, Hungerford drew three cartoons a week for the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 21, 1983%0aFlash floods hit Bedford, Somerset and Cambria counties, causing a large amount of damage.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 1, 1983%0aA window washer plunges 34 stories to his death from One Oxford Centre when his scaffolding falls. The life of his coworker was saved by his safety belt.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 1, 1983%0aRebecca Stafford is elected president of Chatham College.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 20, 1983%0aCopperweld Corporation closes its Glassport plant. 200 men lose their jobs.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 22, 1983%0aPower failures at the Greater Pittsburgh Airport delay flights for up to 12 hours.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 27, 1983%0aIn a Turnpike pileup, caused by a tractor-trailer, four persons are killed, ten injured.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 29, 1983%0aThe city will lose J&L headquarters when parent company LTV Steel buys Cleveland-based Republic Steel.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 4, 1983%0aThe University of Pittsburgh is assigned a key role in the national fight against AIDS with a $4 million grant.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 3, 1983%0aThe 650 employees of the forty-four Giant Eagle Markets end their three-week long strike.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 6, 1983%0aLloyd McBride, president of the United Steel Workers of America, dies at the age of 67.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 14, 1983%0aMayor Caliguiri makes it known that his $263.7 million budget will have no tax increase or reduced spending.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 28, 1983%0aUS Steel cuts 5,574 district jobs- 3,827 in the Mon Valley.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 2, 1984%0aDemocrats Tom Forester and Pete Flaherty and Republican Barbara Hafer are installed as Allegheny County Commissioners.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 9, 1984%0aPlans are unveiled for a 36-story skyscraper -- the Hillman-First Federal Tower -- to be built on the site of the Jenkins Arcade near the Hotel Hilton.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 13, 1984%0aWestinghouse phases out its switch gear production in East Pittsburgh. 950 workers lose their jobs.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 15, 1984%0aVeteran Pittsburgh Press news photographer Raymond Gallivan, who worked for the newspaper for fifty years, dies. He was 88 years old.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 24, 1984%0aAlcoa will renovate the 70-year-old William Penn Hotel. The estimated cost is $20 million.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 26, 1984%0aThe Pittsburgh Steelers sue Three Rivers Stadium Authority for exclusive pro-football use of the stadium. The United States Football League's Maulers had signed a four-year lease with the Stadium.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 4, 1984%0aCharles H. "Chuck" Cooper, former Duquesne University All-American, who joined the Boston Celtics in 1950 to become the first black to play in the National Basketball Association, dies at age 57.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 10, 1984%0aKroger Company sells all of its 45 Pittsburgh-area stores. The 2,845 union employees who had been on strike since January 19 will be out of jobs.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 10, 1984%0aAccording to Roger Ahlbrandt, Assistant Provost at the University of Pittsburgh and Co-Director of the Western Pennsylvania Advanced Technology Center, the new center has already spawned four new companies in its first year, and is expected to bring to Pittsburgh within the next four years 80 more companies creating 6,000 new jobs.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 14, 1984%0aDr. Henry T. Bahnson and Dr. Thomas Starzl perform a simultaneous 16-hour liver and heart transplant operation on a six-year-old girl at Children's Hospital.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 9, 1984%0aU.S. Steel and National Intergroup cancel their merger plans.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 21, 1984%0aAfter strong criticism from the national administration, LTV Corporation, owner of J&L Steel, is allowed so buy Republic Steel for $700 million.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 21, 1984%0aWarner Cable reaches an agreement to sell its city cable operations to TCI for $93 million.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 23, 1984%0aThirty-six-year-old William W. Millar becomes the youngest executive director of the Port Authority.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 27, 1984%0aThe Dixmont State Hospital and Western Restoration Center, two state-run mental health facilities in Allegheny County will be closed.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 1, 1984%0aWQED, the nations first community owned television station, celebrates its 30th anniversary.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 5, 1984%0aThe future of the steel industry is the focus of the debate between Democratic presidential candidates Walter Mondale, Gary Hart and Rev. Jesse Jackson at the Convention Center.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 6, 1984%0aSenator Gary Hart, Rev. Jesse Jackson and Vice President Walter Mondale have a televised Democratic presidential debate at the Convention Center.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 7, 1984%0aA federal judge prohibits U.S. Steel from forcing employees to sign away their rights to file age discrimination suits in return for big pensions.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 12, 1984%0aU.S. Labor Secretary Raymond Donovan and Governor Thornburgh bring $1.5 million in grants to Midland to retrain 4,100 unemployed workers.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 13, 1984%0aThe South Hills street car junction at Overbrook and Mt. Lebanon-Beechview trolley lines closes after 80 years in operation.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 14, 1984%0aTimothy Johnson, the first local patient, receives a heart and kidney transplant. In separate operations at the Presbyterian-University Hospital, Dr. Bartley Griffith and Dr. Alfredo Trento give Johnson a new heart, while Dr. Rodney Taylor and Dr. Thomas Rosenthal provide him with a new kidney.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 26, 1984%0aLouis Mason Jr., the first black president of the City Council, dies at the age of 69.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 29, 1984%0aAndre Previn, music director of the Symphony since 1976, will leave Pittsburgh to take over the direction of the Los Angeles Philharmonic.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 30, 1984%0aFortune magazine lists Pittsburgh as the nation's third largest corporation center. Fifteen of Fortune's 500 companies have their headquarters in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 4, 1984%0aWiretapping leads to gambling and conspiracy charges against 15 area residents who were involved in a $1 million a year betting ring.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 31, 1984%0aThe former Union Trust Building -- since 1946 a national historic landmark- is sold to the Edward J. De Bartolo Corporation.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 14, 1984%0aGurdon Flagg, manager of the Duquesne club for 50 years (from 1931 to 1981) and president of the Pittsburgh Opera for 28 years (from 1954 to 1982), dies in his 83rd year.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 10, 1984%0aDr. Joseph C. Maroon and three other doctors perform a pioneer brain surgery at Allegheny General Hospital.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 6, 1984%0aAllegheny County jurors are allowed to question witnesses during a criminal trial. It is the first time in the areas history. Common Pleas Court Judge Henry R. Smith Jr. said the purpose of a trial is to find the truth, and some of us feel that in order to do that, jurors should be permitted to ask questions.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 11, 1984%0aDavid B. Shakarian, founder and chairman of the board of General Nutrition Centers, the health food company, dies of cancer at the age of 70.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 16, 1984%0aThe 56-year-old Stanley Theatre will become the Benedum Center for Performing Arts as a result of a $5 million gift from the Benedum Foundation. The new center will be the permanent home of the Pittsburgh Ballet Theatre, the Pittsburgh Opera and the Civic Light Opera.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 17, 1984%0aForbes magazine's annual listing of Americas 400 wealthiest people includes six Pittsburghers, Henry L. Hillman, 62; Richard Mellon Scaife, 52; Henry John Heinz II, 76; William Block, 68, and his brother Paul Block, Jr., 73; the late David B. Shakarian and Helen Clay Frick, 95.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 19, 1984%0aA $230 million development plan for the Three Rivers Stadium area is announced. A Science and Technology Center will be part of the project.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 2, 1984%0aThree Carnegie Mellon university scientists -- Raj Reddy, Allen Newell and H.T. King -- receive a $19 million grant to develop a new "supercomputer" for the symbolic processing that is 100 times as fast as those currently available.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 31, 1984%0aThe 64-story U.S. Steel Building is sold to a Connecticut partnership for $292.2 million, constituting the largest real estate sale in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 31, 1984%0aPhilanthropist Alfred M. Hunt dies at the age of 65.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 9, 1984%0aHelen Clay Frick, the daughter of steelman Henry Clay Frick, dies at the age of 96.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 14, 1984%0aCarnegie Mellon University is awarded a five-year $103 million Defense Department contract for a new Software Engineering Institute. It is expected that the Institute will provide 250 new jobs.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 20, 1984%0aThe Galbreath family, after 38 years of association with the Pittsburgh Pirates, decides to sell its 51%25 interest in the team. The Pirates, with a lease of the Stadium until 2011, will remain in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 6, 1984%0aGroundbreaking begins for the $135 million building complex across from the David L. Lawrence Convention Center. The project will include the 615-room Vista International Hotel and a 31-story office building.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 17, 1985%0aRockwell International will acquire Allen-Bradley Company, a Milwaukee-based industrial automation equipment manufacturer, for $1.65 billion.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 4, 1985%0a"Clayton," the Point Breeze home of Helen Clay Frick, according to her will, will be opened to the public.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 20, 1985%0aThe city of Pittsburgh will sever financial ties with several companies that are doing business with South Africa.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 27, 1985%0aRand McNally's Places Rated Almanac lists Pittsburgh as the most livable of the nation's 329 metropolitan areas.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 1, 1985%0aGulf Oil Corporation will donate its Harmarville Research and Development Center to the University of Pittsburgh. The huge center expects to procure jobs for 2,000 scientists and technicians.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 4, 1985%0aCarnegie Mellon University will open a research center that will use fluorescent materials to study living cells. Researchers from the biology, chemistry, physics, engineering and computer science departments will participate in the program.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 15, 1985%0aCharles Robinson 'Chick' Davies, 84, the legendary Duquesne University basketball coach, dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 2, 1985%0aJ. Bruce Johnston, the chairman of the Coordinating Steel Companies Committee says the steel industry will resume company-by-company bargaining in 1987 after the expiration of the present labor agreement.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 5, 1985%0aA married couple, Ken and Lisa Martin of Mesa, Arizona, win victories in the first Pittsburgh Marathon.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 8, 1985%0aThe 10+-mile Light Rail Transit line between South Hills Village and Downtown receives a $19.7 million grant from the Urban Mass Transportation Administration. The money will pay for the completion of the line.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 10, 1985%0aArson is suspected in two simultaneous fires, one in the City-County Building, the other in the basement of the County Office Building.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 29, 1985%0aAGV Enterprises will purchase the 34-story Gulf Building -- a national historic landmark- from the Chevron Corporation.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 12, 1985%0aA special device developed by University-Presbyterian Hospital surgeons Dr. Bartley Griffith, Dr. Robert Hardesty and Dr. Alberto Trento is revealed after a heart-lung transplant at the hospital.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 21, 1985%0aProfessor Ralph Z. Roskies of the University of Pittsburgh plans to give Pittsburgh a new supercomputer, which will make the city the computing center of America.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 29, 1985%0aDr. Ronald B. Herberman, a federal science administrator and tumor researcher, will head the newly formed University of Pittsburgh Cancer Institute.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 3, 1985%0aThe city's first subway opens to traffic. It cost $90 million to build.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 4, 1985%0aJudge Henry Ellenbogen, 85, dies in Miami, Florida. He served on the Allegheny County Common Pleas Court bench for 39 years and in the U.S. House of Representatives for 5 years.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 19, 1985%0aPrime parking spaces in Downtown cost two dollars per hour, twice as much as in the nation's 25 largest cities.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 2, 1985%0aNational Intergroup buys Permain Corporation of Houston, the crude oil gathering company for $172 million.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 4, 1985%0aThe 8th annual Three Rivers Regatta is watched by over a hundred thousand people.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 28, 1985%0aWilleen Benedum, niece of the legendary oil wildcatter Michael Benedum, dies of pneumonia at the age of 80.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 11, 1985%0aThe Pittsburgh Foundation celebrates its 40th anniversary by commemorating Pittsburgh's achievements over the past forty years that "shaped the city's renaissance."%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 13, 1985%0aA Port Authority study outlines the economic advantages of extending the subway north to Allegheny Center and east to Oakland and Squirrel Hill. The proposed $400 million expansion would replace buses with trolleys and would help PAT save over $2 million a year.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 26, 1985%0aGeorge A. Ferris, the new Chief Executive Officer of the Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Corporation, orders layoffs and pay edits for management and vows to work without pay until the 69-day labor dispute involving 8,200 workers is settled.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 2, 1985%0aA private-public partnership led by Malcolm Prince, the Chairman of Ryan Homes Inc., buys the Pittsburgh Pirates for $22 million from the Galbreath family. The public and private partners will contribute $50 million, while Mayor Caliguiri plans to raise the city's share -- $25 million -- through selling Three Rivers Stadium.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 8, 1985%0aRoger Miles Blough, former U.S. Steel Chairman of the Board and Chief Executive Officer, dies at age 81.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 28, 1985%0aDr. Bartley Griffith leads a three-man surgical team at Presbyterian-University Hospital that gives Pittsburgh's first artificial heart reappoint, Thomas J. Gaidosh, a new heart which replaces the Jarvik-7 artificial heart that had kept the patient alive for 4 days.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 5, 1985%0aMayor Richard Caliguiri is elected to a third consecutive term.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 6, 1985%0aThe Monongahela River is closed from Pittsburgh south to the West Virginia border after floodwater dislodges 62 barges from their moorings.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 8, 1985%0aThe Pittsburgh City Council unanimously approve Mayor Caliguiri's proposal to sell Three Rivers Stadium, thus enabling the Pirates to remain in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 20, 1985%0aKimberly Fuller, 9, becomes the youngest American to undergo lung-heart transplant surgery in a 5.5-hour operation performed by Dr. Bartley Griffith and Dr. Robert Hardesty at the Children's Hospital.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 6, 1985%0aMark Di Suvero's 90-foot-tall steel sculpture for a traffic island in Gateway Center is approved by the city's Art Commission.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 8, 1986%0aWestinghouse Electric celebrates its 100th Anniversary.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 17, 1986%0aA supercomputer consortium (Westinghouse Electric Corp., Carnegie-Mellon University and the University of Pittsburgh) receives the CRAY X-MP/48 supercomputer capable of performing 840 million operations per second. The Pittsburgh group is part of a national supercomputer consortium along with Cornell University, Princeton University, the University of Illinois and the University of California in San Diego.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 22, 1986%0a15 million passengers traveled through the Greater Pittsburgh International Airport in 1985, a 1.6 million increase over the previous year.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 28, 1986%0aAll 7 crew members, including 1970 Carnegie-Mellon University graduate Judith Resnick, die as the Space Shuttle Challenger explodes after takeoff from Cape Canaveral.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 31, 1986%0aAn earthquake shakes Pittsburgh for the first time in 23 years.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 7, 1986%0aA $28 million merger offer by Australia's Swan Brewing Co. to the Pittsburgh Brewing Co. is accepted by the city's only beer maker.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 11, 1986%0aU.S. Steel Chairman David Roderick announces the completion of a $3 billion merger agreement between U.S. Steel Corporation and Texas Oil and Gas Company.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 21, 1986%0aMarilyn, the prize cow at the Pennsylvania Holstein Association auctions, is sold for $9,500.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 28, 1986%0aSeven major league baseball players, including former Pirates Dale Berra and Dave Parker, have to pay fines and perform community service to avoid drug-related suspensions handed down by Commissioner Peter Ueberroth. Former Pirates Lee and Lacy and Al Holland are given 60-day suspensions; Willie Stargell and Bill Madlock are absolved of any wrong-doing.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 17, 1986%0aThe City Council approves a $21 million loan to keep the Pirates in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 19, 1986%0aSentry, a new security robot developed by Remming Mobile Robotics, with the help of Carnegie Mellon University and the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, is presented in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 1, 1986%0aThe Allegheny Tower apartments will be converted into a 273-room hotel.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 6, 1986%0aRetired President of Jones and Laughlin Steel Corporation William P. Gerry, 76, dies of cancer in West Penn Hospital.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 7, 1986%0aMellon Bank assumes ownership of the Trimont condominium complex's 115 apartments and 44,900 square feet of office space to settle a $30 million debt owed to the bank by Washington Heights Associates.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 9, 1986%0aStanley C. Ellerspan, vice president of human resources at National Steel Corporation, announces the company's intentions to dismiss 3,500 of its employees during the next five years.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 17, 1986%0aPittsburgh Press reporters Mary Pat Flaherty and Andrew Schneider win the Pulitzer Prize for their series, "The Challenge of a Miracle: Selling the Gift," in which they investigated the organ transplantation program.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 21, 1986%0aWilliam Moore, a 35-year veteran of the police force, is appointed as the city's police chief. He is the first black appointed police chief in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 1, 1986%0aPresident Anthony O'Reilly of H.J. Heinz Company is the highest paid executive in the city. In 1985 he earned $1.96 million in salary and in bonuses.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 18, 1986%0aTwo parachutists, Don Sulkowski and Alan Danko, jump off the roof of the 64-story U.S. Steel building and land safely on the parking lot of the Civic Arena. They are immediately arrested.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 27, 1986%0aMayor Caliguiri and Pittsburgh Penguins Vice-President Paul Martha announce a city and county sponsored $11.4 million renovation of the Civic Arena that will keep the National Hockey League Club in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 30, 1986%0aThunderstorms bring about flash flooding causing $20 million damages.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 2, 1986%0aUniversity of Arkansas third baseman Jeff King is chosen by the Pirates as the first pick in the 1986 major league baseball amateur draft.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 4, 1986%0aLawyer John G. Buchanan, who practiced law in Pittsburgh for 74 years, dies in his Shadyside home at age 97.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 30, 1986%0aThe University of Pittsburgh receives a $4.6 million federal grant for a research center in which drugs against AIDS will be tested.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 1, 1986%0aThe state budget gives Carnegie Mellon University $30 million to build a high technology center. Private investors and the University will combine forces to raise an additional $10 million for a National Center for Advanced Manufacturing and Software Engineering.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 8, 1986%0aU.S. Steel Corporation, formed in 1901, changes its name to USX Corporation and plans a major corporate restructuring.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 14, 1986%0aWith gross revenues of $53 million, the law firm Reed, Smith, Shaw and McClay ranks 48th in a survey of the 75 highest grossing law firms in America.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 14, 1986%0aLegendary football coach Peter Dimperio ("Mr. Pete"), who led Westinghouse High School to 17 City League championships, dies in his 81st year.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 15, 1986%0aThe merger of Buhl Science Center and the Carnegie is approved by Buhl's Board of Trustees.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 27, 1986%0aBroadcaster Joseph G. Tucker, the voice of the Steelers for 32 years, dies at the age of 76.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 29, 1986%0aThe Pittsburgh Post-Gazette, the city's oldest newspaper, celebrates its 200th anniversary.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 19, 1986%0aFederal Aviation Administration rates the Greater Pittsburgh International Airport as the fifth best of the nations large airports.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 28, 1986%0aAfter 62 years, the YMCA Health Club on Wood Street closes its doors.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 10, 1986%0aThe Ritz-Carlton Hotel Company plans to build a 350-room hotel at Grant and Ross Streets.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 11, 1986%0aLorin Maazel will be the music director of the Pittsburgh Symphony in 1988.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 13, 1986%0aThe downtown department store of Gimbels closes after 61 years in business.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 28, 1986%0a12,000 runners run in the 10th annual Great Race.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 8, 1986%0aDartmouth Medical School Chairman Dr. George Matthew Bernier is named Dean of the University of Pittsburgh's School of Medicine.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 11, 1986%0aGail Lawson Campbell is elected as President of the Chatham College Alumnae Association.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 14, 1986%0aLouise Pershing Berlin, a founder of the Pittsburgh Center for the Arts, dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 15, 1986%0aCarnegie-Mellon University and the University of Pittsburgh unveil a new $900,000 nuclear magnetic resonance instrument which will conduct research on cancer and organ transplants.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 29, 1986%0aThe University of Pittsburgh receives the Smithsonian Institution's radiocarbon dating laboratory.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 22, 1986%0aSite is chosen for new $36 million Buhl Science Center. Ground breaking next to the Stadium will be in the spring of 1988.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 1, 1986%0aJake Milliones is elected to a fourth consecutive one-year term as President of the Pittsburgh Board of Education.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 8, 1986%0aHarvey Adams is elected to his sixth consecutive term as President of the Pittsburgh chapter of the NAACP.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 11, 1986%0aThe University of Pittsburgh Cancer Institute begins researching OK-432, a Japanese drug reported to shrink tumors and lengthen the life of cancer patients.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 16, 1986%0aCarnegie-Mellon University receives an $11.8 million corporate research grant for the fiscal year 1985.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 30, 1986%0aPresbyterian-University Hospital officials announce a $230 million renovation project that will provide more space for the hospital's transplant center and the Cancer Institute.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 8, 1987%0aThe Western Pennsylvania School for Blind Children in Oakland celebrates 100 years of service with a $9 million construction and renovation project to be completed in 1988.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 31, 1987%0aUnited Steelworkers negotiator James MeGeehan announces the ratification of a four-year concessions pact with the USX Corporation. The agreement brings to an end the longest shutdown at a major steelmaker in U.S. history.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 22, 1987%0aPop artist Andy Warhol. who was born in Pittsburgh, dies at age 58. He is buried at St. John the Baptist Byzantine Catholic Church Cemetery.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 23, 1987%0aChairman of the H.J. Heinz Corporation Henry J. Heinz II dies in his winter home on Jupiter Island, Florida, at the age of 78.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 4, 1987%0aDuquesne Light is ordered by the Public Utility Commission to reduce rates by $18.6 million.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 15, 1987%0aCo-publisher of the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette Paul Block Jr. dies in Monterey, Cal. at the age of 75.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 4, 1987%0aMayor Caliguiri proposes a $105 million expansion of the David L. Lawrence Convention Center that would increase its exhibit space by 50%25, double its meeting space and add five times as much storage room.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 12, 1987%0a15,000 Lawrenceville and Bloomfield residents, evacuated when toxic gas seeped out of a train's derailed tanker car, return to their homes.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 16, 1987%0aThe Pittsburgh Press wins its second consecutive Pulitzer Prize for a series by Andrew Schneider and Matthew Brelis that revealed inadequacies in Federal Aviation Administration screening of pilots.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 26, 1987%0aMonroeville's Vivel Rao finishes first out of 700 contestants at the National High School Chess Championship in Paluski, Virginia.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 29, 1987%0aJack M. Brewer, Sr., Pittsburgh's first black assistant superintendent of public schools and Pennsylvania's first black principal, dies at the age of 69.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 1, 1987%0aWestinghouse Electric Corporation announces the "phasing out" of its 94-year-old East Pittsburgh turbine plant. Because of this, eight hundred workers will lose their jobs.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 11, 1987%0aPittsburgh's first black chief of police, William H. Moore, after a year on the job, retires.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 20, 1987%0aThe Duquesne Heights Incline celebrates 110 years of ascents and descents.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 22, 1987%0aUrban Mass Transit Administration opens the final segment of the Port Authority's $542 million Light Rail System through the South Hills.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 7, 1987%0a"Fences," a family drama written by Pittsburgh native August Wilson, set in the Hill District, wins four 1987 Tony Awards, including best play, best actor and best director.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 19, 1987%0a12,177 fans pack Pittsburgh's Civic Arena to watch the Pittsburgh Gladiators defeat the Washington Commandos 48-46 in the first season game of the newly formed Arena Football League.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 26, 1987%0aGround is broken for construction of the $503 million Greater Pittsburgh International Airport's new midfield terminal.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 28, 1987%0aPlans for construction of a new $500 million retail and industrial complex for Robinson Township is announced.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 29, 1987%0aThree tornadoes down trees, damage homes and cause power outages as thunderstorms rip through southwestern Pennsylvania.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 29, 1987%0aLocal pilot Joseph Longo arrives home after spending more than two months as a prisoner of the government of Angola.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 1, 1987%0aUniversity of Pittsburgh trustees vote to divest the university of its investments in U.S. companies that do business in South Africa.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 16, 1987%0aPresident Reagan awards Pittsburgh the status of an All-American City.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 18, 1987%0aAnti-nuclear demonstrators gather on the Bloomfield Bridge on the first anniversary of shipments of radio-active waste from Three Mile Island through Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 22, 1987%0aGideon Toeplitz will become in October the new managing director of the Pittsburgh Symphony.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 22, 1987%0aAccording to the U.S. Bureau of the Census, Pittsburgh has lost 18,300 people since 1985.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 23, 1987%0aAllegheny County Commissioners declare there will be no county tax increase next year.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 23, 1987%0aThe Ben Franklin Partnership approves a $6.9 million grant to a university sponsored center in Pittsburgh that funds jobs-creation efforts in the fields of robotics, computers and advanced medical technology.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 29, 1987%0aThe Carnegie is restoring the "Noble Quartet" statues in the front of the museum and music ball.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 30, 1987%0aThe Reverend Donald Nesti resigns as President of Duquesne University, ending weeks of public controversy.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 3, 1987%0aFormer Pittsburgh Congressman William Moorhead dies of cancer.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 13, 1987%0aThe Chicago West Pullman Transportation Corporation announces that it will be buying the Pittsburgh & Lake Erie Railroad.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 19, 1987%0aThe East Street Valley Roadway opens. It runs between the 1-79 junction and downtown.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 20, 1987%0aThe Regional Industrial Development Corporation, with the University of Pittsburgh and Carnegie Mellon University. receives a $150,000 contract to coordinate plans for a new High Technology Park on the site of the old J & L steel plant.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 25, 1987%0aThe Reinhold Ice Cream Company will market the world's first microwavable milkshake, the "D'Frosta Shake."%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 27, 1987%0aUSX's National Plant in McKeesport closes. Employment was down to 186 from a high of 4600.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 31, 1987%0a17 months after opening the country jail annex, the jail and the annex are filled to capacity.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 1, 1987%0aThe population of Allegheny County declined by 5.3%25.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 6, 1987%0aThe University of Pittsburgh receives $49 million in Federal research funds during 1985.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 7, 1987%0aThe Reverend Jesse Jackson walks in the city's Labor Day parade and discloses that he will become a Democratic candidate in the presidential campaign.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 7, 1987%0aTransplant doctors and patients from around the world gather in honor of Dr. Thomas Starzl, regarded as a leader in the field of transplant surgery.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 10, 1987%0aThe city will spend $4 million to improve the appearance of Fifth Avenue.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 11, 1987%0aThe Duchess of Devonshire visits the opening of her family's art exhibition, "Old Masters Drawings from Chatsworth," at the Frick Museum.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 14, 1987%0aUnions representing 750 employees of the Pittsburgh and Lake Erie Railroad struck today attempting to stop the sale of the P & LE to a Chicago based group.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 21, 1987%0aThe parent companies of West Penn Hospital and Forbes Health System will merge in 1988.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 23, 1987%0aLa Roche College celebrates its 25th anniversary with the opening a new $4.2 million College Center.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 23, 1987%0aThe former Braddock Public Library, the oldest Carnegie Library in America, has received donations of $80,000 to restore the closed building.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 24, 1987%0aThe state announces that the removal of 744 bodies from the 120-year old Voeghtly cemetery accidentally uncovered last summer by highway construction workers will cost $1.1 million.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 25, 1987%0aThe Benedum Center for the Performing Arts opens. After a three-year restoration of the Stanley Theater, the Benedum is the third largest stage house in the country and one of the best equipped in terms of modern technical capability.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 1, 1987%0aMayor Caliguiri stunned the city by announcing he is suffering from amyloidosis, a rare and incurable disease that attacks vital body tissues and organs.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 6, 1987%0aLuciano Pavarotti starred in the Pittsburgh Opera's first performance at the Benedum Center.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 14, 1987%0aCarrick native Danny Seemiller with five other table tennis players will play for the U.S. team in the 1988 Summer Olympic games in South Korea.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 15, 1987%0aThe 24-day National Football League players strike ends.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 23, 1987%0aThe Fort Pitt Tunnel is closed during the morning rush hour after a truck carrying 40,000 pounds of bananas lost its brakes.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 23, 1987%0aHerr's Island is renamed Washington's Landing. Ground is broken for a $130 million development leading to a new marina, park, stores, offices and industrial buildings.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 23, 1987%0aMalcolm Prine, President of the Pittsburgh Pirates, resigns in dispute with Syd Thrift, the team's General Manager.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 7, 1987%0aThe George Westinghouse Museum opens.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 9, 1987%0a1,200 cafeteria and custodial workers strike the Pittsburgh School District when negotiations fail to produce a new contract.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 11, 1987%0aVice President George Bush marches through downtown in the annual Veteran's Day Parade.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 21, 1987%0aVolkswagen's Westmoreland County Plant, dedicated with fanfare on October 5, 1976, will close. 2500 people will lose their jobs.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 23, 1987%0aAn ordinance known as the no-smoking law is enacted by the City Council for areas in public and private buildings.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 7, 1987%0aJake Milliones is re-elected president of the Pittsburgh School Board for the fifth straight year.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 8, 1987%0aPittsburgh Bishop Anthony Bevilacqua is named to succeed John Cardinal Krol as Archbishop of Philadelphia.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 11, 1987%0aIsraeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres visits the city to sign an agreement between Carnegie Mellon University and five Israeli universities to share information about computer research.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 18, 1987%0aJames G. Roddey steps down after four years as Chairman of the Port Authority Transit Board.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 24, 1987%0aMayor Caliguiri, in a 45-minute operation, has a pacemaker implanted in his chest to regulate his heartbeat.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 31, 1987%0aThe estimated population of Pittsburgh for the past year was 387,499; that of Allegheny County 1,373,600.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 2, 1988%0aAn oil tank in Robinson township ruptures into the Monongahela River, spilling millions of gallons of oil.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 4, 1988%0aSophie Masloff becomes the first woman president of the City Council.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 18, 1988%0aEast Liberty dedicates a park to the memory of civil rights activist Wilhelmia Byrd Brown.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 4, 1988%0aThe Prince of Wales visits Pittsburgh and gives the keynote address to the "Remaking Cities" Conference.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 25, 1988%0aDonald W. Wuerl is installed as Bishop of the Pittsburgh Roman Catholic Diocese.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 31, 1988%0aHerbrick and Held, the city's oldest printing firm, closes.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 14, 1988%0aFifth Avenue Place office building is dedicated on the site of the former Jenkins Arcade.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 19, 1988%0aA memorial is unveiled on the Carnegie Mellon University Campus in honor of Judith A. Resnick, the first woman astronaut.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 22, 1988%0aUniversity of Pittsburgh names its center for International Security Studies after General Matthew Ridgway.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 25, 1988%0aGeorge Bush, Jesse Jackson and Michael Dukakis campaign in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 5, 1988%0aOpening of the Martin Luther King Jr. Reading Center at Heron and Milwaukee Avenues.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 6, 1988%0aPopular Mayor Richard S. Caliguiri dies at the age of 56. Caliguiri devoted his entire career to the City of Pittsburgh including service in the Department of Parks and Recreation, as President of City Council, and finally as mayor winning two elections to that position. He is credited with bringing about Renaissance II.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 6, 1988%0aSophie Masloff, Council President, is sworn in as Pittsburgh's first woman mayor.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 22, 1988%0aFirst Presbyterian Church of Allegheny on the North Side, built in 1866, is destroyed by fire.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 23, 1988%0aTHE PENNSYLVANIAN Apartment complex at the old Pennsylvania Railroad Station opens.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 15, 1988%0aCity officials unveil plans for the Pittsburgh Technology Center at the former Jones and Laughlin steel mill site at the Monongahela River.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 14, 1988%0aThe last Volkswagen rolls off the line in New Stanton.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 20, 1988%0aJohn W. Galbreath, real estate developer and owner of the Pittsburgh Pirates, dies at the age of 90.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 13, 1988%0aThe 34th day of over 90-degree temperature is recorded as Pittsburgh suffers from the worst droughts since 1881.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 25, 1988%0aArthur J. Rooney, who acquired the Steelers in 1933 for $52,500 and saw them win four Super Bowls, dies at the age of 87.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 29, 1988%0aSecret Service agents seize $2.5 million in counterfeit $20 bills in a search of a storage locker in East Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 17, 1988%0aJohn E. Murray Jr. is installed as President of Duquesne University, the first layman to head the institution.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 11, 1988%0aThe Veterans Memorial Bridge over the Allegheny River is dedicated on the 70th anniversary of Armistice Day.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 14, 1988%0aDemolition begins at the Shippingsport Atomic Power Plant, the world's first commercial nuclear power plant.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 3, 1989%0aBill Burns retires from broadcasting at KDKA-TV after a career of five decades.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 2, 1989%0aThe Pittsburgh Penguins defeat the Philadelphia Flyers for the first time in 15 years, with a 5-3 win in Philadelphia.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 18, 1989%0aFour hundred anti-abortion and abortion proponents clash at three clinics. Two hundred are arrested.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 22, 1989%0aInterstate 279 opens 1.3 miles along the North Shore, easing traffic congestion.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 3, 1989%0a500 Grateful Dead rock fans clash with police outside the Civic Arena after a performance.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 28, 1989%0aThe Port Authority train from McKeesport to the city has its final run.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 1, 1989%0aDavid M. Roderick, chairman of USX retires after ten years, a period of historic change including the longest steel strike in history, the closing of over 140 facilities, and the transformation of USX's focus from steel to energy.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 12, 1989%0aBraun Baking Company, the makers of Town Talk and Wonder Bread, closes its doors and moves to Philadelphia.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 16, 1989%0aSophie Masloff wins the Democratic primary for mayor beating County Controller Frank Lucchino, lawyer Byrd Brown, State Senator Tom Murphy and City Controller Tom Flaherty in a close five-way race.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 31, 1989%0aEdgar J. Kaufmann Jr., architectural historian, curator, philanthropist, and preserver of his family's estate, Fallingwater, dies at the age of 79.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 3, 1989%0aWilliam Larimer Mellon, Jr. dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 23, 1989%0aMario Lemieux signs a five-year, $12 million contract with the Pittsburgh Penguins.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 1, 1989%0aSchenley Park celebrates its 100th anniversary with hot-air balloon races.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 5, 1989%0aGround breaking ceremonies for The Carnegie Science Center near Three Rivers Stadium.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 20, 1989%0aBarbara Bush, the President's wife, visits the Carnegie Library in Homewood.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 1, 1989%0aPresbyterian University Hospital will buy Montefiore Hospital for $75 million.%0a%0a%0a%0a1990%0aJanuary 4, 1990%0aTraffic resumes on the Monongahela River, three days after sixty runaway barges drifted down stream and thousands of gallons of gasoline were spilled.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 8, 1990%0aRadio personality Ed Schaugheny (Uncle Ed) dies at 77.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 14, 1990%0aPittsburgh City Council gives final approval to an ordinance for recycling newspapers, plastic, glass and aluminum cans.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 17, 1990%0aCity Councilman President Ben Woods is sentenced to eight years for conspiracy, income tax evasion, extortion and racketeering.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 17, 1990%0aDreamer, a giant schnauzer from Fox Chapel owned by Marcia Nanel, wins the top prize at the Westminster Kennel Club Dog Show in New York.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 12, 1990%0aA 78 degree temperature breaks the 114 year-old record.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 25, 1990%0aThe Gulf Tower pyramid re-lit for the first time since the 1970's.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 31, 1990%0aA landslide ruptures a transmission line of Buckeye Pipe Line Company of Freeport, spilling an estimated 75,600 gallons of gasoline into the Allegheny River.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 4, 1990%0aUniversity Trustees vote Robert Mehrabian from the University of California, Santa Barbara to be Carnegie Mellon's seventh president.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 5, 1990%0aThe University of Pittsburgh announces the establishment of the University Heart Institute that will combine research with patient care and community outreach. Dr. Bruce Wilson will head the new institute.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 12, 1990%0aPittsburgh native, August Wilson wins his second Pulitzer Prize for his play "The Piano Lesson."%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 21, 1990%0aMayer DeRoy, a 30-year veteran police officer, becomes the new police chief.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 7, 1990%0aTwenty-three fire companies are called for as fire rages in the Strip District.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 13, 1990%0aDr. Solomon B. Freehof, Rabbi of Rodef Shalom Congregation for 32 years, dies at the age of 97.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 7, 1990%0aEdward M. Ryan, co-founder of Ryan Homes, donates the Bank Center Mall on Wood Street to Point Park College.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 18, 1990%0aFormer Republican minority Allegheny County Commissioner William Hunt dies at 76.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 1, 1990%0aDespite public and union protests, Dorothy Six, a blast furnace at USX Corporation's Duquesne works, is demolished.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 30, 1990%0aThe Pirates win their first Eastern Division Championship since 1979. They will lose to the Cincinnati Reds 4-2 games in the National League Playoff.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 11, 1990%0aStormie Jones, who survived the world's first heart and liver transplant which was performed at Children's Hospital, dies at 13.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 15, 1990%0aPirate Pitcher Doug Drabek wins the National League's Cy Young Award.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 20, 1990%0aCity public school officials say enrollment of 39,661 shows an increase for the first time since the 1960s.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 27, 1990%0aTemperatures in the city reach 75 degrees breaking the 103 year record high of 74.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 4, 1990%0aPipes carrying wires along the ceiling of the Liberty Tunnels collapse during rush hour, trapping some 150 cars and three buses.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 2, 1991%0aThe Urban Redevelopment Authority purchases the new City-County jail site along the Monongahela River.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary, 1991%0a"Friends of the Riverfront" is formed with the mission to "promote public access to and appreciation on for Pittsburgh's riverfronts" according to John Stevens, a co-founder and director of the nonprofit group. In addition to general riverfront cleanups, the group is working toward the opening of a 12-mile-long "Three River's Heritage Trail."%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 27, 1991%0aThe University of Pittsburgh will build two new buildings at the cost of $50 million.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 4, 1991%0aPopular and highly regarded Senator H. John Heinz III is killed in an accident when the shuttle airplane carrying him collides with a helicopter near Philadelphia.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 9, 1991%0aHarris Wofford is appointed to the U. S. Senate to fill the seat of the late H. John Heinz III.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 25, 1991%0aThe Pittsburgh Penguins win their first Stanley Cup in the franchise's 24-year history by defeating the Minnesota North Stars. 20.000 fans greet the Pens when they arrive back in Pittsburgh the following day.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 3, 1991%0aA six-week strike at the Giant Eagle Food Stores comes to an end.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 17, 1991%0a250,000 Pittsburghers honor returning servicemen from the Persian Gulf War with a parade in Downtown.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 5, 1991%0aPittsburgh artist Henry Koerner dies in a car accident while visiting his native Vienna.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 20, 1991%0aThe Christian Buhl House, a restored 1805 house once occupied by the Buhl family, opens to the public in Zelienople.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 8, 1991%0aJames Irwin, the Pittsburgh astronaut who walked on the moon in 1971, dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 27, 1991%0aDespite public protest, the University of Pittsburgh begins demolition of the Syria Mosque Hall.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 22, 1991%0aThe Pirates clinch the Eastern division title, but lose to the Atlanta Braves in the playoffs.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 23, 1991%0aA citizens' group proposes forming a non-profit corporation to take over the Pittsburgh Aviary from the city; it becomes the National Aviary in 1993.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 5, 1991%0aHarris Wofford defeats Republican challenger Dick Thornburgh for U.S. Senator.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 19, 1991%0aThe Pittsburgh Penguins are sold for more than $563 million.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 30, 1991%0aEdwin Grinberg, who served with distinction for two terms on the Pittsburgh School Board, ends his service as a 