iring of Ellsworth H. Brown, President and Director of the Chicago Historical Society, to become its seventh president.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 13, 1993%0aA blizzard leaves four feet of snow on the streets.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 1, 1993%0aWorkers in the CNG Tower get the afternoon off as the office building is evacuated after an April Fool's Day bomb threat.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 17, 1993%0aPresident Bill Clinton speaks at the new airport.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 24, 1993%0aSamuel Hazo, founder of the Pittsburgh International Poetry Forum, is named Pennsylvania's first official poet.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 14, 1993%0aGov. Robert P. Casey receives a heart-liver transplant at the Presbyterian Hospital.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 22, 1993%0aThe new $2.5 million entrance walkway and plaza to the Pittsburgh Zoo's lower parking lot is opened.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 26, 1993%0aGeneral Matthew B. Ridgway dies at his home in Fox Chapel.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 31, 1993%0aChuck Noll, former Pittsburgh Steeler Head Coach, is inducted into the Pro Football Hall of Fame in Canton, Ohio.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 24, 1993%0aHelen Stinner Ball, a pioneer aviatrix dies. Ball, with her husband Clifford Ball, helped start air mail service in the U.S.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 28, 1993%0aCongress designates the Pittsburgh Aviary as the "National Aviary in Pittsburgh."%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 8, 1993%0aPittsburgh Mounted Police begin patrolling the streets.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 10, 1993%0aThe Pennsylvania Historical and Museum Commission awards a $100,000 grant to the Historical Society of Western Pennsylvania to help secure and interpret a rockshelter near Avella which was used by Native Americans 16,000 years ago and is one of the oldest such sites in North America.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 3, 1994%0aThomas J. Murphy, former State Senator, is sworn in as Pittsburgh's 55th mayor.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 4, 1994%0aUp to 2-1/2 feet of snow fall in Southwestern Pennsylvania in the wake of a paralyzing blizzard.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 1, 1994%0aBritish Prime Minister John Major, whose father worked briefly in East Pittsburgh as a bricklayer in the 1890's before returning to England, meets with President Clinton in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 9, 1994%0aGroundbreaking ceremonies for the $42 million Senator John Heinz Pittsburgh Regional History Center in the Strip District.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 29, 1994%0aHorne's Department Store, which was founded in 1849, is bought by Federated Department Stores of Cincinnati.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 30, 1994%0aPittsburgh Symphony names Marvin Hamlish to fill the new post of Principal Pops Conductor.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 3, 1994%0aLa Roche College receives $5 million from Gateway Clipper Fleet owner, John Connelly, for its new sports and fitness center.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 13, 1994%0aOpening of the Andy Warhol Museum on the North Side.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 16, 1994%0aThe U.S. Open Golf Championship begins at Oakmont Country Club. Ernie Els of South Africa wins after a twenty hole sudden death playoff on June 21.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 27, 1994%0aLorin Maazel, Director of the Pittsburgh Symphony, will not renew his contract after the 1996 season.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 27, 1994%0aThe site for the Korean War Veteran's Memorial in Roberto Clemente Park on the North Shore is dedicated.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 8, 1994%0aUSAir Boeing 737 crashes, killing 131 passengers and crew near Hopewell, Beaver County.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 27, 1994%0aPittsburgh Port Authority breaks ground for the new Airport to Downtown Express Busway.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 8, 1994%0aValerie McDonald, former President of the Pittsburgh School Board, is elected as the first African-American woman on City Council.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 15, 1994%0aMonsignor Judson Procyk, rector of St. John's Cathedral in Munhall, is named by Pope John Paul III as the Metropolitan Archbishop of the Byzantine Catholic Archdiocese in the city.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 18, 1994%0aReopening of the 111 year old Smithfield Street Bridge after an eleven month $16 million in repairs and improvements.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 18, 1994%0aThe 124-year-old Monongahela Incline reopens after a $3-million renovation.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 17, 1994%0aA program offering $50 gift certificates for each gun turned in to Pittsburgh Police nets 800 guns.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 17, 1995%0aDr. Row Lubove, social historian at the University of Pittsburgh dies at 60. His two volumes "Twentieth Century Pittsburgh" are the outstanding chronicle of the city over the past 100 years.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 18, 1995%0aFuneral at St. Paul's Cathedral for the three fire fighter's who lost their life in a house fire on Valentine's Day, Patricia Ann Conroy, 43; Thomas Brooks, 42; and Marc Kolenda, 27.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 22, 1995%0aBobby Lewis, who coached the University of Pittsburgh Basketball team for 38 years and won more than 400 games, dies at his home.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 21, 1995%0aWilkinsburg School Board agrees to privatize Turner School, an elementary school which will be run by Alternative Public Schools Inc. of Nashville, the first private public school in the state.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 5, 1995%0aMyron Cope, sportscaster and creator of the "Terrible Towel," gives his final afternoon talk show on WTAE. Cope continues as voice of the Steelers.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 10, 1995%0aTile Pittsburgh Symphony appoints Mariss Jansons as Music Director to succeed Lorin Maazel.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 10, 1995%0aUniversity of Pittsburgh Chancellor. J. Dennis O'Conner announces his resignation.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 28, 1995%0a"Miss Pittsburgh," an open cockpit hi-wing airplane, is unveiled at the new airport. The plane completed the first commercial airmail delivery here on April 21, 1927, landing in West Mifflin's Bettis Field.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 29, 1995%0aThe new $147 million Allegheny County Jail Building opens.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 16, 1995%0aIn an upset victory in the Democratic Primary. Mike Dawida and Colleen Vuono, defeat Allegheny County Commissioners, Tom Forester and Pete Flaherty, two incumbents with a combined 40 years in office.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 26, 1995%0aTeresa Heinz, the widow of Senator John Heinz, marries U.S. Senator John Kerry, D-Mass. in Nantucket, Massachusetts. She will remain active in the Pittsburgh area.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 8, 1995%0aSony Corporation will construct a glass making factory at the site of its TV assembly plant near New Stanton.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 13, 1995%0aH.J. Heinz Company lights a 30 foot tall red and white neon sign at its North Side plant showing a full ketchup bottle.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 23, 1995%0aDr. Jonas Salk, who developed the polio vaccine while working in Pittsburgh, dies of heart failure in La Jolla, California at 80.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 6, 1995%0aDr. James 0. Van Trump, historian and co-founder of Pittsburgh History and Landmark Foundation, dies at the age of 88.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 25, 1995%0aForty-seven people are injured in a train collision in Beechview.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 1, 1995%0aWestinghouse Electric Corp., in a major shift of business emphasis, purchases CBS for $5.4 billion.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 5, 1995%0aDespite the rain, 31,147 fans attend the Pirates' game at Three Rivers Stadium, as part of the Post-Gazette's sponsored, "Ballot by Ballpark" in support of keeping the team in Pittsburgh. The Bucs win 3-1.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 21, 1995%0aSean Hitchman is arrested and charged with embezzling $1.2 million from ATMs while working for Mellon Bank.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 6, 1995%0aCarnegie-Mellon celebrates its 100th anniversary.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 12, 1995%0aJonny F. Gammage, a black motorist, dies after an incident with police officers.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 24, 1995%0aThe Downtown Lazarus department store closes, marking the end of a 102 year old store which was previously a Horne's store.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary, 1996%0aNeal Holmes, chairman of the Board of Allied Security, is unanimously reelected to his 4th term as chairman of the Port Authority.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 1996%0aRepublicans Larry Dunn and Bob Cranmer take the oath of office as Allegheny County Commissioners along with Democrat Mike Dawida, giving Republicans control of the county for the first time in 60 years.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 3, 1996%0aNationally recognized forensic pathologist, Dr. Cyril Wecht, is sworn in as Allegheny County coroner after a 16 years hiatus.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 13, 1996%0aCity Council unanimously approves a package of loans and lease concessions to open the way for California newspaper owner, Kevin McClatchy, to purchase the Pirates.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 14, 1996%0aSteelers defeat the Indianapolis Colts 20-16 earning a trip to Super Bowl XXX after a 16 year absence. They lose two weeks later to the Dallas Cowboys 20-17.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 22, 1996%0aPittsburgh cleans up from the worst flood in 24 years.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 21, 1996%0aMrs. Mary Hagan Barrett, executive secretary in charge of public relations at the Pittsburgh Hilton 1959-1983 and founder and two-terms president of the National Secretaries Association, dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 5, 1996%0aBill Foster, pitcher for the Homestead Grays and the Pittsburgh Crawfords who led the Negro League in strikeouts four times, is elected to Baseball's Hall of Fame by the Veteran's Committee.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 8, 1996%0aLong term Allegheny County Public Works Director Joseph P Moses and two codefendants are found guilty of participating in a kick-back conspiracy.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 15, 1996%0aRobert Mehrabian retires as president of Carnegie Mellon University.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 2, 1996%0aRobert McNeilly Jr., a member of the city's police force for 19 years, is named chief of police.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 25, 1996%0aThe Pittsburgh Penguins complete the longest game in their history (6 hours, 38 minutes) by defeating the Washington Capitals 3-2 at 2:16 am, in a Stanley Cup playoff game held in Landover, Maryland.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 5, 1996%0aThe Pittsburgh Marathon is won by Ruben Maza of Venezuela and Tamara Karlioukova of Russia.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 15, 1996%0aElsie Hillman announces plans to step down from the Republican National Committee after 21 years of service.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 20, 1996%0aLorin Maazel conducts his 41st concert and his last as Music Director of the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra, a position he held since 1984.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 5, 1996%0aThe University of Pittsburgh Medical Center and Shadyside Hospital confirm plans to merge, establishing an institution more than twice the size of its closest competitor.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 7, 1996%0aHillary Rodham Clinton, the President's wife visits the Manchester Craftsmen's Guild and the Strip District.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 7, 1996%0aThe Austrian Nationality Room opens at the University of Pittsburgh as the 24th nationality classroom.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 17, 1996%0aWilliam Strickland, ceramic artist and director of the Manchester Craftsmen's Guild and the Bidwell Training Center, is honored with a grant of $295,000 by the MacArthur Foundation for his work with the city's youth and unemployed.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 20, 1996%0aPenguins' Center Mario Lemieux wins the Hart Trophy for the third time as the National Hockey Leagues Most Valuable Player.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 20, 1996%0aMark Nordenberg, former Dean of the university's law school, is named Chancellor of the University of Pittsburgh after serving as interim chancellor since August 1, 1995.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 29, 1996%0aA renovated 1898 foundry in Lawrenceville is dedicated as the home of the newly established National Robotics Engineering Consortium which links NASA and the world renowned robotics research department of Carnegie Mellon University in commercial projects for mobile robots.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 31, 1996%0aKurt Angie of Mt Lebanon wins the gold medal in freestyle wrestling at the Olympic Games in Atlanta.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 1, 1996%0aRosa Parks, civil rights heroine, visits Pittsburgh to promote the "Pathways to Freedom" program of workshops on black history for students ages 11 to 17.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 12, 1996%0aRichard Armstrong, chief curator of the Carnegie Museum of Art, is appointed as the museum's 