useum of Natural History.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 15, 1997%0aJared Cohon is named the 8th president of Carnegie Mellon University.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 23, 1997%0aMario Lemieux plays his final game at the Civic Arena, scoring a goal in the 4-1 victory over the Philadelphia Flyers in a Stanley Cup playoff match.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 24, 1997%0aH.J. Heinz Co. Chairman Anthony O'Reilly breaks ground for the new home of the Pittsburgh Public Theater to be built on Penn Avenue and be named the O'Reilly Theater.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 1, 1997%0aThomas J. Kennelly, a 44-year veteran Pittsburgh firefighter who served as Chief of the Bureau of Fire for nine years in the Flaherty and Caliguiri administrations, dies at the age of 87.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 4, 1997%0aDale E. Frederick, former superintendent of Warren Ohio schools, is named superintendent of the Pittsburgh Public Schools.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 1, 1997%0aAfter nearly closing in 1995 due to financial difficulties, the Harvard-Yale-Princeton Club merges with another historic institution, the Pittsburgh Club (founded in 1879), to become the HYP-Pittsburgh Club. "Instead of losing two beloved and venerable institutions, Pittsburgh got the best of both worlds by combining the membership of the two Clubs and keeping a longtime luncheon tradition in old-world elegance alive," said Simin Yazdgerdi Curtis, President of the HYP-Pittsburgh Club, 1997-1998.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 12, 1997%0aFrancisco Cordova and Ricardo Rincon pitch the first combined extra-inning no-hitter in major league history and the third no hit performance in Three Rivers Stadium as the Pirates defeat the Houston Astros 3-0 in 10 innings.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 14, 1997%0aLTV Steel, Pittsburgh's remaining link to its once dominant steel industry, will permanently close its Hazelwood coke plant.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 14, 1997%0aAlbert Fondy is elected to his ninth, two-year term as President of the 38,000 member Pennsylvania Federation of Teachers. Fondy has served continuously since 1967 as President of the Pittsburgh Federation of Teachers and since 1980 as Vice-President of the American Federation of Teachers.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 17, 1997%0aPresident Clinton addresses the 88th NAACP convention being held in Pittsburgh for the first the since 1931.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 21, 1997%0aFred Rogers is granted a Lifetime Achievement Award by the Television Critics Association.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 26, 1997%0aMike Webster is the 14th former Steeler football player to be inducted into the Pro Football Hall of Fame.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 4, 1997%0aCity Council, led by Councilman Sala Udin, creates an independent civilian review board to investigate complaints against city police officers.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 14, 1997%0aRepublican commissioner Bob Crammer and Democratic Commissioner Mike Dawida collaborate to unseat the Republican chairman of the Allegheny County Commissioners Larry Dunn.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 5, 1997%0aPNC Bank announces that it will build a new operations center to provide office space for 5600 employees on the site of the former B & 0 terminal overlooking the Monongahela River.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 12, 1997%0aLandmark America, a Portland, Maine development firm, will turn Armstrong Cork Complex in the Strip District into 300+ apartments with retail stores and restaurants on the first floor.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 13, 1997%0a"Pioneer," a robot developed by CMU's National Robotics Engineering Consortium and Red Zone Robotics, is selected to help clean up the site of the world's worst nuclear accident at Chernobyl, Ukraine.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 16, 1997%0aBill Burns, popular Pittsburgh radio and television broadcaster for 36 years, dies at age 84.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 19, 1997%0aMariss Jansons conducts his first concert as the eighth music director of The Pittsburgh Symphony.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 6, 1997%0aFore Systems Inc., a firm employing 1500 which was founded by CEO Eric Cooper and 3 CMU colleagues in 1990, opens a new $44 million headquarters in Warrendale.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 17, 1997%0aThe Pennsylvania General Assembly authorizes the spending of $16 million for the construction of a 72-mile segment of the bike path which will eventually connect Pittsburgh with Washington D.C.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 23, 1997%0aDana Scott, CMU Professor of Computer Science, Philosophy and Mathematical Logic is awarded a Schrock prize in math a ceremony in Stockholm for his developments in computer science.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 29, 1997%0aJoan Apr, founder of Pittsburgh Public Theater, is inducted as a Distinguished Daughter of Pennsylvania.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 4, 1997%0aTom Murphy is reelected to a second 4-year term as mayor of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 14, 1997%0aRenowned photojournalism pioneer and author Stefan Lorant dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 17, 1997%0aHundreds of Pittsburgh Penguin hockey fans travel to Toronto to witness the ceremonies in which Brian Trottier and Mario Lemieux are inducted into Hockey's Hall of Fame. The 3 year waiting period is waived for Lemieux who retired earlier that year.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 2, 1997%0aAnthony J. F. O'Reilly, chairman and CEO of H.J. Heinz, is stepping down as of April 30, 1998, although he will continue as non-executive chairman until September 2000. William Johnson, currently president, takes over the day to day control of the firm.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 3, 1997%0aPitt's Walt Harris is named college football's Big East Coach of the Year.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 22, 1997%0aFred Rogers is named Pittsburgher of the Year by Pittsburgh Magazine in recognition of his 30 years in public television broadcasting.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 5, 1998%0aBob O'Connor is elected City Council president.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 13, 1998%0aSavio Woo, a researcher with the University of Pittsburgh, is awarded the International Olympics Prize for Sports Science for his work on the treatment of knee injuries.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 16, 1998%0aPNC, Pittsburgh's largest bank, reports its second straight year of record profits, rising above the $1 billion mark for the first time.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 16, 1998%0aMartin G. McGuinn is named chairman and CEO of Mellon Bank effective April 1, replacing Frank Cahouet, who will be retiring at the end of the year.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 2, 1998%0aThe Pittsburgh Zoo, celebrating its centennial this year, announces a $29.5 million expansion.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 2, 1998%0aHenry Steele Commager, a Pittsburgh-born prominent American historian and author of the first chapter of this book, dies in Amherst, Massachusetts at age 95.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 4, 1998%0aMellon Bank announces plans to construct a $100 million operations center on land above the Steel Plaza transit station.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 10, 1998%0aAlcoa. the world's largest producer of aluminum proposes, a $3.8 billion deal to take over Atlanta based Alumax, the Nation's 3rd ranked aluminum producer.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 20, 1998%0aThe 105 year old Phipps Conservatory is renamed Phipps Conservatory and Botanical Gardens as plans are revealed for a $30 million expansion.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 27, 1998%0aDemolition begins at the Greater Pittsburgh drive-in in North Versailles. [Super Wal-Mart will be constructed on site.]%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 15, 1998%0aMartha Rial of the Post Gazette wins a Pulitzer Prize for spot news photography for her photos of Rwandian and Burundian refugees in Tanzania.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 19, 1998%0aMariss Jansons conducts 2048 young musicians from the tri-state area to set the record for the "World's Largest Orchestra" according to the Guinness Book of Records.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 20, 1998%0aHonus Wagner, former player and coach for the Pirates and one of the first 5 players elected to the Baseball Hail of Fame, will be memorialized with a plaque on Mansfield Blvd. in Carnegie where Wagner was born.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 3, 1998%0aKeith Brantly wins the men's division of the Pittsburgh Marathon and U.S. men's National Championship with a new American course record of 2:12:31 for which he earns a $ 100.000 bonus.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 19, 1998%0aAllegheny County voters narrowly approve Home Rule Charter, which changes county government to a single executive and a 15 member county council.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 28, 1998%0aPittsburgh has the highest percentage of women police officers among 100 of the largest law enforcement agencies in the country.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 2, 1998%0aAt least 14 tornadoes rip through the Pittsburgh area from 5:30 to 9:30 PM, hitting hardest in Mt Washington and parts of Shadyside and Squirrel Hill causing power outages and extensive damage by falling trees.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 6, 1998%0aThe ALCOA Foundation Hall of American Indians opens at the Carnegie Museum of Natural History.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 12, 1998%0aCharles H. "Teenie" Harris, famed principal photographer for The Pittsburgh Courier from 1936 to 1975, dies at the age of 89.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 7, 1998%0aPittsburgh hosts the 18th National Veterans Wheelchair games for 600 athletes from 48 states, Puerto Rico and Great Britain.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 23, 1998%0aArletta Scott Williams is named Executive Director of ALCOSAN. Arletta, an engineering graduate of CMU, is the first woman and first African American to serve as Executive Director in the Authority's history.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 31, 1998%0aDistrict Attorney Stephen A. Zappala, Jr. brings to a close Jonny Gammage case. His office will nor appeal a judge's decision dismissing involuntary manslaughter charges against the two policemen in involved in the traffic stop that led to Mr. Gammge's death.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 1, 1998%0aThe Cultural Trust announces that Allegheny Riverfront Park, a project funded by the Vira I. Heinz Endowment and the state, will open in the fall. The two-tier park will run from the Point to the 9th Street Bridge.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 2, 1998%0aThe Thee Rivers Regatta, in a new format of 4 days over one weekend under the new direction of James Roddey, draws 1.5 million spectators. Terry Phipps, executive director of International Outboard Grant Prix, calls the Pittsburgh regatta, "The Indianapolis 500 of the Waterways".%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 8, 1998%0aThe two Shadyside arts festivals -- one on Shady Ave., the other on Ellsworth -- attract 300,001 people.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 22, 1998%0aThe County 911 System begins operations at Lexington Technology Park in Point Breeze.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 23, 1998%0aMark McGuire hits homerun 53 at Three Rivers Stadium.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember, 1998%0aHilda Pang Fu is selected by the Pittsburgh Regional Alliance to head a program to promote Pittsburgh, the Pittsburgh Regional Champions.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 4, 1998%0aSammy Sosa hits homerun 57 at Three Rivers Stadium.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 7, 1998%0aU.S. Census Bureau finds that 19.2%25 of residents of Pittsburgh and the six surrounding counties are "stayers" They live in the same house for 30 or more years.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 15, 1998%0aTank barge leaks 3100 gallons of diesel fuel into the Monongahela near Donora, PA.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 2, 1998%0aIn a national survey released by the Land Grant Trust Alliance, Pennsylvania ranks second in conservation acres with 348.000 acres from 75 land trusts. 236,000 of the acres were designated by the Western Pennsylvania Conservancy. The only state with more is California.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 7, 1998%0aRichard Cyert dies at 77. Cyert served as president of CMU for two decades. Cyert's vision took CMU from a struggling college to a competitive university.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 14, 1998%0aThe Nobel Prize in Chemistry is awarded to John A. Pople, professor emeritus of CMU, for his work using mathematical calculations to predict the properties of molecules.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 15, 1998%0a100 CEO's visit Pittsburgh for the 8th Annual Fortune 500 Forum.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 6, 1998%0aLazarus opens its new downtown store at 5th Avenue and Wood Street.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 9, 1998%0aThe Chatham College Arboretum, which preserves 37 acres of historic landscape, is officially recognized by the American Association of Botanical Gardens and Arboretums.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 12, 1998%0aThe Tibetan Dali Lama visits Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 19, 1998%0aEast Liberty's Nabisco plant shuts down.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 30, 1998%0aDorothy Miller, publisher of "Rich/Poor Man's Guide to Pittsburgh" notes that there are now 72 outdoor cafes in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 4, 1999%0aHerbert Elish is named Director of Carnegie Library of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 23, 1999%0aThe Bost Building is recognized as a National Landmark for its role as the steelworker's headquarters in the Homestead Strike. August R. Carlino. the executive director of the Steel Industry Heritage Corporation, which owns the Bost Building, is planning a $4 million renovation.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 27, 1999%0aAlbert Miller, founder of Meadowcroft Village and discoverer of Meadowcroft Rock Shelter, dies at age 87.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 29, 1999%0aLeon Anthony Arkus, associated with Carnegie Museum of Art from 1954 to 1980, dies at 53. He was instrumental in planning the Sarah Scaife Gallery and in developing the permanent collection.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 3, 1999%0aPlan B is passed in the state senate. Four new stadiums will be built in Pennsylvania, two in Philadelphia and two in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 4, 1999%0aMichael Douglas is in Pittsburgh filming the movie "Wonder Boys." The movie is based on a book of the same name by University of Pittsburgh graduate, Michael Chabon.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 28, 1999%0aRafael Vinoly's design for the new Convention Center is chosen. The expanded David Lawrence Convention Center will be a tool in revitalizing Pittsburgh and showcasing the riverfront.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch, 1999%0aThe University of Pittsburgh announces that Pitt Stadium will be razed, a convocation and events center will be built in its place, and the Panthers will play football in the new Steelers stadium.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 26, 1999%0aHome Depot breaks ground for a new store in East Liberty on the site of the former Sears store.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 6, 1999%0aGeorge D. Lockhart, a founder of the city's largest law firm, Kirkpatrick & Lockhart, dies at the age of 89. A respected lawyer and man of quiet dignity, he served for many years as a trustee of Chatham College, the University of Pittsburgh and the former Presbyterian University Hospital.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 7, 1999%0aConstruction begins for the $228 million PNC Park, the new home of the Pirates, set to open in 2001. During a public "block party" to celebrate the groundbreaking, the Sixth Street Bridge was renamed the Roberto Clemente Bridge. When this bridge opened in 1928, it was named "the most beautiful bridge erected in U.S. or Canada that year" by the American Institute of Steel Construction.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 8, 1999%0aMaxwell King, former editor of the Philadelphia Inquirer is named as the executive director of the Heinz Endowments, to be effective May 17.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 25, 1999%0aAt the intersection of Center Avenue and Crawford Street, ground is broken for a monument at "Freedom Corner" to honor the struggles and successes of civil rights demonstrators.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 26, 1999%0aFore Systems, a Warrendale networking firm, is bought by London-based General Electric (not related to the Connecticut General Electric Company) for $4.5 billion.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 8, 1999%0aThe Pittsburgh Parks Conservancy raises $135,000 for the Frick Park restoration at its Spring Hat Luncheon.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 18, 1999%0aFormer long term County Commissioner Tom Forester running as an unendorsed candidate easily wins the Democratic nomination for a seat on the new County Council.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 18, 1999%0aRepublican James Roddey and Democrat Cyril Wecht win the nominations for the new position of Allegheny County Executive. County Commissioner Mike Dawida and Larry Dunn were both defeated.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 20, 1999%0aMayor Murphy and about a dozen other cyclists begin a five day bicycle journey from Point State Park to Washington, D.C. to promote Rails to Trails.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 14, 1999%0aThe Pittsburgh Board of Public Education announces that Dr. Helen Faison will serve as Interim Superintendent during the search for a person to fill the position left vacant when Dr. Dale Frederick accepted a position at Arizona. Faison began teaching for the district in 1950 and retired as a deputy superintendent in 1993. The past four years Dr. Faison has served as Dean of Education at Chatham College.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 18, 1999%0aA crowd of 3000 attends the groundbreaking for the new $262 million stadium, new home of the Steelers and the University of Pittsburgh Panthers.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 23, 1999%0aUniversity of Pittsburgh graduate, John Peterson and his wife make the largest individual gift ever to the university. The gift will be used for the new convocation center which will be called the John M. and Gertrude E. Peterson Events Center.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 23, 1999%0aThe second International Trails & Greenways Conference sponsored by the Rails-to-Trails Conservancy is held in Pittsburgh. The conference is expected to attract 1000 participants from 20 countries. According to Rails-to-Trails President, David Burwell, "the city is recreating itself on a foundation of trails and Greenways, making Pittsburgh one of America's most livable communities."%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 24, 1999%0aJaromir Jagr receives the Hart Trophy as the league's most valuable player.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 24, 1999%0aMario Lemieux's plan for Penguin ownership is approved by Federal Bankruptcy Court.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 30, 1999%0aMay Company purchases the Mellon bank Building on Smithfield Street for use as a Lord and Taylor Department Store.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 10, 1999%0aA 3000 pound fiberglass replica of Diplodocus carnegii, named after Andrew Carnegie, is dedicated on the grounds of the Carnegie Museum in honor of the 100th anniversary of the discovery of the dinosaur.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 11, 1999%0aThe LTV Steel stacks are toppled with dynamite. The demolition clears the site for a riverfront redevelopment.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 11, 1999%0aMayor Murphy announces a blue ribbon Riverlife Task Force, co-chaired by Alcoa Chairman Paul O'Neill and Post-Gazette editor, John G. Craig Jr. The task force will make recommendations regarding future development along Pittsburgh's riverfronts.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 12, 1999%0aLTV Hazelwood Steel Plant demolition begins. The last steel mill in the city of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 21, 1999%0aDrought emergency declared in fifty-five counties in Pennsylvania.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 29, 1999%0aThird highest rainfall in Pittsburgh area. 3.48 inches of rain are recorded at Greater Pittsburgh International Airport.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 5, 1999%0aWest Penn Hospital and Allegheny General Hospital agree to combine and operate under the name of West Penn Allegheny Health System.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 20, 1999%0aPaul Spadafora, a McKees Rocks native, wins the International Boxing Federation lightweight championship by beating Israel Cardona.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 30, 1999%0aThe Drake Line, part of the South Hills trolley system since 1936 is discontinued.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember, 1999%0aPalazzo Nudo, a sculpture by Alexander Brodsky is installed at Seventh and Penn.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 3, 1999%0aMario Lemieux headed financial to group formally acquire the Pittsburgh Penguins.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 8, 1999%0aViacom purchases Columbia Broadcasting System, the successor to the Westinghouse Corporation (owner of KDKA).%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 9, 1999%0aHomestead Waterfront (shopping and entertainment) opens on the former site of United States Steel Homestead Works at a cost of three hundred million dollars.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 10, 1999%0aLTV announces the purchase of Copperweld Steel and plans permanent headquarters in Pittsburgh for expanding steel tube business.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 11, 1999%0aWestmoreland County Airport renamed the Arnold Palmer Airport.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 5, 1999%0aTed Papp named to succeed Eddie Gilbert as Pittsburgh Public Theatre artistic director.