nies make Fortune 500: Alcoa at No. 88 with $22.8 billion revenue; H.J. Heinz Co. at 206 with $9.4 billion; PPG Industries at 237 with $8.1 billion; PNC Financial Services Group at 269 with $6.9 billion; and Mellon Financial Corp. at 398 with $4 billion.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 10, 2002%0aThe Carnegie Museum of Natural History unveils plans for a $37 million renovation of Dinosaur Hall.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 12, 2002%0aPart of Mon-Fayette Expressway opens between I-70 and Route 51.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 16, 2002%0aCarnegie Library of Pittsburgh presents new logo as part of its first branding campaign in its 107-year history.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 14, 2002%0aFounded in Pittsburgh in 1902 by Chester Garfield Fisher, Fisher Scientific celebrates its 100 year anniversary. His company was the first commercial source of equipment and reagents for the laboratories of western Pennsylvania's booming factories, as America became an industrial nation.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 31, 2002%0aA macro stormburst downs trees and damages buildings from West Mifflin to Lawrenceville. The roof of the Whip (a ride at Kennywood) collapses, killing one.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 20, 2002%0aPresident George W. Bush names Lynn Swann, former Pittsburgh Steelers wide receiver, chairman of the President's Council on Physical Fitness and Sports.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 24, 2002%0aHard Rock Caf Pittsburgh opens in Station Square.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 1, 2002%0aAllegheny General Hospital opens its new $30 million cancer center, a five-story 100,000 square foot facility.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 24, 2002%0aNine miners at Quecreek Mine near Shanksville, Somerset County become trapped 240 feet underground.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 27, 2002%0aAll nine miners are rescued from Quecreek Mine.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 3, 2002%0aJohn Stallworth, former Pittsburgh Steeler, and Jim Kelly, a native of East Brady, Pa., are inducted into the Professional Football Hall of Fame.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 3, 2002%0aMay Department Stores Company closes Kaufmann's Pittsburgh business headquarters and moves it to Boston.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 11, 2002%0aUS Airways files a Chapter 11 bankruptcy petition.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 19, 2002%0aChildren's Hospital of Pittsburgh to relocate to the former St. Francis Medical Center in Lawrenceville.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 7, 2002%0aSt. Francis Health System in Lawrenceville closes after 137 years.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 30, 2002%0aAfter five years of renovations, the Fort Pitt Bridge and Tunnel construction project is completed.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 11, 2002%0aUniversity of Pittsburgh Medical Center Hillman Cancer Center opens in Shadyside named for the generous donation of Henry L. Hillman and the Hillman Foundation.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 16, 2002%0aUnited States Steel to sell Clairton Works.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 31, 2002%0aThe Pittsburgh law firm Reed Smith approves a merger with Crosby, Heafey, Roach & May of California, putting it among the 20 largest law firms in the world.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 17, 2002%0aA team of western Pennsylvanians began their walk across Antarctica to the South Pole in an awareness and fund-raising effort called "The Ultimate Walk to Cure Diabetes."%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 18, 2002%0aElephant kills handler, Michael Gatti, at the Pittsburgh Zoo.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 19, 2002%0aThe Buhl Foundation gives the largest single gift in its history ($3 million grant) to the Carnegie Science Center to endow the Science Center's director position.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 26, 2002%0aPittsburgh selected as site for the nineteenth Senior Olympics in 2005.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 7, 2002%0aPaul O'Neill, former head of Alcoa, resigns as and Secretary of the Treasury of the United States.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 10, 2002%0aGrok Technology and 3 Rivers Connect launch Grok Secure Net, Pittsburgh's first secure wireless network in the Oakland area.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 10, 2002%0aUPMC South Side Hospital opens new digital operating rooms with learning center for orthopedic surgery.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 16, 2002%0aA.J. Palumbo, local philanthropist who donated millions of dollars to Roman Catholic colleges in the area, dies at 96.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 20, 2002%0aHeinz Company merges with Del Monte Foods. Heinz now owns 75%25 of Del Monte and has spun off some of its products to them. Del Monte takes over the North Side plant.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 23, 2002%0aFreeMarkets Inc. chairman and CEO Glen Meakem is appointed chairman of the Historical Society of Western Pennsylvania board of directors.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 3, 2003%0aAlcoa Business Service Center on the North Side is completed.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 22, 2003%0aParent company of the New Pittsburgh Courier acquired by Real Times Inc. of Chicago.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 9, 2003%0aPennsylvania state stores allow Sunday sales of wine and liquor. Sunday sales had been illegal since before prohibition.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 27, 2003%0aFred Rogers, host of the children's program "Mr. Roger's Neighborhood" on the Public Broadcasting System, dies at age 74.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 6, 2003%0aGroundbreaking for the University of Pittsburgh Biomedical Tower 3, which will house the Pittsburgh Institute for Neurodegenerative Diseases.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 12, 2003%0aBayer Corporation debuts its newly remodeled polymer research center "Americas Technical Center" in Robinson Township, one of only three such centers in the world.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 1, 2003%0aUS Airways receives financing to emerge from bankruptcy.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 2, 2003%0aUnited States Steel buys Sertid, Serbia's largest steel company.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 17, 2003%0aUnited States Steel acquires bankrupt National Steel for $1.5 billion.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 23, 2003%0aNick Perry, broadcast pioneer and host of "Bowling for Dollars," dies at age 86. His career ended when he helped rig the Pennsylvania Lottery in 1980.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 8, 2003%0aThe Historic Isaac Meason Mansion in Fayette County is put up for sale on eBay. There were no bids high enough for the sale.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 13, 2003%0aThe Heinz Endowments give Saint Vincent College funds for