ector," a project to construct a light-rail tunnel beneath the Allegheny River connecting Downtown to the North Shore.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 12, 2004%0aUS Airways reached an agreement with the Air Transportation Stabilization Board to revise the terms of the $1 billion loan that was made to US Airways upon its emergence from Chapter 11 on March 31, 2003.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 13, 2004%0aEbenezer Baptist Church, a presence in the Hill District community for 131 years, is destroyed by fire. Two firefighters die fighting the blaze.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 27, 2004%0aDam at Locks and Dam 2 at Braddock on the Monongahela River is removed by a controlled explosion as part of the renovation of the Monongahela River locks and dams.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 28, 2004%0aWQED, the nation's first educational television channel, marks their 50th anniversary in broadcasting.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 1, 2004%0aEllsworth Brown resigns as president of Carnegie Museums of Pittsburgh and Carnegie Library of Pittsburgh, a position he held since 1993.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 16, 2004%0aThe National Rifle Association (NRA) holds their first annual meeting in Pittsburgh at the new David L. Lawrence Convention Center.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 25, 2004%0aThe Pittsburgh Steelers select Ben Roethlisberger from Miami University (Ohio) as their number one choice in the NFL football draft.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 6, 2004%0aThe University Club sells its 81-year-old building in Oakland to the University of Pittsburgh for $3.1 million.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 14, 2004%0aThe Downtown Lazarus-Macy's department store closes.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 24, 2004%0aMariss Jansons conducts his last concert as director of the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 29, 2004%0aJosie Carey, who hosted the television show on WQED that would later become Mr. Rogers' Neighborhood, dies at age 73.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 2, 2004%0aGlobal aluminum company ALCOA plans to outsource 130 jobs, including 70 IT positions, to an India-based services provider as part of a move to reduce costs.%0a%0a%