lp fund construction of a new building for the School of Computer Science.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 17, 2004%0aRemnants of Hurricane Ivan dump up to nine inches of rain across Western Pennsylvania. Thousands of homes and businesses in Allegheny County and surrounding counties were severely damaged or destroyed.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 1, 2004%0aState historical marker placed at the site of the former home of the Pittsburgh Courier in the Hill District in honor of the late legendary reporter Frank E. Bolden.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 12, 2004%0aCarnegie Mellon University professor Finn Kydland shares the 2004 Nobel Prize in Economics with Edward C. Prescott, a former CMU professor.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 22, 2004%0aMembers of the University Club agree to dissolve the 114-year-old club. Founded in 1890 and originally located Downtown, the club was chartered to bring together college graduates who shared an affinity for literature, art and other culture. It later moved to Oakland for closer proximity to the city's college campuses and into its present building, designed by architect Henry Hornbostel in 1923.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 6, 2004%0aAnchor Glass Container Company in Connellsville closes eliminating 340 jobs.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 13, 2004%0aSenator John Heinz Pittsburgh Regional History Center opens the Western Pennsylvania Sports Museum and the Smithsonian wing of the original building.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 15, 2004%0aSarah Heinz House Boys & Girls Club breaks ground on an $8.7 million expansion project to increase the amount of programming offered and provide a new gymnasium and indoor pool.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 20, 2004%0aA court-appointed trustee operating the Glenshaw Glass Company in Shaler orders the 109-year-old bottle maker to cease production.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 2, 2004%0aDuquesne University announces plans for $70 million in construction projects, including retail stores, a pharmacy or grocery store, high-rise housing and buildings for academic use, across from the campus on 