med the Andy Warhol Bridge. The bridge spans the Allegheny River between Downtown and the North Side where the Andy Warhol Museum is located.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 25, 2005%0aThe Frick Building, constructed by Henry Clay Frick in 1902, is bought by Rugby Realty Company, Inc. of New Jersey for an undisclosed sum.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 1, 2005%0aPhipps Conservatory opens its new environmentally-friendly Welcome Center designed by IKM Architects of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 10, 2005%0aUniversity of Pittsburgh hosts the 50th anniversary celebration of the Salk polio vaccine.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 18, 2005%0aPete Flaherty, former mayor of Pittsburgh from 1970 to 1977, dies at age 80.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 19, 2005%0aPittsburgh Parks Conservancy receives a $5 million check from Governor Ed Rendell to help transform Schenley Plaza in Oakland from a parking lot into a park.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 28, 2005%0aUniversity of Pittsburgh Medical Center and IBM enter into an eight year agreement worth $420 million to upgrade medical technologies and health information systems.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 3, 2005%0aSouthwest Airlines begins service at Pittsburgh International Airport.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 13, 2005%0aPNC Financial Services Group Inc. acquires Riggs National Corp. of Washington, D.C. for $652 million.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 17, 2005%0aDavid M. Hillenbrand is appointed as president of the Carnegie Museums of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 3, 2005%0aPittsburgh welcomes the 2005 Senior Olympics and hosts more than 10,000 athletes competing in 18 sports during the next two weeks.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 6, 2005%0aThe 64-story US Steel Tower building is sold at sheriff's sale for $1.35 million as part of a plan to shift title from 600 Grant Street Associates to 600 GS Prop GP LLC without exchanging money.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 20, 2005%0aThe University of Pittsburgh Cancer Institute and UPMC Cancer Centers receive a $20 million donation from Henry and Elsie Hillman.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 21, 2005%0aH. J. Heinz Company acquires the HP Foods Group, which includes the Lea & Perrins brand Worcestershire sauce, for $855 million.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 22, 2005%0aThe Byham Theatre hosts the premiere of the Zombie horror film "Land of the Dead."%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 22, 2005%0aThe Pittsburgh Penguins win the draft lottery and select teenage sensation Sidney Crosby as their first overall pick.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 24, 2005%0aMark Roosevelt, great-grandson of President Theodore Roosevelt, is selected by the Pittsburgh Public Schools to be the next superintendent.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 28, 2005%0aKaufmann's Department Store announces that Federated Department Stores Inc. will convert Kaufmann's to its Macy's brand.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 1, 2005%0aPittsburgh Ballet Theatre announces it will replace the musicians of the Pittsburgh Ballet Theatre Orchestra with recorded music for its 2005-2006 season.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 7, 2005%0aDan Marino is inducted into the National Football League Hall of Fame. He played for the Central Catholic Vikings in high school and the University of Pittsburgh Panthers before his professional career.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 17, 2005%0aGateway Center is flooded when a 36-inch water main breaks in Downtown.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 26, 2005%0aThe 911th Airlift Wing becomes part of a regional homeland security center after surviving a final base closing vote.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 6, 2005%0aAfter leading the Pittsburgh Pirates to a 55-81 season standing, manager Lloyd McClendon is fired while Pete Mackanin completes the rest of the season as manager.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 7, 2005%0aA permanent memorial named Crescent of Embrace is chosen to honor the passengers and crew of Flight 93 which crashed in Shanksville, PA on September 11, 2001.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 26, 2005%0aUS Airways merges with America West Airlines to become the nation's largest discount airline.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 28, 2005%0aThe Rolling Stones perform a sold-out concert at PNC Park.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 2, 2005%0aAugust Wilson, an African-American playwright who won two Pulitzer Prizes and grew up in the Hill District, dies at the age of 60.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 4, 2005%0aCMU alumnus John Hall shares the Nobel Prize in physics.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 11, 2005%0aPittsburgh Pirates name Jim Tracy as their next manager.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 8, 2005%0aBob O'Connor is elected mayor of Pittsburgh, replacing Tom Murphy.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 10, 2005%0aHarris N. Ferris is hired as the executive director of the Pittsburgh Ballet Theatre.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 19, 2005%0aThe last original map of Pittsburgh is sold at a Philadelphia auction for $55,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 24, 2005%0aAfter falling to the West Virginia Mountaineers, the University of Pittsburgh football team finishes its inaugural season under head coach Dave Wannstedt with a 5-6 record.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 7, 2005%0aFaced with a $2.5 million delinquent sewage bill, Pittsburgh Brewing Company files for bankruptcy to keep the city from shutting off its water supply.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 11, 2005%0aMichel Thierrien is named the next head coach of the Pittsburgh Penguins after the firing of Ed Olczyk.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 19, 2005%0aPNC Financial Services Group announces plans to build a 30-story building in Downtown.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 3, 2006%0aBob O'Connor (Democrat) is inaugurated as mayor of the City of Pittsburgh replacing Tom Murphy, who previously served three terms.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 10, 2006%0aPittsburgh Zoo & PPG Aquarium purchases land in Somerset County for care and breeding of large animals.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 5, 2006%0aThe Pittsburgh Steelers win Super Bowl XL in Detroit with a score of 21 to 10 over the Seattle Seahawks. This is the fifth Super Bowl win for the Steelers.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 7, 2006%0aAn estimated crowd of 250,000 celebrate the Steelers win during a parade in Downtown Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 17, 2006%0aK. Leroy Irvis, former Speaker of the House of Pennsylvania, dies. He was the first African-American to serve in this position in any state legislature in the United States.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 3, 2006%0aMarshall Goldberg, an All-American at Pitt on the 1936 team that won the Rose Bowl and the 1937 team that won the National Collegiate Championship, dies.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 9, 2006%0aThe Carnegie Library of Pittsburgh -- Allegheny Regional branch on the North Side is struck by lightning, forcing the building to permanently close to the public.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 23, 2006%0aPittsburgh's Ninth Street Bridge spanning the Allegheny River is renamed the Rachel Carson Bridge. Born in Springdale, Carson was a marine biologist and nature writer whose writings are often credited with launching the global environmental movement.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 17, 2006%0aThe Most Reverand Donald Wuerl, bishop of the Catholic Diocese of Pittsburgh, is named the archbishop of the Diocese of Washington, D.C.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 25, 2006%0aPittsburgh Public School board approves plan to close 22 schools.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 5, 2006%0aA Macquarie-led consortium announces plan to acquire Duquesne Light Holdings for $1.59 billion.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 11, 2006%0aPittsburgh hosts the Major League Baseball All-Star Game for the second time. The American League beat the National League by a score of 3-2.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 1, 2006%0aMayor Bob O'Connor dies at 61 from a rare form of brain cancer only seven months into his term. Luke Ravenstahl, City Council President, is sworn in as new mayor.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 16, 2006%0aFive Duquesne University basketball players are shot on campus after a dance in the worst act of random violence to strike a major college sports program.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 19, 2006%0aRoute 65 in Kilbuck Township is closed after a major landslide resulted from the construction of a Wal-Mart on the site of the former Dixmont State Hospital. The slide also covers the tracks of the Norfolk Southern Railroad.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 4, 2006%0aMellon Financial merges with the Bank of New York.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 20, 2006%0aState Gaming Commission awards Pittsburgh casino rights to PITG Gaming for its Majestic Star casino on the North Shore.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 5, 2007%0aBill Cowher resigns as head coach of the Pittsburgh Steelers after fifteen seasons.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 22, 2007%0aMike Tomlin announced as the new head coach of the Pittsburgh Steelers; he is the first African-American to hold this position within the Steelers organization.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 24, 2007%0aViennese Manfred Honeck named as new conductor of the Pittsburgh Symphony.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 5, 2007%0aA failed expansion joint causes a slab from the David L. Lawrence Convention Center to crash onto 10th Street leading to the replacement and repair of fifty other beams.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 21, 2007%0aPittsburgh is chosen for US Airways' new $25 million flight operations control center, which will employ 600 positions.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 23, 2007%0aFormer Allegheny County Sheriff Pete DeFazio is sentenced to six months of house arrest for permitting the pressuring of county employees to contribute to his campaign fund.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 13, 2007%0aPittsburgh Penguins agree to remain in Pittsburgh with a 30-year lease and a new $290 million arena built in the Lower Hill.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 22, 2007%0aAnother rock slide, due to warm and wet weather, closes Route 28 South.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 9, 2007%0aUniversity of Pittsburgh Medical Center announces that it will relocate its headquarters from Oakland to the US Steel Tower Downtown.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 11, 2007%0aMayor Luke Ravenstahl and Allegheny County Executive Dan Onorato were present when building demolition began for new Pittsburgh Penguins arena in the Lower Hill.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 16, 2007%0aTwo students from Pittsburgh were injured in the massacre on the Virginia Tech campus that killed 32 people.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 26, 2007%0aPittsburgh named the most livable city in the United States by Places Rated Almanac.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 1, 2007%0aAllegheny County's new smoking ban goes into effect with waivers for small venues; the ban is later revoked by an appeals court.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 15, 2007%0aUniversity of Pittsburgh announces $1 billion plan to update facilities and build new buildings.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 30, 2007%0aPittsburgh Planning Commission approves master plans for the casino on the North Shore.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 12, 2007%0aFive children, home alone and playing with matches, die in house fire in Lincoln-Larimer neighborhood of Pittsburgh; the mother is later charged with manslaughter and endangerment.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 19, 2007%0aDollar Bank in Pittsburgh leads the region in allowing customers to perform bank transactions via text messaging from cell phones.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 1, 2007%0aMellon Bank merges with Bank of New York to become Bank of New York Mellon.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 18, 2007%0aThe Reverend David A. Zubik, Roman Catholic bishop of Green Bay, Wisconsin and native of Ambridge, is named to head the Diocese of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 26, 2007%0aRespironics Inc., maker of sleep therapy devices, announces plans to build a $32 million manufacturing plant in Upper Burrell which will employ 575 workers.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 9, 2007%0aTrio of storms cause flooding in Millvale, Etna and Sharpsburg.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 17, 2007%0aThe Diocese of Pittsburgh announces settlement of lawsuits by 32 plaintiffs for sexual assault by priests for $1.25 million.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 8, 2007%0aRecord high temperature of 87 degrees in Pittsburgh; previous high of 86 degrees in 1916.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 15, 2007%0aThe merger of the University of Pittsburgh Medical Center and Mercy Hospital of Pittsburgh was cleared by federal regulators preserving the last Catholic hospital in Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 22, 2007%0aRichard K. Mellon Foundation awards Carnegie Mellon University $25 million for bio-sciences programs.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 31, 2007%0aAs part of a reorganization of the city high schools, plans are announced to close Schenley High School due to asbestos and deteriorating infrastructure.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 6, 2007%0aLuke Ravenstahl elected in his own right to finish Bob O'Connors's term as mayor.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 13, 2007%0aPittsburgh City Councilwoman Twanda Carlisle pleads no contest to charges for taking $43,000 in kickbacks and resigns her seat on council.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 20, 2007%0aThe 31st Street Bridge reopens after a $27 million, two year renovation.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 1, 2007%0aUnited States Steel commits $1 billion to upgrade the Clairton Coke Works.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 5, 2007%0aAllegheny County Council votes to enact a 10%25 drink tax on poured alcoholic beverages and a $2 per day rental car tax to help finance the Port Authority.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 11, 2007%0aSpanish company Parques Reunidos announces plans to purchase Kennywood, Idlewild, Sandcastle and other properties from Kennywood Entertainment of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 2008%0aFour years after it was closed to save money, the Pittsburgh West End police station reopens.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 1, 2008%0aAllegheny County's 10 percent poured drink tax goes into effect.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 3, 2008%0aUniversity of Pittsburgh Medical Center incorporates Mercy Hospital into the system creating UPMC Mercy.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 5, 2008%0aIn the first round of AFC playoffs, the Steelers lose to Jacksonville, 31-29.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 4, 2008%0aFormer Pittsburgh City Coucilwoman Twanda Carlisle receives a sentence of one to two years imprisonment for taking kickbacks in excess of $43,000.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 8, 2008%0aThe deck of the Birmingham Bridge drops eight inches forcing thousands of motorists to take alternate routes while the bridge is closed for repairs.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 20, 2008%0aAn Allegheny County jury convicts Patrick Stollar, landscaper, of first-degree murder for the strangling and stabbing of Jean Heck, 78, in her Upper St. Clair home in 2003.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 27, 2008%0aBeloved Pittsburgh sportscaster, Myron Cope, dies from respiratory failure.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 12, 2008%0aThe Duquesne Men's basketball team ends its first winning season since 1993-94.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 18, 2008%0aRespironics Inc., a Murrysville-based manufacturer of sleep-therapy and breathing-aid devices, is acquired by Royal Philips Electronics for $4.9 billion.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 20, 2008%0aThe city county Sports & Exhibition Authority agrees to buy and relocate Beth Hamedrash Hagodol synagogue in the Hill District for $5.5 million as the final step in clearing the area for the Penguin's new hockey arena.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 24, 2008%0aFor the first time in its program's history, the Pitt women's basketball team advances to the Sweet 16 by besting Baylor.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 8, 2008%0aAfter jurors announced that they were hopelessly deadlocked, a federal judge declares a mistrial in the corruption case against Cyril H. Wecht.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 9, 2008%0aA state Ethics Commission investigation into receipt of gifts from an advertising executive who does business with the city results in the resignation of Mayor Ravenstahl's press secretary, Alecia Sirk, and forces her husband, Pat Ford, to take a paid leave of absence from his position as executive director of the Urban Redevelopment Authority.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 23, 2008%0aOfficials report that a Romare Bearden mural located in a Downtown Port Authority subway station that is to be demolished as part of the North Shore expansion is appraised at $15 million.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 24, 2008%0aIn Somerset Township, a tractor-trailer slams into a van from a Bentleyville group home for mentally disabled adults killing five.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 26, 2008%0aThe Pittsburgh International Children's Theater and the Pittsburgh Cultural Trust agree to a merger.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 2, 2008%0aDick's Sporting Goods announces its sponsorship of the 2009 Pittsburgh Marathon.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 3, 2008%0a"Life on Mars: The 55th Carnegie International" opens at the Carnegie Museum of Art located in Oakland.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 10, 2008%0aManfred Honeck, the incoming music director for the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra, makes his first recording with the symphony.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 18, 2008%0aThe Penguins beat the Philadelphia Flyers and advance to the Stanley Cup final.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 23, 2008%0aThe $500 million RiverParc project, a plan to build condominiums, townhouses and a four-star hotel along the Allegheny River, has been indefinitely delayed according to the Pittsburgh Cultural Trust.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 28, 2008%0aPittsburgh judge fines two Oakland landlords over $460,000 for years of neglect of building and fire code violations.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 2, 2008%0aArmy Specialist Ross McGinnis, 19, who died in Iraq when he threw himself onto a grenade, thus saving his comrades, is awarded the Medal of Honor posthumously at a White House ceremony.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 13, 2008%0aA statewide smoking ban, prohibiting smoking in 95 percent of Pennsylvania workplaces and public places including restaurants, is signed by Governor Ed Rendell.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 15, 2008%0aThe Carnegie Museum of Natural History in Oakland opens "T.rex vs. T.rex", the final phase of its $36 million renovation of the Hall of Dinosaurs .%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 6, 2008%0aNate McLouth, Pirates center fielder, is named to the National League All-Star team.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 10, 2008%0aThe first of two tubes to be bored under the Allegheny River for the Port Authority's North Shore Connector light-rail project is completed.%0a%0a%0a%0aJuly 18, 2008%0aThe Squirrel Hill Theatre and the former Poli's Restaurant, two neighborhood landmarks, will be demolished to make way for a $50 million project that includesretail stores, condominiums, a hotel and restaurant.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 14, 2008%0aState gambling regulators approve the takeover by an investment group led by Neil Bluhm, a Chicago billionaire, of the North Shore casino project to avoid possible foreclosure of the casino site.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 3, 2008%0aThe so-called East End Rapist, Keith O. Wood of Highland Park, receives an 80 to 160 year prison sentence.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 11, 2008%0aThe closed St. George Crystal Ltd. Plant in Jeannette is acquired for $2.75 million at a Westmoreland County sheriff's auction by Pittsburgh businessman, William A. Kelman. Kelman previously rescued L.E. Smith Glass of Mt. Pleasant and the former Glenshaw Glass of Shaler.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 27, 2008%0aManfred Honeck begins his tenure as music director of the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 1, 2008%0aThe long time voice of the Pirates, Lanny Frattare, announces his retirement.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 24, 2008%0aDue to insubordinate comments following an overtime scandal in his department, Pittsburgh Public Works Director, Guy Costa, is suspended without pay for four days.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 24, 2008%0aPNC Financial Services Group announces plans to buy the troubled National City Corporation for $5.6 billion.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 14, 2008%0aL.L. Bean, the famous catalog retailer, opens a store at Ross Park Mall.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 19, 2008%0aThirty-three year old FBI Special Agent Samuel Hicks was fatally shot during a drug raid in Indiana Township.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 25, 2008%0aThe Pittsburgh Cultural Trust takes over the management of the Three Rivers Arts Festival, formerly run by the Carnegie Museums of Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 28, 2008%0aPitt wins the Backyard Brawl against West Virginia, 19-15.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 2, 2008%0aPittsburgh City Council votes in a bill that would fine all gun owners who do not report lost or stolen weapons within 24 hours.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 2, 2008%0aAllegheny County Council votes to reduce the 10 percent poured drink tax to 7 percent.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 6, 2009%0aAlcoa, a Pittsburgh based aluminum manufacturer, announced they will have to cut 13,500 jobs locally and globally due to the economy.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 18, 2009%0aFor the third time in the season, the Pittsburgh Steelers beat the Baltimore Ravens, 23-14, to win the AFC Championship.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 21, 2009%0aDue to demands of the state Insurance Department, health insurers Highmark, Inc. of Pittsburgh and Independence Blue Cross in Philadelphia dismissed their proposed merger.%0a%0a%0a%0aJanuary 25, 2009%0aFranco Harris unveils an "Immaculate Reception" statue at the Western Pennsylvania Sports Museum.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 1, 2009%0aThe Steelers claim their record sixth Super Bowl title against the Arizona Cardinals, 27-23.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 3, 2009%0aSteelers fans, numbering around 350,000, horde a mile-long parade route welcoming home the Steelers after winning Super Bowl XLIII.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 16, 2009%0aThe Pitt basketball team wins its first game against a No. 1 ranked program, the University of Connecticut.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 16, 2009%0aStanley Grumberg, age 81, passed away. He was the chairman of J.J. Gumberg Co., a real estate development firm that controlled four of the 25 largest retail centers in the Pittsburgh area.%0a%0a%0a%0aFebruary 27, 2009%0aThe music director of the River City Brass Band, Denis Colwell, announces his resignation.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch, 2009%0aFor only the second time in 53 years, the Pittsburgh Folk Festival had to be canceled due to financial problems.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 12, 2009%0aPPG Industries Inc. stated the company would cut 2,500 jobs globally, including some at the Downtown corporate headquarters.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 17, 2009%0aSteelers owner, Dan Rooney, was nominated by President Obama to be the ambassador to Ireland.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 23, 2009%0aThe NFL names three new partners in the Steelers ownership group: Bruce V. Rauner, chairman of GTCR Golder Rauner; Hall of Famer and former Steelers player John Stallworth, president and CEO of Genesis II; and the Varischetti family.%0a%0a%0a%0aMarch 27, 2009%0aUniversity of Pittsburgh's Men's basketball team makes it to the Elite Eight for the first time in history of the 64-team NCAA "March Madness" tournament field.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 2, 2009%0aU.S. Steel Corp. indefinitely suspends its $1.1 billion modernization of its Clairton coke plant due to the global recession.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 2, 2009%0aHolly Childs is named executive director of Pittsburgh's Green Building Alliance.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 4, 2009%0aEric G. Kelly, Stephen J. Mayhle and Paul J. Sciullo II, three Pittsburgh police officers, were shot and killed outside a Stanton Heights home by suspect Richard Poplawski, who was waiting for them with an AK-47 and other firearms after his mother made a call to 911.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 11, 2009%0aPenguins star, Evgeni Malkin, achieves his first NHL scoring title, ending with 113 points.%0a%0a%0a%0aApril 20, 2009%0aConstruction began on the first of four nuclear power plants being built in China by Westinghouse Electric Co. of Monroeville.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 2, 2009%0aUPMC opened the new Children's Hospital in Lawrenceville. The old Children's Hospital in Oakland closed that morning.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 2, 2009%0aVirgil Cantini, a University of Pittsburgh professor, passed away at the age of 90. He was named one of the "Hundred Leaders of Tomorrow" by Time magazine in 1953.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 6, 2009%0aThe 110 year-old Davis Avenue Bridge, which connects Bellevue with Brighton Heights, falls onto Wood Run Avenue after explosives separate it from its supports.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 14, 2009%0aChrysler gives 19 Western Pennsylvania automobile dealers their termination notices.%0a%0a%0a%0aMay 15, 2009%0aUpper St. Clair School District named No. 1 in the PBT Honor Roll by the Business Times.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 2, 2009%0aCharges against Dr. Cyril H. Wecht of Squirrel Hill were dropped by federal prosecutors. Wecht was accused of cheating taxpayers and trading unclaimed bodies during his time as the Allegheny County coroner.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 10, 2009%0aPittsburgh named most livable city in the United States and ranked 29th worldwide in a survey by The Economist.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 11, 2009%0aIron City beer reported the 148-year-old brewery was moving from Pittsburgh to a Latrobe brewery that once made Rolling Rock.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 12, 2009%0aThe Penguins earned their third Stanley Cup, defeating the Detroit Red Wings in seven games.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 13, 2009%0aA new, permanent exhibit focusing on robots, called Roboworld, opened at the Carnegie Science Center.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 15, 2009%0aAfter 17 years of waiting, an estimated 375,000 Penguins fans lined up along Grant Street and the Boulevard of the Allies to welcome back the Stanley Cup to Pittsburgh.%0a%0a%0a%0aJune 29, 2009%0aJohn Mullarkey of Monroeville receives a mandatory life sentence for the first-degree murder of a Gateway High School cheerleader, Demi Cuccia, on August 15, 2007.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 2, 2009%0aParts of the Eighth Street Market, a 108-year-old building in Braddock, collapsed onto the street after twenty years of decay.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 4, 2009%0aGeorge Soudini of Scott opened fire in a Collier LA Fitness center aerobics class, killing three women and wounding nine others. Soudini then killed himself.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 5, 2009%0aShareholders of Tollgrade Communications Inc. elect three directors to a telecommunications company in Harmar after a months-long proxy fight.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 7, 2009%0aAfter 17 years of operation, the Open Stage Theatre closes due to the bad economy and accumulated debt.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 9, 2009%0aRivers Casino opens on the North Shore.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 14, 2009%0aHindered by Internet fraud, federal regulators seize Dwelling House Savings & Loan Association, a 119-year-old institution in the Hill District, and hand it over to PNC Bank.%0a%0a%0a%0aAugust 14, 2009%0aDue to funding problems, the Fort Pitt museum closes indefinitely.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 7, 2009%0aThe Pittsburgh Pirates become the first North American professional sports program to post a 17th consecutive losing season.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 17, 2009%0aNamed after the Pulitzer prize-winning playwright born in Pittsburgh, the August Wilson Center opens in the Cultural District.%0a%0a%0a%0aSeptember 24, 2009%0aPresident Obama and other world leaders gathered at the David L. Lawrence Convention Center for the Group of 20 (G-20) economic summit. Nearly 200 people were arrested for protesting.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 6, 2009%0aThe Children's Museum of Pittsburgh received an Institute of Museum and Library Services National Medal, the highest honor for a library and museum.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 7, 2009%0aPittsburgh named No. 1 in the 16th Annual Best Sports Cities in the United States and Canada by Sporting News.%0a%0a%0a%0aOctober 10, 2009%0aRoger Brockenbrough from Mt. Lebanon wins the 75-79 age group in the Ironman Triathlon in Hawaii, grabbing the World Triple Crown in his sport.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 3, 2009%0aPittsburgh Mayor Luke Ravenstahl was re-elected, defeating two independent challengers to win his first full term as mayor.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 7, 2009%0aPNC Financial Services takes over National City Bank, converting over 100 branches to PNC branches.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 7, 2009%0aKen Salazar, Secretary of the Interior, Gov. Ed Rendell and other officials partook in the groundbreaking of a memorial to the passengers and crew of United Airlines Flight 93 near Shanksville in Somerset County who died on September 11, 2001.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 12, 2009%0aJohn Perzel, former House Speaker, is charged with being the mastermind of a "sophisticated criminal strategy" to spend more than $10 million of taxpayers' money on political campaigns. Nine other Republicans were charged as well.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 17, 2009%0aKuhn's Market decides not to go forward with plans to build a government-subsidized grocery store in the Hill District.%0a%0a%0a%0aNovember 23, 2009%0aBaltimore FBI field office is renamed the Sam Hicks Building in honor of Agent Sam Hicks, who was fatally shot while serving a warrant in Indiana Township to Robert Korbe. More than 200 people gathered for the ceremony.%0a%0a%0a%0aDecember 2