diff:1644260127:1578100739:=1c1%0a%3c https://i.imgur.com/WTCZurQ.png%0a---%0a> https://i.imgur.com/7OlUpfb.png%0a9,10c9,10%0a%3c !%25center%25'''Pittsburgh'''%0a%3c %0a---%0a> !%25center%25'''Miami'''%0a> %0a13,20c13,24%0a%3c Pittsburgh is located in the southwest of the state, at the confluence of the Allegheny River and the Monongahela River, forming the Ohio River. Pittsburgh is known both as "the Steel City" for its more than 300 steel-related businesses and as the "City of Bridges" for its 446 bridges. The city features 30 skyscrapers, two inclined railways, a pre-revolutionary fortification and the Point State Park at the confluence of the rivers. The city developed as a vital link of the Atlantic coast and Midwest, as the mineral-rich Allegheny Mountains led to the region being contested by the French and British empires, Virginians, Whiskey Rebels, and Civil War raiders.%0a%3c %0a%3c Aside from steel, Pittsburgh has led in the manufacturing of other important materials  aluminum and glass  and in the petroleum industry. Additionally, it is a leader in computing, electronics, and the automotive industry. For part of the 20th century, Pittsburgh was behind only New York City and Chicago in corporate headquarters employment; it had the most U.S. stockholders per capita. Deindustrialization in the 1970s and 1980s laid off area blue-collar workers as steel and other heavy industries declined, and thousands of downtown white-collar workers also lost jobs when several Pittsburgh-based companies moved out. The population dropped from a peak of 675,000 in 1950 to 370,000 in 1990. However, this rich industrial history left the area with renowned museums, medical centers, parks, research centers, and a diverse cultural district.%0a%3c %0a%3c After the deindustrialization of the mid-20th century, Pittsburgh has transformed into a hub for the health care, education, and technology industries. Pittsburgh is a leader in the health care sector as the home to large medical providers such as University of Pittsburgh Medical Center (UPMC). The area is home to 68 colleges and universities, including research and development leaders Carnegie Mellon University and the University of Pittsburgh. Google, Apple Inc., Bosch, Facebook, Uber, Nokia, Autodesk, Amazon, Microsoft and IBM are among 1,600 technology firms generating $20.7 billion in annual Pittsburgh payrolls. The area has served as the long-time federal agency headquarters for cyber defense, software engineering, robotics, energy research and the nuclear navy. The nation's fifth-largest bank, eight Fortune 500 companies, and six of the top 300 U.S. law firms make their global headquarters in the area, while RAND Corporation (RAND), BNY Mellon, Nova, FedEx, Bayer, and the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) have regional bases that helped Pittsburgh become the sixth-best area for U.S. job growth.%0a%3c %0a%3c In 2015, Pittsburgh was listed among the "eleven most livable cities in the world".[17][18] The Economist's Global Liveability Ranking placed Pittsburgh as the most or second-most livable city in the United States in 2005, 2009, 2011, 2012, 2014 and 2018. The region is a hub for Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design and energy extraction.%0a%3c %0a---%0a> Thousands of years before Europeans arrived, a large portion of south east Florida, including the area where Miami, Florida exists today, was inhabited by Tequestas. The Tequesta (also Tekesta, Tegesta, Chequesta, Vizcaynos) Native American tribe, at the time of first European contact, occupied an area along the southeastern Atlantic coast of Florida. They had infrequent contact with Europeans and had largely migrated by the middle of the 18th century. Miami is named after the Mayaimi, a Native American tribe that lived around Lake Okeechobee until the 17th or 18th century.%0a> %0a> In 1566, Pedro Menndez de Avils was sent by the Spanish monarchy to remove the French from Florida who had already established several colonies. Although Menndez left behind two Jesuit missionaries in an attempt to convert the Tequesta to Roman Catholicism, the tribe were indifferent to their teachings. The Jesuits returned to St. Augustine after a year. Fort Dallas was built in 1836 and functioned as a military base during the Second Seminole War.%0a> %0a> The Miami area was better known as "Biscayne Bay Country" in the early years of its growth. The few published accounts from that period describe the area as a wilderness that held much promise. The area was also characterized as "one of the finest building sites in Florida". After the Great Freeze of 1894, the crops of the Miami area were the only ones in Florida that survived. Julia Tuttle, a local landowner, convinced Henry Flagler, a railroad tycoon, to expand his Florida East Coast Railway to Miami. On July 28, 1896, Miami was officially incorporated as a city with a population of just over 300.%0a> %0a> Miami prospered during the 1920s, but weakened when the real-estate bubble burst in 1925, which was shortly followed by the 1926 Miami Hurricane and the Great Depression in the 1930s. When World War II began, Miami played an important role in the battle against German submarines due to its location on the southern coast of Florida. The war helped to increase Miami's population to almost half a million. After Fidel Castro rose to power in 1959, many Cubans emigrated to Miami, further increasing the population. In the 1980s and 1990s, various crises struck South Florida, among them the Arthur McDuffie beating and the subsequent riot, drug wars, Hurricane Andrew, and the Elin Gonzlez affair. Despite these, Miami remains a major international, financial, and cultural center.%0a> %0a> The city's name is derived from the Miami River, which is ultimately derived from the Mayaimi people who lived in the area at the time of European colonization.%0a> %0a> Though spelled the same in English, the Florida city's name has nothing to do with the Miami people who lived in a completely different part of North America.%0a> %0a23,91c27,74%0a%3c !%25center%25'''Early colonization (17471763)'''%0a%3c %0a%3c The first Europeans arrived in the 1710s as traders. Michael Bezallion was the first to describe the forks of the Ohio in a manuscript in 1717, and later that year European traders established posts and settlements in the area. Europeans first began to settle in the region in 1748, when the first Ohio Company, a Virginian land speculation company, won a grant of 200,000 acres in the upper Ohio Valley. From a post at present-day Cumberland, Maryland, the company began to construct an 80-mile wagon road to the Monongahela River employing a Delaware Indian chief named Nemacolin and a party of settlers headed by Capt. Michael Cresap to begin widening the track into a road. It mostly followed the same route as an ancient Amerindian trail which is now known as Nemacolin's Trail. The river crossing and flats at Redstone creek, was the earliest point and shortest distance for the descent of a wagon road. Later in the war, the site fortified as Fort Burd (now Brownsville) was one of several possible destinations. Another alternative was the divergent route that became Braddock's Road a few years later through present-day New Stanton. In the event, the colonists did not succeed in improving the Amerindian path to a wagon road much beyond the Cumberland Narrows pass before they were confronted by hostile Native Americans. The colonists later mounted a series of expeditions in order to accomplish piecemeal improvements to the track.%0a%3c %0a%3c The nearby Native American community of Logstown was an important trade and council center in the Ohio Valley. Between June 15 and November 10, 1749, an expedition headed by Celeron de Bienville, a French officer, traveled down the Allegheny and Ohio to bolster the French claim to the region. De Bienville warned away British traders and posted markers claiming the territory.%0a%3c %0a%3c In 1753, Marquis Duquesne, the Governor of New France, sent another, larger expedition. At present-day Erie, Pennsylvania, an advance party built Fort Presque Isle. They also cut a road through the woods and built Fort Le Boeuf on French Creek, from which it was possible at high water to float to the Allegheny. By summer, an expedition of 1,500 French and Native American men descended the Allegheny. Some wintered at the confluence of French Creek and the Allegheny. The following year, they built Fort Machault at that site.%0a%3c %0a%3c Alarmed at these French incursions in the Ohio Valley, Governor Dinwiddie of Virginia sent Major George Washington to warn the French to withdraw. Accompanied by Christopher Gist, Washington arrived at the Forks of the Ohio on November 25, 1753%0a%3c %0a%3c Proceeding up the Allegheny, Washington presented Dinwiddie's letter to the French commanders first at Venango, and then Fort Le Boeuf. The French officers received Washington with wine and courtesy, but did not withdraw.%0a%3c %0a%3c Governor Dinwiddie sent Captain William Trent to build a fort at the Forks of the Ohio. On February 17, 1754, Trent began construction of the fort, the first European habitation at the site of present-day Pittsburgh. The fort, named Fort Prince George, was only half-built by April 1754, when over 500 French forces arrived and ordered the 40-some colonials back to Virginia. The French tore down the British fortification and constructed Fort Duquesne.%0a%3c %0a%3c Governor Dinwiddie launched another expedition. Colonel Joshua Fry commanded the regiment with his second-in-command, George Washington, leading an advance column. On May 28, 1754, Washington's unit clashed with the French in the Battle of Jumonville Glen, during which 13 French soldiers were killed and 21 were taken prisoner. After the battle, Washington's ally, Seneca chief Tanaghrisson, unexpectedly executed the French commanding officer, Ensign Joseph Coulon de Jumonville. The French pursued Washington and on July 3, 1754, George Washington surrendered following the Battle of Fort Necessity. These frontier actions contributed to the start of the French and Indian War (17541763), or, the Seven Years' War, a global confrontation between Britain and France fought in both hemispheres.%0a%3c %0a%3c In 1755, the Braddock Expedition was launched, accompanied by Virginia militia officer George Washington. Two regiments marched from Fort Cumberland across the Allegheny Mountains and into western Pennsylvania. Following a path Washington surveyed, over 3,000 men built a wagon road 12 feet wide, that when complete, was the first road to cross the Appalachian Mountains. Braddock's Road, as it was known, blazed the way for the future National Road (US40). The expedition crossed the Monongahela River on July 9, 1755. French troops from Fort Duquesne ambushed Braddock's expedition at Braddock's Field, nine miles from Fort Duquesne. In the Battle of the Monongahela, the French inflicted heavy losses on the British, and Braddock was mortally wounded.[20] The surviving British and colonial forces retreated. This left the French and their Native American allies with dominion over the upper Ohio valley.%0a%3c %0a%3c On September 8, 1756, an expedition of 300 militiamen destroyed the Shawnee and Lenape village of Kittanning, and in the summer of 1758, British Army officer John Forbes began a campaign to capture Fort Duquesne. At the head of 7,000 regular and colonial troops, Forbes built Fort Ligonier and Fort Bedford, from where he cut a wagon road over the Allegheny Mountains, later known as Forbes' Road. On the night of September 1314, 1758, an advance column under Major James Grant was annihilated in the Battle of Fort Duquesne. The battleground, the high hill east of the Point, was named Grant's Hill in his memory. With this defeat, Forbes decided to wait until spring. But when he heard that the French had lost Fort Frontenac and largely evacuated Fort Duquesne, he planned an immediate attack. Hopelessly outnumbered, the French abandoned and razed Fort Duquesne. Forbes occupied the burned fort on November 25, 1758, and ordered the construction of Fort Pitt, named after British Secretary of State William Pitt the Elder. He also named the settlement between the rivers, "Pittsborough" (see Etymology of Pittsburgh). The British garrison at Fort Pitt made substantial improvements to its fortification. The French never attacked Fort Pitt and the war soon ended with the Treaty of Paris and French defeat. They ceded their territories east of the Mississippi River.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c !!%25center%25''Gateway to the West (17631799)''%0a%3c %0a%3c In 1760, the first considerable European settlement around Fort Pitt began to grow. Traders and settlers built two groups of houses and cabins, the "lower town," near the fort's ramparts, and the "upper town," along the Monongahela as far as present-day Market Street. In April 1761, a census ordered by Colonel Henry Bouquet counted 332 people and 104 houses.%0a%3c %0a%3c After Britain's victory in the French and Indian War, increasing dissatisfaction among Native Americans with British policies led to the outbreak of Pontiac's War. The Odawa leader Pontiac launched an offensive against British forts in May 1763. Native American tribes from the Ohio Valley and the Great Lakes overran numerous British forts; one of their most important targets was Fort Pitt. Receiving warning of the coming attack, Captain Simeon Ecuyer, the Swiss officer in command of the garrison, prepared for a siege. He leveled the houses outside the ramparts and ordered all settlers into the fort: 330 men, 104 women, and 196 children sought refuge inside its ramparts. Captain Ecuyer also gathered stores, which included hundreds of barrels of pork and beef. Pontiac's forces attacked the fort on June 22, 1763, and the siege of Fort Pitt lasted for two months. Pontiac's warriors kept up a continuous, though ineffective, fire on it from July 27 through August 1, 1763. They drew off to confront the relieving party under Colonel Bouquet, which defeated them in the Battle of Bushy Run. This victory ensured British dominion over the forks of the Ohio, if not the entire Ohio valley. In 1764 Colonel Bouquet added a redoubt, the Fort Pitt Blockhouse, which still stands, the sole remaining structure from Fort Pitt and the oldest authenticated building west of the Allegheny Mountains.%0a%3c %0a%3c The Iroquois signed the Fort Stanwix Treaty of 1768, ceding the lands south of the Ohio to the British Crown. European expansion into the upper Ohio valley increased. An estimated 4,000 to 5,000 families settled in western Pennsylvania between 1768 and 1770. Of these settlers, about a third were English-American, another third were Scotch-Irish, and the rest were Welsh, German and others. These groups tended to settle together in small farming communities, but often their households were not within hailing distance. The life of a settler family was one of relentless hard work: clearing the forest, stumping the fields, building cabins and barns, planting, weeding, and harvesting. In addition, almost everything was manufactured by hand, including furniture, tools, candles, buttons, and needles. Settlers had to deal with harsh winters, and with snakes, black bears, mountain lions, and timber wolves. Because of the fear of raids by Native Americans, the settlers often built their cabins near, or even on top of, springs, to ensure access to water. They also built blockhouses, where neighbors would rally during conflicts.%0a%3c %0a%3c Increasing violence, especially by the Shawnee, Miami, and Wyandot tribes, led to Dunmore's War in 1774. Conflict with Native Americans continued throughout the Revolutionary War, as some hoped that the war would end with expulsion of the settlers from their territory. In 1777, Fort Pitt became a United States fort, when Brigadier General Edward Hand took command. In 1779, Colonel Daniel Brodhead led 600 men from Fort Pitt to destroy Seneca villages along the upper Allegheny.%0a%3c %0a%3c With the war still ongoing, in 1780 Virginia and Pennsylvania came to an agreement on their mutual borders, creating the state lines known today and determining finally that the jurisdiction of Pittsburgh region was Pennsylvanian. In 1783, the Revolutionary War ended, which also brought at least a temporary cessation of border warfare. In the 1784 Treaty of Fort Stanwix, the Iroquois ceded the land north of the Purchase Line to Pennsylvania.%0a%3c %0a%3c After the Revolution, the village of Pittsburgh continued to grow. One of its earliest industries was boat building. Flatboats could be used to carry large numbers of pioneers and goods downriver, while keelboats were capable of traveling upriver.%0a%3c %0a%3c The village began to develop vital institutions. Hugh Henry Brackenridge, a Pittsburgh resident and state legislator, introduced a bill that resulted in a gift deed of land and a charter for the Pittsburgh Academy on February 28, 1787. The Academy later developed as the University of Western Pennsylvania (1819) and since 1908 has been known as the University of Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c Many farmers distilled their corn harvest into whiskey, increasing its value while lowering its transportation costs. At that time, whiskey was used as a form of currency on the frontier. When the federal government imposed an excise tax on whiskey, Western Pennsylvania farmers felt victimized, leading to the Whiskey Rebellion in 1794. Farmers from the region rallied at Braddock's Field and marched on Pittsburgh. The short-lived rebellion was put down, however, when President George Washington sent in militias from several states.%0a%3c %0a%3c The town continued to grow in manufacturing capability. In 1792, the boatyards in Pittsburgh built a sloop, Western Experiment.[24] During the next decades, the yards produced other large boats. By the 19th century, they were building ocean-going vessels that shipped goods as far as Europe. In 1794, the town's first courthouse was built; it was a wooden structure on Market Square. In 1797, the manufacture of glass began.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c !%25center%25'''Iron City (18001859)'''%0a%3c %0a%3c Commerce continued to be an essential part of the economy of early Pittsburgh, but increasingly, manufacture began to grow in importance. Pittsburgh was located in the middle of one of the most productive coalfields in the country; the region was also rich in petroleum, natural gas, lumber, and farm goods. Blacksmiths forged iron implements, from horse shoes to nails. By 1800, the town, with a population of 1,565 persons, had over 60 shops, including general stores, bakeries, and hat and shoe shops.%0a%3c %0a%3c The 1810s were a critical decade in Pittsburgh's growth. In 1811, the first steamboat was built in Pittsburgh. Increasingly, commerce would also flow upriver. The War of 1812 catalyzed growth of the Iron City. The war with Britain, the manufacturing center of the world, cut off the supply of British goods, stimulating American manufacture. In addition, the British blockade of the American coast increased inland trade, so that goods flowed through Pittsburgh from all four directions. By 1815, Pittsburgh was producing $764K in iron; $249K in brass and tin, and $235K in glass products. When, on March 18, 1816, Pittsburgh was incorporated as a city, it had already taken on some of its defining characteristics: commerce, manufacture, and a constant cloud of coal dust.%0a%3c %0a%3c Other emerging towns challenged Pittsburgh. In 1818, the first segment of the National Road was completed, from Baltimore to Wheeling, bypassing Pittsburgh. This threatened to render the town less essential in eastwest commerce. In the coming decade, however, many improvements were made to the transportation infrastructure. In 1818, the region's first river bridge, the Smithfield Street Bridge, opened, the first step in developing the "City of bridges" over its two rivers. On October 1, 1840, the original Pennsylvania Turnpike was completed, connecting Pittsburgh and the eastern port city of Philadelphia. In 1834, the Pennsylvania Main Line Canal was completed, making Pittsburgh part of a transportation system that included rivers, roads, and canals.%0a%3c %0a%3c Manufacture continued to grow. In 1835, McClurg, Wade and Co. built the first locomotive west of the Alleghenies. Already, Pittsburgh was capable of manufacturing the most essential machines of its age. By the 1840s, Pittsburgh was one of the largest cities west of the mountains. In 1841, the Second Court House, on Grant's Hill, was completed. Made from polished gray sandstone, the court house had a rotunda 60 feet in diameter and 80 feet high.%0a%3c %0a%3c Like many burgeoning cities of its day, Pittsburgh's growth outstripped some of its necessary infrastructure, such as a water supply with dependable pressure. Because of this, on April 10, 1845, a great fire burned out of control, destroying over a thousand buildings and causing $9M in damages. As the city rebuilt, the age of rails arrived. In 1851, the Ohio and Pennsylvania Railroad began service between Cleveland and Allegheny City (present-day North Side). In 1854, the Pennsylvania Railroad began service between Pittsburgh and Philadelphia.%0a%3c %0a%3c Despite many challenges, Pittsburgh had grown into an industrial powerhouse. An 1857 article provided a snapshot of the Iron City:%0a%3c %0a%3c 939 factories in Pittsburgh and Allegheny City employing more than 10K workers producing almost $12M in goods using 400 steam engines. %0a%3c Total coal consumed  22M bushels%0a%3c Total iron consumed  127K tons%0a%3c In steam tonnage, third busiest port in the nation, surpassed only by New York City and New Orleans.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c !%25center%25'''Steel City (18591946)'''%0a%3c %0a%3c The iron and steel industry developed rapidly after 1830 and became one of the dominant factors in industrial America by the 1860s.%0a%3c %0a%3c !!%25center%25''Scots Irish leadership''%0a%3c %0a---%0a> !%25center%25'''City History'''%0a> %0a> The earliest evidence of Native American settlement in the Miami region came from about 10,000 years ago. The region was filled with pine hardwood forests and was home to plenty of deer, bear, and wild fowl. These first inhabitants settled on the banks of the Miami River, with their main villages on the northern banks. These early Native Americans created a variety of weapons and tools from shells.%0a> %0a> When the first Europeans visited in the mid-1500s, the inhabitants of the Miami area were the Tequesta people, who controlled an area covering much of southeastern Florida including what is now Miami-Dade County, Broward County, and the southern parts of Palm Beach County. The Tequesta Indians fished, hunted, and gathered the fruit and roots of plants for food, but did not practice any form of agriculture. They buried the small bones of the deceased, but put the larger bones in a box for the village people to see. The Tequesta are credited with making the Miami Circle.%0a> %0a> !!%25center%25''16th to 18th centuries: Early Spanish settlement''%0a> In 1513, Juan Ponce de Len was the first European to visit the Miami area by sailing into Biscayne Bay. He wrote in his journal that he reached Chequescha, which was Miami's first recorded name, but it is unknown whether or not he came ashore or made contact with the natives. Pedro Menndez de Avils and his men made the first recorded landing in this area when they visited the Tequesta settlement in 1566 while looking for Avils' missing son, who had been shipwrecked a year earlier. Spanish soldiers, led by Father Francisco Villareal, built a Jesuit mission at the mouth of the Miami River a year later, but it was short-lived. By 1570, the Jesuits decided to look for more willing subjects outside of Florida. After the Spaniards left, the Tequesta Indians were left to fight European-introduced diseases, such as smallpox, without European help. Wars with other tribes greatly weakened their population, and they were easily defeated by the Creek Indians in later battles. By 1711, the Tequesta had sent a couple of local chiefs to Havana to ask if they could migrate there. The Spanish sent two ships to help them, but their illnesses struck, killing most of their population. In 1743, the Spaniards sent another mission to Biscayne Bay, where they built a fort and church. The missionary priests proposed a permanent settlement, where the Spanish settlers would raise food for the soldiers and Native Americans. However, the proposal was rejected as impractical and the mission was withdrawn before the end of the year.%0a> %0a> !!%25center%25''18th to 19th centuries: Early non-Spanish settlement''%0a> In 1766, Samuel Touchett received a land grant from the British government of 20,000 acres (81 km2) in the Miami area. The grant was surveyed by Bernard Romans in 1772. A condition for making the grant permanent was that at least one white settler had to live on the grant for every 100 acres (0.4 km2) of land. While Touchett wanted to place a plantation on the grant, he was having financial problems and was never able to develop it.%0a> The first permanent European settlers in the Miami area arrived around 1800. Pedro Fornells, a Menorcan survivor of the New Smyrna colony, moved to Key Biscayne to meet the terms of his Royal Grant for the island. Although he returned with his family to St. Augustine after six months, he left a caretaker behind on the island. On a trip to the island in 1803, Fornells had noted the presence of squatters on the mainland across Biscayne Bay from the island. In 1825, U.S. Marshal Waters Smith visited the Cape Florida Settlement (which was on the mainland) and conferred with squatters who wanted to obtain title to the land they were occupying. On the mainland, the Bahamian "squatters" had settled along the coast beginning in the 1790s. John Egan had also received a grant from Spain during the Second Spanish Period. John's son James Egan, his wife Rebecca Egan, his widow Mary "Polly" Lewis, and Mary's brother-in-law Jonathan Lewis all received 640-acre land grants from the U.S. in present-day Miami. Temple Pent and his family did not receive a land grant, but nevertheless stayed in the area.%0a> %0a> Treasure hunters from the Bahamas and the Keys came to South Florida to hunt for treasure from the ships that ran aground on the treacherous Great Florida reef, some of whom accepted Spanish land offers along the Miami River. At about the same time, the Seminole Indians arrived along with a group of runaway slaves. In 1825, the Cape Florida Lighthouse was built on nearby Key Biscayne to warn passing ships of the dangerous reefs.%0a> %0a> In 1830, Richard Fitzpatrick bought land on the Miami River from Bahamian James Egan. He built a plantation with slave labor where he cultivated sugarcane, bananas, maize, and tropical fruit. In January 1836, shortly after the beginning of the Second Seminole War, Fitzpatrick removed his slaves and closed his plantation.%0a> %0a> The area was affected by the Second Seminole War, where Major William S. Harney led several raids against the Indians. Fort Dallas was located on Fitzpatrick's plantation on the north bank of the river. Most of the non-Indian population consisted of soldiers stationed at Fort Dallas. The Seminole War was the most devastating Indian war in American history,[citation needed] causing almost a total loss of native population in the Miami area. The Cape Florida lighthouse was burned by Seminoles in 1836 and was not repaired until 1846.%0a> %0a> After the Second Seminole War ended in 1842, Fitzpatrick's nephew, William English, re-established the plantation in Miami. He charted the "Village of Miami" on the south bank of the Miami River and sold several plots of land. When English died in California in 1852, his plantation died with him.%0a> %0a> The Miami River lent its name to the burgeoning town, extending an etymology that derives from the Mayaimi Indian tribe. In 1844, Miami became the county seat, and six years later, a census reported that there were ninety-six residents living in the area. The Third Seminole War lasted from 1855 to 1858, but was not nearly as destructive as the previous one. However, it did slow down the rate of settlement of southeast Florida. At the end of the war, a few of the soldiers stayed and some of the Seminoles remained in the Everglades.%0a> %0a> From 1858 to 1896, only a handful of families made their homes in the Miami area. Those that did lived in small settlements along Biscayne Bay. The first of these settlements formed at the mouth of the Miami River and was variously called Miami, Miamuh, and Fort Dallas. Foremost among the Miami River settlers were the Brickells. William Brickell had previously lived in Cleveland, Ohio, California, and Australia, where he met his wife, Mary. In 1870, Brickell bought land on the south bank of the river. The Brickells and their children operated a trading post and post office on their property for the rest of the 19th century.%0a> %0a> Other settlements within Miami's city limits were Lemon City (now Little Haiti) and Coconut Grove. Settlements outside the city limits were Biscayne, in present-day Miami Shores, and Cutler, in present-day Palmetto Bay. Many of the settlers were homesteaders, attracted to the area by offers of 160 acres (0.6 km2) of free land by the United States federal government.%0a> %0a> %0a> !!%25center%25''1890s: Fast growth and formation''%0a> %0a> In 1891, a Cleveland woman named Julia Tuttle decided to move to South Florida to make a new start in her life after the death of her husband, Frederick Tuttle. She purchased 640 acres on the north bank of the Miami River in present-day downtown Miami.%0a> %0a> She tried to persuade railroad magnate Henry Flagler to expand his rail line, the Florida East Coast Railway, southward to the area, but he initially declined. In December 1894, Florida was struck by a freeze that destroyed virtually the entire citrus crop in the northern half of the state. A few months later, on the night of February 7, 1895, the northern part of Florida was hit by another freeze that wiped out the remaining crops and the new trees. Unlike most of the rest of the state, the Miami area was unaffected. Tuttle wrote to Flagler again, asking him to visit the area and to see it for himself. Flagler sent James E. Ingraham to investigate and he returned with a favorable report and a box of orange blossoms to show that the area had escaped the frost. Flagler followed up with his own visit and concluded at the end of his first day that the area was ripe for expansion. He made the decision to extend his railroad to Miami and build a resort hotel.%0a> %0a> On April 22, 1895, Flagler wrote Tuttle a long letter recapping her offer of land to him in exchange for extending his railroad to Miami, laying out a city and building a hotel. The terms provided that Tuttle would award Flagler a 100-acre (0.4 km2) tract of land for the city to grow. Around the same time, Flagler wrote a similar letter to William and Mary Brickell, who had also verbally agreed to give land during his visit.%0a> %0a> While the railroad's extension to Miami remained unannounced in the spring of 1895, rumors of this possibility continued to multiply, fueling real estate activity in the Biscayne Bay area. The news of the railroad's extension was officially announced on June 21, 1895. In late September, the work on the railroad began and settlers began pouring into the promised "freeze proof" lands. On October 24, 1895, the contract agreed upon by Flagler and Tuttle was approved.%0a> With the railroad under construction, activity in Miami began to pick up. Men from throughout Florida flocked to Miami to await Flagler's call for workers of all qualifications to begin work on the promised hotel and city. By late December 1895, seventy-five of them already were at work clearing the site for the hotel. They lived mostly in tents and huts in the wilderness, which had no streets and few cleared paths. Many of these men were victims of the freeze, which had left both money and work scarce.%0a> %0a> On February 1, 1896, Tuttle fulfilled the first part of her agreement with Flagler by signing two deeds to transfer land for his hotel and the 100 acres (0.4 km2) of land near the hotel site to him. The titles to the Brickell and Tuttle properties were based on early Spanish land grants and had to be determined to be clear of conflict before the marketing of the Miami lots began. On March 3, Flagler hired John Sewell from West Palm Beach to begin work on the town as more people came into Miami. On April 7, 1896, the railroad tracks finally reached Miami and the first train arrived on April 13. It was a special, unscheduled train and Flagler was on board. The train returned to St. Augustine later that night. The first regularly scheduled train arrived on the night of April 15. The first week of train service provided only for freight trains; passenger service did not begin until April 22.%0a> %0a> On July 28, 1896, the incorporation meeting to make Miami a city took place. The right to vote was restricted to all men who resided in Miami or Dade County. Joseph A. McDonald, Flagler's chief of construction on the Royal Palm Hotel, was elected chairman of the meeting. After ensuring that enough voters were present, the motion was made to incorporate and organize a city government under the corporate name of "The City of Miami", with the boundaries as proposed. John B. Reilly, who headed Flagler's Fort Dallas land company, was the first elected mayor.%0a> %0a> Initially, most residents wanted to name the city "Flagler". However, Henry Flagler was adamant that the new city would not be named after him. So on July 28, 1896, the City of Miami, named after the Miami River, was incorporated with 502 voters, including 100 registered black voters. The blacks provided the primary labor force for the building of Miami. Clauses in land deeds confined blacks to the northwest section of Miami, which became known as "Colored Town" (today's Overtown).%0a> %0a> !%25center%25'''Twentieth century'''%0a> !!%25center%25''1900s to 1930s: The Magic City''%0a> %0a102,256c85,152%0a%3c !!%25center%25''Technology''%0a%3c %0a%3c In 1859, the Clinton and Soho iron furnaces introduced coke-fire smelting to the region. The American Civil War boosted the city's economy with increased production of iron and armaments, especially at the Allegheny Arsenal and the Fort Pitt Foundry.[30] Arms manufacture included iron-clad warships and the world's first 21" gun.[35] By war's end, over one-half of the steel and more than one-third of all U.S. glass was produced in Pittsburgh. A milestone in steel production was achieved in 1875, when the Edgar Thomson Works in Braddock began to make steel rail using the new Bessemer process.%0a%3c %0a%3c Industrialists such as Andrew Carnegie, Henry Clay Frick, Andrew W. Mellon, and Charles M. Schwab built their fortunes in Pittsburgh. Also based in Pittsburgh was George Westinghouse, credited with such advancements as the air brake and founder of over 60 companies, including Westinghouse Air and Brake Company (1869), Union Switch & Signal (1881), and Westinghouse Electric Company (1886). Banks played a key role in Pittsburgh's development as these industrialists sought massive loans to upgrade plants, integrate industries and fund technological advances. For example, T. Mellon & Sons Bank, founded in 1869, helped to finance an aluminum reduction company that became Alcoa.%0a%3c %0a%3c Ingham (1991) shows how small, independent iron and steel manufacturers survived and prospered from the 1870s through the 1950s, despite competition from much larger, standardized production firms. These smaller firms were built on a culture that valued local markets and the beneficial role of business in the local community. Small firms concentrated on specialized products, particularly structural steel, where the economies of scale of larger firms were no advantage. They embraced technological change more cautiously than larger firms. They also had less antagonistic relations with workers and employed a higher percentage of highly skilled workers than their mass-production counterparts.%0a%3c %0a%3c !!%25center%25''Geography of industrialization.''%0a%3c %0a%3c Beginning in the 1870s, entrepreneurs transformed the economy from small, craft-organized factories located inside the city limits to a large integrated industrial region stretching 50 miles across Allegheny County. The new industrial Pittsburgh was based on integrated mills, mass production, and modern management organization in steel and other industries. Many manufacturers searched for large sites with railroad and river accessibility. They purchased land, designed modern plants, and sometimes built towns for workers. Other firms bought into new communities that began as speculative industrial real estate ventures. Some owners removed their plants from the central city's labor unions to exert greater control over workers. The region's rugged topography and dispersed natural resources of coal and gas accentuated this dispersal. The rapid growth of steel, glass, railroad equipment, and coke industries resulted in both large mass-production plants and numerous smaller firms. As capital deepened and interdependence grew, participants multiplied, economies accrued, the division of labor increased, and localized production systems formed around these industries. Transportation, capital, labor markets and the division of labor in production bound the scattered industrial plants and communities into a sprawling metropolitan district. By 1910 the Pittsburgh district was a complex urban landscape with a dominant central city, surrounded by proximate residential communities, mill towns, satellite cities, and hundreds of mining towns.%0a%3c %0a%3c Representative of the new industrial suburbs was the model town of Vandergrift, according to Mosher (1995). Caught up in a dramatic round of industrial restructuring and labor tension, Pittsburgh steelmaker George McMurtry hired Frederick Law Olmsted's landscape architectural firm in 1895 to design Vandergrift as a model town. McMurtry believed in what was later known as welfare capitalism, with the company going beyond paychecks to provide for the social needs of the workers; he believed that a benign physical environment made for happier and more productive workers. A strike and lockout at McMurtry's steelworks in Apollo, Pennsylvania, prompted him to build the new town. Wanting a loyal workforce, he developed a town agenda that drew upon environmentalism as well as popular attitudes toward capital's treatment of labor. The Olmsted firm translated this agenda into an urban design that included a unique combination of social reform, comprehensive infrastructure planning, and private homeownership principles. The rates of homeownership and cordial relationships between the steel company and Vandergrift residents fostered loyalty among McMurtry's skilled workers and led to McMurtry's greatest success. In 1901 he used Vandergrift's worker-residents to break the first major strike against the United States Steel Corporation.%0a%3c %0a%3c !!%25center%25''Germans.''%0a%3c %0a%3c During the mid-19th century, Pittsburgh witnessed a dramatic influx of German immigrants, including a brick mason whose son, Henry J. Heinz, founded the H.J. Heinz Company in 1869. Heinz was at the forefront of reform efforts to improve food purity, working conditions, hours, and wages, but the company bitterly opposed the formation of an independent labor union.%0a%3c %0a%3c !!%25center%25''Labor unions.''%0a%3c %0a%3c As a manufacturing center, Pittsburgh also became an arena for intense labor strife. During the Great Railroad Strike of 1877, Pittsburgh workers protested and had massive demonstrations that erupted into widespread violence, known as the Pittsburgh Railway Riots.[43] Militia and federal troops were called to the city to suppress the strike. Forty men died, most of them workers, and more than 40 buildings were burned down, including the Union Depot of the Pennsylvania Railroad. Strikers also burned and destroyed rolling stock: more than 100 train engines and 1000 railcars were destroyed. It was the city with the most violence of any affected by the strikes.%0a%3c In 1892, a confrontation in the steel industry resulted in 10 deaths (3 detectives, 7 workers) when Carnegie Steel Company's manager Henry Clay Frick sent in Pinkertons to break the Homestead Strike. Labor strife continued into the years of the Great Depression, as workers sought to protect their jobs and improve working conditions. Unions organized H.J. Heinz workers, with the assistance of the Catholic Radical Alliance.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c !!%25center%25''Carnegie.''%0a%3c %0a%3c Andrew Carnegie, an immigrant from Scotland, a former Pennsylvania Railroad executive turned steel magnate, founded the Carnegie Steel Company. He proceeded to play a key role in the development of the U.S. steel industry. He became a philanthropist: in 1890, he established the first Carnegie Library, in a program to establish libraries in numerous cities and towns by the incentive of matching funds. In 1895, he founded the Carnegie Institute. In 1901, as the U.S. Steel Corporation formed, he sold his mills to J.P. Morgan for $250 million, making him one of the world's richest men. Carnegie once wrote that a man who dies rich, dies disgraced. He devoted the rest of his life to public service, establishing libraries, trusts, and foundations. In Pittsburgh, he founded the Carnegie Institute of Technology (now Carnegie Mellon University) and the Carnegie Museums of Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c The third (and present) Allegheny County Courthouse and Jail was completed in 1886. In 1890, trolleys began operations. In 1907, Pittsburgh annexed Allegheny City, which is now known as the North Shore.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c !%25center%25'''Early 20th century'''%0a%3c %0a%3c By 1911, Pittsburgh had grown into an industrial and commercial powerhouse:%0a%3c %0a%3c Nexus of a vast railway system, with freight yards capable of handling 60K cars%0a%3c 27.2 miles (43.8 km) of harbor%0a%3c Yearly river traffic in excess of 9M tons%0a%3c Value of factory products more than $211M (with Allegheny City)%0a%3c Allegheny county produced, as percentage of national output, about:%0a%3c 24%25 of the pig iron%0a%3c 34%25 of the Bessemer steel%0a%3c 44%25 of the open hearth steel%0a%3c 53%25 of the crucible steel%0a%3c 24%25 of the steel rails%0a%3c 59%25 of the structural shapes%0a%3c %0a%3c !!%25center%25''Prohibition''%0a%3c %0a%3c During the Prohibition era, 1920 to 1933, Pittsburgh was a hotbed of bootlegging and illicit alcohol consumption. Several factors fed into resistance to Prohibition, including a large immigrant population, anti-establishment animosity dating to the Whiskey Rebellion, fragmented local government, and pervasive corruption. The Pittsburgh crime family controlled significant portions of the illegal alcohol trade.%0a%3c %0a%3c During that time, Prohibition Administrator John Pennington and his federal agents engaged in 15,000 raids, arrested over 18,000 people and closed down over 3,000 distilleries, 16 regular breweries, and 400 'wildcat' breweries. Even the term "Speakeasy," meaning an illegal drinking establishment, is said to have been coined at the Blind Pig in nearby McKeesport, Pennsylvania.%0a%3c %0a%3c The last distillery in Pittsburgh, Joseph S. Finch's distillery, located at South Second and McKean streets, closed in the 1920s. In 2012, Wigle Whiskey opened, becoming the first since the closure of Finch's distillery.%0a%3c %0a%3c The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette produced a large web feature on this period in the city's history.%0a%3c %0a%3c !!%25center%25''Environment''%0a%3c %0a%3c During the late 19th century, city leaders debated the responsibility and expense of creating a waterworks system and disposal of sewage. Downstream users complained about Pittsburgh's dumping of sewage into the Ohio River. Allegheny County cities did not stop discharging raw sewage into rivers until 1939. Pittsburgh's smoke pollution, seen in the 1890s as a sign of prosperity, was recognized as a problem in the Progressive Era and was cleared up in the 1930s1940s. Steel plants deposited mountains of slag until 1972, especially in Nine Mile Run Valley.%0a%3c %0a%3c In November 1927, 28 people were killed and hundreds were wounded in an explosion of a gas tank.%0a%3c %0a%3c To escape the soot of the city, many of the wealthy lived in the Shadyside and East End neighborhoods, a few miles east of downtown. Fifth Avenue was dubbed "Millionaire's Row" because of the many mansions lining the street.%0a%3c %0a%3c On March 17 and 18, 1936, Pittsburgh suffered the worst flood in its history, with flood levels peaking at 46 feet. This catastrophe killed 69 victims, destroyed thousands of buildings, caused $3B (2006 dollars) in damages, and put more than 60,000 steelworkers out of work.%0a%3c %0a%3c !!%25center%25''High culture''%0a%3c %0a%3c Oakland became the city's predominant cultural and educational center, including three universities, multiple museums, a library, a music hall, and a botanical conservatory. Oakland's University of Pittsburgh erected what today is still the world's fourth-tallest educational building, the 42-story Cathedral of Learning. It towered over Forbes Field, where the Pittsburgh Pirates played from 1909 to 1970.%0a%3c %0a%3c !!%25center%25''New immigrants and migrants''%0a%3c %0a%3c Between 1870 and 1920, the population of Pittsburgh grew almost sevenfold, with a large number of European immigrants arriving to the city. New arrivals continue to come from Britain, Ireland, and Germany, but the most popular sources after 1870 were poor rural areas in southern and eastern Europe, including Italy, the Balkans, the Austro-Hungarian Empire, and the Russian Empire. Unskilled immigrants found jobs in construction, mining, steel mills and factories. They introduced new traditions, languages, and cultures to the city, creating a diversified society as a result. Ethnic neighborhoods developed in working-class areas and were built on densely populated hillsides and valleys, such as South Side, Polish Hill, Bloomfield, and Squirrel Hill, home to 28%25 of the city's almost 21,000 Jewish households. The Strip District, the city's produce distribution center, still boasts many restaurants and clubs that showcase these multicultural traditions of Pittsburghers.%0a%3c %0a%3c !!%25center%25''African Americans''%0a%3c %0a%3c The years 19161940 marked the largest migration of African Americans to Pittsburgh during the Great Migration from the rural South to industrial cities of the Northeast and Midwest. These migrants came for industrial jobs, education, political and social freedom, and to escape racial oppression and violence in the South. Migrants going to Pittsburgh and surrounding mill towns faced racial discrimination and restricted housing and job opportunities. The black population in Pittsburgh jumped from 6,000 in 1880 to 27,000 in 1910. Many took highly paid, skilled jobs in the steel mills. Pittsburgh's black population increased to 37,700 in 1920 (6.4%25 of the total) while the black element in Homestead, Rankin, Braddock, and others nearly doubled. They succeeded in building effective community responses that enabled the survival of new communities. Historian Joe Trotter explains the decision process:%0a%3c %0a%3c Although African-Americans often expressed their views of the Great Migration in biblical terms and received encouragement from northern black newspapers, railroad companies, and industrial labor agents, they also drew upon family and friendship networks to help in the move to Western Pennsylvania. They formed migration clubs, pooled their money, bought tickets at reduced rates, and often moved ingroups. Before they made the decision to move, they gathered information and debated the pros and cons of the process....In barbershops, poolrooms, and grocery stores, in churches, lodge halls, and clubhouses, and in private homes, southern blacks discussed, debated, and decided what was good and what was bad about moving to the urban North.%0a%3c The newly established Black communities nearly all endured, apart from Johnstown where blacks were expelled in 1923. Joe Trotter explains how the Blacks built new institutions for their new communities in the Pittsburgh area:%0a%3c %0a%3c Black churches, fraternal orders, and newspapers (especially the Pittsburgh Courier); organizations such as the NAACP, Urban League, and Garvey Movement; social clubs, restaurants, and baseball teams; hotels, beauty shops, barber shops, and taverns, all proliferated.%0a%3c The cultural nucleus of Black Pittsburgh was Wylie Avenue in the Hill District. It became an important jazz mecca because jazz greats such as Duke Ellington and Pittsburgh natives Billy Strayhorn and Earl Hines played there. Two of the Negro League's greatest baseball rivals, the Pittsburgh Crawfords and the Homestead Grays, often competed in the Hill District. The teams dominated the Negro National League in the 1930s and 1940s.%0a%3c %0a%3c !!%25center%25''1930s''%0a%3c %0a%3c Pittsburgh was a Republican stronghold starting in the 1880s, and the Republican governments provided jobs and assistance for the new immigrants in return for their votes. But the Great Depression starting in 1929 ruined the GOP in the city. The Democratic victory of 1932 meant an end to Republican patronage jobs and assistance. As the Depression worsened, Pittsburgh ethnics voted heavily for the Democrats, especially in 1934, making the city a stronghold of the New Deal Coalition. By 1936, Democratic programs for relief and jobs, especially the WPA, were so popular with the ethnics that a large majority voted for the Democrats.%0a%3c %0a%3c Joseph Guffey, statewide leader of the Democrats, and his local lieutenant David Lawrence gained control of all federal patronage in Pittsburgh after Roosevelt's landslide victory in 1932 and the election of a Democratic mayor in 1933. Guffey and Lawrence used the New Deal programs to increase their political power and build up a Democratic machine that superseded the decaying Republican machine. Guffey acknowledged that a high rate of people on relief was not only "a challenge" but also "an opportunity." He regarded each relief job as Democratic patronage.%0a%3c %0a%3c !!%25center%25''1940s''%0a%3c %0a%3c Pittsburgh was at the center of the "Arsenal of Democracy" that provided steel, aluminum, munitions and machinery for the U.S. during World War II. Pittsburgh's mills contributed 95 million tons of steel to the war effort. The increased production output created a workforce shortage, which resulted in African Americans moving en masse during the Second Great Migration from the South to the city in order to find work.%0a%3c %0a%3c !!%25center%25''Postwar''%0a%3c %0a%3c David Lawrence, a Democrat, served as mayor of Pittsburgh from 1946 to 1959 and as Pennsylvania's governor from 1959 to 1963.[64] Lawrence used his political power to transform Pittsburgh's political machine into a modern governmental unit that could run the city well and honestly. In 1946 Lawrence decided to enforce the Smoke Control Ordinance of 1941 because he believed smoke abatement was crucial for the city's future economic development. However, enforcement placed a substantial burden on the city's working-class because smoky bituminous coal was much less expensive than smokeless fuels. One round of protests came from Italian-American organizations, which called for delay in enforcing it. Enforcement raised their cost of living and threatened the jobs of their relatives in nearby bituminous coal mines. Despite dislike of the smoke abatement program, Italian Americans strongly supported the reelection of Lawrence in 1949, in part because many of them were on the city payroll.%0a%3c %0a%3c !%25center%25'''Renaissance I (19461973)'''%0a%3c %0a%3c Rich and productive, Pittsburgh was also the "Smoky City," with smog sometimes so thick that streetlights burned during the day as well as rivers that resembled open sewers. Civic leaders, notably Mayor David L. Lawrence, elected in 1945, Richard K. Mellon, chairman of Mellon Bank and John P. Robin began smoke control and urban revitalization, also known as Urban Renewal projects that transformed the city in unforeseen ways.%0a%3c %0a%3c "Renaissance I" began in 1946. Title One of the Housing Act of 1949 provided the means in which to begin. By 1950, vast swaths of buildings and land near the Point were demolished for Gateway Center. 1953 saw the opening of the (since demolished) Greater Pittsburgh Municipal Airport terminal.%0a%3c %0a%3c In the late 1950s and early 1960s, the lower Hill District, an area inhabited predominantly by people of African descent, was completely destroyed. Ninety-five acres of the lower Hill District were cleared using eminent domain, forcibly displacing hundreds of small businesses and more than 8,000 people (1,239 black families, 312 white), to make room for a cultural center that included the Civic Arena, which opened in 1961. Other than one apartment building, none of the other buildings planned for the cultural center were ever built.%0a%3c %0a%3c In the early 1960s, the neighborhood of East Liberty was also included in Renaissance I Urban Renewal plans, with over 125 acres of the neighborhood being demolished and replaced with garden apartments, three 20-story public housing apartments, and a convoluted road-way system that circled a pedestrianized shopping district. In the span of just a few years during the mid-1960s, East Liberty became a blighted neighborhood. There were some 575 businesses in East Liberty in 1959, but only 292 in 1970, and just 98 in 1979.%0a%3c %0a%3c Preservation efforts by the Pittsburgh History and Landmarks Foundation, along with community neighborhood groups, resisted the demolition plans. The neighborhoods containing rich architectural heritage, including the Mexican War Streets, Allegheny West, and Manchester, were spared. The center of Allegheny City, with its culturally and socially important buildings, was not as lucky. All of the buildings, with the exception of the Old U.S. Post Office, the Carnegie Library, and Buhl Planetarium were destroyed and replaced with the "pedestrianized" Allegheny Center Mall and apartments.%0a%3c %0a%3c The city's industrial base continued to grow in the post-war era partly assisted by the area's first agency entirely devoted to industrial development, the RIDC. Jones and Laughlin Steel Company expanded its plant on the Southside. H.J. Heinz, Pittsburgh Plate Glass, Alcoa, Westinghouse, U.S. Steel and its new division, the Pittsburgh Chemical Company and many other companies also continued robust operations through the 1960s. 1970 marked the completion of the final building projects of Renaissance I: the U.S. Steel Tower and Three Rivers Stadium. In 1974, with the addition of the fountain at the tip of the Golden Triangle, Point State Park was completed. Although air quality was dramatically improved, and Pittsburgh's manufacturing base seemed solid, questions abound about the negative effects Urban Renewal continues to have on the social fabric of Pittsburgh. Pittsburgh, however, was about to undergo one of its most dramatic transformations.%0a%3c %0a%3c Like most major cities, Pittsburgh experienced several days of rioting following the assassination of Martin Luther King Jr. in April 1968. There were no further major riots, although tension remained high in the inner-city black neighborhoods.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c !%25center%25'''Reinvention (1973present)'''%0a%3c !!%25center%25''Collapse of steel''%0a%3c %0a%3c Free market pressures exposed the U.S. steel industry's own internal problems, which included a now-outdated manufacturing base that had been over-expanded in the 1950s and 1960s, hostile management and labor relationships, the inflexibility of United Steelworkers regarding wage cuts and work-rule reforms, oligarchic management styles, and poor strategic planning by both unions and management. In particular, Pittsburgh faced its own challenges. Local coke and iron ore deposits were depleted, raising material costs. The large mills in the Pittsburgh region also faced competition from newer, more profitable "mini-mills" and non-union mills with lower labor costs.%0a%3c %0a%3c Beginning in the late 1970s and early 1980s, the steel industry in Pittsburgh began to implode along with the deindustrialization of the U.S. Following the 19811982 recession, for example, the mills laid off 153,000 workers. The steel mills began to shut down. These closures caused a ripple effect, as railroads, mines, and other factories across the region lost business and closed. The local economy suffered a depression, marked by high unemployment and underemployment, as laid-off workers took lower-paying, non-union jobs. Pittsburgh suffered as elsewhere in the Rust Belt with a declining population, and like many other U.S. cities, it also saw white flight to the suburbs.%0a%3c %0a%3c In 1991 the Homestead Works was demolished, replaced in 1999 by The Waterfront shopping mall. As a direct result of the loss of mill employment, the number of people living in Homestead dwindled. By the time of the 2000 census, the borough population was 3,569. The borough began financially recovering in 2002, with the enlarging retail tax base.%0a%3c %0a%3c !!%25center%25''Corporations''%0a%3c %0a%3c Top corporate headquarters such as Gulf Oil (1985), Koppers (1987), Westinghouse (1996) and Rockwell International (1989) were bought out by larger firms, with the loss of high paying, white collar headquarters and research personnel (the "brain drain") as well as massive charitable contributions by the "home based" companies to local cultural and educational institutions. At the time of the Gulf Oil merger in 1985 it was the largest buyout in world history involving the company that was No. 7 on the Fortune 500 just six years earlier. Over 1,000 high paying white collar corporate and PhD research jobs were lost in one day.%0a%3c %0a%3c Today, there are no steel mills within the city limits of Pittsburgh, although manufacture continues at regional mills, such as the Edgar Thomson Works in nearby Braddock.%0a%3c %0a%3c !!%25center%25''Higher education''%0a%3c %0a%3c Pittsburgh is home to three universities that are included in most under-graduate and graduate school national rankings, The University of Pittsburgh, Carnegie Mellon University and Duquesne University. Carnegie Mellon University and the University of Pittsburgh had evolved in the mid-20th century along lines that followed the needs of the heavy industries that financed and directed their development. The collapse of steel put pressure on those two universities to reinvent themselves as research centers in science and technology which acted to pull the regional economy toward high-technology fields. Other regional collegiate institutions include Robert Morris University, Chatham University, Carlow University, Point Park University, La Roche College, Pittsburgh Theological Seminary, Trinity School for Ministry (an Episcopal seminary) and the Community College of Allegheny County.%0a%3c %0a%3c Beginning in the 1980s, Pittsburgh's economy shifted from heavy industry to services, medicine, higher education, tourism, banking, corporate headquarters, and high technology. Today, the top two private employers in the city are the University of Pittsburgh Medical Center (26,000 employees) and the West Penn Allegheny Health System (13,000 employees).%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c !!%25center%25''Civic improvements''%0a%3c %0a%3c Despite the economic turmoil, civic improvements continued. In the mid-1970s, Arthur P. Ziegler, Jr. and the Pittsburgh History and Landmarks Foundation (Landmarks) wanted to demonstrate that historic preservation could be used to drive economic development without the use of eminent domain or public subsidies. Landmarks acquired the former terminal buildings and yards of the Pittsburgh and Lake Erie Railroad, a 1-mile  long property at the base of Mt. Washington facing the City of Pittsburgh. In 1976, Landmarks developed the site as a mixed-use historic adaptive reuse development that gave the foundation the opportunity to put its urban planning principles into practice. Aided by an initial generous gift from the Allegheny Foundation in 1976, Landmarks adapted five historic Pittsburgh and Lake Erie Railroad buildings for new uses and added a hotel, a dock for the Gateway Clipper fleet, and parking areas. Now shops, offices, restaurants, and entertainment anchor the historic riverfront site on the south shore of the Monongahela River, opposite the Golden Triangle (Pittsburgh). Station Square is Pittsburgh's premier attraction, generating over 3,500,000 visitors a year. It reflects a $100 million investment from all sources, with the lowest public cost and highest taxpayer return of any major renewal project in the Pittsburgh region since the 1950s. In 1994, Pittsburgh History and Landmarks Foundation sold Station Square in to Forest City Enterprises which created an endowment to help support its restoration efforts and educational programs. Each year the staff and docents of Pittsburgh History and Landmarks Foundation introduce more than 10,000 people  teachers, students, adults, and visitors  to the architectural heritage of the Pittsburgh region and to the value of historic preservation.%0a%3c %0a%3c During this period, Pittsburgh also became a national model for community development, through the work of activists such as Dorothy Mae Richardson, who founded Neighborhood Housing Services in 1968, an organization that became the model for the nationwide NeighborWorks America. Activists such a Richardson shared the aim of Landmarks to rehabilitate Pittsburgh's existing built landscape rather than to demolish and redevelop.%0a%3c %0a%3c In 1985, the J & L Steel site on the north side of the Monongahela river was cleared and a publicly subsidized High Technology Center was built. The Pittsburgh Technology Center, home to many major technology companies, is planning major expansion in the area soon. In the 1980s, the "Renaissance II" urban revitalization created numerous new structures, such as PPG Place. In the 1990s, the former sites of the Homestead, Duquesne and South Side J&L mills were cleared. In 1992, the new terminal at Pittsburgh International Airport opened. In 2001, the aging Three Rivers Stadium was replaced by Heinz Field and PNC Park, despite being rejected by voter referendum. In 2010, PPG Paints Arena, replaced the Civic Arena, which at the time was the oldest arena in the National Hockey League.%0a%3c %0a%3c Also in 1985, Al Michaels revealed to a national TV audience how Pittsburgh had transformed itself from an industrial rust belt city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c !%25center%25''Pittsburgh today''%0a%3c %0a%3c Present-day Pittsburgh, with a diversified economy, a low cost of living, and a rich infrastructure for education and culture, has been ranked as one of the World's Most Livable Cities. Tourism has recently boomed in Pittsburgh with nearly 3,000 new hotel rooms opening since 2004 and holding a consistently higher occupancy than in comparable cities. Meanwhile, tech giants such as: Apple, Google, IBM Watson, Facebook, and Intel have joined the 1,600 technology firms choosing to operate out of Pittsburgh. As a result of the proximity to CMU's National Robotics Engineering Center (NREC), there has a boom of autonomous vehicles companies. The region has also become a leader in green environmental design, a movement exemplified by the city's convention center. In the last twenty years the region has seen a small but influential group of Asian immigrants, including from the Indian sub-continent.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a---%0a> !!%25center%25''1940s: World War II''%0a> By the early 1940s, Miami was still recovering from the Great Depression when World War II started. Though many of the cities in Florida were heavily affected by the war and went into financial ruin, Miami remained relatively unaffected. Early in the war, German U-boats attacked several American ships including the Portero del Llano, which was attacked and sunk within sight of Miami Beach in May 1942. To defend against the U-boats, Miami was placed in two military districts, the Eastern Defense Command and the Seventh Naval District.%0a> %0a> In February 1942, the Gulf Sea Frontier was established to help guard the waters around Florida. By June of that year, more attacks forced military leaders in Washington, D.C. to increase the numbers of ships and men of the army group. They also moved the headquarters from Key West to the DuPont building in Miami, taking advantage of its location at the southeastern corner of the U.S. As the war against the U-boats grew stronger, more military bases sprang up in the Miami area. The U.S. Navy took control of Miami's docks and established air stations at the Opa-locka Airport and in Dinner Key. The Air Force also set up bases in the local airports in the Miami area.%0a> %0a> In addition, many military schools, supply stations, and communications facilities were established in the area. Rather than building large army bases to train the men needed to fight the war, the Army and Navy came to South Florida and converted hotels to barracks, movie theaters to classrooms, and local beaches and golf courses to training grounds. Overall, over five hundred thousand enlisted men and fifty thousand officers were trained in South Florida. After the end of the war, many servicemen and women returned to Miami, causing the population to rise to nearly half a million by 1950.%0a> %0a> !!%25center%25''1950s to 1970s.''%0a> !!!%25center%25''First Cuban wave''%0a> Following the 1959 Cuban revolution that unseated Fulgencio Batista and brought Fidel Castro to power, most Cubans who were living in Miami returned to Cuba. Soon after, however, many middle class and upper class Cubans moved to Florida en masse with few possessions. Some Miamians were upset about this, especially the African Americans, who believed that the Cuban workers were taking their jobs. In addition, the school systems struggled to educate the thousands of Spanish-speaking Cuban children. Many Miamians, fearing that the Cold War would become World War III, left the city, while others started building bomb shelters and stocking up on food and bottled water. Many of Miami's Cuban refugees realized for the first time that it would be a long time before they would get back to Cuba. In 1965 alone, 100,000 Cubans packed into the twice daily "freedom flights" from Havana to Miami. Most of the exiles settled into the Riverside neighborhood, which began to take on the new name of "Little Havana". This area emerged as a predominantly Spanish-speaking community, and Spanish speakers elsewhere in the city could conduct most of their daily business in their native tongue. By the end of the 1960s, more than four hundred thousand Cuban refugees were living in Dade County.%0a> %0a> In the 1960s and 1970s, the Attorney General's authority was used to grant parole, or special permission, to allow Cubans to enter the country. However, parole only allows an individual permission to enter the country, not to stay permanently. To allow these immigrants to stay, the Cuban Adjustment Act was passed in 1966. This act provides that the immigration status of any Cuban who arrived since 1959 who has been physically present in the United States for at least a year "may be adjusted by the Attorney General to that of an alien lawfully admitted for permanent residence" (green card holder). The individual must be admissible to the United States (i.e., not disqualified on criminal or other grounds).%0a> %0a> !!!%25center%25''Civil Rights Movement''%0a> %0a> Although Miami is not really considered a major center of the Civil Rights Movement of the 1950s and 1960s, it did not escape the change that occurred. Miami was a major city in the southern state of Florida, and had always had a substantial African American and black Caribbean population.%0a> %0a> On August 7 and 8, 1968, coinciding with the 1968 Republican National Convention, rioting broke out in the black Liberty City neighborhood, which required the Florida National Guard to restore order. Issues were "deplorable housing conditions, economic exploitation, bleak employment prospects, racial discrimination, poor police-community relations, and economic competition with Cuban refugees.". Overcrowding due to the near-destruction of the black Overtown neighborhood was also a factor.%0a> %0a> During the 1970s, Miami was a news leader due to the response to a Dade County ordinance protecting individuals on the basis of sexual orientation. Opposition to this ordinance, which was repealed, was led by Florida orange juice spokeswoman, Anita Bryant.%0a> %0a> In December 1979, police officers pursued motorcyclist Arthur McDuffie in a high-speed chase after McDuffie made a provocative gesture towards a police officer. The officers claimed that the chase ended when McDuffie crashed his motorcycle and died, but the coroner's report concluded otherwise. One of the officers testified that McDuffie fell off of his bike on an Interstate 95 on-ramp. When the police reached him he was injured but okay. The officers removed his helmet, beat him to death with their batons, put his helmet back on, and called an ambulance, claiming there had been a motorcycle accident. Eula McDuffie, the victim's mother, said to the Miami Herald a few days later, "They beat my son like a dog. They beat him just because he was riding a motorcycle and because he was black." A jury acquitted the officers after a brief deliberation.%0a> %0a> After learning of the verdict of the McDuffie case, one of the worst riots in the history of the United States, the Liberty City Riots of 1980, broke out. By the time the rioting ceased three days later, over 850 people had been arrested and at least 18 people had died. Property damage was estimated at around one hundred million dollars.%0a> %0a> In March 1980, the first black Dade County schools superintendent, Dr. Johnny L. Jones, was convicted on grand theft charges linked to gold-plated plumbing. His conviction was overturned on appeal and, on July 3, 1986, the state attorney Janet Reno announced that Jones would not be retried on these charges. However, in a separate case, he was convicted on misdemeanor charges of soliciting perjury and witness tampering and received a two-year jail sentence.%0a> %0a> !!%25center%25''1980s and 1990s''%0a> !!!%25center%25''Later immigration''%0a> The Mariel Boatlift of 1980 brought 150,000 Cubans to Miami, the largest transport in civilian history. Unlike the previous exodus of the 1960s, most of the Cuban refugees arriving were poor, some having been released from prisons or mental institutions to make the trip. During this time, many of the middle class non-Hispanic whites in the community left the city, often referred to as the "white flight". In 1960, Miami was 90%25 non-Hispanic white, but by 1990, it was only about 10%25 non-Hispanic white.%0a> %0a> In the 1980s, Miami started to see an increase in immigrants from other nations, such as Haiti. As the Haitian population grew in Miami, the area known today as "Little Haiti" emerged, centered on Northeast Second Avenue and 54th Street. In 1985, Xavier Suarez was elected as Mayor of Miami, becoming the first Cuban mayor of a major city. In the 1990s, the presence of Haitians was acknowledged with Haitian Creole language signs in public places and ballots during voting.%0a> %0a> Another major Cuban exodus occurred in 1994. To prevent it from becoming another Mariel Boatlift, the Clinton Administration announced a significant change in U.S. policy. In a controversial action, the administration announced that Cubans interdicted at sea would not be brought to the United States but instead would be taken by the Coast Guard to U.S. military installations at Guantanamo Bay or to Panama. During an eight-month period beginning in the summer of 1994, over 30,000 Cubans and more than 20,000 Haitians were interdicted and sent to live in camps outside the United States.%0a> %0a> On September 9, 1994, the United States and Cuba agreed to normalize migration between the two countries. The agreement codified the new U.S. policy of placing Cuban refugees in safe havens outside the United States, while obtaining a commitment from Cuba to discourage Cubans from sailing to America. In addition, the United States committed to admitting a minimum of 20,000 Cuban immigrants per year. That number is in addition to the admission of immediate relatives of U.S. citizens.%0a> %0a> On May 2, 1995, a second agreement with the Castro government paved the way for the admission to the United States of the Cubans housed at Guantanamo, who were counted primarily against the first year of the 20,000 annual admissions committed to by the Clinton Administration. It also established a new policy of directly repatriating Cubans interdicted at sea to Cuba. In the agreement, the Cuban government pledged not to retaliate against those who were repatriated.%0a> %0a> These agreements with the Cuban government led to what has been called the Wet Foot-Dry Foot Policy, whereby Cubans who made it to shore could stay in the United States  likely becoming eligible to adjust to permanent residence under the Cuban Adjustment Act. However, those who do not make it to dry land ultimately are repatriated unless they can demonstrate a well-founded fear of persecution if returned to Cuba. Because it was stated that Cubans were escaping for political reasons, this policy did not apply to Haitians, who the government claimed were seeking asylum for economic reasons.%0a> %0a> Since then, the Latin and Caribbean-friendly atmosphere in Miami has made it a popular destination for tourists and immigrants from all over the world. It is the third-biggest immigration port in the country after New York City and Los Angeles. In addition, large immigrant communities have settled in Miami from around the globe, including Europe, Africa, and Asia. The majority of Miami's European immigrant communities are recent immigrants, many living in the city seasonally, with a high disposable income.%0a> %0a> !!!%25center%25''Growth as a global city''%0a> In the 1980s, Miami became one of the United States' largest transshipment point for cocaine from Colombia, Bolivia, and Peru. The drug industry brought billions of dollars into Miami, which were quickly funneled through front organizations into the local economy. Luxury car dealerships, five-star hotels, condominium developments, swanky nightclubs, major commercial developments and other signs of prosperity began rising all over the city. As the money arrived, so did a violent crime wave that lasted through the early 1990s. The popular television program Miami Vice, which dealt with counter-narcotics agents in an idyllic upper-class rendition of Miami, spread the city's image as one of America's most glamorous subtropical paradises.%0a> %0a> Miami was host to many dignitaries and notable people throughout the 1980s and '90s. Pope John Paul II visited in November 1987, and held an open-air mass for 150,000 people in Tamiami Park. Queen Elizabeth II and three United States presidents also visited Miami. Among them is Ronald Reagan, who has a street named after him in Little Havana. Nelson Mandela's 1989 visit to the city was marked by ethnic tensions. Mandela had praised Cuban leader Fidel Castro for his anti-apartheid support on ABC News' Nightline. Because of this, the city withdrew its official greeting and no high-ranking official welcomed him. This led to a boycott by the local African American community of all Miami tourist and convention facilities until Mandela received an official greeting. However, all efforts to resolve it failed for months, resulting in an estimated loss of over US$10 million.%0a> %0a> !!!%25center%25''1990s''%0a> In 1992 Hurricane Andrew, caused more than $20 billion in damage just south of the Miami-Dade area.%0a> %0a> Several financial scandals involving the Mayor's office and City Commission during the 1980s and 1990s left Miami with the title of the United States' 4th poorest city by 1996. With a budget shortfall of $68 Million and its municipal bonds given a junk bond rating by Wall Street, in 1997, Miami became Florida's first city to have a state appointed oversight board assigned to it. In the same year, city voters rejected a resolution to dissolve the city and make it one entity with Dade County. The City's financial problems continued until political outsider Manny Diaz was elected Mayor of Miami in 2001.%0a> %0a> !%25center%25'''Twenty-first century'''%0a> !!%25center%25''2000s: A new era''%0a> %0a> In 2000, the Elin Gonzlez affair was an immigration battle in the Miami area. The controversy concerned six-year-old Elin Gonzlez who was rescued from the waters off the coast of Miami. The U.S. and the Cuban governments, his father Juan Miguel Gonzlez, his Miami relatives, and the Cuban-American community of Miami were all involved. The climactic stage of this prolonged battle was the April 22, 2000, seizure of Elin by federal agents, which drew the criticism of many in the Cuban-American community. During the controversy, Alex Penelas, the mayor of Miami-Dade County at the time, vowed that he would do nothing to assist the Bill Clinton administration and federal authorities in their bid to return the six-year-old boy to Cuba. Tens of thousands of protesters, many of whom were outraged at the raid, poured out into the streets of Little Havana and demonstrated. Car horns blared, demonstrators turned over signs, trash cans, and newspaper racks and some small fires were started. Rioters jammed a 10-block area of Little Havana. Shortly afterwards, many Miami businesses closed, as their owners and managers participated in a short, one-day boycott against the city, attempting to affect its tourism industry. Employees of airlines, cruise lines, hotels, car rental companies, and major retailers participated in the boycott. Elin Gonzlez returned to Cuba with his father on June 28, 2000.%0a> %0a> In 2003, the controversial Free Trade Area of the Americas negotiation occurred. It was a proposed agreement to reduce trade barriers while increasing intellectual property rights. During the 2003 meeting in Miami, the Free Trade Area of the Americas was met by heavy opposition from anti-corporatization and anti-globalization protests.%0a> %0a> On June 27, 2005, the popular ex-city commissioner Arthur Teele walked into the main lobby of the Miami Herald headquarters, dropped off a package for columnist Jim DeFede, and told the security guard to tell his wife Stephanie he "loved her", before pulling out a gun and committing suicide. His suicide happened the day the alternative weekly Miami New Times published salacious details of Teele's alleged affairs, including allegations that Teele had sex with a transsexual prostitute and used cocaine. At the time, Teele was being investigated by federal authorities for fraud and money laundering for allegedly taking $59,000 in kickbacks to help a businessman get millions of dollars in contracts at Miami International Airport. Teele was suspended from his job in 2004 by Florida governor Jeb Bush after being arrested for trying to run a police officer off the road. Teele was also charged in December 2004 with ten counts of unlawful compensation on charges he took $135,000 from TLMC Inc., promising that it would be awarded lucrative contracts to redevelop neighborhoods in Miami. Teele was also found guilty in March 2005 for threatening an undercover detective.%0a> %0a> In the latter half of the 20002010 decade, Miami saw an extensive boom of high rise architecture, dubbed a "Miami Manhattanization" wave. This included the construction of many of the tallest buildings in Miami, with nearly 20 of the cities tallest 25 buildings finished after 2005. 2008 and 2007 saw the completion of even more of these buildings. This boom transformed the look of downtown Miami, which is now considered to have one of the largest skylines in the United States, ranked behind New York City and Chicago.[A] This boom slowed after the 2008 global financial crisis, with some projects being put on hold and none of the cities tallest buildings being constructed in 2010.%0a> %0a> The Port Miami Tunnel connecting Watson Island to PortMiami on Dodge Island, which cost $700 million, was opened in 2014.%0a> %0a> In the 2010s, there was a second skyscraper building boom.%0a> %0a262,17407c158,564%0a%3c !!'''History of Pittsburgh Pennsylvania'''%0a%3c !!1700s%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1717'''%0a%3c *Michael Bezallion, Pennsylvania fur trader, passed the future site of Pittsburgh en route from the Illinois country to Philadelphia, where he made a report of the trip.%0a%3c %0a%3c *White traders began to establish trading posts in the territory of the Ohio, Allegheny, and Monongahela valleys. The largest settlement was Logstown (now Ambridge), about four miles north of the fork of the Ohio.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1748'''%0a%3c *Conrad Weiser (1696-1760), the German, who for thirty years was prominent in Pennsylvanias negotiations with the Indians, was the guest of the Delaware Indian Chief Shannopin at the mouth of Two Mile Run (the present Lawrenceville section of Pittsburgh).%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1749'''%0a%3c *August 7, Celoron de Blainville (1693-1759), with 43 French soldiers, 180 Canadians, and a band of Indians, floated past the site of Pittsburgh, once more claiming possession of the Ohio Valley for King Louis XV of France. Chaplain Father Bonnecamps kept a journal and made a map of the trip.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1751'''%0a%3c *May, Philippe Thomas Joncaire, with a troop of Indians, passed by en route to Logstown to establish a French trading house there.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1752'''%0a%3c *May 28, Joshua Fry, James Patton, and Lunsford Lomax, Virginia agents chosen to treat with the Indians at Logstown, held a conference with Chief Shannopin.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1753'''%0a%3c *November 23,  The 21-year old Major George Washington (1732-99), emissary from Virginias Governor Robert Dinwiddie to the French commandant at Fort LeBoeuf on French Creek (now Waterford, Pa.), observed the land at the junction of the Allegheny and Monongahela rivers (where Pittsburgh is today) and described it as "extremely well situated for a Fort; as it has the absolute Command of both Rivers. The Land at the Point is 20 or 25 Feet above the common Surface of the Water; and a considerable Bottom of flat, well timbere%0a%3c %0a%3c *December 30, George Washington and his guide, Christopher Gist, were stranded on Garrison Island in the Allegheny River after their raft had been dashed to pieces by floating ice.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1754'''%0a%3c *February 17, William Trent (1715-87), the Indian trader, came to the forks. When the militiamen whom he had enlisted in the Monongahela Valley arrived, Trent began to build a fort and named it Fort Prince George.%0a%3c %0a%3c *April 13, Ensign Edward Ward, temporarily in charge of Fort Prince George, learned that French troops were on the march against him.%0a%3c %0a%3c *April 17, When the French force of about 500 men, under Commandant Pierre de Contreoeur, arrived at the forks, Ensign Ward and his 41 men had to surrender their building. The French began to build a large fort on the spot and named it Fort Duquesne, after the Marquis de Duquesne (1700-78), governor general of New France from 1752 to 1755.%0a%3c %0a%3c *July 4, The French subdued Colonel Washington at Fort Necessity.%0a%3c %0a%3c *July 28, The Scotsman Robert Stobo, a friend of Governor Dinwiddie, was one of two hostages taken to Fort Duquesne after the battle at Fort Necessity. During his imprisonment he sent out letters and a sketch of the fort to the English.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1755'''%0a%3c *May 24, The French commandant announced that Fort Duquesne was completed.%0a%3c %0a%3c *July 9, A British expedition under General Edward Braddock, marching to attack Fort Duquesne, was defeated not far from the fort by an army of French and Indian warriors. Some of the English captives were burned alive by the Indians.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1756'''%0a%3c Spring Fort Duquesne was damaged by a flood.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1758'''%0a%3c *August 30, The French commandant at Fort Duquesne learned that a British force led by General John Forbes was at Loyalbanna (the present Ligonier) and was planning to advance against the fort.%0a%3c %0a%3c *September 14, Major James Grant, with Forbess army, received permission to attack Fort Duquesne. He led his force of 800 into disaster; one third of his men were killed.%0a%3c %0a%3c *November 24, General Forbess army took possession of the remnants of Fort Duquesne, which the French had burned and evacuated earlier in the day.%0a%3c %0a%3c *November 25, The English flag flew over the ruins of the demolished Fort Duquesne.%0a%3c %0a%3c *November 26, Five thousand soldiers knelt near the fort in observance of Thanksgiving.%0a%3c %0a%3c *November 29, A detachment of soldiers who had been with Major Grant on his fateful attack in September, buried the bodies of their dead comrades.%0a%3c %0a%3c *November 29, ...the camp at Fort Duquesne was referred to as Fort Argyle.%0a%3c %0a%3c *December 1, General Forbes formally named the camp Pittsburgh. On January 21 the following year, writing from Philadelphia, the general told William Pitt, the English prime minister, that he had "used the freedom of giving your name to Fort Duquesne, as - - - it was in some measure the being activated by your spirits that now makes us Masters of the place."%0a%3c %0a%3c *December 4, Indian chiefs, at a conference in the fort, promised peace to Colonel Henry Bouquet (1719-65), the Swiss soldier who accompanied General Forbes. They also promised the return of all English captives.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1759'''%0a%3c *January 9, Temporary barracks, about a thousand feet from the site of Fort Duquesne, had been built; General Forbes authorized a payment of 124/13/2 for the work.%0a%3c %0a%3c *March 1, The building of a permanent fort -- Fort Pitt -- had begun under the direction of a new commanding officer, General John Stanwix, and engineer Harry Gordon.%0a%3c %0a%3c *October 24, General Stanwix made a treaty of peace and friendship with the Indians.%0a%3c %0a%3c *October 29, Adam Stephen, a lieutenant colonel in the Virginia regiment who survived Grants defeat, complained that the Pennsylvania Indian traders were taking over the lucrative fur trade and that the Indians had brought 20 tons of skins and furs to Fort Pitt in the previous three months.%0a%3c %0a%3c ''1760''%0a%3c *July, Colonel James Burd counted the population of Pittsburgh; he found that 149 people, besides the soldiers, were living there.%0a%3c %0a%3c *August 12, General Robert Monckton, in command at Fort Pitt, reaffirmed Stanwixs treaty with the Indians.%0a%3c %0a%3c *August 12, James Boggs, Alleghenys first white settler, built his cabin.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1761'''%0a%3c *March, Lieutenant Bernard Ratzer drew up a plan for the British military reservation which included 40 acres of vegetable and flower gardens and the "Kings Orchard" of apple and pear trees in the area between Fort Pitt and the Allegheny River.%0a%3c %0a%3c *April 14, According to a count ordered by Colonel Bouquet, Pittsburghs population consisted of 163 men, 45 women, and 25 children, who lived in 160 houses outside the fort.%0a%3c %0a%3c *October 12, George Croghan, an Irishman who came to America in 1741, was the most prominent of the Pennsylvania traders. As Indian agent at Fort Pitt, he noted that the Indians had returned 338 white captives to the fort since June 1759.%0a%3c %0a%3c *December, Fort Pitt, surrounded by moats drawing water from the Allegheny River, was completed. Its cost was estimated between 60,000 and 100,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1762'''%0a%3c *January 9, The Allegheny, Monongahela, and Ohio rivers, reaching a stage of 39.2 feet at the Point, badly damaged the fort. All but 13 barrels of powder were destroyed.%0a%3c %0a%3c *May 2, The Indian Chief Delaware George a faithful friend of the British, was buried with full military honors on the north side of the Allegheny River opposite Fort Pitt.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1763'''%0a%3c *March 9, When the rivers rose to 41 feet at the Point, Fort Pitt was inundated by six inches of water.%0a%3c %0a%3c *March 30, Pontiacs uprising against the whites brought all the inhabitants from the outside within the confines of Fort Pitt. Most of the surrounding homes were demolished.%0a%3c %0a%3c *June 3, Those houses which had not been destroyed were burned by the Indians.%0a%3c %0a%3c *August 11, Colonel Bouquets army defeated the Indians at the Battle of Bushy Run on August 5 and 6, thus the siege of Fort Pitt had come to an end. The people, who had taken shelter in the fort, returned to the places where they once lived and set out to build new cabins.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1764'''%0a%3c *October 3, Bouquets army forced the Delaware and Shawnee Indians to fulfill their agreement and bring all their English captives to the fort.%0a%3c %0a%3c *November 15, The Indians brought 60 captives to Fort Pitt%0a%3c %0a%3c *November 15, Colonel Bouquets Redoubt -- the Blockhouse, which is still in existence -- was built outside the walls of the fort, midway between the Ohio and Monongahela bastions.%0a%3c %0a%3c *November 15, John Campbell made a plan for the town, consisting of four blocks between Water and Second streets and Ferry and Market Streets, with an alley, Chancery Lane, between Ferry and Market.%0a%3c %0a%3c *November 15, Richard and William Butlers log cabins were the first to be completed after the lifting of the siege.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1766'''%0a%3c *March, Baynton, Wharton, and Morgan, the well-known Philadelphia trading firm, erected a storehouse, the first shingle-roofed building in Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1768'''%0a%3c *April, Conferences between the Indians and the British were held at Fort Pitt; 1103 male Indians came with their retinue of wives and children.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1769'''%0a%3c *The Penns Pittsburgh Manor, some of it within the present Golden Triangle area, was surveyed and found to include 5766 acres.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1770'''%0a%3c *October, George Washington arrived for a visit in Pittsburgh. He noted in his diary: "We lodged in what is called the Town, distant about 300 yards from the Fort, at one Mr. Semples, who keeps a very good house of entertainment."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c '''1772'''%0a%3c *October 12, Captain Charles Edmonstone of the Eighteenth Royal Regiment, in command at Fort Pitt, sold the installation to William Thompson and Alexander Ross for 50 pounds New York currency. Thus ended the Crowns jurisdiction over the military reservation and fort at Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1773'''%0a%3c *John Ormsby was granted the right to keep the first licensed ferry across the Monongahela River.%0a%3c %0a%3c *Pennsylvania obtained permission from Great Britain to garrison militia at Fort Pitt.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1774'''%0a%3c *January 6, The unsettled boundary between Pennsylvania and Virginia became hotly contested when Dr. John Connolly posted a proclamation on the walls of Fort Pitt to announce his appointment by Lord Dunmore, governor of the southern colony, as "Captain, Commandant of the Militia of Pittsburgh and its Dependencies." He ordered the people to assemble as a militia on January 25.%0a%3c %0a%3c *January 24, Pennsylvania challenged Virginias claim to Pittsburgh by arresting Dr. Connolly and removing him to Hannastown to stand trial.%0a%3c %0a%3c *February 2, By promising to return in April for trial, Dr. Connolly persuaded the sheriff of Westmoreland County to release him. He then obtained a commission as justice of the peace from the court of Augusta County, Virginia, which was held to include Pittsburgh, and returned to the forks, took possession of Fort Pitt, and organized his militia.%0a%3c %0a%3c *April 25, Governor Dunmore ordered all the inhabitants "to pay their quit-rents and all public dues" to officers appointed by him.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c '''1775'''%0a%3c *February 21, Dr. Connolly changed the name of Fort Pitt to Fort Dunmore. The Augusta County Court, which had been adjourned from Staunton, Virginia, on December 6, 1774, was organized at the Fort.%0a%3c %0a%3c *February 23, Jacob Bausman was licensed by the Virginia Court to keep a ferry over the Monongahela at the foot of Wood Street where John Ormsby had his establishment for the previous two years.%0a%3c %0a%3c *March, Governor Dunmore advised Dr. Connolly to disband his militia and devote himself to winning the support of the Indians for the British cause.%0a%3c %0a%3c *May 16, In a convention held at Pittsburgh, frontiersmen of the territory set up a Committee of Safety approved the action of the colonies in their revolt against the Crown, and resolved that it was the "indispensable duty of every American" to resist tyranny.%0a%3c %0a%3c *July 25, Dr. Connolly left for Virginia; Pennsylvania authority prevailed generally in the Pittsburgh area.%0a%3c %0a%3c *August, John Neville (1731-1803), with 100 militia, took possession of the fort.%0a%3c %0a%3c *August 25, A band of "patriots" burned the tea stock of the merchants Joseph Symonds and John Campbell.%0a%3c %0a%3c *October 7, By the Treaty of Pittsburgh, the chiefs of the Indian tribes in the area pledged friendship and neutrality in the conflict between Great Britain and her colonies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c '''1776'''%0a%3c *October, By a Second Treaty of Pittsburgh, the Indians confirmed their agreement of the year before.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c '''1777'''%0a%3c *June 1, Fort Pitt, once again bearing its proud name, became a United States fort when Brigadier General Edward Hand took it over from Captain John Neville.%0a%3c %0a%3c *August 20, The Virginia Court moved out of the fort.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c '''1778'''%0a%3c *June, David Rogers, with about 40 men, left Fort Pitt to bring a much-needed cargo of ammunition from New Orleans. His return was intercepted.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c '''1779'''%0a%3c *August 11, Colonel Daniel Brodhead left Fort Pitt with 600 men to destroy the Seneca Indian villages along the upper Allegheny River.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c '''1781'''%0a%3c *Hugh Henry Brackenridge arrived from Philadelphia to practice law. He soon became an important civic and political leader in western Pennsylvania.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c '''1782'''%0a%3c *The German Evangelical Protestant (Congregational) Church, the first organized religious group in Pittsburgh, held services in a small block-house at the corner of present Wood and Diamond streets. Reverend John William Weber was pastor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c '''1784'''%0a%3c *June, In the first real estate sale on record, Isaac Craig and Samuel Bayard purchased three acres of land lying between Fort Pitt and the Allegheny River.%0a%3c %0a%3c *June, Bouquets Redoubt-the Blockhouse was converted into a dwelling and continued as such until April 1, 1894.%0a%3c %0a%3c *June, The Penns Pittsburgh Manor was laid out in lots by George Woods and Thomas Vickroy. The manor embraced the tongue of land between the two rivers as far as present Grant Street and Eleventh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c '''1785'''%0a%3c *August 15, The Supreme Executive Council of Pennsylvania ordered John Ormsby to "take possession of Fort Pitt in behalf of the Commonwealth, upon its being relinquished" by the United States.%0a%3c %0a%3c *August 15, Lodge No. 45, Ancient Order of York Masons, was organized.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c '''1786'''%0a%3c *February 28, The State Legislature granted a charter for the Pittsburgh Academy "for the education of youth in useful arts, sciences and literature." Judge Hugh Henry Brackenridge was prime organizer.%0a%3c %0a%3c *July 29, The Pittsburgh Gazette, first newspaper west of the Allegheny Mountains, was published as a weekly by John Scull and Joseph Hall, printers.%0a%3c %0a%3c *July 29, In the columns of the newly launched gazette, Hugh H. Brackenridge wrote that, at the junction of the three rivers in the morning, "a light fog is usually incumbent." But, he observed, "in as much as it consists of vapor. . . Which the sun of the preceding day had extracted from trees and flowers and in the evening had sent back into dew it is experienced to be healthful."%0a%3c %0a%3c *July 29, Niles Weekly Register reported that "36 log houses, one stone house, one frame house, and five small stores" extended along Chancery Lane and Market Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c *September 24, The Penns donated two and one half lots each to the First Presbyterian, the German Evangelical Protestant, and the Trinity Protestant Episcopal churches.%0a%3c %0a%3c *September 29, The First Presbyterian Church was incorporated by an act of the Legislature.%0a%3c %0a%3c *September 29, David Redick was appointed by the Supreme Executive Council to lay Out the "Town Common and lots in the reserve tract opposite Pittsburgh." The reserved tract had been authorized by the Legislature in September 1787.%0a%3c %0a%3c *September 29, The first market house was erected.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c '''1788'''%0a%3c *September 24, Mainly through efforts of Hugh H. Brackenridge, lawyer and state assemblyman, Allegheny County was created out of parts of Westmoreland and Washington counties; Pittsburgh was decreed the county seat.%0a%3c %0a%3c *November 19, Lots in the reserved tract were sold at public sale in Philadelphia.%0a%3c %0a%3c *December 16, The first Quarter Sessions Court of Allegheny County convened in Pittsburgh at Andrew Watson's tavern.%0a%3c %0a%3c *December 16, Regular mail service to Philadelphia was inaugurated.%0a%3c %0a%3c *December 16, A Mechanical Society, devoted to the betterment of the workingman, was organized.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c '''1789'''%0a%3c *March 14, The first Court of Common Pleas convened in Andrew Watson s tavern.%0a%3c %0a%3c *July 2, The gazette reported: "Yesterday was brought to this place and buried, the bodies of two young men, named Arthur Graham and Alexander Campbell, who had gone out to fish. They were killed by the savages about two miles from this place."%0a%3c %0a%3c *July 2, Captain Thomas Hutchins, geographer of the United States, died at John Ormsbys.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c '''1790'''%0a%3c *April, Army garrison officers gave a theatrical presentation -- Cato and All the 'World's a Stage.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1791'''%0a%3c *February, Isaac Craig was appointed quartermaster general and was given permission to repair Fort Pitt.%0a%3c %0a%3c *September 6, Robert Johnson, the revenue collector, was tarred and feathered by angered citizens.%0a%3c %0a%3c *November, An army hospital was established "in a rented house in the town," with Dr. Carmichael in charge. Samuel Slater started a cotton mill with a staff of nine children from seven to twelve years of age.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c '''1792'''%0a%3c *May 1, Captain Hughes, in command of the army garrison at Fort Pitt, occupied Fort Fayette (LaFayette), just completed near the Allegheny close to the old bastion.  General Anthony Wayne and his army arrived in town.%0a%3c %0a%3c '''1793'''%0a%3c September 12, %0a%3c The citys first fire engine was purchased at a cost of 1200, and the Eagle Fire Engine and Hose Company, the first to be organized in the town, was formed with headquarters at First Street (Avenue) between Market and Ferry.%0a%3c %0a%3c *October 14, Regular river packet service was inaugurated by Jacob Myers between Pittsburgh and Cincinnati.%0a%3c %0a%3c *October 14, Modern Chivalry, volume three, a novel by Hugh Henry Brackenridge. was printed by John Scull. It was the first book printed west of the Allegheny Mountains.%0a%3c %0a%3c *October 14, George Anshutz built a small furnace in Two Mile Run (present Shadyside). One of its first tasks was to manufacture cannon balls for General Anthony Waynes army.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c '''1794'''%0a%3c *April 22, Pittsburgh was incorporated as a borough.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 19, 1794%0a%3c George Robinson and Josiah Tannehill were chosen chief burgesses in the first borough election.%0a%3c %0a%3c *August, Farmers who protested against the collection of excise tax on whisky marched to Pittsburgh from their rendezvous at Braddocks Field.%0a%3c %0a%3c *November 12, Burgess George Robinson and three other Pittsburghers were among 18 southwestern Pennsylvanians arrested by General Irvines troops during the "dreadful night" of the Whisky Insurrection.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1795%0a%3c First glass factory was built by Major Isaac Craig and General OHara on the north bank of the Ohio River across from the Point. It manufactured bottles.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 18, 1795%0a%3c Weekly mail service was established between Pittsburgh and Philadelphia.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1796%0a%3c A census of Pittsburgh showed a population of 1300.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1796%0a%3c The first Methodist Episcopal Church service was held in the "unoccupied meeting house" of the Presbyterians.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 28, 1797%0a%3c Red Pole, great Shawnee Indian chief, died at Pittsburgh and was buried in Trinity churchyard.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 5, 1797%0a%3c Notice of July 8 advertised the sale of all building material remaining on the site of the abandoned Fort Pitt.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 19, 1798%0a%3c The ship President Adams was launched at nearby Elizabeth; it was built in Pittsburgh and armed for service against the Spaniards on the lower Mississippi. The Senator Ross was built in Pittsburgh the same year. Glass was blown at OHaras Glass-works, the first flint glass made west of the Alleghenies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1799%0a%3c The first courthouse, a two-story brick structure, was completed. It stood on the western half of the Diamond. County, state, and federal courts convened here until 1841.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1799%0a%3c Reformed Presbyterian Church was organized.%0a%3c %0a%3c 1800s %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1800%0a%3c Zadok Cramer, a New Jersey printer, purchased Gilkinsons Book Store, renamed it the Sign of the Franklin Head, began a printing and book-binding business, and printed his first Almanack.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1800%0a%3c Pittsburgh commercial life revolved around 63 shops, 23 of them general stores, six shoe shops, four bakeries, and four hat shops.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1800%0a%3c Population: 1565; Allegheny County, 15,087.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1800%0a%3c Perkins store, first "department store" west of Philadelphia, was opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 16, 1800%0a%3c The citys second news-paper, Tree of Liberty, was published by John Israel, with Hugh Henry Brackenridge as chief backer and chief editorial writer.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 24, 1801%0a%3c The associate Presbyterian Church was organized. Zadok Cramer printed the first edition of the Navigator. a guide to river navigation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1802%0a%3c Jeffery Scaife Tin and Japanned Ware Manufactory, parent organization of the William B. Scaife & Sons Company began business in the Diamond.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1802%0a%3c Pittsburgh Almanack stated that industry in Pittsburgh included one large brewery, two glassworks, one fine-glass factory, one large paper mill, several oil mills, powder works, ironworks, saltworks, saw - and grist - mills, and a boat yard.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 9, 1802%0a%3c The Borough Council ordered four public wells to be sunk on Market Street -- the beginning of Pittsburghs water system.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1803%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Almanack for the Year 1803 estimated the total value of Pittsburgh manufacturing at $358,903. Of that amount, iron manufacturing accounted for $56,548 from the production of 180 tons of castings and bar iron and 40 tons of nails. Textile manufacturing was second in value with $46,825.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1803%0a%3c The rivers were beginning to be used for the shipment of coal from Pittsburgh to Philadelphia via New Orleans.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 26, 1803%0a%3c In the first theatrical production in the city, the Bromly and Arnold traveling troupe of actors presented a tragedy, The gamester, at the courthouse.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 26, 1803%0a%3c A public meeting was held to consider a proposal for a bank in the borough.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1804%0a%3c A newly established stagecoach line was offering "speedy" six-day service between Pittsburgh and Philadelphia. Peter Eltonhead, an Englishman, founded the first large-scale cotton mill.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1804%0a%3c General Presley Neville, burgess of Pittsburgh, asked George Stevenson, president of the Council, to study smoke problems and, in particular, the possibility of higher chimneys as a smoke-control measure. His letter stated that "not only the comfort, health and, in some measure, the con-sequence of the place, but the harmony of the inhabitants, depends upon speedy measures being adopted to remedy this nuisance."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1804%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Foundry (predecessor of Mackintosh-Hemphill Company), first in the city, was established at Fifth and Smithfield by Joseph McClurg.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 9, 1804%0a%3c Pittsburghs first bank, a branch of the Bank of Pennsylvania at Philadelphia, opened for business at a location on Second Street, between Market and Ferry.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December, 1804%0a%3c In the first recorded strike in Pittsburgh, traveling journeymen shoemakers "made a turnout for higher wages."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1805%0a%3c Commonwealth, a weekly newspaper, began publication.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 1, 1805%0a%3c Cornerstone was laid for the Old Round Church of St. Lukes Protestant Episcopal Congregation. Its charter was granted on September 1.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 21, 1806%0a%3c The United States gazette for the Country, at Philadelphia, published a letter from a Pittsburgh correspondent reporting: "On Wednesday last (the 8th inst.) a duel was fought in the vicinity of Pitts-burgh between Tarleton Bates, Esq., the prothonotary of Allegheny County, and a person of the name of Stewart, a storekeeper here, in which Mr. Bates was killed at the second fireThe minds of the people of Pittsburgh appear much inflamed."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February, 1806%0a%3c The first company prepared to build a turnpike from Pittsburgh to Harrisburg was incorporated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 10, 1806%0a%3c A flood of 37.1 feet was recorded.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1807%0a%3c George Robinson and Edward Ensel glassworks was in operation. Anthony Beelen established the Eagle foundry.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1807%0a%3c George Miltenbergers Copper and Tinware Manufactory was established.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1808%0a%3c Bakewell and Page purchased the Robinson and Ensel glassworks. In 1818 the firm furnished President Monroe "a complete set of flint glass, each piece engraved with the arms of the United States."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1808%0a%3c James B. Scott and Company (Follansbee Steel Corporation) was founded by James Park.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1809%0a%3c Pittsburgh Steam Flour Mill, the first west of the Alleghenies, was established by Oliver and Owen Evans.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1810%0a%3c Bank of Pittsburgh, second in the borough and first with local capital, was organized and operated for a time under the name of Pittsburgh Manufacturing Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1810%0a%3c Population: 4786; Allegheny County, 25,317.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 9, 1810%0a%3c The city was inundated by a flood of 35.2 feet.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1811%0a%3c The Reverend Francis Herron began a 49-year pastorate in the First Presbyterian Church.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 31, 1811%0a%3c The Vigilant Fire Company was organized.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 24, 1811%0a%3c First Masonic Hall dedicated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August, 1811%0a%3c Old St. Patricks Church, the citys first Roman Catholic church, was dedicated at Liberty and Washington streets.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 25, 1811%0a%3c The New Orleans, which was built at a cost of $40,000 by Nicholas Roosevelt, sailed down the Ohio to establish the first regular packet service between Natchez and New Orleans and thus became the first steamboat to navigate western rivers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1812%0a%3c The first rolling mill was built by Christopher Cowan.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1812%0a%3c Rigging for Oliver H. Perrys fleet on Lake Erie was made in the borough. Steam-engine works, built by Oliver Evans and managed by Mark Stackhouse, went into operation in May.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1812%0a%3c Christopher Cowan built a steam mill for slitting iron.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1812%0a%3c Elliott Nursery was established at Smithfield Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 7, 1812%0a%3c William Turner and Company opened what is believed to have been the citys first theater.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 10, 1812%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Blues, a military unit, left on a years expedition in the Ohio Country, in the service of the United States.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1813%0a%3c The Comet, a stern-wheel steamboat, was built.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 10, 1813%0a%3c Humane Society was organized.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 27, 1813%0a%3c First recorded meeting of the Pittsburgh Permanent Library Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1814%0a%3c A stern-wheel steamboat left Pittsburgh with a cargo of guns destined for General Jackson at New Orleans. Pepin, Brishard, and Cayetano conducted the first circus.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1814%0a%3c Western Medical Society was organized%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1814%0a%3c Allegheny Arsenal was established by the federal government. It was designed by B. H. Latrobe and built in the Lawrenceville district under the direction of Colonel Abraham R. Butler at a cost of $300,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1814%0a%3c Anchor Steam Paper Mill, first paper-mill in Pittsburgh, was built by Henry Holdehip.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 10, 1814%0a%3c A letter printed in the gazette said: "Although much of the prosperity of Pittsburgh is owing to its Fires, it is not be concealed that the effects of those fires have become subjects of complaint. That the evil (if it be an evil to be enveloped in smoke) is daily increasing and that relief is now universally called for."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 23, 1814%0a%3c Bank of Pittsburgh was reorganized with capital of $600,000 and George Wilkins as president.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1815%0a%3c Pittsburgh Directory for 1815, the citys first directory, was compiled and published by James M. Riddle.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1815%0a%3c The Farmers and Mechanics Bank, founded by John Scull, was incorporated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1815%0a%3c The weekly Mercury began publication.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March, 1815%0a%3c Newspapers advocated "some plan for smoke abatement."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1816%0a%3c Whale-oil lamps were installed as the citys first street lights.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 27, 1816%0a%3c According to the gazette, Alexander Thompson, "who resides on the turnpike road 4~2 miles from Pittsburgh," reported that during 1815, excluding iron shipments, a total of "5,800 road waggons laden with merchandise, etc., passed his farm for Pittsburgh. The greater part of these waggons returned loaded with cordage, salt petre, etc., to the east of the mountains."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February, 1816%0a%3c Flood waters reached a stage of 36.2 feet.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 18, 1816%0a%3c Pittsburgh was incorporated as a city under an act providing for a mayor, one select and one common council, 12 aldermen, and a recorder.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 9, 1816%0a%3c Ebenezer Denny, merchant, began serving term as the first mayor of Pittsburgh; James Ross as first president of the select council; William Wilkins as first president of the common council.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 2, 1816%0a%3c The Farmers and Mechanics Bank was chartered.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1817%0a%3c First shoe-jobbing firm in United States, H. Childs and Company, was established.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1817%0a%3c A branch of the second Bank of the United States was established in Pittsburgh with John Thaw as cashier. This bank took over the business of the defunct Bank of Pennsylvania and was named Office of Discounts and Deposits of the United States.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1817%0a%3c John Darragh began his eight-year term as the citys second mayor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 5, 1817%0a%3c President James Monroe visited arsenal in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 25, 1818%0a%3c Ten thousand men, women, and children witnessed the first execution of a white man in Allegheny County, the hanging of John Tiernan, who was found guilty of killing his best friend.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 6, 1818%0a%3c Pittsburgh first bank robbery, $104,000 was stolen from Farmers and Mechanics Bank; the accused robbers, Pluymart and Emmons, were captured soon thereafter.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 20, 1818%0a%3c A federal court for Western Pennsylvania was established here; Jonathan Hoge Walker was appointed first judge by President James Monroe. The Pittsburgh-Harrisburg turnpike was opened to travel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 18, 1819%0a%3c Pittsburgh Academy was rechartered by the Legislature and renamed Western University of Pennsylvania; its location was on Third Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 16, 1819%0a%3c General James OHara, Pittsburghs pioneer industrialist, died at his home at the Point.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 16, 1819%0a%3c The first bridge across the Allegheny River (Federal and St. Clair streets) was completed. It served till 1860, when it was replaced by a suspension bridge.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 16, 1819%0a%3c Monongahela Bridge was erected at a cost of $102,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 16, 1819%0a%3c Angle iron was rolled at the Union Rolling Mill, the first complete rolling mill in the United States.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 16, 1819%0a%3c The citys first steam cotton mill, James Arthurs and Sons Cotton Factory, began production.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1820%0a%3c Population: 7248; Allegheny County, 34,927.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1820%0a%3c The citys Alms House was built.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1821%0a%3c Turnpike was completed from Pittsburgh to Erie, via Butler, Mercer, and Meadville.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1821%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Recorder, a Presbyterian journal, was first issued.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June, 1821%0a%3c Pittsburgh Medical Society was organized.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1822%0a%3c N. Holmes and Sons, the citys first family-owned bank, was established.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 28, 1823%0a%3c Henry Clay was a visitor. The Apprentice Library was established as Pittsburghs first free public library.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1824%0a%3c Western University of Pennsylvania conferred bachelors degrees for the first time. There were six in the graduating class.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1824%0a%3c The Councils passed an ordinance providing for a central city water system.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1825%0a%3c Allegheny Theological Seminary was established in Allegheny by the Associate Reformed Presbyterian Church.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 7, 1825%0a%3c Western Theological Seminary was founded in Allegheny City by Presbyterian Church.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 30, 1825%0a%3c The Marquis de Lafayette arrived at the Mansion House for a two-week visit. One of the most spectacular social events was a ball held at Colonel Ramsays Hotel on Wood Street at Third Avenue in honor of the French statesman.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 4, 1826%0a%3c Composer Stephen Collins Foster was born at 3600 Penn Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September, 1826%0a%3c The citys first water reservoir was completed on Grants Hill.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December, 1826%0a%3c Work was started on the Pennsylvania Canal.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1827%0a%3c St. Pauls Church was organized under leadership of Father Charles Bonaventure Maguire, and a building, which six years later became St. Pauls Cathedral, was erected at Fifth Avenue and Grant Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February, 1827%0a%3c The Bethel African Methodist Episcopal Church, the first Negro church west of the Allegheny Mountains, was instituted at Water and Smithfield streets.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April, 1827%0a%3c The Albion, first steamboat to travel up the Allegheny River as far as Kittanning, left the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 20, 1827%0a%3c Henry Clay, Secretary of State, visited the city again.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 16, 1827%0a%3c Western Theological Seminary was opened for study.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 22, 1827%0a%3c Western Penitentiary, the first state penal institution west of the mountains, was completed in Allegheny.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 28, 1827%0a%3c Contract was let to construct the Aqueduct to carry the Pennsylvania Canal over the Allegheny River to the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1828%0a%3c John Irwin was elected the first burgess of Allegheny.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1828%0a%3c First museum and art gallery was opened to public.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1828%0a%3c Etna Iron Works, first iron-pipe manufacturing plant west of Alleghenies, was built by H. S. Spang and Son (Predecessor of Spang, Chalfant and Company).%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 14, 1828%0a%3c Allegheny was incorporated as a borough.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 3, 1828%0a%3c Foundation stone was laid for the Washington Lock, the first of four, to connect the Pennsylvania Canal and the Monongahela River.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September, 1828%0a%3c The citys first water-supply system, with a reservoir on Grants Hill and a pumping station at the foot of Cecil Alley, was ready for service.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 10, 1829%0a%3c The Aqueduct carrying the Canal over the Allegheny River to the Canal basin in the city went into service.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1830%0a%3c The anti-Masonic, anti-Jackson councils elected Mathew B. Lowrie mayor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1830%0a%3c Population: Pittsburgh, 12,568; Allegheny, 2801 citizens, eight slaves; Allegheny County, 50,552.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March, 1830%0a%3c Natural gas was discovered in Saw Mill Run at depth of 627 feet.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1831%0a%3c David G. Blythe, the artist, arrived in the city to study wood carving.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1831%0a%3c John H. Mellor established on Wood Street a firm said to be the first piano house in America.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 12, 1831%0a%3c Pittsburgh Times began publication.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 1, 1831%0a%3c First steam ferry began operating at the foot of Penn Street. Duquesne Grays, a citizens militia, was organized.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1832%0a%3c John M. Roberts and Son opened a jewelry and watchmaking establishment at Fifth Avenue and Market.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1832%0a%3c Samuel Pettigrew was chosen mayor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1832%0a%3c The Farmers Deposit National Bank of Pittsburgh began business as the Pittsburgh Savings Fund Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 10, 1832%0a%3c Flood waters reached a level of 38.2 feet at the Point.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 5, 1832%0a%3c Orphan Society of Pittsburgh and Allegheny, the present Protestant Home for Children and the oldest institution of its kind in Pennsylvania, was founded. It was incorporated in 1834.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1833%0a%3c St. Pauls Roman Catholic Church was dedicated. It was consecrated the sects first cathedral in the city on August 7,1843.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 4, 1833%0a%3c Daniel Webster visited.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 30, 1833%0a%3c The gazette, under management of John I. Scull and Morgan Neville, became a daily paper.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 2, 1833%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Theater, known as Old Drury and located on Fifth Avenue between Wood and Smithfield streets, opened with the play Busy Body and the afterpiece Age of Tomorrow. Tyrone Power played 7-lam let in the third presentation at the theater.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1834%0a%3c Pennsylvania canal system from Philadelphia to Pittsburgh was completed at a cost of $10,000,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1834%0a%3c Samuel Pettigrew was returned to office in the first public election for mayor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 27, 1834%0a%3c The first historical society was organized.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March, 1834%0a%3c A route between Pittsburgh and Philadelphia via canal and rail-road (Pennsylvania Canal, Portage and Columbia railroads) was opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 9, 1834%0a%3c William Lesky, sheriff, issued a proclamation establishing a "general system of common schools."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1835%0a%3c The Pittsburgh, the first steam locomotive to be built west of the Allegheny Mountains, was built by McClurg, Wade, and Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 8, 1835%0a%3c The select and common councils authorized the first gas works to be built in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 11, 1835%0a%3c Pittsburghs first public school opened in a rented room in a Seventh Street building; five pupils attended class taught by James F. Gilmore.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1836%0a%3c Jonas R. McClintock was first successful public candidate for mayor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1836%0a%3c N. R. Smith founded a system of lyceums which dominated the citys intellectual life for the next ten years.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 26, 1836%0a%3c The Councils adopted an ordinance establishing a system of police to include one captain of the watch, two lieutenants, and 16 watchmen.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 31, 1836%0a%3c The Monongahela Navigation Company was chartered and began construction of locks and dams in Monongahela River.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 26, 1836%0a%3c A city ordinance was passed authorizing the initial grading of Grants Hill, familiarly known as "the Hump," a cut of ten feet in Fifth Avenue hill just east of Central City.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 6, 1836%0a%3c Fourteen trade unions amalgamated to form the Pittsburgh Central Labor Union.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 13, 1836%0a%3c A cornerstone was laid for construction of the second courthouse.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1837%0a%3c Isaac Harris Directory for 1837 estimated the value of Pittsburgh manufacturing at $11,606,350.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1837%0a%3c The Orphan Society built its first orphanage.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 6, 1837%0a%3c For the first time, manufactured gas lighting appeared on the streets of the city and in many stores.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 15, 1837%0a%3c All Pittsburgh banks suspended gold payments as the result of nationwide inflation caused by overexpansion of business and "disorderly currency."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 1, 1837%0a%3c The first public school for Negroes was opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1838%0a%3c Mechanics Bridge was built over the Allegheny River at Sixteenth Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1839%0a%3c The bridge over the Allegheny River at Hand (Ninth) Street was completed. The roof of the bridge became a fashionable promenade.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1839%0a%3c Grogan Company, jewelers, was established.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March, 1839%0a%3c Over 1400 canal boats carrying 25,000 tons of freight passed through Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September, 1839%0a%3c Valley Forge, the first large iron steamboat, was built by Robinson and Minis.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1840%0a%3c Pittsburgh developed as a coal port; in this year coal shipments out of city totaled 464,826 tons.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1840%0a%3c Peter Duffs Mercantile College (Duffs Business College) established.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1840%0a%3c Population: 21,515; Allegheny City, 10,089; Allegheny County, 81,235.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 13, 1840%0a%3c Allegheny was incorporated as a third-class city with a population of 10,989.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 4, 1840%0a%3c Claytons "aerial mail packet" balloon, bound for Philadelphia, took off from Pittsburgh and landed the same evening in the vicinity of Tarentum.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 17, 1840%0a%3c William Robinson was inaugurated as first mayor of Allegheny City.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January, 1841%0a%3c En route to Washington for his inauguration, President-elect William H. Harrison visited the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April, 1841%0a%3c The hostelry Monongahela House, opened its doors.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 31, 1841%0a%3c A strike followed by riots in six cotton factories in Allegheny. September 8: The Pittsburgh Weekly Chronicle began publication.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1842%0a%3c The second courthouse, designed by John Chislett, was completed on Grants Hill.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 20, 1842%0a%3c Charles Dickens, the English author, arrived with his wife at the Exchange Hotel, Penn Avenue at Sixth, for a three-day visit.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 10, 1842%0a%3c Pittsburgh Daily Morning Post was first published. The Henry Oliver family, including 2-year-old Henry William Oliver, emigrated from Ireland to Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1843%0a%3c The Aqueduct was rebuilt on the suspension principle, using wire cable made by John Roebling. This was the first great public work in which wire cable was used in place of wooden beams.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 7, 1843%0a%3c The See of Pittsburgh was created with the Right Reverend Michael OConnor as first bishop.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 22, 1843%0a%3c Seven Sisters of Mercy arrived from Ireland to establish their Order here.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1844%0a%3c Joseph Woodwell, well known in the city as a wood carver of unusual ability, entered the hardware business in partnership in a store named Walker and Woodwell.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 13, 1844%0a%3c The Monongahela River was formally opened for navigation as far as Brownsville; seven dams and 11 locks were in operation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1845%0a%3c Steamboats were first used here for towing coal barges.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1845%0a%3c The iron frigate Allegheny was built here for the United States Navy.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 10, 1845%0a%3c A fire that started in the back of an icehouse at Ferry Street and Second Avenue destroyed 982 buildings, made about 12,000 persons homeless, resulted in damage estimated between $5,000,000 and $8,000,000 and left one third of city in ashes.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 22, 1845%0a%3c Mary Cassatt, noted impressionist painter, was born in Allegheny. (She died in 1926.)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1846%0a%3c First manufacture of a new explosive gun cotton.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1846%0a%3c Samuel M. Kier, Pittsburgh druggist, began to sell crude oil for medicinal purposes.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1846%0a%3c The covered wooden bridge over the Monongahela River at Smithfield Street was replaced by a wire suspension one, the first so constructed by John Roebling, builder of the Brooklyn Bridge.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1846%0a%3c A Society of Jews, forerunner of the Rodef Shalom Congregation, was formed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 8, 1846%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Dispatch, first successful penny newspaper west of Alleghenies, was founded by Colonel J. Heron Foster.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 13, 1846%0a%3c The Pennsylvania Railroad was incorporated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 22, 1846%0a%3c Duquesne Grays and Jackson Blues, first Pittsburgh regiments, left by boat for New Orleans and Vera Cruz to join in the war against Mexico.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 29, 1846%0a%3c Pittsburgh dispatched its first telegraphic message, a report from General Bowman of the Pennsylvania militia notifying President Polk that the second Pennsylvania regiment was ready to leave for Mexico.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1847%0a%3c The Post became the first city newspaper to utilize the telegraph for news coverage.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1847%0a%3c Pittsburgh-born Jane Grey Swisshelm, reformer and abolitionist, began publication of The Saturday Visitor, a weekly journal.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 1, 1847%0a%3c The Sisters of Mercy opened their first hospital here, called it the "Mercy."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 1, 1847%0a%3c The Joseph Woodwell Company, situated at Second Avenue and Wood Street, opened its doors to the public.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 5, 1847%0a%3c The Monongahela House, rebuilt after being destroyed in the 1845 fire, was opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 9, 1847%0a%3c A citizens meeting was held to plan erection of a public hospital.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 13, 1847%0a%3c The Mercantile Library Association, a union of several library groups, was founded.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 1, 1848%0a%3c The Mercury published the citys first Sunday newspaper.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 18, 1848%0a%3c Western Pennsylvania Hospital (West Penn) was chartered.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 9, 1848%0a%3c Sisters of Mercy completed a hospital on Stevenson Street with bed capacity for 60 patients.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 17, 1848%0a%3c Allegheny Medical Society was organized as a branch of the State Medical Society.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 17, 1848%0a%3c Thirteen-year-old Andrew Carnegie and his family left Scotland for Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 17, 1848%0a%3c Anesthesia in the form of chloroform was used for the first time in Pittsburgh by Dr. William H. Wright in a tooth extraction.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1849%0a%3c Iron City Industrial Congress was organized by 23 local unions.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1849%0a%3c Pittsburgh City Glass Works was started by Wilson Cunningham and his two brothers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1849%0a%3c A second cut, this one seven feet, was made in the "Hump."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 22, 1849%0a%3c An advertisement appeared in Daily gazette announcing that "J. Horne, Trimmings, Notions, Millinery and Fancy Goods," was open for business at 63 Market Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 20, 1849%0a%3c Puddlers and boilers in iron mills began a five-month strike in protest against a reduction in wages; this action led to later organization of the Sons of Vulcan.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 20, 1849%0a%3c A two-hour speech by Salmon P. Chase, Ohio Free-Soil senator, at Allegheny Market House, set the trend of abolitionist thinking in Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 20, 1849%0a%3c First waterworks in Allegheny was completed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1850%0a%3c Colonel James Anderson established in Allegheny an Apprentices Library and opened it to working boys. Andrew Carnegie was one of the regular boy patrons.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1850%0a%3c The value of Pittsburgh manufacturing was estimated at $50,000,000 by Samuel Fahnestock in the Pittsburgh Directory for the Year 1850.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1850%0a%3c B. F. Jones resigned as manager of the Pennsylvania Canal to begin operating a puddling iron works on the south bank of the Monongahela River.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1850%0a%3c Population: Pittsburgh, 46,601; Allegheny City, 21,262; Allegheny County, 138,290.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January, 1850%0a%3c Passavant Hospital, founded in 1849 under the name Pittsburgh Infirmary by the Reverend William Passavant of Zelienople, was chartered.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 7, 1850%0a%3c Joseph Barker, an itinerant reformer, was elected mayor while serving a years term in jail for disturbing the peace.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 10, 1850%0a%3c Pennsylvania Railroad began operating trains between Pittsburgh and Johnstown.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1851%0a%3c A Marine Hospital, designed to care for disabled rivermen, was established by the federal government at nearby Woods Run.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1851%0a%3c The report-card system was established in the city schools.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January, 1851%0a%3c Jane Grey Swisshelm, advocate of womens rights, polled only three votes in her campaign for the office of mayor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 25, 1851%0a%3c In the citys greatest musical event of the era, Jenny Lind, under the management of Phineas T. Barnum, sang at Masonic Hall, Fifth Avenue, before 1000 persons who paid an average of $7 each for tickets sold on auction.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 16, 1851%0a%3c Evergreen Hamlet, an experiment in communal living, started.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 30, 1851%0a%3c Regular passenger service was inaugurated by the Ohio and Pennsylvania Railroad (Fort Wayne) between Allegheny and New Brighton.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 10, 1851%0a%3c The Pennsylvania Railroad formally began business in the city of Pittsburgh with its rail line extended as far as Turtle Creek. At that point passengers transferred to stagecoach, which bridged a 28-mile gap in the rail connection.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1852%0a%3c Pittsburgh Board of Health was created.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 19, 1852%0a%3c The rivers went to a stage of 35.1 feet in another flood.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 19, 1852%0a%3c Flood waters reached a mark of 31 feet, 9 inches.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September, 1852%0a%3c The National Free-Soil Convention, one of the first mass abolitionist meetings in the country, was held in Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 17, 1852%0a%3c The Ohio and Pennsylvania Railroad posted regular schedules between Pittsburgh, Alliance, Canton, Massillon, and Wooster, Ohio. It offered four trains daily, the first leaving Pittsburgh at 8 A.M. and arriving in Wooster at 3:30 P.M.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 29, 1852%0a%3c The Pennsylvania Railroad opened an all-rail route from Pittsburgh to Philadelphia, utilizing the Portage and Columbia railroads.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 29, 1852%0a%3c The Pennsylvania State Teachers Association was organized at a meeting in Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1853%0a%3c The Economites, a religious society near Ambridge, Pa., completed the Saw Mill Run Railroad to Banksville, a distance of three miles.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1853%0a%3c The citys first Jewish congregation held services in a temporary synagogue located over the Vigilant Fire Engine House on Third Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1853%0a%3c The borough of West Pittsburgh was formed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1853%0a%3c The first Pittsburgh post office and federal government building was erected at Fifth Avenue and Smithfield Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1853%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Legal Journal (second law periodical in the United States and third in the world) was published by Thomas J. Keenan and John Hastings.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June, 1853%0a%3c Benjamin F. Jones formed a partnership with Bernard and John Lauth and Samuel Kier, with whom he had operated the Mechanics Line, a canal boat line from Pittsburgh to Philadelphia. They established on the south bank of the Monongahela River puddling furnaces and rolling mills under the name of Jones, Lauth and Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September, 1853%0a%3c The Morning Post listed the following hotels in operation in Pittsburgh: Monongahela House, Exchange Hotel, Merchants Hotel, American Hotel, United States, Spread Eagle, Millers Mansion House, and Broadhurst Mansion House.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 15, 1854%0a%3c The Summit tunnel of the Pennsylvania Railroad was opened, allowing continuous rail travel between Pittsburgh and Harrisburg.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March, 1854%0a%3c The first bill was introduced in the Legislature to consolidate the cities of Pittsburgh and Allegheny.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September, 1854%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Post reported a total of 400 deaths in two weeks in the citys worst cholera epidemic.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September, 1854%0a%3c Rodef Shalom Congregation was organized.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1855%0a%3c A new city hall and market, at Diamond and Market, was completed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March, 1855%0a%3c Ladies were first employed as clerks in dry-goods stores.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 24, 1855%0a%3c Andrew W. Mellon was born in East Liberty.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 19, 1855%0a%3c The Dollar Savings Bank, founded as the Pittsburgh Dollar Savings Institution, was opened for business.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 29, 1855%0a%3c The first county Republican convention adopted an abolition resolution.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 25, 1855%0a%3c The first public high school (Central) was opened in rented quarters, at 508 Smithfield Street, for 114 pupils.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1856%0a%3c Joseph L. Lowry built the first steam fire engine for the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1856%0a%3c John Lauth, sold his interests in Jones, Lauth, and Company to the other partners. James A. Laughlin bought into the business.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 29, 1856%0a%3c The Allegheny Valley Railroad was opened to Kittanning.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 22, 1856%0a%3c The first national convention of Republicans met in Lafayette Hall in Pittsburgh for a two-day session to complete national party organization.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 29, 1856%0a%3c The Pittsburgh, Fort Wayne and Chicago Railroad was incorporated and its line was opened through to Chicago from Allegheny.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1857%0a%3c The Pennsylvania Railroad purchased the Pennsylvania Canal for $7,500,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1857%0a%3c The Diamond Savings Institution (predecessor of the Union National Bank of Pittsburgh) was founded.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 23, 1857%0a%3c Novelist Margaret Wade Deland was born in Allegheny. (She died in 1945.)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August, 1857%0a%3c The financial panic reached a climax in Pittsburgh when all local banks, with the exception of the Bank of Pittsburgh, suspended payments "until such time as the Philadelphia banks resume."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September, 1857%0a%3c Charlotte Jones, convicted of killing her aunt and uncle for their money in the notorious "McKeesport cabin murder," became the first woman to be hanged in Allegheny County. She said, "I did this for the great love I had for Denny Fife."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 22, 1857%0a%3c The first railroad bridge across the Allegheny River, a wooden structure, was opened to bring the Ohio and Pennsylvania Railroad into the city of Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1858%0a%3c Mackeown and Finley agreed to sell to the A. C: Ferris and Company of New York City two thirds of their output of carbon oil. This contract marked the beginning of the use of petroleum products in New York.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1858%0a%3c Samuel Kier set up his first commercial oil refinery or "still" in his drugstore basement at 363 Liberty Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1858%0a%3c A small group of iron puddlers, meeting in an old Diamond Street hotel, organized the Sons of Vulcan, first union movement in the iron industry in Pittsburgh. The action was the result of the financial panic of 1857, which had forced their wage to be reduced to $3.25 per ton.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1858%0a%3c In Millvale, the Kloman brothers began operating the forge works which led to the Carnegie steel organization. The first tin plate (iron coated with tin) ever made was produced by C. G. Hussey and Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 10, 1858%0a%3c The first train operated from Allegheny into the citys first Union Station, located at Seventh Street and Liberty Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 26, 1858%0a%3c The United Presbyterian Church of North America was created by the merger of the Associate Reformed and the Associate Presbyterian churches. The merger took place in the old City Hall in Market Square.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1859%0a%3c Cold rolling of iron and steel was invented and patented by Bernard Lauth, a partner of Benjamin F. Jones.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1859%0a%3c H. Samson began operating as a funeral director.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 10, 1859%0a%3c The Western Pennsylvania Historical Society held its first meeting in the Merchants Exchange.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 22, 1859%0a%3c The Citizen Passenger Railway Company was granted a charter for construction and operation of first street railway in city. The first track was laid on Penn Avenue from St. Clair (Sixth) Street to 26th Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July, 1859%0a%3c James Laughlin, a banker and merchant, built the first two Eliza blast furnaces with beehive coke ovens, on the north side of the Monongahela River, directly opposite the Jones, Lauth plant. The new plant was known as Laughlin and Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 5, 1859%0a%3c The first horsecar, "a single-truck vehicle, seating 14 passengers, dimly lighted at night," began operating; the fare from Butler Street to East Liberty was six cents.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 29, 1859%0a%3c The petroleum industry had its birth when Colonel Edward L. Drake struck oil at 69 feet at Titusville about 75 miles north of the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 1, 1859%0a%3c The Union National Bank was organized as a successor to the Diamond Savings Institution.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 16, 1859%0a%3c Clinton, the second blast furnace built in the district, and the first to use coke for the blast, went into operation at the South Side plant of Graff, Bennett, and Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1860%0a%3c Allegheny Observatory was founded.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1860%0a%3c Population: 49,221; Allegheny City, 28,702; Allegheny County, 178,031.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 22, 1860%0a%3c An announcement was made of the opening of "books to receive subscription of stock" for construction of a "free bridge" over the Allegheny.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 29, 1860%0a%3c Professor S. Wilson ascended from Pittsburgh in his balloon, great Western, disappeared from view, and landed hours later on a bill near Sharpsburg.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 1, 1860%0a%3c The Prince of Wales, the later Edward VII of the United Kingdom, was warmly greeted by Pittsburghers when he arrived at the Monongahela House for an overnight stay. He visited factories and manufacturing establishments.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 28, 1860%0a%3c Because of Civil War clouds, all Pittsburgh banks except the Bank of Pittsburgh suspended specie payments.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December, 1860%0a%3c The city refused to comply with the Secretary of Wars order for the transfer of guns from the Allegheny Arsenal to the South.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1861%0a%3c Baltimore and Ohio Railroad, via connecting railroads, was extended to the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1861%0a%3c The Trimble Construction Company began operations as the Crawford, Trimble and Gilliland Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 15, 1861%0a%3c From a balcony of the Monongahela House, President-elect Lincoln, who had stopped in the city on his way to Washington, in a reference to the secession from the Union of southern states, declared that "notwithstanding the trouble across the river, there is no crisis but an artificial one."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April, 1861%0a%3c Camp Wilkins, near Penn Avenue and 26th Street, was established by Governor Andrew G. Curtin; a home guard was organized.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 24, 1861%0a%3c Eighty men comprising "Turners Rifles" departed for Harrisburg to join Union troops; they became the first Pittsburgh soldiers to see action in the war.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August, 1861%0a%3c Bernard Lauth retired and James Laughlin bought his interest. Jones, Lauth, and Company became Jones and Laughlins American Iron Works.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 21, 1861%0a%3c Property damage was heavy in a flood that reached a mark of 30 feet, 9 inches.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October, 1861%0a%3c United States Sanitary Commission, designed to receive donations of clothing and medical supplies for the Army, was established by the Citizens Committee of 100, which had been selected at a mass meeting in City Hall on April 15.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 1, 1862%0a%3c Iron City Forge Company, the parent of Kloman and Company and of the Carnegie iron and steel interests, was organized as a partner-ship of the Kloman brothers, Thomas Miller, and Henry Phipps.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 4, 1862%0a%3c The Home for the Friendless was chartered.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 17, 1862%0a%3c Seventy-eight persons, mostly boys and girls employed there, were killed and twice as many injured in an explosion at the Allegheny Arsenal in Lawrenceville, where munitions were being manufactured for the Union army.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 25, 1862%0a%3c Ethelbert Nevin, composer, author, and pianist, was born in nearby Edgeworth. He was the composer of "The Rosary."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1863%0a%3c The iron frigates Manayunk and Umpqua were built.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1863%0a%3c The Third National Bank of Pittsburgh was founded at the corner of Wood Street and Virgin Alley (Oliver Avenue)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March, 1863%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Trades Assembly was organized by representatives of 46 local unions.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April, 1863%0a%3c The United States Christian Commission, directed by the Reverend Herrick Johnson, assumed most of work of Sanitary Commission and hospital activities of the Subsistence Committee.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 14, 1863%0a%3c In a Sunday meeting at the Monongahela House, Pittsburgh businessmen and manufacturers, fearing a raid by the Confederate cavalry forces of J. E. B. Stuart, decided to suspend business and set up a defense.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 16, 1863%0a%3c Two thousand men, paid at rate of $L25 per day by their own employers, began digging rifle pits on hills as a line of defense around the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 25, 1863%0a%3c Pittsburgh militia and home guard prepared for an attack on receipt of a telegraphic message that Jeb Stuarts troops had occupied McConnellsburg and were moving toward the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 26, 1863%0a%3c There were 11,828 men at work on 32 separate defense installations in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 4, 1863%0a%3c All fortifications were completed, but the Confederate retreat after the Union victory at Gettysburg removed the threat to Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 5, 1863%0a%3c Following their surrender to Union troops at Lisbon, Ohio, 118 officers of General John H. Morgans cavalry, the only Confederate prisoners held in Pittsburgh in the Civil War, were brought to Western Penitentiary.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1864%0a%3c The firm that was the forerunner of the A. M. Byers Company was established.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January, 1864%0a%3c New city hall, market house, and weight house, bordering on the public square in Allegheny City, were completed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 13, 1864%0a%3c Stephen Collins Foster, Pittsburghs best-known composer, died destitute in New York.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 21, 1864%0a%3c Ulysses S. Grant, en route to take command of the Army of the Potomac, was the guest of honor at a dinner in the Monongahela House.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 2, 1864%0a%3c Andrew Carnegie, at 29, entered the iron-producing business by purchasing a sixth interest in the Iron City Forge Company for $8,925. Other shareholders included Andrew Kloman and Henry Phipps.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 16, 1864%0a%3c Allegheny Citys Sanitary Fair closed after raising $363,570 in 16 days for benefit of Union soldiers and their dependents. At the end of the war $200,000 unused funds were given to West Penn Hospital as a nucleus for an endowment.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 30, 1864%0a%3c The first train ran between Pittsburgh and Erie.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 19, 1864%0a%3c The Quarterly Trade Circular reported that there were 58 oil refineries in the city with a weekly capacity of 26,000 barrels.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 11, 1864%0a%3c Thurstons (oil) Stock Exchange opened on Fourth Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December, 1864%0a%3c Newspapers reported that the wage of iron puddlers had risen from $3.56 per ton in October 1861 to $9 per ton.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1865%0a%3c The new Pennsylvania Railroad Station went into service. Located at 11th Street and Liberty Avenue, it was a four-story structure with upper floors assigned to a hotel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1865%0a%3c The Sisters of St. Francis converted a frame building into a hospital for 12 patients.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1865%0a%3c Pittsburgh Diocese of the Protestant Episcopal Church was created. John E. Kerfoot was the first bishop. Pittsburgh School of Design was instituted.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1865%0a%3c Merchants and Manufacturers Bank was organized.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February, 1865%0a%3c After an eight-month strike, the first trade-union agreement in America was made between the Sons of Vulcan and the iron industry. Among major provisions of the con-tract was a sliding wage scale on economic conditions in the industry.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 5, 1865%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Clearing House Association was opened for business with John Harper as president.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March, 1865%0a%3c Cyclops Mill, a Thomas Miller and Carnegie enterprise, was completed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 25, 1865%0a%3c The Keystone Bridge Company was organized, designed to use iron from the Iron City Forge and the new Cyclops Mill.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 1, 1865%0a%3c Iron City Forge and Cyclops Mill were merged to form Union Iron Mills.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 4, 1865%0a%3c A tremendous ovation was given General Grant when he arrived in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 31, 1865%0a%3c George Westinghouse, at 19, received his first patent for the invention of a rotary steam engine.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1866%0a%3c Smith and Porter (H. K. Porter Company) began manufacturing locomotives in Pittsburgh. The first one operated under its own steam on street car rails across a Monongahela River bridge.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 3, 1866%0a%3c Peoples Savings Bank of Pittsburgh was chartered.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August, 1866%0a%3c Homeopathic Medical and Surgical Hospital and Dispensary was founded.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 29, 1866%0a%3c The police night call, "All's well," was abolished.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 13, 1866%0a%3c Once more General Grant came to Pittsburgh, this time with President Andrew Johnson and Admiral David G. Farragut.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 13, 1866%0a%3c Annual exchange clearings of the Pittsburgh Clearing House Association, reflecting the amount of business activity in Pittsburgh, totaled $83,791,242.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1867%0a%3c First fire-alarm telegraph system was established in Allegheny.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1867%0a%3c Samuel Pierpont Langley was appointed Director of the Allegheny Observatory.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1867%0a%3c Andrew Carnegie acquired the controlling interest in the Union Iron Mills.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1867%0a%3c Rosenbaum and Company was established at 76 Market Street as Rosenbaum and Fleischman, a retail and wholesale millinery firm.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1867%0a%3c The Peoples First National Bank and Trust Company was founded as the Safe Deposit Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1867%0a%3c An act of the Legislature officially transferred to the city of Allegheny the Allegheny Parks, the land of which was originally the gift of the Penn family.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April, 1867%0a%3c The councils of Allegheny and Pittsburgh agreed on a plan of union in the first definite step toward consolidation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 12, 1867%0a%3c Monongahela Incline Plane Railroad, up the face of Mount Washington, was chartered.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 30, 1868%0a%3c The city of Pittsburgh extended its eastern boundary by annexing the townships of Pitt, Peebles, Liberty, Collins, and Oakland.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 8, 1868%0a%3c Cornerstone was laid for the new City Hall on Smithfield Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1869%0a%3c H. J. Heinz, at 25, planted in Millvale a three-quarter of an acre patch of horseradish, and thus began the world-renowned H. J. Heinz Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 9, 1869%0a%3c The Boggs and Buhl department store was opened at 512 Federal Street in Allegheny as the Boggs, Blair and Buhl notions and dry goods shop.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 13, 1869%0a%3c In the first practical demonstration, an air-brake train made a trip from Union Station in Pittsburgh to Steubenville.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 10, 1869%0a%3c The Home for Aged Protestant Women was founded.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July, 1869%0a%3c George Westinghouses first major enterprise, the Westinghouse Air Brake Company, was organized to manufacture air brakes for steam railways. The first site of the company was at 25th Street and Liberty Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 10, 1869%0a%3c Pennsylvania Female College (now Chatham College) opened. The new telephone switchboard provided service to 777 subscribers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 14, 1869%0a%3c President Ulysses S. Grant visited the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 11, 1869%0a%3c Pennsylvania College for Women, founded by the Reverend W. T. Beatty, was incorporated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1870%0a%3c The 642-foot Monongahela Incline, first in the city, was completed to the top of "Coal Hill" (Mount Washington).%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1870%0a%3c Jacob, Henry, Morris, and Isaac Kaufmann, German immigrants with $1500 between them, opened a mens clothing business in an I 8-by-28 foot storeroom at 1918 Carson Street, primarily to serve puddlers of the nearby Jones and Laughlin steel mill (Kaufmanns Store, incorporated in 1871).%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1870%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Coal Exchange was chartered for coal companies engaged in river transportation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1870%0a%3c Allegheny Bar Association was incorporated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1870%0a%3c The establishment of Pittsburgh titles for land belonging to the Penns was completed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1870%0a%3c Population: 86,076; Allegheny City, 51,180; Allegheny County, 262204.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 1, 1870%0a%3c The Old Drury Theater closed its doors after 37 years of service.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 2, 1870%0a%3c Judge Thomas Mellon, the father of Andrew W. and Richard B. Mellon, retired from the bench to open a private banking establishment under the name of T. Mellon and Sons on Smithfield Street near Sixth Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 17, 1870%0a%3c The first professional teachers organization was established in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 6, 1870%0a%3c The Pittsburgh and Ormsby Passenger Railroad Company was incorporated to construct a railway from the borough of Ormsby to a Market Street terminal.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 13, 1870%0a%3c Pittsburghs first paid fire department was organized.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 28, 1870%0a%3c Pennsylvania College for Women opened under the auspices of the Presbyterian Church.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 13, 1870%0a%3c The first Pittsburgh Weather Bureau was established by the War Department and Signal Corps at 25 Fifth Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1871%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Grand Opera House, on Fifth Avenue, was completed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1871%0a%3c Making of steel castings from crucible steel was begun at the Pittsburgh Steel Casting Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1871%0a%3c Baltimore and Ohio Railroad opened continuous service from the east to Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 24, 1871%0a%3c The retail division of the Joseph Horne Company moved into Library Hall (Penn Avenue), a building which previously had housed Mercy Hospital.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 30, 1871%0a%3c General George G. Meade, a Civil War military leader, and Governor John W. Geary were speakers at a dedication of the Soldiers Monument on Monument Hill in Allegheny.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1872%0a%3c The Mount Oliver Incline; 1600 feet long and the first to be cable-driven, was built.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 2, 1872%0a%3c The city of Pittsburgh annexed the boroughs of South Pittsburgh, Monongahela, Allentown, St. Clair, Lawrenceville, Temperanceville, Birmingham, Sligo, Mount Washington, West Pittsburgh, and Ormsby.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May, 1872%0a%3c The Lucy furnace of Kloman, Phipps, and Carnegie went into blast.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 18, 1872%0a%3c It was reported that Pittsburgh oil refineries were using about 10,000 barrels of crude oil daily from the Oil Creek and Allegheny River fields.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 23, 1872%0a%3c The new City Hall, erected at Smithfield and Oliver Way at a cost of $600,000, was officially opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1873%0a%3c The Duquesne Club was founded by a group of industrialists and financiers. The Pittsburgh Art Society was organized.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 13, 1873%0a%3c Carnegie, McCandless, and Company, with $750,000 capital, was organized to build a steel-rail mill at nearby Braddock; Andrew Carnegie had one-third interest.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1874%0a%3c Construction started on the Union Bridge (Manchester) to connect Allegheny with the Point.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 27, 1874%0a%3c The Central District and Printing Telegraph Company was organized as the first telephone company in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 26, 1874%0a%3c One hundred and fifty persons died in the "Butchers Run Flood" which deluged Allegheny, Woods Run, West End, South Side, and neighboring communities.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 12, 1874%0a%3c Edgar Thomson Steel Company, Limited, with $1,000,000 capital, was organized and took over Carnegie, McCandless, and Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November, 1874%0a%3c The first Exposition Society was formed to exploit Pittsburgh goods, and built several great halls on Killbuck Island.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 5, 1874%0a%3c At a meeting in the Germania Bank Building, at Wood and Diamond, the Pittsburgh Chamber of Commerce was organized, with General Thomas H. Howe as the first president.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1875%0a%3c Natural gas was first used in manufacturing.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1875%0a%3c Womens Club of Pittsburgh, the first such club in Pennsylvania and the second in the nation, was organized.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1875%0a%3c Mrs. William A. Herron and Mrs. William Thaw organized the Pittsburgh Association for the Improvement of the Poor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 19, 1875%0a%3c A "heavy smoke" entry in the daily journal of the Weather Bureau stated: "Extremely dark this morning. Had to keep all gaslights burning until 11 oclock. Street lamps were lighted for a time after 9 oclock (AM.)"%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 1, 1875%0a%3c The Duquesne Incline Plane Company was chartered to build an incline to the top of "Coal Hill" (Mount Washington)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 1, 1875%0a%3c The first steel rail was rolled at the Edgar Thomson works, under the supervision of Captain William R. Jones. This was the first use of the Bessemer process in the United States.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1876%0a%3c Poet Richard Realf dedicated his "Hymn of Pittsburgh" to the city. The poem started with the line, "My father was a mighty Vulcan".%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1876%0a%3c The Point Bridge was completed, providing an important connection between the central portion of the city and the south and west parts.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1876%0a%3c The London Bakery (predecessor of the Ward Baking Company of New York) was opened by R. B. Ward on Penn Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 11, 1876%0a%3c The See of Allegheny was created by the Roman Catholic Church.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 11, 1876%0a%3c Writer Mary Roberts Rinehart was born. (She died on September 22, 1958.)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 8, 1876%0a%3c Pittsburgh Chamber of Commerce was chartered.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 4, 1876%0a%3c The unions of steel heaters and steel roll hands, in convention in Pittsburgh, merged to form the Amalgamated Association of Iron and Steel Workers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1877%0a%3c The Pittsburgh and Lake Erie Railroad completed organization and began building its first rail line from Pittsburgh to Youngstown.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1877%0a%3c Armstrong Cork Company was organized.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1877%0a%3c The first public exhibition of electric lights took place on Duquesne Heights.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June, 1877%0a%3c First experiment with the telephone was made by Captain William Boylston and T. B. A. David of the Central District and Printing Telegraph Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 19, 1877%0a%3c Pittsburgh railroad workers struck in protest against a nationwide reduction of railroaders wages and a Pennsylvania Railroad order cutting employment of brakemen.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 20, 1877%0a%3c Large crowds gathered at 28th Street crossing of Pennsylvania Railroad; switches and trains were blocked.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 21, 1877%0a%3c Twenty-six were killed and many wounded in the "Battle of 28th Street," which started when militiamen from Philadelphia fired on strikers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 22, 1877%0a%3c The gazette proclaimed: "Riot Law Triumphant-The Reign of Anarchy in the Smoky City" The Union Depot was burned out and Pennsylvania Railroad property was destroyed as far as 33rd Street. Damage was estimated at $5,000,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 18, 1877%0a%3c The See of Allegheny of the Roman Catholic Church was merged with the See of Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 4, 1877%0a%3c The first exposition opened on Smoky Island, Allegheny; the citys first telephone was in operation there.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1878%0a%3c T. B. A. David strung telephone wires from his office in the First National Bank Building to the Iron Exchange on Fourth Avenue and publicly engaged in the first telephone conversation in Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 21, 1878%0a%3c Pittsburgh Oil Exchange (forerunner of the Pittsburgh Stock Exchange) was organized with a membership of 180.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 1, 1878%0a%3c Order of the Holy Ghost began operating a college.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1879%0a%3c The citys water pumping station at Brilliant went into operation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1879%0a%3c The beginning of electric street lighting.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 24, 1879%0a%3c The Pittsburgh and Lake Erie Railroad inaugurated rail traffic between Pittsburgh and Youngstown.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 27, 1879%0a%3c The Pittsburgh and West End Railway Company was chartered; it ran a line from Fifth Avenue near the Union Station to West End and the Washington Turnpike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1880%0a%3c The Allegheny County Light Company, first ambitious electric light concern in the city, began operation with a generator that supplied energy to 40 lights at one time.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1880%0a%3c The F. J. Kress Box Company was founded for the manufacture of wooden boxes.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1880%0a%3c Assessed valuation of real estate in the city of Pittsburgh was set at $99,600,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1880%0a%3c Population: 156,389; Allegheny City, 78,682; Allegheny County, 355,869.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1881%0a%3c The Homestead mill of the Pittsburgh Bessemer Steel Company, built by Andrew Kloman and a group of other Pittsburgh industrialists, went into operation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1881%0a%3c The Union Switch and Signal Company, a pioneer in the manufacture of automatic signals for trains, was founded by George Westinghouse.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March, 1881%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Press Club was organized by newspaper workers at a meeting in the Common Council Chambers at City Hall.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 15, 1881%0a%3c With Samuel Gompers a prime mover the Federation of Organized Trades and Labor Unions (American Federation of Labor) was organized, in a Pittsburgh convention, by the Knights of Labor and other trade unions, including the Amalgamated Association of Iron and Steel Workers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 25, 1881%0a%3c Andrew Carnegie made his first move to create a free library for Pittsburgh; he offered $250,000 on the condition that the city government agree to appropriate $15,000 annually for its maintenance. The city was unable to accept the gift as it had no funds on hand for such a purpose.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 28, 1881%0a%3c Pittsburgh Catholic College of the Holy Ghost (Duquesne University) received a state charter.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1882%0a%3c Historical Society of Western Pennsylvania became the new name for the Old Residents Association of Pittsburgh and Western Pennsylvania, founded in 1879 as the fourth historical society in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 6, 1882%0a%3c The Homestead mill of the Pittsburgh Bessemer Steel Company had its first strike when millworkers refused to sign "yellow dog" contracts; violence followed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 5, 1882%0a%3c H. C. Frick Coke Company was incorporated with $2,000,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 7, 1882%0a%3c The second courthouse, on Grants Hill, was destroyed by fire.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 1, 1882%0a%3c A nationwide strike resulted from a general stoppage of work called by the Amalgamated Association of Iron and Steel Workers in a wage dispute.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 22, 1882%0a%3c Jane Grey Swisshelm, newspaper publisher, reformer, author, and one of the first nurses to accompany Union troops in the Civil war, died.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 4, 1882%0a%3c Allegheny General Hospital was incorporated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1883%0a%3c The 17th Street Incline was built by the Penn Incline Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1883%0a%3c Carnegie, Phipps and Company was organized to purchase and operate the Homestead mill, owned by a coalition of seven Pittsburgh firms.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1883%0a%3c Jones and Laughlins American Iron Works became Jones and Laughlin, Limited, and the first stock was issued.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1883%0a%3c Officers were Benjamin F. Jones, Sr., chairman, G. M. Laughlin, secretary treasurer; T. M. Jones, general manager.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January, 1883%0a%3c The Penn Fuel Gas Company opened a line to 16th Street from Murraysville, location of the areas first gas field opened in 1878, and thus brought the first natural gas into the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 1, 1883%0a%3c Western Pennsylvania Medical College was opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 8, 1883%0a%3c The county commissioners offered $2500 each to five outstanding architects to prepare sketches for a new courthouse and jail.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 3, 1883%0a%3c The first Exposition buildings on Smoky Island in Allegheny burned to the ground.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1884%0a%3c An incandescent lamp was used for the first time in Pittsburgh in a restaurant located at 52-1/2 Fifth Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1884%0a%3c The first school for nurses between the Allegheny Mountains and Chicago was opened at the Homeopathic Medical and Surgical Hospital and Dispensary.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1884%0a%3c George Westinghouse began the manufacture of electric lamps.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1884%0a%3c Monongahela Natural Gas Company was organized.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1884%0a%3c Benjamin F. Jones, Sr., became president of the American Iron and Steel Association, a post he held for 18 years.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1884%0a%3c A Postal Telegraph bureau was established in Pittsburgh as a rival for Western Union.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 1, 1884%0a%3c Henry Hobson Richardson, noted for his Romanesque architecture, was appointed by the county commissioners to design the new courthouse.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 6, 1884%0a%3c The city was flooded, the rivers reached a mark of 36.5 feet.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May, 1884%0a%3c George Westinghouse drilled a gas well on his property in the Homewood district, and his home was the first in Pittsburgh to be lighted and heated by gas.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 20, 1884%0a%3c Pittsburgh Press, a daily newspaper, began publication as the Evening Penny Press.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July, 1884%0a%3c George Westinghouse acquired control of the one-year-old Philadelphia Company for the development of natural gas; it became the worlds largest in that field.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 5, 1884%0a%3c William F. (Buffalo Bill) Cody visited the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 1, 1884%0a%3c A contract for construction of the new courthouse was let to Norcross Brothers of Worcester, Massachusetts, on a bid of $2,243,024.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1885%0a%3c Boggs and Buhl announced installation of a telephone. The store also introduced delivery service, utilizing a wheelbarrow and a horse and wagon.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 5, 1885%0a%3c The Pitt Medical College was opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 13, 1885%0a%3c The cornerstone for the new courthouse was laid on the 49th anniversary of the cornerstone laying for the previous courthouse.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 30, 1885%0a%3c The Western Pennsylvania Exposition Society was chartered for the purpose of establishing a technical school in the city, and buildings were erected on Duquesne Way; dissolved, April 10, 1934.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November, 1885%0a%3c Elizabeth Cochrane (1867-1922), the Nellie Bly of the "Around the world in 72 days" fame began her newspaper career as a reporter for the Pittsburgh Dispatch. She investigated the factories and public institutions of the city and reported about them.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1886%0a%3c George Westinghouse introduced Saturday as half holiday for employees and vacations with pay for salaried employees.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1886%0a%3c Riverside Penitentiary of Western Pennsylvania (Western Penitentiary) was built in Woods Run on the Ohio River to replace the old institution in Allegheny.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1886%0a%3c Andrew Carnegie offered the city of Allegheny $300,000 for a Carnegie free library, with provision that the city maintain it.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 8, 1886%0a%3c The Westinghouse Electric Company was established in Garrison Alley to manufacture and promote the use of equipment for the alternating electric current system.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 19, 1886%0a%3c Jones and Laughlin constructed two seven-ton Bessemer converters at the South Side plant for the job of making its first steel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September, 1886%0a%3c Western Pennsylvania Medical College was established on Brereton Street, near West Penn Hospital.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 27, 1886%0a%3c The Fidelity Trust Company was incorporated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December, 1886%0a%3c The Federation of Organized Trades and Labor Unions changed its name to the American Federation of Labor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 18, 1887%0a%3c Pittsburgh Hospital for Children was incorporated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 30, 1887%0a%3c President Grover Cleveland visited Pittsburgh. At the sight of natural gas he remarked: "An uncanny picture, a superb spectacle".%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1888%0a%3c The Oliver interests were reorganized to form the Oliver Iron and Steel Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 31, 1888%0a%3c Under the name of the Pittsburgh Reduction Company, the first aluminum producing company was organized at the home of Captain Alfred E. Hunt, 272 Shady Lane (Avenue), by five young men, all under 35. They were Captain Hunt, a military figure; Charles Martin Hall, developer of the new metal; Romaine C. Cole, George H. Clapp, and Howard Lash.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 7, 1888%0a%3c The first electric streetcar was placed in service by the Pittsburgh, Knoxville and St. Clair Street Railways, but was destined to failure.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 24, 1888%0a%3c The new Allegheny County courthouse and jail, designed by H. H. Richardson, was dedicated on the final day of the countys centennial anniversary.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 3, 1888%0a%3c Fire destroyed Machinery Hall and other exposition buildings. The Arabian, the first steam locomotive to run in the United States, and Stephen Fosters piano were among the exhibits destroyed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November, 1888%0a%3c Charles M. Hall and Arthur V. Davis poured the first commercial ingot of aluminum in the Smallman Street plant of the Pittsburgh Reduction Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1889%0a%3c New exposition buildings were built at the Point.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 29, 1889%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Chamber of Commerce began urging construction of a Lake Erie and Ohio River canal.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 31, 1889%0a%3c Pittsburgh dispatched aid to Johnstown, where the flood toll was mounting to 2300 dead.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September, 1889%0a%3c Allegheny Citys first trolley operated on Pennsylvania Avenue and was the first to run into downtown Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 4, 1889%0a%3c The Western Exposition opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 12, 1889%0a%3c The Fifth Avenue Horse Car System was replaced by cable cars, which reduced the running time from Downtown to East Liberty by 30 minutes to one hour. The five-and-a-half-mile system, built by the Pittsburgh Traction Company, was considered to be the citys first "rapid transit" facility.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 2, 1889%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Reduction Company, its pilot plant having demonstrated the success of the Hall aluminum making process, was capitalized at $1,000,000, and 10,000 shares were issued.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 26, 1889%0a%3c South Side Hospital was founded.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 28, 1889%0a%3c The Union Trust Company of Pittsburgh was established in the Oil Exchange Building.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 30, 1889%0a%3c Mrs. Mary E. Schenley presented the city of Pittsburgh with 300 acres of land for park purposes, and Schenley Park, the citys first, was developed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 16, 1889%0a%3c Playwright George S. Kaufman was born in the city. (He died in 1961.)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 8, 1889%0a%3c Hervey Allen, novelist, was born in East Liberty. (He died on December 28, 1949.)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1890%0a%3c The Joseph Horne Company was the first large store in the city to substitute electricity for gas illumination. The Pittsburgh Incline to Knoxville was rebuilt.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1890%0a%3c Assessed valuation of Pittsburgh real estate totaled $207,300,000. Annual clearings of the Pittsburgh Clearing House Association totaled $786,694,231.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1890%0a%3c Population: 238,617; Allegheny City, 105,287; Allegheny County, 551,959.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 16, 1890%0a%3c A. W. Mellon and his brother, Richard B. Mellon, acquired their first stock in the Pittsburgh Reduction Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 25, 1890%0a%3c Nellie Bly completed her trip around the globe in 72 days 6 hours and 11 minutes.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 6, 1890%0a%3c Andrew Carnegie repeated his original library proposal first made November 25, 1881, and offered to increase his gift to $1,000,000 to include funds for a museum of natural history and art gallery and for branch libraries.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 13, 1890%0a%3c The Carnegie Library in Allegheny, the first Carnegie Free Library, was opened to the public after being dedicated by President Benjamin Harrison.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March, 1890%0a%3c Oil discovery in Westview.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 4, 1890%0a%3c Childrens Hospital opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 17, 1890%0a%3c The city of Allegheny celebrated its Golden Jubilee.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 15, 1890%0a%3c Western Pennsylvania Institute for the blind opened in Oakland. The site was given by Mrs. Mary Schenley.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 13, 1890%0a%3c Marc Connelly, playwright, was born in McKeesport, The Second Avenue Line, the citys first successful electric trolley line, began operating between Downtown and Glenwood.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1891%0a%3c The United States Glass Company, one of the countrys first large industrial combines, was formed; 17 flintglass factories, most of them in or near Pittsburgh, were acquired.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1891%0a%3c A "Roads Congress" was held in Allegheny Carnegie Library lecture hall, under auspices of the Chamber of Commerce, to consider ways of improving public roads.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January, 1891%0a%3c Pittsburgh eyes were on nearby Youngwood, where 100 miners were killed in a mine explosion.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 6, 1891%0a%3c Andrew Carnegie gave the promised $1,000,000 to be controlled by a Board of Trustees appointed by the City Council, for a library and other buildings to be erected in Oakland.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 2, 1891%0a%3c Coke workers went on strike at the Morewood mines of the H. C. Frick Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 3, 1891%0a%3c City Council adopted an ordinance authorizing erection of Carnegie Library on a 19-acre tract acquired from Mrs. Schenley.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 13, 1891%0a%3c Samuel Gompers, of the AFL, hailed the "eight-hour day" during a Pittsburgh visit.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September, 1891%0a%3c The Alvin Theater opened with Pauline Hall and her opera company in La Belle Helene.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October, 1891%0a%3c Three hundred delegates of the American Street Railway Association assembled at the Monongahela House for their 10th annual national convention. The convention slogan was "The Mule Must Go."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 19, 1891%0a%3c First telephone line between Pittsburgh and New York City was in operation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1892%0a%3c The Castle Shannon Incline was built. City Council enacted Pittsburghs first antismoke ordinance, which proved to be a wholly ineffective instrument.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1892%0a%3c Western University of Pennsylvania instituted a Department of Medicine and absorbed the Western Pennsylvania Medical College.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 30, 1892%0a%3c H. C. Frick discharged the entire labor force of 3800 workers at the Homestead works after they threatened to strike for higher wages.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 6, 1892%0a%3c Three hundred Pinkerton men were engaged by millworkers in a pitched battle at the Homestead works after arriving via the Monongahela River on two barges; 16 men were killed and many more wounded.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 6, 1892%0a%3c The central branch of the Pittsburgh Young Womens Christian Association was incorporated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 13, 1892%0a%3c National Guard troops were ordered to Homestead by the governor to prevent further violence; the strike ended soon thereafter.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1893%0a%3c Highland Park opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1893%0a%3c The Joseph Horne Company opened a modern new six-story building at Penn Avenue and Fifth (Stanwix).%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1893%0a%3c Construction work started on "steel headquarters" -- the 15-story Carnegie Building on Fifth Avenue, regarded citys first "skyscraper."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 20, 1893%0a%3c Ground was broken for the first Ferris wheel, invented by George Washington Ferris of the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July, 1893%0a%3c Construction began for Carnegie Public Library in Oakland.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 7, 1893%0a%3c Phipps Conservatory in Schenley Park was completed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1894%0a%3c Free textbooks were adopted in city schools.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1894%0a%3c Jones and Laughlin scrapped 40 puddling furnaces and discontinued a highly successful wrought-iron business.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1894%0a%3c Oliver Wire Company, a merger of all the Oliver wire interests, was incorporated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1894%0a%3c Mrs. Mary Schenley presented to the D.A.R. the Blockhouse at the Point.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 15, 1894%0a%3c Pittsburgh citizens contributed to a fund to be used to put 1000 to 2000 unemployed men to work on city projects.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April, 1894%0a%3c Pittsburgh Stock Exchange was in operation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 3, 1894%0a%3c The vanguard of General Coxeys army of 300,000 unemployed men reached Pittsburgh en route to demonstrate in Washington, D. C.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 1, 1894%0a%3c The city of Pittsburgh annexed the borough of Brushton.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1895%0a%3c The Carnegie Steel Company moved from 48 Fifth Avenue into its new building, the steel frame of which had been allowed to stand unfinished one year to demonstrate the use of steel as a construction material.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1895%0a%3c The National Tube Works of John and Harvey Flagler became the first company in America to manufacture seamless steel tubing by the rotary piercing method for the bicycle, automobile, and pipe industries.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1895%0a%3c Women were first admitted to the Schools of Law and Pharmacy at the Western University of Pennsylvania.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 4, 1895%0a%3c Presbyterian Hospital was founded.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 22, 1895%0a%3c Eye and Ear Hospital received a charter to operate.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 13, 1895%0a%3c Miss Agnes Watson was the first woman admitted to the Allegheny County Bar.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 5, 1895%0a%3c The Carnegie Library building was dedicated and opened to the public in a ceremony marked by Andrew Carnegies announcement of an additional gift for enlarging the building.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1896%0a%3c The city purchased the Point Bridge for $750,000 and the Smithfield Street Bridge for $1,152,583.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 27, 1896%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Orchestra, which developed from the "Symphony Society," presented its first concert at Carnegie Music Hall with Frederic Archer as conductor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 25, 1896%0a%3c The 22nd Street Bridge, first toll free bridge to be built in the city, was dedicated to public use.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 22, 1896%0a%3c Experimental X-rays were successful at Homeopathic Hospital.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 12, 1896%0a%3c St. Johns Hospital was opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 8, 1896%0a%3c As the result of recurring typhoid epidemics, the city appointed a Pittsburgh Filtration Commission to study water problems; it subsequently recommended that the citys water be filtered.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 25, 1896%0a%3c Pittsburgh Stock Exchange officially began operating under that name.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 24, 1896%0a%3c The conversion from cable cars to electric streetcars began on Fifth Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 7, 1896%0a%3c The Lumiere company's Cinematographe, the French forerunner of motion pictures, opened in Harry Davis' Avenue Theater.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 23, 1896%0a%3c The police department organized a bicycle corps.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 5, 1896%0a%3c The First International Art Exhibition was held at Carnegie Institute with 312 paintings on display; 19 Pittsburgh artists were represented.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1897%0a%3c The 15-story Park Building, one of the citys earliest "skyscrapers," was erected on Fifth Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 3, 1897%0a%3c Joseph Horne and Company department store was destroyed by fire.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 29, 1897%0a%3c The Union Trust Company and Pittsburgh Stock Exchange were destroyed by fire.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 3, 1897%0a%3c In a Founders Day speech at Carnegie Institute, President William McKinley praised Pittsburgh for its progressive spirit.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 18, 1897%0a%3c D. Herbert Hostetter announced that five of the largest gas companies in the city were consolidated into a new company capitalized at $5,000,000. He also announced a plan to build an $800,000 plant on the site of the Pittsburgh Gas Company on Second Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1898%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Chamber of Commerce opposed free and unlimited grants of street franchises, contending that they should be held by the city in trust for the people.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1898%0a%3c Victor Herbert, cellist and composer of operas, began a six-year reign as conductor of the Pittsburgh Orchestra.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1898%0a%3c Willa Cather, novelist, joined the staff of the Pittsburgh Dispatch. Two years later she became reporter for the Pittsburgh Leader, the citys leading newspaper.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1898%0a%3c Mesta Machine Company was formed by the merger of the Leechburg Foundry (George Mesta) and the Robinson-Rea Manufacturing Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 1, 1898%0a%3c The borough of Beltzhoover was annexed by the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 29, 1898%0a%3c Troops for service in the Spanish-American War entrained for camp at Mount Gretna.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 4, 1898%0a%3c The Edgar Thomson Steel Works began shipping rails to South Africa and Japan.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1899%0a%3c City Council authorized a purifying system for the city water supply.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1899%0a%3c Pittsburgh Coal Company of Pennsylvania was organized.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1899%0a%3c The Duquesne Club erected a five-story building on Sixth Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1899%0a%3c National Tube Works consolidated with other pipe producers to form the National Tube Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 4, 1899%0a%3c James Whitcomb Riley, poet, lectured in Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May, 1899%0a%3c The citys first six-hole golf course, known as Belmar, was laid out in Homewood, and the Western Pennsylvania Golf Association came into being.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 4, 1899%0a%3c First automobile races conducted in Schenley Park.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September, 1899%0a%3c Western University began playing regular football schedules at Recreation Park; it was the first school in the city to do so.%0a%3c %0a%3c 1900s%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1900%0a%3c Assessed valuation in the city totaled $321,700,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1900%0a%3c Annual clearings of the Pittsburgh Clearing House Association amounted to $1,615,641,592.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1900%0a%3c Isaac Seder and Jacob A. Frank formed a partnership and organized a wholesale firm known as the Pittsburgh Wrapper Manufacturing Company, the forerunner of the Frank and Seder Store.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1900%0a%3c The 12-story Empire Building was erected at 508 Liberty Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1900%0a%3c Population: Pittsburgh, 321,616; Allegheny City, 129,896; Allegheny County, 775,058.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March, 1900%0a%3c Barney Dreyfuss began a 32-year reign as owner and president of the Pittsburgh Pirates professional baseball club.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 1, 1900%0a%3c The Carnegie Company, with capitalization of $320,000,000, was formed by the merger of the H. C. Frick Coke Company and Carnegie Steel Company, Limited.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 1, 1900%0a%3c Grant Boulevard (Bigelow Boulevard), a "rapid transit" road to the east, conceived in 1891 by E. M. Bigelow and cut out of the side of Bedford Hill, was opened to traffic after three years of work.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 14, 1900%0a%3c At a dinner of Carnegie Institute trustees in the Schenley Hotel, Andrew Carnegie proposed an endowment of $1,000,000 for establishment of a polytechnic school on condition that the city provide a suitable site for it.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 12, 1900%0a%3c At a testimonial dinner for him in New York, Charles M. Schwab, president of the Carnegie Company, made a speech that impressed one of the guests, J. P. Morgan, and led later to organization of the United States Steel Corporation, the greatest steel corporation in the world.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1901%0a%3c The 18-story Arrott Building on Wood Street and the 16-story Peoples-Pittsburgh Trust Building on Fourth Avenue and Wood were completed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 1, 1901%0a%3c United States Steel was incorporated; the founding companies included Federal Steel Company, American Steel and Wire Company, National Tube, National Steel, American Tin Plate, American Steel Hopp Company, and the American Sheet Steel Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 17, 1901%0a%3c Ethelbert Nevin, Pittsburgh composer of "Cradle Song," "A Day in Venice," "The Rosary," and other well-known songs, died.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 7, 1901%0a%3c The "ripper" act, changing the city charter, became law. William J. Diehl, of the Magee-Flinn "ring," was ousted as mayor; Adam M. Brown, first president of the Allegheny County Bar Association and a judge of Common Pleas Court, was named first city recorder.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 11, 1901%0a%3c Andrew Carnegie sold his steel interests to J. P. Morgan receiving value of $492,000,000 for it.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 14, 1901%0a%3c Andrew Carnegie announced a $4,000,000 pension plan for employees and a gift of $1,000,000 for maintenance of the Homestead, Braddock, and Duquesne libraries established by him.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 17, 1901%0a%3c All exposition buildings near the Point, excepting Machinery Hall, were destroyed by fire. They were soon replaced by new structures.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 1, 1901%0a%3c J. P. Morgan completed organization of the worlds largest steel trust. The United States Steel Corporation was capitalized at $1,402,000,000. Charles M. Schwab became its first president.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 17, 1901%0a%3c First automobile accident in the city was reported.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 20, 1901%0a%3c The Triangle had a flood equaling that of February 1884, when floodwaters reached a level of over 36 feet.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1909 and July 14, 1901%0a%3c The Amalgamated Association of Iron, Steel and Tin Workers called a general strike against the U.S. Steel Corporation subsidiaries, the first steelworkers strike since 1892.%0a%3c and%0a%3c The Amalgamated Association of Iron, Steel and Tin Workers was eliminated as a bargaining factor in the steel industry as the result of a 14-month strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 5, 1901%0a%3c Newspapers and the general public demanded construction of a water filter system as hospitals became crowded with 266 victims of typhoid fever.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 21, 1901%0a%3c The Mellons sold their street car interests to the Philadelphia Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 12, 1901%0a%3c The new Pennsylvania Railroad Station, at 10th and Liberty, went into service.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 20, 1901%0a%3c The Iron City Trades Council (Pittsburgh Central Labor Union) was organized by craft and trade unions of the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 10, 1901%0a%3c The first Sunday gazette was issued.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 27, 1901%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Railways Company was created by the merger of several city traction companies, including Southern Traction.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1902%0a%3c The l4-story Keystone Bank Building was built at 325 Fourth Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 1, 1902%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Railways Company took over properties of the Consolidated Traction Company and United Traction Company, and began operating a city-wide system of 400 miles of single track.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 5, 1902%0a%3c Andrew Carnegie announced a gift to form Carnegie Technical Schools, the present Carnegie Institute of Technology.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 30, 1902%0a%3c The notorious Biddle boys, Edward and John, convicted murderers of grocer Thomas D. Kahney and Detective Patrick Fitzgerald, sawed their way out of their cells, overpowered guards, and escaped from the county jail.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 1, 1902%0a%3c Another flood disabled the city, the rivers rising to a level of 35.6 feet at the Point.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 15, 1902%0a%3c The first tenants moved into the 20-story Frick Building, erected by H. C. Frick on Fifth Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 21, 1902%0a%3c The Daughters of the American Revolution (DAR) won a legal suit to prevent removal of the historic Blockhouse from its original site at the Point.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July, 1902%0a%3c T. Mellon and Sons was incorporated as the Mellon National Bank.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 4, 1902%0a%3c A crowd estimated at between 75,000 and 100,000 assembled on Flagstaff Hill to hear a Fourth of July oration by President Theodore Roosevelt.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 14, 1902%0a%3c The Union Savings Bank began operations.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 25, 1902%0a%3c Henry Steele Commager, noted historian, was born in the city. Benjamin F. Jones, Sr. died; Jones and Laughlin, Limited, and Laughlin and Company, Limited were reorganized to form Jones and Laughlin Steel Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1903%0a%3c The 24-story Farmers Bank Building, on Liberty Avenue, and the 13-story Bessemer Building, at 100 Sixth Street, were constructed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 24, 1903%0a%3c A "Greater Pittsburgh" bill was passed in Harrisburg to permit annexation of the territory surrounding the city of Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 23, 1903%0a%3c The office of mayor was restored to the city charter; William B. Hays, who had taken office as city recorder on March 17, 1903, assumed the title of mayor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 9, 1903%0a%3c The Pennsylvania Railroad presented plans to Councils for construction of a new passenger station in East Liberty.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October, 1903%0a%3c Three months prior to the Wright Brothers historic Kitty Hawk flight, Samuel Pierpont Langley, director of the Allegheny Observatory and builder of the famous "Whirling Table" in the early 1880s, experimented with a man-carrying airplane, which became known as "Langleys Folly."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 13, 1903%0a%3c The first of baseballs modern World Series ended in Pittsburgh before 7455 persons at Exposition Park; the Pirates were defeated by Boston, 4 to 3, and lost the Series three games to five.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 19, 1903%0a%3c The Wabash Bridge over the Monongahela collapsed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 4, 1903%0a%3c Mrs. Mary E. Schenley died in London.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 7, 1903%0a%3c The Nixon Theater, built by Samuel F. Nixon-Nirdlinger with support from Senator George T. Oliver and others, was described as the "worlds most perfect playhouse" at its formal opening.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1904%0a%3c McCreerys Department Store opened for business at Sixth and Wood with 450 employees.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 23, 1904%0a%3c The rivers reached a 32-foot flood level.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 4, 1904%0a%3c City Councils passed an ordinance permitting the Wabash Railroad to enter the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 9, 1904%0a%3c Henry W. Oliver, who was instrumental in opening up the Mesabi iron ore regions to Pittsburgh steel and iron manufacturers, died at the age of 64 at his home at Ridge and Grant Avenues.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 21, 1904%0a%3c Virgin Alley, one of the first streets in the city, was renamed Oliver Avenue in honor of Henry W. Oliver.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 2, 1904%0a%3c After three years struggle and conflict, George Jay Goulds Wabash Railroad operated its first train out of Pittsburgh -- a special to the Worlds Fair at St. Louis.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1905%0a%3c A special windshield glass was invented by Banker Brothers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1905%0a%3c George Jay Gould built his ornate Wabash Railroad terminal and 11-story office building on Liberty Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1905%0a%3c Ground was broken 20 miles down the Ohio River for the new Aliquippa works of Jones and Laughlin. The Gulf Oil Company began using its first tank wagons in Pittsburgh to haul gasoline and other fuel. The 13-story Diamond National Bank Building was erected.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 3, 1905%0a%3c On a Schenley Park site provided by the city, ground was broken for the first group of buildings for the Carnegie Technical Schools.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 16, 1905%0a%3c The world's first mainline electric locomotive was demonstrated in the East Pittsburgh railway yards.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 19, 1905%0a%3c The "Nickelodeon," the countrys first all-motion picture house, was opened by Harry Davis and John P. Harris at 433-35 Smithfield Street with the showing of two short films, "Poor but Honest" and "The Baffled Burglar." It was a great success, with people flocking to the place and marveling at the moving figures.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 25, 1905%0a%3c The Pennsylvania Railroad began construction of elevated rail-road tracks on Duquesne Way along the Allegheny River.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 16, 1905%0a%3c First Carnegie Technical Schools buildings were opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 31, 1905%0a%3c The 'Gayety," which later became one of the best-known burlesque houses in the nation, opened as a legitimate theater for the carriage trade.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1906%0a%3c Among the large structures built in the city in this year were the Fort Pitt Hotel, the 21-story Commonwealth Building on Fourth Avenue, the 19-story Frick Annex on Diamond, and the 19-story Benedum-Trees Building on Fourth Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 7, 1906%0a%3c The Carnegie Steel Company announced plans for a $7,000,000 expansion of the Homestead works.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 20, 1906%0a%3c Historic old City Hall, in "the Diamond," a Civil War landmark, was destroyed by fire.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 4, 1906%0a%3c The University Club was in the process of purchasing a site on Grant (Bigelow) Boulevard, in the Bellefield district, for its new home.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 2, 1906%0a%3c George W. Guthrie was inaugurated as Mayor. He held office for three years.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 12, 1906%0a%3c By a majority of 19,943 votes, an act of the Legislature uniting the cities of Pittsburgh and Allegheny was approved in a public referendum.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 1, 1906%0a%3c The Pennsylvania Railroads elevated line on Duquesne Way was ready for service, and the removal of tracks from Liberty Avenue (where since 1851 they had occupied the center strip of the street from 11th Street to the Point) was completed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 24, 1906%0a%3c St. Pauls Cathedral, one of the citys most notable examples of Gothic architecture, built at a cost of $885,481, was consecrated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1907%0a%3c The citys first Bureau of Smoke Control was instituted. William Holdship Rea was chief inspector, 1907-09. Pittsburgh Reduction Company was renamed the Aluminum Company of America.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1907%0a%3c Pittsburghs death rate was 143.6 per 100,000 persons.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1907%0a%3c The 21-story Union National Bank Building was erected at 306 Fourth Avenue and the 12-story Century Building at 130 Seventh Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1907%0a%3c The Frank and Seder organization rented a storeroom on Fifth Avenue and launched a retail business.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 15, 1907%0a%3c Duquesne Way was under nine feet of water and River Avenue on the North Side under 14 feet in a flood that recorded a crest of 38.7 feet.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 11, 1907%0a%3c Andrew Carnegie formally presented the $6,000,000 Carnegie Institute in a dedication ceremony witnessed by 20,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 15, 1907%0a%3c An ordinance giving the Pittsburgh Subway Company the right to build a subway to East End was introduced in Councils.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 4, 1907%0a%3c The historic old Union Bridge, built about 1835 over the Allegheny River at the Point, was closed to traffic, and dismantling of it began.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 19, 1907%0a%3c The Schenley Park oval and matinee race track was opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 21, 1907%0a%3c Lillian Russell at the Nixon Theatre in the comedy, Wildfire.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 23, 1907%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Stock Exchange closed for a three-month period because of the effects of the nationwide depression.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 18, 1907%0a%3c The United States Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of the Guthrie-Watson Greater Pittsburgh bill.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 7, 1907%0a%3c Pittsburgh officially annexed Allegheny City and became a city of 521,000 population, the sixth largest in the nation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1908%0a%3c The number of typhoid cases in Pittsburgh was 1853 for the year 1908, compared with 2969 in 1905, and 5730 in 1906.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1908%0a%3c The Jones and Laughlin Steel Company built a 12-story office building on Ross Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 4, 1908%0a%3c Beechview borough was annexed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February, 1908%0a%3c Wages of millworkers at the Homestead works were reduced 10 to 30 per cent by the Carnegie Steel Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 3, 1908%0a%3c Judge Thomas Mellon died at his home on Negley Avenue at the age of 95.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 26, 1908%0a%3c Carry Nation, the celebrated crusader against the saloons, came for a visit.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 11, 1908%0a%3c Western University of Pennsylvania was rechartered as the University of Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 2, 1908%0a%3c As a climax of the citys sesquicentennial festivities, two cornerstone -- laying ceremonies were staged in Oakland, one for Soldiers and Sailors Memorial Hall and the other for State Hall (School of Mines), first building to be erected in the new University of Pittsburgh campus.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 18, 1908%0a%3c The citys filtration plant, undertaken in 1905, began delivering the first filtered water to residents.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 4, 1909%0a%3c The citys first taxicab company, organized by John Weibley, began operating with a fleet of 18 motorized cabs.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 23, 1909%0a%3c Cornerstone was laid for the $300,000 East Liberty Y.M.C.A.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 29, 1909%0a%3c President William H. Taft arrived for a two-day visit, watched the Pirates lose to Chicago, 8 to 3, and participated in the dedication of Memorial Fountain in Arsenal Park.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 31, 1909%0a%3c Gladys Schmitt, novelist, was born in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June, 1909%0a%3c Montefiore Hospital was founded.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 9, 1909%0a%3c The University of Pittsburgh began its removal from the North Side to Oakland, where it dedicated State Hall, laid the cornerstone for Thaw Hall (School of Engineering) and broke ground for the School of Medicine.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 10, 1909%0a%3c The Pennsylvania Railroad and borough of Wilkinsburg agreed on a plan for elevating the main-line tracks and thus eliminating all grade crossings in the borough.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 27, 1909%0a%3c Mayor William A. Magee, inaugurated on April 5 of this year was credited with settling the two-day strike of 2900 motormen and conductors; settlement was a blow to railroads, which had put on 400 extra cars in absence of trolley service.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 29, 1909%0a%3c In the final game played in Exposition Park, the Pittsburgh Pirates defeated Chicago, 8 to 1.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 30, 1909%0a%3c Forbes Field, named after the head of the British forces in 1758, General John Forbes, was dedicated; 30,338 persons watched the Pirates lose the opening game there to Chicago, 3 to 2.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 15, 1909%0a%3c Rioting workers of the Pressed Steel Car Company, near McKees Rocks, clashed with guards; Coal and Iron Police and State Constabulary were called out; many strikers were wounded by volleys of buckshot fired to halt their charges; state police were ordered to "shoot to kill" if attacked by strikers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 23, 1909%0a%3c Five were killed, scores injured in two more riot battles between police and Press Steel Car strikers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 29, 1909%0a%3c Plans were announced for a $450,000 state armory (18th Regiment) on a site in Schenley Farms.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 12, 1909%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Aero Club was organized, with Philip S. Flinn as first president, and planned an international balloon race for Pittsburgh as its first project.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 16, 1909%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Pirates, winners of 110 games in their regular season, defeated the Detroit Tigers, 8 to 0, to win the seventh and deciding game of the World Series before 17,562 fans at Forbes Field.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1910%0a%3c Population: Pittsburgh, 553,905; Allegheny County, 1,018,463.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1910%0a%3c U. S. Bureau of Mines established a center in Oakland District.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1910%0a%3c Annual clearings of the Pittsburgh Clearing House amounted to $2,587,325,785.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1910%0a%3c New 215-bed Homeopathic Hospital opened at Center and Aiken avenues. Assessed valuation of real estate in the city rose to $745,700,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1910%0a%3c A. W. and R. B. Mellon announced that they were providing funds for creation of Mellon Institute for Industrial Research.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1910%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Courier was published for the first time.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1910%0a%3c John Kowalski, marine engine maker, recorded the first flight of an airplane built in Pittsburgh when he accidentally took off in a four-cylinder plane he had devised.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1910%0a%3c Because of lack of funds, the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra was disbanded.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 23, 1910%0a%3c Three were dead and communications and streetcar service disrupted in a nine-inch snowfall.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 1, 1910%0a%3c The new Henry W. Oliver Building, 25 floors high, was ready for occupancy.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 9, 1910%0a%3c Soldiers and Sailors Memorial Hall was dedicated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1911%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Industrial Development Commission was organized by the Chamber of Commerce for the purpose of securing diversified industries for Pittsburgh; it received contributions of $136,473 to begin work. The Jenkins Arcade was erected on Liberty Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 1, 1911%0a%3c The first old age retirement plan for United States Steel employees was created with a fund of $12,000,000. of which $4,000,000 had been provided by Andrew Carnegie ten years before.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 19, 1911%0a%3c The Elizabeth Steel Magee Hospital, founded by Christopher L. Magee, began operation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 2, 1911%0a%3c New St. Josephs Hospital was opened to the public.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 1, 1911%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Catholic College of the Holy Ghost became Duquesne University and was chartered to award degrees in major educational fields.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 16, 1911%0a%3c The county commissioners formally declared the Sixth, Seventh, Ninth, 16th, and 30th Street Bridges free to the public.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 26, 1911%0a%3c A new city charter act, replacing the Select and Common Councils with a single Council of nine members, was signed by Governor John K. Tener.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 5, 1911%0a%3c Calbraith Perry Rodgers, Pittsburgh aviator, completed the first transcontinental flight, which started at Sheepshead Bay, Long Island, on September 17. Rodgers Field in Allegheny County was later named for him.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 23, 1911%0a%3c An Art Commission was organized under a state act to pass official judgment on plans for buildings, bridges, and other structures in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 31, 1911%0a%3c New West Penn Hospital was opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1912%0a%3c The 26-story First National Bank Building, the citys tallest to this date, was erected at 511 Wood Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1912%0a%3c The Syria Mosque in Oakland was dedicated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1912%0a%3c The Gulf Oil Company opened on Baum Boulevard the first company-owned service station in the world, forerunner of the modern super-service station.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 22, 1912%0a%3c A 28-foot crest was reached by the rivers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 5, 1912%0a%3c A contract was let for the grading of Grants Hill on Fifth Avenue from Smithfield Street to Sixth Avenue and from Fourth to Sixth Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 20, 1912%0a%3c The Carnegie Technical Schools were renamed Carnegie Institute of Technology.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 12, 1912%0a%3c Alexander Moore, editor of the Pittsburgh Leader, was married to the singer, Lillian Russell.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 18, 1912%0a%3c In a pre-election speech before 12,000 persons at Duquesne Gardens, Governor Woodrow Wilson, of New Jersey, Democratic candidate for president, attacked the government s "protective tariff."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 19, 1912%0a%3c The Pitt Panthers were defeated, 45 to 8, by Jim Thorpe and the Carlisle Indians.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 21, 1912%0a%3c William Jennings Bryan appeared before 4000 at the Lyceum and made three other speeches in the Pittsburgh district in behalf of the democratic ticket.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 5, 1912%0a%3c Although Woodrow Wilson won over Bull Moose candidate Theodore Roosevelt and regular Republican candidate William Howard Taft in the presidential election, Roosevelt carried Pittsburgh by a plurality of 8300 votes.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 26, 1912%0a%3c Andrew Carnegie, at 77, turned over all but $25,000,000 of his vast fortune to the Carnegie Corporation for charitable and philanthropic distribution.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 11, 1912%0a%3c City and county officials agreed on a joint plan to erect a City-County Building at Grant and Diamond.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1913%0a%3c The Bell Telephone Company of Pennsylvania built a 20-story office building and equipment headquarters on Seventh Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1913%0a%3c The Central District Telephone and Printing Company was incorporated with other telephone companies into the Central District Telephone Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 1, 1913%0a%3c The first parcel-post deliveries were made in Pittsburgh by the post office at a rate of five cents for the first pound and one cent for each additional pound.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 9, 1913%0a%3c The rivers crested at 31 feet in another flood.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 14, 1913%0a%3c The famous evangelist Billy Sunday held a revival meeting in a tabernacle erected for that purpose on the site of the present Heinz Chapel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 25, 1913%0a%3c A number of people were killed in a sewer explosion.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1914%0a%3c Dr. Heinrich Koppers sold the patents for his by-product coke ovens to Andrew Mellon for $300,000, and the Koppers Company, founded in Illinois, was reorganized with main offices in Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1914%0a%3c The Gulf Oil Company began the practice of issuing free road maps to motorists, one of the most successful promotion efforts in the country.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 1, 1914%0a%3c Excavations of 14.9 feet at Fifth and Grant and of 16.3 feet at Fifth and Wylie completed the grading of Grants Hill.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 25, 1914%0a%3c A public subscription campaign for the University of Pittsburgh was completed with a total of $2,000,000 collected.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 10, 1914%0a%3c The cornerstone was laid for the Masonic Temple on Fifth Avenue in Oakland.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 12, 1914%0a%3c George Westinghouse died in his country home in Lenox, Massachusetts.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 5, 1914%0a%3c Ten thousand Westinghouse workers went on strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 31, 1914%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Stock Exchange suspended operations (for four months) because of the economic effects of the World War.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 6, 1914%0a%3c Eugene (Wild Bill) Heth piloted a Wright biplane to Pittsburgh, the first to carry a passenger, Colonel Harry C. Fry, to the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 1, 1915%0a%3c The Carnegie Steel Company announced that it was increasing employment rolls by 8000 in order to meet increasing demands for steel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 26, 1915%0a%3c The Mellon Institute for Industrial Research, on OHara Street, Oakland, was dedicated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 1, 1915%0a%3c All steel mills in Pittsburgh were operating night and day to meet steel demands of nations at war.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 9, 1915%0a%3c The new Manchester Bridge, connecting the Point with the North Side, was ready for traffic.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 9, 1915%0a%3c Rosenbaum and Company moved into its new building at Sixth and Liberty.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 24, 1915%0a%3c Henry Clay Frick repaid schoolchildren the savings ($169,000) they lost when the Pittsburgh Bank for Savings closed its doors.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January, 1916%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Coal Company was created through the merger of the Pittsburgh Coal Company of Pennsylvania and the Monongahela River Consolidated Coal and Coke Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March, 1916%0a%3c The William Penn Hotel was completed on Grant Street at Sixth at a cost of $6,000,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 18, 1916%0a%3c The cornerstone was laid for the new City-County Building.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 27, 1916%0a%3c A strike of 24,000 miners was settled.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 1, 1916%0a%3c Martial law was declared in Braddock following riots at the Edgar Thomson works.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 9, 1916%0a%3c Thirty thousand Westinghouse workers were on strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 30, 1916%0a%3c Pittsburgh troops entrained for the Mexican border as trouble increased in Mexico.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 6, 1916%0a%3c A $200,000 fire destroyed the city block bounded by Second and Third avenues and Market and Ferry streets.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 25, 1916%0a%3c The Mellons purchased a site at the corner of Smithfield Street and Oliver Avenue for construction of a new bank building.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 16, 1916%0a%3c Beginning of the last exposition held in the old Exposition Buildings.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 17, 1916%0a%3c Schenley High School in Oakland opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1917%0a%3c The 15-story Union Trust Building, rated architecturally as one of the finest structures in the nation, was erected on a Grant Street block-square site.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 27, 1917%0a%3c The Grand Opera House was destroyed by fire, along with other Fifth Avenue buildings, including the Frank and Seder Store.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 1, 1917%0a%3c The new Chamber of Commerce Building, at Seventh and Smithfield, was completed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 5, 1917%0a%3c Enrico Caruso, the great Italian tenor, gave his first Pittsburgh concert.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 20, 1917%0a%3c The first draft lists were published; many Pittsburghers were destined to go overseas in the 28th and 80th divisions.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 25, 1917%0a%3c Ex-President Theodore Roosevelt visited the city; 30,000 people listened to his address.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 29, 1917%0a%3c The University of Pittsburgh organized a hospital unit to go overseas.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 22, 1917%0a%3c Trolley fares were raised to six cents.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 24, 1917%0a%3c Twenty were killed in a Mount Washington streetcar accident in one of the citys worst transit tragedies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 7, 1918%0a%3c The new Grand Theater (Warner) was opened on the site of the old Opera House.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 11, 1918%0a%3c Pittsburgh branch of the Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland began business at Ninth Street and Liberty.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 1, 1918%0a%3c Daylight-saving time, conceived and promoted by Robert Garland, of Pittsburgh, went into effect.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 23, 1918%0a%3c Sixteenth Street Bridge burned.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 18, 1918%0a%3c Explosion at nearby Etna Chemical Company killed 114 persons, many of them were residents of the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 1, 1918%0a%3c A Red Cross benefit show, starring George M. Cohan, established a box-office record for the city with one-night receipts of $138,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 12, 1918%0a%3c Pittsburgh ranked third in the nation in per capita sales of war savings stamps.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 24, 1918%0a%3c Pittsburgh fire fighters staged a strike for higher wages, leaving the city without fire protection for six hours.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 5, 1918%0a%3c An influenza epidemic, starting at the Cantonment Hospital in Point Breeze, victimized 23,268 Pittsburgh residents. Of the total, 1374 died of lobar pneumonia and 678 of bronchopneumonia.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 20, 1918%0a%3c Allegheny County went $10,000,000 over its $165,000,000 quota in the fourth Liberty Loan drive.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 29, 1918%0a%3c A group of the citys leading citizens met and formulated the Citizens Committee on City Plan for Pittsburgh; C. D. Armstrong was elected president; R. B. Mellon, vice-president, and J. D. Hailman, secretary.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 11, 1918%0a%3c A summary at the Armistice showed approximately 60,000 Allegheny County men had seen service in the war, mostly in the 80th and 28th divisions; 1527 died or were killed in action; government war contracts executed in Pittsburgh totaled $215,405,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December, 1918%0a%3c Frederick Bigger, one of the citys first planning engineers, was named full-time executive secretary of the Citizens Committee on City Plan; under his direction work was started toward a master plan; studies were initiated to cover playgrounds, a street plan, transit problems, parks, railroads, and waterways%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1919%0a%3c Natural gas was discovered in nearby McKeesport.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1919%0a%3c Air transportation was inaugurated in Pittsburgh with the organization of the Kennedy Aircraft Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1919%0a%3c Mayer Field, Pittsburghs first commercial airport, was established in Bridgeville by Casper P. Mayer, realtor and aviation pioneer.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March, 1919%0a%3c The Aero Club -- for Pitt and Carnegie Tech war fliers -- was organized in a leather shop on First Avenue, with Barney Mulvihill as president and Joseph M. (Hap) Slater as vice-president.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 10, 1919%0a%3c The Pittsburgh district went over the top in the fifth Liberty Loan with subscriptions totaling $117,210,350.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 14, 1919%0a%3c Henry John Heinz, founder of the H. J. Heinz Company, one of the worlds largest food manufacturing firms and owner of one of the nations outstanding private art collections, died of pneumonia at the age of 75 at his home, 7009 Penn Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 15, 1919%0a%3c The streetcar system suspended operation at midnight when motormen and conductors struck to enforce demands for a 12-cent hourly pay increase.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 8, 1919%0a%3c Pittsburgh voters authorized a $22,996,000 improvement program, including $6,000,000 for a proposed Downtown subway system.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 1, 1919%0a%3c The five cent zone fare was discontinued; trolley fares were raised to 10 cents.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 11, 1919%0a%3c Andrew Carnegie died in his eighty fourth year at his summer home, "Shadowbrook," in Lenox, Massachusetts, after three days of pneumonia. His philanthropies up to this time had totaled $350,000,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 15, 1919%0a%3c Three thousand streetcar men again walked off the job, this time in protest against War Labor Boards award of a six-cent-an-hour raise, only half of what they asked.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 26, 1919%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Railways Company attempted to operate strike-bound cars; the result was a series of riots in downtown Pittsburgh and other sections of the city; many of the strikers were injured.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 28, 1919%0a%3c The streetcar strike was broken when the national union expelled local leaders; the strikers returned to work with great reluctance.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 21, 1919%0a%3c A campaign to unionize the steel industry started in Pittsburgh when a strike was called by National Committee for Organizing Iron and Steel Workers, headed by William Z. Foster, later general secretary of the American Communist party; 365,000 steel workers struck throughout nation for union recognition and reduction of the 12-hour day.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 29, 1919%0a%3c The United States Bureau of Mines dedicated its new $1,000,000 laboratories on Forbes Street in a three-day ceremony.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 17, 1919%0a%3c Dr. Frank Conrad began regular broadcasting of phonograph records (8XK).%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 23, 1919%0a%3c King Albert of Belgium visited the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 1, 1919%0a%3c Forty two thousand miners in Pittsburgh district left jobs in start of nationwide strike closing coal mines; the National Guard was alerted.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 2, 1919%0a%3c Gulf Oil Company opened its first Downtown gasoline service station, at Liberty Avenue and Water Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 2, 1919%0a%3c Henry Clay Frick, industrial and financial leader of Pittsburgh, died suddenly at his New York residence at the age of 69; his body was brought to Pittsburgh for burial. His philanthropies while living were said to total $60,000,000. His probated will disposed of a total estate of $143,000,000 and left $20,000,000 to public, educational, and charitable institutions of Pittsburgh. The city received a 150-acre plot for a park in Fern Hollow, below Beechwood Boulevard, in addition to a $2,000,000 endowment fund to maintain it.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 10, 1919%0a%3c The nationwide coal strike ended, but a national coal conservation order, restricting use of coal everywhere except in private homes, went into effect under rigid enforcement.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 20, 1919%0a%3c Ground was broken for the Liberty Tubes with Governor William C. Sproul participating.%0a%3c 1920%0a%3c "Population: 588,343; Allegheny County, 1,018,463.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 2, 1920%0a%3c A total of 233 suspected leaders of the Communist movement in Pittsburgh were arrested by federal agents in two days as part of a nationwide roundup ordered by Attorney General A. Mitchell Palmer.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 11, 1920%0a%3c Judges wore gowns in court for the first time in Allegheny County.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 13, 1920%0a%3c The Pennsylvania Railroad announced a $100,000,000 improvement and expansion program for the Pittsburgh area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 15, 1920%0a%3c Henry Ford came to Pittsburgh to place in person $15,000,000 worth of steel contracts in the area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 20, 1920%0a%3c The national steel workers organizing strike ended after the fourth month without achieving its objective.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 22, 1920%0a%3c B. F. Jones, Jr., of Jones and Laughlin Steel, purchased the old Monongahela House for $750,000 with the intention of converting it into an office building.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 28, 1920%0a%3c The great Italian tenor, Enrico Caruso, sang at the Syria Mosque.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 1, 1920%0a%3c The United States Supreme Court declined to dissolve the United States Steel Corporation and its subsidiary companies as asked by the federal government in a suit alleging violation of antitrust laws.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 28, 1920%0a%3c Dr. John Brashear, noted astronomer and maker of astronomical lenses and other scientific instruments, died at 80 at his South Side home.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June, 1920%0a%3c The Citizens Committee completed the first of a series of six major studies leading toward a comprehensive city plan, issued a report analyzing the citys recreational deficiencies, and recommended a system of playgrounds.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 2, 1920%0a%3c Allegheny County women appeared at polling places to cast their first ballots.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 2, 1920%0a%3c Station KDKA, first licensed radio broadcasting station, gave the Harding-Cox election returns as its first scheduled broadcast Allegheny County gave Harding a plurality of 105,000 over Governor Cox.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 6, 1920%0a%3c Repeated landslides occurred below Bigelow Boulevard as rainfall continued; engineers waged a losing fight in their efforts to stop the slides and protect Pennsylvania Railroad tracks.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 20, 1920%0a%3c General George W. Goethals, builder of the Panama Canal, on invitation of city officials, came to Pittsburgh and inspected the Bigelow Boulevard slide. He reported: "The situation will prevail until all has come down."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 31, 1920%0a%3c The Citizens Committee on City Plan was incorporated and chartered as the Municipal Planning Association, with a goal of promoting "orderly and efficient development of municipalities" and "scientific methods of city and municipal planning."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 2, 1921%0a%3c Church service was broadcast from the Calvary Protestant Episcopal Church in East Liberty -- the worlds first such broadcast.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 4, 1921%0a%3c Andrew W. Mellon, Pittsburgh financier, was appointed Secretary of the Treasury, and James J. Davis, former union steelworker of Pittsburgh, was named Secretary of Labor in the cabinet of President Warren G. Harding.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 16, 1921%0a%3c To relieve traffic congestion, City Council banned automobile parking on Downtown streets between 4:30 and 6 P.M. daily.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 25, 1921%0a%3c Madame Marie Curie, famed French scientist and co-discoverer of radium, arrived in Pittsburgh for a visit but was taken ill and confined to the home of Mrs. Henry R. Rea in Sewickley. Although weak from her illness, Madame Curie appeared at Memorial Hall the following day to receive her fifty-ninth honorary degree, conferred by Chancellor Bow-man of the University of Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 4, 1921%0a%3c The Carnegie Corporation of New York announced a $21,662,888 appropriation for Carnegie Institute and Carnegie Tech.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 29, 1921%0a%3c The Reverend Hugh C. Boyle was consecrated bishop of the Catholic diocese of Pittsburgh; 100,000 persons assembled in and around St. Pauls Cathedral for the ceremony.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 30, 1921%0a%3c The $30,000,000 will of the late steel magnate, William P. Snyder, was contested in court.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 13, 1921%0a%3c The body of Thomas F. Enright, first American soldier killed in action in the World War, was brought home to Pittsburgh. The Enright Theater in East Liberty was later named in his honor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 8, 1921%0a%3c The Boulevard of the Allies was dedicated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October, 1921%0a%3c KQV, the citys second radio station, began operation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 4, 1921%0a%3c Secretary of War Weeks gave the county commissioners final warning to raise all bridges over the Allegheny River in order to make the river free for navigation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 4, 1921%0a%3c Census report for 1920 listed 20,297 persons over 10 years of age in Pittsburgh as illiterate.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 8, 1921%0a%3c William A. Magee, Republican, was elected Mayor of Pittsburgh by 50,000 votes over William N. McNair, Democrat.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 10, 1921%0a%3c Marshal Ferdinand Foch, leader of French forces in the war, was given a tremendous ovation during a daylong visit to Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 26, 1921%0a%3c A. W. and R. B. Mellon presented a 14-acre H. C. Frick estate tract in Oakland, valued at $2,500,000, to the University of Pittsburgh for further development of a campus. This became the site of the Cathedral of Learning.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1922%0a%3c Radio Station WCAE began broadcasting.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 2, 1922%0a%3c Mrs. Enoch Rauh, long active in welfare work, became the first woman to hold a cabinet post in a major Pennsylvania city when she took office as head of the Department of Charities in the new Magee administration.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 2, 1922%0a%3c Westinghouses radio station KDKA at East Pittsburgh was broadcasting nightly from 7:30 to 10 oclock.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 9, 1922%0a%3c Mrs. Minnie Penfield was the first woman to serve on a jury in Allegheny County.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 9, 1922%0a%3c The cost of the Boulevard of the Allies, nearing completion, was expected to be $1,600,000 per mile, said to be most expensive road construction job in the world.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 15, 1922%0a%3c Hotel Chatham, a "popular hostelry" on lower Penn Avenue, was purchased by the Manufacturers Club of Pittsburgh for its headquarters.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 11, 1922%0a%3c The first Liberty Tube was completed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 3, 1922%0a%3c Announcement was made of a $7,000,000 plan to develop the Hotel Schenley into a "galaxy of the finest and most modern metropolitan structures" by building apartments immediately adjoining the hotel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 5, 1922%0a%3c A posse of humane agents routed 500 "cocking main" enthusiasts assembled in an amphitheater at Kellers Grove, Mount Nebo Road, a historic spot for cock fighting.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 6, 1922%0a%3c Mrs. Lillian Russell Moore, wife of Alexander Moore, died at the age of 61 at her Point Breeze home.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 21, 1922%0a%3c Part of Reserve Township was annexed to the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 5, 1922%0a%3c A new record for auto fatalities in a single day in Allegheny County was established when the coroners office reported five deaths.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 21, 1922%0a%3c A $1,000,000 fire destroyed three buildings at the Duquesne Steel Foundry.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1923%0a%3c Jones and Laughlin became a corporation and sold its first stock on the open market.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 13, 1923%0a%3c Henry Ford announced purchase of the Allegheny Plate Glass Company plant at Glassmere for establishment of the first Ford plant in the Pittsburgh district.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 14, 1923%0a%3c Daily newspapers Dispatch and Leader ceased publication.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 4, 1923%0a%3c Alexander Moore, of Pittsburgh, was appointed ambassador to Spain.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 5, 1923%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Skin and Cancer Foundation opened a clinic at 1901 Fifth Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 6, 1923%0a%3c Governor Pinchot created a Metropolitan Plan Commission for the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August, 1923%0a%3c Harry Greb, of Pittsburgh, defeated Johnny Wilson in New York to win the middleweight title he held for three years.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August, 1923%0a%3c The citys first zoning ordinance, one of the earliest in the United States, became effective amid claims of opposition that it would discourage construction in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October, 1923%0a%3c The Municipal Planning Association issued its final report; it included recommendations for canalization of the Ohio River, a river rail terminal, greater use of wharves, and a system of water-storage reservoirs for flood protection advocated by the 1911 Flood Commission.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 2, 1923%0a%3c Boulevard of the Allies was opened to traffic.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 24, 1923%0a%3c Historic Mount Mercy Academy, on Fifth Avenue, suffered $100,000 damages in a fire which injured seven.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 24, 1923%0a%3c In a speech at Syria Mosque, David Lloyd George, war-time Premier of Great Britain, pleaded for mercy to end wars.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 27, 1923%0a%3c The last horse car on Sarah Street suspended operation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 13, 1923%0a%3c Twenty thousand persons attended formal opening of new banking room of Union Trust Company at Fifth and Grant.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 13, 1923%0a%3c The first unit traffic-light system was installed as an experiment at all corners intersecting the Boulevard of the Allies in the downtown area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1924%0a%3c Bettis Field, sponsored by Samuel Brendel, Harry Neal, and D. Parr Peat, of McKeesport, was established on the Pittsburgh-McKeesport road as a commercial flying enterprise.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 1, 1924%0a%3c The Schenley Apartments, consisting of five structures in a new-type housing development, were ready for occupancy at monthly rents of $150 and up.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 4, 1924%0a%3c The rivers hit a crest of 30.4 feet causing $5,000,000 damage, heaviest from a flood in the city since 1913.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 30, 1924%0a%3c The Liberty Tubes were opened for a two-week chemical test.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 7, 1924%0a%3c Parts of lower St. Clair Township were annexed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 10, 1924%0a%3c It was announced that the first city-county airport would be built and named in honor of Calbraith Perry Rodgers of the city, first aviator to span the U.S. on November 5, 1911.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 21, 1924%0a%3c A few days after her final performance in The Closed Door here, Eleanora Duse, celebrated tragedienne on tour, died in her suite at the Schenley Hotel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 10, 1924%0a%3c The citys fifth trolley strike in 15 years started; the Downtown area was jammed with automobile traffic; the Pittsburgh Railways imported 900 electric railways operators and guards from New York to run trolleys.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 10, 1924%0a%3c The Liberty Tubes were closed for further work on the ventilation system after 12 persons were overcome by gas; a trolley strike had caused a traffic jam in them.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 12, 1924%0a%3c Motormen and conductors voted to return to work, ending the 39-hour streetcar strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 22, 1924%0a%3c Seven police inspectors and three fire chiefs were demoted in the biggest police shake-up in 20 years.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June, 1924%0a%3c Rodgers Airfield, on a 41-acre tract near Aspinwall, was completed for operation as the first city-county airport.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 3, 1924%0a%3c A total of $2,266,893 was pledged by 8341 Jewish residents of the city for construction of new Montefiore Hospital.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 4, 1924%0a%3c Calvin Coolidge, in winning the presidential election, carried Allegheny County by 75,000 votes.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 6, 1924%0a%3c Pitt Chancellor John G. Bowman announced plans for a "52-story" Gothic skyscraper to be built at a cost of $10,000,000 and known as the Cathedral of Learning.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 1, 1924%0a%3c In the face of heated protests, the county commissioners asked for bids for the razing of the Ninth Street Bridge.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1925%0a%3c The United States Steel Corporation developed a process for producing seamless pipe 16 inches in diameter, more than twice the size previously possible.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 1, 1925%0a%3c Burton W. Marsh, the citys first traffic engineer, submitted his first traffic survey to City Council, recommending strict parking regulations for the downtown area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 8, 1925%0a%3c H. P. Davis, president of Westinghouse, urged broadcasting stations to link themselves together by short wave for simultaneous broadcasting of programs.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 31, 1925%0a%3c City Council enacted an ordinance eliminating the practice of compelling policemen to work two days a month without pay.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 1, 1925%0a%3c A city assessors report fixed total taxable values of Pittsburghs 28 wards of realty at $990,000,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 13, 1925%0a%3c A bill to create a Greater Pittsburgh by joining all boroughs and townships to the city was killed in committee at Harrisburg.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 22, 1925%0a%3c George Mesta died.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 10, 1925%0a%3c Evangeline Booth visited the city to dedicate the new Salvation Army home for business girls, located on the Boulevard of the Allies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 13, 1925%0a%3c County commissioners tabled action on a plan to remove the county jail from Its Ross Street site, purchase nearby sites, and erect a $3,500,000 county office skyscraper and jail.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 14, 1925%0a%3c The largest electric locomotive in the world, 152 feet long and weighing 1,275,900 pounds, was given a test run at Westinghouses East Pittsburgh yards.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 19, 1925%0a%3c The fund for construction of the Cathedral of Learning reached a total of $5,597,782 -- more than twice as much as ever raised in the citys history for an educational or philanthropic purpose.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 23, 1925%0a%3c The Young Mens and Womens Hebrew Association in Oakland was dedicated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 26, 1925%0a%3c The Philadelphia Company dedicated its new $3,500,000 building, on Sixth Avenue, and President Arthur W. Thompson announced a five-year, $100,000,000 utility improvement program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 27, 1925%0a%3c The Keystone Athletic Club announced purchase of the old St. Charles Hotel property, at Third Avenue and Wood, and plans for construction of a 20-story, $3,000,000 building.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 8, 1925%0a%3c Plans were announced for erection of another Downtown skyscraper -- the Law and Finance Building.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 26, 1925%0a%3c Pitt Stadium, with a capacity of 60,000, was formally opened with the Panthers defeating Washington and Lee, 28 to 0, before a crowd of 20,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 15, 1925%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Pirates defeated the Washington Senators, 9 to 7, in the seventh and deciding game of the World Series before 42,856 at Forbes Field; Downtown stores suspended business, and traffic stopped as Pittsburghers celebrated the victory.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November, 1925%0a%3c General W. W. Atterbury, president of the Pennsylvania Railroad, in Pittsburgh with other railroad officials to inspect the $14,000,000 station and street improvement program, stated: "While Pittsburgh has called for all the Pennsylvania Railroad could produce, Pittsburgh itself has been our greatest producer." Motor buses were introduced on a large scale on city streets.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 6, 1925%0a%3c United States Steel stock jumped 5-1/2 points in one day to 138, highest quotation ever recorded to this date.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1926%0a%3c The $1,650,000 Webster Hall, on Fifth Avenue, was erected as a hotel to specialize in club residences for men.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 5, 1926%0a%3c R. B. Mellon, president of the Mellon National Bank, was elected chairman of Allegheny County Planning Commission.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 26, 1926%0a%3c Marcus Loew announced plans to erect the largest theater in Pennsylvania, a 4000-seat house on the site of the old Hotel Anderson, Sixth and Penn, at cost of $2,500,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 3, 1926%0a%3c Twenty men were killed in an explosion that wrecked a mine of the Pittsburgh Terminal Company at Horning, near Castle Shannon.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March, 1926%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra, reorganized and financed by its own musicians, began playing public concerts.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 18, 1926%0a%3c Pittsburgh voters approved a $19,902,000 bond issue for various city improvements.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 12, 1926%0a%3c Approximately $60,000,000 was being expended to improve steel mills in the area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 13, 1926%0a%3c The new Seventh Street Bridge was opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 28, 1926%0a%3c Plans were announced for a $7,000,000 campaign for establishment of a Presbyterian "medical center."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 28, 1926%0a%3c Duquesne Light Company announced a plan to build the "largest and most modern" electric power plant in the world at Shippingport on the Ohio River at a cost of $40,000,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 27, 1926%0a%3c Ground was broken for the University of Pittsburghs Cathedral of Learning.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November, 1926%0a%3c Double-deck trolleys, declared too dangerous for Pittsburgh, were abandoned.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 6, 1926%0a%3c Official opening was held for Armstrong Tunnels, named for Commissioner Joseph G. Armstrong.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 13, 1926%0a%3c An air show featured dedication of Bettis Field as a Pittsburgh-McKeesport airport.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 27, 1926%0a%3c Carnegie Tech upset Notre Dame, 19 to 0 at Forbes Field before 45,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1927%0a%3c Construction crews began erecting the Pittsburgher Hotel on Diamond Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 1, 1927%0a%3c Forty-five thousand miners in the district joined in a nationwide coal strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 21, 1927%0a%3c Carrying .a single pouch of mail, an open cockpit Waco belonging to Clifford Ball, Inc., the citys pioneer airline, inaugurated airmail service between Pittsburgh and Cleveland.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 24, 1927%0a%3c After a Sunday concert, which drew an audience of 4000, nine members of the executive board of the Pittsburgh Symphony were arrested on charges of violating "blue laws". All were found guilty and fined $25 each by Alderman Samuel McKinley; group included Richard S. Rauh, secretary of the society; Edward Specter, chairman of the orchestra committee; Elias Breeskin, assistant conductor, and seven others.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 3, 1927%0a%3c Carrick Borough was annexed to the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 12, 1927%0a%3c The Buhl Foundation was established with a $15,000,000 gift announced by Henry Buhl, Jr.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 12, 1927%0a%3c The New Point Bridge was dedicated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 25, 1927%0a%3c Frick Park, 380 acres in Squirrel Hill willed to the city by H. C. Frick, was opened for public use.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 2, 1927%0a%3c After a series of negotiations the Post-Gazette came into being under ownership of Paul Block, and the Sun-Telegraph was organized under ownership of William Randolph Hearst.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 3, 1927%0a%3c Charles Lindbergh, the first to fly alone over the Atlantic to Europe, was feted by the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 12, 1927%0a%3c The widening of Grant Street, Downtown, was started.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October, 1927%0a%3c The new Roosevelt Hotel, at Sixth Street and Penn, was opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 8, 1927%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Pirates lost the fourth straight game of the World Series, 4 to 3, to the New York Yankees.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 13, 1927%0a%3c President Coolidge was guest speaker at the Carnegie Institutes 31st Founders Day exercises at Carnegie Music Hall. He also appeared before Carnegie Tech students in accordance with a promise made to them by Samuel H. Church, Institute president, and made a speech -- a nine word address: "I shall not break Colonel Churchs promise to you."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 27, 1927%0a%3c J. P. Morgan, Jr., New York financier, became chairman of the board of the United States Steel Corporation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 27, 1928%0a%3c Stanley Theater opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 27, 1928%0a%3c The Liberty Bridge was dedicated and opened to public use.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May, 1928%0a%3c The 23-story Clark Building, on Liberty Avenue, was ready for occupancy.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 2, 1928%0a%3c Air express service was inaugurated between Pittsburgh and Cleveland by the Clifford Ball Air Line; 1000 spectators watched Pilot Dewey Noyes take off in a plane carrying first express parcels.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 31, 1928%0a%3c The National Elimination Balloon Races, witnessed by 150,000 persons at Bettis Field, resulted in the death of two balloonists -- W. W. Morton and Lieutenant Paul Evert, of the United States Army.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 26, 1928%0a%3c Allegheny County voters approved a $43,680,000 bond issue for public works, including $6,000,000 for a town hall, $2,550,000 for a county office building, and $10,930,000 for new boulevards and highways.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 3, 1928%0a%3c Fire destroyed the Cameo Theater building at 347 Fifth Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 12, 1928%0a%3c State Superior Court approved Sunday symphony concerts for Pittsburgh; Sabbath Association announced it intended nevertheless to demand enforcement of the blue laws of 1794.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 16, 1928%0a%3c The first film "talkie," titled Tenderloin, was introduced at the Stanley Theater. Previewers said it had less than 10 minutes "audible" dialogue, and one commented the "project is so new that its possibilities scarcely can be gauged yet."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 17, 1928%0a%3c Called the "scenic boulevard of Pittsburgh," Mount Washington Roadway, to the top of Mount Washington, was opened with a mile-long parade followed by a celebration.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 8, 1928%0a%3c Westinghouse staged what was said to be the worlds first demonstration of "motion pictures broadcast by radio" -- "television" -- in its East Pittsburgh laboratories. The idea was worked out by Dr. Frank Conrad, assistant chief engineer at Westinghouse.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 15, 1928%0a%3c Air passenger service from the city was instituted.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 28, 1928%0a%3c Site for a new county airport (Lebanon Church Road) was chosen.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 6, 1928%0a%3c In the election of Herbert Hoover as President, Allegheny County gave Hoover 213,681 votes, and Al Smith 159,718.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 19, 1928%0a%3c Two thousand scientists, representing 20 different nations, assembled at Carnegie Tech for the opening of the Second International Conference on Bituminous Coal, initiated in 1926 by Tech President Thomas S. Baker.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 26, 1928%0a%3c A constitutional amendment to permit Pittsburgh and Allegheny County to consolidate into a metropolitan district was approved by a state-wide vote.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 11, 1929%0a%3c Declaring that the city should assume leadership in the fight against air pollution, City Council authorized installation of smoke prevention equipment at the citys pumping station at Brilliant.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 13, 1929%0a%3c President James A. Farrell, of the United States Steel Corporation, announced a $20,000,000 expansion program for subsidiary plants at Duquesne, McKeesport, and Braddock.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 1, 1929%0a%3c The 37-story Grant Building, tallest in the city and topped by an airplane beacon spelling out Pittsburgh in Morse code, was ready for occupancy.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 7, 1929%0a%3c A metropolitan charter bill, designed to make Pittsburgh the fifth largest city in the United States with a consolidated population of 1,319,684, was prepared for the State Legislature.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March, 1929%0a%3c The 32-story Koppers Building was opened to tenants.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 25, 1929%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Metropolitan District Charter, submitted to an Allegheny County vote, failed to acquire the required two thirds majority in each of 62 municipalities, a majority of the total in the county; city voters were eight to one in favor of the bill, but only 47 municipalities cast two thirds vote.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 28, 1929%0a%3c A five-day work week was adopted by the building trades of Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 12, 1929%0a%3c Contract for the new airport on Lebanon Church Road was signed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September, 1929%0a%3c Freda Seund became the first woman in Pittsburgh to be instructed in flying and to solo at a Pittsburgh airfield.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 24, 1929%0a%3c Mount Mercy College for Women was opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 18, 1929%0a%3c A crowd of 100,000 persons viewed a river pageant marking the completion of the canalization of the Ohio River.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 5, 1929%0a%3c Pittsburgh residents voted overwhelmingly in favor of adoption of voting machines in Pennsylvania.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 5, 1929%0a%3c R. B. Mellon, president of Mellon National Bank, resigned as chairman of the County Planning Commission in order, he said, to make a trip to Europe. His action was construed as an indication that a proposal to built a $6,000,000 town hall would be delayed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December, 1929%0a%3c The Gulf Oil Company was making final plans for erection of its 11 million dollar office building at Seventh and Grant.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 16, 1929%0a%3c Maurice Falk announced creation of a $10,000,000 fund by the Maurice and Laura Falk Foundation for welfare and charitable purposes.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 21, 1929%0a%3c Saw Mill Run Boulevard was opened to the public.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1930%0a%3c Population: 669,817.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1930%0a%3c KDKA announced the erection of a powerful transmitter at Saxonburg.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 3, 1930%0a%3c The United States purchased land for a new Post Office Building.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 12, 1930%0a%3c Pittsburgh taxi drivers held a mass meeting at Duquesne Gardens to begin a strike against the Green and Yellow Cab companies in protest against what they claimed was a pay cut.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 28, 1930%0a%3c United States Steel reported record peacetime profits of $197,531,349.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 14, 1930%0a%3c Police used tear-gas bombs to disperse a crowd on Center Avenue; two cabs were burned and 10 persons arrested as taxi strike violence continued.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 16, 1930%0a%3c The cornerstone was laid for the new $2,700,000 county office building at Ross and Diamond Streets.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 9, 1930%0a%3c Jones and Laughlin announced a $20,000,000 expansion program for its plants in Pittsburgh and Aliquippa.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 10, 1930%0a%3c The Better Traffic Committee recommended a ban on all Downtown curb parking; it also urged Mayor Charles H. Kline to eliminate the practice of "fixing" traffic tags.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 11, 1930%0a%3c The Baltimore and Ohio Railroad applied for a federal permit to build a river-rail terminal on the Monongahela River.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 27, 1930%0a%3c Sara Soffel was sworn in by Judge Richard Kennedy as judge of County Court, the first woman jurist in Pennsylvania.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September, 1930%0a%3c Construction work started on the $6,000,000 Mellon Institute building at Fifth and Bellefield.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 18, 1930%0a%3c Chamber of Commerce recommended to the United States Census Bureau a Greater Pittsburgh metropolitan area with 4043 square miles in 13 counties of Pennsylvania, Ohio, and West Virginia with a population of 2,203,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 2, 1930%0a%3c Rear Admiral Richard E. Byrd addressed 3000 at Syria Mosque during National Safety Congress here.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 12, 1930%0a%3c Eucharistic Congress was held in Forbes Field.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 21, 1930%0a%3c City Council passed an emergency proposal to set up a fund of $100,000 to aid families in need.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 21, 1930%0a%3c McCann and Company opened for business in its new 10-story building at Diamond and Ferry Streets.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 25, 1930%0a%3c The Mississippi Valley Association, in convention at St. Louis, endorsed proposed construction of an Ohio River-Lake Erie canal at the request of Pittsburgh and Youngstown business interests.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 25, 1930%0a%3c A capacity audience filled the Stanley Theater for a benefit show for Pittsburgh unemployed and needy families; among those featured were Phil Baker, Fred Stone and Dick Powell.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December, 1930%0a%3c The Gulf Oil Company was engaged in the construction of a research center at Craft Avenue and the Boulevard of the Allies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 30, 1930%0a%3c A deed of trust filed by Andrew Mellon created the A. W. Mellon Educational and Charitable Trust.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 15, 1931%0a%3c The Chamber of Commerce reported that 27 new manufacturing plants and warehouses, representing investments totaling $2 9,502,-000, started operations in the Pittsburgh district in 1930.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 16, 1931%0a%3c Their funds exhausted, relief agencies warned that approximately 47,750 Pittsburgh district residents would "begin starving" immediately.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 27, 1931%0a%3c Gulf Oil opened a new refinery on Neville Island.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 5, 1931%0a%3c McClintock-Marshall and Bethlehem Steel Companies merged.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 11, 1931%0a%3c The Homer Smith, pleasure steamboat, burned at the North Side wharf.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 17, 1931%0a%3c The county commissioners voted $3,000,000 for construction of the Homestead High Level Bridge.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 11, 1931%0a%3c Pittsburghs first police radio "cruisers" were patrolling the streets as WPOU, police radio station, began broadcasting.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 3, 1931%0a%3c Buhl Foundation announced plans for a 45-acre housing development on Mount Washington to be known as Chatham Village, the first low-rent community housing project in the nation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 14, 1931%0a%3c Florenz Ziegfelds Follies opened the new season of their 23rd edition at the Nixon Theater; among those featured in the cast were Helen Morgan, Gladys Glad, Ruth Etting, Harry Richman, and, in the chorus, two Pittsburgh girls -- Zecil Silvonia and Mony Lange.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 25, 1931%0a%3c Mayor Kline was indicted with Bertram L. Succop, former director of supplies, on 49 counts of misdemeanor in office.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 30, 1931%0a%3c About 5000 hunger strikers paraded in the city streets.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 23, 1931%0a%3c Forty-two aged men and women were killed in or died from the effects of a fire that destroyed the Little Sisters of the Poor Home at Penn Avenue and South Aiken; 157 others were hurt.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 29, 1931%0a%3c Wiley Post and Harold Gatty, renowned round-the-world fliers, were given an enthusiastic welcome in Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 19, 1931%0a%3c The McKees Rocks-Ohio River Boulevard Bridge was opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 15, 1931%0a%3c For the first time in Allegheny County, voting machines -- 186 of them -- were used in the primary election.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 21, 1931%0a%3c The Bank of Pittsburgh announced its decision to close to conserve interests of depositors and stockholders.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 30, 1931%0a%3c The 583 feet tall Gulf Building went into construction.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 28, 1931%0a%3c The Edgar Thomson works in Braddock prepared to re-open; plans were announced to reemploy about 7000 at Homestead and Braddock.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 4, 1931%0a%3c Hunger Marchers, en route in trucks and autos to Washington, D.C., to urge an unemployment insurance bill, stopped over in Pittsburgh and requested food and shelter from Helping Hand Society headquarters.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 22, 1931%0a%3c Five million dollars were distributed to various institutions by the H. C. Frick estate.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1932%0a%3c Of the 197 homes designed on Buhl Foundations Chatham Village, 129 were completed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 5, 1932%0a%3c Led by Father James R. Cox, a jobless army of 15,000 men left St. Patricks Church, at Seventeenth Street and Liberty Avenue, and headed for the Capital of the nation; many were afoot in a driving rain.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 6, 1932%0a%3c The county government was reorganized, and six departments were created: Highways, Property and Supplies, Parks, Airport, Elections, and Law.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 8, 1932%0a%3c Exhausted and hungry, Father Coxs jobless army arrived home after making a plea to Congress and President Hoover for immediate relief and jobs and warning that "something must be done to avert violence."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 17, 1932%0a%3c More than 55,000 persons, in a rally at Pitt Stadium, cheered Father Cox, "Shepherd of the Unemployed," as he announced formation of the "Jobless Party" and himself as its candidate for president.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 22, 1932%0a%3c Patrick T. Fagan, president of District 5, United Mine Workers, announced union acceptance of a 10 per cent wage cut for coal miners employed by the Pittsburgh Terminal Coal Corporation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 4, 1932%0a%3c A. W. Mellon, at the age of 76, was appointed ambassador to Great Britain after serving 11 years as Secretary of the Treasury.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 5, 1932%0a%3c Barney Dreyfuss, president and owner of the Pittsburgh Pirates since 1899 and an organizer of the first World Series, died at the age of 66 at Mount Sinai Hospital in New York.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 7, 1932%0a%3c Winston Churchill visited the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 28, 1932%0a%3c In order to provide employment for the needy, the city began to extend the Mount Washington Road project; six stations were also set up for free food distribution.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 28, 1932%0a%3c The "Snodgrass-Herron" plan for a $5,500,000 Downtown subway to relieve traffic congestion was presented to Council.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 26, 1932%0a%3c A $5,000,000 unemployment relief bond issue was approved in the primary election by Pittsburgh voters.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 14, 1932%0a%3c Mayor Charles H. Kline and his ousted supplies director, Bertram L. Succop, were found guilty of misconduct in office in a jury trial in Butler.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 6, 1932%0a%3c A "Bonus Army", World War I veterans seeking payouts from the government, marches through Pittsburgh en route to Washington.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 8, 1932%0a%3c Students demonstrated against General Douglas MacArthur when he delivered the commencement address at the University of Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 8, 1932%0a%3c Construction was started on the new $8,000,000 federal building and post office on Grant Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 5, 1932%0a%3c Organized labor of Pittsburgh held its first parade in a dozen years and ended it at West View Park, where William Green, president of the AFL, called for shorter working hours and a more equitable distribution of wealth.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 10, 1932%0a%3c Thirty thousand persons attended the dedication of the George Westinghouse Bridge, the $1,750,000 link in relocated Lincoln Highway over Turtle Creek.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 15, 1932%0a%3c Mayor Kline returned to City Hall and to his "political fence mending" after Judge Thomas D. Finletter reversed a jury verdict and set him free; former Supplies Director Succop was sentenced to one year in jail.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 15, 1932%0a%3c President Herbert Hoover campaigned in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 19, 1932%0a%3c Speaking as a presidential candidate before 30,000 at Forbes Field, Governor Franklin D. Roosevelt, of New York, expressed opposition to payment of the soldiers bonus "until the government has balanced the budget and has a surplus of cash in the treasury." It was his first public; declaration on the bonus issue since his nomination.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 8, 1932%0a%3c Franklin D. Roosevelt carried Allegheny County by 40,000 votes in the Democratic sweep that placed him in the White House.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 14, 1932%0a%3c Distribution of free milk to 50,000 needy and undernourished children was started in 500 schools of Allegheny County.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 14, 1932%0a%3c The Duquesne National and Diamond banks closed their doors because of heavy withdrawal of deposits.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December, 1932%0a%3c The Duquesne Club was building a 13-story addition to its Sixth Street headquarters.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 2, 1932%0a%3c Property owners threatened a "taxpayers strike" unless Mayor Kline reduced proposed $25,000,000 budget for 1933 by 25 per cent.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 15, 1932%0a%3c City Council lowered the mill levy and cut Mayor Klines budget 20 per cent.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 10, 1933%0a%3c The 10th Street Bridge was completed and opened to traffic.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 5, 1933%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Stock Exchange closed at the start of a bank holiday ordered by the President; the Pittsburgh Clearing House prepared to issue scrip.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 9, 1933%0a%3c At a rally of 2000 persons in Syria Mosque, plans were made to send a delegation to Harrisburg to fight for city-manager form of government for Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 14, 1933%0a%3c Thirty-three banking institutions in Pittsburgh reopened for normal business activity and were crowded through the day with thousands of depositors.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 31, 1933%0a%3c Mayor Charles H. Kline, described as a "defeated and broken man," resigned after seven years in office; Council President John S. Herron became Mayor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 7, 1933%0a%3c The Post-Gazette reported: "With a whoop of joy, thousands of parched Pittsburgh throats greeted the end of the Great Dry Era at 12:01 oclock this morning." Large crowds milled about outside Pittsburgh breweries waiting for first legalized 3.2 beer.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 11, 1933%0a%3c A group of 224 men -- the first from Pittsburgh to join President Roosevelts reforestation army -- entrained for Virginia.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 5, 1933%0a%3c Relocated and widened Pittsburgh-Butler Highway (Route 8) was opened to traffic.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 1, 1933%0a%3c The Chamber of Commerce estimated that 95 per cent of all Pittsburgh businesses were enrolled under the banner of the NRA Blue Eagle.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 20, 1933%0a%3c Modern professional football began in Pittsburgh when the Pittsburgh Pirates, under ownership of Arthur J. Rooney, lost, 23 to 2, to the New York Giants before 25,000 at Forbes Field.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 9, 1933%0a%3c After President Roosevelt ordered "captive mine" owners to make peace, 75,000 miners of western Pennsylvania returned to work. Philip Murray, international vice-president of the United Mine Workers, and Thomas Moses, president of the H. C. Frick Coke Company, began negotiating differences.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 11, 1933%0a%3c Three thousand men ended a six-day attempt to "bring back prosperity" by staying on the job and producing steel while barricaded inside the Clairton byproducts plant of Carnegie Steel Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 7, 1933%0a%3c Pittsburghers voted out the "blue laws" and voted in Sunday baseball and other sports. They also approved a constitutional amendment to permit the State Legislature to draft a new metropolitan charter for Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 7, 1933%0a%3c William McNair was elected Mayor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 10, 1933%0a%3c In a conference at the White House, President Roosevelt advised Mayor-elect McNair and his campaign chairman, David L. Lawrence: "Now give the people of Pittsburgh good administration."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 1, 1933%0a%3c Richard Beatty Mellon, junior partner in the Mellon banking empire, brother of A. W. Mellon, died at the age of 75 in his Fifth Avenue mansion.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 1, 1934%0a%3c New year reports showed Pittsburgh business in 1933 increased 18 per cent in volume over 1932.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 2, 1934%0a%3c According to news accounts, "pandemonium broke loose" at City Hall as Mayor McNair, in his first day in office, began feuding with Council over confirmation of his cabinet appointments.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 14, 1934%0a%3c Civil Works Administrator Harry L. Hopkins ordered an investigation into trade union charges of "political favoritism" in the hiring of men for CWA jobs in Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 13, 1934%0a%3c Plans were announced for a $350,000 juvenile court and detention home in Oakland.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 26, 1934%0a%3c An Akron-to-Pittsburgh passenger train of the Pennsylvania Railroad plunged off a bridge at Merchant Street as it sped into the North Side station; nine persons were killed and 39 injured.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 27, 1934%0a%3c Steel mills in the Pittsburgh district retained the 40-hour week and granted 10 per cent pay raises so 100,000 steel workers, increasing district payrolls by a total of approximately $1,750,000 per month.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June, 1934%0a%3c Hervey Allen, Pittsburgh novelist, visited in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 28, 1934%0a%3c The government approved a $25,000,000 loan to the Allegheny County Authority for a construction program entailing 12,000 jobs for unemployed men.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 9, 1934%0a%3c Pittsburgh artist John Kane became a controversial figure in the national art world.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 13, 1934%0a%3c Postmaster James A. Farley dedicated Pittsburghs new $7,000,000 post office-federal building in an outdoor ceremony on Grant Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 28, 1934%0a%3c One of the lecturers at the meeting of the American Association for the Advancement of Science, attended by a selected group of 400 scientists, was Professor Albert Einstein; he spoke on the "equivalent of mass and energy" in the Carnegie Tech Little Theater.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 2, 1935%0a%3c Business activity in Pittsburgh in 1934 was 68 per cent higher than 1933; industrial production was up 5.6 per cent over 1933 and 20 per cent over 1932, according to business summaries.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 19, 1935%0a%3c Andrew Mellon announced that he would give his art collection to the federal government to be housed in a gallery in Washington, D.C.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 25, 1935%0a%3c The United Engineering and Foundry Company of Pittsburgh received a $3,000,000 order for the Zaporoptal Steel Works in Soviet Russia -- one of the largest contracts ever placed in the United States for foreign shipment.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 26, 1935%0a%3c In what was said to be the largest industrial dismantling project in the citys history, the National Tube Company began disassembling its Pennsylvania plans, Second Avenue, and Republic plant, on 24th Street, South Side.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 1, 1935%0a%3c A slight earth tremor was felt in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 4, 1935%0a%3c In a Democratic caucus in Harrisburg, State Democratic Chairman David L. Lawrence demanded that the McNair ripper bill be pushed through the Legislature. While he later denied having made such a speech in the caucus, he was quoted as saying: "I put him [McNair] in, and Ill take him out."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 21, 1935%0a%3c Two Pittsburghers -- William P. Witherow, representing industry, and Philip Murray, representing organized labor -- were named by President Roosevelt to the NRA board.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 21, 1935%0a%3c Father Coxs Old St. Patricks Church, a 125-year-old Pittsburgh landmark and one of the most popular churches in the city, was destroyed by fire.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 12, 1935%0a%3c The Monongahela House, where policy-making party caucuses were held prior to and during the first Republican convention in 1856 and said to be, for that reason, the "birthplace of the Republican Party," closed its doors. A plan to convert it to Jones and Laughlin office building failed to materialize.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 12, 1935%0a%3c Nearly 6000 persons gathered in and about the chapel for dedication of the East Liberty Presbyterian Church, built at a cost of more than $4,000,000 by Mr. and Mrs. R. B. Mellon as a memorial to their respective mothers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 3, 1935%0a%3c Mayor McNair installed a bed in his office in preparation for a long siege in the event the ripper bill against him was passed by State Legislature.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 19, 1935%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Metropolitan District Charter bill, amended drastically by the House, was defeated in the State Senate.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 23, 1935%0a%3c The McNair ripper bill died with adjournment of the Legislature.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 14, 1935%0a%3c Andrew Mellon announced a gift of $10,000,000 for construction of the National Gallery of Art in Washington, D.C.; his private art collection, accumulated at a cost of $25,000,000 and valued at $40,000,000, was made immediately available to the gallery.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 5, 1935%0a%3c Pittsburgh and Allegheny County voters approved Sunday movies by a vote of three to one.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 24, 1935%0a%3c Large crowds filled theaters of the city as Sunday movies were shown for the first time.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 16, 1935%0a%3c In the citys healthiest economic signs since before the 1929 crash, Jones and Laughlin announced a $40,000,000 expansion program, including a new $25,000,000 sheet and strip mill on Second Avenue, and the Pennsylvania Railroad placed an order for 10,000 brake sets with the Westinghouse Air Brake Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 2, 1936%0a%3c Business reviews showed a definite upturn of Pittsburgh business in 1935; general business activity was up 14.7 per cent over 1934 and 45.3 per cent over 1932; department store sales were up 6.5 per cent.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 25, 1936%0a%3c Dr. Robert E. Doherty, Yale dean and electrical researcher, was elected president of Carnegie Tech to succeed Dr. Thomas S. Baker.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 26, 1936%0a%3c An ice gorge formed in the Allegheny River and moved toward Pittsburgh; flood waters swept over many Western Pennsylvania communities.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 17, 1936%0a%3c (St. Patricks Day): The rivers rose to 34 feet at the Point, and for the first time in 23 years water flowed over the citys low-level streets.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 18, 1936%0a%3c Floodwaters reached a crest of 46.4 feet, highest in the citys history, and began receding; some streets were inundated by 20 feet of water.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 19, 1936%0a%3c More than 60 persons were believed dead as the flood stage dropped to 32.1 feet; health, relief, and city agencies mustered support to fight disease, hunger, and cold; explosions and fires added to the peril.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 19, 1936%0a%3c Between 5000 and 7000 men, women, and children were rescued from flooded homes in the McKees Rocks "Bottoms."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 20, 1936%0a%3c The flood death toll was reported at 46 known dead and 384 injured; the Red Cross was attempting to assist 50,000 homeless persons; drinking water was restored; bandits and vandals roamed the area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 20, 1936%0a%3c Municipal officers from 200 cities arid towns in the Tri-State area met here in an emergency conference to discuss flood prevention for the future.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 22, 1936%0a%3c The Pittsburgh district struggled to get back to normal, but 110,144 men, women, and children remained homeless in Allegheny County.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 24, 1936%0a%3c City Council asked the federal government for $10,000,000 to replace and repair 1000 homes destroyed and 8000 damaged by flood waters.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 27, 1936%0a%3c The flood death toll rose to 74. The Chamber of Commerce, representing the business interests of Pittsburgh, informed the federal government that the delay of an adequate flood-control program, sought since 1907, had cost Allegheny County between $150,000,000 and $200,000,000 in property loss.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 30, 1936%0a%3c The National Guard was withdrawn, the Triangle was reopened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 18, 1936%0a%3c Mayor McNair was jailed for disobeying a court order directing him to return a $100 fine to an alleged numbers writer who had successfully appealed his conviction to County Court; the Mayor was released from jail on agreeing to return the fine.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 17, 1936%0a%3c The Steel Workers Organizing Committee held its first meeting in the Commonwealth Building and named Philip Murray, international vice-president of United Mine Workers, as chairman of a planned organizing campaign.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 22, 1936%0a%3c Congress passed the flood-control act, setting up funds for flood-control work in this district.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 27, 1936%0a%3c Newly completed Allegheny General Hospital was dedicated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 2, 1936%0a%3c Addressing 50,000 persons at Forbes Field, President Roosevelt predicted a balanced budget based on an increase in national income.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 6, 1936%0a%3c With no advance notice, William H. McNair resigned and turned the office of Mayor over to Cornelius P. Scully, president of Council and McNairs bitterest personal enemy in his three years in office.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 8, 1936%0a%3c The Reverend Charles E. Coughlin, Detroit radio priest and head of the National Union for Social Justice, in a speech to an overflow crowd of 4500 at Syria Mosque, charged that President Roosevelt "has adopted communistic activities."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 11, 1936%0a%3c One hundred thousand Catholic men of Pittsburgh assembled at Pitt Stadium for a eucharistic rally.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 13, 1936%0a%3c Mayor McNair repented and withdrew his resignation, but Council declined to accept it. Mayor Scully fired Leslie Johnston, public works director.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 27, 1936%0a%3c Governor Alfred M. Landon, of Kansas, appeared in Pittsburgh as the Republican presidential candidate and spoke to a crowd of 20,000 at Duquesne Gardens.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 3, 1936%0a%3c A total of 560,000 Allegheny County citizens voted in the presidential election to set a balloting record, 150,000 above the previous high. President Roosevelt carried the county by 188,478 votes; county Democrats won five seats in Congress, two in the United States Senate, and 27 in the State House.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 8, 1936%0a%3c At the conclusion of a two-day meeting of the CIO, headed by John L. Lewis, Lewis refused to meet William Green of AFL to discuss peace terms between the two union groups.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 20, 1936%0a%3c In a mass meeting at the Fort Pitt Hotel, Philip Murray, CIO chairman, declared in his keynote speech that "the company union must be put out of business." Employee representatives of 42 steel plants pledged full support to the CIO in its drive to organize all steel workers into one trade union.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 1, 1937%0a%3c Pittsburgh business in 1936 was at its highest level since 1930, up 29.2 per cent from 1935.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 14, 1937%0a%3c With 500 business guests in attendance, the Carnegie-Illinois Steel Corporation formally opened a new $10,000,000 plant in Homestead, a 100-inch semicontinuous plate mill with a capacity of 729,000 tons per year.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 15, 1937%0a%3c William A. Irvin, president of United States Steel, and Benjamin F. Fairless, president of Carnegie-Illinois, announced plans for the expenditure of $60,000,000 for the expansion and improvement of plants at Clairton and Braddock.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 20, 1937%0a%3c Three-month strike of 6000 Pittsburgh Plate Glass workers ended with an agreement for an eight-cent hourly pay raise.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 3, 1937%0a%3c The famed Lucy Furnace, first blast furnace built by Andrew Carnegie and named for his brothers wife, was dismantled.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 17, 1937%0a%3c Five United States Steel subsidiaries, headed by Benjamin F. Fairless, of Carnegie-Illinois, signed the first wage contract with the Steel Workers Organizing Committee. It established in the steel industry the $5-a-day minimum wage, the 40-hour week, vacations with pay, seniority rights, and grievance procedure.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 21, 1937%0a%3c Buhl Foundation gave $750,000 to the city for a planetarium and institute of popular science on the site of the old Allegheny City Hall.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 26, 1937%0a%3c Rivers hit crest of 35.1 feet, but only low-lying areas were affected. State Senator William B. Rodgers, Jr. demanded federal government make an immediate start on the long-delayed flood control program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 4, 1937%0a%3c The Better Traffic Committee endorsed Mayor Scullys plan to make Forbes Street and Fifth Avenue one-way streets and to construct a short trolley loop in the downtown area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 6, 1937%0a%3c Andrew W. Mellon dedicated the $10,000,000 Mellon Institute at the start of a five-day program in Carnegie Music Hall, highlighted by an announcement of a new successful treatment for pneumonia, developed by Institute scientists. Among the scores of leading scientists in attendance were three Nobel prize winners -- Drs. H. C. Urey, W. P. Murphy, and Irving Langmuir.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 11, 1937%0a%3c Mayor Scully proposed a $70,400,000 "pure water supply" to be brought to Pittsburgh and neighboring communities by an aqueduct system from northern creeks.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 12, 1937%0a%3c Twenty-five thousand men were idled at Jones and Laughlins Pittsburgh and Aliquippa plants by a strike ordered by Philip Murray in the Steel Workers Organizing Committee organizational drive. Jones and Laughlin and a group of other operators were accused by the union of violating the Wagner Labor Relations Act by refusing to sign wage scale contracts.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 20, 1937%0a%3c In the nations largest collective bargaining election, steel workers in Jones and Laughlin plants voted 17,028 for the CIO Amalgamated Association of Iron, Steel, and Tin Workers and 7207 against.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 21, 1937%0a%3c Governor Earle signed a bill to create a turnpike commission to is-sue $50,000,000 to $65,000,000 in bonds to finance construction of an "all-weather" toll highway from Pittsburgh to Harrisburg.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 22, 1937%0a%3c The Carnegie-Illinois Steel Corporation broke ground for its new Irvin works in West Mifflin Township estimated to cost $63,000,000 and employ 4000 men.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 2, 1937%0a%3c The Stephen C. Foster Memorial adjoining the Cathedral of Learning was dedicated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 4, 1937%0a%3c The Westinghouse Electric Corporation was building a cyclotron.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 7, 1937%0a%3c As the climax of a week-long celebration of the 150th anniversary of its founding, the University of Pittsburgh celebrated the completion of its 42-story Cathedral of Learning a decade after construction on the building was started.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 10, 1937%0a%3c The Kelsey-Hayes Wheel Company of Detroit, nations largest manufacturer of auto wheels, announced purchase of a Neville Island property as site for a $1,000,000 plant to employ 1500 persons.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 13, 1937%0a%3c The Post-Gazette initiated a series of articles by Ray Sprigle, exposing United States Supreme Court Justice Hugo L. Black as a member of the Ku Klux Klan; the articles led to demands for Justice Blacks resignation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 13, 1937%0a%3c The PWA in Washington announced a $2,847,000 appropriation for construction of a proposed psychiatric hospital on the Pitt campus.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 16, 1937%0a%3c The AFL-Central Labor Union expelled its president, Patrick C. Fagan, for his support of Mayor Scully. The Mayor had opposed the unions endorsement of the Kane-McArdle faction in the Democratic primary. All other CIO delegates were also expelled, and Fagan immediately announced formation of a "CIO-Central Labor Union" (Steel City Industrial Union).%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 20, 1937%0a%3c Andrew W. Mellon, who died on August 26, left his vast estate to his son, Paul Mellon, and son-in-law, David K. E. Bruce, to be administered "as they shall deem advisable and for best interests of my estate." The will bound them only to the deed that created the A. W. Mellon Educational and Charitable Trust, under which Mr. Mellons bequest to the public was estimated at between $100,000,000 and $500,000,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 1, 1937%0a%3c In a nationwide radio talk Justice Hugo Black admitted membership in the Ku Klux Klan, as charged by Ray Sprigle, but stated that he resigned after a successful primary race for the United States Senate and disclaimed all sympathy for the movement.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 20, 1937%0a%3c Chief Justice John W. Kephart, of the State Supreme Court, dedicated the new $350,000 Juvenile Court here, calling it a "monument to an enlightened judicial system."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 20, 1937%0a%3c Ground was broken at Crooked Creek dam site on upper Allegheny River, first of a network of dams to protect the Pittsburgh area from floods.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 21, 1937%0a%3c After a 10-year rebuilding job, directed by Edward Specter, the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra, backed by a successful public campaign for $300,000, presented its first concert as a major orchestra with Otto Klemperer as guest conductor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 27, 1937%0a%3c Benjamin F. Fairless was elected president of the U.S. Steel Corp.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 20, 1937%0a%3c The Homestead High Level Bridge was dedicated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 2, 1937%0a%3c Allegheny Housing Authority was established.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 3, 1937%0a%3c Air pilots said Pittsburgh appeared "like a ball of black ink" as one of the citys heaviest smoke screens cut Downtown visibility to 300 feet, slowed traffic, and caused lights to be turned on at high noon; home furnaces were held to be the chief cause.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 8, 1937%0a%3c Pittsburgh became the center of national steel production when United States Steel decided to move its management headquarters to Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 8, 1937%0a%3c The federal government earmarked $10,000,000 for low-cost housing projects planned by the Pittsburgh Housing Authority.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 1, 1938%0a%3c Reports showed that, de-spite a recession in the closing months of the year, Pittsburgh business activity for 1937 was up 8.7 per cent over 1936; the total resources of 97 banks in Allegheny County were reported to be $1,507,604,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 1, 1938%0a%3c At this date wage contracts between the Steel Workers Organizing Committee and the steel industry totaled 445.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 20, 1938%0a%3c Fallingwater, Edgar Kaufmanns country home designed by Frank Lloyd Wright, was viewed by interested visitors.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 27, 1938%0a%3c A plan for creating a historic memorial park in Pittsburgh, covering a 36-acre area at the Point and including proposed restoration of Fort Pitt and Fort Duquesne on their original sites, was before the National Park Service in Washington.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 27, 1938%0a%3c The WPA fixed the cost of a proposed sewage-disposal system to end stream pollution in Allegheny County at $25,000,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 3, 1938%0a%3c Fritz Reiner, noted Hungarian conductor, was appointed full-time director of the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 26, 1938%0a%3c Six hundred Pittsburgh business and civic leaders, at a dinner in the William Penn Hotel, were informed that Secretary of the Interior Harold Ickes had approved the Point as a site for a historic memorial. A Point Park commission was promoting the plan under chairmanship of Frank C. Harper.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 5, 1938%0a%3c Myron C. Taylor resigned as chairman of the board of United States Steel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 14, 1938%0a%3c Using the same gold-plated shovel that started the grading of Grants Hill, known locally as the Hump, Mayor Scully broke ground for the $1,050,000 Buhl Planetarium.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 2, 1938%0a%3c Ray Sprigle was awarded the Pulitzer Prize for his expose of Justice Hugo Blacks affiliation with Ku Klux Klan.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 5, 1938%0a%3c Downtown traffic was bottled up by a city-wide strike of parking-lot and garage attendants called by taxi-cab drivers union.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 11, 1938%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Railways Company, which had emerged from a receivership in 1922, again went into bankruptcy.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 12, 1938%0a%3c Homeopathic Hospital changed its name to Shadyside.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 12, 1938%0a%3c A survey conducted by the citys Bureau of Smoke Regulation indicated that smog was a major factor in Pittsburghs high pneumonia death rate.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 17, 1938%0a%3c The Allegheny and Ludlum Steel companies were merged.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June, 1938%0a%3c Steel Workers Organizing Committee contracts in the steel industry were increased to cover 529 mills.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 24, 1938%0a%3c Carnegie-Illinois announced a reduction in steel prices to approximately the level prior to 1938.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 2, 1938%0a%3c Douglas "Wrong Way" Corrigan, solo transatlantic flier, was a special guest at the opening of Allegheny Countys Sesquicentennial Anniversary celebration.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 1, 1938%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Housing Authority announced its first low-cost housing project would be located in the Hill District and named Bedford Dwellings, initial step in a $40,000,000 city-county slum-clearance program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 8, 1938%0a%3c The Democrats lost heavily in Allegheny County.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 15, 1938%0a%3c In its first constitutional convention at the Grotto, in North Side Pittsburgh, the CIO became a permanent organization; it also voted for a "no compromise" stand for peace on its own terms in its three-year war with the AFL.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 20, 1938%0a%3c After five years in construction, the Heinz Chapel, topped by a 235-foot spire, was dedicated on the Pitt campus as the gift of the Heinz family.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 21, 1938%0a%3c David L. Lawrence testified in Harrisburg before a legislative committee investigating charges that he and other high officers of state had engaged in a conspiracy involving "bribery, extortion, and coercion."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December, 1938%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Regional Planning Association, successor to the Municipal Planning Association, undertook a series of studies to attempt to find ways of halting the decline of property values in Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 13, 1938%0a%3c The worlds largest slabbing mill went into operation at the Edgar Thomson works of Carnegie-Illinois in Braddock.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 15, 1938%0a%3c Nearly 2000 business leaders attended dedication of new $60,000,000 Irvin works.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 19, 1938%0a%3c Again with the gold-plated "Hump shovel," Mayor Scully broke ground for the $3,000,000 Bedford Dwellings, low-cost housing community for 420 families.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January, 1939%0a%3c A $5,000,000 Monongahela River front improvement was started with WPA funds.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 3, 1939%0a%3c The effects of a business recession were felt in 1938, when business activity was down 39.3 per cent from 1937.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 21, 1939%0a%3c Army engineers recommended a $207,000,000 Beaver-Youngstown canal with "dead end" at Youngstown. Pittsburgh civic and business interests immediately mobilized to continue their 20-year fight for a canal extending to Lake Erie.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 5, 1939%0a%3c The University of Pittsburghs greatest era as a national football power ended with the resignation of Dr. John B. (Jock) Sutherland as head coach.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 10, 1939%0a%3c Pitt students went on strike in protest against Dr. Sutherlands resignation and against what they called "autocratic administrative evils" and the "bungling policies" of Chancellor John G. Bowman.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 13, 1939%0a%3c The city began construction of an $890,000 incinerator plant, its first, at the foot of 29th Street in Lawrenceville.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 14, 1939%0a%3c A new metropolitan commission was created at a meeting of business, labor, and civic representatives; its purpose was to formulate a "political reorganization which will produce the maximum of efficiency under the maximum of home rule."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 17, 1939%0a%3c The newly proposed metropolitan plan of government, seeking to establish Pittsburgh as the nations fifth city in size with a population of 1,700,000, was defeated at Harrisburg when it failed to receive the backing of Allegheny County senators, Democrats and Republicans alike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 27, 1939%0a%3c After five years of planning, work was underway to widen and re-build Bigelow Boulevard into a four-lane highway at a cost of $1,800,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 27, 1939%0a%3c Federal Court issued an injunction, sought by the Pittsburgh Railways Company, to restrain the city from enforcing a one-way traffic plan on Forbes and Fifth Avenue during closing of Bigelow Boulevard.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 27, 1939%0a%3c A 310-family project in McKees Rocks, with rents averaging $12.50 to $15 per month, was authorized by President Roosevelt for immediate construction as the first project in Allegheny Countys $19,000,000 public-housing program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June, 1939%0a%3c A glass house, the first of its kind to be made, was built in the city to be exhibited at the Worlds Fair in New York.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 2, 1939%0a%3c Because of improved business conditions, Westinghouse made full restoration of pay cuts ordered in 1938.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 19, 1939%0a%3c State Supreme Court upheld a verdict awarding $800,000 to Pennsylvania Railroad for damages against the city as the result of 1920 Bigelow Boulevard landslide.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 3, 1939%0a%3c Thousands of persons of all faiths, attending the county fair, joined in a peace demonstration as Great Britain declared war on Nazi Germany.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 24, 1939%0a%3c Buhl Planetarium, built at a cost of $1,100,000 and containing a giant projector, was dedicated; 400 scientists were guests at the first sky show.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 3, 1939%0a%3c Pittsburgh had its first movie "world premiere" in Hollywood style, with the showing of Allegheny Uprising at Loews Penn; among guests was Claire Trevor, one of the stars of the film.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 16, 1939%0a%3c After a three-month study, Robert Moses, of New York, and other leading planners unveiled their comprehensive "arterial plan" for solution of the Triangle traffic problem. At a total cost of $38,000,000, the plan included a Pitt Parkway, from a point east of Wilkinsburg to downtown Pittsburgh; a cross-town highway at upper border of the Triangle; reconstruction of Duquesne Way as the first step in a highway system to encompass the Triangle; removal of the Wabash Station and railroad tracks leading to it; im%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 8, 1939%0a%3c Democratic State Chairman David L. Lawrence was acquitted by a Dauphin County jury of three counts of conspiracy, one of statutory blackmail, and one of violating election laws. Thus the politically inspired charges came to nothing. Next day five thousand cheering Democratic leaders and workers gave Lawrence an enthusiastic welcome when he arrived at Pennsylvania Station from Harrisburg.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 26, 1939%0a%3c The Duquesne Light Company announced a $16,000,000 program of expansion and construction in the Pittsburgh district.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1940%0a%3c Population: 671,659.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 2, 1940%0a%3c Pittsburgh business activity for 1939 was 34.9 per cent over that of 1938, approaching 1929 levels in the closing months.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 5, 1940%0a%3c City and county officials announced that the $38,000,000 "Moses Plan" would be put into motion in 1940 with reconstruction of Duquesne Way, at a cost of $2,500,000, as the first project. Next on the list were a $1,400,000 Liberty Tubes grade separation plaza and a $1,500,-000 extension of Saw Mill Run Boulevard to West End.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 25, 1940%0a%3c "Musical Americana" the national radio program of Westinghouse, was instituted by KDKA.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 15, 1940%0a%3c A 20-inch snowfall stopped auto and trolley traffic and forced a two-day suspension in business and trading activities.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 26, 1940%0a%3c Investigators for the Dies Congressional Committee raided Pittsburgh Communist headquarters at 305-7 Seventh Avenue following arrest of James H. Dolsen, local Communist leader, on a congressional contempt citation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 27, 1940%0a%3c David L. Lawrence and seven other state Democratic leaders went on trial in Harrisburg on charge of conspiring to "mace" state payrolls (forcing employees to make political contributions); the original charges were made by ex-Attorney General Charles J. Margiotti. On April 12 Lawrence and his co-defendants were acquitted by a Dauphin County Court jury.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 15, 1940%0a%3c Bedford Dwellings, the first large federal public housing development, was completed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 4, 1940%0a%3c The Pirates played their first night game in Forbes Field.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 4, 1940%0a%3c Irving S. Olds succeeded Edward R. Stettinius, Jr., as Chairman of the United Steel Corporation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 13, 1940%0a%3c Industrial leaders met with public officials to plan mobilization of Pittsburgh district resources for the nations $5,000,000,000 defense program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 28, 1940%0a%3c Highland Park Zoo, completely overhauled and modernized, was reopened to the public.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 1, 1940%0a%3c A reorganization plan, consolidating 55 interlocking street transit systems into a single company, was filed, in Federal Court by trustees for the bankrupt Pittsburgh Railways Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 18, 1940%0a%3c Spear and Company leased a Wood Street 14-story building, formerly occupied by McCreerys Department Store, and announced plans for a $1,000,000 renovation program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 22, 1940%0a%3c Preparations were made to raze old Allegheny General Hospital and 25 other buildings in a congested North Side section, site of a huge new Sears, Roebuck and Company store and parking lot.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 23, 1940%0a%3c The two-level Water Street Bypass, built at a cost of $3,000,000 to relieve Downtown congestion, was opened to traffic.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 16, 1940%0a%3c The Mesta Machine Company received an $8,390,000 contract for "artillery material," largest national defense order placed in the Pittsburgh district to this date.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 1, 1940%0a%3c The nations longest toll expressway, the 160-mile, $70,000,000 Pittsburgh-to-Harrisburg "dream highway," was opened, and 1560 motorists paid tolls to use it the first day. Governor James ordered the speed limit fixed at 50 miles per hour.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 3, 1940%0a%3c Wendell L. Willkie spoke at a campaign rally in Forbes Field.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 4, 1940%0a%3c Fritzie Zivic, of Pittsburgh, won the decision from the favored Henry Armstrong to capture worlds welterweight title in a bout at Madison Square Garden, New York.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 10, 1940%0a%3c Plans for a park at the Point were announced.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 11, 1940%0a%3c After inspecting the flood-control program in the area, President Roosevelt arrived in Pittsburgh for a brief visit; in a two-and-a-half hour period he toured steel mills, inspected armament plants, and personally dedicated the $13,800,000 Terrace Village, second largest public-housing project in the nation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 16, 1940%0a%3c A total of 188,876 Allegheny County men registered for the nations first peacetime draft; of that number, 89,069 were city residents.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 5, 1940%0a%3c A record vote of 630,000 was cast in Allegheny County which gave President Roosevelt a majority of 105,599 over Wendell L. Willkie.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 14, 1940%0a%3c Two hundred men, women, and children escaped serious injury and probable death when the roof of the 50-year-old Harris-Alvin Theater, on Sixth Street, collapsed, bringing down tons of masonry and rafters; four persons were slightly hurt.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 14, 1940%0a%3c Mayor Scully created a new Point Park commission, with Councilman Fred Weir as chairman.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 22, 1940%0a%3c Philip Murray was unanimously elected president of the CIO at the conclusion of its Atlantic City convention; in a speech he protested President Roosevelts efforts to force a merger of the CIO and AFL.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 25, 1940%0a%3c A group of 40 young men, comprising the citys first draft contingent, passed physical examinations and entrained for Fort Meade, Maryland.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 11, 1940%0a%3c For his work in labor and national defense, Philip Murray was honored by the Junior Chamber of Commerce as Pittsburghs "man of the year".%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 18, 1940%0a%3c Crucible Steel Company announced a $10,000,000 expansion of its Midland plant.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1941%0a%3c An influenza epidemic caused the absence of 6000 pupils and 138 teachers from the citys schools.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 1, 1941%0a%3c Spurred by war demands for goods, business activity in the Pittsburgh district in the closing months of 1940 equaled that of 1929, according to surveys. Steel firms were operating at 100 per cent of capacity; all mills were planning major expansion; defense contracts placed with Pittsburgh district industries totaled $75,000,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February, 1941%0a%3c Mrs. Alan M. Scaife presented a cyclotron to the University of Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 5, 1941%0a%3c Dr. I. Hope Alexander, city health director, stepped up his efforts for a smoke-abatement campaign as a black smoke pall blotted out the sun and hung over the city. The Allegheny County Medical Society endorsed efforts to obtain an anti-smoke law.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 9, 1941%0a%3c Howard Heinz, president of the H. J. Heinz Company, and son of its founder, died at the age of 63 in a Philadelphia hospital.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 13, 1941%0a%3c City Hall was flooded with mail complaints about the smog that continued to blanket the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 14, 1941%0a%3c The Koppers Company received orders totaling $10,000,000 for coke ovens.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 19, 1941%0a%3c Eight members of City Council visited St. Louis in a body to witness the effects of that citys smoke-control program. They were advised by Mayor Bernard F. Dickmann that Pittsburghs air could be cleansed, too, "if you have the courage of your convictions."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March, 1941%0a%3c Richard K. Mellon was elected president of Pittsburgh Regional Planning Association to succeed Howard Heinz.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 20, 1941%0a%3c Dr. Joseph H. Barach of Presbyterian Hospital, in the first public hearing before the smoke commission, testified that smog increased the incidence of colds, pneumonia, and other illnesses in Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 14, 1941%0a%3c A major strike in the steel industry was averted when "Big Steel" signed a pact with the Steel Workers Organizing Committee for a 10-cent hourly wage increase for 240,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 5, 1941%0a%3c The University of Pittsburgh Bureau of Business Research reported that business activity in Pittsburgh was at its highest level in the 57 years for which records were available.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 22, 1941%0a%3c Paul Block, publisher of the Post-Gazette, died at the age of 63 in the Hotel Waldorf-Astoria in N.Y.C.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 1, 1941%0a%3c Pittsburghs eight major hotels were closed by a strike of 2400 AFL service employees.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 1, 1941%0a%3c A new and more stringent smoke control ordinance was passed by the City Council. Its enforcement was postponed because of the war.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 16, 1941%0a%3c The 15-day strike which closed the hotels was settled when union members voted to accept pay raises totaling $215,000 a year.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 22, 1941%0a%3c M. W. Clement, president of the Pennsylvania Railroad, announced the beginning of a program to modernize the Pittsburgh Pennsylvania Station.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 4, 1941%0a%3c W. P. Witherow, Pittsburgh industrialist, was elected president of the National Association of Manufacturers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 7, 1941%0a%3c Pittsburgh was shocked over the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 8, 1941%0a%3c More than 1200 Pittsburgh young men volunteered for enlistment in the armed services in one day.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 12, 1941%0a%3c Dr. Frank Conrad, father of radio broadcasting, died.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 1, 1942%0a%3c An industrial review for 1941 showed the steel industry produced approximately 18,000,000 net tons of steel ingots in 1941 to set a new production record; the output was 200 per cent greater than that of 1938 and 500 per cent over 1932.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 1, 1942%0a%3c The amount of prime defense contracts awarded to Pittsburgh industries totaled $137,865,000, and industry expansion projects amounted to $137,106,000. During the previous year, 23,000 workers were added to payrolls of iron and steel industry in the area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 1, 1942%0a%3c United States Steel prepared to move ahead with construction of a $75,000,000 mill in Homestead.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 9, 1942%0a%3c Archaeologists excavating near the intersection of the Boulevard of the Allies and Liberty Avenue found what was believed to be part of the curtain of Fort Pitt.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 16, 1942%0a%3c A total of 115,000 Allegheny County men in the expanded 20-to-44-year age group registered for the draft.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 1, 1942%0a%3c Domestic use of natural gas was curtailed as a war measure.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 3, 1942%0a%3c A 17-inch snowfall, one of the citys heaviest in history, paralyzed traffic.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 5, 1942%0a%3c The Dravo Corporation became the first defense industry to receive the all-Navy "E" in a ceremony highlighted by the launching of a submarine chaser built by Dravo.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 5, 1942%0a%3c Air raid drills were organized.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 6, 1942%0a%3c An estimated 300,000 persons assembled in the Downtown area to watch 35,000 marchers in an Army Day demonstration of loyalty and patriotism.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 7, 1942%0a%3c For the first time since labors split in 1936, CIO President Philip Murray and AFL President William Green spoke from the same platform and renewed their pledge of labor peace in a rally at Syria Mosque.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 19, 1942%0a%3c The 13 and 16 year-old sons of David L. Lawrence, national Democratic committeeman, were both killed in an automobile crash north of Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 19, 1942%0a%3c Corporal Frank Basa, wounded hero of the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor, was welcomed home by 40,000 persons who turned out for a parade in Lawrenceville.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 20, 1942%0a%3c Following an auction sale of prize dairy herds, bulldozers began leveling an 1100-acre tract of the old Bell farm in Moon Township for a $3,000,000 defense airport.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 29, 1942%0a%3c Pittsburgh and nine surrounding counties were designated by the federal government as a defense rental area, and rents were frozen.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May, 1942%0a%3c After serving as first assistant to nine city solicitors, Anne X. Alpern was appointed city solicitor by Mayor Scully as replacement for William A. Stewart, who entered the army. She was the first woman to become the chief legal officer of a major American city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 23, 1942%0a%3c The United Steel Workers of America, successor to the Steel Workers Organizing Committee, in convention at Cleveland, elected Philip Murray its first president at $20,000 a year.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 28, 1942%0a%3c Philip Murray was ousted as vice-president of the United Mine Workers as result of his break with John L. Lewis; John OLeary, of Pittsburgh, was appointed to succeed him.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 8, 1942%0a%3c First "blackout" practice took place.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 3, 1942%0a%3c The Army War Show was given at Pitt Stadium.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 17, 1942%0a%3c United Steel Workers wage policy committee, meeting at William Penn Hotel, accepted a 44-cents-a-day wage increase granted by War Labor Board to employees of "Little Steel" firms.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 11, 1942%0a%3c Western State Psychiatric Hospital, a 17-story building started in 1938 and built at a cost of $2,500,000, was dedicated by Governor Arthur H. James.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 16, 1942%0a%3c The Pittsburgh and West Virginia Railroad began razing its huge steel train shed behind the old Wabash Station and consigned it to the Pittsburgh scrap drive.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 22, 1942%0a%3c Women bus drivers were first employed%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 9, 1942%0a%3c H. J. Heinz, II, president of the 1942 United War Fund, which conducted a successful $4,500,000 drive, was honored by the Junior Chamber of Commerce as the "man of the year".%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 9, 1942%0a%3c John P. Busarello, a John L. Lewis follower, was elected president of District 5, United Mine Workers, defeating Patrick T. Fagan, holder of the office for 22 years and a leader of the Murray forces.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 25, 1942%0a%3c For the first time in Pittsburghs history the steel mills operated on Christmas Day.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 30, 1942%0a%3c Allegheny and Monongahela rivers overflowed, crested at 36.6 at the Point, forced war plants and Downtown theaters to close, made 7500 persons temporarily homeless, and disrupted auto and trolley traffic.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 2, 1943%0a%3c The Pittsburgh district was recognized as the nations No. 1 steel center after its 1942 record of having produced 20,000,000 tons of steel, chiefly for war purposes; employment was up 10 per cent.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 1, 1943%0a%3c Judge Sara M. Soffel, of Common Pleas Court, became the first woman ever to preside over an Allegheny County criminal court.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 1, 1943%0a%3c The Allegheny County War Transportation Committee appealed for "no compromise" co-operation from business in proposed plan to stagger working hours in order to prevent serious traffic congestion.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 11, 1943%0a%3c Twenty-nine German aliens living near war plants in the Pittsburgh district were arrested.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 17, 1943%0a%3c The USO-Variety Club Canteen at Pennsylvania Station was opened with 1700 servicemen as guests.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 20, 1943%0a%3c Pittsburgh police, enforcing an OPA ban on pleasure driving, stopped scores of motorists and cited a total of 403 in two days for violation of ration rules.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 24, 1943%0a%3c Drastic curtailment of bus and taxi service was required by ODTs 40 per cent cut in Pittsburghs gasoline allotment; the city faced a serious transportation problem as Pittsburgh Railways eliminated five bus routes, curtailed nine others.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 26, 1943%0a%3c The nations first gasoline "night court," set up by the OPA office here to speed up action against pleasure driving, opened in the Fulton Building.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 3, 1943%0a%3c Mayor Scully had his gas-ration privileges suspended for three months for violating the OPA driving ban by making a 350-mile trip to West Virginia.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 14, 1943%0a%3c A federal grand jury began a probe of an insurgent strike which hampered coal production in Western Pennsylvania for nearly a month and slowed steel mills.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 20, 1943%0a%3c Colonel Richard K. Mellon, 44-year-old Pittsburgh financier, was named director of the Pennsylvania Selective Service.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 19, 1943%0a%3c The $2,000,000 Duquesne Way improvement, another link in the planned Downtown arterial highway system, was opened to traffic. The county commissioners announced that the next step in the Moses Plan would be construction of a cross-town highway at a cost of about $10,000,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September, 1943%0a%3c The Allegheny Conference on Community Development was incorporated as a private, nonprofit organization "to develop, stimulate, encourage, and coordinate" planning activities in the area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 12, 1943%0a%3c A "Hollywood Cavalcade" at Forbes Field sold $87,000,000 in United States war bonds; among those featured were Greer Garson, Fred Astaire, and Harpo Marx.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 1, 1943%0a%3c The 19-county western Pennsylvania area went $6,567,000 over its $305,808,900 quota in the third War Loan bond drive.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 11, 1943%0a%3c Samuel Harden Church, 85, president of Carnegie Institute, died at Shadyside Hospital after he was stricken at his desk while planning the Institutes 46th annual Founders Day.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 26, 1943%0a%3c William Frew was elevated from the position of vice-president to the presidency of Carnegie Institute.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 29, 1943%0a%3c Contracts for the long planned Pitt Parkway (known as the Parkway East today) were signed in Harrisburg but the start of construction was postponed to the end of the war; the cost for the nine-and-a-half mile toad was estimated at$20,000,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 2, 1944%0a%3c Harry S. Truman, Democratic nominee for vice-president, called for the re-election of President Roosevelt at Syria Mosque.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 14, 1944%0a%3c Although granted a 10 per cent raise at the first of the year, 290 city garbage collectors staged their eighth strike in three years for higher wages.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 18, 1944%0a%3c A "ceiling zero" smog blanketed Pittsburgh and prevented thousands of war workers from reaching their jobs and homes%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 23, 1944%0a%3c Private haulers, hired by the city to collect accumulation of garbage, were operating under protection of an 80-man police squad after some trucks were attacked by roving pickets.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 24, 1944%0a%3c On the 11th day of the garbage strike, City Council passed two ordinances to end the three-year-old municipal operation and to place the collection of garbage in the hands of private contractors.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 2, 1944%0a%3c The city garbage collectors voted to return to work and began hauling away 9000 tons of refuse that had accumulated during their 20-day walkout.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 24, 1944%0a%3c Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra went on tour.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 24, 1944%0a%3c Technical Sergeant Charles E. "Commando" Kelly, Pittsburghs first Congressional Medal of Honor winner in World War II, received a heros welcome when he arrived home.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 10, 1944%0a%3c Mrs. Eleanor Roosevelt made her second visit to Pittsburgh in three months, spent the day touring the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 30, 1944%0a%3c LST-750, financed by Allegheny County residents through the purchase of $5,000,000 worth of extra war bonds, was launched at Dravos East shipyard on Neville Island before a crowd of 25,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 8, 1944%0a%3c In a mass rally outside the East Pittsburgh plant, 20,000 employees of Westinghouse reaffirmed a no-strike pledge for duration of the war.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 13, 1944%0a%3c The fifth War Loan went $5,000,000 over the $334,914,500 quota for the 19-county Western Pennsylvania area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 7, 1944%0a%3c A survey showed that war contracts completed to date or underway in Pittsburgh district plants totaled $903,398,644, with $322,000,000 of it delivered to the front lines.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 20, 1944%0a%3c Governor Thomas E. Dewey, of New York, Republican candidate for president, in a pre-election address at Hunt Armory in Pittsburgh, charged the New Deal with having "turned collective bargaining into political bargaining." While in the city he conferred with top union representatives of 65,000 coal miners in Western Pennsylvania.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 8, 1944%0a%3c In winning his fourth term, President Roosevelt carried Allegheny County with a 75,582 majority over Thomas E. Dewey.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 9, 1944%0a%3c As the countys first postwar project, the county commissioners scheduled construction of the $4,000,000 Dravosburg Bridge over the Monongahela River.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 14, 1944%0a%3c In one of the districts worst trolley disasters, six persons were killed and 34 injured when a Homestead-East Pittsburgh streetcar loaded with war workers crashed into the rear of an empty East Liberty-Homestead car at Munhall Junction.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 4, 1944%0a%3c Pittsburgh realty values dropped to $980,000,000, their lowest point in 25 years and about $30,000,000 under the 1941 assessment.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 11, 1944%0a%3c Thousands of Monday night Christmas shoppers were stranded Downtown by a 15-inch snowfall; all hotels were filled to capacity and lobbies were pressed into service as shelter; mills, schools, and many other activities were forced to suspend for two days.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1945%0a%3c Work stoppages were reduced 50 per cent during the year by a United States Steel -- United Steel Workers agreement on principle of a "fair days work for a fair days pay," setting up 32 job classifications and eliminating "speed up."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January, 1945%0a%3c Pittsburgh Foundation was instituted.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 3, 1945%0a%3c Mayor Scully signed an ordinance setting the 1946 budget at $25,417,422 -- highest since 1931.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 30, 1945%0a%3c Park H. Martin, who, as chief engineer of the County Works Department, formulated the countys long-range planning program in 1936, was appointed executive director of the Allegheny Conference on Community Development by Dr. Robert E. Doherty, chairman.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 16, 1945%0a%3c Dr. John G. Bowman the nations highest-paid educator of the day at $31,500 a year, resigned after 15 years as chancellor of the University of Pittsburgh; Dr. Rufus H. Fitzgerald, vice-chancellor, was designated his successor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 7, 1945%0a%3c Heavy production losses resulted and 25,000 persons in industry were idled by swollen rivers which rose to a crest of 33.4 feet.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 10, 1945%0a%3c The city marked the 100th anniversary of its great fire of 1845 with a parade and pageantry.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 12, 1945%0a%3c The city and county governments, business, schools, and all other activities were suspended, all churches scheduled special prayer services, and Mayor Scully asked all amusement places to close in mourning for President Franklin D. Roosevelt.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 30, 1945%0a%3c Dr. Paul R. Anderson, dean of Lawrence College in Appleton, Wisconsin, was elected president of Pennsylvania College for Women to succeed Dr. Herbert L. Spencer.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 8, 1945%0a%3c Councilman George E. Evan, chairman of the Pittsburgh Housing Authority and a pioneer in slum-clearance planning, died at the age of 69.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 25, 1945%0a%3c One hundred thousand persons turned out to extend a heros welcome to 64 officers and enlisted men returning home from the war.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 25, 1945%0a%3c Stockholders of the Pittsburgh Coal Company approved a merger with the Consolidation Coal Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 9, 1945%0a%3c Russian labor leaders arrived to tour the districts steel mills.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 14, 1945%0a%3c The city was jubilant over the surrender of Japan.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 17, 1945%0a%3c Pittsburgh district industries laid off 7000 workers as the first cancellation of a war contract became effective.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 6, 1945%0a%3c David L. Lawrence, 56-year-old Democratic state chairman, was elected Mayor of Pittsburgh by a margin of 12,000 votes; five Democratic councilmen retained their seats.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 14, 1945%0a%3c At meeting of civic leaders in the Duquesne Club, Richard K. Mellon, president of Regional Planning Association, urged concerted action on plans for a proposed 36-acre $6,000,000 state park at the Point.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 5, 1945%0a%3c Council passed an ordinance setting the highest real estate levy in the citys history-28 mills on land and 14 mills on buildings, a 12 per cent increase over that of 1945.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 15, 1945%0a%3c Artemas C. Leslie, son of State Senator Max G. Leslie, was elected district attorney by the judiciary to succeed Russell H. Adams, judge-elect.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 18, 1945%0a%3c The county commissioners approved a resolution to create the Allegheny County Sanitary Authority to build and operate a $50,000,000 county-wide sewage disposal system.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 21, 1945%0a%3c Park Superintendent Ralph E. Griswold angrily resigned in protest against an "archaic administrative system" for maintaining and operating the citys $25,000,000 park system.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1946%0a%3c Carnegie Institute of Technology received an $8,000,000 grant from the Carnegie Foundation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 7, 1946%0a%3c Sworn in as the citys 47th mayor for the start of the 13th year of unbroken Democratic rule in the city, Mayor David L. Lawrence promised that his basic objective was to make Pittsburgh "outstanding where it is now merely good."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 10, 1946%0a%3c The Commonwealth asked the city and county to contribute a total of $6,000,000 as their share of the estimated $31,000,000 cost of the Penn-Lincoln Parkway.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 15, 1946%0a%3c In the Pittsburgh district 18,000 Westinghouse employees joined a nationwide strike of 200,000 electrical industry workers seeking a $2-a-day wage increase.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 20, 1946%0a%3c In the largest single walk-out in the nations history, 800,000 CIO United Steel Workers -- 227,000 of them in the Pittsburgh district -- closed down the steel industry after President Trumans 11th hour fact-finding efforts failed. The first picket line appeared at the Irwin works and National Tube plant.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 21, 1946%0a%3c All mills in the district were silent, steel production hit a 50 year low; Philip Murray, in nation-wide broadcast from Pittsburgh, accused American business of an "evil conspiracy" to destroy labor unions.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 27, 1946%0a%3c R. K. Mellon and Sarah Mellon Scaife announced gift of a 13-acre tract of land at Fifth and Penn and $100,000 in cash for development by the city of a public recreation center.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 12, 1946%0a%3c Trolley service was suspended and the area was blacked out by a one-day strike of 3400 Duquesne Light employees demanding a 20 per cent cost-of-living pay increase.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 15, 1946%0a%3c Seventy thousand United States Steel employees in the Pittsburgh area began to return to work following the signing of an agreement for an 18-cent hourly wage increase, ending a 27-day shutdown of mills.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 28, 1946%0a%3c Attorney General James H. Duff, a Carnegie citizen, was slated as Republican nominee for governor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 1, 1946%0a%3c Threats of a power blackout were removed when Duquesne Lights independent union agreed to arbitrate the wage dispute.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 6, 1946%0a%3c A $200,000, five-alarm fire destroyed a building-supply building at 410 Liberty Avenue, and flames spread to the nearby Pittsburgh and West Virginia Railroad trestle and to part of the old Wabash Terminal.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 14, 1946%0a%3c The county commissioners proposed a $300,000 peoples bond issue for public improvements, including $8,000,000 for the Greater Pittsburgh Airport and an Ohio River Boulevard extension through the North Side into the Triangle.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 14, 1946%0a%3c The Farmers Deposit National Bank prepared to become a $200,000,000 institution with acquisition of the Pitt National Bank.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 18, 1946%0a%3c Maurice Falk, Pittsburgh philanthropist, co-founder of the Falk Chemical Company, and originator of the Maurice and Laura Falk Foundation, died at the age of 79 in Florida.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 22, 1946%0a%3c Another fire, with damages estimated at $500,000, gutted the Wabash Terminal and railroad trestle and damaged 11 warehouses. It was this group of structures which blocked the development of the Point area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 22, 1946%0a%3c State police moved into areas around Westinghouse plants to enforce a court order limiting picketing in the 67-day strike of Westinghouse workers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 25, 1946%0a%3c General Brehon B. Somervell, commander of the Army Service Forces in World War II, was elected president of the Koppers Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 1, 1946%0a%3c Smoke-control regulations, suspended with the start of the war, were revived in a new ordinance establishing October 1 as the effective date for first half of program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 4, 1946%0a%3c Enforcement of home provisions of the smoke-control ordinance was postponed one year as result of an agreement worked out by the Allegheny Conference on Community Development and the Western Pennsylvania Conference on Air Pollution, representing coal producers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 12, 1946%0a%3c An 18-cent hourly wage raise was awarded to Duquesne Light workers by the arbitration board.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 7, 1946%0a%3c Federal Court ordered the Pittsburgh Railways to reorganize and find an immediate solution to its financial problems.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 9, 1946%0a%3c A 115-day strike of 75,000 Westinghouse workers -- longest major walkout since the war -- ended with the CIO-United Electrical accepting an 18-cent hourly wage increase; 15,000 Pittsburgh district employees approved pact and prepared to go back to work.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 3, 1946%0a%3c The Civic Light Opera, founded on a $50,000 gift from Edgar J. Kaufmann and the 10-year efforts of a civic group headed by A. L. Wolk, H. Edgar Lewis, Mrs. Clifford Heinz, and others, opened its first eight-week summer season with a performance of Victor Herberts Naughty Marietta before 5000 persons at Pitt Stadium.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 19, 1946%0a%3c Pittsburghs Billy Conn was knocked out at Yankee Stadium, New York, in the eighth round of his second attempt to win the heavyweight boxing championship from Joe Louis.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 26, 1946%0a%3c Official casualty lists of the United States War Department placed Allegheny Countys World War II dead at 3982 out of a total of 26,554 for Pennsylvania.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 8, 1946%0a%3c The Mellon National Bank and Trust Company became a billion-dollar financial institution, one of the nations largest and strongest, as the result of an approval of merger by directors of the Union Trust Company of Pittsburgh and the Mellon National Bank.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 18, 1946%0a%3c Ground was broken in Moon Township for a $10,000,000 Greater Pittsburgh Airport extension.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 27, 1946%0a%3c The first Civic Light Opera season ended as a success, with total attendance of 270,000 and gate receipts at $319,121.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August, 1946%0a%3c Construction work started on a new bus terminal on the site of the old Monongahela House at Smithfield and Water streets.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 4, 1946%0a%3c The 13-story, 500-room Roosevelt Hotel was purchased by Charles M. Morris and Norbert Stern for $1,800,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 8, 1946%0a%3c After 47 years under ownership of the Dreyfuss family, the Pittsburgh Pirates Baseball Club was purchased, at a price reported to be about $2,250,000, by a combine headed by Frank E. McKinney, Indianapolis banker, and including singer Bing Crosby, attorney Thomas P. Johnson, of Pittsburgh, and realtor John W. Calbraith, of Columbus, Ohio.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 3, 1946%0a%3c In a move to break a deadlock in their wage dispute with the Duquesne Light Company, members of the 3800-member power union voted to strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 24, 1946%0a%3c The citys power supply was cut to 45 per cent when Duquesne Light Company employees failed to report for work; Union President George L. Mueller was sentenced to one year in jail for inspiring the strike in defiance of a court restraining order. Pittsburgh labor leaders, headed by County Commissioner John J. Kane, protested Muellers arrest.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 25, 1946%0a%3c Eight thousand steel and electrical workers in the Pittsburgh district struck in protest against George Muellers arrest; despite Muellers plea to them to return to work, union members voted in a meeting to refuse to consider a company offer until the court lifted its antistrike injunction. Trolley service was cut 50 per cent; many stores closed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 26, 1946%0a%3c Negotiations were resumed and formal picketing started when the contempt citation against George Mueller was dismissed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 28, 1946%0a%3c Trolley service was stopped by a sympathy strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 1, 1946%0a%3c The citys eight major hotels -- William Penn, Roosevelt, Fort Pitt, Pittsburgher, Keystone, Webster Hall, Schenley, and Henry -- closed at midnight when AFL hotel restaurant employees, Local 237, walked off job to enforce wage demands.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 1, 1946%0a%3c The citys smoke-control law became effective for industry, railroads, and commercial establishments.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 7, 1946%0a%3c Closed two weeks because of the power blackout, the department stores reopened and were stormed by crowds of eager shoppers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 14, 1946%0a%3c Despite the power strike, business and social life in Pittsburgh returned to near-normal; a number of auxiliary generating plant appeared on sidewalks outside Downtown buildings; traffic into the Downtown area increased 25 per cent; steel production was running at from 80 to 100 per cent of capacity; schools opened; crime decreased.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 14, 1946%0a%3c Trolley and bus operators voted to cross the electric union picket lines, and limited transit service was resumed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 21, 1946%0a%3c Full street lighting was resumed after the union agreed to submit wage demands to arbitration, ending the 27-day power strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 5, 1946%0a%3c The Very Reverend Daniel Ivancho, 38-year-old Cleveland priest, was consecrated bishop of the Byzantine-Slavonic Rite of the Roman Catholic Church in a four-hour ceremony at St. Pauls Cathedral; he was the second American to be so honored.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 12, 1946%0a%3c City Council approved an ordinance creating a five-man Urban Redevelopment Authority as an instrument for acquiring and clearing land in the citys fight against blight and slums; Mayor Lawrence became its chairman.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 18, 1946%0a%3c In a meeting called by the United Smoke Council, a majority of municipal officers of Allegheny County demanded that the proposed county-wide smoke-control law include all railroads.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 22, 1946%0a%3c A 53-day shutdown of eight Pittsburgh hotels ended when 1700 striking employees voted to go back to work.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 25, 1946%0a%3c The citys first "brown-out" became effective with a national order to curtail electric power consumption as the result of a coal short-age caused by another nationwide strike of miners.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 26, 1946%0a%3c Pittsburgh was assured funds for the Conemaugh Dam flood-control project when the Truman administration decided to spend an additional $55,000,000 for such work.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 5, 1946%0a%3c Some 120,000 steel workers, railroaders, and miners were idle in the Pittsburgh area because of the coal strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 9, 1946%0a%3c At the annual dinner of the Regional Planning Association in the Duquesne Club, announcement was made of the organization of the Pittsburgh Public Parking Authority and a plan to build 20 new parking garages for 25,819 cars daily at a total cost of $36,000,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 11, 1947%0a%3c The Veterans Administration approved plans for a 1248-bed hospital above Pitt Stadium at a cost of $11,000,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 22, 1947%0a%3c Hundreds of persons were forced to seek overnight shelter Downtown when an 11-inch snow-storm hit the city and disrupted traffic.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March, 1947%0a%3c Pittsburghs new "Ladycops," 100 strong, appeared for the first time at school crossings to protect children from traffic.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 17, 1947%0a%3c Ben Moreell, Chief of the United States Navy Bureau of Yards and Docks in World War II and organizer and commander of the construction battalions -- the famed "Seabees" -- was elected president and chairman of the board of Jones and Laughlin.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 20, 1947%0a%3c Mayor Lawrence ordered all-out crackdown on railroad violators of the citys new antismoke law.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 20, 1947%0a%3c Richard K. Mellon, as president of the Regional Planning Association, expressed wholehearted support of all 10 bills in the "Pittsburgh Package" legislative program for improving the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 2, 1947%0a%3c A six-month brewery jurisdictional war ended with a truce between AFL Teamsters and CIO Brewery Workers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 18, 1947%0a%3c Westinghouse and the United Electrical Workers signed a pact providing for an 11-1/2-cent hourly wage increase for workers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 18, 1947%0a%3c A record opening-day crowd at Forbes Field -- 38,2 16, including Bing Crosby -- saw the Pittsburgh Pirates, under new ownership, defeat Cincinnati, 12 to II.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 18, 1947%0a%3c The new bus terminal was opened at Water and Smithfield Streets and hailed as the first step in "the Downtown of tomorrow."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 20, 1947%0a%3c United States Steel granted a $1-a-day wage increase to 140,000 employees.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 23, 1947%0a%3c Pitt announced plans to build a $2,000,000 field house and gymnasium.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 30, 1947%0a%3c The State Senate passed, 25 to 4, a county-wide smoke-control bill covering railroads; also enacted in the Legislature was a bill to create a county-wide system of incineration.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 6, 1947%0a%3c Defeated in the House, a bill to create the Pittsburgh Parking Authority was rescued by Governor Duff and submitted for reconsideration.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 9, 1947%0a%3c A 31-day taxi strike ended when 900 members of Local 128, AFL Teamsters, agreed to a 45-cent hourly pay raise.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 21, 1947%0a%3c Philip Murray issued a two-year, no-strike order to 3000 United Steel Workers locals.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 23, 1947%0a%3c As the first step in a station improvement program, the Pennsylvania Railroad began dismantling its huge passenger train shed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 27, 1947%0a%3c A major advancement in smoke control was represented in the Pennsylvania Railroads announcement of a complete dieselization program, with the first 47 diesel locomotives scheduled for operation before the end of 1947.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 4, 1947%0a%3c The Allegheny Conference on Community Development, in its first "mass transit" report, branded Pittsburghs transportation system as outmoded; it recommended an Oakland to Downtown subway, express buses, a curb parking ban, and other measures.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 5, 1947%0a%3c The Parking Authority Act became law.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 8, 1947%0a%3c In the preceding 15-year period, the A. W. Mellon Educational and Charitable Trust contributed a total of $76,000,000 to local and national institutions, a trust report showed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 12, 1947%0a%3c The Brentwood Motor Coach strike ended after 44 days of one of the longest transportation tie-ups in city history.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 19, 1947%0a%3c The annual assessment report showed assessed valuation in the city had dropped to $957,234,801- nearly $250,000,000 below the 1936 figure.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 31, 1947%0a%3c A 60-day strike which idled 2500 truck drivers in Western Pennsylvania ended.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 31, 1947%0a%3c The Allegheny County Free Fair drew the largest one-day crowd in its history-roughly estimated at 450,000 persons.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 2, 1947%0a%3c For the first time police began enforcing the citys ban on Downtown curb parking between 8 and 9,30 AM, and 4:30 and 6 P.M. daily.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 9, 1947%0a%3c A river excursion boat, the Island Queen, said to be the largest river pleasure boat in the world, exploded as it was tied to the Monongahela River wharf; 19 persons were fatally injured.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 9, 1947%0a%3c City voters approved a $21,000,000 bond issue for an assortment of municipal improvements to cover sewers, streets, parks, and other facilities.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 23, 1947%0a%3c Mayor Lawrence returned to his desk after a six-week layoff enforced by a delicate eye operation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 1, 1947%0a%3c The citys antismoke ordinance, expected to save the city $16,000,000 a year in cleaning, health, and decorating bills was extended to 141,788 coal-burning private homes.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 3, 1947%0a%3c A survey showed that the steel industry was spending "in excess of $100,000,000" in the Pittsburgh district for expansion and replacement of old equipment.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 23, 1947%0a%3c A three-man congressional investigating committee opened a hearing on Pittsburghs critical housing shortage. Its climax came when the committee chairman, Senator Joseph R. McCarthy, of Wisconsin, threatened to expel City Solicitor Anne X. Alpern from the hearing room when she repeatedly called attention to the senator's failure to support public housing measures.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 29, 1947%0a%3c President Richard K. Mellon of the Pittsburgh Regional Planning Association, at its annual dinner, announced plans for redevelopment of 70 acres of the Lower Hill District and creation there of a "Pittsburgh Center," to include a sports arena for 18,000, apartment housing, a new street pattern, and other improvements.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 4, 1947%0a%3c William S. Rahauser, Democrat of Coraopolis, was elected district attorney over incumbent Artemas C. Leslie; five Democratic councilmen were re-elected; County Commissioners Kane and Rankin were re-elected; Earnest Hillman was elected minority commissioner.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 10, 1947%0a%3c A financial drive to back Henry A. Wallace for president as a third-party candidate was launched in Pittsburgh at Syria Mosque, where he spoke to an overflow crowd.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 24, 1947%0a%3c Mayor Lawrence presented to Council an all-time high budget, totaling $30,110,973 for 1948.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 28, 1947%0a%3c City Council passed the record-high budget and enacted three new special taxes -- mercantile, amusement, and personal property -- over the bitter opposition of business interests.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 28, 1947%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Board of Education adopted an $18,000,000 budget, an increase of $3,000,000 over 1947, and levied a new $5-a-year head tax on all city residents over 21 years.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 5, 1948%0a%3c Trolley fares went up to 10 cents cash and three-for-a-quarter tokens were eliminated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 15, 1948%0a%3c Secretary of State George C. Marshall spoke at the 74th annual dinner of the Pittsburgh Chamber of Commerce, warned against any cuts in United States aid to Europe.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 19, 1948%0a%3c State Supreme Court upheld the citys new mercantile and personal property taxes.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 20, 1948%0a%3c Richard K. Mellon, the Jaycees "man of the year," announced creation of a $6,400,000 Richard King Mellon Foundation -- the seventh to be set up by members of his family.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 29, 1948%0a%3c A long-smoldering feud between left- and right-wing factions of the CIO-United Electrical flared into riot proportions during a meeting at the Fort Pitt Hotel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 31, 1948%0a%3c Boggs and Buhl, 79-year-old North Side department store, was purchased for $2,500,000 by a group of Pittsburghers and New Yorkers and thus saved from liquidation; plans were announced for a $1,000,000 rejuvenation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 4, 1948%0a%3c The Equitable Life Assurance Society of New York purchased the 33-story Koppers Building for $6,000,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 14, 1948%0a%3c Workmen Evert J. Hungerford and John E. Morse were killed in a rock fall during construction of the Squirrel Hill Tunnels of the Penn-Lincoln Parkway.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 16, 1948%0a%3c At the outset of a strike of 1100 Yellow Cab drivers, Louis Di Lembo, 28, a striker, was killed on a Downtown street by a shot fired from a passing Owl Cab.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 24, 1948%0a%3c Fritz Reiner announced his resignation after 10 years as conductor of the Pittsburgh Symphony.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 26, 1948%0a%3c The Pennsylvania Railroad announced plans to build a $4,500,000 warehouse covering three blocks between Penn and Liberty avenues.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 9, 1948%0a%3c The 24-day Yellow Cab strike came to an end.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 11, 1948%0a%3c Judge William H. McNaugher ruled invalid a 1947 city ordinance to sell the historic Diamond Market House. He held that the city had no right to sell because it never legally owned the property, which was laid out in 1784 as a "public square" by John Penn and John Penn, Jr.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 21, 1948%0a%3c Duquesne Light announced plans for a $28,000,000 power plant at Elrama, near Clairton, to serve the area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 31, 1948%0a%3c George Hubbard Clapp, one of five men responsible for the production of aluminum, the founder of the Aluminum Company of America and the oldest alumnus of Pitt, died at the age of 90 at Sewickley Valley Hospital.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 11, 1948%0a%3c Dr. John B. (Jock) Sutherland, coach of the Pittsburgh Steelers and regarded as Pittsburghs greatest gridiron figure, died at the age of 59 at West Penn Hospital.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 12, 1948%0a%3c Soft-coal miners of western Pennsylvania began returning to work on the 29th day of a walkout that won for them $100-a-month retirement pay.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 14, 1948%0a%3c The rivers went to 29.5 feet in a "surprise" flood.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 15, 1948%0a%3c Thomas A. Mellon, retired president of Mellon-Stuart Company and nephew of the late A. W. Mellon, died at the age of 74.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 22, 1948%0a%3c United States Steel announced a $25,000,000 price cut after rejecting demands for a pay increase.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 24, 1948%0a%3c Pennsylvania Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of the Pittsburgh Public Parking Authority and opened the way for the start of a parking program in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 26, 1948%0a%3c W. L. Mellon, at 80, retired as chairman of the board of the Gulf Oil Corporation after 45 years as the firms active head; J. F. Drake was named his successor; S. A. Swensrud was named president. At the same annual meeting the company announced plans to spend $250,000,000 for expansion.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 31, 1948%0a%3c A five-alarm fire destroyed Pitts chemical engineering and metallurgical laboratory on the upper campus at a loss of $500,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 1, 1948%0a%3c The Philadelphia Company, Pittsburgh utility holding company, was ordered by the Securities Exchange Commission to dispose of its gas and transportation properties and dissolve its business.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 3, 1948%0a%3c The University of Pittsburgh announced the greatest single expansion move in its 161-year history, a $19,500,000 program to build eight new structures, including a new medical school, nurses home, and library. A campaign for $16,500,000 in public subscriptions was started.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 20, 1948%0a%3c Westinghouse agreed to an 8 per cent wage increase for 70,000 employees.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 1, 1948%0a%3c Wallace Richards, 44, director of Pittsburgh Regional Planning for 11 years and one of Pittsburghs leading professional planners, became assistant director of Carnegie Museum in charge of a revitalization program for that institution.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 20, 1948%0a%3c United States Steel raised prices of finished steel product an average of $9.34 per ton.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 22, 1948%0a%3c The city hired Herbert J. Dunsmore, Michigan expert in food and milk sanitation, as its first public health engineer.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 9, 1948%0a%3c Plans were announced for a 40-story combination United States Steel-Mellon National Bank and Trust Company office skyscraper to connect with the Mellon Bank Building on Fifth at Smithfield.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 23, 1948%0a%3c The city signed a $3,475,000 contract with the Broadway Maintenance Corporation of New York for installation and maintenance of an entirely new and modern street-lighting system.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 1, 1948%0a%3c The Veterans Administration revealed plans for a $17,000,000 hospital to consist of 11 major buildings on a 200-acre site adjoining the citys Leech Farm Tuberculosis hospital.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 2, 1948%0a%3c Edward V. Babcock, World War I Republican Mayor, former member of Council, county commissioner, and multimillionaire lumberman, died at the age of 84 at his home, 5135 Ellsworth Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 9, 1948%0a%3c William N. McNair, Pittsburghs most publicized, most quixotic Mayor and the citys best-known and most fervent single-tax advocate, died at the age of 68 when he was stricken in the St. Louis, Missouri, Union Station. He had gone to that city to address the Henry George School of Social Science.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 15, 1948%0a%3c Tens of thousands of Pittsburghers visited the Freedom Train during its stopover at Pennsylvania Station.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 28, 1948%0a%3c Bernard Nieman, president of Frank and Seder, died at the age of 68 at his home, 5405 Northumberland.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 1, 1948%0a%3c Senator Alben W. Barkley, Democratic vice-presidential nominee, campaigned in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 2, 1948%0a%3c Pittsburgh Playhouse announced plans for a new theater.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 3, 1948%0a%3c Mrs. William Thaw, Jr., once the "grand matron" of Pittsburgh society, died at the age of 94 at her home, 5427 Forbes Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 11, 1948%0a%3c In a major campaign address before 20,000 at Hunt Armory, Governor Thomas E. Dewey offered a 12-point program for labor to strengthen "free society."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 18, 1948%0a%3c Henry A. Wallace, Progressive candidate for President, spoke to a crowd of 3100 at Duquesne Gardens.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 22, 1948%0a%3c General Motors leased the Ambridge shipyards for a metal stamping plant.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 23, 1948%0a%3c President Truman addressed 25,000 enthusiastic partisans in and around Hunt Armory. Philip Murray shared the platform and spoke in support of the Presidents re-election.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 25, 1948%0a%3c General Motors announced plans to build a second metal stamping plant in the Pittsburgh district after purchasing a Mifflin Township site from Carnegie-Illinois Steel for its Fisher Body Division.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 27, 1948%0a%3c Westinghouse gave $200,000 to Pitt for a science building.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 31, 1948%0a%3c A four-day smog began to lift from the Pittsburgh district after causing the death of 20 people in nearby Donora.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 2, 1948%0a%3c Allegheny County gave Truman 325,411; Dewey 252,638; Wallace 10,883 in the presidential election. Congressman John R. McDowell, Republican member of the House un-American Activities Investigating Committee, was defeated by Harry J. Davenport in his bid for re-election.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 19, 1948%0a%3c For the second time in less than a year, the Pittsburgh Railways sought a fare increase -- to 12 cents cash; the Bell Telephone Company requested a 25.5 per cent increase for private phones.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 22, 1948%0a%3c City Council authorized City Solicitor Anne X. Alpern to wage a fight against the "highly unjust advance" asked for trolleys.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 23, 1948%0a%3c The United States Public Health Service, in a 100,000-word survey report, charged that the city was deficient in its health department and recommended $1,000,000 worth of improvements.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 24, 1948%0a%3c Captain Thomas J. Hamilton, twice football coach of the United States Naval Academy at Annapolis, was named athletic director of the University of Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 1, 1948%0a%3c Edgar J. Kaufmann, president of the Civic Light Opera Association, announced plans for construction of a $1,000,000 amphitheater with a retractable roof.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 7, 1948%0a%3c The H. J. Heinz Company disclosed plans for a $15,000,000 expansion program at its North Side plant, including construction of four new buildings.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 13, 1948%0a%3c Carnegie Tech announced a $4,000,000 building and renovation program in a move to relieve overcrowding.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 27, 1948%0a%3c Thomas J. Fitzpatrick, head of the left-wing forces in Local 601, United Electrical Workers, was defeated in his bid for re-election as president. The "Rank and File" forces, headed by Phil Counahan, assumed control of the union after a long and bitter fight.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 28, 1948%0a%3c The job of building the nations first atomic-powered engine -- for use in propelling a navy ship -- was assigned by the Atomic Energy Commission to the Westinghouse Electric Corporation, which immediately made preparation to employ some 600 persons in the district for the project.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 2, 1949%0a%3c A report by the Pittsburgh Industrial Development Council of the Chamber of Commerce showed that 50 new industries were established in the Pittsburgh area in 1948.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 4, 1949%0a%3c Jones and Laughlin Steel prepared to launch a $210,000,000 postwar expansion program, including a new six-furnace open-hearth shop at the South Side works.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 4, 1949%0a%3c A report from the Building Owners and Managers Association showed the rate of occupancy in 40 Pittsburgh office buildings was 99.8 per cent.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 11, 1949%0a%3c Pittsburghs first television station -- DuMonts WDTV, Channel 3 -- went on the air with a program originating on the stage of Syria Mosque.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 2, 1949%0a%3c The Aluminum Company of America announced plans for the nations first all-aluminum office skyscraper.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 13, 1949%0a%3c The State purchased from the Pennsylvania Railroad 1 3 acres for the projected Point Park.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April, 1949%0a%3c The largest project in a flood -- control network to protect Pittsburgh -- the $44,000,000 Conemaugh Dam, near Saltsburg -- went into construction.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 2, 1949%0a%3c A minor riot had to be quelled by police when a crowd outside Carnegie Music Hall, North Side, closed in on 250 Communists after a rally.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 11, 1949%0a%3c More than 100,000 items went on sale at auction at the Hotel Henry preparatory to its demolition to clear the site for the new United States Steel-Mellon building.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 13, 1949%0a%3c A grant of $225,000 for revival of the International Exhibit of Contemporary Painting at Carnegie Institute was provided by the A. W. Mellon Educational and Charitable Trust.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 23, 1949%0a%3c The Mellon family gave $4,000,000 to the city for acquisition of a midtown site and establishment of a park over a 1000-car, block-square underground parking garage.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 17, 1949%0a%3c Harry W. Fowler, 58-year-old chairman of the County Planning Commission, became the first North Sider to be named to the board of county commissioners.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 19, 1949%0a%3c Crucible Steel opened a new $18,000,000 sheet and strip mill at its Midland works.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 21, 1949%0a%3c More than 200,000 persons lined the banks of the Monongahela River to watch Carnegie-Illinoiss Homestead defeat Jones and Laughlins William Larimer Jones by inches in a modern-day race of stern-wheelers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 28, 1949%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Public Parking Authority announced a program to build four off-street parking garages Downtown to alleviate the growing traffic problem.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 6, 1949%0a%3c Carnegie Institute of Technology opened a nuclear research center at nearby Saxonburg.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 9, 1949%0a%3c Dr. J. C. Warner, chemistry department head and wartime atomic scientist, was named to succeed Dr. Robert E. Doherty on the latters retirement July 1, 1950, as president of Carnegie Tech.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 18, 1949%0a%3c The United Engineering and Foundry, the Mesta Machine Company, and Westinghouse received major portions of a $149,360,000 contract for a French steel mill scheduled for construction under the European Recovery Administration program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 28, 1949%0a%3c On request of the city, the State Supreme Court postponed trolley rate increases indefinitely.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 13, 1949%0a%3c The Urban Redevelopment Authority announced the first public-private project of its kind in the nation-a plan to clear 30 South Side blocks of substandard housing and small business for Jones and Laughlins $42,000,000 South Side expansion, improve surrounding streets, and eliminate three railroad grade crossings.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 5, 1949%0a%3c President Truman addressed an estimated crowd of 200,000 at the County Fair; later, 15,000 AFL members marched through Downtown in the citys first Labor Day parade in eight years.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 13, 1949%0a%3c Following a bitter campaign, Mayor Lawrence won the nomination for re-election; his primary election opponent was AFL-backed Councilman Edward J. Leonard.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 20, 1949%0a%3c The Equitable Life Assurance Society approved plans to convert 23 acres in lower Triangle into a modern, landscaped business area, the first project consisting of three 20-story office buildings.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 22, 1949%0a%3c The Mellon Educational and Charitable Trust Fund gave $13,600,000 to the University of Pittsburgh to build and operate a Graduate School of Public Health.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 2, 1949%0a%3c Because of alleged Communist leanings, the United Electrical Workers Union was expelled from the CIO in a convention at Cleveland; United Electrical locals in the Pittsburgh area, under right-wing control, withdrew from the parent union and prepared to charter a CIO electrical union.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 8, 1949%0a%3c Mayor Lawrence was given a majority of 56,000 votes, the largest ever accorded a Mayoralty candidate of Pittsburgh, in his victory over Timothy F. (Tice) Ryan for reelection to his second term.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 11, 1949%0a%3c A 42-day strike, which halted production in steel mills of the district and nation, was ended when United States Steel signed a contract with the CIO-United Steel Workers for a company-financed pension plan.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 11, 1949%0a%3c The city had its largest Armistice Day parade in 31 years, with 20,000 veterans of three wars participating.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 16, 1949%0a%3c The Pennsylvania Railroad raised district commuter fares 22 per cent.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 20, 1949%0a%3c After an eight-month trial, the Post-Gazette printed the final edition of its Sunday paper and returned to a six-day operation; copyrights and features were sold to the Sunday Sun-Telegraph.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 23, 1949%0a%3c The 12-cent trolley and 15-cent bus fare became effective; State Supreme Court refused the citys plea for a further suspension of higher rates.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 5, 1949%0a%3c Mayor Lawrence again submitted to Council a record-high budget, proposing appropriation of $34,400,000 for 1950.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 11, 1949%0a%3c Edward T. Leech, 57, editor of the Pittsburgh Press for 18 years, died at Mercy Hospital.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 15, 1949%0a%3c United States Steel announced a price increase averaging $4 a ton.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 21, 1949%0a%3c Charles R. Cox resigned as president of Carnegie-Illinois Steel and was succeeded by Clifford Hood.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1950%0a%3c Population: 676,806. Pittsburgh is listed as the 12th largest city in America.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 4, 1950%0a%3c For the third time in two years, the Pittsburgh Railways Company announced rate increases -- to 15 cents on trolleys and 20 cents on buses.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 11, 1950%0a%3c Lawsuits brought by property owners in the Lower Triangle were dismissed by State Supreme Court and the way was clear for construction of the 23-acre Gateway Center.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 25, 1950%0a%3c January heat records were shattered when the temperature went to 76.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 10, 1950%0a%3c Detailed plans were disclosed for construction of the Penn-Lincoln Parkway West with a large interchange in Carnegie.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 14, 1950%0a%3c Fifty million dollars worth of contracts were signed in the Mayors office for the start of Gateway Center. At the same time the Urban Redevelopment Authority announced purchase of the Jones and Laughlin building, on Ross Street, for use as civic headquarters. The city also announced purchase of the Peoples Gas building for $1,116,000 for demolition in the Mellon Square Park project.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 22, 1950%0a%3c In testimony before the House committee, Matt Cvetic placed the number of Communist party members in Western Pennsylvania at 550, listed a number of Pittsburgh organizations as Communist "fronts," and exposed the names of many Pittsburghers alleged to be connected with the Communist party.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 27, 1950%0a%3c The Central Christian Church in Bellefield was destroyed by fire; the loss was estimated at $175,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 3, 1950%0a%3c A power-conserving "dimout" ended in the Pittsburgh district as the United Mine Workers and coal-mine operators agreed on a wage increase to settle a nationwide strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 21, 1950%0a%3c City Council passed six ordinances banning billboards along the route of the Penn-Lincoln Parkway, except for a portion west of Bates Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 30, 1950%0a%3c The Nixon Theater-47 years and 48 seasons old-closed its doors with a performance of Mae Wests Diamond Lil before an audience of 2256.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 2, 1950%0a%3c Some 150,000 persons were without transportation after 130 drivers of the Harmony Short Line, serving the Allegheny Valley, went on strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 15, 1950%0a%3c Governor Duff gave the signal that set in motion an 1800-pound demolition ball that began wrecking a 103-year-old building at 110 Penn Avenue, first of many destined for destruction in the 36-acre Point Park area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 17, 1950%0a%3c Five additional bus lines were idled by a strike of 750 drivers, depriving 450,000 district residents of transportation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 18, 1950%0a%3c Mayor Lawrence and Ben Moreell, president of Jones and Laughlin, jointly broke ground for the start of Jones and Laughlins $60,000,000 open-hearth plant at its South Side works.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 31, 1950%0a%3c Allegheny Countys smoke-control ordinance, covering 128 municipalities, became partially effective.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 9, 1950%0a%3c A strike of 3250 dairy drivers shut off milk supplies to seven counties of Western Pennsylvania.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 29, 1950%0a%3c Members of Local 205, AFL Teamsters, agreed to wage terms, ending a 21-day milk strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 1, 1950%0a%3c Western Pennsylvanias famed 28th Division was called into active service to strengthen United States ground forces in the Korean war.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 11, 1950%0a%3c State Supreme Court overrode arguments of the city of Pittsburgh for a postponement and permitted 15-cent trolley and 20-cent bus fares to take effect.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 29, 1950%0a%3c A 118-day strike of Harmony Bus Line drivers ended.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 31, 1950%0a%3c Steve Nelson, Western Pennsylvania Communist party leader, was arrested with two other party leaders on bench warrants sworn out by Judge Michael A. Musmanno and charged with sedition. Later in the day Judge Musmanno personally led a raid on Communist headquarters in the Bakewell Building.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 4, 1950%0a%3c The Senator motion-picture house on Liberty Avenue became the new Nixon Theater with the opening of Oklahoma.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 10, 1950%0a%3c More than 130,000 Catholic men filled Forbes Field for a Holy Name rally in one of the citys largest religious demonstrations in history.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 13, 1950%0a%3c A 119-day Brentwood Motor Coach strike ended.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 19, 1950%0a%3c Oriole Motor Coach drivers ended their 125-day strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 29, 1950%0a%3c At a height of 550 feet, the U.S. Steel-Mellon Building is topped out in a flag-raising ceremony. Thirty-five feet shorter than the Gulf Building, it was the city's second-tallest skyscraper. (The building later became known as Three Mellon Center and is now officially called 525 William Penn Place.)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 1, 1950%0a%3c Two hundred mailing-room employees failed to report for work because of a contract dispute, forcing the Sun-Telegraph, Press, and Post-Gazette to suspend publication and idle 2500 other employees.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 15, 1950%0a%3c Under leadership of the Pittsburgh local of the American Newspaper Guild, members of 10 unions idled by the newspaper strike published the Daily Reporter after two weeks of a virtual news and advertising blackout.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 15, 1950%0a%3c Ground was broken for the 16-story nurses residence, first major project to be started in the building program for the Pitt Medical Center.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 15, 1950%0a%3c Excavation started for construction of three stainless steel office buildings in Gateway Center and a large underground parking area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 19, 1950%0a%3c General Dwight D. Eisenhower, president of Columbia University, told a Carnegie Institute Founders Day audience at Carnegie Music Hall that "there is no such thing as a preventive war." The occasion marked the opening of the Institutes 38th International Art Exhibit, its first in eleven years.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 6, 1950%0a%3c Branch Rickey, builder of the St. Louis Cardinals and Brooklyn Dodgers, was named general manager of the Pittsburgh Pirates.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 6, 1950%0a%3c AFL Teamster delivery truck drivers began a strike against Kaufmanns, Gimbel's, and Hornes.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 8, 1950%0a%3c CIO telephone workers of the district joined a nationwide strike, interrupting telephone service here.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 18, 1950%0a%3c After posing for years as a Communist Party member, Matt Cvetic, 41-year-old executive secretary of the American Slav Congress of Pittsburgh, appeared before the House Un-American Activities Investigating Committee in Washington and revealed himself to be an FBI undercover agent.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 18, 1950%0a%3c The 47-day-old newspaper strike ended; 3000 employees returned to their jobs.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 24, 1950%0a%3c Auto, bus, and trolley traffic was brought to a standstill by a 30.5-inch snowfall -- heaviest in the citys history. Snowbanks on streets were piled as high as automobile tops.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 27, 1950%0a%3c The city and its environs were snowbound. Newspapers failed to publish; most stores were closed; schools were closed; deaths resulting from the storm totaled 15.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 29, 1950%0a%3c Downtown stores reopened with National Guardsmen on hand to prevent a traffic impasse. Trolleys and buses resumed operation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 30, 1950%0a%3c City tow trucks began removing some 5000 snowbound autos from trolley routes; snow-removal machines were also in action.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 1, 1950%0a%3c National Guard road-blocks were removed and the blocks were removed and the Triangle was opened to all traffic.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 18, 1950%0a%3c More than 8000 members of 19 other AFL unions returned to work after AFL delivery drivers ended a 29-day strike against the three major department stores-Kaufmanns, Gimbel's, and Hornes.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 22, 1950%0a%3c Bishop Hugh C. Boyle, 77-year-old spiritual leader of 800,000 Roman Catholics in the Pittsburgh diocese, died in Mercy Hospital; he was immediately succeeded by Coadjutor Bishop John F. Dearden.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 2, 1951%0a%3c The State Supreme Court sustained the citys controversial "A-B-C" restaurant sanitation code, and the Department of Public Health prepared to enforce it.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 18, 1951%0a%3c Another trolley fare increase-this one raising the price of tokens one and three-quarters cents- became effective.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 27, 1951%0a%3c William Alvah Stewart, a city councilman, was appointed a federal judge by President Truman.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 6, 1951%0a%3c Koppers Kobuta rubber plant was knocked out of defense production for three months by a $500,000 fire.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 26, 1951%0a%3c In a message to City Council, Mayor Lawrence outlined plans for Pittsburghs third major redevelopment program-the clearance of 100 acres of slums in the Hill District and construction of a public arena, 30 acres of housing, and other improvements.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 1, 1951%0a%3c Mayor Lawrence invited representatives of school districts and colleges and universities to meet with him to discuss organization of an educational television station for Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 16, 1951%0a%3c Design of a giant lighted fountain, shooting a brilliant column of water 100 feet into the air, was approved by the Point Park committee as an appropriate decoration for the tip of Point Park.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 19, 1951%0a%3c I. W. Wilson, senior vice-president, was elected president of the Aluminum Company of America.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 5, 1951%0a%3c Mrs. Edith Oliver Rea, who pioneered in the field of Veterans Rehabilitation (World War I) and who instituted the Grey Ladies service of the Red Cross, died in Boston, Massachusetts.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 25, 1951%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Railways Company asked the Public Utilities Commission for permission to abandon its 79-year-old Mount Oliver Incline.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June, 1951%0a%3c Washington Boulevard was flooded and one woman, trapped in her car, was drowned.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 27, 1951%0a%3c A special grand jury recommended indictment of Mayor Lawrence, City Controller Edward R. Frey, and nine others as the result of an investigation into city light and coal contracts.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 18, 1951%0a%3c Joe Walcott, 37, knocked out Ezzard Charles in the seventh round in a heavyweight championship fight at Forbes Field before 28,272 persons -- a record fight turnout for Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 25, 1951%0a%3c In the primary election, Judge Michael A. Musmanno upset the Democratic leadership and won a 21-year term on the bench of Pennsylvania State Supreme Court.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 10, 1951%0a%3c In connection with the Penn-Lincoln Parkway project, the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad agreed to get its passenger station out of the way and build a new one at the foot of Grant Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 10, 1951%0a%3c Pittsburgh Railways asked that fares be raised to 17 cents on trolleys and 23 cents on buses.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 17, 1951%0a%3c Steve Nelson, already on trial on sedition charges, was arrested by the FBI with five other district Communist leaders in the latest of a nationwide series of raids.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 31, 1951%0a%3c After a 35-week trial, Communists Andrew Onda and James Dolsen were found guilty by a Criminal Court jury of advocating overthrow of the government by force and violence.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 9, 1951%0a%3c In a radio and television speech Mayor Lawrence denounced the management of the Pittsburgh Railways Company and appealed to the public to join the city in fighting fare increases.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 20, 1951%0a%3c Judge Timothy F. (Tice) Ryan, 1949 Republican Mayoralty candidate, died at 65 at his East End home.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 5, 1951%0a%3c Mayor Lawrence was cleared by a grand jury, but seven other officials were indicted in connection with alleged discrepancies in contracts for a new city lighting system.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 11, 1951%0a%3c Kaufmanns department store announced purchase of the 19-story Frick Annex building for the start of a multi-million-dollar enlargement program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 24, 1951%0a%3c A district epidemic of bank frauds spread to Pittsburgh; three officials of the Federal Credit Union of Kaufmanns were arrested on charges of embezzling $338,901.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 30, 1951%0a%3c Defense Mobilizer Charles E. Wilson tapped the first heat, putting into operation the new $70,000,000 open-hearth shop at the South Side plant of Jones and Laughlin Steel Corporation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November, 1951%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Housing Authority initiated construction of the 1089-unit St. Clair Village housing project on the South Side.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 6, 1951%0a%3c James F. Malone, Republican leader, was elected district attorney over Judge Francis J. OConnor; Democratic County Commissioners Kane and Fowler were reelected; State Senator John M. Walker of Oakmont was named minority commissioner.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 26, 1951%0a%3c The 67-mile $77,500,000 western extension of the Pennsylvania Turnpike was dedicated at the Ohio border with Governor Frank J. Lausche, of Ohio, promising that his state would extend the expressway.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 29, 1951%0a%3c The first mass transit study made under sponsorship of the Allegheny Conference on Community Development urged reconsideration of a Triangle subway estimated to cost $65,000,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 22, 1951%0a%3c City Council, at Mayor Lawrences request, passed another record-high budget, totaling $41,881,900 for 1952.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 19, 1952%0a%3c Five years after its opening, the Union Bus Terminal, Downtown, closed its doors because of bankruptcy, leaving five bus lines "homeless."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 25, 1952%0a%3c William Steinberg, director of the Buffalo Philharmonic Orchestra, was appointed conductor of the Pittsburgh Symphony; he became the orchestras first permanent director since the departure of Fritz Reiner in 1948.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 29, 1952%0a%3c C. L. Austin, a former banker, was elected president of Jones and Laughlin; Ben Moreell relinquished that post but continued as chairman of the board.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 31, 1952%0a%3c Following a 19-day trial, a Criminal Court jury found Steve Nelson guilty of sedition.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 6, 1952%0a%3c Edward Specter, manager of the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra, resigned.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 24, 1952%0a%3c The Bigelow, first apartment house to be built in downtown Pittsburgh, was opened to tenants.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 1, 1952%0a%3c The Carlton House, the citys first new hotel in 25 years, received its first guests.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 1, 1952%0a%3c At midnight 100 men of the United States Steel Corporation sat around a horseshoe table in the Carnegie Building, then emptied of all tenants, and drank a toast to what had been "steel headquarters" for 57 years. At 8 AM, demolition crews began the long and arduous task of disassembling this structure, beam by beam, to clear the site for a Kaufmanns annex.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 3, 1952%0a%3c Allegheny County reduced taxes to a 22-year low while adopting a $32,400,000 budget, highest in its history.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 8, 1952%0a%3c President Truman ordered steel mills seized, and the United Steel Workers called off a scheduled strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 21, 1952%0a%3c A precedent was established when Pittsburgh industry and business, through 65 of its leaders, pledged financial support to the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra; they approved a novel plan under which companies were to be designated sponsors with contributions of $10,000 annually.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 23, 1952%0a%3c Clifford Ball, 61-year-old aviation promoter for more than 35 years and founder of Pennsylvania (Capital) Airlines, was named director of the new Greater Pittsburgh Airport.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 29, 1952%0a%3c President Truman s seizure of the steel industry was declared illegal by Federal Court and district steel workers joined 650,000 throughout the nation in a walkout that paralyzed the industry.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 31, 1952%0a%3c The new Greater Pittsburgh Airport, completed at a cost of $33,000,000, was dedicated, and more than 100,000 persons went to Moon Township over the holiday weekend to inspect the 1600-acre air terminal.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 2, 1952%0a%3c Commercial airlines began flying a total of 228 flights daily into and out of the new airport.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 25, 1952%0a%3c Pittsburgh Railways asked the Public Utilities Commission for permission to institute a 20-cent trolley and 25-cent bus fare-the sixth rate increase in four years and the third in less than 20 months.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 30, 1952%0a%3c Judge Henry Ellenbogan ruled out the Public Parking Authoritys plan for the sale of gas, oil, and services in its parking garages.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 24, 1952%0a%3c At the White House, President Truman, flanked by Philip Murray and Benjamin F. Fairless, announced settlement of the 53-day steel strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 8, 1952%0a%3c Pittsburghs Old City Hall, built in 1872 at a cost of $600,000, was sold for nearly $2,500,000 to a real estate group planning to demolish it for commercial development.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 11, 1952%0a%3c Police Superintendent Harvey J. Scott, the citys police chief for 13 years, was fired by Safety Director George E. A. Fairley for misconduct.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 15, 1952%0a%3c The Point Park Commission approved detailed plans for landscaping and developing Point Park. Wallace Richards, Parking Authority chairman, suggested a 1000-car parking garage be built on the park fringe area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 22, 1952%0a%3c Cornelius Decatur Scully, who had served nine consecutive years as Mayor, died at the age of 73 in Winchester, Virginia.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 6, 1952%0a%3c William D. Mansfield, former state senator, former county commissioner, editor of the McKeesport Daily News, and one of McKeesports best-known citizens, died at 74 in McKeesport Hospital.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 8, 1952%0a%3c Senator Richard M. Nixon, Republican candidate for vice-president, charged in a speech to 3900 persons at Syria Mosque that the Communist party was aiding the Democrats.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 22, 1952%0a%3c President Truman, in an address to an overflow crowd at Syria Mosque, accused General Eisenhower of following a "straight isolationist line."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 27, 1952%0a%3c After being welcomed by huge crowds, General Eisenhower, in an address at Hunt Armory, promised that the first objective of a Republican administration in Washington would be an "honorable" peace in Korea.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 29, 1952%0a%3c City Council approved an ordinance, recommended by Mayor Lawrence, to create a municipal authority to purchase and reconstruct the citys deteriorated water-supply system at a cost of $27,000,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 29, 1952%0a%3c Pittsburghs first public parking garage, a 776-car facility built at a cost of $2,100,000 at Sixth Avenue and Bigelow Boulevard, was officially opened by Mayor Lawrence and Authority Chairman Wallace B. Richards.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 30, 1952%0a%3c Governor Adlai Stevenson, of Illinois, in a final bid for votes, declared to a crowd of 25,000 at Hunt Armory that General Eisenhower was a captive candidate of the Republican "Old Guard," the "depression party."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 4, 1952%0a%3c In losing the presidential election to General Eisenhower, Governor Stevenson carried Allegheny County by 13,820 votes.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 6, 1952%0a%3c Special demolition crews began the delicate task of taking apart H. J. Heinzs "Little House Where We Began" to permit expansion of the North Side plant. The house was later reassembled in its original state at Fords Greenfield Village in Dearborn, Michigan.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 8, 1952%0a%3c At its 75th anniversary celebration, Duquesne University announced a $13,300,000 program to clear blight and create a modern, 25-acre Bluff campus. Ground was broken earlier in the day for construction of a womens dormitory, the first of eight new buildings.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 9, 1952%0a%3c Philip Murray, 66-year-old president of both the CIO and the United Steel Workers, died unexpectedly in his room at the Mark Hopkins Hotel in San Francisco after addressing 350 delegates at the United Steel Workers western regional conference.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 14, 1952%0a%3c A storm of protest from Downtown merchants prompted the city to postpone enforcement of a rigid curb-parking restriction adopted for Downtown streets.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 20, 1952%0a%3c Jones and Laughlin, the Urban Redevelopment Authority, and city officials signed contracts for their second joint industrial redevelopment project-the conversion of 30 acres of blighted land in Hazelwood into a productive plant.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 20, 1952%0a%3c The citys second parking garage, a six-level, 815-car structure on Fourth Avenue, built at a cost of $1,500,000, was opened to the motoring public.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 24, 1952%0a%3c In the first event of its kind ever staged, Pittsburghs First International Contemporary Music Festival, a week-long series of concerts featuring works of contemporary composers, opened at Carnegie Music Hall.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 3, 1952%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra played the first of a series of experimental "industrial" concerts for 1600 persons in Scott High School auditorium in North Braddock. It was the first time that any major orchestra attempted to take its music directly to an industrial community.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 5, 1952%0a%3c Mayor Lawrence signed into law the citys first fair employment practices code, prohibiting job discrimination against minority groups; Pittsburgh thus became the 23rd city in the nation with FEPC.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 23, 1952%0a%3c Two ultra-high frequency television stations were authorized for Pittsburgh by the Federal Communications Commission; they were channels 16 and 47.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 30, 1952%0a%3c Chancellor Rufus H. Fitzgerald, of the University of Pittsburgh, announced that 22 Pittsburgh business and industrial firms had subscribed a total of $4,836,000 for construction of a $15,000,000 building for the schools of the health professions.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 30, 1952%0a%3c The ten-month-old Carlton House was sold to a New York syndicate for $7,400,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 14, 1953%0a%3c Mayor Lawrence announced that articles of incorporation were ready to be filed for formation of Pittsburghs "Metropolitan Educational Television Station, Inc.," WQED.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 15, 1953%0a%3c Grading and seeding started at the Point Park in time for greenness in the spring.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 22, 1953%0a%3c Mayor Lawrence announced his candidacy for election to a third term in order to see through "to its climax of achievement" Pittsburghs rebuilding program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 26, 1953%0a%3c Plans were announced for construction of a 2000-unit, $24,500,000 low-rent housing project in City View-Summer Hill section of the North Side. Residents of the area immediately announced plans to fight it.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 2, 1953%0a%3c A 60-day trial of rigid no-parking rules Downtown went into effect; only 17 autos were towed away by police to the city auto pound.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 8, 1953%0a%3c After obtaining Edgar J. Kaufmanns approval of the use of a $1,000,000 grant originally pledged to the Civic Light Opera, Mayor Lawrence announced plans to proceed with construction of a $7,000,000 sports-theater arena, with a retractable roof, as the key project in the Lower Hill District redevelopment area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 10, 1953%0a%3c David J. McDonald, secretary-treasurer of the United Steel Workers since its inception in 1937 and once a prospect for Hollywood filmland, was elected, without opposition, second president of the 1,100,000 union.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 4, 1953%0a%3c The Allegheny Conference on Community Development revealed plans for a toll tunnel under Mount Washington as the most feasible way to finance that link in the Penn-Lincoln Parkway.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 12, 1953%0a%3c A $30,000,000 public-works program for new bridges, highways, and other improvements was announced by the county commissioners.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 26, 1953%0a%3c Dr. Jonas E. Salk, 38-year-old University of Pittsburgh researcher and professor, reported success of a new polio vaccine tried on 90 human beings; the vaccine was developed by him and his staff at Pitt.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 20, 1953%0a%3c Carnegie Tech announced a move to raze Carnegie Inn, a campus landmark, and build a modern $700,000 mens dormitory.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 6, 1953%0a%3c Because of Pittsburgh Railways' opposition, the city discarded its plan for making Forbes Street and Fifth Avenue one way in order to relieve traffic congestion expected with temporary closing of the Boulevard of the Allies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 12, 1953%0a%3c The $4,500,000 Nurses Residence for the Medical Center was dedicated and its quarters were opened for 600 student nurses and 46 staff members.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 19, 1953%0a%3c In the primary election, City Solicitor Anne X. Alpern received both the Democratic and Republican nominations to a judgeship.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 4, 1953%0a%3c Pittsburghs most publicized and highest paid baseball player, Ralph Kiner, was traded to the Chicago Cubs.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 5, 1953%0a%3c Many state and local officials participated in a ribbon cutting opening the $18,000,000 Squirrel Hill Tunnel, the most costly single project ever undertaken by the State Highways Department. This placed in service the first eight mile stretch of the $34,000,000 Penn-Lincoln Highway.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 8, 1953%0a%3c The first and most troublesome of many detours resulting from new highway work took the Boulevard of the Allies out of service for some 30,000 motorists using it daily. This marked the start of Pittsburghs most critical period of traffic congestion.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 22, 1953%0a%3c The Allegheny Conference on Community Development released its second citizens mass transit study; it recommended creation of a transit authority to acquire and unify bus and trolley lines in the county.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 5, 1953%0a%3c It was announced that the Wabash Building, a city landmark, was to be demolished to make way for further development in the Gateway Center.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 5, 1953%0a%3c A building in Oakland, gift of the Pittsburgh Plate Glass to the University of Pittsburgh, was provided for the headquarters of educational television in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 25, 1953%0a%3c Following a six-month trial, Steve Nelson, already under a 20-year sentence to the Workhouse, and five other Communist leaders of Pittsburgh were convicted under the Smith Act in Federal Court and sentenced to five years in prison.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 7, 1953%0a%3c John M. Phillips, pioneer industrialist and well-known conservationist, died at the age of 92 at his home at 2336 Brownsville Road, Carrick. He was the father of Pennsylvanias basic game code, used by many other states as a model.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 15, 1953%0a%3c At the start of a week-long dedication, the Aluminum Company of America opened its new 30-story office building for public inspection. On the first night 7500 invited guests toured the skyscraper, the nations first with an all-aluminum exterior.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 18, 1953%0a%3c Two thousand Pittsburghers and state officials traveled to Saltsburg by special train and auto to participate in the dedication of the Conemaugh Dam, $46,200,000 bulwark against floods, the largest and most important dam in a $125,000,000 flood-control system. The speaker, Major General S. D. Sturgis, Jr., chief of army engineers, warned that navigational locks and dams in the Ohio River were in desperate need of rehabilitation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 23, 1953%0a%3c The newly constituted Metropolitan Study Commission of Allegheny County formed 10 committees to begin the job of assembling information on urban expansion under a $50,000 grant provided by Buhl Foundation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 28, 1953%0a%3c Richard K. Mellon, head of the nations greatest banking empire, tacitly endorsed the Democratic leader, Mayor Lawrence, for re-election. He did so in a short speech at ground-breaking ceremonies for the Mellon Square Park and underground garage, site of which was acquired with a $4,000,000 grant from the Mellon family.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 29, 1953%0a%3c Ten thousand campaign volunteers began canvassing homes in the Pittsburgh area in solicitation of 100,000 family subscriptions of $2 each for educational television station WQED; the proceeds were to supplement grants of $350,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 6, 1953%0a%3c Pittsburgh voters overwhelmingly defeated a proposed raise in school taxes following a bitter battle.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 15, 1953%0a%3c The $15,000,000 Penn-Lincoln Parkway West, opening up a fast route between Downtown Pittsburgh and the Greater Pittsburgh Airport and routes west was dedicated by Governor John S. Fine and Senators James H. Duff and Edward Martin. All, as governors, were instrumental in various phases of its construction. The dedication ceremony was held at the interchange in Senator Duffs home town Carnegie.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 23, 1953%0a%3c The Allegheny Foundation, a new organization to aid charitable, scientific, literary, and other public activities, was chartered by the Mellon family.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 28, 1953%0a%3c The Public Auditorium Authority was created by Mayor Lawrence and the county commissioners for the purpose of building and operating an all-purpose civic arena in the Hill District. Brehon B. Somervell, president of Koppers Company, was chosen first chairman.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 3, 1953%0a%3c David L. Lawrence defeated Leonard P. Kane by 54,000 votes and became the first Mayor in the history of Pittsburgh to be elected to a third consecutive term. The Democrats swept the city and county.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 23, 1953%0a%3c A brief noon-time ceremony was held at Gateway Center to inscribe into history "November 23, 1753," as the date on which George Washington first envisioned the Point as a natural site. Pittsburgh thus memorialized its distinction of being "the only city in the United States to have had its location chosen by the first president."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 27, 1953%0a%3c Five hundred delivery truck drivers of Local 249, AFL Teamsters, began a strike against the citys major department stores. The stores remained open; the Joseph Horne Companys warehouse was stoned in the first incidence of violence.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 2, 1953%0a%3c Edgar J. Kaufmann, charter financial backer of Lower Hill District civic arena project, promised to contribute $500,000, in addition to $1,000,000 already pledged, if needed on completion of fund-raising efforts.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 2, 1953%0a%3c For the first time in seven months, the Boulevard of the Allies was open to traffic on a restricted basis.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 4, 1953%0a%3c Mayor Lawrence presented to City Council what he termed the "most difficult" budget in the eight years of his administration; he also indicated reluctant approval of a wage tax as a means of raising money.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 27, 1953%0a%3c Delayed 17 months by court orders resulting from actions started by City Solicitor Anne X. Alpern, trolley and bus rate increases -- to 20 and 25 cents, respectively -- became effective.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 30, 1953%0a%3c Anne X. Alpern (Mrs. Irwin Swiss in private life) was sworn in as a judge of Common Pleas Court. She was the first Democratic woman in Pennsylvania elected to a judgeship.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 31, 1953%0a%3c Mayor Lawrence signed into law another record high budget, with appropriations totaling $47,282,991; it also committed the city to a 1 per cent tax on all, earned incomes within the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 1, 1954%0a%3c Fifty squads of policemen and detectives manned road blocks in the city to halt violence in the 36-day department store strike; earlier the homes of two store executives were stoned and "paint bombed."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 3, 1954%0a%3c The Pennsylvania Railroad unveiled a $3,611,400 plan for a new ramp and platform for trains to and from the west as part of its $27,000,000 station modernization program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 4, 1954%0a%3c After Mayor Lawrence was sworn in for his third term, City Council received from him a recommendation for a precedent-shattering wage tax ordinance estimated to yield the city $6,300,000 in 1954.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 18, 1954%0a%3c In one of the largest grants of its kind ever made, the Mellon family, represented by three foundations, gave $15,000,000 to the University of Pittsburgh for medical education. The money was designated chiefly for development of Pitts first full-time medical school teaching staff.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 21, 1954%0a%3c Powered by the worlds first atomic engine, built by the Westinghouse Electric Corporation, the submarine USS Nautilus, christened by Mrs. Dwight D. Eisenhower, was launched at Groton, Connecticut.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 25, 1954%0a%3c The citys first wage tax was adopted with March 1 as the effective date. Councilman John F. Counahan was Councils only dissenter in the vote.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 25, 1954%0a%3c State Supreme Court dismissed the Common Pleas Court conviction and 20-year sentence of Communist Steve Nelson on grounds that the case legally belonged in Federal Court under the Smith Act.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 24, 1954%0a%3c The attention of parents around the world was on Arsenal Elementary school in Lawrenceville, where Dr. Jonas E. Salk began his polio vaccine tests on a large-scale basis. In the gymnasium of that school 137 youngsters, first of 5000 Pittsburgh school volunteers, were given injections of the new serum.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 25, 1954%0a%3c The Chamber of Commerce and Allegheny Conference on Community Development undertook a joint campaign to form an "industrial development corporation" to bolster Pittsburghs economy by attracting new light industry.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 1, 1954%0a%3c The wage tax of one cent on each dollar of earned income went into effect in Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 9, 1954%0a%3c Frederick Bigger, Pittsburghs "dean of planners," resigned after 31 years of membership on the City Planning Commission, which he served for 20 years as chairman. He was co-organizer of Regional Planning Association and was noted nationally as chief planner in the New Deals famed model-town projects of "Greenbelt," Maryland, "Greenhills," Ohio, and "Greendale," Wisconsin.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 12, 1954%0a%3c The Regional Planning Association issued its first report on a suburban community under an expanded new policy. The report recommended that a planned industrial district, first in the Pittsburgh area be developed in a blighted McKeesport district at the Monongahela -Youghiogheny river junction.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 24, 1954%0a%3c Teamster delivery truck drivers ended their 113-day strike against five furniture stores -- Hahns, Spear and Company, Rubens, Obringers, and May-Stern.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April, 1954%0a%3c The University of Pittsburgh began demolishing 32 structures on a 10-acre Oakland site preparatory to erecting its graduate school of public health.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April, 1954%0a%3c Dr. M. Graham Netting, a member of the staff for 32 years, was named director of Carnegie Museum to succeed Wallace Richards after the latter was stricken ill.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 1, 1954%0a%3c Station WQED, the worlds first community-sponsored educational noncommercial television station, went on the air.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 12, 1954%0a%3c The Atomic Energy Commission assigned to the Westinghouse Electric Corporation and Duquesne Light Company the job of building the first atomic electric power plant in the world. It also announced the site as Shippingport, a once important river port on the Ohio River 25 miles north of Pittsburgh. Operation of the plant also was assigned to Duquesne Light.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 28, 1954%0a%3c A "schematic plan" for rebuilding 1286 deteriorating acres of North Side property was proposed by the Regional Planning Association, in a dinner at the H. J. Heinz plant, as the fourth major redevelopment project in the city. It included recommendations for 3000 new parking spaces, an "Allegheny Center" shopping district, new housing, additional recreation, planned neighborhood and industrial districts, all compatible with the proposed Ohio River Boulevard high-speed extension through the North Side.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 2, 1954%0a%3c Four new buildings were dedicated on the campus of the Pennsylvania College for Women.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 9, 1954%0a%3c Dozens of traffic tie-ups occurred after bus and trolley were cut off by a strike of 2700 operators.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 11, 1954%0a%3c The Chamber of Commerce recommended the Allegheny Valley as the most practical route for the proposed Pittsburgh-to-Erie extension of the Pennsylvania Turnpike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 23, 1954%0a%3c The garages of the Public Parking Authority were ruled tax-exempt by the State Supreme Court; the way was thus opened for construction of more garages. The same ruling held as that for taxable garage space rented to private interests for commercial purposes.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 28, 1954%0a%3c District Attorney James Malone warned against "paint bombings" after eight homes were hit by a wave of vandalism in the sixth month of the department store strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 14, 1954%0a%3c Trolleys and buses resumed normal operation with the settlement of the 34-day strike, longest and costliest in the history of Pittsburgh Railways Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 23, 1954%0a%3c The Board of Education approved a $5,000,000 bond issue for a building and renovation program and elected attorney J. Garfield Houston as its new president.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 28, 1954%0a%3c Mrs. Alan M. Scaife, wife of the president of the board of trustees of the University of Pittsburgh, turned the first spade of earth to start excavation for the $15,000,000 building to house the schools of medicine, dentistry, pharmacy, and nursing.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 29, 1954%0a%3c United States Steel and the United Steel Workers union signed a contract for a five-cent hourly wage increase, forestalling a scheduled strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 1, 1954%0a%3c Ground was broken on Fifth Avenue site, facing the Cathedral of Learning, for Pitts new $2,500,000 center of natural sciences. It was named in memory of George Hubbard Clapp, the noted scientist, co-founder of the Aluminum Company of America, and president of the University of Pittsburgh board of trustees for 42 years until his death in 1949.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 11, 1954%0a%3c Contracts were awarded for the basic design of the $25,000,000 Fort Pitt Tunnel through Mount Washington.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 28, 1954%0a%3c The State General Authority completed negotiations with Equitable Life Assurance Society for purchase of a Gateway Center site, at a price of $1,041,143, for construction of a new $8,000,000 state office building to serve as capital of Western Pennsylvania.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 28, 1954%0a%3c Allegheny General Hospital broke ground for a two-story building to house a "cobalt bomb," second such cancer-treatment unit to be established in the city. The first was in process of construction at Mercy Hospital.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 29, 1954%0a%3c The State Department of Commerce issued a report showing 46 new industries or expansions in 1954 in the Pittsburgh district; investments totaled $125,000,000, and 13,448 persons were added to payrolls.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 10, 1954%0a%3c Dr. Bryn J. Hovde, executive director of the Pittsburgh Housing Association and a nationally known expert on housing, died at the age of 58 after he was stricken on a Downtown streetcar.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 27, 1954%0a%3c The Board of Education announced plans to construct four new schools in the biggest building program in many years.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 2, 1954%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Parking Authority announced it was ready to proceed with construction of 1388 additional off-street spaces in two parking garages, to be built at a total cost of $6,000,000 and operated by Kaufmanns store primarily for the shopping convenience of customers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 6, 1954%0a%3c In Denver, 1600 miles away, President Eisenhower waved an "atomic wand" over an electronic cabinet. He thus relayed the impulse that sent into motion huge steam shovels at the Shippingport site of the worlds first atomic power plant. Some 1 500 business, industrial, and scientific leaders of the Pittsburgh area attended the Labor Day ground-breaking ceremony starting construction of the $45,000,000 installation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 7, 1954%0a%3c City Council passed an ordinance to permit erection of a $3,500,000 eight - story apartment building on the Shady Avenue site of the historical Kenmawr Hotel, a 90-year-old landmark. The ordinance upset height building regulations for this East End area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 11, 1954%0a%3c A strike against the Westinghouse Electric Corporation was averted at the zero hour with the signing of a two-year contract.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 12, 1954%0a%3c Vice-Admiral Joel T. Boone, chief medical officer for the Veterans Administration, dedicated the new 11-story, 750-bed VA general medical and surgical hospital, situated above Oakland.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 17, 1954%0a%3c United States Steel announced a $10,000,000 expansion program for its Homestead Works.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 21, 1954%0a%3c The Peoples First National Bank and Trust Company announced plans to construct a central headquarters building in the Gateway Center.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 10, 1954%0a%3c After 16 months of restrictions, the vital Boulevard of the Allies was fully reopened to traffic.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 18, 1954%0a%3c The National Foundation for Infantile Paralysis contracted to buy the Salk polio vaccine for 9,000,000 persons in 1955.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 27, 1954%0a%3c Jones and Laughlin Steel announced a $51,000,000 program for expanding and improving its plants in 1955.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 29, 1954%0a%3c Sidney A. Swensrud, board chairman and chief executive officer of the Gulf Oil Company, became chairman of the Public Auditorium Authority following the resignation of Brehon B. Somervell. The Authority set spring of 1956 as its target date for starting construction of a civic arena in the Lower Hill District redevelopment area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 2, 1954%0a%3c The county gave State Senator George M. Leader, 37-year-old chicken farmer, a plurality of more than 87,000 votes over Lloyd H. Woods for the governorship in a Democratic victory that ended 16 gears of Republican rule in Harrisburg.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 16, 1954%0a%3c The Allegheny County Redevelopment Authority prepared to proceed with a $3,500,000 slum clearance and redevelopment project in McKees Rocks.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 19, 1954%0a%3c The Baltimore and Ohio Railroad announced a decision to abandon plans for a central office building and to construct instead a small new passenger station in connection with its Penn-Lincoln Parkway relocation project.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 22, 1954%0a%3c State Supreme Court dismissed complaints of North Side residents, enabling the Pittsburgh Housing Authority to proceed with plans for construction of a 1000-unit low-rent housing project on Summer Hill.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 26, 1954%0a%3c Teamster delivery drivers signed a contract ending their strike against five Downtown department stores on the eve of its first anniversary; but the union served notice the drivers would not resume deliveries until 11 other store unions ended their strike. It was estimated that the walkout cost the 760 drivers and helpers a total of $5,000,000 in wages.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 3, 1954%0a%3c Westinghouse Electric Corporation announced purchase of Pittsburghs pioneer television station, WDTV, from DuMont Laboratories, Inc., for $9,750,000, highest amount ever paid for a television station.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 3, 1954%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Board of Public Education adopted an "austerity" budget of $23,882,326 for 1955, rejecting teachers requests for pay raises but retaining kindergartens for another year.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 5, 1954%0a%3c The county commissioners made public proposed legislation, drafted by a seven-member citizens committee, for creation of a countywide public transportation authority to acquire and consolidate bus and trolley lines. The legislation required approval of voters in a referendum scheduled for primary election of 1956.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 6, 1954%0a%3c One hundred and eighteen business firms, schools, and hospitals 80 years or older were honored by the Pittsburgh Chamber of Commerce at its 80th anniversary dinner, attended by 900 persons in the William Penn Hotel. The speakers were William Block, publisher of the Post-Gazette, the citys oldest (1786), and Alan M. Scaife, chairman of the board of the Scaife Company, second oldest (1802). Each received a special plaque.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 10, 1954%0a%3c The University of Pittsburgh announced plans to build four additional structures at a total cost of $2,900,000-a 336-parking-space garage, and physicians office building to serve the Medical Center, a student union, and mens dormitory.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 12, 1954%0a%3c Dr. John C. Warner, Carnegie Tech president, was named national president of the American Chemical Society for the year 1956. He was the second Pittsburgher to be so honored. The first was Dr. E. R. Weidlein, director of the Mellon Institute, in 1937.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 15, 1954%0a%3c Equitable Life Assurance Society of New York announced it had decided to construct a parking garage in Gateway Center for at least 600 cars.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 22, 1954%0a%3c Duquesne University announced it was ready to build the third structure in its $13,000,000 campus expansion program -- a hall of law and business, featuring a moot courtroom made possible by a $100,000 grant from the Maurice and Laura Falk Foundation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 24, 1954%0a%3c Mayor Lawrence signed a $48,320,473 budget for 1955, the eighth record high appropriation ordinance in eight consecutive years.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 4, 1955%0a%3c Five employees at the Westinghouse Electric Corporations East Pittsburgh plant were fired as "undesirable" following hearings at Washington by Senator McCarthys investigations subcommittee.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 18, 1955%0a%3c The Allegheny County School Board approved working plans for a $1,300,000 new school construction program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 1, 1955%0a%3c The Board of Public Education supported redevelopment of the Lower Hill area by indicating they would relinquish several vital properties situated in the heart of the district.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 14, 1955%0a%3c General Brehon Somervell, Koppers Company board chairman and president, died at 62.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 22, 1955%0a%3c James J. Thomas, director of District 15, CIO United Steel Workers, and veteran organizer in the steel industry, died.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 1, 1955%0a%3c Pittsburghs new housing code -- an attempt to upgrade the citys residential property -- became effective. Every residential unit was required to have electricity, effective heating facilities, hot and cold running water, kitchen sink, a flush water closet, lavatory basin, and either a bathtub or a shower.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 9, 1955%0a%3c W. F. Munnikhuysen was elected chairman of the board of Koppers Company, and Fred C. Foy was named president and chief executive officer at a special meeting of the hoard of directors.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 10, 1955%0a%3c The Defense Department announced that $15,000,000 would be spent during 1955 for antiaircraft defense of Pittsburgh. Half of the sum was to pay for installation of Nike missiles, the rest for support of the 18th AAA Group.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 13, 1955%0a%3c Henry Kaufmann, 94, pioneer Pittsburgh merchant, one of the four founders of Kaufmanns Department Store, died in New York City.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 17, 1955%0a%3c AFL Teamsters prepared to roll delivery trucks at the five Downtown department stores for the first time in nearly 16 months. Pickets were removed although some differences remained to be negotiated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 15, 1955%0a%3c Edgar J. Kaufmann -- merchant prince and pioneer planner of Pittsburghs physical and cultural redevelopment -- one of the citys outstanding citizens, died suddenly at 69 in his Palm Springs, California home.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 25, 1955%0a%3c Bell Telephone Company announced that its new headquarters building -- the fifth structure to be added to Pittsburghs Gateway Center -- was going into construction.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 28, 1955%0a%3c Jones and Laughlin Steel Corporation added $86,000,000 to its expansion program, including new mills to be constructed in the Pittsburgh area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 2, 1955%0a%3c Benjamin F. Fairless resigned as board chairman and chief executive officer of the United States Steel Corporation; he was succeeded by Roger M. Blough%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 3, 1955%0a%3c It was announced that construction on the Baltimore and Ohio Railroads new passenger terminal, at the foot of Grant Street, would begin within the next month.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 23, 1955%0a%3c A capital improvement program for 1955, amounting to almost $6,000,000, was submitted to City Council by Mayor Lawrence. Plans included a start on rehabilitation of the citys water system, construction of new fire stations, a fire-police training center, street and sewer repairs, and grants to the Auditorium Authority and Carnegie Library.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 1, 1955%0a%3c Approximately 10,000 Westinghouse Electric Corporation workers voted to stay away from their jobs in protest against disciplinary furloughs given 1100 East Pittsburgh workers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 8, 1955%0a%3c The strike at East Pittsburgh and three other Westinghouse plants was settled.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 13, 1955%0a%3c General Matthew B. Ridgway was appointed chairman of the board of Mellon Institute. Dr. E. R. Weidlein remained as president and member of the board.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 20, 1955%0a%3c The Regional Industrial Development Corporation, a nonprofit organization, was created.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 22, 1955%0a%3c T. M. Girdler resigned as chief executive officer of Republic Steel Corporation, but remained as board chairman. C. M. White, the firms president, was named chief executive officer.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 1, 1955%0a%3c A nationwide steel strike began, but ended 12 hours later when agreement was reached.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 8, 1955%0a%3c At a hearing conducted by the Public Utility Commission, it was decided to remove the Pennsylvania Railroads last Downtown elevated, leaving Fort Duquesne Boulevard free to be developed into a sunlit, landscaped, riverside drive.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 14, 1955%0a%3c County Commissioners adopted broad revisions in the smoke-control ordinance, giving industry an additional two to four years to comply.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 15, 1955%0a%3c Pittsburghs fourth municipal parking garage, at Boulevard of the Allies and Smithfield Street, was opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 29, 1955%0a%3c Greyhound Lines announced plans for a new bus terminal covering more than two and one-half acres bounded by 11th Street, 12th Street, Penn Avenue, and Liberty Avenue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 8, 1955%0a%3c More than 2200 members of Local 601, CIO International Union of Electrical Workers, struck at Westinghouse Electric Corporation in protest against the companys time-study program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 15, 1955%0a%3c The citys first heliport was established atop the Gateway Parking Garage, at Fourth Avenue and Stanwix Street, in anticipation of regular helicopter service between Downtown and the airports.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 24, 1955%0a%3c Thousands of persons gathered at Greater Pittsburgh Airport for the dedication of a spectacular fountain as a memorial to the countys dead of all wars.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 30, 1955%0a%3c H. J. Heinz Company announced plans for immediate construction of one of the worlds most advanced food research centers at a cost of $3,000,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 6, 1955%0a%3c Plans for construction of a new $3,000,000 chemical plant on Neville Island were made by Pittsburgh Coke and Chemical Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 9, 1955%0a%3c Dr. James Purdy Kerr, 91, the oldest active surgeon in the country, died at St. Josephs Hospital, which he had helped to found.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 12, 1955%0a%3c At the annual dinner of the Allegheny Conference on Community Development, Commissioner James W. Follin of the Urban Renewal Authority, Washington, assured Pittsburgh of $17,386,610 for slum clearance and redevelopment of the Lower Hill District.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 17, 1955%0a%3c Forty-four thousand members of the CIO International Union of Electrical Workers started another strike against the Westinghouse Electric Corporation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 18, 1955%0a%3c Mellon Square Park -- the most spectacular in the citys expanding park system -- formally became a possession of the citizens of Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 24, 1955%0a%3c Harry W. Fowler, a member of the board of Allegheny County Commissioners since 1949 and long a leader in the countys highway planning and designing, died at 64.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 25, 1955%0a%3c A contract signing set the stage for the four-year four-month job of moving families out of the 100 acres of Lower Hill District scheduled for redevelopment. The Housing Authority of Pittsburgh agreed to handle relocation of 1800 families.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 27, 1955%0a%3c Jones and Laughlin Steel Corporation announced it would enlarge its 1955-56 expansion program to an expenditure of $250,000,000 covering 1955-58.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 14, 1955%0a%3c Dr. Charles F. Lewis, director of the Buhl Foundation since it was organized in 1928, announced his retirement, effective June 30, 1956.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 15, 1955%0a%3c The National Steel Corporation planned to spend a minimum of $200,000,000 on additions to existing plants within the next three and one-half years.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 30, 1955%0a%3c Pennsylvania College for Women was renamed Chatham College and announced a $12,000,000 development program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 14, 1955%0a%3c Dr. Charles B. Nutting, vice chancellor of the University of Pittsburgh, was named director of the Buhl Foundation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 20, 1956%0a%3c Contracts totaling $10,333,062 for two major projects on the Penn-Lincoln Parkway -- the Downtown link and the Fort Pitt Bridge -- were awarded by the State Highways Department.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 8, 1956%0a%3c The University of Pittsburghs Cathedral of Learning was officially dedicated to President Honorarius John G. Bowman, who served as Pitts Chancellor from 1921 to 1946.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 19, 1956%0a%3c Dr. Edward R. Weidlein, long-time president of Mellon Institute announced his retirement.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 20, 1956%0a%3c The long and bitter Westinghouse strike came to an end after 156 days.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 1, 1956%0a%3c Twenty-two persons were killed when a twin-engine TWA plane crashed just after taking off from Greater Pittsburgh Airport. This was the first disaster at the airport and the worst in the history of local commercial aviation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 4, 1956%0a%3c Mayor Lawrence recommended a new and broader attack against neighborhood blight under a $4,740,250 capital improvement program. Included was more than $800,000 to represent the citys first cash commitments to the Lower Hill redevelopment and Crosstown Boulevard projects.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 18, 1956%0a%3c Irwin D. Wolf, 61, who succeeded Edgar J. Kaufmann as president and general manager of Kaufmann Department Store, a civic and philanthropic leader, died at his Fifth Avenue home after a long illness.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 8, 1956%0a%3c United States Steel Corporation formally opened its newly built Research Center, consisting of four buildings and covering 142 acres in Monroeville.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 9, 1956%0a%3c The Koppers Company revealed plans for a multimillion-dollar research center in the borough of Monroeville.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 10, 1956%0a%3c Rodef Shalom Congregation observed its 100th anniversary and dedicated its new Temple at Fifth and Morewood avenues.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 11, 1956%0a%3c Hilton Hotels Corporation announced that it would build a $15,000,000 hotel next to Point State Park.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 1, 1956%0a%3c A nationwide steel strike began. Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service entered the dispute which idled 600,000 United Steelworkers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 16, 1956%0a%3c The last canvas tent performance of Ringling Brothers and Barnum & Bailey Combined Shows was given at Heidelberg Raceways, marking the end of an era of entertainment.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 27, 1956%0a%3c A master settlement, providing a three-year, no-strike agreement, ended the strike which shut down 85 per cent of the nations steel productive capacity for 27 days.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 9, 1956%0a%3c The United Steelworkers and the Aluminum Company of America signed a three-year no-strike agreement ending a nine-day strike of 18,000 members of 12 of the companys 21 plants.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 13, 1956%0a%3c Razing of the Gardens, historic landmark and scene of sports events for more than 50 years, was begun, to make room for an eight-story apartment house containing 127 luxury-type dwellings.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 16, 1956%0a%3c A program to expend $81,304,000 for additions to the National Tube Division of United States Steel in McKeesport was announced.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 5, 1956%0a%3c According to a Navy announcement, an atomic reactor for the worlds first nuclear powered surface warship would be built by Westinghouse.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 3, 1956%0a%3c Democratic presidential candidate Adlai E. Stevenson spoke in the city and made a network television broadcast from KDKA-TV.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 3, 1956%0a%3c The last steam engine in the Pittsburgh area was sent to the scrap heap.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 8, 1956%0a%3c Ex-President Harry S. Truman campaigned in Pittsburgh for the Democratic ticket.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 9, 1956%0a%3c President Dwight D. Eisenhower made a major campaign speech at Hunt Armory for the Republican ticket.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 17, 1956%0a%3c Admiral Benjamin Moreell, chairman of Jones and Laughlin Steel Corporation, received the John Fritz Medal -- one of the nations highest awards for scientific and engineering achievement -- at the National Convention dinner of the American Society of Civil Engineers in the Penn-Sheraton Hotel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 31, 1956%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Department of Public Health revealed that nine of every ten North Side houses examined by city housing inspectors were in violation of the new code.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 31, 1956%0a%3c More than 12,000 jammed into Hunt Armory to hear a major address by the Democratic presidential candidate, Adlai E. Stevenson.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 1, 1956%0a%3c Theodore L. Hazlett, Jr., executive director of the Urban Redevelopment Authority, warned that a critical shortage of housing for relocation of families threatened to undermine Pittsburghs ambitious program for eliminating blight.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 5, 1956%0a%3c The Commission on Human Relations announced the formation of a Citizens Committee for Integrated Housing, to be composed of about 150 persons from all segments of community life, and a subcommittee of builders and mortgage bankers, to work on plans for a pilot integrated housing project.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 6, 1956%0a%3c President Eisenhower was re-elected for a second term. He won a smashing victory in Allegheny County, moving the area into the Republican column for the first time since 1928. Adlai E. Stevenson carried the city of Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 8, 1956%0a%3c Final totals for the Allegheny County United Fund Drive, the countys first combined charity appeal, amounted to 107.8 per cent of the goal, a total of $9,564,222.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 20, 1956%0a%3c Mayor Lawrence recommended an all-time high city budget of $44,273,292, but at the same time called for a slight reduction in real estate taxes.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 30, 1956%0a%3c H. K. Porter Company made it known that it would build a 17-story, $7,000,000 office building at the corner of Sixth Avenue and Grant Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 11, 1956%0a%3c Equitable Life Assurance Society announced plans for a 15- to 22-story office building in the Gateway Center, costing between $9,000,000 and $12,000,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 23, 1957%0a%3c Western Pennsylvanias heavy construction industry and the Laborers District Council ended a three-week strike by signing a two-year wage contract.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 4, 1957%0a%3c Paul H. Martin, retiring head of the Pittsburgh Regional Planning Association, urged comprehensive planning on a regional basis for the Pittsburgh area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 19, 1957%0a%3c The Board of Education voted to spend another $10,000,000, most of it within the next five years, to build new schools and modernize a number of others. Money was to be raised by selling general obligation bonds.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 1, 1957%0a%3c A federal grant for construction of a new east-west runway at the Pittsburgh Airport was announced.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 8, 1957%0a%3c Carnegie Institute of Technology embarked on a $26,000,000-plus plan of progress.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 9, 1957%0a%3c Six industrial concerns were named as violators of the countrys smoke-control ordinance.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 13, 1957%0a%3c Public Works Director James S. Devlin said that $2,850,000 would be spent in street resurfacing and rebuilding projects during 1957.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 14, 1957%0a%3c Thomas E. Kilgallen, former president of City Council, died at 64.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 17, 1957%0a%3c Ground was broken for construction of the $17,000,000 Fort Pitt Tunnels under Duquesne Heights, to provide the final link between the eastern and western sections of the Penn-Lincoln Parkway.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 26, 1957%0a%3c The State Office Building in Gateway Center was dedicated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 11, 1957%0a%3c Dr. Edward H. Litchfield was inaugurated as the 12th chancellor of the University of Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 21, 1957%0a%3c The Allegheny Conference urged state, county, and city governments to join in a long-range highway program to meet traffic requirements.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 4, 1957%0a%3c The last three contracts were awarded for construction of an east loading dock, the first major expansion of the terminal building at Greater Pittsburgh Airport.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 21, 1957%0a%3c The University of Pittsburgh announced plans for a new graduate program to train engineers in all phases of air pollution control in keeping with the citys pioneering advances in that field.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 26, 1957%0a%3c Plans were made for the merger of Pittsburgh Xenia Theological Seminary (Presbyterian), North Highland Avenue, and the Western Theological Seminary (Presbyterian), Ridge Avenue, North Side.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 26, 1957%0a%3c Ernest T. Weir, 81, long a "rugged individualist" in the well-organized steel industry and former chief executive of the National Steel Corporation, died in Philadelphia.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 25, 1957%0a%3c Television City, Incorporated, was granted authority by the Federal Communications Commission to operate a Pittsburgh television station on Channel 4.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 25, 1957%0a%3c Avery C. Adams, president and chief operating officer of Jones and Laughlin Steel Corporation, was elected chief executive officer, effective October 1. Admiral Benjamin Moreell remained as board chairman and chairman of the executive committee.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 1, 1957%0a%3c Carnegie Institute of Technology was purchasing eight acres of property fronting on Forbes Street near Morewood Avenue for faculty and student residences.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 14, 1957%0a%3c The National Steel Corporation elected George M. Humphrey, former Secretary of the Treasury, as its chairman of the board.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 28, 1957%0a%3c Drilling began on the $17,000,000 Fort Pitt Tunnels.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 1, 1957%0a%3c Pittsburghs Channel 4, WIIC, began broadcasting as the nations newest and most powerful VHF television station.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 10, 1957%0a%3c The city was assured of a federal grant of nearly $11,000,000 with which to begin urban renewal in East Liberty and the North Sides Manchester District.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 20, 1957%0a%3c Ground was broken at Gateway Center by Conrad N. Hilton for the new Hilton hotel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 14, 1957%0a%3c A strike by operators of the Pittsburgh Railways Company began.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 18, 1957%0a%3c A Pittsburgh to Erie extension of the Pennsylvania Turnpike became a definite prospect with the announcement that it had been added to the National Interstate Highway System.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 5, 1957%0a%3c Mayor Lawrence won a fourth term victory by a 59,500 vote majority over his Republican opponent, John Drew.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 2, 1957%0a%3c A total municipal budget of more than $54,000,000 for 1958 was proposed by Mayor Lawrence.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 9, 1957%0a%3c The transit strike ended and within hours the trolley and bus lines were in operation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 18, 1957%0a%3c Pittsburgh started receiving electricity generated by atomic power from Shippingport, Pennsylvania, site of the worlds first full-scale atomic electric power plant.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 18, 1957%0a%3c Westinghouse was awarded a $46,050,000 Navy contract for nuclear power plant components for the worlds first atomic-powered aircraft carrier.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 17, 1958%0a%3c Penn-Lincoln Parkway, in its 12th year of construction was directly linked to the Downtown Triangle with the opening of a new Grant Street outbound ramp.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 27, 1958%0a%3c Mayor Lawrence presented his 1958 capital improvements budget to City Council, calling for expenditure of $13,221,300.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 12, 1958%0a%3c Boggs and Buhl, one of Pittsburghs oldest department stores, announced it would go out of business after 89 years of operation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 3, 1958%0a%3c Mayor Lawrence agreed to run for the Democratic nomination for governor in order to end a contest that threatened to split the Democratic party.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 5, 1958%0a%3c Spear and Company, which had operated a department store in the city since 1893, was sold to the Hahn Furniture Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 18, 1958%0a%3c Mrs. John M. Phillips, for more than 40 years an outstanding figure in Pittsburgh life, and a militant fighter for the rights of others, died in Mercy Hospital at 76.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 31, 1958%0a%3c Mayor Lawrence and Governor George M. Leader set off a charge that created an opening in the upper arc of Fort Pitt Tunnels north portal, above West Carson Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 8, 1958%0a%3c Allegheny Countys Common Pleas Court judges ordered a drastic reform in court procedure and urged the Legislature to create four new judgeships to reduce the ever-increasing backlog of civil cases in the court.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 9, 1958%0a%3c Common Pleas Court judges extended their battle to speed up justice to the year-and-one-half backlog in Criminal Court.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 28, 1958%0a%3c The United Presbyterian Church of the United States of America was formed by the merger of the Presbyterian Church USA and the United Presbyterian Church of North America in ceremonies at Fifth Avenue and Bigelow Boulevard. Dr. Theophilus Mills Taylor of Pittsburgh Xenia Theological Seminary was elected moderator.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 3, 1958%0a%3c Allegheny County prepared to start on a public improvement program authorized in the May primary. Projects included a $9,575,000 Glenwood Bridge over the Monongahela, a new high-level bridge over the Allegheny and a $5,000,000 viaduct to span Turtle Creek in East Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 17, 1958%0a%3c It was revealed that the Mellon family foundations had paid $3,000,000 for 3650 acres in six strategic locations in Allegheny County. The land was to be sold to the county at cost for a regional park system for Pittsburghs suburbs.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 11, 1958%0a%3c The United States Steel Corporation announced that production at its Edgar Thomson Works would be curtailed because of declining demand. About 1500 men were to be laid off.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 24, 1958%0a%3c Alan M. Scaife, a leader in Pittsburghs cultural life, died at 58.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 30, 1958%0a%3c Leland Hazard, vice-president and general counsel of the Pittsburgh Plate-Glass Company and one of the sparkplugs for Pittsburghs renaissance was named professor of industrial administration and law at Carnegie Institute of Technology.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 3, 1958%0a%3c The Urban Redevelopment Authority began final planning for the $15,000,000 Chateau Street-West renewal project in the Manchester District of the North Side.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 6, 1958%0a%3c The federal government assured Pittsburgh of aid for the proposed $15,000,000 redevelopment project for substandard areas at East Liberty.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 6, 1958%0a%3c The State Highway Department approved plans for a new Glenwood Bridge, thereby making it possible for the county to receive $10,000,000 in federal aid.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 29, 1958%0a%3c Jones and Laughlin Steel Corporation was to spend $35,000,000 on mill improvements at its Pittsburgh and Aliquippa plants, increasing planned projects for 1958-1959 to $93,000,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 5, 1958%0a%3c By switching WQEX, the new educational outlet, from channel 22 to channel 16, the Federal Communications Commission assured the operation of a second educational television station in Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 9, 1958%0a%3c Chancellor Edward H. Litchfield of the University of Pittsburgh unveiled a huge long-range, multimillion-dollar campus development plan, which would require eviction of the Pittsburgh Pirates from Forbes Field.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 21, 1958%0a%3c Judge A. Marshall Thompson, 86, oldest member of Allegheny County Common Pleas Court, died. A former dean of the University of Pittsburgh Law School, he was serving his third 10-year term on the court.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 22, 1958%0a%3c Mary Roberts Rinehart, 82, a native of Pittsburgh, died in New York City.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 22, 1958%0a%3c A 22-day strike at Pittsburghs five major hotels ended.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 27, 1958%0a%3c President Dwight D. Eisenhower campaigned for the Republican ticket in an address at the Syria Mosque.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 28, 1958%0a%3c Carnegie Institute of Technology received a gift of $2,800,000 from Mr. and Mrs. Roy A. Hunt for the construction of a campus library.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 4, 1958%0a%3c Mayor Lawrence was elected governor of Pennsylvania over Republican Arthur T. McGonigle.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 9, 1958%0a%3c The General Services Administration announced that Pittsburghs new Federal Building would be constructed near the Greyhound Terminal, ending a three-year debate over location.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 9, 1958%0a%3c Dr. I. Hope Alexander, director of the Pittsburgh Health Department for 20 years before retirement in 1956, died at 79.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 20, 1958%0a%3c The Crosstown Boulevard moved nearer reality when the State Highway Department awarded two contracts for $3,349,690 to start its construction.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 27, 1958%0a%3c Thousands assembled in Point State Park, at the very spot where Fort Duquesne once stood, to hear Mayor David Lawrence and General Matthew B. Ridgway begin the citys bicentennial celebration. It was two hundred years ago that the French abandoned Fort Duquesne (on November 24, 1758) and General Forbes army took possession of the area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 28, 1958%0a%3c Sale of Forbes Field to University of Pittsburgh is approved; the Pirates will stay on for five years, until new Northside stadium is built. In reality, the Pirates stayed on not for five but for twelve years, until 1970 when the new stadium opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 1, 1958%0a%3c Red Manning hired as coach of Duquesne Universitys basketball team.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 16, 1958%0a%3c A. W. Mellon Educational and Charitable Trust gives $12 million to the University of Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 17, 1958%0a%3c John Dearden, Roman Catholic bishop of Pittsburgh, is appointed archbishop of Detroit.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 23, 1958%0a%3c City Solicitor Anne X. Alpern named attorney general of Pennsylvania.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 1, 1959%0a%3c The 51-year-old Frank & Seders department store will have a going-out-of-business sale.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 16, 1959%0a%3c City Council President Thomas Gallagher sworn in as mayor of Pittsburgh, replacing David Lawrence, who on January 20 will he inaugurated as governor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 31, 1959%0a%3c In a trade that will later be credited with making the Pittsburgh Pirates pennant winners in 1960, the baseball team obtains Harvey Haddix, Don Hoak, and Smoky Burgess from the Cincinnati Reds.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 7, 1959%0a%3c Art Rooney, president of the Steelers, is dissatisfied with Pitt Stadium and wants to return his club to Forbes Field.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 9, 1959%0a%3c Governor David Lawrence will ask the state legislature for a law banning racial discrimination in housing.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 16, 1959%0a%3c The Democratic slate of candidates for May primary includes Joseph M. Barr for mayor; John Kane and William McClelland for county commissioners.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 19, 1959%0a%3c Thirteen men are arrested in a raid on the headquarters of the alleged numbers-racket boss Tony Grosso.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 25, 1959%0a%3c Industrialist Paul Reinhold enters race for mayor on the Republican ticket.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 18, 1959%0a%3c John J. Wright is installed as Roman Catholic bishop of Pittsburgh in St. Pauls Cathedral.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 27, 1959%0a%3c David J. McDonald, president of the United Steelworkers asserts that big-steel management is "hell-bent" on fomenting a strike when contract expires July 1.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 10, 1959%0a%3c A consensus is forming for legislation to provide for public ownership of mass transit.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 11, 1959%0a%3c United Steelworkers refuse one-year extension of their contract.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 17, 1959%0a%3c A mock air-raid is a failure; passersby laughingly refuse to take cover.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 21, 1959%0a%3c The Allegheny Conference on Community Development urges support for publicly-owned mass transit.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 1, 1959%0a%3c Jones and Laughlin announces a $234 million capital expenditure program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 6, 1959%0a%3c Walter A. Munford becomes president of United States Steel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 13, 1959%0a%3c A bill establishing public ownership of mass transit is reported out of committee in Harrisburg.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 19, 1959%0a%3c In the primary election, Joseph Barr and Paul Reinhold win nominations for mayor on the Democratic and Republican tickets respectively.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 21, 1959%0a%3c Peoples First National Bank and Trust and Fidelity Trust approve the merger of their institutions.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 1, 1959%0a%3c Pittsburgh becomes second city in the United States to ban discrimination in residential renting or purchasing, due to a new "Fair Housing Practices Ordinance."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 4, 1959%0a%3c Up to $60 million in residential and commercial construction, designed for the Pittsburgh of tomorrow, is envisioned for the Lower Hill District in bids from eleven developers. The development did not materialize.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 4, 1959%0a%3c Alcoma Golf Club suffers considerable fire damage.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 8, 1959%0a%3c The Public Utility Commission authorizes shift from trolleys to buses, on a temporary basis, as the tracks may not be removed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 8, 1959%0a%3c Possibility of a $722,000 federal loan for Allegheny Countys new Northside sports stadium is announced.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 11, 1959%0a%3c Allegheny County Boroughs Association votes to oppose the mass transit bill in its present form. The bill, bitterly attacked by spokesmen for the Independent Bus Operators and others, is sent back to House committee for further amendments.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 19, 1959%0a%3c Fort Pitt Bridge, vital link in Penn-Lincoln Parkway, is opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 23, 1959%0a%3c Allegheny Countys transit bill is passed by House; goes to state Senate for final action.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 24, 1959%0a%3c H. I. Casteel, businessman, dies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 1, 1959%0a%3c Four members of Pittsburgh Pirates picked for All-Star Game: Smoky Burgess, Dick Groat, Elroy Face and Bill Mazeroski.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 7, 1959%0a%3c Pittsburgh hosts All-Star Game (National League wins 5-4; Vice President Richard M. Nixon throws out first ball).%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 14, 1959%0a%3c Pickets at the steel mills, as another steel strike begins.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 15, 1959%0a%3c John J. Kane announces his withdrawal from race for re-election as county commissioner.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 21, 1959%0a%3c Steel strike slows down construction of the Civic Arena.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 28, 1959%0a%3c United Steelworkers union extends contracts with nations major aluminum producers, averting walkout of 30,000 members.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 30, 1959%0a%3c Michael L. Benedum, multimillionaire oil wildcatter dies two weeks after his 90th birthday.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 4, 1959%0a%3c 2,000 striking steelworkers in a rally at Memorial Hall voice all-out support to union leadership in their fight for wage increase and benefits.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 23, 1959%0a%3c In violent storms, three city buildings were damaged.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 25, 1959%0a%3c Steelworkers President McDonald declares that the USW will stay on strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 2, 1959%0a%3c Two officials of the Russian embassy are in Pittsburgh to arrange details of Nikita Khrushchevs forthcoming tour.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 19, 1959%0a%3c The unfinished East Hills Shopping Center is offered to highest bidder at auction ("largest sheriffs sale ever"). The center is worth $8 million.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 20, 1959%0a%3c Religious services mark a protest against Khrushchevs visit. Khrushchev arrives and speaks of eagerness for peace. Thousands of Pittsburghers are on hand to see him.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 25, 1959%0a%3c Steelworkers Union breaks off talks in 73-day steel strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 29, 1959%0a%3c Dr. Jonas Salk gets a March of Dimes grant of $413,439 to continue his study at the University of Pittsburgh of viruses and cells.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 1, 1959%0a%3c Sam Grosso and ten of his racketeers are found guilty.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 9, 1959%0a%3c President Eisenhower invokes the Taft-Hartley Act to break the deadlock between management and labor in the steel industry.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 20, 1959%0a%3c The Carnegie Institute of Technology gets $2.25 million grant from the Ford Foundation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 23, 1959%0a%3c The new Port Authority (mass transportation) gets off to a shaky start.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 3, 1959%0a%3c Joseph M. Barr, Democrat, elected mayor. Barr --124,500; Reinhold -- 71 ,202.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 8, 1959%0a%3c After striking for 116 days, steelworkers return to the mills.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 13, 1959%0a%3c A new site, closer to Allegheny River, is chosen for the stadium.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 23, 1959%0a%3c Representatives of trolley operators and representatives of the Pittsburgh Railways negotiate.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 31, 1959%0a%3c Pittsburgh Railways rejects new union contract offer.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 2, 1959%0a%3c Joseph M. Barr sworn in as 51st mayor of the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 4, 1959%0a%3c Mayor Barr invites trolley union and management to a meeting.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 8, 1959%0a%3c After the Mayors proposal is rejected by management and labor, trolley strike begins.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 13, 1959%0a%3c Vote of 914-11 ratifies a 26 cent-per-hour increase in wages, as trolley strike ends after six days.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1960%0a%3c January 11, 1960%0a%3c The eight-year-old stalemate about trolley-to-bus conversion in West End routes threatens to jeopardize key "Renaissance" projects near Point State Park.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 21, 1960%0a%3c The Public Auditorium Authority announces that Deeter and Ritchey Architects of Pittsburgh, Michael Baker Jr. of Rochester, and Osborn Engineering of Cleveland are commissioned to design the Northside stadium.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 2, 1960%0a%3c Racketeer Sam Grosso sentenced to 16-32 months in Western Penitentiary.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 14, 1960%0a%3c Twelve-inch snowstorm closes airports and schools.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 21, 1960%0a%3c KDKA performers, members of the American Federation of Television and Radio Artists, go on strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 1, 1960%0a%3c A $500,000 fire destroys ten downtown businesses.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 11, 1960%0a%3c Announcement is made of the departure in 1961 of Dr. Jonas Salk from the University of Pittsburgh. He will become the head of a research institute in San Diego, California.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 14, 1960%0a%3c A $20 million new construction work in Pittsburgh district highway program will begin in the spring. Included is the linkage of the Penn-Lincoln Parkway with the turnpike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 23, 1960%0a%3c $170 million is set for improvement expenditures at the University of Pittsburgh within the next ten years.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 14, 1960%0a%3c Three Pittsburgh bishops -- John Wright, Roman Catholic, Austin Pardue, Episcopal, and Nicholas T. Elko, Byzantine Catholic -- oppose ballot issue to allow betting on harness racing.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 18, 1960%0a%3c A new chapter in Pittsburgh redevelopment begins with Simpson Brothers plan to build private homes.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 22, 1960%0a%3c The afternoon Sun-Telegraph is purchased by the Post-Gazette.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 26, 1960%0a%3c The issue of harness racing, opposed by the bishops (see above) is defeated -- 219,509 people voted "No"; 167,195, "Yes.".%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 14, 1960%0a%3c General Matthew B. Ridgway, the chairman and chief executive officer of Mellon Institute, retires.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 25, 1960%0a%3c City Safety Director Louis Rosenberg orders halt to all bingo games, even those sponsored by churches.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 9, 1960%0a%3c AFL and CIO merge.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 19, 1960%0a%3c Northside "Lower Belt" plan for $99 million interstate expressway wins formal support of State Highway Secretary Park H. Martin.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 31, 1960%0a%3c 17,000 baseball fans crowd Greater Pittsburgh Airport to welcome 1st-place Pirates home from Chicago.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 1, 1960%0a%3c Fort Pitt Tunnel is opened.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 25, 1960%0a%3c Pirates win National League pennant, even though losing 4-2 to Braves. (St. Louis Cardinals loss on same day gives Pirates the victory.)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 5, 1960%0a%3c World Series begins. Pirates beat Yankees in first game, 6 - 4.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 10, 1960%0a%3c Senator John F. Kennedy, the Democratic presidential candidate, speaks in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 13, 1960%0a%3c With the World Series even, three games each, the Pirates win the seventh game 10-9 with a home run by Bill Mazeroski in the ninth inning.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 24, 1960%0a%3c Richard Nixon, the Republican presidential candidate, speaks in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 25, 1960%0a%3c University of Pittsburgh will buy five blocks in Oakland to build new dormitories.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 3, 1960%0a%3c President Eisenhower and former President Harry Truman speak in Pittsburgh for their partys nominees.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 8, 1960%0a%3c Allegheny County joins in Pennsylvanias support of John F. Kennedy, who is elected to the presidency.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 5, 1960%0a%3c The six-year battle for the "Lower-Belt" system in Northside is won.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 18, 1961%0a%3c North Park ice skating rink opens.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 24, 1961%0a%3c East Liberty urban renewal project is approved.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 2, 1961%0a%3c Conversion from trolleys to buses is discussed again.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 5, 1961%0a%3c John J. Kane, retired county commissioner, dies at the age of 70.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 20, 1961%0a%3c The Carnegie Institute of Technology receives grant by Ford Foundation to help raise the standards of the American theatre.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 6, 1961%0a%3c Yellow Cab drivers and mechanics go on strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 5, 1961%0a%3c Alcoa joins with a Kansas City real estate developer to rebuild the 79-acre commercial area, part of Northside renewal.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 15, 1961%0a%3c After 70 days, cab strike is settled.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 18, 1961%0a%3c Liquor sales at hotel bars on Sunday become legal.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 16, 1961%0a%3c Jones and Laughlin plans a quarter of a billion dollar expansion program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 30, 1961%0a%3c The Post-Gazette celebrates its 175th birthday.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 25, 1961%0a%3c Port Authority rejects Pennsylvania Railroads bid for public subsidies to keep its commuter trains running.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 17, 1961%0a%3c Civic Arena opens for the public.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 1, 1961%0a%3c Plans for a 55,000-seat, $22 million sports stadium go before the city and county officials.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 6, 1961%0a%3c Plans for the thirteen-story IBM building in Gateway Center is approved.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 7, 1961%0a%3c Democrats sweep elections in city and county. Barr elected to his first full term as mayor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 28, 1961%0a%3c Allegheny County voters will have the final say on unified mass transit for the county.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 1, 1962%0a%3c Benjamin Fairless, former president of US Steel, dies at 71.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 20, 1962%0a%3c Civic Arena reaches agreement over jurisdiction with unions. Agreement insures that the arena will be the summer home for the Civic Light Opera.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 11, 1962%0a%3c United States Steel sets increase of $6 a ton as a "catch-up adjustment."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 20, 1962%0a%3c Troubles at the Civic Arena as air conditioning cooling system fails during the Western Pennsylvania Kennel show.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 14, 1962%0a%3c An $84 million rebuilding plan for the Golden Triangle is announced.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 12, 1962%0a%3c President Kennedy assails Republicans in the city. 300,000 Pittsburghers welcome him.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 6, 1962%0a%3c William Scranton elected governor of Pennsylvania.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 19, 1962%0a%3c Allegheny County Port Authority has acquisition agreements with 2