h building trade unions (except Brotherhood of Electrical Workers) agree to accept black men in their ranks.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 29, 1963%0a%3c Milk strike starts; the main reason for it: job security.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 23, 1963%0a%3c Westinghouse offers its four major unions a 14 cent raise and a five-year pension improvement.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 27, 1963%0a%3c After a record drought, showers bring relief to the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 5, 1963%0a%3c Democratic victory in the Allegheny County election. Reelected are Commissioners McClelland and McGrady. The only Republican to be elected to major office is the new district attorney, Robert W. Duggan.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 11, 1963%0a%3c Mayor Barr announces that he is "looking into" the possibility of imposing an occupation tax on all working in Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 11, 1963%0a%3c Avery Adams, chairman of Jones and Laughlins executive committee, dies at age 65.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 19, 1963%0a%3c Earl Belle, "financial wizard," returns from Brazil to face trial.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 28, 1964%0a%3c Former Judge William H. McNaugher dies at age 72.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 2, 1964%0a%3c Dapper Dan banquet gives top award to Pitt football coach John Michelosen.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 28, 1964%0a%3c Port Authority wins control of the Pittsburgh Railways Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 11, 1964%0a%3c In the worst flood of the past decade, water reaches 31.6 foot crests.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 17, 1964%0a%3c Fire destroys the Pittsburgher Motel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 5, 1964%0a%3c Sabin anti-polio vaccine is administered to 800,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 29, 1964%0a%3c Police Detective Ralph Barnett sworn in as citys first black police inspector.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 1, 1964%0a%3c Pittsburghs WIIC-TV, Channel 11, sold by Post-Gazette and Brennan family to the Cox Broadcasting Company for more than $20 million.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 20, 1964%0a%3c Groundbreaking ceremonies at Chatham Center.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 27, 1964%0a%3c President Lyndon B. Johnson arrives for rally in Civic Arena.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 29, 1964%0a%3c Republican presidential candidate Barry Goldwater speaks at the Civic Arena.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 3, 1964%0a%3c In the presidential election, the Johnson-Humphrey ticket wins, defeating the Republican ticket of Goldwater-Miller.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 6, 1964%0a%3c I. W. Abel, United Steelworkers secretary-treasurer, will oppose USW President David J. McDonald in the forthcoming election of the Steelworkers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 30, 1965%0a%3c I. W. Abel wins the presidency of USW.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 6, 1965%0a%3c John W. Galbreath plans a 60-story building at a cost of $50 million to house U. S. Steel offices.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 27, 1965%0a%3c Edward Litchfield resigns as chancellor of the University of Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 5, 1965%0a%3c United Steelworkers accept new 35-month wage agreement.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 2, 1965%0a%3c Mayor Barr and his five City Council running mates are re-elected, with new councilman Peter Flaherty leading the ticket.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 11, 1966%0a%3c Sarah Mellon Scaifes bequest of $7.9 million to institutions is announced. The University of Pittsburgh will receive $5 million.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 20, 1966%0a%3c Bill Austin named new Pittsburgh Steelers head coach.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 26, 1966%0a%3c Dr. Stanton C. Crawford, acting chancellor of the University of Pittsburgh, dies. He is succeeded by David Kurtzman.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 9, 1966%0a%3c Pittsburgh is granted National Hockey League franchise.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 5, 1966%0a%3c K. C. Morrissey named as first president of Allegheny County Community College. Monument Hill, Northside, will be the site of the colleges first campus.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 19, 1966%0a%3c Pittsburgh board of public education takes first steps in a $50 million construction program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 22, 1966%0a%3c Court ends roadblock to construction of new stadium brought about by taxpayers suit.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 25, 1966%0a%3c The creation of UHF television Channel 53 is announced.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 10, 1966%0a%3c Harry Keller is appointed fire chief, succeeding Steven Adley.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 30, 1966%0a%3c "Commuter bandit" hits the Oakland Western Pennsylvania National Bank branch for $9,554. This is the "commuters" 14th robbery.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 6, 1966%0a%3c Pittsburgh Symphony is given a $2.5 million grant by the Ford Foundation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 11, 1966%0a%3c Stadium Authority declares that the projected stadium as designed is too costly. It asks for alternative designs.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 9, 1966%0a%3c The University of Pittsburgh appropriations bill -- $ 19,757,200 -- passes the state House and Senate and is sent to the governor for his signature. It will enable Pitt to reduce tuition for full-time Pennsylvania residents to $450 annually.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 25, 1966%0a%3c The new stadium plans are unveiled; it is similar to stadiums in St. Louis and Atlanta and it will cost $12 million less than the original design.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 14, 1966%0a%3c A plan to merge Mellon Institute and Carnegie Institute of Technology is announced by Paul Mellon and Aiken Fisher, the respective board chairmen of the two institutions.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 19, 1966%0a%3c Classes began for some 950 students at the Community Colleges Allegheny Campus and at Boyle Campus, then named East Campus on October 6.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 21, 1966%0a%3c Roy Arthur Hunt, 85, retired president and chairman of Alcoas executive committee and member of its board of directors since 1914, dies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 14, 1966%0a%3c Richard K. Mellon retires as chairman of the Board of Mellon National Bank and Trust Co.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 17, 1966%0a%3c The State Highway Department discloses that a bridge might be built over the Ohio River parallel to the West End Bridge.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 21, 1966%0a%3c David L. Lawrence, who on November 4 suffered a heart attack while attending a political rally at the Syria Mosque, dies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 1, 1966%0a%3c Maury Wills traded to Pittsburgh Pirates.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1967%0a%3c A survey conducted in 1967 by the American Insurance Association gave the citys fire defenses the worst rating in Pittsburghs history.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 13, 1967%0a%3c Wesley Posvar named chancellor of the University of Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 27, 1967%0a%3c Mrs. Henry Hillman elected county Republican party chairman.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 15, 1967%0a%3c US Steel breaks ground for its new skyscraper headquarters, the worlds second largest high-rise office building.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 19, 1967%0a%3c H. J. Heinz II and the Howard Heinz Endowment acquire the Penn Theater for the Pittsburgh Symphony.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 9, 1967%0a%3c "Secret" project entailing new wing for Carnegie Institute financed by Scaife family is reported.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 21, 1967%0a%3c State Highway Commission says that the finishing of the "Bridge to Nowhere" will start shortly.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 17, 1967%0a%3c "Commuter Bandit" hits the Bloomfield branch of the Pittsburgh National Bank for the second time.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 11, 1967%0a%3c A master plan for a new 