3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 5, 1968%0a%3c Gangs of black youth wreaked destruction in the Hill District and in other sections of the city following the April 4 assassination of Martin Luther King, Jr., the black civil rights leader.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 7, 1968%0a%3c Mayor Barr imposes a five-day curfew for Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 10, 1968%0a%3c Ling-Temco-Vought, Inc. of Texas offers $85 a share for up to five million shares of Pittsburghs Jones and Laughlin Steel. The deal would give LTV 63 percent of J and L stock.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 22, 1968%0a%3c Hotel Penn Sheraton is sold to Pittsburgh investors. Local 327 and Bartenders Union Local 188 reaches agreement with new owners.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 6, 1968%0a%3c Dr. Sidney Marland resigns as superintendent of the city school system and is succeeded by Bernard J. McCormick.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 11, 1968%0a%3c William K. Whiteford, retired chairman and chief executive of Gulf Oil Corp., killed in traffic accident.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 12, 1968%0a%3c State Supreme Court Justice Michael Angelo Musmanno 71, one of the prosecutors in the Nuremberg trials, dies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 16, 1969%0a%3c Pittsburgh Federation of Teachers reaches agreement preventing teachers strike in city schools.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 24, 1969%0a%3c The Democratic Policy Committee unanimously endorses Judge Harry Kramer to run for Democratic nomination for Mayor against City Councilman Peter Flaherty who announced his candidacy earlier.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 2, 1969%0a%3c John Tabor accepts Republican nomination for mayor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 28, 1969%0a%3c Pope Paul appoints Bishop John Wright of Pittsburgh a cardinal. He will be a member of the Curia at the Vatican.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 16, 1969%0a%3c Dr. Louis Kishkunas is named to succeed Dr. Bernard McCormick as schools superintendent.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 20, 1969%0a%3c Councilman Peter Flaherty wins Democratic nomination for mayor, in an upset victory against the Democratic machine.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 4, 1969%0a%3c Vincent M. Leonard, the auxiliary bishop to Wright becomes the new bishop of the Diocese.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 23, 1969%0a%3c Democratic majority commissioners approve PATs Skybus-PATway (Early Action) mass transit plans.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 9, 1969%0a%3c Danny Murtaugh named to manage Pittsburgh Pirates for the 1970 season.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 4, 1969%0a%3c Peter Flaherty elected mayor over Republican John Tabor. Cyril Wecht, lawyer-doctor, elected county coroner.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 30, 1969%0a%3c Penn Theater approved as new home for Pittsburgh Symphony.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1970%0a%3c January 2, 1970%0a%3c Mayor-elect Flaherty replaces Police Supt. James Slusser with Inspector Stephen Joyce. The city council holds over confirmation of Mayor Flahertys cabinet appointments: Joseph W. Cosetti for City Treasurer, Ralph Lynch, Jr. for City Solicitor and Bruce D. Campbell for Director of Lands and Buildings.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 7, 1970%0a%3c Flaherty, the new mayor, freezes city jobs.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 18, 1970%0a%3c The Flaherty administration fires 71 rank-and-file pay-rollers begins its austerity plan.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 2, 1970%0a%3c Flaherty threatens to close Pittsburgh Zoo.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 1, 1970%0a%3c Attorney John H. Bingler named Director of Public Safety.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 4, 1970%0a%3c Allison Krause of nearby Churchill was among four Kent State University students killed by National Guardsmen.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 3, 1970%0a%3c Richard King Mellon, 70, the key figure in Pittsburghs Renaissance, dies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 23, 1970%0a%3c Board of Public Education votes to abandon "Great High School" plans.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 16, 1970%0a%3c After many delays, the Three Rivers Stadium on Northside opens with Pirates losing to Cincinnati 3-2.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 27, 1970%0a%3c William R. Roesch named Jones and Laughlin Steel president and chief operating officer.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 11, 1970%0a%3c Robert J. Paternoster named City Planning Director; Bruce D. Campbell the interim planning director becomes Executive Secretary to the mayor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 13, 1970%0a%3c John F. Counahan, president of City Council, dies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 2, 1971%0a%3c The elimination of city truck drivers from driving plumbers to install water meters leads to a ten-day strike of the citys non-uniformed employees.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 17, 1971%0a%3c Pressmen at the Pittsburgh Press, on strike for twelve days, are back at work.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 4, 1971%0a%3c Thomas Kennelly succeeds Harry Keller as Fire Chief.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 10, 1971%0a%3c Mayor Flaherty replaces Stephen Joyce with Robert E. Colville, as superintendent of police.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 16, 1971%0a%3c Two police inspectors retire; demoted Joyce replaces one of them.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 17, 1971%0a%3c First moves toward correcting a system by which police collected unearned witness fees is taken by Robert Peirce, the new county clerk of courts.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 25, 1971%0a%3c Peirce announces the introduction of new witness-fee system.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 25, 1971%0a%3c U.S. Representative Robert Corbett, 65, who had represented the 18th district in Congress for half his lifetime, dies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 15, 1971%0a%3c Because of the pressmens strike at the Post-Gazette, both Pittsburghs daily newspapers cease to appear.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 10, 1971%0a%3c Heinz Hall for the Performing Arts opens.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 20, 1971%0a%3c John Bingler resigns as citys safety director, because he finds the position unnecessary. Henceforth, Mayor Flaherty will act as his own safety director.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 20, 1971%0a%3c In a July 28 letter the state Department of Commerce urged Flaherty to abandon his administrations support of the Mon Plaza site for the proposed convention center.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 21, 1971%0a%3c Allegheny County files suit to get back more than $41,000 in witness fees allegedly collected by 34 Pittsburgh policemen.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 22, 1971%0a%3c The Flaherty administration serves notice in court that it will resist any attempt by PAT to renovate the old Wabash Tunnel, which is a vital link to the Early Action phase of the Skybus lines to the South Hills.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 6, 1971%0a%3c Pittsburgh Pirates win National League pennant.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 6, 1971%0a%3c James Fulton, Dormont Republican, dies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 22, 1971%0a%3c In a defeat for the Mayor, city council votes unanimously in private caucus to throw full support behind PATs Early Action mass transit plan.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 26, 1971%0a%3c Robert R. Dorsey, president of Gulf Oil, will become chief executive officer of the company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 2, 1971%0a%3c In the election, Robert Duggan is re-elected district attorney. Republican William Hunt, a Skybus opponent, wins largest vote for county commissioner; Straisey and Foerster also re-elected. Robert Peirce, county clerk of courts by appointment, is also elected.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 8, 1971%0a%3c Mrs. Gladys McNairy, a black woman, elected president of the Pittsburgh Board of Public Education.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 23, 1971%0a%3c Danny Murtaugh, who retired as Pirate manager, is replaced by Bill Virdon.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 1, 1971%0a%3c Mayor Flaherty announces that the second annual surplus will allow a reduction in taxes.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 23, 1971%0a%3c County commissioners again refuse to hold a referendum on Skybus issue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 27, 1971%0a%3c PAT and the John F. Casey Company went to court to seek relief from malicious interference by the City of Pittsburgh to halt renovation of the Wabash Tunnel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 28, 1971%0a%3c Mayor Flaherty lifts tunnel blockade.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 10, 1972%0a%3c Flaherty, Commissioner William Hunt and the mayors of 14 communities file suit to enjoin PAT from spending any money on Early Action (Skybus) program until it complies with six specific legal requirements PAT allegedly ignored.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 12, 1972%0a%3c Flaherty, saying that the city must have tighter control over the Highland Park Zoo and aquarium, cancels all existing agreements with the Pittsburgh Zoological Society for the operation and maintenance of the facility.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 22, 1972%0a%3c PAT formally charges that anti-Skybus suit is a delaying tactic without legal foundation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 10, 1972%0a%3c Pittsburgh Zoological Society sues Mayor Flaherty to enjoin him from taking control of Zoo.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 16, 1972%0a%3c Common Pleas Court order re-establishes Zoological Society as operator of Highland Park Zoo.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 16, 1972%0a%3c Harold Joseph (Pie) Traynor, third baseman and former Pittsburgh Pirates star, dies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 6, 1972%0a%3c Arthur Van Buskirk, 76, leader in Pittsburghs postwar renaissance, dies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 13, 1972%0a%3c Eugene Coon elected Democratic party chairman of Allegheny County.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 8, 1972%0a%3c Skybus trial comes to an end after 69 days.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 10, 1972%0a%3c Carnegie-Mellon University chooses Dr. Richard Cyert as its sixth president.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 26, 1972%0a%3c J. F. Hillman, 83, prominent coal operator and philanthropist, dies. The survey of the American Insurance Association indicates that Pittsburghs fire protection services are the best since World War II.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 24, 1972%0a%3c Flood water crests at 35.82 feet, about eleven feet over flood level.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 17, 1972%0a%3c Commonwealth Court rules that the mayor must sign over to PAT parcels of land at both ends of the Wabash Tunnel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 24, 1972%0a%3c Judge Anne X. Alpern orders the halt of further spending on the Early Action transit program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 14, 1972%0a%3c Pittsburgh-born pianist Oscar Levant dies in Hollywood at the age of 65.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 3, 1972%0a%3c Gladys Schmitt, novelist and Carnegie-Mellon faculty member, dies at age 61.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 6, 1972%0a%3c Judge Alpern issues a permanent injunction halting financing and construction of the proposed rapid transit system. Decree moves case closer to final adjudication in the state Supreme Court.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 29, 1972%0a%3c Edgar B. Speer elected chairman of the board of US Steel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 1, 1972%0a%3c Mayor Flaherty announces that the 13.5 million surplus in 1972 will allow the elimination of the wage tax imposed in 1954, adjustment in the amusement tax and tax on parking lot operators. He also announces a 60 million dollar Capital Improvement Program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 31, 1972%0a%3c Roberto Clemente, Pirates outfielder, died in the crash of a cargo plane on mercy mission to Managua, Nicaragua.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 19, 1973%0a%3c The State Supreme Court by 6-1 vote overturns Judge Alperns injunction and puts Skybus back on the track.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 13, 1973%0a%3c City Councilman Richard Caliguiri announces candidacy for Democratic nomination for mayor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 24, 1973%0a%3c After Mayor Flahertys announcement that he will seek reelection, the Democratic city committee endorses Richard Caliguiri.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 15, 1973%0a%3c Flaherty wins both the Democratic and Republican nominations for re-election.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 24, 1973%0a%3c Federal grand jury opens investigation into business activities of Allegheny County District Attorney Robert W. Duggan.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 6, 1973%0a%3c Bill Virdon fired as Pirates manager; he will be succeeded by Danny Murtaugh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 12, 1973%0a%3c Mayor Flaherty unveils his transit plan, which will cost $82 million. He would utilize the existing rail lines and would upgrade trolley lines to southern suburbs.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 29, 1973%0a%3c Pittsburgh "numbers boss" Tony Grosso testifies that former county racket squads chief Samuel G. Ferraro had received payments from him.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 2, 1973%0a%3c Ferraro found guilty by federal jury; sentenced to six years in prison and a $30,000 fine.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 6, 1973%0a%3c Mayor Flaherty, Sheriff Coon, Coroner Wecht are re-elected.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 6, 1973%0a%3c It is revealed that District Attorney Duggan had married Cordelia Scaife May, a Mellon heiress, on August 29.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 9, 1973%0a%3c According to a Post-Gazette story, Duggans marriage took place less than a week after his new wife was to appear before the Internal Revenue Service. Duggan calls the newspaper story "sick."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 2, 1973%0a%3c Patrick Fagan, ex-city councilman, dies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 21, 1974%0a%3c The end of the Professional Theater at Pittsburgh Playhouse had been decided.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 30, 1974%0a%3c State Crime Commission charges that District Attorney Robert W. Duggan concealed $68,000 in contributions and expenditures, squeezed more than $36,000 from employees, and falsified election records in his 1971 re-election campaign. Duggan replies that the mistakes happened because of "poor bookkeeping practices."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 22, 1974%0a%3c Grand jury demands Duggans financial records.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 5, 1974%0a%3c Robert W. Duggan found dead in his Westmoreland County home. Not long after his death, the federal grand jury charges against him becomes known. He supposedly evaded $93,000 in income taxes.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 12, 1974%0a%3c The Westmoreland County coroner closes investigation of Duggans death without ruling.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 1, 1974%0a%3c Strike at the Post-Gazette and the Pittsburgh Press. For six weeks the city is without newspapers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 21, 1974%0a%3c In the primary, the home-rule charter for Allegheny County is defeated. Mayor Flaherty wins nomination for the senatorial race over ex-insurance commissioner Herbert S. Denenberg.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 13, 1974%0a%3c Gulf Building shaken by dynamite explosion, causing a million dollars damage. No one was hurt. A caller identifying himself as member of the terrorist Weather Underground said the bomb had been planted by his group. Another caller told Associated Press that the bombing was to protest Gulfs "racist policies" in the Portuguese colony of Angola.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 8, 1974%0a%3c James Higgins becomes board chairman of the Mellon National Corporation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 30, 1974%0a%3c Dedication of the Point State Park Fountain. After three decades of planning and construction, Point Park is finally completed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 5, 1974%0a%3c A smaller and cheaper Penn Central site between Ft. Duquesne Blvd. and Penn Avenue is recommended by Mayor Flaherty for the citys convention center.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 9, 1974%0a%3c President Ford visits Pittsburgh among cheers and boos -- booed for giving pardon to ex-President Nixon.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 27, 1974%0a%3c County Commissioner Thomas Foerster pronounces Sky-bus "deader than a doornail."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 15, 1974%0a%3c Urban Mass Transportation Administration says Skybus is feasible. It says local governments must resolve conflict over the plan or lose federal funds.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 25, 1974%0a%3c Colorful inaugural reception is held at the magnificent Sarah Scaife gallery in Oakland.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 5, 1974%0a%3c In the senatorial race, Peter Flaherty is defeated by incumbent GOP Senator Richard S. Schweiker.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 12, 1974%0a%3c Mayor Flaherty announces balanced budget for 1975. There wont be a tax increase.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 10, 1974%0a%3c City of Pittsburgh and Allegheny County settle their differences about the construction of the convention center; they will go jointly to the state agencies to seek approval of plan.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 9, 1975%0a%3c Mayor Flaherty increases exhibit space of proposed convention center from 104,000 to 135,000 square feet.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 12, 1975%0a%3c Steelers win Super Bowl in New Orleans, 16-6 over Minnesota Vikings. 10,000 people invade Downtown area after victory; 224 were arrested for drunkenness.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 19, 1975%0a%3c William Steinberg, because of ill health, resigns as Director of the Pittsburgh Symphony.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 31, 1975%0a%3c John Robin calls for independent engineering study of proposed mass-transit systems (rail vs. rubber tire).%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 3, 1975%0a%3c County Democratic chairman Eugene L. Coon calls for federal investigation of U.S. Atty. Richard L. Thornburgh, whom Coon says was motivated by partisan politics in his investigation of alleged official corruption.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 4, 1975%0a%3c PAT directors authorize creation of 8-member task force to develop independent engineering study. Mayor Flaherty, county commissioners included. Decision comes after Federal Urban Mass Transportation administrator Herringer sets deadline for new attempt to resolve mass-transit controversy.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 4, 1975%0a%3c Thornburgh defends himself against Coons charges of partisan politics.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 6, 1975%0a%3c NAACP, state attorney general and minority groups sue City of Pittsburgh charging race and sex discrimination in police hiring and promotion. Similar charges had been filed with regard to hiring in the Bureau of Fire in 1972 and subsequent year, charges which consequently were dismissed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 7, 1975%0a%3c The Mayor and county commissioners agree on convention center proposal. Proposal is for a 130,000 - 140,000 sq. foot site center on site bounded by Penn Avenue, Tenth Street and Ft. Duquesne Blvd.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 11, 1975%0a%3c I. W. Abel, United Steelworkers president who will retire in June of 1977, says he will refuse election to George Meanys job as head of AFL-CIO.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 14, 1975%0a%3c Staisey and Foerster announce they will run for renomination as county commissioners, as a team, in May 20 primary election.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 16, 1975%0a%3c Mayor Flaherty will cooperate with Allegheny Conference on Community Development in exploring possibilities for a 1984 Worlds Fair in Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 28, 1975%0a%3c Robert Coll replaces Robert Colville as Superintendent of Police. Colville resigned to run for the office of District Attorney.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 17, 1975%0a%3c Perle Mesta, the fabulous hostess, dies. She will be buried in Homewood Cemetery.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 9, 1975%0a%3c Port Authority Transit (PAT) begins construction route from Downtown through Mt. Washington Trolley Tunnel and up Sawmill Run Boulevard.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 21, 1975%0a%3c University of Pittsburgh receives $1 million from Japan Iron and Steel Federation as an endowment for Pitts Asian Studies Program. It would finance a rotating visiting professorship in Japanese studies and an Asian library.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 28, 1975%0a%3c Zoological Society will quit all operations by August 1, charging "senseless, irrational interference and harassment by City officials."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 4, 1975%0a%3c Mayor Flaherty plans three new structures in the Zoo to replace 80 year old main Zoo building.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 14, 1975%0a%3c Andre Previn appointed as the new Director of the Symphony.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 18, 1975%0a%3c The city administration hires Illinois firm of McFadzean and Everly to design new plan for Zoo.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 20, 1975%0a%3c Leonard Staisey denied renomination as county commissioner by Democratic voters. Ticket will be Thomas J. Forester and James Flaherty, brother of the Pittsburgh mayor. Republicans nominate Robert N. Peirce and Dr. William Hunt, incumbent GOP commissioner.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 21, 1975%0a%3c James Flaherty, the Mayors brother, and Thomas J. Foerster win in primary election for County Commissioners.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 25, 1975%0a%3c University of Pittsburgh School of Medicine will graduate Elaine Morris, the first black woman.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 3, 1975%0a%3c Jones and Laughlin will lay off 1200, bringing total to 2600 out of work at its Pittsburgh Works.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 4, 1975%0a%3c Mayor Flaherty and the State agree on a six-lane East Street Valley Expressway.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 9, 1975%0a%3c City policemen sent home for having long hair. They do eventually get it cut before returning to duty.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 16, 1975%0a%3c DeLeuw, Cather & Company will study Skybus concept. The firm of engineers chosen by Transit Task Force will receive for the study $446,745.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 20, 1975%0a%3c A great fire destroys part of Kennywood Amusement Park, causing $400,000 damage. Roadrunner, Ghost Ship and the 75 year old dance hall burn down.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 25, 1975%0a%3c David M. Roderick is elected President of United States Steel Corporation. He will replace W. A. Walker on August 1st.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 27, 1975%0a%3c As Teamsters Local 211 calls a strike, the City of Pittsburgh is without newspapers till July 28.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 3, 1975%0a%3c The top floors of the old Duquesne University Administration building are destroyed by fire, apparently caused by lightning.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 4, 1975%0a%3c Pittsburgh celebrates the countrys 199th birthday with fireworks and firecrackers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 27, 1975%0a%3c The month-long strike of teamsters against the Pittsburgh Press and Post-Gazette comes to an end.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 28, 1975%0a%3c The conviction of former State Senator Frank Mazzei on federal extortion charges is upheld by the Third Circuit Court of Appeal.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 7, 1975%0a%3c "Medic One" superambulance begins its operation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 21, 1975%0a%3c Jones and Laughlin Steel Corporation signs a $200 million pollution control agreement with the Environmental Protection Agency assuring J & Ls continued operation and jobs for its 6,000 workers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 30, 1975%0a%3c The wildcat strike by West Virginia and Western Pennsylvania coal miners spreads, in spite of union and court demands.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 8, 1975%0a%3c Pittsburgh School Board announces a $45 million school desegregation plan.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 25, 1975%0a%3c Governor Milton Shapp joins the race for the 1976 Democratic Presidential nomination.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 29, 1975%0a%3c Pittsburgh Symphony musicians go on strike for the first time in the orchestras 49-year history.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 8, 1975%0a%3c The School Board announces a 113 million dollar budget.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 30, 1975%0a%3c Radio Station KDKA and the Pittsburgh Pirates fire Bob Prince and Nellie King, their longtime baseball announcers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 5, 1975%0a%3c Control of the Board of County Commissioners is retained by the Democrats when Thomas Foerster and Jim Flaherty defeat their Republican opponents Robert Peirce and William Hunt.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 13, 1975%0a%3c The 46-day strike of the Symphony musicians ends.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 1, 1975%0a%3c City Public School teachers vote overwhelmingly for a strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 10, 1975%0a%3c H. John Heinz III announces his candidacy for the U.S. Senate.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 15, 1975%0a%3c Milo Hamilton is chosen as Pirate announcer, replacing Bob Prince.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 17, 1975%0a%3c At Three Rivers Stadium, the Steelers defeat the Baltimore Colts 28-10 in the Super Bowl play-off before a crowd of 50,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 30, 1975%0a%3c Gulf Oils own fact-finding committee confirms that the corporations executives had a multimillion dollar political "slush fund."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 8, 1976%0a%3c A 7-inch snowfall snarls traffic in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 12, 1976%0a%3c The striking teachers are ordered by the court to return to work.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 16, 1976%0a%3c The Steelers beat the Dallas Cowboys 21 to 17, retaining the title as World Champions. Three days later the city celebrates the victory in bitter cold weather with a downtown parade.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 26, 1976%0a%3c School strike ends; teachers ratify a compromise contract.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 27, 1976%0a%3c James R. Maloney becomes executive director of the Pittsburgh Port Authority (PAT).%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 1, 1976%0a%3c A 10 cent fare increase goes into effect on PAT buses and trolleys.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 12, 1976%0a%3c Governor Shapp withdraws as a Democratic Presidential candidate.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 19, 1976%0a%3c The two young daughters of banker Seward S. Mellon are abducted. Their abduction is a part of the battle between the banker and his wife.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 24, 1976%0a%3c City Civil Service Committee asks for the hiring of equal numbers of whites and minorities in the fire department.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 13, 1976%0a%3c The Pirates rout the St. Louis Cardinals 14-0 in the season opener with 40,937 fans in attendance at the Three Rivers Stadium.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 27, 1976%0a%3c City voters, by a 3 to 2 margin, retain an elected school board.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 12, 1976%0a%3c Demonstrators stage a sit-in at Rockwell International headquarters, protesting the corporations involvement with the B-I bomber.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 15, 1976%0a%3c Helped by a $5 million grant from the Allegheny Foundation, City authorities will rehabilitate the Pittsburgh and Lake Erie R.R. Station.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 25, 1976%0a%3c U.S. Steel Corporation will reduce the level of air pollution at its Clairton coke works.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 4, 1976%0a%3c A giant Bicentennial Fourth of July celebration with fireworks from atop the US Steel Building.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 9, 1976%0a%3c Jones and Laughlin will install new electric blast furnaces which will reduce pollution and increase productive capacity; it will also cost 700 jobs.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 13, 1976%0a%3c In a wildcat strike pickets close down the East Pittsburgh plant of Westinghouse Electric.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 18, 1976%0a%3c Two more unions representing 28,000 workers join a nationwide strike against Westinghouse.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 2, 1976%0a%3c Thirteen-year-old Terry Ford is killed in his Sewickley home when a bomb, intended for his brother, blows up in his face.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 5, 1976%0a%3c Most of the mines in the district are closed by a wildcat strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 27, 1976%0a%3c A federal grand jury indicts 38 district magistrates charging them with conspiracy and racketeering.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 3, 1976%0a%3c Two of the three Cleveland gunmen convicted of murdering UMW leader Jock Yablonski, his wife and daughter are sentenced to life imprisonment.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 15, 1976%0a%3c Governor Shapp signs an agreement with the Volkswagen Corporation of Germany ensuring the establishment of the firms American assembly plant at New Stanton.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 30, 1976%0a%3c Members of the States General Assembly receive a 20%25 pay raise, while the pay of the citys firemen raise, while the pay of the citys firemen is boosted by $1,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 1, 1976%0a%3c Duquesne Light Co. ask the Public Utility Commission for a rate increase which would raise the average residential electric bill by 31.6%25. Oct. 8, Mayor Flaherty orders all rookie policemen to walk the beat instead of riding in patrol cars.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 12, 1976%0a%3c The countys "flu clinics" close and an investigation is launched into the cases of three residents whose illnesses were related to their "swine flu" inoculations.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 28, 1976%0a%3c Assistant District Attorney Jo Ann DAriggo is dismissed from the courtroom by Judge Nicholas Papadakos who refused to hear her because she was dressed in a pant-suit.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 2, 1976%0a%3c In the presidential election of 1976 Democrat Jimmy Carter narrowly defeats Gerald Ford. H. John Heinz III  is successful in his Senate bid.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 17, 1976%0a%3c The State Superior Court upholds the legality of the Sunday "Blue" laws which prohibit most retail stores from doing business on Sunday.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 1, 1976%0a%3c Allegheny Countys mass transit system grinds to a halt as Port Authority Transit workers shut down all public transportation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 2, 1976%0a%3c A snowstorm snarls traffic.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 30, 1976%0a%3c A $600 million "cleanup" pact is signed by U.S. Steel and county and state officials. It provides for an extensive anti-pollution rehabilitation of the Clairton Coke Works.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 1, 1977%0a%3c Pitt Panthers beat Georgia 27-3 in the Sugar Bowl to tighten their grip on the 1977 National College Football Championship.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 17, 1977%0a%3c Record low temperatures of -17 F and gas shortages force the closing of the public school system.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 20, 1977%0a%3c A blast at Langley Hall on the University of Pittsburgh campus caused by a gas leak kills three and injures 22.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 23, 1977%0a%3c As ice-packed rivers rise to danger levels the river towns brace for floods.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 1, 1977%0a%3c A gaping crack threatening its collapse was found in the $50 million bridge on Interstate 1-79, which was completed in 1976 as part of the Bicentennial celebration.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 2, 1977%0a%3c Richard Karp, 94, musical director of the Pittsburgh Opera for 35 years dies of cancer in Montefiore Hospital.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 9, 1977%0a%3c In the election for president of the United Steelworkers of America, AFL-CIO Lloyd McBride, the organization candidate, turns back Edward Sadlowski, the candidate of the rank and file reform movement.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 18, 1977%0a%3c Four city policemen who moonlighted as "security guards" at a North Side "pornography warehouse" are suspended.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 21, 1977%0a%3c President Carter names Pittsburgh Mayor Pete Flaherty as Deputy U.S. Attorney General.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 25, 1977%0a%3c George E. Lee, whose massage parlor operations are under investigation, shot dead in a parking lot on Seventh Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 8, 1977%0a%3c City Democrats choose County Commissioner Thomas J. Foerster for Mayor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 1, 1977%0a%3c An Oakland cobbler arrested for bookmaking invented an ingenious method for taking bets. He wrote them on the soles of shoes which he repaired.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 9, 1977%0a%3c A tentative three-year contract which includes some lifetime income security is approved by the Steelworkers Union.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 11, 1977%0a%3c Richard S. Caliguiri is sworn in as Mayor in City Hall, replacing Pete Flaherty who resigned.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 25, 1977%0a%3c Eleanor Cutri Smeal, a housewife from Mt. Lebanon, is elected president of the National Organization of Women.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 10, 1977%0a%3c Striking Teamsters block installation of voting machines for the upcoming primary elections.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 17, 1977%0a%3c Thomas Foerster wins the Democratic Mayoral primary and prepares to campaign against Joseph Cosetti, the Republican nominee and Richard Caliguiri who runs on the independent ticket.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 20, 1977%0a%3c The nude body of 18-year-old Brenda Lee Ritter is found on a bill, the fourth young woman to be slain in Washington County during the past six months.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 21, 1977%0a%3c Thirty-nine suspected heroin pushers are arrested in a drug bust.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 25, 1977%0a%3c Flooding and explosions kill 45 people in Johnstown.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 27, 1977%0a%3c The Board of Education rejects a plan to reinstate corporal punishment in the citys schools, a measure backed by the Teachers Union.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 1, 1977%0a%3c The strike of 14,000 steelworkers is the first major walkout in the basic steel industry during the past eighteen years.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 7, 1977%0a%3c Seventeen prisoners escape from the Allegheny County jail.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 19, 1977%0a%3c Thousands of state employees, including guards at several prisons and aides in hospitals, join a "sick out," protesting the states failure to pay their salaries because of the budget crisis in Harrisburg.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 20, 1977%0a%3c The state budget is passed and paychecks go out to state employees.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 26, 1977%0a%3c The PAT board, by an 11-1 vote, approves application for $93 million in federal funds to construct a $110 million busway from downtown to the eastern suburbs.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 8, 1977%0a%3c The report by Sheriff Eugene 'Gene' Coon about the deterioration of the County jail stirs the prison board into approving sweeping reforms.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 19, 1977%0a%3c Jones and Laughlin Corporation lays off some 500 workers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 29, 1977%0a%3c West View Park, an amusement attraction for over four decades, will close its doors.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 6, 1977%0a%3c Over the next six months U.S. Steel intends to lay off 4,500 of its white collar employees.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 8, 1977%0a%3c In the mayoral election Richard Caliguiri defeats Thomas Foerster. Democrats sweep the contested City Council seats.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 14, 1977%0a%3c Mayor Caliguiri announces plans for a no-tax-hike budget and for the beginning of "Renaissance II," to revitalize the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 16, 1977%0a%3c Massage parlor operator Anthony Robert Pugh is found shot to death at his suburban apartment. Dec. 27 Webster Hall Hotel, a landmark in Oakland, will be converted into luxury apartments.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 20, 1978%0a%3c Another big snowfall made January the snowiest month since the "Big Snow" of 1950.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 22, 1978%0a%3c Former Mayor Pete Flaherty announces his Democratic candidacy for Governor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 24, 1978%0a%3c A blizzard strikes the area, knocking out power and disrupting telephone service. Rivers crest two feet below flood level at the Point.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 29, 1978%0a%3c UMW President Arnold Miller declares that the miners strike might go on indefinitely.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 6, 1978%0a%3c UMW strikers stage a large rally downtown; they demonstrate before the U.S. Steel and Duquesne Light buildings.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 27, 1978%0a%3c Thirty-five-year-old Phyllis Wyberg, from the North Side, becomes the third million dollar winner in the Pennsylvania lottery.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 1, 1978%0a%3c Bus driver Rosie Lee and her passengers are routed from their No. 87 Ardmore bus by a rat.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 2, 1978%0a%3c A large group of truck drivers stage a slowdown to protest the huge potholes on 1-70 between the Turnpike and the Pennsylvania border.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 6, 1978%0a%3c UMW rank and file rejects a proposed contract; President Carter invokes the Taft-Hartley Act; miners must return to work.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 7, 1978%0a%3c The miners vow to defy the Taft-Hartley injunction.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 14, 1978%0a%3c Jennifer Lee Wesner, a former topless model, draws the top spot in the Democratic primary for governor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 17, 1978%0a%3c School officials confiscate knives, guns, baseball bats and an ax after a racial brawl at Brashear High School.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 25, 1978%0a%3c Area miners prepare to return to work under a new contract which they first opposed but which had been accepted by the majority of the UMWs members.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 28, 1978%0a%3c Schenley High Schools Spartans win the Pennsylvania Triple A Basketball Championship, defeating Lebanon High 5 1-50 at Hershey, Pa.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 30, 1978%0a%3c The state government authorizes over $55 million in federal, state and local funds to pay for the first phase of the proposed East Bus-way in Allegheny County.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 4, 1978%0a%3c The City Council overrides Mayor Caliguiris veto of an antipornography referendum designed to provide a mandate for "cleaning up" Liberty Avenue and other pornography retail areas.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 6, 1978%0a%3c The FBI and the District Attorneys Office begin their investigation of Community Action Pittsburgh, the Agency which is dispensing federal anti-poverty funds.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 9, 1978%0a%3c The majority in the county commission votes against putting the anti -pornography referendum on the May 16 primary ballot.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 23, 1978%0a%3c PennDot seeks a three-year guarantee from all asphalt contractors.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 16, 1978%0a%3c William Steinberg, 78, music director emeritus of the Pittsburgh Symphony who was conductor of the Symphony for more than a quarter century, dies in New York.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 17, 1978%0a%3c Peter Flaherty and Richard Thornburgh win the respective Democratic and Republican gubernatorial nominations.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 23, 1978%0a%3c After being pinned by his legs for two hours atop the Brady Street Bridge, a screaming construction worker is freed by a physician who climbs to the top of the bridge and amputates his leg.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 6, 1978%0a%3c Bail Bondsman David Wander and Edward Reddington are convicted on a sex-blackmail scheme against County Commissioner Robert N. Peirce.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 19, 1978%0a%3c Mayor Caliguiri, speaking before the U.S. Conference of Mayors, throws his support behind a plan which would make it easier for cities to annex their suburbs.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 27, 1978%0a%3c State legislature approves the death penalty.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 5, 1978%0a%3c Nathaniel Rosen, the Pittsburgh Symphonys first cellist, wins the Tschaikovsky Gold Medal in Moscow.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 5, 1978%0a%3c Edward Suratt, wanted for two murders, is arrested in Florida.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 6, 1978%0a%3c A major urban renewal project in Market Square will be spearheaded by the 40-story Pittsburgh Plate Glass Building.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 6, 1978%0a%3c The Greater Pittsburgh Airport reports a $2.3 million profit.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 8, 1978%0a%3c Parkway East is "papered" with money for the second consecutive day, with an accident littering a mile-long stretch with canceled Series E government savings bonds. The day before, a collision with a messenger's car causes scores of welfare checks to be strewn on the road.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 11, 1978%0a%3c The State Supreme Court unanimously upholds a Commonwealth Court order requiring the city to submit a desegregation plan to the Pennsylvania Human Relations Commission before fall, 1979.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 15, 1978%0a%3c Parents and community groups charge the city School Board with promoting a racially segregated system.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 7, 1978%0a%3c Thomas Ware, a city detective with fifteen years service, is charged with the murder of a city fireman in the Hill District.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 21, 1978%0a%3c Edward Suratt of Aliquippa, already charged with three murders and a suspect in 17 others, is convicted of the rape of a woman and her daughter in Vilano Beach, Florida.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 25, 1978%0a%3c Northview Heights public housing project wins a $10 million federal grant to rehabilitate its deteriorating North Side complex.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 23, 1978%0a%3c The federal government charges Westinghouse Corporation with making false statements to cover up overseas bribery.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 2, 1978%0a%3c Pittsburgh is allocated $23.9 million and Allegheny County $27.19 million to operate the Comprehensive Employment and Training Act (CETA) programs in the coming fiscal year.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 8, 1978%0a%3c Richard Thornburgh upsets Peter Flaherty by 200,000 votes to become Governor of Pennsylvania. In 25 Congressional races, the Democrats lose three seats and gain one. Allegheny County voters overwhelmingly reject a home rule charter.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 28, 1978%0a%3c Sixteen-year-old Dorene Crawford is shot to death in the stairway of her Terrace Village apartment. City homicide detectives search for her boyfriend, twenty-six-year-old Fred Mahaffey.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 13, 1978%0a%3c Alcoa Corporation intends to spend $5.1 million on an "extensive renovation" of the William Penn Hotel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 23, 1978%0a%3c "Lonesome George," the Pittsburgh Zoos only gorilla, dies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 31, 1978%0a%3c The Steelers defeat the Denver Broncos 33-10 before a crowd of 48,921 and advance to the final game of the Championship, Super Bowl XIII.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 4, 1979%0a%3c The sexually assaulted and strangled body of Monica Renee Jones, an 18-year-old Pitt coed, is found in the basement of her dormitory.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 16, 1979%0a%3c Governor Richard Thornburgh is sworn in in Harrisburg, pledging "integrity, frugality, simplicity and humanity."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 19, 1979%0a%3c Members of the Fraternal Association of Steel Handlers (FASH) vote to end their violence-torn strike as a result of a court-ordered injunction.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 22, 1979%0a%3c The Steelers defeat the Dallas Cowboys 35-31 in Miami to return their World Championship title for a third consecutive year.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 26, 1979%0a%3c Duquesne Light, having just implemented a billing increase, announces another which will increase the average monthly electric bill by $5.70.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 2, 1979%0a%3c An estimated 7,000 fans join in a Steelers victory celebration at Market Square.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 11, 1979%0a%3c Controller John P. Lynch begins an investigation of the county morgue in connection with private bank accounts used for deposit of cut-of-county autopsy receipts.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 5, 1979%0a%3c Controller John P. Lynch indicates that Coroner Cyril Wecht and members of his staff might be liable under theft of service statutes for the private autopsy work which they performed at the county morgue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 7, 1979%0a%3c The $10.8 billion state budget will he financed in part by an increase in the gasoline tax.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 14, 1979%0a%3c According to the countys law department, Coroner Wechts private autopsy work was illegal.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 28, 1979%0a%3c A cooling failure in the Three-Mile Island nuclear plant results in its shutdown as radiation begins leaking in the Harrisburg area. Pittsburghers worry about the implications for nuclear facilities in the city and its vicinity%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 4, 1979%0a%3c 3,500 Volkswagen workers at New Stanton are laid off.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 15, 1979%0a%3c An investigating grand jury will crack down on the massage parlor industry.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 18, 1979%0a%3c Police and paramedics work for more than 373 hours to free a driver from his wrecked truck which hung precariously from a Fort Pitt Bridge ramp.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 30, 1979%0a%3c Steel trucks begin to roll as steel haulers vote to end their three-week strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 1, 1979%0a%3c The strike at the Pittsburgh Brewing Company stops the production of Iron City Beer.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 7, 1979%0a%3c The federal government formally commits $265 million to PAT for the proposed light-rail transit system that will connect the South Hills with Downtown.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 10, 1979%0a%3c The unexplained failure of a 23,000-volt line ignites sewer gas, touching off a series of electrical explosions, setting overhead wires on fire and knocking out power in 25,000 East End homes.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 4, 1979%0a%3c The U.S. Attorneys office loses its second major Medicare fraud case when a federal judge acquits Dr. Leonard Merkow of Squirrel Hill.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 9, 1979%0a%3c An Erie jury finds former Allegheny County Manpower director Robert L. Hawkins guilty of payroll frauds totaling $80,000.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 21, 1979%0a%3c Independent truckers launch a nationwide shutdown; gunfire erupts on the highways.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 25, 1979%0a%3c Shots are fired at produce trucks on a highway near the city, as the striking truckers attempt to shut down the shipment of food.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 28, 1979%0a%3c The strike by service station owners, resulting in long lines at the few open stations, lulls. A new 'odd-even' gas rationing plan eases the run on gasoline.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 3, 1979%0a%3c Hope fades for an early resolution of the state budget deadlock which has already ended payments to thousands of state workers and families on welfare.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 8, 1979%0a%3c Theodore L. Hazlett, President of the A. W. Mellon Educational and Charitable Trust, and the legal architect of the citys Renaissance, dies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 14, 1979%0a%3c Only 11%25 of the areas service stations are open. Pittsburgh motorists are hit hard by the shutdown of the independent station operators.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 16, 1979%0a%3c An eleventh-hour attempt by federal mediators fails to avert a strike by 38,000 Westinghouse workers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 25, 1979%0a%3c The City Council gives preliminary approval to a P.P.G. Industries plan to build its $100 million headquarters in Market Square, but area merchants are fighting the plan.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 2, 1979%0a%3c An 11-year-old girl and her teenage panderer are arrested on a downtown street on prostitution charges.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 3, 1979%0a%3c A woman jogger told police she was attacked under Panther Hollow Bridge near the area where Carol Jursik, a Pittsburgh University graduate student, disappeared.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 7, 1979%0a%3c The body of Carol Jursik is found. Her murderer is never apprehended.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 15, 1979%0a%3c Allegheny County Health Agency might lose $197,000 in federal air pollution aid as a result of bureaucratic bungling.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 4, 1979%0a%3c Mt. Lebanon schools are the latest to be closed in a rash of teachers strikes affecting more than 30,000 pupils in ten Western Pennsylvania school districts.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 11, 1979%0a%3c Lawyers, businessmen and office workers are routed from the Law and Finance Building, as flames race through its 14th floor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 17, 1979%0a%3c The illegal numbers racket is doing well in spite of the state lotterys success.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 6, 1979%0a%3c The Pirates win the National League pennant by defeating the Cincinnati Reds 7-1 at Three Rivers Stadium.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 9, 1979%0a%3c Over strong objections by two city school directors, the school board held its fifth closed meeting of the year on desegregation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 11, 1979%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Pirates defeat the Baltimore Orioles 3-2 in the second game of the World Series.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 12, 1979%0a%3c A tentative agreement is reached in the six-weeks-old Mt. Lebanon school teachers strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 13, 1979%0a%3c Edgar B. Speer, President of U.S. Steel Corporation, dies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 16, 1979%0a%3c The Pirates tie up the World Series 3-3 by beating the Orioles 4-0.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 17, 1979%0a%3c The Pirates defeat the Baltimore Orioles 4-1 to win the 1979 World Series.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 19, 1979%0a%3c 25,000 fans welcome the World Champion Pirates at Market Square.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 22, 1979%0a%3c Coroner Cyril Wecht files a seven million dollar suit against Controller John P. Lynch because of Lynchs alleged defamatory remarks on a radio show.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 25, 1979%0a%3c The crash of a PAT bus on Center Avenue injures forty people. A massive probe into Pittsburgh organized crime is launched by state and local authorities.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 2, 1979%0a%3c The Hillman Company was to take back a chemically contaminated Ohio River Park site on Neville Island which the firm had donated to the county in 1976.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 7, 1979%0a%3c Democrats are assured control of the County Board of Commissioners as Thomas J. Foerster and Cyril Wecht are elected to majority seats on the Board. Most of the other county offices in the election were also won by Democrats.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 13, 1979%0a%3c Mayor Caliguiri asks the City Council for a 1%25 wage tax hike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 26, 1979%0a%3c The State Human Relations Commission allows the Pittsburgh School Board 18 days to submit a plan for desegregating.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 27, 1979%0a%3c U.S. Steel announces massive cuts in production; 13,000 jobs will be lost, 1,800 of them in Western Pennsylvania.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 1, 1979%0a%3c State Labor and Industry Secretary Charles J. Lieberth declares that Pennsylvania would have to borrow $350 million from the federal government to cope with the projected layoffs by U.S. Steel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 5, 1979%0a%3c Moments after the newly-elected Pittsburgh School Board takes office, its members agree to begin school desegregation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 10, 1979%0a%3c The Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Corporation presents its employees with an ultimatum: accept cuts in their "excessive" incentive pay or see the firms Allenport plant closed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 14, 1979%0a%3c Controller Lynch asks for the dismissal of Coroner Wechts lawsuit against him.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 28, 1979%0a%3c Workers at U.S. Steels Ambridge Works vote to accept a paycut in order to keep the plant from closing.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 31, 1979%0a%3c The City Council overrides Mayor Caliguiris veto of its 28-mill land tax increase.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 1980%0a%3c January 7, 1980%0a%3c The Steelers dump the Houston Oilers 27-13 to get their fourth shot at the Super Bowl.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 9, 1980%0a%3c The newly installed County Commissioner Cyril Wecht announces his resignation as County Coroner.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 14, 1980%0a%3c A large crowd sends the Steelers off to their fourth consecutive Super Bowl game in Miami.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 20, 1980%0a%3c The "Super Steelers" rally three times in a close contest to defeat the Los Angeles Rams 31-19 and win Super Bowl XIV, the fourth Super Bowl victory in six years.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 23, 1980%0a%3c University of Pittsburgh students make hundreds of dollars worth of free long distance calls when the pay phones in a dormitory lobby malfunction.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 30, 1980%0a%3c U.S. Steel reported a loss of $293 million, the largest quarterly decline in the firms history.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 1, 1980%0a%3c A jury orders the electrocution of Bennie Graves, a Homewood-Brushton man convicted in the strangulation killing of two children for whom he had been babysitting.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 6, 1980%0a%3c Contract negotiations continue between the United Steelworkers and the "Big 9" companies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 8, 1980%0a%3c PATs Board of Directors approve a 10 cents fare increase.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 11, 1980%0a%3c Robert L. Hawkins, Jr., former Allegheny County Manpower Director, receives a 6-1/2-year prison sentence and is ordered to pay a $10,000 fine and $79,000 restitution on 83 counts of payroll fraud.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 17, 1980%0a%3c A Carnegie Mellon University study asserts that the outlook for the steel industry in Pittsburgh is brighter than expected because the firms will invest $1.1 billion dollars updating equipment, building new facilities and installing environmental controls.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 18, 1980%0a%3c A record number of speakers and spectators packed the school boards public hearing to oppose the boards desegregation plan.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 21, 1980%0a%3c Six days before the deadline set by the state Human Relations Commission, the school board remains divided over desegregation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 28, 1980%0a%3c The County Commissioners offered a $18.3 million plan to line the Allegheny River with parks.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 1, 1980%0a%3c PAT bus and trolley fares are raised 10 cents despite a last-ditch court battle by a community group.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 4, 1980%0a%3c Dozens of couples line-up in the pouring rain for more than 24 hours at the doors of the Catholic Social Services of Allegheny County in the hope of adopting children.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 10, 1980%0a%3c Penn Dots "pot hole patching team" begins its season under a new Director, District Engineer Roger Carrier.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 8, 1980%0a%3c Senator Edward Kennedy, campaigning at the Cyclops Steel Corporation plant in Bridgeville, accuses President Carter of reneging on his promise to protect steel jobs.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 11, 1980%0a%3c A State Supreme Court Justice orders a halt to P.P.G. Industries $100 million downtown development plan until the court can decide on the legal issues raised by five Market Square merchants opposing the plan.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 14, 1980%0a%3c Vice President Mondale attacks the policies of Senator Kennedy in a campaign visit to the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 15, 1980%0a%3c Leaders of the United Steelworkers ratify a 3-year contract providing an estimated $2.85 hike in wages and fringe benefits.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 17, 1980%0a%3c Senator Kennedy, Republican candidate George Bush and Rosalyn Carter are in the Pittsburgh area campaigning for votes in the Pennsylvania presidential primary.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 19, 1980%0a%3c Jail terms and fines against striking Western Penitentiary guards are ordered by a Commonwealth Court judge.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 22, 1980%0a%3c The federal Nuclear Regulatory Commission declares that a low-level radioactive leak, at a nuclear plant in nearby Shippingport is not dangerous.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 23, 1980%0a%3c In the Pennsylvania presidential primary, George Bush defeats Ronald Reagan and Senator Edward Kennedy wins over President Carter.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 10, 1980%0a%3c The steel lay-offs might reach 60,000 by September.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 22, 1980%0a%3c Penn Dot announces that an $8 million reconstruction project on the Parkway West will begin in June.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 27, 1980%0a%3c U.S. Steel will temporarily shut down its third and last furnace at the Edgar Thomson Works in Braddock.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 31, 1980%0a%3c Oxford Development Company reveals plans for a 46-story $100 million office-commercial building on Grant Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 19, 1980%0a%3c Independent presidential candidate John Anderson campaigns in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 21, 1980%0a%3c The six-week strike by moving van drivers ends.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 25, 1980%0a%3c The School Board announces a lay-off of 141 teachers as a result of declining enrollment, low attrition and the pending desegregation plan.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 26, 1980%0a%3c Oliver Tyrone Corporation will build a 20-story office tower at Stanwix Street.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 27, 1980%0a%3c The PAT board reveals plans for a downtown transit center at the old B&O railroad depot.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 30, 1980%0a%3c Unemployment in the area reaches 7.8%25.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 18, 1980%0a%3c An agreement between the Market Square merchants and the PPG Industries is made. The merchants will get space for their stores elsewhere. The agreement clears the way for the construction of the PPG skyscraper.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 18, 1980%0a%3c The State Human Relations Commission asks the Commonwealth Court to stop the city's Board of Education from implementing its desegregation plan.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 21, 1980%0a%3c On the first day of the draft registration, there is widespread vandalism at the citys post offices.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 24, 1980%0a%3c The Commonwealth Court rules against school desegregation, paving the way for the school board bussing plan.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 27, 1980%0a%3c The University Health Center announces a $250 million expansion plan for the city hospitals.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 6, 1980%0a%3c Richard Wallace is named city school superintendent.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 18, 1980%0a%3c Leland Hazard -- the philosopher at the Pittsburgh Renaissance -- dies at the age of 87. His autobiography "Attorney for the Situation" was published in 1975.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 20, 1980%0a%3c U.S. Steel will recall 800 furloughed employees to the Edgar Thompson works.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 31, 1980%0a%3c The 28-year old Canton House one of the citys great hotel buildings, is demolished, to make way for the Dravo skyscraper which later was named One Mellon Center.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 2, 1980%0a%3c Desegregation plan affecting 12,000 students begins.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 4, 1980%0a%3c The County Grand Jury recommends the filing of six criminal charges against County Commissioner Cyril Wecht, who allegedly used the morgue when he was coroner "to the benefit of his private laboratory."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 8, 1980%0a%3c "I have not committed any crime or engaged in any misconduct" responds Wecht to the charges.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 12, 1980%0a%3c PAT approves a 15-cent increase in base transit fares.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 19, 1980%0a%3c An investigating grand jury determines that the April 24: drawing of the Daily Number "666" has been fixed. Six persons including WTAE-TVs popular Nick Perry are charged with conspiracy.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 29, 1980%0a%3c Gipsy, the monkey, an escapee from the Zoo for over a week, pelts officers who try to capture him with a barrage of crabapples.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 4, 1980%0a%3c Sihugo "Si" Green, who played on the Duquesne University basketball team, which won the national invitation tournament in 1955, dies of cancer at the age of 46.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 29, 1980%0a%3c Urban Redevelopment Authority designates Grant Liberty Development Corporation to build a $26 million hotel complex across from the Convention Center.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 5, 1980%0a%3c Former California Governor and movie actor Ronald Reagan defeats President Carter in the presidential election. Republican Arlen Specter is elected to the U.S. Senate. Leroy Zimmermann wins the race for the State Attorney General.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 10, 1980%0a%3c Mayor Richard Caliguiri announces a balance budget for 1981 without raising taxes.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 13, 1980%0a%3c J&L Steel will close the continuous strip and sheet department of its Pittsburgh works. Thousands of steelworkers will lose their jobs.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 6, 1980%0a%3c A contaminated water system leaves 20,000 South Hills residents without fresh water.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 17, 1980%0a%3c The Mellon Stuart Company announces the construction of office building for its headquarters In the North Shore.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 18, 1980%0a%3c A grand jury identifies WTAE-TVs personality Nick Perry as the planner of the $1.8 million lottery fix. Perry supposedly netted $35,000 as his share of the winnings.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 19, 1980%0a%3c Allegheny Countys 1981 budget includes a 5-mill increase in the real estate tax.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 21, 1980%0a%3c The playwright Marc Connelly, best known for his play The Green Pastures, dies at the age of 90. He was born in McKeesport.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 21, 1980%0a%3c Allegheny Ludlum Steel is purchased by a local investment group for $195 million.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 29, 1981%0a%3c Gulf Oil settles its fight with Westinghouse over monopolistic activities with a payment of $25 million.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 3, 1981%0a%3c Mayor Caliguiri plans to increase the citys $10 annual occupation tax to $40.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 7, 1981%0a%3c The David L. Lawrence Convention Center opens with a ribbon-cutting ceremony.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 13, 1981%0a%3c Duquesne Light receives from the Public Utility Commission the approval of a $47.5 million annual rate increase.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 20, 1981%0a%3c The 13-week strike of the Steel Valley teachers comes to an end, enabling 2,700 pupils to return to the classrooms.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 24, 1981%0a%3c The Pirate organization files suit for the annulment of their 40-year lease with the Three Rivers Stadium Authority.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 2, 1981%0a%3c After the state Supreme Court refused to allow Dr. Joshua A. Paper to keep his post, Sanford H. Edberg becomes Allegheny County Coroner.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 3, 1981%0a%3c Penn-DOT launches a two-year construction program for Parkway East.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 15, 1981%0a%3c Plans for 400 condominiums and apartments, 60,000 square feet of office and retail space, and a 600-car parking garage are proposed for Mt. Washington. The development will cost $60 million.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 18, 1981%0a%3c Because of a wildcat strike, twelve Southwestern Pennsylvania coalmines are closed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 14, 1981%0a%3c Striking Mesta Machine Company workers end their 45-day walkout at the West Homestead plant.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 16, 1981%0a%3c According to a grand jury report the Allegheny County Jail was a haven of administrative corruption, drug trafficking, sexual assaults during the five-year administration of former warden James Jennings.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 27, 1981%0a%3c Mayor Caliguiri sues the city of New Orleans and the Louisiana Superdome in Federal Court to stop interference with Pittsburghs contract dispute with the Pirates.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 28, 1981%0a%3c A federal judge orders the school districts of Churchill, Edgewood, Swissvale, Turtle Creek and General Braddock to consolidate their desegregation plans.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 17, 1981%0a%3c After the 380 striking employees of the Pittsburgh Brewing Company accepted the companys offer, the only remaining brewery in the city will continue operations.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 18, 1981%0a%3c Striking United Mine Workers block the entrances to the headquarters of Consolidation Coal Company in Upper St. Clair.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 19, 1981%0a%3c Former coroner Cyril Wecht is acquitted of the charges that he used the city morgue for private gain.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 19, 1981%0a%3c A new building and fire code is passed by the City Council. Houses in Pittsburgh must install smoke alarms.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 20, 1981%0a%3c The voters of Allegheny County approve a plan for a harness racing track.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 26, 1981%0a%3c Common places Court orders PAT to roll back base fare to 60 cents and transfers to 10 cents; also to realign bus and trolley zones and eliminate all savings on pass purchases.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 28, 1981%0a%3c A fire at a Lawrenceville industrial building forces the closing of the 62nd Street Bridge.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 29, 1981%0a%3c End of the twenty-two-day-old strike by county employees.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 31, 1981%0a%3c End of the fifty-day-old major league baseball strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 5, 1981%0a%3c Thousands of air traffic controllers across the country (including 58 from Pittsburgh) get their pink slips after defying the Presidents back-to- work-order.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 20, 1981%0a%3c As part of an adjustment to population changes, three Allegheny County House seats are eliminated by the Reappointment Commission in Harrisburg.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 25, 1981%0a%3c Mayor Caliguiri proposes a 15 percent cut in capital spending for 1982. Inflation hits 19.2%25 for July.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 4, 1981%0a%3c PAT eliminates buses dinning between 1:30 A.M. and 5 A.M. With this the "night coach era" coach era comes to an end.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 8, 1981%0a%3c A school desegregation plan combines five east suburban districts into one.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 11, 1981%0a%3c Six thousand Nabisco women employees are awarded $5 million in damages against the company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 3, 1981%0a%3c The federal governments plan to build 100 B-I bombers by Rockwell International will add $400 million to the company's profits in the next seven years.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 10, 1981%0a%3c The eight-block area between the Monongahela River and the Boulevard of the Allies (from Grant to Stanwix Streets) is proposed to become Firstside.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 16, 1981%0a%3c Dr. Joshua Perper is cleared of perjury charges.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 21, 1981%0a%3c Governor Thornburgh's proposed private enterprise liquor store system fails in its first test vote.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 28, 1981%0a%3c Governor Thornburgh and Mayor Caliguiri announce that two of the four "missing link" highways will be built. The East Street and North Shore Expressways get the green light. Crosstown Boulevard and North Hills Expressway will be built later.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 4, 1981%0a%3c Mayor Caliguiri is reelected, the Democratic Party keeps their domination in Pittsburgh and in Allegheny County.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 24, 1981%0a%3c Governor Thornburgh vetoes Abortion bill.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 29, 1981%0a%3c The citys budget for 1982 will be $229 million.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 6, 1982%0a%3c Rand McNallys Places Rated Almanac, names Pittsburgh as the third most livable city in the country.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 7, 1982%0a%3c U.S. Steel obtains 51 percent of Marathon Oil stock.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 7, 1982%0a%3c The budget of the state government is $13 billion.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 8, 1982%0a%3c At the Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Company, 40%25 of the work force is laid off.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 10, 1982%0a%3c The Crucible Steel Plant in Beaver County is up for sale.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 19, 1982%0a%3c Penn-DOT asks a federal court to free $302 million in highway funds frozen by a judge because the state failed to put an auto emissions inspection program into effect. Twenty-four hours later the freeze is lifted.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 17, 1982%0a%3c The cost of living in the city is ranked $700 below the national average in a year.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 20, 1982%0a%3c The citys public schools are ordered to improve the racial balance in three high schools and ten elementary schools.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 25, 1982%0a%3c Federal prosecutors investigate bid-rigging and anti-trust violations by contractors who were handling public roadway work in Western Pennsylvania.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 19, 1982%0a%3c State police and city detectives complete a large sting operation. They arrest fifty people in connection with a stolen goods operation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 8, 1982%0a%3c Colt Industries will sell its Crucible Stainless & Alloy Division in Midland to Cyclops Corporation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 16, 1982%0a%3c Ground is broken for the East Street Valley Expressway.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 18, 1982%0a%3c The city asks additional millions in taxes to improve Three Rivers Stadium so the Pirates can be kept in Pittsburgh. $11 million will be needed to renovate the stadium.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 29, 1982%0a%3c Allegheny Ludlum will spend $12 million on modern equipment at its West Leechburg plant as a trade-off for contract concessions from its employees.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 17, 1982%0a%3c A 150,000-pound drill press falls off a truck on the Parkway West and levels a Scott Township house.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 21, 1982%0a%3c The City Council gives a tentative approval to the proposed takeover of Three Rivers Stadium by the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 22, 1982%0a%3c Colt Industries refuses to sell its crucible plant to Cyclops Corporation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 26, 1982%0a%3c A last-minute contract settlement averts a nationwide strike by 30,000 Westinghouse employees, half of them Pittsburgh residents.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 29, 1982%0a%3c Colt Industries begins closing its Crucible Steel Plant. 400 employees will lose their jobs.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 29, 1982%0a%3c The USW rejects the steel industrys plea for concessions from 300,000 basic steel employees.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 2, 1982%0a%3c Mellon Bank agrees to merge with Girard, a Philadelphia holding company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 3, 1982%0a%3c Toxic waste halts the construction of Bloomfield Bridge.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 27, 1982%0a%3c The basic fee for riding PAT buses and trolleys will be raised to $1 beginning October 3, 1982.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 31, 1982%0a%3c Mayor Caliguiri announces a six-year, $504 million capital spending plan that stresses street, bridge, water and sewage systems.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 9, 1982%0a%3c After more than a decade of planning, the redevelopment of the North Shore begins.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 14, 1982%0a%3c Common Pleas Judge Silvestri refuses to order the McKeesport Area School District to resume the busing of 1,900 high school students.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 24, 1982%0a%3c The National Football League players go on strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 6, 1982%0a%3c State police in Homewood arrest 25 people involved in drug operation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 20, 1982%0a%3c Carnegie-Mellon University concludes an agreement with IBM to become an experimental computer center, with more than 20,000 PCs.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 25, 1982%0a%3c A desegregation plan is agreed to by city schools.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 26, 1982%0a%3c After 20 months of repairs costing $58 million, the Parkway is at last open to full traffic.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 27, 1982%0a%3c US Steel has an $82 million loss in its third quarter and cuts its dividend from 50 cents to 25 cents.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 3, 1982%0a%3c Election Day: Republican Governor Thornburgh wins a second term in a close race against Alan Ertel. H. John Heinz III is re-elected to the U.S. Senate, defeating his Democratic opponent, Cyril Wecht, by 700,000 votes.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 5, 1982%0a%3c Unemployment in Pennsylvania hits 11.5 percent.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 17, 1982%0a%3c The 57-day NFL players strike ends.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 11, 1982%0a%3c "Spectator," a Philadelphia management firm, has been chosen to run the Three Rivers Stadium.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 16, 1982%0a%3c University of Pittsburgh football player Todd Joseph Becker is killed in a fall from his dorm window.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 17, 1982%0a%3c PAT agrees to a record budget of $133.5 million, $8 million more than the year before.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 24, 1983%0a%3c City inspectors charge Warner Cable with electrical safety violations.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 9, 1983%0a%3c Mesta Machine files for bankruptcy after a foreclosure by three local banks.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 12, 1983%0a%3c The East is buried by three feet of snow.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 13, 1983%0a%3c Mrs. Henry Hillman ("Elsie") is named by the Pittsburgh Chapter of Vector International as "Woman of the Year."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 17, 1983%0a%3c A rock and mudslide on Saw Mill Run Boulevard closes the road for three weeks.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 1, 1983%0a%3c City government will spend $1.7 million in surplus funds to create short-term jobs for the unemployed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 3, 1983%0a%3c U.S. Steel will start up the No. 2 blast furnace at the Edgar Thomson works and recall 300 employees.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 15, 1983%0a%3c Aldege "Baz" Bastien, general manager of the Penguins, is killed in a motor car accident.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 6, 1983%0a%3c President Reagan visits Pittsburgh and makes a reassuring speech about the survival of the steel industry. Four thousand protestors boo him.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 23, 1983%0a%3c City officials launch a multi-million dollar reclamation project along the Monongahela and Allegheny Rivers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 10, 1983%0a%3c County Commissioner Cyril Wecht is ordered to pay back $172,000, the sum be allegedly made through the misuse of the morgue.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 11, 1983%0a%3c USW head Lloyd McBride announces that the steelworkers organization will sue US Steel to prevent the corporation from importing foreign steel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 18, 1983%0a%3c In the primary election the voters of Allegheny County oust County Commissioners Cyril Wecht and William Hunt.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 25, 1983%0a%3c Cyrus C. "Cy" Hungerford, whose cartoons brightened newspaper pages for over 70 years, dies in his 95th year, four days after the death of his wife Dorothy. Until his retirement in 1977, Hungerford drew three cartoons a week for the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 21, 1983%0a%3c Flash floods hit Bedford, Somerset and Cambria counties, causing a large amount of damage.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 1, 1983%0a%3c A window washer plunges 34 stories to his death from One Oxford Centre when his scaffolding falls. The life of his coworker was saved by his safety belt.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 1, 1983%0a%3c Rebecca Stafford is elected president of Chatham College.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 20, 1983%0a%3c Copperweld Corporation closes its Glassport plant. 200 men lose their jobs.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 22, 1983%0a%3c Power failures at the Greater Pittsburgh Airport delay flights for up to 12 hours.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 27, 1983%0a%3c In a Turnpike pileup, caused by a tractor-trailer, four persons are killed, ten injured.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 29, 1983%0a%3c The city will lose J&L headquarters when parent company LTV Steel buys Cleveland-based Republic Steel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 4, 1983%0a%3c The University of Pittsburgh is assigned a key role in the national fight against AIDS with a $4 million grant.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 3, 1983%0a%3c The 650 employees of the forty-four Giant Eagle Markets end their three-week long strike.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 6, 1983%0a%3c Lloyd McBride, president of the United Steel Workers of America, dies at the age of 67.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 14, 1983%0a%3c Mayor Caliguiri makes it known that his $263.7 million budget will have no tax increase or reduced spending.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 28, 1983%0a%3c US Steel cuts 5,574 district jobs- 3,827 in the Mon Valley.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 2, 1984%0a%3c Democrats Tom Forester and Pete Flaherty and Republican Barbara Hafer are installed as Allegheny County Commissioners.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 9, 1984%0a%3c Plans are unveiled for a 36-story skyscraper -- the Hillman-First Federal Tower -- to be built on the site of the Jenkins Arcade near the Hotel Hilton.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 13, 1984%0a%3c Westinghouse phases out its switch gear production in East Pittsburgh. 950 workers lose their jobs.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 15, 1984%0a%3c Veteran Pittsburgh Press news photographer Raymond Gallivan, who worked for the newspaper for fifty years, dies. He was 88 years old.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 24, 1984%0a%3c Alcoa will renovate the 70-year-old William Penn Hotel. The estimated cost is $20 million.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 26, 1984%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Steelers sue Three Rivers Stadium Authority for exclusive pro-football use of the stadium. The United States Football Leagues Maulers had signed a four-year lease with the Stadium.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 4, 1984%0a%3c Charles H. "Chuck" Cooper, former Duquesne University All-American, who joined the Boston Celtics in 1950 to become the first black to play in the National Basketball Association, dies at age 57.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 10, 1984%0a%3c Kroger Company sells all of its 45 Pittsburgh-area stores. The 2,845 union employees who had been on strike since January 19 will be out of jobs.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 10, 1984%0a%3c According to Roger Ahlbrandt, Assistant Provost at the University of Pittsburgh and Co-Director of the Western Pennsylvania Advanced Technology Center, the new center has already spawned four new companies in its first year, and is expected to bring to Pittsburgh within the next four years 80 more companies creating 6,000 new jobs.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 14, 1984%0a%3c Dr. Henry T. Bahnson and Dr. Thomas Starzl perform a simultaneous 16-hour liver and heart transplant operation on a six-year-old girl at Childrens Hospital.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 9, 1984%0a%3c U.S. Steel and National Intergroup cancel their merger plans.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 21, 1984%0a%3c After strong criticism from the national administration, LTV Corporation, owner of J&L Steel, is allowed so buy Republic Steel for $700 million.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 21, 1984%0a%3c Warner Cable reaches an agreement to sell its city cable operations to TCI for $93 million.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 23, 1984%0a%3c Thirty-six-year-old William W. Millar becomes the youngest executive director of the Port Authority.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 27, 1984%0a%3c The Dixmont State Hospital and Western Restoration Center, two state-run mental health facilities in Allegheny County will be closed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 1, 1984%0a%3c WQED, the nations first community owned television station, celebrates its 30th anniversary.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 5, 1984%0a%3c The future of the steel industry is the focus of the debate between Democratic presidential candidates Walter Mondale, Gary Hart and Rev. Jesse Jackson at the Convention Center.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 6, 1984%0a%3c Senator Gary Hart, Rev. Jesse Jackson and Vice President Walter Mondale have a televised Democratic presidential debate at the Convention Center.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 7, 1984%0a%3c A federal judge prohibits U.S. Steel from forcing employees to sign away their rights to file age discrimination suits in return for big pensions.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 12, 1984%0a%3c U.S. Labor Secretary Raymond Donovan and Governor Thornburgh bring $1.5 million in grants to Midland to retrain 4,100 unemployed workers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 13, 1984%0a%3c The South Hills street car junction at Overbrook and Mt. Lebanon-Beechview trolley lines closes after 80 years in operation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 14, 1984%0a%3c Timothy Johnson, the first local patient, receives a heart and kidney transplant. In separate operations at the Presbyterian-University Hospital, Dr. Bartley Griffith and Dr. Alfredo Trento give Johnson a new heart, while Dr. Rodney Taylor and Dr. Thomas Rosenthal provide him with a new kidney.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 26, 1984%0a%3c Louis Mason Jr., the first black president of the City Council, dies at the age of 69.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 29, 1984%0a%3c Andre Previn, music director of the Symphony since 1976, will leave Pittsburgh to take over the direction of the Los Angeles Philharmonic.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 30, 1984%0a%3c Fortune magazine lists Pittsburgh as the nations third largest corporation center. Fifteen of Fortunes 500 companies have their headquarters in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 4, 1984%0a%3c Wiretapping leads to gambling and conspiracy charges against 15 area residents who were involved in a $1 million a year betting ring.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 31, 1984%0a%3c The former Union Trust Building -- since 1946 a national historic landmark- is sold to the Edward J. De Bartolo Corporation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 14, 1984%0a%3c Gurdon Flagg, manager of the Duquesne club for 50 years (from 1931 to 1981) and president of the Pittsburgh Opera for 28 years (from 1954 to 1982), dies in his 83rd year.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 10, 1984%0a%3c Dr. Joseph C. Maroon and three other doctors perform a pioneer brain surgery at Allegheny General Hospital.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 6, 1984%0a%3c Allegheny County jurors are allowed to question witnesses during a criminal trial. It is the first time in the areas history. Common Pleas Court Judge Henry R. Smith Jr. said the purpose of a trial is to find the truth, and some of us feel that in order to do that, jurors should be permitted to ask questions.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 11, 1984%0a%3c David B. Shakarian, founder and chairman of the board of General Nutrition Centers, the health food company, dies of cancer at the age of 70.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 16, 1984%0a%3c The 56-year-old Stanley Theatre will become the Benedum Center for Performing Arts as a result of a $5 million gift from the Benedum Foundation. The new center will be the permanent home of the Pittsburgh Ballet Theatre, the Pittsburgh Opera and the Civic Light Opera.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 17, 1984%0a%3c Forbes magazines annual listing of Americas 400 wealthiest people includes six Pittsburghers, Henry L. Hillman, 62; Richard Mellon Scaife, 52; Henry John Heinz II, 76; William Block, 68, and his brother Paul Block, Jr., 73; the late David B. Shakarian and Helen Clay Frick, 95.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 19, 1984%0a%3c A $230 million development plan for the Three Rivers Stadium area is announced. A Science and Technology Center will be part of the project.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 2, 1984%0a%3c Three Carnegie Mellon university scientists -- Raj Reddy, Allen Newell and H.T. King -- receive a $19 million grant to develop a new "supercomputer" for the symbolic processing that is 100 times as fast as those currently available.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 31, 1984%0a%3c The 64-story U.S. Steel Building is sold to a Connecticut partnership for $292.2 million, constituting the largest real estate sale in Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 31, 1984%0a%3c Philanthropist Alfred M. Hunt dies at the age of 65.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 9, 1984%0a%3c Helen Clay Frick, the daughter of steelman Henry Clay Frick, dies at the age of 96.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 14, 1984%0a%3c Carnegie Mellon University is awarded a five-year $103 million Defense Department contract for a new Software Engineering Institute. It is expected that the Institute will provide 250 new jobs.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 20, 1984%0a%3c The Galbreath family, after 38 years of association with the Pittsburgh Pirates, decides to sell its 51%25 interest in the team. The Pirates, with a lease of the Stadium until 2011, will remain in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 6, 1984%0a%3c Groundbreaking begins for the $135 million building complex across from the David L. Lawrence Convention Center. The project will include the 615-room Vista International Hotel and a 31-story office building.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 17, 1985%0a%3c Rockwell International will acquire Allen-Bradley Company, a Milwaukee-based industrial automation equipment manufacturer, for $1.65 billion.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 4, 1985%0a%3c "Clayton," the Point Breeze home of Helen Clay Frick, according to her will, will be opened to the public.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 20, 1985%0a%3c The city of Pittsburgh will sever financial ties with several companies that are doing business with South Africa.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 27, 1985%0a%3c Rand McNallys Places Rated Almanac lists Pittsburgh as the most livable of the nations 329 metropolitan areas.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 1, 1985%0a%3c Gulf Oil Corporation will donate its Harmarville Research and Development Center to the University of Pittsburgh. The huge center expects to procure jobs for 2,000 scientists and technicians.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 4, 1985%0a%3c Carnegie Mellon University will open a research center that will use fluorescent materials to study living cells. Researchers from the biology, chemistry, physics, engineering and computer science departments will participate in the program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 15, 1985%0a%3c Charles Robinson Chick Davies, 84, the legendary Duquesne University basketball coach, dies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 2, 1985%0a%3c J. Bruce Johnston, the chairman of the Coordinating Steel Companies Committee says the steel industry will resume company-by-company bargaining in 1987 after the expiration of the present labor agreement.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 5, 1985%0a%3c A married couple, Ken and Lisa Martin of Mesa, Arizona, win victories in the first Pittsburgh Marathon.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 8, 1985%0a%3c The 10+-mile Light Rail Transit line between South Hills Village and Downtown receives a $19.7 million grant from the Urban Mass Transportation Administration. The money will pay for the completion of the line.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 10, 1985%0a%3c Arson is suspected in two simultaneous fires, one in the City-County Building, the other in the basement of the County Office Building.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 29, 1985%0a%3c AGV Enterprises will purchase the 34-story Gulf Building -- a national historic landmark- from the Chevron Corporation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 12, 1985%0a%3c A special device developed by University-Presbyterian Hospital surgeons Dr. Bartley Griffith, Dr. Robert Hardesty and Dr. Alberto Trento is revealed after a heart-lung transplant at the hospital.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 21, 1985%0a%3c Professor Ralph Z. Roskies of the University of Pittsburgh plans to give Pittsburgh a new supercomputer, which will make the city the computing center of America.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 29, 1985%0a%3c Dr. Ronald B. Herberman, a federal science administrator and tumor researcher, will head the newly formed University of Pittsburgh Cancer Institute.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 3, 1985%0a%3c The citys first subway opens to traffic. It cost $90 million to build.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 4, 1985%0a%3c Judge Henry Ellenbogen, 85, dies in Miami, Florida. He served on the Allegheny County Common Pleas Court bench for 39 years and in the U.S. House of Representatives for 5 years.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 19, 1985%0a%3c Prime parking spaces in Downtown cost two dollars per hour, twice as much as in the nations 25 largest cities.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 2, 1985%0a%3c National Intergroup buys Permain Corporation of Houston, the crude oil gathering company for $172 million.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 4, 1985%0a%3c The 8th annual Three Rivers Regatta is watched by over a hundred thousand people.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 28, 1985%0a%3c Willeen Benedum, niece of the legendary oil wildcatter Michael Benedum, dies of pneumonia at the age of 80.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 11, 1985%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Foundation celebrates its 40th anniversary by commemorating Pittsburgh's achievements over the past forty years that "shaped the citys renaissance."%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 13, 1985%0a%3c A Port Authority study outlines the economic advantages of extending the subway north to Allegheny Center and east to Oakland and Squirrel Hill. The proposed $400 million expansion would replace buses with trolleys and would help PAT save over $2 million a year.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 26, 1985%0a%3c George A. Ferris, the new Chief Executive Officer of the Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Corporation, orders layoffs and pay edits for management and vows to work without pay until the 69-day labor dispute involving 8,200 workers is settled.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 2, 1985%0a%3c A private-public partnership led by Malcolm Prince, the Chairman of Ryan Homes Inc., buys the Pittsburgh Pirates for $22 million from the Galbreath family. The public and private partners will contribute $50 million, while Mayor Caliguiri plans to raise the citys share -- $25 million -- through selling Three Rivers Stadium.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 8, 1985%0a%3c Roger Miles Blough, former U.S. Steel Chairman of the Board and Chief Executive Officer, dies at age 81.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 28, 1985%0a%3c Dr. Bartley Griffith leads a three-man surgical team at Presbyterian-University Hospital that gives Pittsburgh's first artificial heart reappoint, Thomas J. Gaidosh, a new heart which replaces the Jarvik-7 artificial heart that had kept the patient alive for 4 days.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 5, 1985%0a%3c Mayor Richard Caliguiri is elected to a third consecutive term.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 6, 1985%0a%3c The Monongahela River is closed from Pittsburgh south to the West Virginia border after floodwater dislodges 62 barges from their moorings.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 8, 1985%0a%3c The Pittsburgh City Council unanimously approve Mayor Caliguiris proposal to sell Three Rivers Stadium, thus enabling the Pirates to remain in Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c November 20, 1985%0a%3c Kimberly Fuller, 9, becomes the youngest American to undergo lung-heart transplant surgery in a 5.5-hour operation performed by Dr. Bartley Griffith and Dr. Robert Hardesty at the Childrens Hospital.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 6, 1985%0a%3c Mark Di Suveros 90-foot-tall steel sculpture for a traffic island in Gateway Center is approved by the citys Art Commission.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 8, 1986%0a%3c Westinghouse Electric celebrates its 100th Anniversary.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 17, 1986%0a%3c A supercomputer consortium (Westinghouse Electric Corp., Carnegie-Mellon University and the University of Pittsburgh) receives the CRAY X-MP/48 supercomputer capable of performing 840 million operations per second. The Pittsburgh group is part of a national supercomputer consortium along with Cornell University, Princeton University, the University of Illinois and the University of California in San Diego.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 22, 1986%0a%3c 15 million passengers traveled through the Greater Pittsburgh International Airport in 1985, a 1.6 million increase over the previous year.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 28, 1986%0a%3c All 7 crew members, including 1970 Carnegie-Mellon University graduate Judith Resnick, die as the Space Shuttle Challenger explodes after takeoff from Cape Canaveral.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 31, 1986%0a%3c An earthquake shakes Pittsburgh for the first time in 23 years.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 7, 1986%0a%3c A $28 million merger offer by Australias Swan Brewing Co. to the Pittsburgh Brewing Co. is accepted by the citys only beer maker.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 11, 1986%0a%3c U.S. Steel Chairman David Roderick announces the completion of a $3 billion merger agreement between U.S. Steel Corporation and Texas Oil and Gas Company.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 21, 1986%0a%3c Marilyn, the prize cow at the Pennsylvania Holstein Association auctions, is sold for $9,500.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 28, 1986%0a%3c Seven major league baseball players, including former Pirates Dale Berra and Dave Parker, have to pay fines and perform community service to avoid drug-related suspensions handed down by Commissioner Peter Ueberroth. Former Pirates Lee and Lacy and Al Holland are given 60-day suspensions; Willie Stargell and Bill Madlock are absolved of any wrong-doing.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 17, 1986%0a%3c The City Council approves a $21 million loan to keep the Pirates in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 19, 1986%0a%3c Sentry, a new security robot developed by Remming Mobile Robotics, with the help of Carnegie Mellon University and the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, is presented in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 1, 1986%0a%3c The Allegheny Tower apartments will be converted into a 273-room hotel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 6, 1986%0a%3c Retired President of Jones and Laughlin Steel Corporation William P. Gerry, 76, dies of cancer in West Penn Hospital.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 7, 1986%0a%3c Mellon Bank assumes ownership of the Trimont condominium complexs 115 apartments and 44,900 square feet of office space to settle a $30 million debt owed to the bank by Washington Heights Associates.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 9, 1986%0a%3c Stanley C. Ellerspan, vice president of human resources at National Steel Corporation, announces the companys intentions to dismiss 3,500 of its employees during the next five years.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 17, 1986%0a%3c Pittsburgh Press reporters Mary Pat Flaherty and Andrew Schneider win the Pulitzer Prize for their series, "The Challenge of a Miracle: Selling the Gift," in which they investigated the organ transplantation program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 21, 1986%0a%3c William Moore, a 35-year veteran of the police force, is appointed as the citys police chief. He is the first black appointed police chief in Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 1, 1986%0a%3c President Anthony OReilly of H.J. Heinz Company is the highest paid executive in the city. In 1985 he earned $1.96 million in salary and in bonuses.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 18, 1986%0a%3c Two parachutists, Don Sulkowski and Alan Danko, jump off the roof of the 64-story U.S. Steel building and land safely on the parking lot of the Civic Arena. They are immediately arrested.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 27, 1986%0a%3c Mayor Caliguiri and Pittsburgh Penguins Vice-President Paul Martha announce a city and county sponsored $11.4 million renovation of the Civic Arena that will keep the National Hockey League Club in the city.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 30, 1986%0a%3c Thunderstorms bring about flash flooding causing $20 million damages.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 2, 1986%0a%3c University of Arkansas third baseman Jeff King is chosen by the Pirates as the first pick in the 1986 major league baseball amateur draft.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 4, 1986%0a%3c Lawyer John G. Buchanan, who practiced law in Pittsburgh for 74 years, dies in his Shadyside home at age 97.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 30, 1986%0a%3c The University of Pittsburgh receives a $4.6 million federal grant for a research center in which drugs against AIDS will be tested.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 1, 1986%0a%3c The state budget gives Carnegie Mellon University $30 million to build a high technology center. Private investors and the University will combine forces to raise an additional $10 million for a National Center for Advanced Manufacturing and Software Engineering.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 8, 1986%0a%3c U.S. Steel Corporation, formed in 1901, changes its name to USX Corporation and plans a major corporate restructuring.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 14, 1986%0a%3c With gross revenues of $53 million, the law firm Reed, Smith, Shaw and McClay ranks 48th in a survey of the 75 highest grossing law firms in America.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %