rant to the Historical Society of Western Pennsylvania to help secure and interpret a rockshelter near Avella which was used by Native Americans 16,000 years ago and is one of the oldest such sites in North America.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 3, 1994%0a%3c Thomas J. Murphy, former State Senator, is sworn in as Pittsburghs 55th mayor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 4, 1994%0a%3c Up to 2-1/2 feet of snow fall in Southwestern Pennsylvania in the wake of a paralyzing blizzard.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 1, 1994%0a%3c British Prime Minister John Major, whose father worked briefly in East Pittsburgh as a bricklayer in the 1890s before returning to England, meets with President Clinton in Pittsburgh.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 9, 1994%0a%3c Groundbreaking ceremonies for the $42 million Senator John Heinz Pittsburgh Regional History Center in the Strip District.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 29, 1994%0a%3c Hornes Department Store, which was founded in 1849, is bought by Federated Department Stores of Cincinnati.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 30, 1994%0a%3c Pittsburgh Symphony names Marvin Hamlish to fill the new post of Principal Pops Conductor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 3, 1994%0a%3c La Roche College receives $5 million from Gateway Clipper Fleet owner, John Connelly, for its new sports and fitness center.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 13, 1994%0a%3c Opening of the Andy Warhol Museum on the North Side.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 16, 1994%0a%3c The U.S. Open Golf Championship begins at Oakmont Country Club. Ernie Els of South Africa wins after a twenty hole sudden death playoff on June 21.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 27, 1994%0a%3c Lorin Maazel, Director of the Pittsburgh Symphony, will not renew his contract after the 1996 season.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 27, 1994%0a%3c The site for the Korean War Veterans Memorial in Roberto Clemente Park on the North Shore is dedicated.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 8, 1994%0a%3c