c %0a%3c April 5, 1995%0a%3c Myron Cope, sportscaster and creator of the "Terrible Towel," gives his final afternoon talk show on WTAE. Cope continues as voice of the Steelers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 10, 1995%0a%3c Tile Pittsburgh Symphony appoints Mariss Jansons as Music Director to succeed Lorin Maazel.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 10, 1995%0a%3c University of Pittsburgh Chancellor. J. Dennis OConner announces his resignation.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 28, 1995%0a%3c "Miss Pittsburgh," an open cockpit hi-wing airplane, is unveiled at the new airport. The plane completed the first commercial airmail delivery here on April 21, 1927, landing in West Mifflins Bettis Field.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 29, 1995%0a%3c The new $147 million Allegheny County Jail Building opens.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 16, 1995%0a%3c In an upset victory in the Democratic Primary. Mike Dawida and Colleen Vuono, defeat Allegheny County Commissioners, Tom Forester and Pete Flaherty, two incumbents with a combined 40 years in office.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 26, 1995%0a%3c Teresa Heinz, the widow of Senator John Heinz, marries U.S. Senator John Kerry, D-Mass. in Nantucket, Massachusetts. She will remain active in the Pittsburgh area.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 8, 1995%0a%3c Sony Corporation will construct a glass making factory at the site of its TV assembly plant near New Stanton.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 13, 1995%0a%3c H.J. Heinz Company lights a 30 foot tall red and white neon sign at its North Side plant showing a full ketchup bottle.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 23, 1995%0a%3c Dr. Jonas Salk, who developed the polio vaccine while working in Pittsburgh, dies of heart failure in La Jolla, California at 80.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 6, 1995%0a%3c Dr. James 0. Van Trump, historian and co-founder of Pittsburgh History and Landmark Foundation, dies at the age of 88.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 25, 1995%0a%3c Forty-seven people are injured in a train collision in Beechview.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 1, 1995%0a%3c Westinghouse Electric Corp., in a major shift of business emphasis, purchases CBS for $5.4 billion.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 5, 1995%0a%3c Despite the rain, 31,147 fans attend the Pirates game at Three Rivers Stadium, as part of the Post-Gazettes sponsored, "Ballot by Ballpark" in support of keeping the team in Pittsburgh. The Bucs win 3-1.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 21, 1995%0a%3c Sean Hitchman is arrested and charged with embezzling $1.2 million from ATMs while working for Mellon Bank.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 6, 1995%0a%3c Carnegie-Mellon celebrates its 100th anniversary.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c October 12, 1995%0a%3c Jonny F. Gammage, a black motorist, dies after an incident with police officers.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 24, 1995%0a%3c The Downtown Lazarus department store closes, marking the end of a 102 year old store which was previously a Hornes store.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January, 1996%0a%3c Neal Holmes, chairman of the Board of Allied Security, is unanimously reelected to his 4th term as chairman of the Port Authority.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 1, 1996%0a%3c Republicans Larry Dunn and Bob Cranmer take the oath of office as Allegheny County Commissioners along with Democrat Mike Dawida, giving Republicans control of the county for the first time in 60 years.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 3, 1996%0a%3c Nationally recognized forensic pathologist, Dr. Cyril Wecht, is sworn in as Allegheny County coroner after a 16 years hiatus.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 13, 1996%0a%3c City Council unanimously approves a package of loans and lease concessions to open the way for California newspaper owner, Kevin McClatchy, to purchase the Pirates.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 14, 1996%0a%3c Steelers defeat the Indianapolis Colts 20-16 earning a trip to Super Bowl XXX after a 16 year absence. They lose two weeks later to the Dallas Cowboys 20-17.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 22, 1996%0a%3c Pittsburgh cleans up from the worst flood in 24 years.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 21, 1996%0a%3c Mrs. Mary Hagan Barrett, executive secretary in charge of public relations at the Pittsburgh Hilton 1959-1983 and founder and two-terms president of the National Secretaries Association, dies.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 5, 1996%0a%3c Bill Foster, pitcher for the Homestead Grays and the Pittsburgh Crawfords who led the Negro League in strikeouts four times, is elected to Baseballs Hall of Fame by the Veterans Committee.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 8, 1996%0a%3c Long term Allegheny County Public Works Director Joseph P Moses and two codefendants are found guilty of participating in a kick-back conspiracy.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c March 15, 1996%0a%3c Robert Mehrabian retires as president of Carnegie Mellon University.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 2, 1996%0a%3c Robert McNeilly Jr., a member of the citys police force for 19 years, is named chief of police.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c April 25, 1996%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Penguins complete the longest game in their history (6 hours, 38 minutes) by defeating the Washington Capitals 3-2 at 2:16 am, in a Stanley Cup playoff game held in Landover, Maryland.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 5, 1996%0a%3c The Pittsburgh Marathon is won by Ruben Maza of Venezuela and Tamara Karlioukova of Russia.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 15, 1996%0a%3c Elsie Hillman announces plans to step down from the Republican National Committee after 21 years of service.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c May 20, 1996%0a%3c Lorin Maazel conducts his 41st concert and his last as Music Director of the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra, a position he held since 1984.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 5, 1996%0a%3c The University of Pittsburgh Medical Center and Shadyside Hospital confirm plans to merge, establishing an institution more than twice the size of its closest competitor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 7, 1996%0a%3c Hillary Rodham Clinton, the Presidents wife visits the Manchester Craftsmens Guild and the Strip District.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 7, 1996%0a%3c The Austrian Nationality Room opens at the University of Pittsburgh as the 24th nationality classroom.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 17, 1996%0a%3c William Strickland, ceramic artist and director of the Manchester Craftsmens Guild and the Bidwell Training Center, is honored with a grant of $295,000 by the MacArthur Foundation for his work with the citys youth and unemployed.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 20, 1996%0a%3c Penguins Center Mario Lemieux wins the Hart Trophy for the third time as the National Hockey Leagues Most Valuable Player.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 20, 1996%0a%3c Mark Nordenberg, former Dean of the universitys law school, is named Chancellor of the University of Pittsburgh after serving as interim chancellor since August 1, 1995.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c June 29, 1996%0a%3c A renovated 1898 foundry in Lawrenceville is dedicated as the home of the newly established National Robotics Engineering Consortium which links NASA and the world renowned robotics research department of Carnegie Mellon University in commercial projects for mobile robots.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 31, 1996%0a%3c Kurt Angie of Mt Lebanon wins the gold medal in freestyle wrestling at the Olympic Games in Atlanta.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 1, 1996%0a%3c Rosa Parks, civil rights heroine, visits Pittsburgh to promote the "Pathways to Freedom" program of workshops on black history for students ages 11 to 17.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 12, 1996%0a%3c Richard Armstrong, chief curator of the Carnegie Museum of Art, is appointed as the museums eighth director, effective August 30.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c August 12, 1996%0a%3c Kennywoods 1936 Noahs Ark reopens after a year of renovation. The ark is the countrys only funhouse remaining of the two