es plan to acquire Duquesne Light Holdings for $1.59 billion.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c July 11, 2006%0a%3c Pittsburgh hosts the Major League Baseball All-Star Game for the second time. The American League beat the National League by a score of 3-2.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 1, 2006%0a%3c Mayor Bob OConnor dies at 61 from a rare form of brain cancer only seven months into his term. Luke Ravenstahl, City Council President, is sworn in as new mayor.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 16, 2006%0a%3c Five Duquesne University basketball players are shot on campus after a dance in the worst act of random violence to strike a major college sports program.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c September 19, 2006%0a%3c Route 65 in Kilbuck Township is closed after a major landslide resulted from the construction of a Wal-Mart on the site of the former Dixmont State Hospital. The slide also covers the tracks of the Norfolk Southern Railroad.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 4, 2006%0a%3c Mellon Financial merges with the Bank of New York.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c December 20, 2006%0a%3c State Gaming Commission awards Pittsburgh casino rights to PITG Gaming for its Majestic Star casino on the North Shore.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 5, 2007%0a%3c Bill Cowher resigns as head coach of the Pittsburgh Steelers after fifteen seasons.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 22, 2007%0a%3c Mike Tomlin announced as the new head coach of the Pittsburgh Steelers; he is the first African-American to hold this position within the Steelers organization.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c January 24, 2007%0a%3c Viennese Manfred Honeck named as new conductor of the Pittsburgh Symphony.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 5, 2007%0a%3c A failed expansion joint causes a slab from the David L. Lawrence Convention Center to crash onto 10th Street leading to the replacement and repair of fifty other beams.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c February 21, 2007%0a%3c Pittsburgh is chosen for US Airways new 